A6050 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COTEY-AZR &LR;      06-23 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COTEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUROR AT CENTER OF SYMINGTON RULING FEELS VINDICATED
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hallelujah! Free at last!''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jane Cotey might have been talking about Fife Symington's
reaction to a court ruling overturn ing his bank-fraud convictions.
</P>
<P>
   But Cotey, a former juror in the case, was talking about freedom
for herself, not the ex-governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm free of notoriety,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cotey, 76, is the once-obscure juror whose strange and willful
behavior in the trial deliberations thrust her into the spotlight
and placed her in the role of last hope for Symington. She was at
the heart of the 9th Circuit Court of Appeal's 2-1 ruling that
reversed Symington's criminal convictions.
</P>
<P>
   But the attention she drew - and the eccentric image of her
painted by fellow jurors - has brought her sidelong looks from
strangers and sporadic fits of media scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she felt a sense of vindication.
</P>
<P>
   The justices decided that Cotey should not have been removed
from the federal criminal jury, noting it was ``reasonably
possible'' that she was kicked off because she had decided
Symington was innocent, while the other jurors were con vinced he
was guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like saying what I think,'' Cotey said.
</P>
<P>
   But, as she did in summer 1997, Cotey seemed to be of two minds.
At one point, she said that, before leaving the jury, she had not
made up her mind about Symington's guilt or innocence on 22 federal
criminal charges. But then she said she saw no evidence that he was
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she added, everyone's guilty of something, so who is
she to judge? And no one remains innocent throughout their entire
life, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cotey maintained that the appeals court ruling vindicates her
unwaver ing resistance to group pressure during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   She also shared her wishes for Symington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey guy: High five!'' she beamed. ``I can talk his language if
I want to. (But) I don't feel pretentious today.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington praised Cotey in his noontime press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mary Jane Cotey is a very brave young lady,'' he said.
``She was right and I think she's just a courageous person.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotey said she hasn't talked to Symington since the day he was
convicted in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   She phoned him at the Governor's Office, she recalled, and when
the secretary patched her through, she said she expressed her
condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Cotey said she was shocked that the verdict prompted Symington
to resign as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to see if they would get two governors within 10
years because they were both Re publicans,'' she said she told Sy
mington. ``They'' were political types, she said. Gov. Evan Mecham
was impeached and convicted by the Arizona Legislature and left
office in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Symington dismissed her conspir acy theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he didn't blame me at all,'' she recalled. ``He
told me I did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotey's comprehension of events two summers ago in the U.S.
District Courthouse in downtown Phoenix is at the heart of the
appeals court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Symington successfully argued that the court violated his Sixth
Amendment right to an impartial jury when Judge Roger Strand
dismissed Cotey.
</P>
<P>
   Cotey claimed other jurors were trying to railroad her into a
deci sion. And in an affidavit filed with Symington's appeal, she
stated that ``If I had not been excused from the jury, I would have
voted not guilty on all charges against Mr. Syming ton.''
</P>
<P>
   The other 11 jurors had ap proached Strand several days into
their deliberations, complaining that Cotey was unable to focus on
their talks. For example, she refused to repeat back to her
colleagues the topics they had just discussed, had trouble filling
out her lunch order and often would ramble on, jurors said.
</P>
<P>
   Strand, after individually inter viewing the jurors, dismissed
Cotey from the panel during its eighth day of deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The judge concluded ``that this was not a case where eleven
jurors conspired to remove a single juror simply because that juror
was being difficult or held differing views in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court found that it was ``reasonably possible''
that the jurors clashed with Cotey be cause she had reached
different conclusions on the case than they had. If that was the
case, it was wrong to drop her from the jury, the court held.
</P>
<P>
   Cotey said it took awhile before her problems with her fellow
jurors surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gradually happened that I was being pushed into decisions
on almost every charge on each page,'' she said. Cotey explained
that she still had questions, and therefore had to hold out on a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see the tack that was being taken,'' she said of the
jurors' objections. ``Dementia!''
</P>
<P>
   The label of a daffy old woman hurt her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cotey said she didn't think Sy mington should be retried. But if
he is, she said she would ``watch it closely. Attend it if I could
... to see how this little piece of the justice system expands or
retracts.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotey turned 76 this spring, and said the song ``76 Trombones''
was the theme for her celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The former bookkeeper and tele-marketer said she prefers to see
herself as unemployed, rather than retired.
</P>
<P>
   These days, she busies herself with friends and amuses herself
with Charles Le Roi, her white teacup poodle. She described herself
as a ``philosophical dabbler'' when she was being screened for jury
duty.
</P>
<P>
   She said her sudden notoriety was hard on both her and her
neighbors, drawing camera crews and reporters to her modest home.
</P>
<P>
   She said when she walks around, she tried to deflect attention.
``I say, `Hey, don't look at me, I'm invisible today.' Which makes
you a little more kooky.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotey said she hasn't been called to serve on any other juries,
al though she chuckled when a Mari copa County Superior Court
summons arrived in the midst of her work on the Symington trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Totally involved in a federal case now,'' she said, recalling
the excuse she gave to the county court. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
