<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-SAILORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diggers say they're close to remains of Confederate sailors
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Archaeologists, looking for the first
Confederate sailors who died aboard the submarine H.L. Hunley in
1863, have found what appear to be two grave shafts beneath The
Citadel's football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery late Tuesday comes amid growing notoriety for the
first sub in naval history to sink an enemy ship, a saga to be
depicted in the July 11 premiere of the Turner Network Television
movie ``The Hunley.''
</P>
<P>
   Designed to break up the Union's naval blockade of the
Charleston harbor, the cramped, steel vessel sank in 1864. The nine
sailors who died then were actually the sub's third crew to perish
aboard the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are under way to recover the Hunley, along with its final
crew, in 2001. Discovered in 1995, the submarine is buried under 30
feet of water four miles off Sullivans Island near Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the second crew of eight sailors _ who died late in
1863 during a test dive _ are buried in Charleston's Magnolia
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The whereabouts of the remains of the original crew of five had
been unknown until last year. The original crew died when the
submarine sank at its mooring in August 1863 after waves flooded an
open hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War buff Glenn McConnell, a Republican state senator from
Charleston, discovered a reference to ``the men of the torpedo
boat'' in old documents related to the old Confederate naval
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a search by ground-penetrating radar found evidence of
the graves underneath the stands of The Citadel military college's
football stadium, the site of an abandoned cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Digging started Tuesday just inside the stadium's cinderblock
wall. Heading a team of volunteers from Confederate heritage
groups, deputy state archaeologist John Leader had hoped to
discover skeletal remains by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Digging resumes today for the skeletons, which could be just a
few feet from the surface, Leader said.Chris Burritt writes for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
