<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL DRAMAS ASIDE, YANKS CRUSH DEVIL RAYS, 7-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Baseball bends for births and funerals,
and rarely bends any further. The game is played every day, and the
players are expected to be ready, and to perform. Paul O'Neill,
whose father is ailing, fulfilled both obligations Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill drove in a run and walked, and Orlando Hernandez became
the first Yankee to pitch a complete game this season as he beat
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, 7-0, on a three-hitter. Eighty-two games
had passed since the Yankees' last complete game, when Hernandez
beat the Boston Red Sox last Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, revitalized since moving to the No. 2 spot in
the batting order, had two singles and two doubles for the Yankees,
and Shane Spencer slugged his first home run since May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Playing baseball provides no protection against reality. Second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch's father is suffering from Alzheimer's
disease, and Scott Brosius' father is fighting cancer. O'Neill told
manager Joe Torre last week that his father was suffering from
heart failure; on Monday, Torre received a call from Nevalee
O'Neill, Paul's wife, who passed on the news that Paul had to fly
back to Columbus, Ohio, to be with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Charles O'Neill had surgery Monday, and Tuesday, his youngest
son rejoined the Yankees, arriving in midafternoon. Paul O'Neill
was in the starting lineup Tuesday night against the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays. The baseball schedule relents for no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you guys go to to work,'' Torre said, speaking directly
to reporters, ``there are other things going on in your life, and
it's the same thing here. The only difference is we don't call in
sick here. We have to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had a strange experience while driving from Miami on
Monday night. On Interstate 75, he smashed into an animal with his
white BMW. Unhurt, Hernandez got out to inspect the front of his
car and to check on the animal _ and in the headlights of his car
lay a dead panther.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's car was still running, and when he arrived at the
team hotel, he told Jose Cardenal, his closest friend on the team,
about the collision, and Cardenal laughed heartily.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get here, he had to go through water with sharks,''
Cardenal said of the pitcher who defected from Cuba, ``and once he
gets here, he runs into a panther.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident did not bother Hernandez on Tuesday night. He
required only 40 pitches to get through the first four innings. He
allowed a single to Wade Boggs in the fifth, the 2,962nd hit of
Boggs' career. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
