<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PROSECUTOR PONDERS RETRIAL AGAINST SYMINGTON'S DEFENSE
ATTORNEY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like two heavyweights brooding in opposite corners of the ring,
John Dowd in Washington and David Schindler in Los Angeles eyed
each other warily Tuesday, contemplating the possibility of
renewing their bitter legal slugfest.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd, the Fife Symington de fender whose defeat at trial in 1997
was reversed Tuesday by a panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, was jubilant but cautious.
</P>
<P>
   He has reason to be wary. He knows that it's up to Schindler's
team, the federal prosecutors who had their victory snatched away,
to decide whether to continue the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took their shot,'' Dowd said. ``They unloaded all their
barrels. Now, I'm going to try to persuade them that enough is
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowd, a former Justice Depart ment lawyer who has enthusiasti
cally bashed federal prosecutors for what he calls a malicious,
politically motivated prosecution of Syming ton, struck a
conciliatory note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they'll give us a hearing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Schindler was keeping his dukes up. He had doggedly pursued
Symington on a long trail of suspect financial statements that led
to the guilty verdict. The only way talk would settle the Symington
matter, he said, would be if the former governor agreed to plead
guilty to felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler emphasized the plural form, drawing an immediate re
sponse from Dowd that there would be no plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although disappointed by the appellate ruling, Schindler said he
is willing to present the case all over again, with the six counts
on which Symington was convicted and the 11 counts on which the
jury was unable to reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This opinion is in no way an exoneration of Mr. Symington,''
he said. ``Nothing that the judges have written detracts from the
underlying fact that 12 members of a jury found that Mr. Symington
made false statements to lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that two judges con cluded that a juror should not
have been dismissed does not undermine the case we presented.''
</P>
<P>
   Schindler, along with co-counsel George Cardona, presented the
jury with dozens of what they alleged to be bogus Symington
financial state ments.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler refused to talk about widespread reports that he may
soon be leaving the U.S. Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even if that were true,'' he said, ``George is still here.
And there are other attorneys who could try the case, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Schindler noted that part of Tuesday's opinion actually vindi
cated his case against Symington. The court knocked down Syming
ton's claim that prosecutors had failed to present sufficient
evidence to convict him on three counts of defrauding Dai Ichi
Kangyo Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Symington has consistently main tained that although he ``made
mistakes'' in his financial reporting, he never committed the crime
of deliberately deceiving the lenders on his ill-fated real estate
projects.
</P>
<P>
   DKB lent Symington real estate partnerships more than $100
million to build the Camelback Esplanade.
</P>
<P>
   In its opinion, the court reported on the bank's requirement, as
a condition of continued financing, that Symington maintain a net
worth of at least $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is undisputed that Symington did submit affidavits
reaffirming his agreement . . . even after his net worth had sunk
below that level,'' the court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It added that Symington submit ted the false affidavits ``for
the purpose of influencing DKB to continue to disburse funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Schindler said that over the next few weeks, his office will
weigh its options, which range from refiling the case in Phoenix,
dropping it, to appealing it further.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects to seek a 30-day extension of the usual
two-week deadline to file a petition for a rehearing before an
11-judge panel at the 9th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``en banc'' reviews, al though rarely held, include the
court's chief judge, plus 10 others whose names would be drawn at
random.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler would also have the option of appealing directly to
the U.S. Supreme Court, which typically agrees to review less than
5 percent of the petitions it receives each year.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Levenson, a former fraud prosecutor in Schindler's
office, said the most likely course of action is a refiling of the
case in the Phoenix court of U.S. District Judge Roger Strand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's someone this impor tant, and they've already made
such a major investment in it, I think they'll retry it,'' said
Levenson, a law professor at Loyola University in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that got them into trouble here was not the
evidence, it was the juror, something totally outside the evidence.
As we say in trial work, things happen. And here that will probably
mean a whole new trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowd is hoping to avoid another courtroom showdown. Noting that
the federal investigation of Syming ton began a decade ago, he
said, ``Nobody can stand that kind of scrutiny. I don't think
anybody should have to go through that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in the late 1980s that federal investigators made their
first big Symington find: that although his tax return showed
income of $100,000 from his real estate devel opment company, his
financial state ment to lenders showed income of $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   That led agents to shift the focus of an investigation they'd
begun a year earlier, prompted by a report by federal regulators of
possible crimi nal conduct by former directors of Southwest Savings
&AMP; Loan.
</P>
<P>
   Symington served on the board of the thrift, whose failure in
1989 cost taxpayers nearly $1 billion. He left the board in 1984,
shortly after it voted to become his partner in the Esplanade
project, a venture that ultimately left the thrift with a
multimillion-dollar loss.
</P>
<P>
   Though no charges were brought against Symington's colleagues on
the board, he was indicted by a federal grand jury in 1996. In
September of the following year, the jury in Strand's courtroom
delivered the verdict that was reversed Tues day.
</P>
<P>
   The case was handled by the U.S. Attorney's Office in Los
Angeles because when it began the U.S. attorney for Arizona was
Republi can Linda Akers. Akers wanted to avoid any hint of
political conflict that might taint the investigation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
