<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-COLLINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS' CONTRACT EXTENDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Angels general manager Bill Bavasi made two things
clear Tuesday _ he's in charge, and Terry Collins is his manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels announced Tuesday they have extended Collins'
contract. The club did not release terms of the deal, including the
length of the extension. It is believed the extension was for two
years plus a club option for a third.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, in his third year with the Angels, makes about $400,000
per season.
</P>
<P>
   The extension put an end to speculation that Collins' job was in
jeopardy following clubhouse dissension over his managerial style
and the team's poor play. Bavasi made it a point to tell reporters
during a conference call that the players' complaints were heard
but ultimately had no effect on the coach's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't factor into talks with Terry,'' Bavasi said. ``We
take things seriously. If one of the guys has complaints, we
listen. But once we looked into it, it was over. To tell you the
truth, I was not very impressed with the complaints. It did not
impact us at all. The only thing that was a concern was that what
Terry and I discussed with the players ended up in the
newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins was Bavasi's hire before the 1997 season, and Bavasi
wasn't about to allow the team's players to tell him he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man's the manager of the ballclub,'' Bavasi said. ``It's
(the players') responsibility to react to what (Collins) wants
done. Not his responsibility to react to what they want done.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he is happy the situation has been resolved and the
focus will be on the field instead of the clubhouse or manager's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got unfinished business here,'' Collins said. ``I'm real
excited it's done, and we can move forward. But it doesn't change
the way I go about my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Player reaction to Collins' extension was indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it doesn't matter,'' pitcher Chuck Finley said. ``I've had
12 different managers so... I don't make evaluations based on my
being coddled or kicked in the butt. Give me the ball 35 times and
that's it. I'm low maintenance.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Randy Velarde, one of the players who met with
Bavasi to discuss concerns with Collins, said he thought the
meeting was for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was healthy doing it,'' he said. ``(Bavasi) was
hearing things through the grapevine about what was going on. He
got the veterans around a table, and we spoke. It was neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde also said he's noticed a difference in Collins, whom
players complained the only times he spoke to many was to scream at
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a credit to him,'' Velarde said. ``He's molded his
character for years, then he's asked to change. It's not easy. He's
been a lot more vocal, and he's handled his temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he hasn't changed and that his office door has
always been open to players. As far as being too emotional: ``Am I
more emotional than Lou Piniella? Than Tommy Lasorda? Those are
pretty good managers. We can mention a lot more. We all care, and
that's what matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
