u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      06-23 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS RALLY LATE TO SINK MARLINS, 8-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Marlins have the worst record in the major leagues. The
Marlins had dropped six straight games on their road trip. The
Marlins started a knuckleball pitcher who had won just two of 11
starts. So when Florida arrived at Shea Stadium Tuesday night, the
Mets should have been smiling and styling all night, right?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but it took them a good portion of the night before they
could fully smile and fully style.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets were baffled by Dennis Springer's fluttering
pitches for six innings, they awakened to score three runs in the
seventh and four in the eighth for an 8-2 victory. The Mets had
looked listless and helpless against Springer's knuckleballs, but
that changed dramatically with a flurry of late hits that enabled
them to exhale.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez, the shortstop who was touted before and during the
game as an All-Star candidate, poked Antonio Alfonseca's first
pitch for a run-scoring single that gave the Mets a 3-2 lead in the
seventh. Ordonez drove in two more runs with a single in the
eighth, and the Mets won for the 12th time last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez's offensive revival is stunning. The shortstop, who
entered the season with a .242 career average, is now batting a
robust .303. The offensive surge has his manager behaving like a
campaign manager as he discussed the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to evaluate it, I don't want to analyze it, I
just want to appreciate it,'' Bobby Valentine said. ``And I am. If
all those fans who came to the game tonight appreciated it, they
should cast their ballot for him. He has his sights set on Boston,
and I think he deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez, who has become a more productive hitter because he is
not trying to pull the ball every time, tied his career high with
three RBI. The Mets said Ordonez is now performing in games the way
he has always hit in batting practice, and the patient yet
aggressive approach has worked splendidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more confident with men on base,'' Ordonez said. ``I
see a pitch, and I know I can handle it better. I'm more confident
in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Ordonez motivated by starting in the All-Star Game?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm elected, I'll go,'' Ordonez said. ``If not, I'll keep
playing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ordonez's continued hitting did not provide enough flair,
Mike Piazza certainly did. In his final at-bat of the game, Piazza
smacked a 2-2 pitch for a home run off Vic Darensbourg in the
eighth to extend his hitting streak to 24 games and tie Hubie
Brooks' 15-year-old team record.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who have three games against the National League
East-leading Braves in Atlanta this weekend, helped their situation
by taking the cupcake the schedule makers offered and devouring it.
By rallying to defeat the Marlins, the Mets are now three games
behind the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Orie ripped a two-run homer off Masato Yoshii in the
second to put Florida ahead, and then Springer almost turned the
rest of the evening into his own show. It is irksome for batters to
face knuckleball pitchers because they rarely oppose them and it is
tough to know where the ball is going. If the knuckler is dancing,
batters can look and feel helpless.
</P>
<P>
   Until the seventh, the Mets did. Robin Ventura, who had homered
in the Mets' second, started the seventh with a double into the
left-field corner and scored when Roger Cedeno swatted a triple
past sprawling center fielder Preston Wilson to even the score,
2-2. Alfonseca replaced Springer, and Ordonez singled to right to
give the Mets a one-run edge.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo added a run-scoring single in the inning as the
Mets came back and did not waste a solid start by Yoshii. Greg
McMichael (1-1) pitched two-thirds of an inning for the victory,
and Armando Benitez was dominant in finishing the last two innings
for his third save.
</P>
<P>
   There was a runner on first and one out in the second when
Yoshii tried to pump a first-pitch fastball by Orie. It was a bad
idea. Orie crushed the inside pitch and it was obvious from the
sound of the bat meeting the ball that the ball would sail over the
fence. The only question was by how much.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Orie's homer leave the playing field, it left the
stadium as well and landed 436 feet from the plate to give the
Marlins a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The lead lasted for a while, or until the Mets finally decided
to style and smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
