<SLUG> BC-BBA-GRIEVE-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERAGE, NOT CONFIDENCE, DOWN FOR GRIEVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Forget the term ``sophomore jinx.'' It
doesn't apply here, says Oakland Athletics outfielder Ben Grieve.
</P>
<P>
   The struggles Grieve had at the beginning of this season, his
second in the major leagues, were quite simply a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing more, nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a slump,'' Grieve said before yesterday's
Rangers-Athletics game. ``Whether it's your second year or your
15th year, you have them, and they're just slumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Grieve can talk more comfortably about his problems hitting at
the start of the season now. That's because they're long gone,
vanished like the fastball he hit off a Tiger Stadium light
standard against Detroit's Dave Mlicki on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening weeks of the season, the 1998 American League
rookie of the year looked nothing like the player who hit .288 with
18 home runs and 89 runs batted in a year ago. On May 19 _ six
weeks into his second season _ the 1994 Martin high School graduate
was hitting .131.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on,'' Oakland manager Art Howe said, ``he was swinging
at pitches he doesn't normally swing at.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the problem, Grieve seems to have found the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 19, Grieve has hit .369 (32-for-87), raising his
average 106 points to .237, going into last night's game. For the
month of June, he's hitting .352 and has driven in 17 runs during
his past 21 games. That's five more runs than he drove in during
the season's first 39 games.
</P>
<P>
   Howe said Grieve is now more aggressive at the plate, saying
he's actually being more selective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just relaxing more and not trying to do too much,'' Grieve
said. ``I'm getting better pitches to hit and I'm getting good
counts. It helps when you don't get behind in the count as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Things could get even better for Grieve during Oakland's series
with the Rangers, considering his history in Arlington. Going into
last night's game, Grieve was a career .377 hitter against the
Rangers, including a .421 mark with three home runs at The Ballpark
in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers like that hint that Grieve won't be a .237 hitter for
long. Rangers manager Johnny Oates agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Ben Grieve is a .220 hitter,'' Oates said. ``I
think he's closer to what he hit last year.''
</P>
<P>
   What should scare opposing pitchers most is that Grieve seems to
have his confidence back. Though he's hitting .053 against
left-handers (he has just 38 at-bats against them) he believes he
can hit anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel good, I think I can hit anything,'' Grieve said.
``It doesn't matter if it's a left-hander or right-hander. If I'm
feeling good I know I can hit them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
