<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIFE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING GIVES SYMINGTON CAREER OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES 
 and CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Gov. Fife Symington awakened Wednesday to a brand new
life. For the first time since his convic tion in 1997 and
sentencing in 1998, he may buy whatever he wants, apply for a new
real estate license, vote and even run for office.
</P>
<P>
   Symington lost those and other rights after a federal jury
convicted him in September 1997 of financial fraud.
</P>
<P>
   He suddenly was faced Tuesday with a swarm of reporters who
wanted to know whether he might run again for office _ a dramatic
turnaround for a man who now makes his living as a pastry chef.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to step out to face a phalanx of journalists
Tuesday, he turned to former aide Doug Cole and said, ``Just like
the old days.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington then stepped up to the microphones for his first full
news conference since his conviction and told reporters that he has
no current plans to return to political life.
</P>
<P>
   He said later that his baking career, which includes learning
how to make wedding cakes, pull sugar and craft sugar sculptures,
keeps him busy these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've devoted a full year of my life. It's five days a week,''
he said. ``It's very, very hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Symington said he will forge ahead with his fledgling
cooking career, which will include an internship as a pastry chef
at a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Syming ton insisted that ``politics is
far from my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well into the cooking world,'' he said. ``I'm really enjoy
ing what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists that he and his family have moved on from his
troubled past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann (Symington's wife) has been senior warden at our church
and doing a great job, finding a new rector and helping to run the
largest fiscal parish in the state,'' Syming ton said in an
interview. ``All of our kids have been in school. You just get
right back into living life and you try not to be too sad about
nostalgia, and sort of dwell on `Oh gosh, this happened.' That's
just not a constructive way to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Another option for the ex-gover nor might be to return to real
estate, where he made millions but lost everything in the early
1990s. As part of a consent decree, Symington surrendered his real
estate license after he was convicted of bank and wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Arizona Department of Real Estate said the
matter was under review by the state Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Symington gave no indication that he would seek to have his
license reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   When Symington was sentenced, he was also prohibited from making
major purchases, incurring new fi nancial obligations, or entering
into any financial contracts without the prior approval of his
supervising officer. He is free from those restrictions as a result
of the court's ruling Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the political commu nity was abuzz with speculation
over whether Symington might seek to renew his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Former Attorney General Grant Woods said that Symington retains
enough popularity within conserva tive Republican circles to
recapture the GOP nomination for governor, but not necessarily the
nod in a general election, if he were to choose to run in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not surprise me a bit to see him run for governor,''
Woods said. ``I think it's a part of his personality.''
</P>
<P>
   But ASU pollster Bruce Merrill said the chances were slim that
Symington could resume a success ful political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``His time has come and gone and there is no way he can
recapture any significant office in this state,'' Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative Democrats, noting smoother relations with
Symington's replacement, Gov. Jane Hull, also hoped Symington would
remain focused on his life as a chef.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Fife Symington era is gone,'' said Rep. Ken
Cheuvront, D-central Phoenix. ``His political life has pretty much
been ruined and I would hope he would not see this as vindication
for him to run for office.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Cheuvront said Democrats do not rule out the
possibility that Symington might seek to retake his gubernatorial
perch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a man who has a great ego and I would not put
anything past him,'' Cheuvront said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even Republican leaders believe it unlikely that
Symington will attempt to kick-start his politi cal career.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican Party Chairman Mike Minnaugh said in the two
years since Symington left office, many voters have moved on, re
placed by a new crop of residents.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a GOP no longer connected to the Symington era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it really means that much for the party
positively or negatively,'' Minnaugh said of the Symington
decision. ``We don't talk about Fife Symington issues at all down
at the party.''
</P>
<P>
   While wishing Symington and his family well, Minnaugh suggested
the party has moved on from the scandal-plagued final days of his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many new people in Maricopa County _ people don't
even know who Fife Symington is.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's news conference, Symington proclaimed his relief
over the news that his conviction was overturned. It was broken to
him by a member of the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely stunned,'' Sy mington said. ``I'm very
thankful. My heart is full of thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The notoriously combative former governor was noticeably low-key
about the decision, while still assert ing that he would achieve
victory should the case be retried.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it should happen that there is a second trial, we will
prevail,'' he said. ``I always thought we were right. But I wasn't
sure (we would prevail).''
</P>
<P>
   Symington returned to cooking school after the news conference,
where his white-hatted fellow cooks waved to reporters waiting
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the hands of a superb German pastry chef,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One classmate of Symington, Eddie Bayze, said Symington was
``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great guy. I had dinner at his house. I didn't even
know who he was when I met him the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Before heading off to school, Symington said he was postponing
dealing with his upcoming legal options for at least one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just savoring the day,'' he said. ``Let me enjoy the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``This has been a very humbling event. . . .It's just
too bad this legal thing interrupted a won derful public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from Arizona Republic columnist David
Leibowitz. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
