<HEADLINE>
JACKSON CLOSE TO TWO HIRINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The Lakers are close to hiring two assistant
coaches, and at least one member of Phil Jackson's staff will have
Laker ties.
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers' holdover coaches _ Kurt Rambis, Bill Bertka
and Larry Drew _ remain in limbo, Jackson has offered positions to
Jim Cleamons, a former Laker, and Jimmy Rodgers. Both were Jackson
assistants with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of trying to get a deal worked out,''
Cleamons said Tuesday from his home in Chicago. ``I would love to
be part of his staff.... We're not there yet. But there's interest
on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleamons served as a Jackson assistant for seven seasons in
Chicago, winning four championships before a brief and
unspectacular stint as Dallas Mavericks head coach in 1996-97. He
was fired 16 games into the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Cleamons coached the Chicago Condors in the ABL
until the league folded, leaving him in search of a job.
</P>
<P>
   That search is close to ending and will reunite Cleamons with
his first NBA team. Cleamons won an NBA championship as a rookie
guard with the Lakers in 1972, his lone season with the team.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cleamons and Rodgers, Jackson is also trying to
hire Bulls assistant Tex Winter, meaning there may be little room
on his staff for the current Lakers coaches. He plans to meet with
them when he returns to L.A. later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Power source: The Lakers are interested in signing Toronto's
Charles Oakley to fill their greatest need _ a rebounding power
forward who can play strong defense. And Oakley might be interested
in the Lakers, but he's sending mixed signals.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Sun, citing sources close to Oakley, reported that
he would pass on a more lucrative deal in the $5 million range with
Toronto to sign with the Lakers for the $2 million exception. Asked
about the Lakers, he told the Sun, ``I'm available.''
</P>
<P>
   But that same day, the 35-year-old Oakley also told the New York
Post, ``Toronto is my No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams and free agents cannot begin negotiating until July 1 and
cannot agree to contracts until Aug. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
