<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-1STLD     06-23 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA IS LETTING THE HITS FALL WHERE THEY MAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: UPDATES thruout with Piazza extending hitting streak to 24
games.) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Piazza has not worn the same pair of socks or
eaten the same meal or left for the ball park at the same time on
consecutive days during his hitting streak because he believes
superstitions are silly. Piazza has watched other players obsess
over such trivial preparation, and he has promised himself that he
will never be so compulsive.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Piazza is casual, not compulsive, about the streak he
extended to 24 games Tuesday night, matching the Mets' club record
on an eighth-inning home run off a 2-2 pitch during an 8-2 Mets
victory over the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   When Piazza was asked before the game about a streak that
started in Pittsburgh on May 25, he might as well have interspersed
his comments with yawns. He insisted he has never measured his
accomplishments by how many games in a row he gets a hit, and
besides, 24 might be a career high, but it was premature to get
excited. Piazza was more animated about discussing an Iron Maiden
compact disk he received in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say if it ends tonight,'' Piazza said before he
batted Tuesday night, ``I won't have any problem getting to
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Piazza lacks the kind of speed that comes in handy to
leg out infield hits, his performance was especially imposing. And
in addition to his offense, he handles the most demanding defensive
position on the field: catcher.
</P>
<P>
   During the streak, Piazza has gone 36 for 102 (.351), with
eighthomers, nine doubles and 18 RBI; he has raised his batting
average a modest 24 points to .326. Despite Piazza's nonchalance
about his streak, he did know that Benito Santiago has the major
league record for consecutive games with a hit by a catcher. When
told that Santiago hit in 34 straight with San Diego in 1987,
Piazza remembered that Santiago set the record in his rookie
season.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alomar Jr., who hit in 30 straight in 1997 with Cleveland,
is the only other catcher to reach the 30-game mark. Hubie Brooks
set the Mets' record of 24 in 1984, which Piazza tied Tuesday night
with a towering drive to left in his final at-bat, after going 0
for 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did Pete Rose have, 44?'' asked Piazza, obviously agog
over that achievement, which came in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine rested Piazza once during the streak,
against the Reds in Cincinnati nine days ago, and said he would
probably rest him again soon. Valentine could face a delicate
situation if he rests the catcher and then needs to use him as a
pinch-hitter late in a game.
</P>
<P>
   When Valentine asked Piazza about such a scenario, which would
put the streak in jeopardy because Piazza might only get one time
at the plate, Piazza told Valentine not to hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I take a day off and the game is on the line and I have to
hit, what the heck,'' said Piazza. ``It's not like I'm not going to
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine evoked Joe DiMaggio's majestic 56-game hitting streak
by saying, ``I daresay, before he gets to 57, he's going to have a
few days off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine obviously understands how difficult it is for a
catcher to hit safely in so many games. Piazza came into the season
as a .333 career hitter, so this is not a mirage. Still, it is much
easier to stand in right field for nine innings and strive for one
hit a game than it is to endure foul pitches off the fingers and
flash signs for 150 pitches and pursue a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pretty impressive character,'' said Valentine. ``I
think it's more impressive when you play one of the more difficult
defensive positions and you have to maintain both sides of the ball
to a high degree of excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   As Piazza fiddled with the Iron Maiden compact disk Tuesday and
gushed about its three guitarists, he grudgingly admitted that he
might take the streak more seriously if he closed within a few
games of Santiago's record. Until then, Piazza will keep changing
his socks, eating whatever he wants and leaving for the ball park
whenever he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, a hitting streak is not really one of those things that
you worry about,'' said Piazza. ``I haven't done that at any point
in my career. It's kind of cool. It's a nice little footnote.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
