</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SORELY LACKING ALLAN HOUSTON-TYPE MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ NBA watchers desperate for anything vaguely
resembling decent hoops were still praising the 34-point breakout
of the Knicks' silky swingman Allan Houston Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who wanted the ball and who actually could knock down
shots, was the reason the Knicks won Game 3 Monday and why they
have infused the Spurs with a case of the yips.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Houston eliminate any chance of a Spurs sweep, he
breathed new life into the resurrected Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But if Houston's dazzling array of midrange jumpers had deeper
meaning, it was to remind everyone what's missing in today's NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Beauty. Flow. Ball movement.
</P>
<P>
   Offenses that use more than two-fifths of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Players who use their skills and smarts to peel off screens and
stick a 15-foot jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches who don't insist on calling a play every time their
teams cross the half-court line.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, there isn't enough Allan Houston in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is in a world of hurt, thanks to Jaws of Life defenses
(where have you gone, Pat Riley?) that are better suited to strong
safeties and middle linebackers than small forwards and shooting
guards.
</P>
<P>
   And without you-know-who around to satisfy our craving for
basketball perfection, the problems have become more glaring than
all of Broadway's klieg lights.
</P>
<P>
   Even the master of the midrange fadeaway jumper, Michael Jordan,
knew how to use the bump-and-grind game to his advantage. Remember
how right before Jordan's final shot ever, Bryon Russell was first
to swoop his shoulder down low and take a swipe at Jordan? Once
Jordan knew Russell had initiated contact, Sir Air was free to swat
Russell down to the floor and launch that championship-winning
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the NBA is going to do something about all this.
</P>
<P>
   That's what members of a special NBA rules committee said
Tuesday after an all-day meeting produced a short list of
tinkerings that made it clear that the league is not happy when
players are perpetrating more incidental contact than what went
down in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have less contact. It is not intended as a knock
against the officials, but as the game has evolved, there is too
much contact away from the ball,'' NBA vice president Rod Thorn
said.
</P>
<P>
   For that, the NBA is going to introduce four rule changes, which
should get a test run in the summer leagues after their likely
approval in the next three weeks. If they fly, the changes will be
seen in the preseason and into the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Think David Stern's glamour league would mess around?
</P>
<P>
   Two of the items aren't really rules changes, just
clarifications on how games are officiated and how illegal defenses
are called.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the grabbing, holding, the impeding of progress. We're
going to take a real close look at those areas,'' NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to establish guidelines to make them more
understandable to fans, players, coaches and officials,'' Thorn
said.
</P>
<P>
   A new 14-second rule, however, will be a substantive change. Now
when a foul or violation occurs in the front court when there is
less than 14 seconds on the clock, the shot clock will be recycled
only to 14 seconds, not all the way back to 24 seconds. That
includes kicked balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could result in four or five more possessions during the
course of a game,'' Thorn said.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference could come from a new 5-second rule,
one that will prevent players from eating the clock as they back
their man down in the post.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to know what to call this rule. The Charles Barkley
Ordinance. The Gary Payton Clampdown. The Patrick Ewing
Annihilator.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all NBA teams have resorted to this primary offensive
mode in which your best post player relentlessly backs down his
defender until he either draws the double team or gets off a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be three or four guys were involved in the offense.
Now it's down to two,'' Spurs reserve Jerome Kersey said. ``Now
you've got a lot of people standing around and watching. I like to
be part of the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Kersey isn't the only one sick of this scenario. This two-man
game has driven fans to fits of boredom, because other than the
pass out of the double-team for the outside or weak-side shot,
offense has stagnated with the lack of cutting and passing.
</P>
<P>
   All of these items are not necessarily designed to upgrade the
league's scoring average, which at 91 points per game is lower than
anytime since the introduction of the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about how the game looks and having to address that.
This wasn't a mandate to increase scoring, but if the game looks a
little better, then that's what we're after,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   While this post-Jordan era has dawned on a thuggish, low-scoring
day, there are a few players who understand the game is best played
when it flows like art.
</P>
<P>
   Slippery, confident, skilled Allan Houston is one such shining
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like (Walt) Frazier, (Earl) Monroe, Oscar Robertson,
those guys lived off the midrange jumper because it was something
no one could do anything about,'' Houston said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the NBA wants to do something about making sure shooters
like Houston have room to operate. If the rule changes are
successful, the NBA then will have to make sure enough of its
players actually can shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
