<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABBOTT RETURNING TO FACE RANGERS ON FRIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Paul Abbott, back from knee surgery after a winter
ball injury, will be recalled from Tacoma and start on the mound
Friday night for the Mariners against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, 31, made two recent starts in Class AAA, going 1-1 with
a 6.43 earned run average. In 14 innings, the obviously rusty
right-hander gave up 21 hits, but struck out 10 and walked just
four. He last pitched Sunday against Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think right now, preparation-wise, he's about
three-quarters of the way through spring training,'' Mariners
manager Lou Piniella said. ``His velocity is there. His stuff was
better this start. His breaking ball was better.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was 3-1 with a 4.01 ERA in four late-season starts for
the Mariners in 1998, earning Piniella's favor.
</P>
<P>
   STAR IS BORN: When we last saw her, Tina Mares was diving for
groundballs, grabbing more ESPN-TV airtime than the baseball team
that employs her.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners ballgirl since has recovered from three deep
Astroturf abrasions _ one on each knee, a third under her right eye
_ she received while stretching out for a hard-hit ball in
third-base foul territory on June 13 at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   However, the attention showered on her because of her aggressive
approach to her job has barely slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Mares, 18, will fly to Miami this weekend to be interviewed by
Univision, a major Spanish-speaking station. This comes after two
days of nonstop ESPN-TV replays; newspaper and radio interviews,
including one with ESPN radio; and being the subject of countless
``Plays of the Night'' TV features.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never got this much attention before,'' said Mares, who
graduated from Inglemoor High School last week, her school the last
to hold its closing ceremonies at the ill-fated Kingdome. ``But I'm
keeping my feet on the ground, my head out of the clouds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mares is one of 10 Mariner ballgirls who rotate through each
home-stand as well as perform a host of duties, such as escorting
the Mariner Moose through the stands, babysitting children in the
players' wives' lounge, handing out promotional items and
supervising the speed pitch machine.
</P>
<P>
   To become a Mariners ballgirl, Mares, now in her second season
on the job, had to work one year in another capacity for the
Mariners, then attend a tryout. Each candidate was given 15
groundballs of varying difficulty and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Mares answered a flier she spotted at school. She played soccer
and basketball growing up, but her interest in the Mariners grew
after the club's 1995 playoff run and the emergence of shortstop
Alex Rodriguez drew her.
</P>
<P>
   The teen has never met Rodriguez, but she played catch with
third baseman Russ Davis before a game. Bullpen coach Matt Sinatro,
reliever Frankie Rodriguez and former Mariners reliever Mac Suzuki
rushed to her aid after she received turf burns on her diving
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You took a hit,''' Sinatro said. ``I liked her. She
was a nice girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Mares, who will attend the University of Washington in the fall,
said her approach to her job is all reflex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basic instinct,'' she said. ``I saw the ball coming
really fast and I knew I couldn't get it in a regular position. I
just dove for it. I didn't get it, but it was OK. I heard loud
cheers. And I saw myself on Diamondvision, and that was pretty
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   BONE DRY: Mariner right fielder Jay Buhner, on the disabled list
with a pulled hamstring since May 19, has been pushed back another
week, meaning he likely won't play in the Kingdome again. Buhner
underwent a magnetic resonance imaging test Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we'd have him this time,'' Piniella said. ``We're
not exactly sure now. It could be a week.''
</P>
<P>
   SEGUI SORE: Mariner first baseman David Segui strained his left
knee during Monday's 4-3, 12-inning loss at Cleveland and sat out
Tuesday night's game. Piniella said Segui's condition would be
evaluated daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
