<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EXEC-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DAD, A WEEK OF FAMILY PROGRAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What inspired Josh Sapan, a media mogul with the
unlikely distinction of being both tall and modest, to make the
normally competitive leaders of 66 cable networks play nicely in
the sandbox together, and agree to schedule family-friendly
programs in prime-time hours this week?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the feel-good memory of watching shows like ``Bonanza''
and ``McHale's Navy'' with his father?
</P>
<P>
   The feel-lousy memory of a 14-year-old sitting in an East
Village theater, watching his mother in LeRoi Jones' bloody play
about racial warfare, ``The Slave''?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it Rep. Henry Hyde?
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, with legislation that was ultimately voted down,
Hyde, the Illinois Republican, became the latest politician eager
to blame graphic entertainment for violent outbursts in young
people. How very nice for Sapan, the chief executive of Rainbow
Media, a large programming company, that the cable industry's third
annual ``Tune In to Kids and Family Week'' kicked off on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, at least 23 of the networks, including the
Disney Channel, Nickelodeon and the USA Network, featured the same
starting-gun show, a frank discussion among children and their
families about hurtful, offensive language and actions.
</P>
<P>
   The participating networks agreed to schedule at least a
half-hour of family programming one night this week. Most have
arranged more, with some 650 hours of such shows available. Of
course, one network's definition of what's fun for the whole family
will be different from another's, which is exactly the point that
Sapan wants to convey.
</P>
<P>
   For, typical of many of his projects, the week has both
higher-minded and bottom-line incentives. Three years ago, Sapan,
the father of two young children as well as the Big Boss of 15
channels, including American Movie Classics, Bravo, the News 12
networks and seven regional sports networks around the country,
cooked up the cooperative week so that an array of cable networks
could promote their family fare with a united boost.
</P>
<P>
   The week would provoke parents to be more active, critical
viewers with their children, Sapan reasoned, and would also be a
tonic for the industry's rambunctious image.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're subject to a lot of controversy,'' said Tom Rogers, the
president of NBC cable, which owns 25 percent of Rainbow, a
subsidiary of Cablevision. ``And Josh has taken on an awful lot of
our big, white-hat efforts.'' (For the family week this year, Sapan
was joined by the heads of Nickelodeon and the Fox Family Channel.)
</P>
<P>
   And for Sapan, a man colleagues describe as ``not your typical
TV executive'' _ they mean that as a compliment _ the week has yet
another veiled purpose: Let the media demonstrate that they can
produce and identify G-rated entertainment so Congress won't insist
on taking a development meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Striking the balance between concerns over the media's effects
on public behavior and First Amendment protections ``is not a
simple thing,'' Sapan said Tuesday at a Manhattan studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a full awareness of legislative initiatives, and it's
part of our concern to avoid censorship,'' said Sapan, who is also
chairman of the executive committee of People for the American Way,
a liberal policy and litigating group.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his standing in the cable industry as a voice of
social awareness, he said, without sounding self-important, ``It's
quite worthwhile, in the community in which one lives, to watch out
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapan, a 48-year-old New Yorker, came by his political
earnestness and his near-lifelong fascination with TV the
old-fashioned way: Mom and Dad. His mother, who hated television,
was an Off-Off Broadway actress with leftist convictions (his
children call their grandmother ``LaMama''). His father, who loved
television, made commercials and, said his son, wrote gems like
``Ask the man for Ballantine!'' and ``Kiss your clothes with
Softness.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the son, a University of Wisconsin graduate who started his
media empire by renting halls around the Midwest and driving to
them in a station wagon packed with a projector and art-house
films, turned out to be an enlightened capitalist who can utter
``commercial environment'' and ``sincere'' in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Let us not kid ourselves: Sapan wanted to howl with the big
broadcast dogs as much as the next would-be mogul. But reading a
book that predicted the proliferation of diverse, local
programming, as well as not being able to get a network job, pushed
him toward the nascent cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   He is known there for ``niche'' programming, which addresses a
distinct region or interest. In recent years, Rainbow launched the
Independent Film Channel and started producing independent films
and a trio of Metro channels offering events and shopping guides,
weather and traffic, and education and home entertainment programs,
fine-tuned for the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   Sapan, married to Ann Foley, an executive at Showtime, which is
also participating in family week programming, said they allow
their 3-year-old and 5-year-old to watch about an hour and a half
of television a day. But like many parents, they are not enamored
of the scheduling and some of the content of children's shows. So
their children see tapes, rather than shows fresh off the screen.
``That way, the programming is more in our control,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
