<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-OVERSIGHT-NYT     06-23 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-OVERSIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONGER OVERSIGHT OF MUTUAL FUNDS IS SOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mutual fund industry's leading trade group is expected to
recommend sweeping new rules to strengthen independent directors'
oversight of funds, going beyond earlier proposals by Securities
and Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   If widely adopted by the industry, the changes would represent a
victory for Levitt, who in the last year has made strengthening the
authority of independent mutual fund directors a top priority. In
February, he was host at a discussion in Washington, at which
leading industry executives explored ways to increase the
effectiveness of fund boards.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said Tuesday that while many of the 15
proposals were already in practice at larger fund families, they
thought they could prompt many smaller companies to change the way
they operate.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations, by a special committee of the Investment
Company Institute, would require independent directors to meet
alone _ not with those also employed by the advisory firm that runs
the fund _ to consider many of the most important decisions about
the fund, such as whom to hire as investment adviser and what their
pay should be.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations would also require that only independent
directors sit on audit committees; that they be able to hire their
own lawyers, and that they have insurance policies or
indemnification agreements with the fund so they do not have to
worry about paying costs of any lawsuits or proxy fights out of
their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also recommended that independent directors make
up at least two-thirds of a fund's board _ up from the current 40
percent _ and that anyone who worked for a fund's investment
adviser be prohibited from ever serving as an independent director
of that fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's the smaller fund groups where you'll find
that these things won't be as prevalent and where they'll have to
consider making some changes,'' said John Hill, an independent
director and vice chairman of the board that oversees all of Putnam
Investments' funds.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who is also vice chairman of First Reserve Corp., a
Greenwich, Conn., investment firm, said he thought that the 10
largest fund families already tracked most, if not all, the
practices recommended. ``Generally, I think it sounds like a very
good list,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other recommendations expected from the institute Thursday would
call for these steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Require independent directors to set all directors' pay, which
has become a controversial issue as annual pay for many directors
now exceeds $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require independent directors to be self-nominating, which
Levitt had already proposed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require greater disclosure of directors' relationships with
the fund's adviser.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eliminate separate boards for each fund within a family,
placing multiple funds under one board.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the proposals tackle nearly every issue that Levitt had
addressed, either in a formal proposal or by suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   While the trade group's recommendations are only that _ and not
binding on any company _ past proposals by the Investment Company
Institute on fund-company regulations have generally won widespread
acceptance in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt's attention to the issue follows several difficult years
for independent directors. Some have become embroiled in costly
suits and proxy fights after they challenged the way the funds were
being run. Indeed, in recent years the SEC has been criticized for
failing to come to the aid of independent directors in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   But while the SEC regulates the mutual fund industry, it is
limited in imposing new requirements without legislation, and thus
the commissioners often use their positions to try to persuade the
industry to voluntarily adopt changes.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Levitt and other SEC officials declined to
comment Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
