<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICS RALLY TO BEAT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The American League West-leading Rangers
began defense of that position with a thud.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland _ who inherited a one-run, ninth-inning
lead _ surrendered four consecutive base hits, including Miguel
Tejada's game-winning, two-run triple as Oakland rallied for a 5-3
victory last night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Athletics within three games of the
Rangers, who departed with a bitter taste in their mouths after the
first of 15 consecutive games against division opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was feeling for everything the first few
hitters,'' Wetteland said. ``My breaking stuff wasn't as sharp or
close to where I wanted to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland converted a major-league-best 23 saves in 25
opportunities before last night. Oakland manager Art Howe called on
Tim Raines and Mike Macfarlane to pinch hit, and the two greeted
Wetteland with consecutive singles.
</P>
<P>
   Raines scored on an ensuing single by Tony Phillips, and Tejada
drove a 1-2 slider into the gap in left-center field, scoring
Macfarlane and Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had a tougher time getting started tonight,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``He was getting his breaking ball up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers attempted to rally in the bottom of the inning, as
catcher Ivan Rodriguez led off with a single against Oakland closer
Billy Taylor, then Rusty Greer walked.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez then lined a pitch into the gap in
left-center field, but Phillips chased it down and made a diving,
back-handed catch to rob the Rangers of what appeared would be a
game-tying, extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, it resulted in a double play when Greer
passed Rodriguez on the base paths between second and third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if I did it textbook, I should have gotten to second
and stopped and looked,'' Greer said. ``But when it left Juan's
bat, I didn't think anyone had a chance of catching it. I was
thinking, `Score,' as soon as it left the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics' late-inning heroics negated those of left-hander
Mike Venafro, who pitched 2 2/3 scoreless innings in relief of
right-hander Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro served as the bridge to right-hander Jeff Zimmerman, who
recorded the final out of the eighth inning before leaving the
outcome in Wetteland's hands. Wetteland's failure was the bullpen's
first loss in 15 decisions since Wetteland failed to convert a save
April 27 against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take my chances,'' Oates said, ``with three outs to go
and Wetteland on the mound any day of the week.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
