A6077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LENDER-VIOLATIONS-     06-23 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LENDER-VIOLATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME LENDER AGREES TO STOP PRACTICES SKIRTING CIVIL RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The biggest home-equity loan company in the state
agreed Tuesday to settle a lawsuit that state Attorney General
Eliot Spitzer had threatened to file accusing the company of
violating the civil rights of thousands of minority residents in
Brooklyn and Queens by enticing them into loans they could not
afford.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer had planned to file suit Wednesday in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn against the lender, Delta Funding Corp. of
Woodbury, which handles more than $1 billion in loans in New York
and 21 other states.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators said the five-month inquiry found that the
company violated a civil rights law that was enacted in the 1970s
at a time when big banks were red-lining troubled minority
neighborhoods. In this case, they said, Delta was doing the
reverse: blanketing minority neighborhoods in New York with offers
for loans and giving credit to people who did not need it, with
terms prohibited by federal lending laws.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks of settlement negotiations fell apart this week.
But after Spitzer indicated he was preparing to file suit, Delta
agreed in principle in last-minute talks Tuesday evening to end
several practices that the attorney general said violated lending
laws and discriminated against minorities, officials with Spitzer's
office said.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging of these practices, they said, was providing
loans to people based not on their ability to pay but solely on the
equity in their homes. Delta also agreed to end a practice known as
flipping, or refinancing its own loans to defaulting borrowers and
assessing high fees in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The company will provide $6 million to restructure loans of
borrowers whom the attorney general contends have been mistreated,
and it has agreed not to move forward immediately with imminent
evictions. The company also agreed that for the next three years it
will open its books to the scrutiny of a neutral monitor, who will
report to a federal judge in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we got the type of remedial agreement that we
think will change the entire industry,'' Spitzer said. ``Now we can
go to everybody else and say, this is the standard we expect you to
meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts on high-interest lending called the inquiry into Delta
one of the largest civil rights cases ever pursued against such a
lender. While dozens of states have sued high-interest lenders
during the last several years as the industry has mushroomed, most
have focused narrowly on lending and usury laws and not on the
wider effects on poor minority neighborhoods, where most of the
lending is concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators with the attorney general's office said that most
borrowers in the Delta cases they reviewed were elderly. The loans
drained equity they had built up over decades in their homes and
led to ``extreme financial privations'' for many, who lived without
utilities or skipped meals to meet loan payments, investigators
added. In the worst cases, the loans led to foreclosures and
evictions.
</P>
<P>
   Delta admitted no wrongdoing as a part of the settlement, but in
agreeing to stop many of its practices and submit to such close
scrutiny of its competitive business it in effect conceded to most
of the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement Tuesday, Delta officials said they hoped
to ``lead the industry in implementing `best practices' for lending
which go well beyond any federal or state law requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   The average value of the Delta loans examined was about
$100,000, and the attorney general's inquiry looked at loans over
the last three years. A statute of limitations prevents action on
bad loans originating before that time.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the interest on the loans was as high as 14
percent and fees could be as much as 10 percent of the loan value.
Investigators from the attorney general's office said that in as
many as 15 percent of the loans they reviewed, Delta charged a
punitive interest _ which could be as high as 24 percent _ if a
borrower defaulted, a practice that is prohibited by a federal
lending law.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the hallmarks of Delta's lending practices
were high-pressure sales tactics that prompted many borrowers to
take out bigger loans than they intended. Sometimes, without the
knowledge of borrowers, their unsecured debts _ such as credit card
bills, unpaid parking tickets and even city liens for welfare
repayments _ were lumped into the loans and secured against their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, investigators said, the Delta loans replaced
previous mortgages with easy terms that were almost paid off,
greatly increasing borrowers' monthly payments while leaving them
with little cash from the new loan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
