<HEADLINE>
FINLEY WAVERS ON TRADE ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE -- Pitcher Chuck Finley hasn't run to management
offering to waive his 10-and-5 status as a player. But when asked
if that meant he he definitely wanted to remain an Angel, he said:
``I didn't say that, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Players with at least 10 years of major league experience, the
past five with the same team, have a right to refuse a trade. There
have been reports recently that Finley would waive his 10-and-5
status to be traded to a contender so the Angels could acquire
prospects. That is, assuming the Angels are out of the race by
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start any of that,'' Finley said. ``Peter Gammons did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gammons is a national baseball writer for the Boston Globe and a
baseball analyst for ESPN. Finley, though, wouldn't say Gammons was
entirely wrong. Finley, who is a free agent at season's end, has
spent his entire career with the Angels, but hasn't played in the
playoffs since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Finley doesn't want to be perceived as someone eager to
abandon ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be the first guy to jump overboard after the
first leak in the boat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck is a real good guy,'' general manager Bill Bavasi said.
``He's not just concerned about Chuck. He's always been a good team
player. I'll sit down with Chuck when he gets back (from Seattle)
and we'll talk about it. His heart's always in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi said other trades are always possible, but he doesn't
want to give up on what the organization has tried to put together
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The club you see right now is not the club we want to see,''
Bavasi said. ``But if we make wholesale changes, we might not have
the club we want when everybody comes back (from injuries).''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game against the Mariners was the Angels' first of 15
in row against A.L. West opponenents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time we have to make things happen,'' manager Terry
Collins said. ``You can talk a lot about interleague play, and
games we just played in Toronto and New York, but it's time to get
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game at the Kingdome marked the first game of the
stadium's final homestand. After three against the Angels, the
Mariners play three against the Rangers. Then they go on a road
trip that will take them into the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' first game at Safeco Field will be July 15 against
the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' game Saturday against the Oakland A's at Edison
Field is being promoted as ``Turn ahead the clock'' night. Both
teams will wear futuristic uniforms and Edison Field will be
enchanced to give fans a look of baseball in the year 2021.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Mariners play the second game of their three-game
series tonight beginning at 7:35. Ken Hill (3-6, 4.76 ERA) will
start for Anaheim against Seattle's John Halama (5-2, 3.79).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
