r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR &LR;      06-23 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALK KILLING CASE GOING TO JURY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It's a trial that's had the city and nation talking
for months. But Wednesday a Maricopa County Superior Court jury
begins the only discussion that matters about Scott Falater's
sleepwalking murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides finished presenting testimony Tuesday. Wednesday, the
prosecution and defense are set to begin their closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Then the jury will start deciding the fate of Falater, who
claims he was sleepwalking on Jan. 16, 1997, when he stabbed his
wife 44 times and dragged her into the backyard swimming pool and
held her under the water.
</P>
<P>
   His attorneys say the mild-mannered electrical engineer had no
motive for killing his wife of 20 years, and the mother of his two
children.
</P>
<P>
   They contend a sleepwalking Falater went outside to fix a pool
pump using a hunting knife when his wife touched him, sending him
into a violent rage.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Falater intentionally killed his wife. They are
seeking the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ronald Reinstein decided Tuesday to give the jurors the
option of finding Falater, 43, guilty of second-degree murder
instead of first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   For a second-degree murder conviction, the jury must find
Falater killed his wife ``by conduct which he knew would cause
death or serious physical injury,'' according to written jury
instructions released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A first-degree murder conviction would require the jury to
additionally find the murder was premeditated, the jury instruc
tions say.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of first-degree murder, Fala ter could be sentenced
to death. Second-degree murder carries a sentence of 10 to 20 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys wanted Reinstein to tell the jury that it is
the state's job to prove that Falater was not sleepwalking when he
killed his wife. Reinstein refused.
</P>
<P>
   The final day's testimony focused on Yarmila's missing wedding
ring.
</P>
<P>
   The state has hinted at trouble in the marriage, including
disputes over Scott Falater wanting more children, and Yarmila
Falater's waning dedication to the couple's Mormon faith.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy County Attorney Juan Martinez showed jurors close-up
photos of Yarmila Falater's hand, zeroing in on the white line
marking her absent wedding ring.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Chapman, the police de tective who led the investigation
of the murder, said he looked for the ring around the home's
kitchen and bathroom sinks, but didn't find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial thought was maybe this could have been a robbery,''
Chapman said. ``And when an individual has two gold bracelets on
her, but yet she's missing a wedding band set, it just struck me
odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, sleep expert Mark Pressman answered jurors'
questions, read aloud by Judge Reinstein. One asked Pressman, who
directs two sleep clinics in suburban Philadelphia, why he was so
sure Falater was awake.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman gave a laundry list of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   He started with the fact Falater was dressed to ward off the
winter night's chill, wore his contact lenses and grabbed a
flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That all sounds like preparation for going outside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman also said Falater re turned to the body twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second time he came back, he was putting on gloves,''
Press man said, ``and the act of putting on the gloves is
absolutely unlike anything a sleepwalker would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressman said the way Falater dragged his wife into the pool
also showed advanced planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, he concealed all of the evidence,'' Pressman said.
</P>
<P>
   After the murder, Falater put the bloody knife and his
splattered clothes in the spare tire well of his car, according to
court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think hiding evidence,'' Press man said, ``is something that
a sleepwalker just wouldn't do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
