NYT-06-23-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6092 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-SPARKS-COMETS-HNS     06-23 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles coach Orlando Woolridge on Tuesday morning anxiously
approached the Sparks' first meeting with the Comets, calling it a
barometer to determine where his vastly improved team stood in the
early part of the WNBA season.
</P>
<P>
   He found out the Sparks are capable of fighting on even terms
with the two-time defending league champions.
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge also learned there's still a difference between the
Western Division opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, after letting a 12-point second-half lead slip from
their grasp under a heavy assault from former American Basketball
League standout DeLisha Milton and Mwadi Mabika, held the Sparks
scoreless in the final 2:34 and came away with an 84-76 victory
before 10,479 at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that an unbelievable game for television?'' coach Van
Chancellor asked, after the Comets (5-0) matched their best start
in franchise history in a game televised nationally by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   So unbelievable, perhaps, that Chancellor brought a Bible
someone had given him to the postgame news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody gave it to me tonight, and I wanted to make sure I
didn't lose it,'' he said. ``But my thinking is, when you win one
like this, you're always going to be thankful. The Lord blessed
you. If you're not thankful, something's wrong with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor could be thankful for another stellar showing by
Cynthia Cooper, who on Monday was named the league's Player of the
Week.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper made 13 of 14 free throws and scored a season-high 36
points against a Sparks defense that was surprisingly strong for
most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor also could be thankful for Tina Thompson's 11 points
and strong defensive play on Sparks center Lisa Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   There was room to give thanks for the play of Polina Tzekova and
Tammy Jackson, who were a productive force in the middle for the
Comets in the absence of Monica Lamb, who was hurt during the
morning shootaround and had to be hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   And in the final 1:23, with the Sparks (3-3) desperately trying
to fire in 3-pointers, Sheryl Swoopes blocked two shots and
Thompson blocked one.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' tandem of Mabika and Milton combined for eight
offensive rebounds as the Sparks battled back from a 65-53 deficit
with 11:59 to play.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a fast-break layup by Tamecka Dixon, the 1997 Player
of the Year in the Big 12 at Kansas, that gave the Sparks a 74-73
lead with 3:41 left and threatened the Comets' superiority as the
last undefeated team in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   That could have been the final straw on a day filled with
traumatic moments for the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb's status remains uncertain. And the appearance of point
guard Kim Perrot at halftime to receive her 1998 championship ring
was a deeply emotional moment for everyone present.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gone through so many emotions today,'' said
Chancellor. ``When Monica went down, that put us all down in the
dumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then Kim comes out to get her ring, I thought that drained
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go behind by a point; we can't stop them. But some way,
somehow, we find a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The early part of the game was just what might be expected from
two teams predicted to fight it out for the West crown.
</P>
<P>
   There were nine ties before a minor skirmish between Swoopes and
Leslie underneath the Sparks' basket just before halftime seemed to
fire up the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes and Leslie were each assessed a technical foul. Swoopes,
who had been fouled by reserve La'Keshia Frett before the shoving
incident, missed both free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But a 6-2 spurt, with Cooper making two free throws, Thompson a
layup and Swoopes a fast-break layup after a steal, resulted in a
46-39 halftime lead for the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to determine that from the scoreboard, which briefly
went haywire.
</P>
<P>
   And with the public-address announcer keeping track of the
running score aloud to start the second half, the Comets used six
straight points by Cooper and a 3-pointer by reserve Janeth Arcain
to take a 57-47 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It twice grew to 12 points, the final time at 65-53, before the
Sparks began to do some damage of their own.
</P>
<P>
   They held the Comets scoreless for almost four minutes, forcing
them into three turnovers, then used three straight points by
Milton (13 points, 12 rebounds) and one of two free throws by
Mabika (16 points, seven rebounds) to pull to within 69-68.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting a tough game from Los Angeles,'' said
Cooper. ``They're a tough team to play, no matter where you play
them, because they're so talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we were definitely looking for a tough game.''
</P>
<P>
   The basket by Dixon gave the Sparks a short-lived lead. But when
Thompson missed from 3-point range, Swoopes' follow shot regained
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes came away with a steal and another fast-break layup to
make it 77-74. After Leslie (a team-high 19 points) connected from
the lane to make it 77-76, Cooper's floating layup over the
oustretched arms of Leslie provided a 79-76 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson then blocked a 3-point try by Leslie. Swoopes followed
with a block of a try by Mabika, then seconds later slapped a
would-be trey from rookie guard Ukari Figgs of Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Just for good measure, Swoopes, with the clock running out,
thwarted a 3-point attempt by Dixon. Swoopes got the rebound, and
the Comets had the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been happy with the way we had played to this point,''
said Woolridge. ``We wanted to use this game with the champions to
see where we stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we won, that would be good. If not, it will be a learning
experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
