<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-SUBURBS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE WASHINGTON STATE TOWNS MAKE LIST OF WEALTHIEST PLACES TO
LIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ An elderly Medina couple have finally decided to sell
their tiny two-bedroom home that's endured more than 80 soggy
winters.
</P>
<P>
   But they're hardly delighted with the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Not because they're losing a place where they shared decades of
memories. Or because they know the buyer will simply tear it down.
</P>
<P>
   It's the $325,000 list price. They simply thought, their real
estate agent said, that they could get far more in Medina.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to one of the country's top 250 wealthiest towns.
</P>
<P>
   Five Northwest towns made Worth magazine's 1999 list, ranked by
median home prices. All are in Washington and all but one, Woodway,
are on the Eastside.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agents who sell multimillion-dollar mansions in the
48th-richest U.S. town of Medina, 50th-ranked Yarrow Point,
110th-ranked Clyde Hill or 157th-ranked Mercer Island aren't the
least bit surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Microsoft and Amazon.com have turned affluent
waterfront communities into Meccas for some of the country's
wealthiest people. Gita Ansari, an Eastside Windermere Real Estate
agent who specializes in waterfront property, says billionaires are
now buying posh homes that millionaires could only dream of.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some people, five, 10, 20 million dollars is not a big
amount _ they just want the best,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no shortage of opulent choices. Dozens of homes are
listed at more than $1 million on the Eastside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the strength of the high-tech industry may be the most
important driving factor in the high-end market right now,'' said
Kory Bockman, an economist for the National Association of
Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Plush stock options and bonuses offered by companies are
creating a new phenomenon: An increasing number of people are
paying for high-end homes with cash.
</P>
<P>
   Medina, which moved up from last year's 92nd-richest town
ranking, has long been known for considerable wealth and monstrous
houses, trends emphasized by the 40,000-square-foot mega-mansion of
Microsoft founder Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly a dozen houses now for sale in Medina are listed at
prices topping $1 million, according to the Northwest Multiple
Listing Service. In Clyde Hill, there are seven. On Mercer Island,
22 on-the-market homes surpass the $1 million dollar mark.
</P>
<P>
   One _ a 9,000-square-foot two-story with gold-plated bathroom
fixtures, a $125,000 chandelier and a view of Seattle's skyline at
sunset _ is the largest, priciest house ever for sale on the
island, according to Ansari, the agent. Its owners, a couple with a
grown son who lives with them and another in college, simply ``want
to buy something bigger,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ansari notes that many people who sell their large homes don't
go far _ many end up trading their mansion for another one in
another affluent Eastside town.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agents say these communities are appealing to the
wealthy because of seclusion and prestige.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute you get into Clyde Hill, you feel like you're not
in the hustle-and-bustle of Bellevue or the crammed-in feel of
Redmond,'' said Thuan Howard, a John L. Scott Real Estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in a little, peaceful enclave _ you don't go through
Medina to go anywhere,'' said Windermere agent Laurie Hope, who is
selling the 1917 Medina house for its elderly owners so they can
move into a retirement home. ``And, quite frankly, it's the brand
name.''
</P>
<P>
   In Yarrow Point, a tiny peninsula town that catapulted in one
year from 195th to 50th on the Worth list, none of roughly 400
houses were listed for sale Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were any listed in Woodway, a small town off the southern
tip of Edmonds (although agents occasionally list Woodway homes
under the more-familiar heading of Edmonds). Woodway dropped to
103rd on this year's Worth list, after reaching 65th last year.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 on the list is Jupiter Island, Fla., an exclusive island
of 601 people where a one-acre plot of land with 150 feet of
waterfront can fetch up to $3 million. Its median home sales price
was $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 California towns also made the list, as did many
upscale communities in New York and New Jersey. Aspen, Colo.,
ranked second, dropping from first place last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, people are buying houses as never before: 1998 was a
record year for existing-home sales; some 4.78 million houses
changed hands, according to the National Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   The West showed the greatest year-to-year existing-home-price
appreciation: 7.23 percent, according to association's data.
</P>
<P>
   After a record-breaking year of home sales, the real estate
market shows few signs of slowing down. Nationally, says Bockman,
``our numbers are actually coming out ahead of where we were last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from Worth magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
