<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPT-KIDS-AS-PARENTS-A     06-23 2989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-KIDS-AS-PARENTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH KIDS, FULL SCHEDULE GETS FULLER  
 GROWING NUMBERS FACE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Intimidating ponderosa pines frame Camp Tontozona, but
they do not shield Willie Daniel from his reality. Despite the
horns, whistles and helmet-to-shoulder thuds, the Arizona State
safety hears one gentle sound loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ````Daddy.''''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel's interaction with his 1-year-old son, Tristen, at the
Sun Devils' preseason camp last August was a moving snapshot, but
it told only one side of a complicated story. A wide-angle lens on
the athletic landscape of Arizona's high schools and universities
reveals a growing number of players with children.
</P>
<P>
   An already challenging situation _ early parenthood _ is
compounded by the demands of athletics. And it affects everything
and everyone it touches, from the program to the player to the
offspring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough to go to school and play football,'' ASU
Coach Bruce Snyder said. ``You add anything else, any hardship, and
it makes life more complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   How widespread is early parenthood?
</P>
<P>
   An informal survey by ``The Arizona Republic'' found 18 athletes
on last season's Arizona and Arizona State football rosters who
acknowledge fathering children. Five were married or were
subsequently married; two dropped out of school, in part because of
their added responsibilities; and at least one has been taken to
court for child support.
</P>
<P>
   High school athletes with children are also common in Arizona.
Although no records are kept, the high numbers likely reflect
reality in a state that, while making inroads, still ranks fourth
in the nation in teen pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here. I'm alive. I'm surviving,'' said Kisha White, a
senior on the ASU's women's basketball team last season who has a
4-year-old son. ``But there were times I was crying behind closed
doors. There was a two- or three-month period I felt like giving
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Their worlds blur.
</P>
<P>
   Timeout becomes a disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   Dribbling implies the need for a bib.
</P>
<P>
   A sweep is something to do after the Cheerios have been dumped
for the 15th time.
</P>
<P>
   Real life invades sports as young men and women try to juggle
athletics, academics and parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had players miss practice to be in the delivery room,''
ASU assistant football coach Robin Pflugrad said. ``I don't know if
the numbers are greater, but it sure seems like the last five, six
years it has become more prevalent.''
</P>
<P>
   So have the questions. From where comes the financial support?
Who takes care of the children? How willing to adjust are schools
and athletic programs? How is the athlete's future affected? &QL; 
The price to pay
</P>
<P>
   Although Nichole Myers had been dating ASU safety Mitchell
Freedman for more than a year, when she found out in 1997 that she
was pregnant, ``it was a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I didn't want to be real old to have kids, but I
was nervous,'' she said. ``Where am I going to stay? How will I
support him? What about baby-sitting?''
</P>
<P>
   When Mitchell Freedman Jr. was born in November 1997, near the
end of Freedman's junior season, reality hit. After tuition and
fees, a full in-state scholarship at ASU leaves approximately
$3,050 for room and board. Divide that by nine school months, and
$339 a month for rent, food and baby necessities doesn't go very
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scholarship was not meant for more than one person,''
Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, who was 20 when she found out she was pregnant, was
determined to make it work. She knew that because of Freedman's
academic and athletic demands, the brunt of child rearing and
financial support would fall on her. She had been there before for
Freedman's hard times _ academic and financial _ and she believed
they could weather this challenge as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the one who kept me out of trouble, watched over me,
helped me out,'' Freedman said. ``When I was in college, she helped
support me. I owe everything in the world to her.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been easy. Myers wakes up at 5 a.m., loads her
sleeping son into the car, drops him off at Freedman's sister's
home in Phoenix and ends her 30-plus-mile drive at a Tempe Bank of
America, where she works in the legal department, by 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   As with many of the parents interviewed for this story, family
members have made the process easier.
</P>
<P>
   Myers and her son live with Myers' mother, stepfather and
siblings in a comfortable home. Family members from both sides have
helped with child care.
</P>
<P>
   Myers' salary from the bank takes care of most of her son's
expenses while Freedman participates in training camp with the
NFL's Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is, he knows who his daddy is,'' said Freedman,
who signed with Oakland as an undrafted free agent. ``It's hard
financially, and during school I didn't have much. I wanted to give
my son the whole world. We managed, had to budget a lot of stuff.
The main thing is we stay together as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers and Freedman are still together, and Freedman makes
frequent trips to Myers' house to see his son. He said he hopes for
a future in the NFL that will allow him to be a greater contributor
to his son's needs and envisions settling down with Myers
permanently in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be someone spreading children around,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Myers is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he isn't here, he wants to be here,'' Myers said. ``I've
pretty much said, `OK, just be here as fast as you can.' Although
his son comes first, I know football is his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has it been worth it? Yes. It's stopped me from going out,
going to parties, drinking, whatever people are doing. Nowadays
they're getting into really bad trouble. Sometimes I miss it, but
then I think about my baby. He needs me first.'' &QL; 
Bumps in the road &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is able to juggle the demands of parenthood. Two of
ASU's key players heading into the 1998 season, linebacker Larry
Johnson and running back Marlon Farlow, never made it back to the
program. While academic ineligibility was the official reason, the
challenges both faced in trying to be good fathers weighed
significantly into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   Both declined to comment for this story, but Johnson, in a
previous interview with ``The Arizona Republic,'' said, ``The
demands of everything, school, family, got to be too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's son, Elijah, who was born after the player's sophomore
season, is now an upbeat 2-year-old with an attentive father and
mother who are both actively involved in raising him. &QL; 
Angels in the backfield &QL; 
Willie Daniel was a standout athlete at St. Mary's High School when
he learned that his girlfriend, Leah Vance, a Xavier student, was
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked, nervous, in awe and scared. ``Really''
scared,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel's own childhood had been difficult. In his early teens,
problems at home resulted in him living in a variety of friends'
houses for several days at a time. He eventually moved in
permanently with Bill and Cindy Stine, a couple who had befriended
him several years earlier during their involvement with youth
basketball. The Stines, who are White, were particularly sensitive
to the plight of inner-city youth and had taken in Daniel's close
friend, Jacoury Houston.
</P>
<P>
   When Daniel told them his girlfriend was pregnant, they were
floored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to believe someone like Willie could be another
statistic,'' said Cindy Stine, a private investigator. ``Willie's
still in high school. Willie's the homecoming king. This doesn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Stine, a criminal defense attorney, took it hard. Although
they hadn't legally adopted Daniel, for all intents and purposes,
he was their son. He was hard on Daniel: ``You're just going to be
another statistic. You're going to have to drop out of school to
raise this child, or you're just going to walk away like all the
others do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty harsh,'' Bill Stine said. ``I was very
disappointed, very shocked. I really wasn't thinking right for a
while. I had all the normal reactions that a father would have to a
son.''
</P>
<P>
   Two promising futures looked bleak. Willie was fielding a
variety of football scholarship offers. Vance was a classroom
standout who is now on academic scholarship at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   Tristen Vance was born during the summer before Daniel's senior
year in high school. Tristen initially lived with his mother and
her family in Tempe and made frequent trips to the Stines' home in
north Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   But by last fall, when Daniel entered ASU on a football
scholarship, it seemed to make sense, for all parties, that Tristen
live with the Stines so that Daniel and Vance could focus on
school. Now almost 2, Tristen has his own room, filled with
pictures of both parents, in the Stine's new north Scottsdale home.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Leah) has got her future ahead of her, Willie's got his
future ahead of him,'' Stine said. ``We feel it's important that
they be allowed to do what they need to do to benefit Tristen in
the end. We simply feel like surrogate parents until Leah and
Willie are old enough to step in and take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, the little guy isn't going to be helped by
Willie dropping out of school and flipping hamburgers at
McDonald's. That's the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Vance and Daniel, who are no longer together, see and talk
to Tristen often. The Stines simply see their home as a temporary
one for Tristen until his parents are back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think I can describe what they are,'' Daniel
said. ``They're like guardian angels. They stepped up and wanted to
do this so that his mother and I can make a better situation for
him later on. A lot of kids do it by themselves. We're both very,
very grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the generosity of the Stines, who provide much of
Tristen's financial support, Daniel and Vance have paid a price.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel is working as a host at a Tempe restaurant this summer to
help with expenses. Free time that could be spent with friends is
often spent with Tristen instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your social life tends to deteriorate, but then again, (the
Stines) have stepped in and let me be a teenager again,'' Daniel
said. ``But I like to spend time with him anyway. He's brilliant,
he's smart, he amazes me every day. I'd give up anything for
him.'' &QL; 
Coping skills &QL; 
The challenges faced by female athletes who become parents can be
even more demanding.
</P>
<P>
   When Kisha White, then a member of the Yavapai College women's
basketball team, learned she was pregnant, she wondered if her
career was over. But after taking a year off to start raising her
son, Christopher, she was able to return to basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The former South Mountain High School student lived with
Christopher's father in Prescott, so they were able to share
responsibilities. The coaches at Yavapai welcomed her son at
practices and on road trips during the 1995-96 season, which she
said made life easier.
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest challenges came during her junior walk-on season at
ASU, when she had school, Chistopher and 30 hours of work a week at
a bank to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, even I don't know how I did it,'' White said.
``I was on borrowed time. I didn't have time for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   White, who recently completed her final season at ASU, lives
with Christopher at her mother's Phoenix home. She hopes to
continue her basketball career overseas. Although she and
Christopher's father are no longer dating, he is still a big part
of his son's life, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ASU volleyball standout Terri Cox learned she was pregnant
midway through her senior season. She opted not to tell her coach,
a decision she now regrets. She already had a sometimes tenuous
relationship with Coach Patti Snyder-Park, and Cox's sudden
decision to tone down her aggressive play added to the tension.
</P>
<P>
   Justine Spann was born May 1, 1998. Although the following
school year was tough, Cox and her boyfriend, ASU wide receiver
Creig Spann, were able to work it out. Their combined scholarship
money took care of the basics, and the support of family and
friends, who gave them enough diapers at their baby shower to last
six months, helped them through.
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that Spann had just one class during his final
semester, the fall of 1998, so he could watch the baby while Cox
was at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last semester, I was only taking two classes, but it was
the hardest time for me ever,'' Cox said. ``I was juggling school
with her, and even though Creig was there helping me, there were
times I would be doing a paper and she would want me to play with
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helped to have really supportive families, and Creig and
I have met a lot of good people that are in our lives now.''
</P>
<P>
   When the scholarship money ran out, Cox knew it was time to get
creative. While Spann is in training camp with the Oakland Raiders,
also trying to hook on as a free agent, she works as a nanny at a
home that allows her to bring her daughter. She hopes to land a job
as a volleyball coach, and the two plan to get married once they
are settled into their careers. &QL; 
Study shows mixed results
</P>
<P>
   Although research on pregnancy and young athletes is minimal,
one recent study gave high marks to female athletes and mixed
results to males. A Women's Sports Foundation study found that
female teen athletes are less than half as likely to get pregnant
as female non-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   No consistent pattern of differences emerged between male
athletes and non-athletes, although a survey of Western New York
athletes revealed that male athletes typically experience their
first sexual intercourse earlier than male non-athletes. The study
also found that African-American male athletes start earlier than
non-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when we have sex-segregated social settings, whether
it's the military, a motorcycle gang or a football team, it tends
to lead to exaggerated macho posturing, and sometimes subsequently,
parenthood,'' said Don Sabo, a professor of social science at
D'Youville College in Buffalo, N.Y., who has written several books
and studies on sexuality and athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys will do things, or say things, in order to play
up to the cultural expectation. Masculinity is more a performance
than a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of race is one experts have cautiously tried to
address. While the majority of young parents interviewed for this
story are African-American, that's in large part a reflection of
the makeup of teams. In 1997, blacks had the largest race
representation among Division I college athletes in basketball (61
percent) and football (52 percent).
</P>
<P>
   It may be a societal statement as well. According to a recent
study by the National Center for Health Statistics, 70 percent of
Black children nationwide are born to unmarried mothers. But plenty
of non-Black athletes, particularly at the professional level, have
made headlines for paternity-related issues, including Indiana
Coach Larry Bird. &QL; 
What stigma?
</P>
<P>
   The shame that used to accompany a child born out of wedlock is
all but gone, and that's certainly the case in the world of
athletics. Children often are seen waiting outside college locker
rooms after games.
</P>
<P>
   Former Arizona guard Jason Terry would talk freely about his
daughter Jasionna, and had her name tattooed on his right arm.
Former Wildcats guard Mike Bibby, now a member of the NBA's
Vancouver Grizzlies, told ``The Arizona'' ``Republic'' last year
that his son, Michael Dane, made him a better person and player.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Daniel said he's not worried about others' perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not anything I'm afraid of, or embarrassed about, or
really care if anyone thinks bad about that situation,'' he said.
``I'm young, I have a kid, things happen, but he's here now. I love
him more than life, and I don't care if anyone has a problem with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU cornerback Courtney Jackson, who does not have any children
but is friends with several teammates who do, said sometimes it's
the reputation of the female who gets involved with a male athlete
that suffers most.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's accidental, the truth is the girl may be the one
looked down upon more than the guy, just because of the
situation,'' he said. ``The perception, not to say it's fair, is
they know what you're about to have, and that's why they're doing
it.'' &QL; 
Issues for coaches
</P>
<P>
   College coaches now have to take children into account when
they're recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be very challenging recruiting someone from out of
state if they have a child or two,'' said Pflugrad, ASU's
recruiting coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   And how should missed practices be handled? Where does the coach
draw the line about a player attending to a child's needs? Does a
doctor's appointment take precedence over a practice in full pads?
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of what happened at Columbine High School, and the
message that we need to be there for our children, I think the
answer is pretty obvious,'' Arizona Coach Dick Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Jo Angelini, the executive director of the non-profit
Arizona Coalition on Adolescent Pregnancy and Parenting, would like
to see coaches at all levels become more involved in helping to
lower the percentage of teen pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that coaches can be very influential, and sports is an
arena that we need to be entering,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Professional sports has seen a need to address the dangers of
casual sex. All four major sports leagues feature rookie
orientations that include discussions about sexual responsibility.
NFL teams are involved in an initiative sponsored by the U.S.
Department of Child Services that promotes involvement by fathers
in their kids' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christopher's the greatest thing to happen to me, but if I
could have delayed it, I sure would have,'' White said. ``Having a
kid, it's hard work, and anyone who says it's not doesn't plan on
being a good parent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
