r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MICKELSON-CASSTEV     06-23 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MICKELSON-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTHING PAINS ERASE OPEN ACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Phil Mickelson is not the first golfer to play in a
major championship while nine months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   OK, ``he'' wasn't pregnant. His wife was. But Phil was
``expecting,'' and the impending birth of the couple's first child
became a national story.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson announced that if Amy went into labor during the U.S.
Open, he would withdraw immediately and fly home to Scottsdale,
even if he were leading.
</P>
<P>
   The birth of their daughter was more important to him than
winning the national championship and $625,000.
</P>
<P>
   So the Open became a race against time. After each round,
Mickelson described his birdies and bogeys. Then someone in the
press tent would raise a hand and ask about Amy. His face lighting
up, the proud father-to-be said he had just spoken with her on the
phone. Everything was fine. No change. Then Phil would begin using
words like pelvis and cervix. Some in the audience traded sidelong
glances and thought, ``This is more than I want to'' ``know''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Loss was a blessing &QL; 
Sunday, Mickelson finished second to Payne Stewart. He flew home
and slept like a baby. Every two hours he woke up and cried.
</P>
<P>
   (Insert rim shot here).
</P>
<P>
   But in public Mickelson masked his heartache with a smile. He
reminded himself this isn't the end of his career. He will have
other chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next June, we're going to have another U.S. Open,'' Mickelson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a minute,'' one reporter said, ``I thought you were going
to tell us you're going to have another ``baby.''''
</P>
<P>
   The room broke up in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Payne Stewart did Mickelson a favor. Stewart sank
a 15-foot par putt on the last hole to win his second Open. Had he
missed, the two would have played 18 more holes on Monday _ the day
Phil's daughter was born.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson vowed he would go home if called, even during a
playoff. His wife went into labor about the same time Mickelson and
Stewart would have been playing the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   What if Lefty had been leading?.
</P>
<P>
   What a story. Phil, 2 under, picks up his ball on the 10th hole,
shakes Stewart's hand and concedes the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Phil would win Father of the Year. Oprah would invite him on her
show. But for the rest of his life. the former ASU star who hasn't
won a major would have asked himself, ``What if?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What if I had stayed? Would I have won the Open?''
</P>
<P>
   Other players have had to make difficult decisions that pit
career and family. The late Dave Marr won the 1965 PGA championship
the same day his son was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way Dave was going home,'' author Dan Jenkins said fondly
of his longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Calcavecchia decided not to play in the 1989 British Open
in Scotland because his wife was expecting. Sheryl insisted he go.
That weekend she experienced contractions. ``I knew he would come
back immediately,'' Sheryl told ``The Republic,'' ``but I didn't
think there was time.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia won the British Open. Two weeks later, the couple
had its first child. In honor of Mark's victory, the parents named
her Britney Jo. &QL; 
Timing is everything &QL; 
As it turned out, Mickelson got to experience that panicky
ohmygosh-keys!-don't-worry-honey! excitement that seizes husbands
when gently informed that they probably should get to the hospital,
and soon.
</P>
<P>
   Timing, they say, is everything, and the Mickelson's first child
(due June 30) timed her arrival perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Her dad had less than 24 hours to brood over the most
disappointing day in his golf career.
</P>
<P>
   Now he doesn't have time to dwell on what happened on those last
three holes. He has a little girl who demands all his time and
attention.
</P>
<P>
   So, welcome, Amanda. Say hi to your dad. And if the day comes
when your parents ask if you would like a baby brother or sister,
tell them yes, but this time, try to make it the second week in
July, during the Greater Milwaukee Open. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
