<SLUG> BC-CAR-NOTEBOOK-ARMIJO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCK DEBUT TURNS SOUR NEAR FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Memo to  &UR; Jack Sprague from rookie  &UR; Ross  &UR; Thompson:
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the slide job, pal.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Thompson believed a top-10 finish in his NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series debut Friday at Portland, Ore., was within
grasp, someone stuck a pin in his balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Someone named Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Sprague had to flex his muscles and, unfortunately, he
got into us,'' said Thompson, referring to his NASCAR Craftsman
Truck Series debut last Friday at Portland. ``We were running fifth
for a lot of laps, then (Sprague), who was (several) laps down,
punted us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was just one of those racing deals. Someone checked
up in front of me, and I had to swerve to the inside. I clearly had
the line, but the next thing I know, I'm in the grass spinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (truck regulars) are gunfighters. Every lap it's 120
percent. Even if they're a couple laps down, they're racing for
blood. It's still extremely disappointing for me and very
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention very costly.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which wasn't major enough to force a caution flag,
apparently broke the gearbox in Thompson's RoomStore/Sealy Ford
F-150, saddling the Phoenix driver with an eventual 19th-place
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteenth place paid $7,020.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place paid $13,670.
</P>
<P>
   More than the money, however, Thompson was hoping a good finish
would entice team sponsors to ante up more dollars for more races
this season.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, Thompson's next probable start won't be until
late August.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``For never having driven a truck before, I was very
impressed,'' NASCAR official  &UR; Owen Kearns said. ``I felt like he
did a heck of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, however, could be  &UR; Richard Petty and it still wouldn't
matter without a major sponsor to help fund the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we can attract some more sponsors, we'll be sitting out
for a couple of months,'' said Thompson, who has one top-10 finish
in three NASCAR Winston West series starts this season for owner
Dan Selznick.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson won't be sitting on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a former instructor at the Bob Bondurant School of
High Performance Driving, is working the telephone in hopes of
landing a ride in this weekend's NASCAR Southwest Series race at
Sears Point (Calif.) Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   If no one answers, Thompson remains in demand as an instructor.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson's preference is obvious. He'd rather be behind the
steering wheel, not outside coaching someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sealy Mattress wants to see what kind of exposure results they
got from the truck race,'' Thompson said. ``At this point, it's
kind of up to them how involved they want to be with us. But we're
hoping we can put something together for more races this season.'' &QL; 
Father's Day tribute &QL; 
 &UR; Chuck Trickle, whose son,  &UR; Chris, died last year following a 1997
shooting incident in which he was shot in the head by an unknown
assailant, celebrated his first career win Saturday in a NASCAR
Winston Racing Series late model race at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional and very special,'' said Trickle, whose
brother is Winston Cup driver  &UR; Dick Trickle. ``This is my first
victory ever. My brother has won more races than anyone in the
world. Chris won a third of the races he was in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to race, but didn't start until late in life.
It is the one thing in my life that makes me closer to Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Trickle won the race on his 55th birthday and one day
before Father's Day. &QL; 
Pit stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do not _ repeat, do not _ try this on the freeway:  &UR; Dave
 &UR; Marcis smashed into a concrete wall during Sunday's Cup race at
Pocono Raceway and somehow escaped with only a cut chin.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in NASCAR history, the top three circuits
(Winston Cup, Busch Series and trucks) are at road-racing venues
during the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Budweiser's  &UR; Dave Villwock stretched his Unlimited
Hydroplane Racing Association lead following Sunday's win over
runner-up Chip Hanauer. Drivers  &UR; Todd Yarling and  &UR; Mark Weber both
were involved in spectacular crashes but weren't seriously
injured. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at (602) 444-8323 or at
mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
