<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPT-KIDS-AS-PARENTS-P     06-23 1843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-KIDS-AS-PARENTS-PREP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN: `YEAH, THIS WILL CHANGE MY LIFE'  
 HIGH SCHOOL KIDS STRUGGLE TO COPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A baby cries. Lamar Woodberry's summer basketball game
at Trevor Browne High School will have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   There is somebody other than himself to worry about. A son, now
a little more than a week old, who is forcing the child in Lamar to
grow up faster, to look beyond his 17 years at a cold, harsh
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, this will change my life,'' said Woodberry, a Trevor
Browne senior to be. ``I probably won't have that much time to
practice. I have to deal with it and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories are no longer all that uncommon _ high school
athletes dealing with parenthood. Some drop out. Some stick with
it. Some look for safety nets in family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids feel it's never going to happen to them,''
Camelback track and field Coach Jay Edelson said. ``The next you
you know, they're going up to you, saying, `I'm pregnant. I'm going
to have a kid.' In 19 years of coaching, I've had several, and you
never get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been two years since Paula Owens left Chandler High as an
outstanding basketball center and a mother seeking a good life for
herself and a son who was born between her sophomore and junior
years.
</P>
<P>
   Between taking Whakin to day care, being a full-time student,
working a job and trying to stretch her income to meet expenses,
Owens still clings to her dream: to be a major college basketball
player.
</P>
<P>
   But despite earning junior college All-America honors last
season when she averaged 24 points and 12 rebounds while leading
Mesa Community College to the national tournament, Owens has no
scholarship offer. Schools have been unwilling to give a
scholarship to a mother who is a semester short of earning her AA
degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of going home and getting homework done, once again
the priority is picking (Whakin) up, getting him fed, trying to
spend quality time with him,'' MCC women's basketball Coach Pam
Olerich said. ``Something usually gives.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens perseveres. She said she will try to finish at MCC in the
fall and hopes to walk on at Arizona State at the semester break.
All the while, she goes to the gym, sometimes with Whakin in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret having my son or being with him,'' Owens said.
``The only thing I regret is colleges looking at me with a child.
They look over me. They don't look at me. It could have been
different.'' &QL; 
Too much for some
</P>
<P>
   High school and the pressures of plotting one's future are
difficult enough without the added stress of raising a child. Some
kids are emotionally equipped to handle it. Others aren't, and
parents or grandparents, aunts, uncles and siblings are left with
the task of raising the children.
</P>
<P>
   Last basketball season at Central High, boys Coach Bob Strong
became concerned when one of his players had lost his passion for
the game and school.
</P>
<P>
   The senior started missing class, Strong said, and eventually
quit the team, unable to deal with the prospects of fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was real honest about it,'' Strong said. `He came up and
said this is what is going on, and I'm having a hard time with it.
I could understand why his focus wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong says he senses a drop-off in the number of athletes
fathering children compared with the '80s and early '90s. But
Trevor Browne basketball Coach Mike Ellsworth says next fall will
be the third consecutive year in which one of his players is
dealing with parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Woodberry's brother, Kevin, played for Ellsworth last
year. He was the state's Player of the Year and led the Bruins to
the 5A state semifinals, earning a scholarship to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's main focus was basketball and class,'' Ellsworth said.
``You wish you could get them all going the same way. I'm not
saying that because they have a baby they're not looking forward,
but sometimes they get sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to the park and ask why they're not in the NBA, 90
percent will tell you, `Well, I had a baby and that got me away
from basketball and going to class.' So many kids just blow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Browne assistant basketball coach Clinton Polk tries to
educate the players and his three children by relating the mistakes
he made in his life.
</P>
<P>
   After a stellar high school career in Indianapolis in the
mid-1970s, Polk starred two years at Phoenix College before getting
a scholarship at McNeese State in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But Polk said he quit school after getting involved with a girl
and fathering three children.
</P>
<P>
   Now 40, Polk volunteers his time coaching at Trevor Browne and
works as a custodian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not proud of what I do,'' he said. ``I'm thankful to God
I've got a job. But I could have bettered myself. I had everything
there for me. I was one of the top players around. My school was
always going to be paid for. I didn't take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk said he encourages his oldest daughter, Alysia, 16, who
will be a sophomore basketball player and track athlete at Desert
Vista High, and his 14-year-old son, Clinton Jr., who will be a
freshman basketball player at Trevor Browne, to abstain from sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad talks about when he was younger and his situations,
having jobs that don't have a salary,'' Alysia said. ``He also
tells me what's going to happen to me if I get pregnant, what he's
going to do to me.'' &QL; 
`Forces you to grow up'
</P>
<P>
   Jaylene Williams, an honor student who was 29th in her
graduating class at North High two years ago, had an academic
scholarship to ASU. But she's currently putting a
psychology/pre-med major on hold to work full time to support a
son, Alexander, who is now a year and a half old.
</P>
<P>
   She gets helps from the boy's father, Dante Murphy, who is
working toward a comeback in football at Glendale Community
College. Murphy said he gave up football his senior year at North
after he found out he was going to be a father.
</P>
<P>
   He said he worked up to 60 hours a week in a bakery to save
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a really good dad,'' Williams said. ``That's why I'm
working full time. He has a lot of dreams and a lot of aspirations
in football and track. I think he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy and Williams share a home in south Phoenix, where they
split shifts in taking care of Alexander. There are no marital
plans at the present.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they try to commit their time to Alexander and stay
away from a party life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This forces you to grow up,'' Murphy said. ``You deal more
with people who you can benefit from than the ones you just have a
good time with. If you're around responsible people, you're going
to be responsible.'' &QL; 
Playpen at practice
</P>
<P>
   More than a year ago, Maryvale High's gym at times looked like a
nursery during girls basketball practice.
</P>
<P>
   Three girls on the team had babies. Rather than turn his back on
the three, Coach Osborn Shackelford provided a playpen and gave
them no excuses for not being at practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt, `If you didn't have a baby-sitter, then bring them to
practice,' '' Shackelford said. ``I refused to change diapers, but
I can hold them and feed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a student-athlete and keep up your grades is tough
enough. I personally felt that it was good for them to put in
extra-curricular activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all coaches are as sympathetic to a young mom's plight as
Shackelford.
</P>
<P>
   Camelback softball Coach Joyce Fredericks said she wouldn't ever
set up a playpen by the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the choice to have a baby, and there are consequences
that go with that,'' Fredericks said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, however, Fredericks made an exception for a girl
who came out for the team four months after having a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did fine, but I told her up front, `I don't want any
interference. I don't support it (teens with children), so I don't
want to hear it,' '' Fredericks said. ``I never heard a peep about
it. That one worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempe McClintock football Coach Dennis Johnson said that each
year there is at least one player who has fathered a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the players and coaches have problems in their lives,''
Johnson said. ``There's drugs, there's alcohol, there's tobacco,
all sorts of things that are wrong. Sex is another. You have to
deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easy solution to say, `You're done with athletics.' I
don't think it's always the solution. The more you can work with
them and correct it, the better off they'll be.'' &QL; 
Mom talks to classmates
</P>
<P>
   Chandler girls basketball Coach Mike Desper made an exception
for Owens, two years after telling another player she wasn't
welcome on the team because she had a second child while in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a game. That's life,'' Desper told ``The Arizona
Republic'' two years ago while Owens played basketball for him.
``You have to take care of life, and a game is not something you
should be doing anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens won Desper's support by speaking to classmates during her
senior year about the trials and tribulations of early motherhood
and how they should refrain from sex.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who works at a Gilbert bank and says she received only
minimal support from her son's father, wants to get through school.
She wants to play basketball. She wants to be a good mom.
</P>
<P>
   She never used motherhood as an excuse, said Olerich, her coach
at MCC.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had extra baggage in that she had a son, but we took a
chance,'' Olerich said. ``I was pleasantly surprised. It didn't
hinder her responsibilities at school and on the basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be flexible. There were days when the baby was sick
and he couldn't go to day care and he would come to the gym. The
important thing was to communicate to the rest of the team that
she's not getting special treatment, because she has a son. Her son
was her priority. For the rest of the team, school was first and
basketball second, and family, social life came next.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerich feels basketball opportunities will materialize for
Owens but has advised her to keep her priorities in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've always stressed is, `Look at your son's future.
You've got to provide a good income for him,' '' she said. &QL; 
Prepared for sacrifices
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to say which direction Lamar Woodberry's life and
basketball career will go.
</P>
<P>
   He does not work and feels fortunate that family is around to
help out with Antwuan. Lamar says he has missed some basketball
games and practices this summer to be with his girlfriend,
Latrisha, as they take turns caring for the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changes diapers, feeds him,'' Latrisha said. ``Lamar was
scared at first, but he's pulling through.''
</P>
<P>
   While in many cases the father ultimately drifts out of the
picture, Woodberry says he's prepared to make the sacrifices to be
there for his son.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent midafternoon, cradling his newborn son, he answers
the phone.
</P>
<P>
   A teammate reminds him about basketball practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go,'' he says. ``I have to take care of the baby.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
