<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPT-KIDS-AS-PARENTS-P     06-23 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-KIDS-AS-PARENTS-PRO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SINGLE MOM, SHE WASN'T ALONE  
 CAMPBELL GLAD FOR HELP WITH SON, CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - David Campbell, a mixed message in his Titleist
baseball hat, Nike basketball shirt and North Carolina blue shorts,
smoothly worked the basketball between his legs at a discreet
distance from Suns guard Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   Close enough to get a good first eyeball of the All-NBA
first-teamer. Far enough away during the lunchtime shoot-around at
the America West Arena practice court for a 15-year-old to
fantasize in safety.
</P>
<P>
   His surrogate mother told him that he almost certainly would
meet Kidd and Reggie Miller this summer. For that, he can thank his
biological mother, Edna Campbell, playing her first season for the
Mercury and Coach Cheryl Miller, Reggie's sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to dust them,'' David tells Janet Davis, Edna
Campbell's high school coach in Pittsburgh and lifetime confidante.
``I'll give them my shake and bake just like I do to mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right, she replies.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, with practice and a TV public service announcement
already ticked off the day's agenda, David's mom settles into a
discussion of herself at his age. For her, it was an age of fear
and denial and growing up in a hurry. &QL; 
State of denial &QL; 
From a family splintered by alcoholism, Campbell refused to
acknowledge her pregnancy through the fall of 1983 and past her
15th birthday on Nov. 26. She was 17 games into her sophomore
season at Pittsburgh's Allderdice High School and 28 weeks pregnant
when Davis went with her to the doctor and learned the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid to tell anyone,'' Campbell said. ``And I kept
telling myself that I wasn't pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a female athlete, ultimately there's no avoiding the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are so . . . how do I put this?'' she said. ``They don't
get caught with the baggage. So it's easy for them to do something
and to walk away. The women have to sort of look out for
themselves. He (David's father) was like my first real boyfriend
and that was probably the first time I'd had sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet she says she never considered an abortion, and her
aspirations didn't have to be shelved.
</P>
<P>
   David was born more than a month premature by C-section in
February 1984. Before the school year ended, Campbell not only had
been talked into attempting the high jump, but set a city record.
</P>
<P>
   With David being cared for by her family, Campbell went with
Davis to a Blue Star basketball camp in the summer of 1984. She has
been on the national/international basketball radar ever since.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Parade'' and ``USA Today'' All-American in 1986 who still
holds the Allderdice single-game scoring record (40 points),
Campbell played two seasons at Maryland, then transferred to Texas.
She played overseas in Brazil and Hungary before becoming an
American Basketball League All-Star in 1997 and, after the ABL's
demise, a first-round WNBA draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-8 guard starts alongside Michele Timms in the Mercury
backcourt, averaging 12.8 points per game. She is tied for the WNBA
single-game season high with five three-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept on with everything we were doing,'' said Davis,
who treasures a photo of young Edna on a bicycle with David on her
back in a carrier. ``Nobody ever said, `You had this child, you're
staying here.' Everybody moved forward.'' &QL; 
Counting blessings &QL; 
As a preschooler, David's primary caregiver was Campbell's maternal
grandmother, Jane McCloud. When McCloud died in 1991, late in
Campbell's senior season at Texas, the childless Davis accepted the
responsibility of raising a 6-year-old while Campbell was overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to be counted as a statis tic,'' said Campbell,
who has an exercise physiology degree and aspirations to be a
pharmacist or physical therapist. ``I wasn't going to be the high
school mother that became pregnant, dropped out, sat on welfare,
then ended up having two more kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see having my son as a blessing. Without my son, I'm not
sure I would have accomplished the things I needed to accomplish
because I look at my son every day and realize how much he needs
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say, well, I had a child when I was 15 and I just
couldn't do it. But you know when you have that responsibility, it
makes you a bigger, better person.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Coach Jody Conradt says Campbell is not the type to shy
away from a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edna has improved as much as any player I've ever coached,''
said Conradt, the winningest Division I coach. ``She's always had
very, very good ballhandling skills, and her defensive skills are
excellent. I'm very impressed with how she's improved her shooting,
her range.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, becoming a better mother was a learned process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I don't think I identified with motherhood,'' she
said. ``I still wanted to play basketball after school. David just
stayed at the baby-sitter a little longer. Also, I had Janet and my
grandmother, so I was still able to be a 15-, 16-, 20-year-old
because of them and gradually assume the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in that situation, I really believe the most
important thing is to have people around you who support you and
believe in your whole future.''
</P>
<P>
   But how many pregnant teenagers have someone to bank on such as
Davis?
</P>
<P>
   ``David could have stayed here the rest of his life, I didn't
care,'' said Davis, a White woman who has received a cultural
education in exchange for her generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear African-Americans talking about being the only one in
a restaurant and why they feel out of place. There I'm sitting in
an all-Black neighborhood, and David would be getting a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd not only be the only woman, but the only White woman.
People would come in and look at you. They always made you feel
welcome, but now I know the other side of the coin.'' &QL; 
Full-time mother &QL; 
With the advent of U.S. women's pro basketball after the 1996
Olympics, Campbell no longer had to play overseas and went from
being a holiday/off-season mom to a full-time mother. David,
already 12, was moving into middle school.
</P>
<P>
   The Catch-22 of supporting her son in a career that took her
away from him was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really afraid that my relationship with my son would be
affected by being overseas,'' Campbell said. ``You know the years
are passing and passing, and he's getting older and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want my child to have some animosity towards me
because I was never there. Now he's with me and, yeah, we travel
and we're on the road, but when I think about parents who work 9 to
5, how much time do they really spend with their children?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my time with my son is comparable to the average
parent. I wish I could spend more time with him, but you know the
off-season (eight months in the WNBA) is a long season. I'm pretty
content with our relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   When Campbell played for the Colorado Xplosion of the ABL, she
developed a platonic friendship with Jay Humphries, a former Suns
guard and now a restaurateur in Denver. Humphries is a big brother
to David.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an attempt to fill a void,'' Campbell said. ``I'm not
sure if it does or not. I just know David is at the point in his
life where he kind of seeks that bonding with the guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have to realize that's something I can't . . . '' she
breaks off in laughter ``I can't fulfill that need. Always on my
part, I'm trying to get him in an environment where he can interact
with men because I know he needs that.'' &QL; 
Sharing experiences &QL; 
Campbell, who maintains a home in Denver, is not shy about speaking
publicly of her circumstances and how she overcame them. She
created the Young Parents Foundation to provide support for teenage
parents, and she established a scholarship fund for female athletes
at her high school.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Hargrove, who coached the Xplosion last fall before the
ABL went bankrupt, saw Campbell's presentation at several schools,
including David's.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has positive energy for everyone,'' said Hargrove, a
mother of two who also was a sounding board for Campbell. ``She'd
say, `Linda, what did you do? He's wanting to date and talking
about girls.' I was just laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people take motherhood for granted, that it's an
easy, natural thing. It's not necessarily. I think Edna's done a
tremendous job. It's a very heartwarming relationship to see when
you're around them on a fairly consistent level.''
</P>
<P>
   David, shy yet articulate, has a gleaming smile and a
personality that Davis says mirrors his mother's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of hard because I'd go to my mom, then I'd go
back,'' he said. ``I missed my mom a lot when she kept traveling. I
understood it was her job, she had to support me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool because she opens a lot of doorways for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Already with an inch on his mother and on his way to 6 feet 2 or
taller, David wants to be a pro basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to do it,'' he said, sounding like millions
of other boys and now girls his age. ``Jason Kidd, he's like my
role model because he's nice on and off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   But his true influence is the woman wearing Mercury jersey No.
12, a reverse of the No. 21 she has worn throughout her career.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said David lobbied for No. 7, which is worn by Timms, but
maybe the more he thinks about it, No. 15 would be the most fitting
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's real amazing,'' David said of his mother's accepting
responsibility for him at that age. His age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I couldn't do it. She's been a real good mom. I love my
mom. I'm proud of my mom.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
