<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX, WASDIN BOMB OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-ORIOLES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ For those starting to think that John Wasdin might
have struck a deal like that of Joe Hardy, the character who sold
his soul to the devil so he could beat the damn Yankees, relax.
Wasdin apparently is still pure of heart.
</P>
<P>
   And imperfect in his pitches. Wasdin, whose unbeaten record
belies his penchant for serving meatballs at the most inopportune
time, grooved one to Albert Belle in the eighth inning Tuesday
night, and Baltimore's struggling strongman launched it for a
three-run home run that lifted the surging Orioles to a 5-3 win
over the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   While the loss did not mar Wasdin's record, which remains 7-0,
it unquestionably left its mark, not only on him but on lefthanded
reliever Mark Guthrie, the man stuck with the loss, only the third
sustained by Boston in its last nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I didn't do my job,'' said Wasdin, who was aiming to
throw a two-strike fastball up and in to Belle but instead threw it
down and over the middle, resulting in the seventh home run he's
allowed in 31 1/3 innings. ``I gladly would have taken the loss. I
feel badly about giving up somebody else's runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie inherited a 3-1 lead and a runner on first in the eighth
when he gave up a bloop single to Brady Anderson, a ground single
to Mike Bordick, and a sacrifice fly by B.J. Surhoff that cut it to
3-2. Belle then unloaded his 14th home run into the left-center
field seats off Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what to tell you,'' said Guthrie, whose
earned run average climbed to a staff-high 6.84 after he was
charged with two runs. ``I'm getting sick of a situation where I'm
walking off the field with that feeling. It affects everything you
do. I don't want to sit here and give you a sob story. Just get
back and play tomorrow, and hope things turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was the 11th in 12 games for the Orioles, now five games
under .500 after once being 15 games under the break-even point,
while the Sox saw their three-game winning streak come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule says we play three games here,'' said Sox manager
Jimy Williams, knocking down a question about whether losing to a
club as hot as the Orioles would only stoke them more. ``We can't
leave. I don't know anything about hot or cold or whatever. We're
going to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss kept alive Pat Rapp's streak of guaranteed misfortune.
The Sox are 3-10 in games started by Rapp, who Tuesday night
averaged almost a walk an inning (6 in 6 1/3) and threw more balls
(58) than strikes (52), but still left with a 2-1 lead, having held
the Orioles to three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs by Jason Varitek, his eighth of the season, and Troy
O'Leary, his 15th, accounted for the first two Sox runs off Sidney
Ponson. Back-to-back doubles in the eighth by Jose Offerman and Lou
Merloni (one of three hits by the Framingham Kid) made it 3-1 in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp dodged one bullet when Will Clark left third base too soon
on a fly ball in the second, and another when Harold Baines, given
the green light on a 3-and-0 pitch, grounded into a double play in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't one inning in which he didn't have at least one
Oriole on base. But Rapp, a child of the Louisiana delta, knows
something about surviving in a swamp, even though this season the
muck almost always has been waist-high for him.
</P>
<P>
   He was still ahead when reliever Kirk Bullinger, a candidate to
be sent back to the minors Wednesday when Bret Saberhagen is
activated, converted Jeff Conine's bullet back to the mound into an
inning-ending double play, trapping Clark off second after spearing
the low liner.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Rapp was stuck with another no-decision, and has
just one win to show in nine starts since April 28. And with
Saberhagen back Wednesday night, he no doubt is headed back to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been very lucky this year,'' said Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were in an ideal spot to squelch the thought that the
Orioles could climb back into this race. In their previous 15
games, Baltimore starters were 8-1 with a 3.17 ERA, while the
offense also had come to life, batting .320 for the month while
averaging over six runs a game.
</P>
<P>
   Now it will be up to Saberhagen, who has as many wins this
season (2) as he has stints on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't done anything all year,'' said Saberhagen,
who hasn't pitched since stepping on a piece of broken glass at a
team party he hosted in New York a couple of weeks ago. ``Half the
year has gone by, and I haven't really contributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking not only to getting out there and staying out
there. I'll just go out and do what I can. This was a tough one
tonight. Hopefully, we'll bounce back and do it tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
