<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-OVERRUNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS WANT PUBLIC MONEY TO HELP PAY FOR STADIUM OVERRUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN SNEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Just weeks before the opening of Safeco Field, owners
of the Seattle Mariners on Tuesday launched an offensive aimed at
wresting another $60 million in public money to help cover the
ballpark's estimated $100 million cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing what they acknowledge is an unpopular move, team
officials set into motion what may become a marathon legal battle
over unanticipated tax money.
</P>
<P>
   The team says King County must use the tax revenue to issue more
bonds to pay for the $517 million ballpark, which is over budget
largely because of weather-related construction delays,
higher-than-expected concrete costs and upgrades in communication
systems and concession areas.
</P>
<P>
   The county, and the Public Facilities District that is building
Safeco Field, maintain the added revenue must be used to repay the
stadium debt years ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side is shy in stating its case.
</P>
<P>
   King County Executive Ron Sims put it this way: ``No more. A
deal's a deal. Not one more dime.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mariners Chairman John Ellis on Tuesday maintained the
Mariners have a legal claim to the money, and said he's grown tired
of suggestions that the team owners are trying to raid the cookie
jar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quit the cookie jar!'' Ellis told reporters Tuesday. ``We got
into this thing to save baseball. By God, we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis acknowledged that last year he said the team was committed
to paying for construction costs in excess of the $417 million
ballpark budget set in mid-1997. But that was before the county
discovered the hot local economy was fueling a tax surplus, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be here if we had a recession,'' said Nintendo of
America Inc. Chairman Howard Lincoln, a member of the Mariners
board of directors. He represents Nintendo owner Hiroshi Yamauchi,
the team's majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said there was never any ``cap'' on the public's share of
the project. He said the state Legislature's only cap is on the
team's $45 million contribution to the venue's construction. The
team has since paid another $10 million for equipment such as lawn
mowers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not talk about a (public) cap and there was never talk
about a cap,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a popular thing to do. But it is the right thing
to do,'' Lincoln said. ``We think the county is obligated to issue
the bonds. I realize there's a lot of people who don't agree with
us. But even baseball owners are entitled to their day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   That day will come. The Public Facilities District, which owns
the 45,000-seat ballpark, and King County, which floated bonds to
finance the public's share of the project, have dug in for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the Mariners on many occasions that we will not
seek more public funds,'' said Ken Johnsen, the stadium district
executive director. ``We believe our agreements with the Mariners
are clear: They are responsible for all costs above the approved
$417 million budget.''
</P>
<P>
   King County Councilman Larry Phillips added, ``They're going to
get into our knickers one way or the other. And it is absolutely
shameless. These are rich and powerful people who are ruthless when
it comes to protecting their pocketbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners officials said three different law firms have
advised them that excess revenues from items such as car rental and
restaurant taxes must be used for stadium work.
</P>
<P>
   But the state lawmaker who authored the 1995 legislation that
enabled the ballpark to be financed said the bill was adopted
because the Mariners had agreed to pay all cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel the reason the bill passed in the first place ...
was because the Mariners agreed to cover the cost overruns. Some
voted for it based on that fact,'' said Rep. Steve Van Luven,
R-Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in determining who gets the surplus tax revenue
unfolded Tuesday when the team invoked a clause in its agreement
with the stadium district and asked the PFD to help hire a third
party to mediate the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The PFD and the team will hire the mediator within 30 days. The
mediator then has three to six months to help both sides resolve
their differences through non-binding negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   If the team and the stadium district can't reach an agreement,
one of the two parties can ask for binding arbitration. If both
sides don't agree to arbitration, then they head to court.
</P>
<P>
   During mediation, the Mariners will cite a team-financed
analysis that shows $60 million in net proceeds would be available
for stadium bond financing if public money from the state lottery
and taxes for restaurants, admissions and rental cars kept at their
current pace of growth. The Mariners, who open Safeco Field on July
15, did not name the firm that did the analysis in February.
</P>
<P>
   The county initially planned to raise $651 million in tax
revenue through 2016 to pay off $336 million in the stadium bonds.
By the end of 1998, the county had collected $9 million of excess
stadium tax revenue and that amount was projected to grow to $15
million by the end of 1999. If the Mariners are correct and the
surplus grows to $60 million, the county could retire the debt as
early as 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials began privately lobbying the PFD in February, two
months before the stadium district announced cost overruns had
ballooned to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   By April, the stadium district had already run out of money to
pay contractors and began accepting money from the team. The
ballclub paid $15.4 million in March, $13.6 million in April and
$12.6 million in May.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln said this money was ``advanced'' to the stadium district
and that the club's move Tuesday was the first step to recoup those
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln said if the team loses its battle for more bonds,
neither the franchise will be sold nor stars such as Ken Griffey
Jr. will be allowed to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not poverty-stricken,'' Lincoln added.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporter Neil Modie contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
