<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, June 23.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-ROYAL-ACADEMY (Madrid) _ The Royal Spanish Academy once
ruled with absolute authority over the vast Spanish empire, but now
the Americas have their own language academies that propose
home-grown changes. Disputes have even led to threats of linguistic
schisms. So, with nine out of 10 Spanish speakers now living
outside Spain, the Royal Spanish Academy has learned to consult and
negotiate. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-Y2K (Moscow) _ Even as the government rachets up a
crusade to rid Russia's 7 million desktop computers, its software
and its microchips of the so-called Year 2000 Bug, many experts are
urging businesses and other organizations to gird for digital
breakdowns next January that could disrupt industries and services
like power, transportation and telecommunications. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: (NYT 27) is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEAD-STUDIES (Undated) _ One new study suggests that high levels
of vitamin C in the blood is associated with a decreased prevalence
of elevated blood levels of lead, while a second study shows that
environmental lead exposure is associated with an increased
prevalence of tooth decay, according to two articles in the June
23/30 issue of The Journal of the American Medical Association
(JAMA). By John O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON (Naval Weapons Base Concord, Calif.) _
During World War II, an explosion on a segregated naval base here
killed 320 men. After the accident, black sailors were ordered to
resume loading ammunition onto ships. Fifty of them refused, were
court-martialed by an all-white panel, found guilty of mutiny and
imprisoned. Now, in an extraordinary legal battle, lawyers for one
black veteran have filed for a presidential pardon arguing that the
black sailors failed to follow orders out of legitimate fear and
had no intent to mutiny. The petition pits the racial symbolism of
a celebrated case against the military's view that servicemen
cannot choose which orders to obey. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT25) and a map are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients.)
