<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE BEGINS THROW ING AGAIN _ AND LOVES EV ERY MINUTE OF
IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There was no radar gun. No menacing opponent with
bulging biceps standing in the batter's box, waiting to take a big
cut. It was back to basics, plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre loved every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever seen anybody so excited about playing
catch,'' Diamondbacks Manager &UR; Buck Showalter said of the
right-handed Stottlemyre, who threw for the first time on Tuesday
since suffering partial tears of his rotator cuff and labrum on May
17 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who was 4-1 with a 3.59 ERA in nine starts, threw
for about 10 minutes at a distance of 60 feet. He was a bit tight
early, but was fine in the later stages of the session and felt
little or no aftereffects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to feel great, but the fact of the matter is, five
weeks is a long time not to pick up a ball,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not want to put a time frame on his return to
the mound for the big club. He is expected to pitch in at least a
couple of rehabilitation assignments in the minor leagues before
that occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week from now, we'll know a lot more,'' he said. &QL; 
Carlson joins club &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The contract of right-hander  &UR; Dan Carlson, one of the final cuts
of the spring, was purchased from the Triple-A Tucson affiliate. To
make room for him on the roster, the club optioned infielder  &UR; Edwin
Diaz to Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson, who pitched for the San Francisco Giants' Triple-A
affiliate in Phoenix for parts of five seasons, says he has been
told that he will not be gathering dust in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said their middle relievers have thrown a lot lately and
that I'll get some innings. I'm grateful for the opportunity,''
said Carlson, who was 2-5 in 16 games (11 starts) for Tucson. ``I'm
going to pitch as well as I can, and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson entered Tuesday's game to start the seventh inning and
retired the side in order. After retiring the first two batters in
the eighth inning, he gave up singles to Pokey Reese and Michael
Tucker before being relieved by left-hander Dan Plesac.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star update &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Voting for the National League All-Star team was updated
Tuesday, and Diamondbacks third baseman  &UR; Matt Williams saw a
substantial increase in his lead over Atlanta's  &UR; Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had a lead of about 8,000 last week. Now it is up to
almost 76,000 (357,035 to 281,265).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
