<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6110 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-POINT-GUARD     06-23 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-POINT-GUARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POINT WELL TAKEN AS NO. 1 IN DRAFT  
 FRANCIS' TALENT AMAZES SCOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a lot of stories about Maryland guard Steve Francis.
One is worth remembering.
</P>
<P>
   In a pickup game last summer, Francis leaped, took the
basketball and slammed it into the face of Chris Webber, the former
Washington Wizards forward now with the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Francis continues to climb.
</P>
<P>
   At least, his stock in the 1999 NBA draft does.
</P>
<P>
   Francis is projected by some scouts to be the No. 1 pick, which
is owned by the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could very well go Number 1,'' Suns scout Dick Percudani
said. ``He has the energy level of an Allen Iverson. He's in the
attack mode on both ends of the court. He has such a court presence
that he's impossible not to like.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that nobody can identify his real pro position is both
intriguing and a hint at what might prove to be a weak draft class.
</P>
<P>
   Francis is projected as a playmaker, yet he was never at the
position at Maryland long enough for any scout to make a solid
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 3, 194 pounds, he was a shooting guard, but lacks the
size to succeed at that position in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is the guy?'' Percudani said of Francis, who last season
as a junior averaged 17.2 points, 4.2 rebounds, 4.5 assists, 2.8
steals and shot 52.8 percent from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to Percudani's question is merely a projection,
always a hazardous undertaking with an underclassman. But the
scouts like what they see. In Francis, there are the sure signs of
toughness. He's paid some dues, and there are reasons to think his
potential remains untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Francis grew up in a poor Maryland neighborhood. His mom,
Brenda, died when he was in high school. Her name is tattooed on
his right arm.
</P>
<P>
   He played street ball long before he ever put on a prep uniform
in Silver Spring, Md. He was a late bloomer in high school. The
blossoming continued through college. He went to two junior
colleges _ San Jacinto, Texas, and Allegany, Md. _ before he moved
on to Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can dunk the basketball in his socks,'' Percudani said of
Francis' 43-inch vertical leap. ``He's a firecracker.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, Francis has emerged as the potential top pick because
of growing concern about Lamar Odom, who failed to show up for
tryouts with two teams and then began to second-guess his decision
to leave Rhode Island as an underclassman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Odom might be the biggest tease in the draft,'' Percudani said
of the 6-10 player who scouts believe can play any position except
center.
</P>
<P>
   The only safe bet in the 1999 draft appears to be among the
playmakers. Including Francis, there are five who figure to be
lottery picks, Nos. 1-13.
</P>
<P>
   The other four:
</P>
<P>
   Jason Terry of Arizona. As a 6-2 senior last year, he averaged
22.1 points, 5.6 assists and 2.7 steals. He's a do-it-all kind of
backcourt player. ``He has a lot of confidence,'' Percudani said.
``At worst, he's a backup in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Miller of Utah. As a 6-2 senior last year, he averaged
15.9 points, 5.5 rebounds, 5.8 assists and 2.5 steals. He's solid,
although there are questions about his shooting. He's been called
the poor-man's Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Davis of UCLA. As a 6-2 sophomore last year, he averaged
15.9 points, 5.2 assists and 2.5 steals. ``He has a power game and
a very dominating personality,'' Percudani said. ``That might be a
problem as a point. He needs to be the top banana. On some NBA
teams, he might get peeled.'' A surgically repaired knee is another
cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   William Avery of Duke. As a 6-2 sophomore, he averaged 15.1
points and 5.3 assists last year. His relative inexperience is a
worry. ``But, in time, he might prove to be the best of the
bunch,'' Percudani said of the projected scoring playmaker. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
