<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6111 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-EXPAND-DRAFT-LIST     06-23 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EXPAND-DRAFT-LIST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION TEAM GETS SHOT AT VERBEEK, JUNEAU, KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They celebrated winning the Stanley Cup with a victory
parade on Monday, but several members of the Dallas Stars weren't
celebrating a day later when they learned they were left
unprotected for Friday's NHL expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Among those exposed to the Atlanta Thrashers were a handful of
core players from the two-time President's Trophy winners,
including forwards Pat Verbeek, Guy Carbonneau, Brian Skrudland and
Dave Reid, and defensemen Shawn Chambers, Craig Ludwig and Doug
Lidster.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup runner-up Buffalo Sabres did not protect
forwards Joe Juneau, Rob Ray and Geoff Sanderson as well as Dominik
Hasek's backup, Dwayne Roloson.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables left unprotected around the NHL include Detroit
center Igor Larionov, a 63-point scorer for the Red Wings last
season; Ottawa goalie Ron Tugnutt, whose 1.79 goals-against average
led the league; San Jose right wing Joe Murphy, who scored a
team-leading 25 goals for the Sharks; and Toronto left wing Derek
King, who scored 24 goals for the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, as reported Tuesday, protected the majority of
their top players but chose to expose several other key
contributors from last season's team, which finished fourth overall
in the Western Conference and recorded its second-best point total
(90) in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   The casualties include forwards Bob Corkum, Jim Cummins, Mike
Stapleton, Mike Sullivan, Louie DeBrusk and Stephen Leach,
defensemen Gerald Diduck, Stan Neckar, J.J. Daigneault, Jamie
Huscroft and Brad Tiley, and goalies Mikhail Shtalenkov, Jimmy
Waite and Scott Langkow.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining Phoenix players left unprotected are forwards
Brian Noonan, Joe Dziedzic, Barry Nieckar, Jocelyn Lemieux, Rob
Murray, Andrei Vasilyev, Frederik Loven and Mike Alatalo;
defensemen Sean McCann and Michel Petit; and goalie Henrik Smangs.
</P>
<P>
   Every NHL club, with the exception of the Nashville Predators,
will lose at least one player to the Thrashers, who begin play next
season. Teams had to expose one goalie, one experienced defenseman
and two experienced forwards, all of whom either played 40 games
last season or 70 over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Three players on the Coyotes' current roster were picked by the
Pradators in last year's expansion draft: Sullivan, acquired from
Nashville for a seventh-round pick in this year's draft;
Shtalenkov, obtained later from Edmonton; and Daigneault who,
essentially, was the ``future considerations'' portion of the
controversial Cliff Ronning trade with Nashville on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Other NHL players left unprotected by their clubs include Wendel
Clark, Doug Brown, Ulf Samuelsson, Uwe Krupp and Norm Maracle of
Detroit; Dave Manson, Bob Probert, Eddie Olczyk of Chicago; Slyvain
Lefebvre, Dale Hunter and Craig Billington of Chicago; Andreas
Johansson of Ottawa; Geoff Courtnall, Terry Yake and Blair
Atcheynum of St. Louis; Tie Domi and Kris King of Toronto; Murray
Baron and Garth Snow of Vancouver; Steve Duchesne, Luke Richardson
and Ron Hextall of Philadelphia; as well as other veteran goalies
such as the Blues' Grant Fuhr and the Shark's Mike Vernon.
</P>
</TEXT>
