u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGSTORE-SPI &LR;      06-23 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGSTORE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGSTORE.COM SIGNS DEAL TO BE EXCLUSIVE ONLINE RETAILER FOR RITE
AID, GNC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Peter Neupert, the chief executive of Bellevue-based
drugstore.com, has accomplished a lot in his 10 months on the job.
The former Microsoft executive, who took the reins of the Internet
pharmacy in August, has added more than 200 employees, joined with
Amazon.com, raised more than $50 million in venture capital and
filed for an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Still moving at Internet speed, Neupert on Tuesday announced
what could be the most important agreement in his young company's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid, the country's third-largest brick-and-mortar pharmacy
chain, and General Nutrition Centers Inc., the largest specialty
retailer of vitamins and natural care products in the United
States, will scrap their previously announced e-commerce plans and
partner directly with drugstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year agreement _ a lifetime in the Internet age _ makes
drugstore.com the exclusive online retailer for both Rite Aid and
GNC, which together have more than 6,000 stores throughout the
country. While drugstore.com will help the traditional retailers
establish an online presence, some analysts say that Rite Aid and
GNC hold the keys to success for drugstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rite Aid will open a lot of doors that Drugstore has struggled
to get through,'' said Eric Bosshard, an analyst at Midwest
Research. ``This is a combination that creates a real powerful
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Seattle-based Soma.com was sold to CVS Corp.,
the leading pharmacy chain in the United States, for what some
analysts called a bargain basement price of $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Hill, Penn.-based Rite Aid, which is making a $7.6 million
investment in drugstore.com for a 25 percent stake, also appears to
be getting a good deal, said David Restrepo, an analyst at Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the price I would say that drugstore.com needed
Rite Aid more than Rite Aid needed drugstore.com,'' he said. ``Rite
Aid was the company with the greater leverage in the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The main reason traditional pharmacies like Rite Aid, Walgreens
and CVS have the upper hand is because of their strong ties to
pharmacy benefit managers or PBMs, the third-party intermediaries
that handle the paperwork and drug pricing structure for insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Restrepo said that pharmacy benefit managers have been reluctant
to work with the online pharmacies, making it virtually impossible
for them to get customers. ``Access to the PBMs is something that
drugstore.com, Soma and PlanetRX have all been grappling with,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugstore.com had to give up one quarter of its company, which
tells you just how important (the issue) is for these online
drugstores.''
</P>
<P>
   Neupert said that the relationship with Rite Aid would
immediately give drugstore.com access to members of PCS Health
Systems Inc., one of the largest pharmacy benefits managers in the
country. PCS is owned by Rite Aid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Rite Aid investment, Pittsburgh-based GNC
will make a $2.4 million investment in drugstore.com for an 8
percent slice of the company. Its investment dilutes the holdings
of other owners. Amazon.com, which took a 46 percent stake in the
company in February, will own about 29 percent if the deal meets
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors in drugstore.com include Microsoft co-founder
Paul Allen, Starbucks' Howard Schultz and Silicon Valley venture
capital firm Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the benefits of allying with a pharmacy benefit
manager, Neupert said the deal would give consumers more choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really helps us meet our future objective which is to be
the best pharmacy on the Web,'' Neupert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It expands our pharmacy by allowing choice of when the
customer wants to pick up their prescriptions whether ... delivered
to the door or for a more urgent need to go pick up a prescription
at one of Rite Aid's 3,800 stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Grass, chairman and chief executive of Rite Aid, said
that his company would receive revenues on all prescriptions picked
up at the physical stores while drugstore.com collected on mail
order deliveries. Grass, who considered several online drugstores,
said drugstore.com became the natural choice after completing his
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are partnering with the player that we believe will be the
leader in this Internet space because of its well-honed marketing
strategy and strong financial backing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com, which filed to go public last month, could
receive a boost from investors when it issues shares this summer
because of Rite Aid's involvement, said Jupiter Communications'
Restrepo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both drugstore and Rite Aid saw the value in taking
drugstore.com public as a pure Internet company with a real-world
partner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com's competitors greeted the news calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he viewed the new partnership as a threat, Joe
Rosson, chief executive of Austin, Texas-based RX.com, said ``not
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are keeping to our knitting and staying focused on our
business model,'' Rosson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Reed, spokesman for Soma.com in Seattle, sounded a more
competitive tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first online and they followed. We were the first
to make a relationship with a bricks and mortar retailer and they
followed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased that the good folks at drugstore.com
recognize our leadership and follow in our path.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
