<HEADER>
A6113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-23 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ At another time, maybe in another place, this just might
be the day when America climbed aboard the Knicks' bandwagon and
hoped for one of those between-the-lines miracles that keep us
coming back to sports for a fix of emotional inspiration and life
lessons in perseverance and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   The images from Game 3 of the NBA Finals _ of Allan Houston
finding all the open spaces in the defense and hitting silky-smooth
shots to carry New York through the first three quarters, of
Latrell Sprewell slithering his way into cracks to score the big
buckets in the fourth quarter _ are the kind that usually draw the
admiration and rooting interest of the non-partisans who, aside
from wanting to be entertained, are seeking a cause to support.
</P>
<P>
   In the first summer of the post-Jordan playoffs, with NBC's
ratings hemorrhaging more than a season's worth of ER reruns, it
would almost seem a natural to gravitate toward the No. 8-seeded
Knicks over the No. 1-ranked Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   For one, there is the hook of Patrick Ewing, the gallant warrior
who has literally sweated buckets for so many coaches in a 14-year
career. Ewing has always been a solid citizen and a loyal, tireless
worker for the cause. Whatever nitpicking one might conjure up
regarding his individual game, his has most definitely been a
career to admire. And now the team captain is trapped inside
designer suits, forced to cheer on his teammates from the bench,
the result of a torn Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   It is also difficult not to admire Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy,
the tiny, disheveled character with dark circles under his eyes and
a comb-over hairdo who always looks as out of place in high-powered
Manhattan as an Amish farmer inside NASA's mission control. Van
Gundy succeeded big-time image-makers in Pat Riley and Don Nelson
and before this spring was remembered most for the way he hung on
to the ankle of Miami's Alonzo Mourning _ like a Chihuahua to a
mail carrier _ during one celebrated playoff melee last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Van Gundy has his critics in New York. They're mostly
people who can't seem to understand why a fellow who has risen to
his salary level hasn't traded in his house in the Jersey suburbs
for more palatial digs, brags about dining at the drive-in window
of fast-food establishments and still steers his own Honda through
traffic to Madison Square Garden. To wish him ill is like hoping
the Tooth Fairy develops an abscess.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are a batch of 7-footers and cool efficiency, a huge
machine rolling through the playoffs, while the Knicks are a
crackling brush fire, undermanned but unrelenting.
</P>
<P>
   Considering America's rebellious roots and penchant for
invariably backing the underdog, the Knicks would seem a batch of
mongrels to take into a nation's homes and hearts. Instead, this
series has been largely overlooked or tuned out by the masses.
Perhaps because the outcome appears a foregone conclusion. But
maybe also because the Knicks, in the role of cuddly strays, are
about as embraceable as a porcupine with a grudge.
</P>
<P>
   Each time you want to bring them into the kitchen and feed them
a bowl of milk, up pops another TV commercial shouting out that
Sprewell is the embodiment of the American dream. This is a man who
wrapped his hands around the throat of his coach, was pulled off
him, walked away for several minutes and then came back to do it
again.
</P>
<P>
   For that Sprewell was punished, fined big bucks and eventually
given a new start a continent away. Is that right? Absolutely. We
are all capable of screwing up badly. I know. We all deserve
another chance. But there is Sprewell, not repentant and suing
everyone in sight, and now at the Finals often portraying himself
as a victim.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby is the embodiment of the pampered young phenom, his
hand out for every extra on the climb up the blue-chip ladder. He
signed with an agent, accepted money and gifts, and left his
school, UMass, mired in a scandal without ever looking back.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Larry Johnson, long known as a bad actor dating to
his college days at UNLV and for the notoriety he earned making
crude gestures to opponents and fans while representing the United
States at the World Championships in 1994. The other day, he
responded to a request that he fulfill his obligations to the media
by unleashing an obscene torrent at a female member of the NBA's
public-relations department. Now Johnson and his agent say they
will appeal his fine, claiming he is being picked on. Nice.
</P>
<P>
   And so continues the story of these Knicks, still trailing in
the series, still undermanned, still unloved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
