<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6120 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     06-23 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSON STEPS IN TO LIFT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It would have been a cute little story if Gary
DiSarcina's return to the Angels lineup after missing the first 68
games of the season resulted in a dramatic victory.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, it was DiSarcina's replacement who started an
eighth-inning rally that lifted the Angels to a 4-2 victory over
the Seattle Mariners before 26,153 at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson pinch hit for DiSarcina with one out in the eighth
inning and the Angels trailing 1-0. Until then, the visitors had
just three hits off Mariners starter Freddy Garcia. Huson doubled
to right field, then scored on a single by Darin Erstad to tie the
game at 1. Randy Velarde followed with a triple into the
right-center field gap to score Erstad for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was replaced by Jeff Fassero, who induced Mo Vaughn to
ground out. But Garret Anderson was able to come up with a two-out
hit, a single to left to score Velarde and give the Angels a 3-1
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Angels have scored at least three in
an inning since the sixth inning on June 6 against the Dodgers _
when Troy Glaus hit a three-run homer. That's a span of 121
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' big rally wasn't the end of the Mariners, though. In
the bottom of the eighth, Alex Rodriguez doubled home Brian Hunter,
then went to third when Ken Griffey Jr. grounded to second for the
first out.
</P>
<P>
   Huson then made the first of two key defensive plays in the
inning. With the infield in, Edgar Martinez hit a sharp grounder
that Huson fielded, and after looking the Rodriguez back to third,
threw Martinez out at first. Butch Huskey followed with a soft
liner to right field, but Matt Luke made a diving catch to preserve
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the top of the ninth, Luke homered off ex-Angels
pitcher Allen Watson for a 4-2 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   The win was the Angels' second in a row, the first time they've
won back-to-back games since June 1 and 2, when they beat the Twins
two in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In his first major-league game of the season since suffering a
broken bone in his left forearm Feb. 21, DiSarcina went 1 for 2
(infield single) and was errorless on all five grounders hit to
him.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina hit .287 with 56 RBI last season and was named the
team's MVP by his teammates. Obviously, what DiSarcina brings to a
team isn't directly reflected by statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'm capable of doing and what I'm not capable of
doing,'' DiSarcina said. ``I'm not capable of doing what Tim Salmon
can do _ hit home runs and drive in runs. I'm not going to alter a
game with stats. If they're expecting me to hit grand slams and
three-run homers, they're mistaken. But attitude-wise, defensively,
I can be more of a leader out there. I'll try to run the bases
correctly, be aggressive _ that can be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He means everything, he's our leader,'' Angels
catcher/outfielder Todd Greene said. ``He doesn't have to hit .300
or hit 20 home runs. He brings a mentality to the team that we
need. He's aggressive, he's a great baserunner, he's our leader.
There's definitely been a lack of a strong team leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Before going out on a rehab assignment, DiSarcina had been
traveling with the team. He said the attitude doesn't necessarily
need to be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not adjusted, refocused,'' he said. ``Sometimes the focus gets
blurred. Situations with what the manager is doing, or what
(general manager) Billy Bavasi is doing blurs your focus from what
the team needs to focus on, which is winning each game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
