<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS GET TO GARCIA IN EIGHTH IN '70S-STYLE WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was '70s Night at the Kingdome and the Mariners and
Angels played like it. All of a sudden, the mound was higher, the
strike zone wider, hits scarcer.
</P>
<P>
   For 75 minutes Tuesday night, it was a total flashback, with
zeroes filling up half the scoreboard, and the teams limited to one
single per side, five base runners combined.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the bottom of the fifth inning, the Mariners' David
Bell did his best Buddy Bell impersonation, sending a clutch liner
off the left-field wall to drive in Dan Wilson, who had doubled,
with the game's first _ and some were thinking _ only run. Bell
matched dad in footspeed, too, getting thrown out going for a
double.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was snapped back to reality in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim scored four times over the final two innings and stole
away with a 4-2 decision before a shaggy haired, badly dressed
crowd of 26,153. It turned out to be a very '90s outcome, the
Mariners accepting their fourth consecutive defeat to drop to
35-35.
</P>
<P>
   Any generation will agree: it was fun while it lasted.
</P>
<P>
   For seven innings, Mariners rookie pitcher Freddy Garcia, born
in 1976, showed up with Tom Seaver's arm.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander flirted with the Mariners' first complete game
of the season, and seemingly first in two decades, blazing through
the Anaheim lineup three times with little effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling pretty good,'' he said. ``My fastball, curve and
changeup were all pretty good tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia (8-4) was so unhittable, he retired nine of his first 10
batters and had a one-hitter through five innings, a three-hitter
through seven.
</P>
<P>
   But it all came undone in the eighth after Garcia retired the
first batter. Former Mariner Jeff Huson, hitting for Gary
DiSarcina, doubled to right. Huson scored on Darrin Erstad's single
up the middle. Erstad came around on Randy Velarde's triple to
right-center. Jeff Fassero replaced Garcia and served up a
run-scoring single to Garret Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just held in there and stuck around long enough to get a
couple runs off Garcia,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``I'll
tell you what, he's a tremendous pitcher. He had his changeup
working well all night. We hadn't swung our bats well the whole
game. He just got a couple balls in the middle of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Newly acquired Mariners reliever Allen Watson got his first look
at Garcia. He predicted stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a great one,'' Watson said. ``He throws
pitches for strikes, he throws the ball hard and he's got a great
curveball. ... You don't want to have a performance like that and
have an `L' next to it. He's going to win a lot of games pitching
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia finished with a six-hitter, walking two and striking out
five. He threw 115 pitches, 74 for strikes. He pitched into the
eighth inning for the third time in four outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting better,'' Mariners manager Lou Piniella said.
``He pitched well. What can I tell you?''
</P>
<P>
   With the scoreboard revved up, the teams matched runs to finish
things. The Mariners' Alex Rodriguez doubled home Brian Hunter in
the bottom half of the eighth and Anaheim's Matt Luke homered in
the ninth on Watson's third pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The game might have been more suspenseful had Anaheim starter
Steve Sparks not stuck out his pitching hand to deflect Rodriguez's
hard-hit ball. Rodriguez was thrown out on the play by shortstop
DiSarcina to end the third inning. Sparks tried to warm up the next
inning but couldn't continue, leaving with a bruised right ring
finger. The digit was swollen later, but there was no fracture.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels knuckleballer was superb in his 11-batter outing. At
least Phil Niekro would have approved. Sparks had Mariners flailing
at his slow-speed stuff, permitting only a single by Rodriguez and
walk to Edgar Martinez, both in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Three Anaheim relievers finished up, with the second, Mark
Petkovsek (6-2), getting the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitchers kept us in the game tonight,'' the Angels'
Anderson said. ``When that happens, anything can happen. (Garcia's)
a pretty good pitcher. We just had to stay at it. Fortunately, a
couple pitches went our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was '70s or '90s, time was on their side Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
