<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE LETS DOWN DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Don't worry if you miss a Dodgers game. They will
replay it, and not the taped version on television the next
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the movie ``Groundhog Day.'' Every game seems the
same.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers won two straight, but an off day made that a distant
memory and brought back the realization that this team keeps losing
despite loads of talent.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park pitched well, but the Dodgers didn't hit. They lost
4-1 to San Diego in the opener of a three-game series Tuesday night
at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had seven hits, none of them remotely timely as they
failed in their attempt to win three straight games for the first
time in nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we couldn't get anything going,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``We seemed to be swinging at a lot of bad
pitches. We have to be pretty much perfect against a tough pitcher
because we're not scoring any runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Park (4-5) pitched seven innings, marking the first time this
season starters have thrown a pitch in the seventh inning in five
straight starts. In the last four games, Park, Ismael Valdes,
Darren Dreifort and Kevin Brown allowed eight runs in 341/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dodgers are 2-2 in those games and in search of their
first three-game winning streak since winning five straight April
27 through May 1.
</P>
<P>
   In their last nine games, the Dodgers' lack of offense has
produced more than three runs only twice.
</P>
<P>
   Padres lefty Sterling Hitchcock (5-6) added to that misery with
62/3 innings of one-run ball. And, heck, if not for an ill-advised
dive by Padres center fielder Ruben Rivera, the Dodgers may not
have scored at all.
</P>
<P>
   After giving the Padres a 2-0 lead in the top of the second with
a two-run homer _ the 17th Park has allowed _ Rivera dived for Raul
Mondesi's liner. He didn't come close, the ball rolled to the wall
and Mondesi wound up with a triple. He scored on Devon White's
groundout.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Dodgers had five at-bats with runners in scoring
position and got the ball out of the infield once. Much of it has
to do with patience at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make the pitcher work,'' said Dodgers left fielder
Gary Sheffield, who returned after missing three games with a sore
knee. ``If you don't, it's going to make them that much better. You
can't swing at the first pitch on the black (of the plate). When
you're over-aggressive and swing at the pitcher's pitch, that
doesn't help. That's what young hitters do and veteran pitchers eat
that up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's how Hitchcock breezed through the first six innings and how
Padres reliever Will Cunnane got out of Hitchcock's only jam.
Cunnane retired Adrian Beltre on a grounder to second to end the
seventh inning after Trenidad Hubbard and Eric Young had two-out
singles.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Trevor Hoffman pitched the ninth for his 16th save,
giving him 376 in his Padres career, a club record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got anything going against (Hitchcock),'' said
Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros, who went 2 for 4. ``I see hope.
We haven't done anything yet to warrant that, but I still have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Park (4-5) gave up three runs on five hits despite allowing the
Padres' leadoff batter to reach base in his last five innings.
However, the only thing that hurt Park was a 3-2 pitch to Rivera in
the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest blow the Dodgers struck was on the left hand of
Padres catcher Jim Leyritz. Park hit him with a pitch in the fifth
inning, and X-rays revealed a break that will keep Leyritz out four
to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to throw a strike,'' Park said of Rivera's homer. ``I
was a little down, and he's a low fastball hitter. I'm not supposed
to go to 3-2.''
</P>
</TEXT>
