<HEADLINE>
JUST DON'T LET A BUS CATCH YOU
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Are Muni's bumper-bus drivers accident-prone?
<P>
   A recent Chronicle report noted that one of every nine Muni
drivers/operators has been involved in two or more avoidable
accidents in a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Muni's reaction to the story was interesting: ``Wow, that's
amazing! Holy cow! Where did you get those statistics? From our
files? We have files on that? Where? Oh, those. Gee, we just never
have time to go through that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   A Muni employee sends me a confidential report, with note
attached: Maybe this is one of our accident-prone employees?
</P>
<P>
   The report, dated June 15, from the driver of a 38-Geary bus:
Passenger coughed on operator, and operator claimed injury.
</P>
<P>
   THE SKY IS DRIPPING! At the height of Metreon's opening-weekend
frenzy last Friday evening, a pipe in the ceiling was dripping an
unknown liquid onto the winglike baffles and onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the building didn't pass the flush test, says Sam
Whiting.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, no off-duty Muni drivers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   MRE WHEEE! Lotta Dotz sends along a Brigade Quartermasters
survival-gear catalog. It features an MRE Cookbook, tips on making
the most of those Army surplus Meals Ready to Eat.
</P>
<P>
   Boasts the catalog: ``You can make meals that are not just ready
to eat, but are actually great grub!''
</P>
<P>
   They all sound great. I can't choose between the pheasant under
broken glass and the grub tartare.
</P>
<P>
   X GAMES it ain't. But it is hot international sports action, a
big showdown tournament this week between the Brits and the
Americans. In croquet, at Sonoma Cutrer.
</P>
<P>
   Real croquet _ not the namby-pamby picnic knockabout _ is a
ruthless sport, and the Brits traditionally kick our wickets, but
now we've got genuine stars like Jerry Stark, the head croquet pro
at Meadowood resort in St. Helena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Meadowood is such a hot hideaway that even the gophers on the
croquet lawn book holes months in advance. Guests are so pampered
that in the health spa, along with a stair-climber machine, they
have an elevator machine. You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   X-OUT GAMES: Many local pedestrians aren't stupid, they're
merely clue challenged. While waiting for the light to change in
their favor, they step off the curb and into the active roadway,
where they are a threat to injure innocent cars.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroko Jones wonders, ``Do those extra few steps' advantage over
the other pedestrians earn them bonus points?''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are just born with the soul of a matador.
</P>
<P>
   RUSHIN' ROULETTE: Muni's union protects its drivers, sometimes
to the point of hilarity. But what about passenger rights? If one
of every nine drivers is at least somewhat accident-prone, riders
should know what they're getting into.
</P>
<P>
   We need a simple system. On the front right window of every bus
should be decals showing the driver's accident record over the past
two years, indicated by stickers of pedestrians and/or crumpled
cars.
</P>
<P>
   And in the destination box above the driver window, a clue to
the driver's mood. ``Feelin' undertrained.'' ``Feelin' groovy.''
``Hung over.'' ``High on diesel fumes.'' ``NASCAR dropout.'' Just
give riders a clue. Or, to paraphrase Dr. Evil, ``Would someone
throw us a frikkin' bone here?' ''
</P>
<P>
   DR. EVIL? He's the villain in ``The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' If you
can overlook the bathroom humor, it's a great five-minute movie.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still worth seeing because of Dr. Evil, his disaffected
teenage son Scott and the Dr.'s tiny clone, Mini Me. Dr. Evil might
be the best comedy villain since Dr. Strangelove.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT-TO-LAST CALL: In Emeryville, Calif., the Chinese restaurant
called Bavarian Village has changed hands; now it's Sushi Village.
And Douglas Smith notices that the place advertises ``Vegetarian
Drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Grouses Smith, ``I guess I'll be going elsewhere for my
pork-chop smoothies.''
</P>
<P>
   LAST CALL: In the obits Monday, a notice for David F. Stockman
said in part, ``He will be sorely missed by his brother, his niece,
his many friends, as well as several vodka distillers.''
</P>
<P>
   Brother Bill says David had a great sense of humor and ``I'm
sure his friends will get a kick out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   We need more honesty and humor in epitaphs, in the opinion of
Greg Casserly of the Chron classifieds. ``What nugget of truth
would you like in your obit when the time comes?'' asks Greg.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to keep it simple: ``In his spare time, he was
Batman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
