<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP INSIDERS EMBRACE BUSH AS POTENTIAL SAVIOR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican establishment opened its arms _ and
checkbooks _ Tuesday to welcome Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his
surging presidential campaign to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans are pinning their electoral hopes to Bush's
coattails, and they treated the son of the former president more
like a political savior than one of nearly a dozen candidates
seeking the party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In his first foray to Washington since announcing his candidacy,
Bush met with scores of senators and representatives on Capitol
Hill, where more than half of the Republican lawmakers have
endorsed his candidacy. Later, he attended a record-size
fund-raiser crowded with party power brokers who contributed more
than $2 million to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm through exploring,'' he told the enthusiastic crowd of
more than 2,000. ``I realize it is a huge step to go from being
governor of Texas to president of the United States. But I am
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The warm greeting from Washington insiders carries potential
benefits and risks for Bush. On the one hand, it solidifies his
hold on the Republican nomination and makes it harder for
challengers to attract funds or support.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it ties him to an institution that is quite
unpopular throughout much of the country. Even as Bush accepted
laurels from the beltway's GOP establishment, he exploited
anti-Washington sentiment as a way to distinguish himself from Vice
President Al Gore, the Democratic front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Washington, D.C., person,'' Bush said at campaign stop
in South Carolina. ``He thinks Washington has got all the answers.
I don't. I believe the answers are found in our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he arrived in Washington, Bush took a more diplomatic
approach while still tapping into the disgust that many people have
with the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many across the land look at Washington, and they don't like
what they see,'' Bush said at the fund-raiser, where he was careful
not to criticize the lobbyists, lawmakers, former ambassadors and
other influence-peddlers standing before him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush took aim at President Clinton _ without mentioning
him by name _ and his reputation for political expediency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not use my office as a mirror to reflect public
opinion,'' Bush said to sustained applause. ``The purpose of
politics is not to embarrass your opponents. It is to advance your
ideals, to make a difference, to make America a better nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been endorsed by 126 members of the House and 23
members of the Senate _ an unprecedented level of support for a
nonincumbent more than a year before the nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the closed-door meeting at the Capitol, Bush gave only
cursory remarks, devoting the bulk of his time to gladhanding the
lawmakers and saying how much he looks forward to teaming up with a
Republican majority, according to several participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'd work with them,'' Bush said upon emerging from the
sessions, carefully assuring Republicans that he would not try to
bolster his status at their expense. ``I'm not going to bash the
Republican members of the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps reflecting the public's low opinion of the current
Congress, Bush's campaign staff made sure there were no
opportunities for photos of the governor with the mass of
lawmakers. The lawmakers nevertheless gave strong reviews of his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a unified campaign behind a strong candidate is very
important,'' said Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., who has endorsed
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the past two elections have featured presidential
candidates who were unable to help Republicans win seats in
Congress. He said the presidential candidates had ``written off
California since 1988,'' and he was optimistic that Bush will not
only compete in the West, but that he will be a great help in
electing California Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Cox was one of about 100 representatives, 14 senators and 50
former ambassadors who served on the host committee for the
fund-raiser, the biggest in Washington history. Held at the
Washington Hilton, about a mile from the White House, tables were
removed from the hall to make room for at least 2,000 guests, most
of whom had donated $1,000 _ the maximum allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   The money raised last night adds to a campaign coffer far fatter
than that of any other GOP candidate. By month's end, the Bush
campaign expects to have raised between $15 million and $20
million, according to a senior campaign official. No other
Republican candidate is expected to have raised even half that.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore, who reported $10 million in contributions
through last March, is aiming at a total of $65 million. Campaign
spokesman Roger Salazar said the campaign will divulge its balance
next month, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than dinner, the well-heeled crowd was treated to
tortilla chips, guacamole and brownies, as George Strait sang about
West Texas in music piped over the sound system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen this (kind of) enthusiasm since 1980,'' said
veteran GOP strategist Rich Galen, who directs a party political
action committee known as GOPAC.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was accompanied by his wife, Laura, told those
attending he appreciated their support, particularly coming from
``a town that's not easily impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest applause came when he took an indirect swipe at
Clinton's ethical troubles, saying that if elected, ``I will swear
not only to uphold the law of the land, I will swear to uphold the
dignity of the office to which I have been elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Delivering his standard 25-minute stump speech, Bush called for
reduced taxes, fewer regulations, tort reform, improved schools and
a more powerful military.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
