 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 435 -- June 23, 1999  ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 435 -- June 23, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. DISNEY'S 'TARZAN' SWINGS INTO SUMMER Tarzan is one of the
most indelible images on film and it seems he has graced the screen
forever. Since 1918, just six years after Edgar Rice Burroughs sold
his first version of the story, there have been more than 40 movies
based on the character. But ``Tarzan'' marks the first time the
tale has been brought to feature-length animated life. It was
something Burroughs always wanted; he expressed his desires in a
1936 letter to his son. Any animated film of his most famous
creation, Burroughs wrote, would have to ``approximate Disney
excellence.'' By Renee Graham. From The Boston Globe. 1,300 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
ALFRED THE GREAT : MARTIN LANDAU REMEMBERS
</P>
<P>
   ALFRED HITCHCOCK There aren't a lot of people still around who
worked with legendary director Alfred Hitchcock in his prime. But
Martin Landau is one of them. This year, which marks Hitchcock's
centennial, is also the 40th anniversary of Landau's film debut, in
Hitchcock's classic ``North By Northwest'' (1959.) ``Hitchcock
basically had enormous respect for actors, `` Landau says. 'He was
a provocateur. Some of the things they said about him, that he
treated actors like cattle, that wasn't so.'' By Lawrence Wells.
1,300 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
JULIANNE MOORE'S WALK ON THE WILDE SIDE Julianne Moore has entered
costume drama territory, playing the villainess in the screen
version of Oscar Wilde's famous play ``An Ideal Husband,'' ``The
dialogue was a bigger challenge,'' she says, ``Wilde's language is
inherently theatrical, which is part of the beauty of it, but you
can't do too much of that in a film, because it just doesn't work.
The goal was to make it somewhat naturalistic and more
accessible.'' By Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
RACHEL GRIFFITHS : OUT FROM DOWN UNDER AND HEADED
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE TOP The secret to success for today's Australian actors
seems fairly obvious : Pack a bag, leave home and expect to be away
for years. ``It's good to work overseas,'' says Australian actress
Rachel Griffiths. ``Our industry is very small and it makes sense
to do only one picture a year in Australia, otherwise you get
overexposed.'' Earlier this year she was a Best Supporting Actress
contender for her role as Hilary du Pre, older sister of the late
British cellist Jacqueline du Pre in the film ``Hilary and
Jackie.'' In her new film ``My Son the Fanatic'' she plays a
refreshing variation on the classic hooker-with-a-heart-of-gold.
``I was touched by it and the way in which it juxtaposes love and
compassion against hatred and intolerance,'' she says. By Ivor
Davis. 1,300 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
``WEST-WARD HO!'' KEVIN KLINE GOES WILD WILD Kevin Kline thinks of
himself as a character actor, but he has the dashing good looks of
a leading man. He's a workaholic, but he spends a long time waiting
for good roles to come along and his passion for acting remains
undimmed. When his latest film, the megabudget summer blockbuster
``Wild Wild West'' opens, Kline will be co-starring with Will Smith
as two heroes in post-Civil War America, trying to thwart the evil
plans of mad scientist Arliss Loveless (played by Kenneth Branagh.)
Klein had no hesitation in accepting this comedy role. By Cindy
Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
SAMMY KERSHAW BUILDS TO LAST There's nothing typical about country
singer Sammy Kershaw. Unlike many of his peers, some of whom spent
thousands on ``image consultants'' to make sure they appear as
wholesome and politically correct as possible, with Kershaw, what
you see is what you get. And the 40-year-old singer, who grew up in
the heart of rural Louisiana's Cajun country, likes to keep it that
way. By Michael A. Capozzoli Jr. BPI. 800 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
CYNDI LAUPER : THE WOMAN BENEATH THE BLUE HAIR More than 15 years
since Cyndi Lauper burst onto the music scene with wild orange
hair, punk/retro outfits and the revolutionary idea that ``Girls
Just Want To Have Fun,'' her style is still uncompromising (though
her hair is now blue.) After many years of ups and downs in the
business, she is coming out on top as an entertainer. Lauper speaks
about her life with blunt honesty and cutting humour. By Tamara
Conniff. BPI. 1,100 words + photo.
