<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION TRADE GORTER FOR GORI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The rejuvenation of the Revolution continues.
</P>
<P>
   After slogging through the early part of the season, the
Revolution have demonstrated the potential to be a solid playoff
contender after earning 9 points in the last five games and, more
significant, avoiding regulation-time defeat. And Tuesday they
added Argentine defender Mario Gori in a trade with Miami for Edwin
Gorter, a move that should bolster the defense and change the
team's attacking dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Gori, 26, won two MLS Cup titles with D.C. United after joining
the league from Rosario Central in 1996. He is a dynamic left-sided
player and his presence should not only provide depth but also
allow Ted Chronopoulos to move into midfield as the Revolution
prepare to visit Dallas without suspended left-sided midfielder
Ivan McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter, 35, joined the Revolution as a midfield choreographer
last season and played 28 games, but was forced into a sweeper role
as the team suffered through a nine-game losing streak. He was
suspended for the first two games this season after a practice
incident involving former teammate David Nakhid but was expected to
regain a leadership role on the team.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gorter was substituted in the 55th minute of his first
start, against Columbus April 17, and argued with assistant coach
Giuseppe Galderisi on the sideline. Since then, Gorter has played
the entire game in midfield only once, during a 2-0 loss at
Columbus May 15.
</P>
<P>
   He was moved to sweeper for a 2-0 win over Chicago three weeks
later, then provided the last-minute tying goal against Miami, and
was again benched.
</P>
<P>
   Player-coach Walter Zenga apparently made it clear that Gorter
was not in the team's plans, a decision that likely should have
been made earlier.Though Gorter is among the most experienced and
skillful performers ever to have played for the Revolution, his
style apparently clashed with the expectations of Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second Miami-Revolution deal in two weeks, as
defensive midfielder Carlos Parra joined New England last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gori will rejoin two former D.C. United teammates: John Harkes
and Kris Kelderman.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, major trade speculation regarding Miami has centered
around Revolution striker Joe-Max Moore, who has expressed interest
in playing for the Fusion. A Moore-for-Eric Wynalda trade could
happen after the season. But Moore appears to be finding success
with the Revolution, as he scored his fourth and fifth goals of the
season in a 3-2 victory over Tampa Bay Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally focused on my team and getting to the championship
game at Foxboro Stadium,'' Moore said Tuesday. ``There are always
other possibilities, and any player at age 28 needs to take a look
at all of them. But if I can re-sign with the league at comparable
money to what I am making now, I will probably do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore has been encouraged by the Revolution's recent success.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were losing nine games in a row, it was no fun for
us,'' Moore said. ``The guys are enjoying training more now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivan and Carlos are out for this game but I don't think it
will set us back too much. Everyone is feeling good and
confident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN24-COX     06-23 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Treasured memories of a mom
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When her mother sewed her First Communion dress
35 years ago, Renee Lammers was none too happy _ and she made sure
Mom knew about it. Why did she have to wear a simple, homemade
dress? Her heart was set on one of those confections of tulle and
lace, the kind all the other girls were wearing, with ``so much
crinoline it could stick out sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not to be. Lammers had one of those frugal mothers,
one of those mothers who makes all your clothing. You know the
type, the bane of daughters everywhere: One of those mothers who
saves things.
</P>
<P>
   So when Lammers took her youngest daughter, Tricia, shopping
recently, she braced herself when they passed the rack of First
Communion dresses. She waited for the inevitable plea: ``Mom, why
can't I have one of those dresses?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Tricia noted, ``These dresses have lots of
decorations on them, and mine doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added, ``But my dress has lots of love in it, and these
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 7, Lammers marveled, Tricia had discovered what it
had taken her mother more than 30 years to realize.
</P>
<P>
   Lammers immediately got her mother on the phone in Wausau, Wisc.
Shirley Niederhofer nearly wept with pride. It had taken 35 years,
but here at last was somebody who appreciated her handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   Lammers hadn't given her First Communion dress much thought
until she took it out of blue tissue paper three years ago for
oldest daughter Katie, 10. ``Mom saved it all those years,''
Lammers said.
</P>
<P>
   Lo and behold, the once-scorned finery was beautiful _ simple
and elegant, with a linen top, white-eyelet skirt and matching
jacket. Lammers may have grown out of the dress, but her taste had
grown into it.
</P>
<P>
   The family had moved to Ohio two years ago from Minneapolis.
Although Renee and husband Ted love their new neighborhood, it was
wrenching to leave behind their longtime church, St. Hedwig, a
close-knit Polish parish of about 350 families.
</P>
<P>
   For First Communion, you need more than the white dress and the
well-drilled catechism. You need family, tradition, cousin Marcia
St. Hilaire at the organ and Father Ted Guminga on the altar.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of joining more than 100 communicants last month at
her new parish, Incarnation Church, Tricia formed a Communion class
of one last week at St. Hedwig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Father Ted all my life,'' Lammers said. ``He
baptized me, gave me my First Communion, and performed our marriage
ceremony. Now he has baptized and given First Communion to all
three of my kids. He has been trying to retire, but no one will let
him.''
</P>
<P>
   On the big day, Tricia donned the First Communion dress,
discovering, like her mother before her, that she could twirl its
wide A-line skirt like a square dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Like her mother before her, Tricia renewed her Baptismal vows,
and received a scapular blessed by Father Ted. Her parents couldn't
keep from choking up as they watched their shy daughter perform so
gracefully in the spotlight, wearing her dress not like a
hand-me-down but like the most priceless of family heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, it was _ a legacy of family history and family
love, the gift of mothers who save things.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
