<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Sarge' defends life, dignity of area's homeless
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A friend on my street just had a baby so
I cooked them up a casserole _ shepherd's pie, my specialty _ and I
went down there, bubbling dinner in hand. ``Aren't you sweet!'' she
cooed at me, after we got done cooing at her beautiful boy. And I
went home wearing a smile, a big one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was nice,'' I thought. ``I'm a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Then I met Sarge.
</P>
<P>
   You and I, we might do a little something nice every once in a
while, when time or spirit moves us. But Sarge Huffman? He does
something nice every day of his life. Every day!
</P>
<P>
   He puts me to shame, that Sarge.
</P>
<P>
   About three years ago Sarge, a 50-year-old veteran, decided he
was going to take care of the homeless in Palm Beach County. He
knew he couldn't reach them all. He also knew he could very well
try. So he started working with Pastor Tim Bumgardner over at the
Palm Beach Worship Center. Sarge and Pastor Tim opened the City of
Refuge network, and what they do is both simple and enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Every day they take food and supplies to the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The first homeless man Sarge ever met was an old guy named
Popps. Popps was about 85 and he'd lived under the bridge at the
Lake Worth Canal for about 14 years. Like most of Sarge's street
friends, Popps had nothing, nothing at all. Then Popps met Sarge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next few weeks, I didn't just see a person,'' says
Sarge. ``I saw my grandfather.'' Today, Popps lives in a nice
trailer and has himself a bank account. Sarge loves to tell that
story.
</P>
<P>
   Sarge says this is his calling, and when you talk to him _
believer in God or not _ you have to at least believe in a person's
calling. At first all the people with regular paychecks and
air-conditioned cubicles gave him a hard time because Sarge and
Pastor Tim are what the establishment calls a ``faith group.'' And
those Bible thumpers, they're awful hard to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to beat down doors to get any attention,'' says Sarge.
</P>
<P>
   But now when you call the establishment, the folks there give
you Sarge's number. ``He'll know whatever you need to know,'' they
say. And he does.
</P>
<P>
   He knows where they sleep, how they smell. Sarge knows the
demons of their pasts. By conservative estimates, there are about
3,000 homeless people in Palm Beach County. Some say the number is
surely 2 1/2 times that, since it's hard to count the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go home and cry,'' Sarge says. ``I still cry
sometimes, like after what they did with Ronald.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald F. Neuendank, 57, was a homeless man who was sleeping in
his camp over by Summit Boulevard one night back in May when some
teenagers, supposedly mad because Neuendank had mooned them, poured
black tar all over him. Sarge took him to the new veteran's
hospital _ the one that used to ask for all these homeless guys'
discharge papers, their DD214s, until Sarge knocked some sense into
their heads _ and the medical folks there cleaned Neuendank up.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sarge and Pastor Tim tracked down Neuendank's brother.
``They thought he was dead,'' Sarge says. But he wasn't. Sarge sent
Ronald home to Wassau, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, someone will stop Sarge and ask him why
he does what he does. Someone like me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get a phone call at 10 o'clock at night from someone
who says they've been straight now for a year, that's like hitting
the lottery,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That Sarge. Someone should take him a casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
