<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6348 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLD-TRICKS24-COX     06-23 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-TRICKS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At 82, magician is still up to his old tricks
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's all an illusion, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The old man doesn't really turn a one-dollar bill into a fifty.
If he could do that, he wouldn't be sitting in his small kitchen in
West Palm Beach, surrounded by dusty clutter and faded photos
affixed to the walls with cracked and yellowed tape.
</P>
<P>
   He can't really foretell the future, but when he puts a deck of
cards face down on the table and says, ``Go ahead, pick the jack of
clubs,'' and you pull a card at random from the pile and flip it
over and it's the jack of clubs, you wonder.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Peter Gross. He's 82. Illusion has been his life
since he dropped out of high school in 1931 after seeing a guy
named The Great Cardini perform sleight of hand.
</P>
<P>
   He has made a living at prestidigitation, a meager living he
says. He was never a star, never played the big Vegas hotels or
Catskill resorts. Weddings, wakes and wingdings might better
describe his venues. Birthday parties. Fund raisers. Jerry Lewis
telethons.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite possesion is an old manila folder stuffed with
thank-you notes from hospitals and charities. The letters date from
1962 _ typed on a manual typewriter _ to 1998. They are brief
notes. But they speak to Gross. And say something about him, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 40 years, I did parties at big houses all over Palm Beach,
Miami, Boca. I knew Burt Reynolds before he was on Gunsmoke.
Ricardo Montalban. Governor Claude Kirk was my friend, used to eat
breakfast with him in Palm Beach, almost 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew them all.''
</P>
<P>
   But those old friends stopped calling and the magic jobs went
begging after Peter Gross was convicted of selling knock-off
watches and suitcases out of his house. That was 1995. And again in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   He's 82 and on probation for five years. The judge wanted to
send him to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it. I'm a convicted felon. It was a mistake,'' he says.
``Social Security and playing birthday parties didn't pay the
bills. I sold fake Gucci, fake Rolex watches, fake Louis Vuitton
luggage. My customers were cops, a New Hampshire judge, ladies at
beauty parlors, everybody. And rich people too cheap to buy the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted the illusion, didn't they? And I gave it to them.
But could I sell the stuff if nobody wanted to buy it?''
</P>
<P>
   He recounts his past _ three years in a Civilian Conservation
Corps camp, four years in the Army, two marriages _ while attired
in a Kelley green sports jacket, a print shirt and plaid pants.
There is no illusion of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made $10 a month in the CCC. Not much more in the Army. Made
a little on the side playing cards. But I never dealt from the
bottom, no funny business. One, I didn't have to. I was a good card
player. Two, they'd break your arms. Anyway, everyone knew what I
could do with a deck.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1975 a head-on crash at milepost 18 on Florida's Turnpike
killed Gross' brother and left Gross with a dozen smashed bones.
His hands were spared. He went on disability _ Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing 60 and in the hospital for four months, he finally faced
the fact that he'd never be headlining on the Vegas Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, you'll find Gross working his magic on Clematis
Street, being tossed the odd dollar from bar patrons wandering from
one revitalized urban watering hole to the next. You'll also find
him at local nursing homes, where he puts a little magic back into
the lives of old people, some of whom were dealt bad hands.
</P>
<P>
   We all have to play the cards we're dealt in life. It looks like
Peter Gross deals his own. But even when it appears you deal
yourself the hand, you still have to play it. When it comes to
life, Gross, like many old men, plays a great deal of solitaire.
</P>
<P>
   His dog, a big black fluffy mutt, sits at his feet. The dog's
name is Whitey. Gross likes blatant irony, the sort you don't have
to think about.
</P>
<P>
   He rolls out one-liners as if Henny Youngman were his coach:
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't see the card disappear? And you drive a car?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I only play cards when I need money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You wanna play cards? I'll return half your losses. Such a
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He asks a visitor to write something, anything, on a playing
card. He stands in the next room, his back to the visitor. Now put
the card back in the deck, he says. He returns to the room,
shuffles the deck. Then he reaches into his breast pocket, pulls
out a sealed envelope. Tears it open. The card tumbles out.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive, but you need an audience for this. Otherwise, you're
just fooling yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two grown daughters,'' he says, as he shuffles a deck.
``They grew up with their grandmother, in Canada. But I visit them,
and the grandchildren come here. See, on the wall? That's a family
portrait, done by Mort Kaye.''
</P>
<P>
   He drops more names. Actors, singers, politicians, Shep and
Curley of the Three Stooges. They're all dead.
</P>
<P>
   A Life magazine is on the table, along with the morning's
dishes, tea cups, old photo albums, newspapers, pens, pencils and
decks of cards. The Life magazine is from 1939. ``I gotta catch up
with my reading,'' says Gross.
</P>
<P>
   His remaining knock-off inventory is stacked in a corner _ a few
plastic brief cases, thick with dust. ``I think I need help
cleaning up the place, but my cleaning lady just quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Always the joker.
</P>
<P>
   You sit with Gross for an hour and you realize he can do
something so many old people who live in old houses with old
memories can't. He can conjure an illusion, at will, in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Aristotle said a convincing impossibility was preferable to an
unconvincing possibility. That's what puts the magic in magic.
That's what packs the audience into the theater, fills the house.
</P>
<P>
   That's what keeps an old man laughing in an empty house.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
