</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported recently about a lottery drawing of sorts for
two free tickets to the Masters golf tournament each year. You gave
an address, but I lost the clipping. Can you print the information
again?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a bit of a misstatement. There is no lottery drawing
for two free tickets to the Masters. What we have printed in the
past is information about a random drawing for tickets to the
Masters practice rounds. To enter, send a letter with your name,
address, daytime telephone number and Social Security number to:
Masters Tournament, Practice Rounds, P.O. Box 2047, Augusta, GA
30903-2047. To hear recorded information, call 706-667-6700.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all the news about the computer virus problems, can you
offer any update on David L. Smith, the author of Melissa? I
recently read that damage estimates from Melissa were more than
$400 million.
</P>
<P>
   A: Smith, a 30-year-old network programmer for an AT&AMP;T
subcontractor, was arrested April 1 at his brother's house in New
Jersey. He was released on $100,000 bail. At last report,
arraignment had not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey authorities charged Smith with five crimes, including
interruption of public communication. They allege that he wrote the
Melissa software bug _ apparently named by him after a topless
dancer in Florida _ with malicious intent, knowing the chaos it
would cause. For a time, the virus clogged e-mail accounts and shut
down computer networks worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's attorney, Steve Altman, contends that his client never
intended to do harm. Smith faces as much as 40 years in prison and
a $480,000 fine, according to New Jersey authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that the Chelsea Flower Show in England will be
the subject of a TV program in the United States this summer. Do
you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Chelsea Flower Show,'' featuring coverage of the 1998
event, will be rebroadcast at 5 p.m. Aug. 29 on HGTV (Home &AMP; Garden
Television), according to Lisa DeMille, spokeswoman for the cable
network.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When the Census Bureau gets information from everyone, does
it share that with anyone else, or sell it to commercial interests?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The agency says it ``never shares'' the answers given on
census forms and keeps them ``strictly confidential.'' The
information collected provides only local area data needed for
communities to receive federal program funds and for private sector
and community planning, the bureau adds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Henry Aaron hit 715 home runs, a phenomenal feat. Can you
list which teams he was playing for when he amassed this total, and
the years?
</P>
<P>
   A: Aaron's career total was 755 home runs, in 12,364 at-bats,
while he was playing for the Milwaukee/Atlanta Braves (National
League) and the Milwaukee Brewers (American League). These are the
year-by-year statistics:
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Braves: 1954 (13 home runs); '55 (27); '56 (26); '57
(44); '58 (30); '59 (39); '60 (40); '61 (34); '62 (45); '63 (44);
'64 (24); '65 (32).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves: 1966 (44); '67 (39); '68 (29); '69 (44); '70
('38); '71 (47); '72 (34); '73 (40); '74 (20).
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Brewers: 1975 (12); '76 (10).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently published a breakdown of Henry Aaron's home runs
by team and year. Can you do the same for Babe Ruth? Also, can you
compare their number of Major League career games and at-bats?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ruth's teams, with years followed by the number of home runs:
</P>
<P>
   Boston Red Sox: 1914 (0); '15 (4); '16 (3); '17 (2); '18 (11);
'19 (29).
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees: 1920 (54); '21 (59); '22 (35); '23 (41); '24
(46); '25 (25); '26 (47); '27 (60); '28 (54); '29 (46); '30 (49);
'31 (46); '32 (41; '33 (34); '34 (22);
</P>
<P>
   Boston Braves: 1935 (6).
</P>
<P>
   In 23 years, Aaron played in 3,298 games , with 12,364 at-bats.
In 22 years, Ruth played in 2,503 games, with 8,399 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just returned from Ireland, where food products from
Belgium have been banned indefinitely because of possible dioxin
contamination. Is there any such ban on those foods in the United
States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Two government agencies, the Food and Drug
Administration and the Department of Agriculture, are involved. The
United States, like most nations, banned beef, poultry, pork, eggs,
milk, game meat and byproducts from Belgium after it was discovered
that large quantities may have been contaminated by cancer-causing
dioxin. As The Associated Press put it, ``Belgium's gastronomic
reputation has taken a nosedive from Malaysia to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Dioxin is suspected of having spread from tainted animal feed
into all the animals that ate it, as well as all the products made
with those animals.
</P>
<P>
   In a notice dated June 11, the USDA's Food Safety and Inspection
Service reported that it continues, as a precautionary measure, to
hold all poultry and pork products from the European Union shipped
since January. No beef slaughtered in the European Union is
imported into the United States either, the agency added.
</P>
<P>
   Information is available online at www.fda.gov and www.usda.gov
explaining the two federal agencies' actions in response to the
scare.
</P>
<P>
   Q: U.S. Rep. Bob Barr is always in the news, but I've never seen
what congressional committees he is assigned to. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: Barr (R-Ga.) serves on three committees: Banking and
Financial Services; Government Reform and Oversight; and Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a World War II veteran. How can I get my medals replaced?
I've lost them over the years.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Department of Veterans Affairs says medals awarded while
in active service are issued by the appropriate service if
requested by veterans (or by next of kin, if the veteran is
deceased).
</P>
<P>
   Navy, Marine Corps, Coast Guard: Requests should be sent to the
U.S. Navy Liaison Office, National Personnel Records Center, Room
3475, 9700 Page Ave., St. Louis, MO 63132-5100.
</P>
<P>
   Army: U.S. Army Reserve Personnel Center, Attn: ARPC-VSE, (same
street address, city and ZIP code as above).
</P>
<P>
   Air Force: Military Personnel Records, National Personnel
Records Center, (same address).
</P>
<P>
   The veteran's full name should be printed or typed. The request
must contain the signature of the veteran or, if deceased, the
signature of the next of kin. Include the veteran's branch of
service, service number or Social Security number, and exact or
approximate date of service. If available, include a copy of the
discharge or separation document (WDAGO Form 53-55 or DD Form 214).
</P>
<P>
   If possible, send the request on Standard Form 180, Request
Pertaining To Military Records. These forms are available from VA
offices or veterans organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a recent full-page newspaper ad, the National Association
of Letter Carriers stated that the Postal Service refuses to offer
letter carriers a satisfactory contract. My question: How many
people still deliver mail on foot, compared to those using
vehicles?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Postal Service calculates by routes, not people, because
in a typical work week more than one person likely would be
involved on the same route. Nationwide, the number of ``motor
routes'' is 150,871, said Mark Saunders at USPS headquarters in
Washington. The number of ``walk routes'' is 15,840.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a recipe calling for apple cider vinegar. What's the
difference between that and apple cider?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the United States, the term ``apple cider'' usually refers
to freshly prepared apple juice that is bottled without
pasteurization. (Products labeled ``apple juice'' usually have been
pasteurized during bottling). Vinegar is a fermented product. If
your recipe calls for the vinegar product, don't substitute cider
or juice and expect the same results.
</P>
<P>
   The Foods &AMP; Nutrition Encyclopedia explains how apple cider
vinegar is produced: Apples basically are mechanically crushed and
pressed and adjusted to contain not less than 8 percent, and not
more than 20 percent, fermentable sugar. After fermentation by
yeast, the sugar content preferably should be below 0.3 percent.
Next, this alcohol-containing substrate is subjected to the action
of acetobacter organisms until the alcohol is converted to acetic
acid, following which the vinegar is clarified, possibly
pasteurized and then bottled.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
