<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6357 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIVA-OVERKILL24-COX     06-23 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVA-OVERKILL24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overdone on divas
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A true story: Just a few weeks into my
chosen career as a music critic, I reviewed a performance by
Leontyne Price, the legendary soprano whose best years were well
behind her. The piece was balanced, but it did make the point of
noting Price's high opinion of herself: I stopped counting the
number of bows she milked from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The morning the review ran, I got a call. In a dignified voice,
a woman greeted me with a simple, ``This is Leontyne Price.'' I
sputtered something about her feeling free to complain to my
editor, then proceeded to hang up the phone frozen with fear.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a friend's wicked idea of a joke, but it
taught me an invaluable lesson: Don't mess with a diva.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these days you don't have to look very far to find
this paragon of feminine showmanship. Thanks largely to two VH1
concert specials _ Divas Live and Divas Live '99 _ women singers of
a larger-than-life variety are in the news: Aretha, Celine,
Whitney, Mariah... the list goes on and on. And let's not forget
Cher, the self-proclaimed ``Lazarus of pop music,'' who comes to
the National Car Rental Center this weekend after her surprise
return to the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't stop there. Everywhere you turn, there's another
new diva on the scene _ or an established singer who's suddenly
been anointed with the title. Looking for a country diva? Shania
Twain's got your number. How about a couple of divas-in-training?
Consider Brandy and Monica, who teamed up recently on The Boy Is
Mine, a catfight of a single that played into the pair's rumored
rivalry. And then there's Jewel, the sweet-singing folk diva who's
been on the cover of Time.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a sec: A ``folk diva''? Isn't that a contradiction in
terms? An oxymoron of the most moronic sort?
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: We're sick of divas. Not the real divas, but the
pretenders. And we're not too happy about what this tired trend has
to say about the role of women in the musical world, if not society
in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's silliness,'' says Rolling Stone contributing editor
Anthony DeCurtis of this diva deluge. ``It's just a way of putting
a name on something.''
</P>
<P>
   That something doesn't have to be singing. A story in
Entertainment Weekly last October looked at the phenomenon and
found divas everywhere, from ``daytime divas'' (Kathie Lee Gifford,
Susan Lucci) to ``indie divas'' (Parker Posey, Christina Ricci) to
``divas on ice'' (``Everyone named Oksana'').
</P>
<P>
   Even some feminists have gotten in the act: Holly Morris, a book
publisher-turned-TV producer, runs a Seattle-based company called
Adventure Divas, which is creating a travel series for cable TV on
divas worldwide. She's written about the trend in the upcoming
issue of Ms. Magazine and finds nothing wrong with all the diva
labeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think it means a prima donna. (But) it's a word
that has emerged in popular culture in the last five years to have
a much more positive meaning. To me, it's a lot about potential,''
Morris says. The list of divas she's uncovered in her travels
includes a filmmaker and a Santeria priestess. ``They sing their
own song even if they're not musicians,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Gretchen Barbatsis, a Michigan State University
professor of telecommunications and leading feminist scholar, says
the problem is that women are still being categorized. ``What I
think is significant is that the apparently empowered woman is
labeled in a singular kind of way, which tends to deny her
three-dimensional richness,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   If you look up ``diva'' in the dictionary, the first definition
refers to the word's Italian origin as ``goddess.'' Still, it's the
operatic world that can take true credit for turning diva into a
title. Scholars trace the term's use in music to 1831, the year
Bellini wrote the aria Casta diva for the opera Norma. By the mid
20th-century, a diva meant only one thing: a female singer,
preferably a soprano, whose expansive voice was matched by her
personality. If she threw an occasional hissy fit, it went along
with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than being a great singer, it's being a great
artist,'' says Valerie Stoelzel, Palm Beach Opera's music
administrator and a soprano herself (she insists, however, she's
not a diva).
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Arnold, a South Florida baritone who has worked
alongside his share of divas _ ask him about the Carmen who refused
to enter from stage right _ puts it this way: ``There are
performers and there are divas.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one opera star who fit the diva mold, it was Maria
Callas, the tempestuous soprano whose battles with opera-house
execs garnered as much attention as her voice. Other operatic names
frequently cited include Marilyn Horne, Joan Sutherland and, more
recently, Kathleen Battle, whose temper tantrums caused her to be
permanently banished from the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a long way from these women to the likes of LeAnn Rimes
and Chaka Khan, to name two of the featured artists on VH1's Divas
Live `99. How to explain the leap?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, VH1 president Wayne Isaak, the man behind both Divas
specials, makes no bones about the fact that the shows were
basically a marketing gimmick. The cable network had produced a
series of concerts it called Legends, honoring great artists and
their work for charity, but the idea didn't catch fire. Then, Isaak
noticed the number of female artists in the spotlight _ ``Celine
was as popular as a female singer could be, Aretha was probably in
the best voice she's been in her life, Mariah was continuing on a
hot streak'' _ and a new concept emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Let's get the girls together and see if by theming
it, we have a bigger rating,''' he recalls of the first special in
1998, which also featured Gloria Estefan and Shania Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Isaak got far more than just a bigger rating. The show proved to
be the most-watched moment in VH1's history and a recording
released soon after sold three million copies. Thus was born a new
diva consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   As ratings-driven as VH1 was, the show touched a nerve _ perhaps
the same nerve that was behind the success of Sarah McLachlan's
all-female Lilith Fair when it bowed in 1997. Women were enjoying
an unprecedented level of acceptance in the music world. It was
time to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reviving the diva term is a way of allowing these women a kind
of power that had only rarely been accorded them,'' says Rolling
Stone's DeCurtis. As for any negative stereotype associated with
the word _ the female artist as cry-baby or bitch _ DeCurtis says
it has long been erased. For better or worse, it's becomes a point
of pride.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there seems no denying that diva has lost some
of its luster. ``Add `diva' to the list of words _ along with
`classic,' `frankly' and `original' _ that are well on their way to
devaluation,'' wrote Jon Pareles in his New York Times review of
the VH1 Divas Live `99. He was noting the parade of would-be divas
on stage, but producer Isaak says such criticism misses the mark:
Now that diva has gone mainstream, why not have fun with the
concept, he argues?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our society today to bend and stretch labels
because it's entertaining,'' Isaak says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, scholar Barbatsis isn't amused. As far as she's
concerned, all this diva labeling isn't advancing the cause of
women in a male-dominated music world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be seductive to think (the labeling) is providing a
point of resistance,'' she says, but at best it's offering a few
carefully chosen women a greater degree of prominence. She likens
the situation to that of black athletes: All their individual
success notwithstanding, how has that affected the white power base
of owners and executives in professional sports? ``It doesn't look
to me like it's done a whole lot,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   For all this talk of difficult and demanding female singers,
there are just as many ``divos'' out there. Consider the rockers
who trash their hotel rooms _ or smash their instruments on stage.
Little wonder VH1's Isaak is thinking of expanding the concept next
year to include two specials _ one on men, the other women.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not also forget the classical world: When it comes to
choice dressing-room assignments, the Palm Beach Opera's Stoelzel
says she's apt to get as many complaints from tenors as sopranos.
And then there's a certain rotund Italian singer who definitely
qualifies as larger-than-life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't call Pavarotti a divo,'' says local baritone Malcolm
Arnold, ``but in every sense of the word, he is one.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passy writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
