<HEADER>
A6358 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-GOODWILLJEANS     06-23 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-GOODWILLJEANS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Goodwill hunting (for bargain jeans)
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Would you climb out of your Calvins to
wear a pair of bluejeans made in Miami by Goodwill workers?
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill's G.I. Pride jeans, selling for the patriotic price of
$17.76, go on sale July 4 at 17 Miami-Dade County Goodwill stores.
</P>
<P>
   If G.I. Pride sells well in Miami-Dade, the jeans will be rolled
out to 1,600 Goodwill stores nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're as qualified to make a good pair of jeans as anyone
else,'' says Dennis Pastrana, South Florida Goodwill Industries
president.
</P>
<P>
   At the Goodwill Industries factory, a converted Postal Service
warehouse near Miami's Orange Bowl, workers have been turning out
1,400 pairs of Marine and Army fatigues daily for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes 72 steps to make a pair of fatigue pants,'' says
Pastrana, ``and it takes 29 steps to make a pair of jeans.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miami Goodwill can't sell too many jeans, say industry
watchers, or they'll get slaughtered on the toughest turf in the
fashion biz.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've chosen to dive into the shark tank, and what they have
to hope is they stay small enough that the sharks won't come take a
bite out of them,'' says Erik Gordon, director of the University of
Florida's Retail Center, where trends are tracked and taught.
</P>
<P>
   Being Goodwill, insiders say, doesn't foster industry-wide
goodwill when big bucks are at stake. An estimated 600 million
jeans were sold in the U.S. last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a really, really rotten war,'' says Gordon. ``They shoot at
anybody, missionary priests, vehicles with Red Cross on the side.
When it's brutal, there's nobody who's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill plans to ``fly under (industry) radar,'' Pastrana says,
making only 400,000 pairs in a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana says he just wants to sell enough jeans to create 500
jobs for disabled workers. The transitional jobs would allow
workers to learn, establish a work history, and, it's hoped, merge
into the mainstream work force. The Goodwill garment workers can
make $5.50 to $9 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, who came to Miami from Cuba as a 23-year-old
accountant in 1961, is a feisty underdog who isn't wandering into a
war he doesn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let anyone in the fashion industry tell you it takes
rocket scientists to make these,'' he says, patting a stack of G.I.
Pride. ``We already make the toughest pants in the world for the
toughest outfit in the world,'' he adds, referring to the Army and
Marine fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   G.I. Pride jeans were designed by Sylvia Dardon, who ran a Liz
Claiborne plant in Guatemala for 25 years. Workers have been
turning out 100 pairs of jeans daily since January to prepare for
the July launch.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana says his jeans are as good as any competitor's, but he
knows there's no way he can compete with huge jeans marketing
budgets. Tommy Hilfiger, Gitano and Levis, for instance, have all
sponsored recent concert tours.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, though, is set to approach marquee Miami natives in
the sports and music businesses for help.
</P>
<P>
   And there's always the marketing wild card, says George
Rosenbaum, CEO of Leo Shapiro &AMP; Associates, a Chicago consumer
research firm. If an unsolicited, hot, hip-hop star just happens to
wear the jeans, G.I. Pride could soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this became a cultish, underground product,'' says
Rosenbaum, ``they could capture 5 percent of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
