<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6359 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS24-TAKE     06-23 1840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS24-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: A TV announcer discussing the wedding of Prince Edward and
Sophie Rhys-Jones said Britain's new poet laureate had composed a
poem calling for their privacy. Who is the poet, and can you print
the poem?
</P>
<P>
   A: The poet is Andrew Motion, 47. He succeeded Ted Hughes,
Britain's former poet laureate, who died of cancer in October. This
is Motion's first official poem, titled ``Epithalamium St. George's
Chapel, Windsor'':
</P>
<P>
   One day, the tissue-light through stained glass falls/ on vacant
stone, on gaping pews, on air/ made up of nothing more than atom
storms/ which whiten silently, then disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The next, all this is charged with brimming life./ A
people-river floods those empty pews,/ and music-torrents break _
but then stop dead/ to let two human voices make their vows:/
</P>
<P>
   to work _ so what is true today remains the truth;/ to hope _
for privacy and what its secrets show;/ to trust _ that all the
world can offer it will give;/ to love _ and what it has to
understand to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that movie actress Susan Hayward is buried in
Georgia. Do you know where?
</P>
<P>
   A: Her final resting place is Our Lady of Perpetual Help
Catholic Church outside Carrollton. The actress (``I Want to
Live,'' ``With a Song in My Heart'' and dozens of other films) died
March 14, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   A church spokeswoman said many people continue to visit the
actress' burial site. The church is at 210 Old Center Point Road,
about 5 miles off I-20 at exit 4. At Hayward's request, the
tombstone bears the name Mrs. F.E. Chalkley (Her second husband,
after actor Jess Barker, was Carrollton businessman Floyd Eaton
Chalkley). Because of the number of visitors, the church has added
a small marble stone with the name Susan Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Christian Coalition is in trouble and I'd like to help.
What is the address to send a donation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Christian Coalition, 1801-L Sara Drive, Chesapeake, VA 23320.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Newspapers reported recently on a UCLA award to blacklisted
writers. What was the blacklist all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: It dealt with a move in the spring of 1947 by the House
Committee on Un-American Activities to undertake what its chairman,
Rep. J. Parnell Thomas (R-N.J.), called ``Communism in motion
pictures.'' While the accusation that films of the period contained
Communist propaganda was generally discredited, there was at least
one factual substance to the charge. A number of famous Hollywood
directors, screenwriters and actors either joined the Communist
Party or contributed funds to its cause during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these people had dropped their affiliations before the
House committee convened, but in September 1947 some 20 witnesses
named people who, they claimed, were leftists. On the strength of
that cooperative testimony, about 40 filmmakers suspected of
leftist sympathies were subpoenaed to appear before the committee.
The committee said it had evidence that 10 of the filmmakers were
members of the Communist Party. The 10 refused to testify, and were
given prison sentences of six months to a year for contempt of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of the infamous practice of
``blacklisting,'' meaning that many people _ eventually more than
320 _ were fired and no longer permitted to work in the American
movie industry. The practice continued into the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the recent UCLA award to the 10 screenwriters was
sparked by a controversial award presented to director Elia Kazan
at this year's Academy Awards ceremony. Kazan had testified before
the House committee.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that President Clinton enjoyed some of
France's ``famed cuisine'' at a dinner in Paris recently with
French President Jacques Chirac. The restaurant wasn't identified.
Was it Maxim's?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The two presidents, and their wives, dined at Chez L'Ami,
a bistro on a narrow street in a working-class neighborhood on the
Right Bank. The next day, Clinton told reporters that they had a
``wonderful dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Elysee Palace described the meal as cured ham and fois gras from
the Landes region in southwest France, followed by roasted milk-fed
lamb with bearnaise potatoes and girolles mushrooms. The wine was a
1990 Saint-Julien. Fruit finished off the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The WNBA's All-Star game will be played in New York next
month. Do you have ticket information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tickets for the inaugural All-Star Game on July 14 are
available at all Ticketmaster outlets, as well as Ticketmaster
Charge-By-Phone (212-307-7171); through the Ticketmaster Web site
(www.ticketmaster.com); at the game site, Madison Square Garden;
and in New York at the NBA Store, Fifth Avenue at 52nd Street.
Tickets are $10, $30, $40 and $75 (plus surcharges if purchased
from Ticketmaster). The game will be televised nationally on ESPN,
starting at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   More ticket information is available from Madison Square Garden
at 212-465-6741.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you update us on the status of DNA testing in the case of
former Green Beret Jeffrey MacDonald? He was convicted of killing
his wife and two children at Fort Bragg, N.C., in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   A: U.S. District Court Judge James Fox in Wilmington, N.C.,
ruled in March that a new kind of DNA test could be performed on
evidence from the murder scene. Andrew Good, one of MacDonald's
attorneys, described the testing as the same type that was used to
try to connect President Thomas Jefferson with Sally Heming, a
slave.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CBS' ``This Morning'' on March 29, Good said it
would be ``a matter of months'' before his team could identify the
laboratories that would do the testing on hairs found at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The case dates to Feb. 17, 1970, when MacDonald's pregnant wife,
Colette, and their two young children, Kimberly and Kristy, were
murdered in their beds. MacDonald, a physician stationed at Fort
Bragg, claimed intruders beat and stabbed him and then killed his
family. Charges against MacDonald were dropped after a military
hearing, but in 1979 he was tried and convicted in a civilian
court. He was sentenced to three life terms, but released in 1980
after an appeal. Two years later the Supreme Court reinstated his
conviction and sent him back to prison, where he has remained.
MacDonald's case inspired the best-selling book and TV miniseries
``Fatal Vision.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald has a Web site _ www.TheMacDonaldDefense.Org/ _ with a
message on the subject of DNA testing posted by him on March 22.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Episodes of the '60s TV show ``The Prisoner'' were shown the
other night on TVLand. What was the actual location of the village?
</P>
<P>
   A: For those who don't know, let's rehash the essentials of the
plot. Intriguing, highly imaginative and at times complex, ``The
Prisoner'' concerned a secret agent, presumably named John Drake
(we say presumably because his name wasn't revealed, but this
series was a continuation from the last episode of another program,
``Secret Agent,'' which featured Patrick McGoohan as Drake).
</P>
<P>
   Assigned to locate a missing scientist, Drake allowed him to
defect to Russia when he discovered the nature of the scientist's
work: the completion of a deadly mind-transference device. Drake
was gassed, and upon waking found himself the prisoner of a
self-contained community known as The Village, a fantasylike area
bounded by mountains and an ocean, a place from which there was no
escape. He discovered that he was no longer a man, but a number:
No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which had 17 episodes, was filmed almost entirely
at Portmeirion, North Wales. ``The Prisoner'' initially was
broadcast by CBS from June 1, 1968, to Sept. 21, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that MGM recently bought back its film library from
Turner Broadcasting. What effect will this have on Turner Classic
Movies, which shows these films?
</P>
<P>
   A: The film library has not been sold back to MGM, said TBS
spokeswoman Kara Franey, so there will be no effect on Turner
Classic Movies. MGM has taken back only the distribution of home
videos, which may account for the confusion, Franey said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Tom Hanks, appearing on the Blockbuster Entertainment Awards
June 16, gave a toll-free number for people to call to contribute
to the World War II Memorial in Washington. I want to make a
donation in honor of my late father, a World War II veteran, but I
didn't get the number. Do you have it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call 1-800-639-4992. The first voice you'll hear is that of
Hanks, star of the World War II epic ``Saving Private Ryan,'' in a
recorded greeting. Donations to the memorial can be made by calling
that number, or can be mailed to World War II Memorial, P.O. Box
96766, Washington, DC 20090-6766. If you're online, try this
address _ www.wwIImemorial.com _ for more information and to make
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Although I'm a staunch Democrat, I had been seriously
considering Sen. John McCain, if he gets the Republican
presidential nomination. However, I heard that he made a derogatory
remark about Chelsea Clinton. Do you have any details, so I can
decide if he is worthy of my consideration?
</P>
<P>
   A: The remark by McCain (R-Ariz.), which was said to be a slur
against the looks of Hillary Rodham Clinton, Chelsea Clinton and
Janet Reno, was made more than a year ago. News of his offending
quip first appeared in The Washington Post's Reliable Sources
political column June 12, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Post, which did not report the content of the remark, quoted
McCain as saying this afterward: ``Yes. I made a very unfortunate
and insensitive remark. It was the wrong thing to do, and I have no
excuse for it.'' His spokeswoman, Nancy Ives, said at the time that
a letter of apology had been delivered to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, then Clinton's press secretary, said Clinton
considered McCain's apology letter to be heartfelt. ``The president
certainly understands how you get caught saying things you
ordinarily wouldn't have said,'' McCurry added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about a recall or class-action
suit of some type concerning Louisiana-Pacific siding?
</P>
<P>
   A: The case involved compensation for the cost to homeowners of
repairing damage to exterior Louisiana-Pacific Inner-Seal siding
installed between the mid-1980s and Jan. 1, 1996. Eligible
claimants must file a claim before Jan. 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   To hear recorded information from the claims administrator for
the settlement program, call 1-800-245-2722. Or write: L-P
Inner-Seal Siding Litigation, P.O. Box 3240, Portland, OR 97208.
Online information _ available at www.lpsidingclaims.com _ includes
complete details about the litigation and settlement forms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
