<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Larry L. King (the one who wrote
``Best Little Whorehouse in Texas,'' not the little guy on TV)
doesn't fight anymore, except maybe with book publishers and that's
mostly on the phone. But he tells a good story about fighting,
involving a particular fellow Southern author. (Murray, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ In suggesting that public policy must
submit to particularized faith, the gun lobby has placed us on an
amazingly smooth slope, debating all the while how many angels can
dance on the pointy end of a bullet. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ For First Communion, you need
more than the white dress and the well-drilled catechism. You need
family, tradition, cousin Marcia St. Hilaire at the organ and
Father Ted Guminga on the altar. Her parents couldn't keep from
choking up as they watched their shy daughter perform so gracefully
in the spotlight, wearing her dress not like a hand-me-down but
like the most priceless of family heirlooms. Which, of course, it
was _ a legacy of family history and family love, the gift of
mothers who save things. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A friend on my street
just had a baby so I cooked them up a casserole _ shepherd's pie,
my specialty _ and I went down there, bubbling dinner in hand.
``Aren't you sweet!'' she cooed at me, after we got done cooing at
her beautiful boy. And I went home wearing a smile, a big one.
``That was nice,'' I thought. ``I'm a good person.'' Then I met
Sarge. Sarge says tending to the needs of the homeless is his
calling, and when you talk to him _ believer in God or not _ you
have to at least believe in a person's calling. (Minor, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
