<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   OLD-TRICKS _ He's been a magician nearly all his life. He has
made a living at prestidigitation, a meager living he says. He was
never a star, never played the big Vegas hotels or Catskill
resorts. Weddings, wakes and wingdings might better describe his
venues. Birthday parties. Fund raisers. Jerry Lewis telethons. His
favorite possesion is an old manila folder stuffed with thank-you
notes from hospitals and charities. They are brief notes. But they
say something about him. ``For 40 years, I did parties at big
houses all over. I knew Burt Reynolds before he was on Gunsmoke.
Ricardo Montalban. Governor Claude Kirk was my friend, used to eat
breakfast with him.'' But those old friends stopped calling and the
magic jobs went begging after Peter Gross was convicted of selling
knock-off watches and suitcases out of his house. That was 1995.
And again in 1997. He's 82 and on probation for five years. The
judge wanted to send him to jail. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-RICHLIST _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you're the type who
has to keep up with the neighbors, you'll need to win the lottery _
every week for the rest of your life. Forbes' 13th annual World's
Billionaires List, in the magazine's July 5 issue, includes 13
loaded guys who own homes in the Palm Beach area. (Dropped from the
list, by the way, was Donald Trump, worth $1.5 billion in 1998 but
no more.) Here they are, as ranked among America's richest by
Forbes, with a tidbit about each. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PET-RESORT _ The scene of water hijinks recalls memories of
summer camp. Except these participants are furry and four-legged.
Welcome to Pet Lodge where swim time in a bone-shaped pool is al in
a day's play. (Morrow, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TESTKITCHEN _ Before Betty Crocker or Pillsbury product or
recipe reaches you kichen, it goes through rigorous tests in the
test kitchens. There, home economists track tasting and cooking
trends and try to think of every imaginable thing that can go wrong
in a home kitchen -- and then make sure their recipes will stand
up. We visited the two sites in Mineapolis and give report and
recipes. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TESTKITCHEN-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with Test Kitchen
story centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Meat Loaf. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
