<HEADER>
A6375 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-HIGHJUMP-AUSTIN24     06-23 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HIGHJUMP-AUSTIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin has record and Olympic repeat in mind
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ When he broke the American outdoor record in
the high jump, Charles Austin readily acknowledges, ``I didn't know
what I was doing. I was just goofing around.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise, though, isn't necessarily that Austin did what no
American has ever done by clearing a bar 7 feet, 10 1/2 inches off
the ground at an outdoor meet. Perhaps the surprise is that he
hasn't done it since that magical meet in Zurich, Switzerland, on
Aug. 7, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true since the former Southwest Texas State
Bobcat, now 31, definitely knows what he is doing and assuredly
isn't goofing off.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's quest for the two major goals he has remaining in an
illustrious but low-profile career takes another step this week
when he tries for his fourth straight victory at the USA Track and
Field Outdoor national championships in Eugene, Ore. Austin is one
of numerous Central Texas athletes who will participate in the
meet, which also serves as the trials to make the team for the
World Championships in Seville, Spain, in August.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, coached by former University of Texas assistant Sue
Humphrey, is in a four-way tie for second in the world early in
this outdoor season with a leap of 7-7 1/4 at a meet in the Bahamas
in late May. Russian Sergey Klyugin and University of Texas star
Mark Boswell, a Canadian, are tied for the world lead at 7-7 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's ultimate goals are to replace longtime rival/friend
Javier Sotomayor of Cuba as the world record holder, which would
mean joining Sotomayor as the only men to clear the 8-foot barrier
since ``Soto'' set the record of 8-0 1/2 in 1993. Austin also wants
to become the first high jumper in history to win in two Olympics.
He captured the 1996 gold medal in Atlanta with a dramatic 7-10
clearance on his last attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight feet is very doable,'' he said earlier this week before
a workout at SWT's Bobcat Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Has he ever cleared it in practice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope. Never tried,'' he said. ``It would really tick me off if
I did it in practice, wasting a jump like that with no one around
to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Austin has placed the bar at 8 feet and made
several run-throughs just to get the feel for what he hopes someday
will be a world record-breaking clearance. And the jumper who
declares ``a high bar doesn't scare me'' says there's nothing about
the 8-foot barrier he finds intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look much different than 7-9,'' he said. ``The mind
is crazy. I can easily jump 7-9 and clear it by 4 inches. But put
the bar up to 8 (feet) and I feel I have to try harder _ run
faster, jump stronger. If I just stick to my basic techniques, I'll
get it. It's all a mental thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been strictly mental with Austin, though, which
is another reason his assault on 8 feet has been delayed. Even when
he cleared 7-10 1/2 in Zurich, he was jumping on a bad left
(takeoff) leg. He had damaged his patellar tendon at an indoor meet
his senior season at SWT in 1990 when he set a personal best of 7-6
1/2. But he didn't have surgery until 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``July 7, to be exact,'' he said. ``I'll never forget that
date.''
</P>
<P>
   It took until nearly the end of the 1995 season for Austin to
begin feeling comfortable and confident again. He regained his old
touch and big-meet flair at the Atlanta Olympics when, after
missing twice at 7-9 1/4, he had the bar moved to 7-10 and cleared
it on the one and only jump he had left to edge Poland's Artur
Partyka for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   While Austin's immediate goal is winning this week in Eugene _
``At the major meets, I don't want anything less than first place''
_ he would love a crack at 8 feet if the opportunity presents
itself. He estimates that he has taken ``10 to 12'' stabs at the
height after winning competitions rather than simply trying to
improve his own American record.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get to 7-8 or 7-9, I just go for the world record,'' he
said. ``Why move the bar to 7-10 3/4? That's just an American
record and I already have that. I want to go for it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I set the record in '91, I knew if I could get my knee in
shape that there would be no limitations. I knew I could do
something amazing. I'm still waiting to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Riggs writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
