<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Pill remains a reliable option
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS A SIDEBAR TO RUN WITH HYSTERECTOMY-ALTERNATIVE
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regardless of how much new technology has arrived in gynecology,
the first treatment for many causes of uterine bleeding is still
the birth-control pill.
</P>
<P>
   Contraception is only one of several reasons physicians
prescribe the pill, says Dr. Luis Morales of Miami Valley Hospital.
It also regulates the hormonal imbalances that often lead to
excessive menstrual bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still think it causes cancer,'' Morales says. ``In
fact, it protects against cancer of the ovary and cancer of the
endometrium (which lines the uterus).''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 years of research have proven many fears about the
pill from the 1970s and early '80s to be unfounded, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But smokers over 35 should not take it,'' Morales says. They
run a risk of blood clotting.
</P>
<P>
   For healthy women who don't smoke, the risk of blood clots
increases less with the pill than it does during pregnancy. Those
women have no higher incidences of heart attack or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Other research has associated the pill with reductions in benign
breast lumps, functional ovarian cysts and pelvic inflammatory
disease, but not sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
