<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6394 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JESSE-JACKSON-HERO-NY     06-23 2271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSE-JACKSON-HERO-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JESSE FACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By GEORGE E. CURRY  
 c.1999 Emerge  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Jesse Jackson's driver pulls up in front of a U.S. Airways sign
at Washington National Airport when Amy Dupree of Addison, Texas,
recognizes him. Jackson, sitting in the front seat, continues a
conversation on his cellular telephone as Dupree and her husband,
Kyle, wait patiently to take a photograph with him.
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson emerges from the sedan several moments later, Amy
Dupree says, ``We're very proud of what you did.'' She tells
Jackson of her work getting women out of the ``adult
entertainment'' business _ she is a former topless dancer _ and how
God has changed her life.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says, ``God bless you,'' poses for a photo, and with
Yirgalem ``Yuri'' Tadesse, national director of international
affairs for Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH Coalition, and this journalist
in tow, he heads for U.S. Airways Flight 6480, the 3 p.m. shuttle
bound for New York's La Guardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   After appearing on ``The Late Show with David Letterman'' the
previous night, Jackson is returning for a second-straight
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Louis Jackson, fresh from securing the release of three
U.S. soldiers imprisoned for little more than a month in
Yugoslavia, is being heralded as an American hero. This was not the
first time Jackson had gone on a successful mercy mission.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he obtained the freedom of Navy flier Lt. Robert O.
Goodman Jr., who had been shot down over Lebanon. Later in the
year, he got Fidel Castro to release 22 Americans (most of them
held on drug charges) and 26 Cubans from prisons. Jackson also
persuaded Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to release 500 foreign
nationals being held against their will.
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Yugoslavia, however, provided Jackson with the
brightest spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for bringing our boys back home,'' says a middle-age
man with a middle-age middle. ``You're a real American hero.'' At
Legal Sea Foods, a restaurant in the airport, a group of women
pound on a window, wave and smile broadly as Jackson waves back. An
airline employee wants an autograph for his mother _ at least
that's what he says _ and two giddy teen-agers want to pose with
the world's best-known human rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   On the plane, it's more of the same. ``America thanks you ...
Good going, Jesse ... I just want to shake your hand.'' As he
settles in an aisle seat 20 rows back for an overdue interview, an
exhausted Jackson speaks for a few minutes and then suspends the
conversation to take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane lands in New York, he is refreshed and picks up
the conversation exactly where he left off. ``I always thought that
if we got close enough to touch them, we would leave with them,''
he recalls, referring to the soldiers. ``But it was strictly a
faith mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what Jackson says, these are not strictly faith
missions, though faith plays an intricate role. Nor are they merely
publicity stunts in which Jackson is used by unpopular foreign
leaders to manipulate U.S. public opinion. And despite the howls
from the State Department, he goes on these missions with their
tacit approval. After all, they made no effort to lift his
passport. How does he do it?
</P>
<P>
   First, Jackson is brash enough to think that he and only he can
pull off these feats. And so far, he has been right. Generally, he
has obtained the release of prisoners after the State Department
has failed, after back-channel negotiations through third parties
have failed and, in some cases, after U.S. or international
military intervention has failed, as was the case in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In each case Jackson knew when to make his move. Whether it's
securing the release of Goodman or the three Army soldiers _ Staff
Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher
J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.; and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales,
22, of Huntsville, Texas _ Jackson picks the right moment.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. M. William Howard Jr., president of the New York
Theological Seminary and a former president of the National Council
of Churches, remembers when Jackson decided to seek Goodman's
release. A group of ministers were huddling with tax attorneys in
Memphis to see how they could assist Jackson's 1984 presidential
bid without jeopardizing their federal tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse was bored out of his mind,'' Howard recalls. ``We broke
for lunch and went up to his suite. Wherever he is, he sends out
for this greasy fried chicken. He had sent somebody out to a
Popeye's, I believe it was. They brought in these buckets of
chicken. We were sitting around watching TV at lunchtime. I kid you
not, there was a news flash about how Donald H. Rumsfeld (NATO
ambassador under President Richard M. Nixon) had gone to Syria and
they were talking about the war in Lebanon and tensions with
Israel. They said nothing about Goodman.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point, Howard says, that Jackson sat up and
resolved to get a delegation of religious leaders together to go
and get Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   On his recent trip to Yugoslavia, Jackson followed that same
pattern of assembling a list of high-level religious leaders to
accompany him, including Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, general
secretary of the National Council of Churches; an American rabbi; a
priest of the Orthodox Church in America; a Greek bishop; a Serbian
Orthodox bishop; a Baptist minister; an Islamic leader; and a
Methodist bishop. Also with them was Rep. Rod R. Blagojevich
(D-Ill.), the only Serbian-American member of Congress, and other
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson delegation received a formal invitation to visit
their religious counterparts in Yugoslavia. However, just before
departing, they were urged by National Security Council adviser
Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger to call off the trip, reminding them that
their safety could not be assured and that the bombing would not
halt just because they were in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it clear that if we were to get killed going in a
bombing zone, it would represent the ultimate PR coup for
Milosevic,'' Jackson says. ``That was their fear. But they could
have ended that fear just by stopping the bombing while we were
there.'' But they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   On the night the delegation arrived at the Belgrade Hyatt hotel,
the NATO bombing was among the heaviest of the war up to that time,
with some bombs landing just blocks away. ``They never stopped
bombing,'' Jackson says, clearly angry. ``They never stopped
bombing next to us. I think it aroused in us the fires of
determination. I was mentally prepared, spiritually fortified,
psyched, pumped, ready. War was so wrong, and our cause was so
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian officials promised Jackson protection once he was in
the country. They took him and Western reporters on a tour of a
residential area that they said had been hit by NATO's bombs.
During his trip, Jackson told the Yugoslavs that until there was a
peace agreement, the bombs would continue falling. He also repeated
NATO's requirements before there could be a cessation of bombing.
When it was time to meet the young men, only Jackson and
Blagojevich were allowed to visit, even then under the watchful
eyes of a military judge.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were brought in separately and left separately.
Stone, who had bruises healing on the left side of his forehead,
spoke with the visitors first and for the longest amount of time.
The U.S. delegation had brought the soldiers Bibles, small
religious icons, candy, a tape recorder and separate tape-recorded
messages from their families.
</P>
<P>
   The military judge denied Jackson's request to give the gifts
directly to the captive men, saying they had to be inspected. Each
soldier reported that he had been treated well and was feeling
good, considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   During the visit, air-raid sirens sounded and the military judge
called for an end to the visit. But Jackson pressed on, asking that
the three soldiers be brought in together. His request was granted
and the men were reunited for the first time since they were
captured along the Yugoslav-Macedonian border on March 31.
Together, they prayed. ``Help is on the way and hope is in the
air,'' Jackson said. ``Soon, very soon, you will know peace and
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the delegates were allowed to meet with President
Slobodan Milosevic for three hours. In that meeting, they urged
Milosevic to free the soldiers. Bishop Dimitrios of Xanthos of the
Greek Orthodox Church says, ``(Jackson) was persuasive and just
would not let up. He kept saying, 'It's in your power. You can do
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the meeting, Milosevic portrayed NATO as the
aggressor in the conflict, just as the White House had feared. In
Milosevic's view, he was the victim. But when he asked who was
responsible for the bombings, Dr. Nazir Uddin Khaja, a California
physician and president of the American Muslim Council, replied,
``You are responsible.'' According to Khaja, Milosevic seemed
surprised. ``The whole group said that in one way or another. Maybe
I was more direct.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson met privately with Milosevic for about 20 minutes.
Milosevic promised to think about the request for freedom. Jackson
had been back at the hotel for 15 minutes when the delegation
received a call to meet with Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic at
his private residence. When they arrived, he told them, ``I am
pleased to tell you that President Milosevic has issued a decree
today releasing the three soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, there was a formal signing ceremony, which was broadcast
on U.S. television. With cameras rolling, Jackson had the soldiers
sounding more like civil rights workers than military men. They
chanted, ``'Free at last! Free at last! Thank God Almighty, we're
free at last!''
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson delegation left with the freed prisoners in a
Yugoslav bus. Under police escort, they were driven to the Croatian
border. From there, the soldiers were transferred to a Croatian
tourist bus rented by the U.S. Embassy and were driven to the Pleso
airstrip in Zagreb. Then they were flown to Ramstein Air Base in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the soldiers were whisked away to the Landstuhl
Regional Medical Center for a couple of days of testing before
their families arrived. So the Jackson group proceeded to
Washington, without the fruits of their labor.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when Jackson had obtained the release of Goodman,
the pilot was not delayed by military authorities in Europe;
instead, the group was flown home aboard Air Force One and treated
to a ceremony in the Rose Garden. That was under Ronald Reagan, a
Republican president viewed as hostile to civil rights. Under
Clinton, who prides himself as a friend of African-Americans,
Jackson did not receive the red-carpet treatment, causing Jackson
to view the administration as ingrates.
</P>
<P>
   While saying he was ``very pleased'' that the soldiers were
coming home, Clinton said that nearly 1.5 million Kosovars could
not enjoy similar freedom. The president said conditions for ending
the bombing were simple: ``The Kosovars must be able to go home
with security and self-government, Serbian security forces must
leave Kosovo. An international security force must deploy with the
power not just to monitor but to protect all the people of Kosovo,
Albanians and Serbs alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was carrying a private letter to Clinton from
Milosevic, strongly urged the president to release two Serb
soldiers held by U.S. military as a reciprocal peace gesture.
Several weeks later, the administration did just that, denying the
release represented a quid pro quo.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by David Letterman how he could be civil to such an
international outlaw, Jackson's answer was simple: ``He had the
power to keep our guys or let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he returned from Yugoslavia, ``Jetstream Jesse,''
as he is sometimes called, was off to Africa, successfully
brokering a cease-fire in the Sierra Leone civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no budgetary commitment to rebuilding this
war-torn nation as we heard in Europe,'' Jackson said, after taking
credit for securing the release of 2,000 prisoners of war, most of
them children and soldiers from bordering countries. ``When the
Yugoslavia war is over, there will be billions spent on rebuilding
the cities. The same kind of security and stability and democracy
in Kosovo and Yugoslavia must apply to Sierra Leone and to Africa
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's exploits aren't likely to stop with Yugoslavia and
Sierra Leone. After all, this is the same person who crashed the
1985 Geneva Summit that was supposed to feature only Ronald Reagan
and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. Jackson confronted
Gorbachev in a crowded lobby, asking about the treatment of Soviet
Jews. Where he shows up next is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (George E. Curry is editor-in-chief of Emerge magazine.) &LR;
</P>
