<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MBEKI-SAFRICA-INTERVI     06-23 2102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MBEKI-SAFRICA-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN AFTER MANDELA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT  
 c.1999 Emerge  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   During the 27 years that Nelson Mandela was serving time in
apartheid jails, his successor, Thabo Mbeki, was also serving time.
Not in apartheid jails, but, as he once wrote to a friend, ``like a
cosmic wanderer, driven by the winds to land where they will.''
Mbeki was living in forced exile. His ``struggle politics'' made it
impossible to return to the land where he was born on June 18,
1942. Like Mandela, the decision to become a freedom fighter would
be as much destiny as it was choice.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's parents were part of the social, intellectual and
political elite of the Transkei, the southeastern region of the
country that gave birth to many major activists, including Mandela
and the late African National Congress president, Oliver Tambo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 Mbeki's father, Govan, went underground, and to prison,
with Mandela; Thabo, then a student activist, was sent out of the
country. He spent six months in a Rhodesian jail but eventually
made it to England, where he earned a master's degree in economics
from Sussex University and later married another South African
exile, Zanele Dlamini, a social worker and women's rights activist.
</P>
<P>
   While in exile, Mbeki helped build the ANC's youth sections and
received military training as part of the cadre of guerillas known
as ``Umkonto we Sizwe.'' Starting in the late '60s, Mbeki held ANC
postings in England, Botswana, Swaziland and Nigeria, with
intermittent spells in Lusaka, home of the ANC in exile.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Mandela was released in 1990, Mbeki was finally free
to come home, playing a key role in the transition to democratic
rule. He cast his first vote as a South African citizen on April
27, 1994, after which Mandela, the new president, chose him as
deputy president. Highly and warmly regarded by Mandela, Mbeki was
for quite some time at the controls of the government's daily
operations, as well as its long-term planning.
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken, pipe-smoking, private man given to quoting
William Butler Yeats, the Bible and of late, Zulu and Xhosa
proverbs, Mbeki seems an enigma to some. That is bound to change.
</P>
<P>
   When asked one too many times how he felt about stepping into
Mandela's shoes, Mbeki once responded with rarely seen but
characteristic playful humor: ``I don't want to step into Mandela's
shoes because he wears ugly shoes.''
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: During those 27 years in exile, did you
ever dream that you would be president of South Africa?
</P>
<P>
   THABO MBEKI: No, it was never even a thought. You see, I think
it must have been impossible for all of us to conceptualize what
freedom would bring. So we sort of thought, ``Well, freedom will
come and then we will get jobs somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You once said to me that you were trying to run a country
that you didn't know. What were some of the things you found out
that just blew your mind?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, the personnel budget is extremely bloated and ... I
think the other problem here, which I don't think we quite
understood, was the level of corruption in society. I don't merely
mean a civil servant taking some money or being bribed; I mean
generally the collapse of social morality in society _ very
pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   We knew there were some police officers who you certainly didn't
want, and indeed they retired and were encouraged to retire, given
severance packages. But you discover in time that the root is much
deeper, its origins being in an illegitimate system, an
illegitimate government, and hence everybody ended up making their
own rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that you understand that, can you ``move forward
faster,'' as your campaign slogan promised?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think so. We are better educated about what South Africa
is; that is half the answer, to know the reality. I think that what
we should be talking about is an ongoing revolution. Many people
naturally look at what happened in 1994 as an election took place:
One party was defeated and another party won, what normally happens
in democratic systems. But I am saying it was not just a mere
change of system. What we have been about in the past five years is
to change the system. We have a continuing revolution in the
country, but the fact of our experience in the last five years
gives us the possibility to move forward faster. We can and must
move forward faster in every respect. And this thing without
precedent that we've established in the last five years, the
creation of something which is totally new in South Africa _ it
throws out its own lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So the problems are not insoluble.
</P>
<P>
   A: They are not insoluble. You need to discover what the
problems are, as truthfully, correctly and factually as possible,
and indeed that is half of the battle. It is true that the economy
is not growing at a rate which is absorbing unemployment to the
extent that we need. But a whole variety of things will be done.
... Housing construction will necessarily employ a lot of people.
Quite clearly, the rate of construction has to pick up in the next
five years. And the infrastructure problem _ roads in the rural
areas and so forth _ that too will absorb a lot of (unemployed)
people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Let's talk about crime. International investors have seen the
horrendous reports about crime. They don't say they are not coming,
but take ``wait and see'' attitudes because they don't know what
you're going to do. What do you say to them about the future?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, you see, it depends whom you are talking to. General
Electric has decided that it is going to make major investments in
South Africa. I said to them, ``But what I am told is that
investors are being driven away from South Africa by crime.'' And
they say to me: ``Deputy President (because I was deputy president
then), we also work in Poland. We as a corporation are active in
Poland on a smaller scale than in South Africa and we've had 300 of
our cars hijacked. We have not had a single car hijacked in South
Africa. ... There is crime all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: But what about those who aren't here, who read the headlines
and see stories of crime in the newspaper? Do you say, ``Come,
there is no crime''?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, no, we don't. They know there is crime. You need to
explain a lot of it. This understanding about the nature of crime
in South Africa comes from the experience of white South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But black South Africans too. I mean, people in the
townships. My caregiver for my mother, if I asked her to work an
extra half-hour, it would be pitch black by the time she got to
Alexandra township, and she is scared to go there after dark.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure, sure. But the point about all of this is that crime has
been a real problem in South Africa for a long time. A person from
Alexandra township will tell you that the crime problem in
Alexandra township is not new. What has happened is that crime has
begun to affect white areas in ways that it did not affect white
areas before.
</P>
<P>
   Q: OK, but then the bottom line is, there is crime. What do you
say to international investors who are waiting to see what is going
to happen?
</P>
<P>
   A: I say to international investors, I don't believe there are
levels of crime here which would make you take a decision not to
come, as though there is not crime elsewhere in the world. You see,
President (Fernando Henrique) Cardoso of Brazil tells me that
people in Sao Paulo take their children to and from school by
helicopter. Now are investors saying, ``We are not going to put
money in Brazil because of the level of crime?'' Of course not.
There is a presentation of the level of crime as though South
Africa is unique in the world, which it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It isn't unique in the world, but crime is here. You need
international investment for jobs and so forth. So what is the
bottom line?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have to fight crime as all countries must fight crime.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've talked about two separate societies in South Africa,
one white and prospering, one black and declining. Do you see that
changing significantly in the next five years?
</P>
<P>
   A: It takes time; I mean it will take time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have time?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure we do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There is no ticking time bomb out there among these young
people who have no jobs, who, as far as they are concerned, have no
hope?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, no, I don't think so. I think that the critical matter is
first of all to tell people the truth, that these things are going
to take time, and secondly, to do something, as has been done, that
is being done and will be done.
</P>
<P>
   If indeed there was nothing happening, then indeed we would get
an explosion. (A recent newspaper survey showed that) despair and
loss of hope is among your richer people, the white community,
followed by the Indians, who despair about the future because they
are fearful of losing what they have. Whereas the poor take
precisely the opposite position. They are very hopeful about the
future because they can see the changes that have been made (and
believe), ``Even if they have not reached me today, they will reach
me tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: So how do you resolve those sorts of conflicting perceptions?
And what are you going to do about white people?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many of the whites are victims of their own propaganda. The
fear of the future is a fear which they impose on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you reassure them?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it's important to communicate the message to them
continuously that the fears they entertain are unfounded, but I
think that also (we must examine) the practical, the actual things
that happen. They feared, after the elections in 1994, that
terrible things were going to happen to them, that they would be
slaughtered and this and that, and nothing like that happened. And
next they feared that they would lose their jobs because of
affirmative action and end up as the unemployed, and the black
people as the employed. It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You recently told a crowd of black South Africans that they
needed to get angry. Can you explain that?
</P>
<P>
   A: You see, part of the problem is that we are too comfortable
with an ugly past. The consequence is that the impulse to change
the ugly reality that comes from that ugly past gets dulled. So I
say, you see, we have got to be angry about the fact of slavery. It
is not just a matter of saying, ``Oh, it happened.'' We have to be
angry about the history of colonialism. We have to be angry about
this history of neocolonialism, when African leaders robbed the
masses of our people and produced conflicts on the continent. We
have got to be angry about apartheid. Then we put ourselves in a
position to say, ``Let's do something about it to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   If I said to you what is happening in South Africa _ even the
memory of what apartheid meant is receding. There are people here
who, when you talk to them about the pass laws (which required
blacks to carry identification books), they say, ``What? What is
that?'' If you lose that anger and you lose that anger because you
are sitting in a comfortable position, you lose the drive to change
the things which have to be changed. And then perhaps there is too
much such forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you clarify that? Are you quarreling with the notion of
reconciliation?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. You know we must forgive the people who committed the
crime of apartheid, but I think a mistake is made when people then
think that also means forgiving apartheid. Nobody in the world asks
the jury for forgiveness for slavery. Why must we forgive slavery
and apartheid? We have done the forgiving thing. No, I think there
is too much forgiveness here. We never agreed to forgive the system
of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charlayne Hunter-Gault is CNN's Johannsburg bureau chief, a
correspondent for National Public Radio and a widely published
journalist and author.) &LR;
</P>
