<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
June 24. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   BOMB: Morning rush hour traffic over the Missouri River in
Kansas City was snarled Wednesday when police shut down the Paseo
Bridge after discovering a suspicious man who left a suspicious
briefcase on the bridge. The police bomb squad's robot blew it up.
Shawna Hamel. 10.
</P>
<P>
   VERN: Missouri State Rep. Vernon Thompson was indicted by a
federal grand jury Wednesday for mail fraud. The charges stem from
Thompson's activities with Kansas City community housing
development projects, most notably CHIC, chronicled by The Star two
years ago. Mark Morris. 25.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE: The Kansas City Fire Department, while angling to take
over ambulance service for the city, was caught refusing to answer
emergency medical calls during a four-alarm fire in May. A
department dispatcher was disciplined for asking MAST to handle all
but the most life-threatening EMS calls during the fire at 1300
Wyoming, and declining to dispatch fire department personnel to a
total of seven EMS calls during the fire. Steve Penn.
</P>
<P>
   PBS: Kansas and Chicago activists meet in KC for a discussion of
ways to reduce crime and violence. The whole thing is being taped
by PBS as a documentary to air Sept. 22. Kauffman Foundation is
footing the bill for the documentary. Aaron Barnhart. 10-12 inches.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS. Robert Lockett, local gun seller, has irritated the
industry with an opinion column in an industry publication
questioning the ways handguns are marketed. John Dvorak.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   BBOX. GM has begun installing on some vehicles a black box-type
recorder that will give information on how a vehicle has been
driven and will allow law enforcement to know details about what
happened in case an accident occurs. Robert A. Cronkleton. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   QUINT _ Quintiles news conference about expected jobs. By Mark
Couch. Photo
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP _ Trump's Atlantic City operation should be relicensed by
New Jersey authorities sometime late this afternoon. Missouri
regulators are present and watching closely. Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   STAFF _ Remember Alice Errett, The Maids franchise owner who
went to extraordinary lengths to hire the unemployed from Wyandotte
County? The company bought her out. The buyout price was right, but
it still left a bad taste in her mouth. Apparently, she was a bit
too different for them. At Work column by Diane Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   NOTES - special budget for Hemingway package offered by the
Kansas City Star. Embargoed until Sunday, June 27. Kansas City Star
must be credited.
</P>
<P>
   ONLY ONE STAFF PHOTO IS AVAILABLE. ADDITIONAL PHOTOS HAVE BEEN
PURCHASED FROM THE JOHN F. KENNEDY LIBRARY in Boston. That number
is 617 929 4573. Fax is 617 929 4599. Contact is James Hill.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-KC: In one of the short stories that Ernest Hemingway
set in Kansas City, he writes that the city was ``very like
Constantinople.'' Some never-before-published manuscript fragments
of ``God Rest You Merry, Gentlemen,'' showing early drafts of the
opening passages of that story, reveal Hemingway's struggle to put
down on paper just what he thought of Kansas City. And what did he
really mean by the Constantinople comparison? At a time when a
previously unpublished book by Hemingway is making literary waves,
The Kansas City Star adds insult to injury by publishing these
``new'' Hemingway paragraphs about Kansas City. Steve Paul. 71
inches. TO BE MOVED SEPARATELY.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-ERROR:A curious footnote to the Hemingway record in
Kansas City. That 15th Street police station that was part of his
beat was really on 19th Street. Monroe Dodd catches EH and all who
followed him in the error. Steve Paul. 13 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-DEFINE: He was born on July 21, 1899, and died by his
own hand on another July day 62 years later. In the intervening
years, his life not only paralleled the rise of the ``American
century,'' he helped define it.
</P>
<P>
   He was an American abroad. He was all brawn and swagger. And in
one of the surest ways to extend one's life beyond its natural
boundaries he wrote it all down, and much of what he wrote down was
very good.
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the centennial of Ernest Hemingway's birth, and
unlike the 100th anniversary of, say, James Gould Cozzens or Robert
McAlmon, two of his contemporaries, the event is drawing
considerable attention. Steve Paul. 38 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-BIOGRAPHY: That Ernest Hemingway could be exasperating
has been established.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, that's not the entire agenda of Michael Reynolds, the
Hemingway scholar who now has completed his cycle of Hemingway
biographies with Hemingway: The Final Years.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth and final volume of the series Reynolds began
back in 1986 with the appearance of The Young Hemingway. Through
these books Reynolds has established himself a scholar who, while
possessing a vast store of sympathy for the Hemingway the artist,
has never hesitated to identify troglodyte conduct when he
encounters it.
</P>
<P>
   Of that, there's plenty to describe in the period of Hemingway's
life this last volume spans, from 1940 through to his 1961 suicide.
Brian Burnes. 24 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-BIRTHS:. During a poignant period in 1928, Hemingway
and his pregnant wife Pauline spent a few weeks in Kansas City,
where after a difficult pregnancy, their son Patrick was born. This
is during the same period when Hemingway is writing A Farewell to
Arms, whose wrenching end involves a difficult pregancy and fatal
childbirth. Brian Burnes. 52 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-TYLER: We can thank Tyler Hemingway for his nephew's
appearance in Kansas City. Just who was he? Brian Burnes. 22
inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-HANNEMAN:Audre Hanneman toiled in modest obscurity for
many years to produce one of the most important resources ever
created for Hemingway students, researchers and collectors: A
two-volume descriptive bibliography of works by and about him,
which scholars still today find indispensible. And they also lament
that she or no one else has filled in the blanks since her last
volume appeared in 1975. Not bad for the onetime Kansas Citian who,
after some 30 years in New York, returned to the Kansas City of her
youth to live in semi-retirement. PHOTO. Steve Paul. 57 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-TIMELINE: A Hemingway timeline, including the KC
connection. 26 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-BIBLIOGRAPHY: A selected bibliography. 7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-LETTERS: Excerpt of letters, some of them previously
unpublished, which Hemingway wrote during his stint on the Kansas
City Star. 23 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-WRITERS: Contemporary writers on Hemingway. 15 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-RESOURCES: Listing new books and web sites for
Hemingway info and study. 18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-EVENTS: Listing of Hemingway-related events. 10
inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-TRIVIA: Little known facts about Hemingway. 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-HISWORDS: Selected quotes from Hemingway and his
writings. 15 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-WEB: Copy block on Hemingway web site constructed by
the Kansas City Star. 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-INDEX: Introductory paragraph to series and items for
use at will by newspapers. 9 inches.
</P>
<P>
   TENNIS-PROFILE: Judy Ade Levering, the first woman president of
the United States Tennis Association in its 118 years, visited her
old neighborhood in Kansas City recently and reminisced about Arbor
Villa Park, the first steppingstone to her historic role. 37
inches. Photos. Laura Rollins Hockaday.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-BRIEFS: A file of briefs related to summer. For use at
will. Credit is Knight Ridder Newspapers. 19 inches. Kansas City
Star staff members.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   NBAGAME. Blair Kerkhoff. 18-20. Advance on Game 4 of the NBA
Finals. We'll see what develops after Game 3, possibly something
focusing on the relationship between Tim Duncan and David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Dutton. 16-18. Detroit at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WHITLOCK. Jason Whitlock column on the Tigers' Dean Palmer.
</P>
