<HEADLINE>
HAWKE MOVES OFF THE SET, ONTO THE STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Refiling for those needing.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ Ethan Hawke is in a contemplative mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a very a good movie star, you know?'' the
actor muses.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour earlier he'd certainly been acting like a movie
star. A Mercedes with Hawke as passenger had double-parked on
Williamstown's busy, main commercial strip while the actor trotted
into a store for a beverage. Because a delivery truck on the
opposite side of the street also had double-parked, traffic in both
directions stopped dead for more than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That was an accident, Hawke says. Could have happened to
anybody. That he, a movie star, shut down the town while searching
to quench his thirst was just, well, bad timing. You know?
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a bench on the lawn of the Williamstown Theatre
Festival (WTF), squinting into the afternoon sun as if it's the
glare from television cameras, Hawke says: ``For some reason, I
don't seem to play that whole `fame' angle well. Not the acting
part, all the rest. ... It's very difficult to be a male movie
actor when you have to worry about to what extent your career will
go if you don't take your shirt off for magazine covers or carry a
gun in movies. I've never done that, you know? It's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering Ethan Hawke's life is ``difficult''? Hawke, now 28,
has almost two dozen movies behind him.
</P>
<P>
   He's married to an actress of heavenly allure (Uma Thurman),
with whom he has an infant daughter who will be a year old early
next month.
</P>
<P>
   And Hawke can choose his pick of projects, from Westerns (``The
Newton Boys'') to a contemporary retelling of a classic (this
fall's ``Hamlet'') to an adaptation of a literary best-seller
(``Snow Falling On Cedars,'' also due out in the fall).
</P>
<P>
   What's he complaining about? He's not. He's considering,
figuring things out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hawke recalls upon reflection, he has fired weapons
onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I did shoot a gun in `The Newton Boys,''' he concedes.
``But that's the only _ no, I did in `A Midnight Clear,' and I do
in `Hamlet.' But you know what I mean, you know? It's not like
...''
</P>
<P>
   He trails off. Words having failed, he demonstrate physically:
jerks his head and shoulders forward and looks mean,
action-heroish.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't done that kind of gunning in movies.
</P>
<P>
   The point clarified, Hawke moves on to talk about ``Camino
Real,'' the Tennessee Williams play in which he's starring at the
WTF. The high-powered cast boasts such name actors as Blair Brown,
Hope Davis and Jeffrey Jones, who despite their fame and acclaim
are among the lesser-knowns in a WTF summer that includes Hawke,
David Schwimmer of ``Friends,'' Bebe Neuwirth (Lilith on
``Cheers'') and, of course, recent Oscar honoree Gwyneth Paltrow in
Shakespare's ``As You Like It.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williams play (pronounced Cam-I-no Ree-AL) runs through July
4. Rarely produced, and always an audience-baffler when it is,
``Camino Real'' finds Williams at his most dreamlike: mannered and
obscure and poetic. Before the play opened, in 1953, with Elia
Kazan as director and Eli Wallach in the part Hawke plays, Williams
acknowledged its difficult style, themes and weighty symbolism:
``This play will exasperate and confuse a certain number of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the playwright added hopefully, ``Not (as many) as it is
likely to please.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in the town square of an unnamed Latin American country, the
plot brings together an American boxer, Kilroy (Hawke), with such
historical figures as Casanova, Lord Byron and Don Quixote to
create a dreamscape of beauty and horror in a mythic neverland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is hard for people when they read it (because)
Williams is trying to tell you a story in a different way than
you're used to,'' says Hawke, who was invited to act in the
production by its director, Nicholas Martin. When he initially read
the play, Hawke says, ``I thought, `This is insane.' But Nicky
begged me to read it again, and the second time I read it I was
deeply moved by it.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he promises, ``I think (audiences) will be shocked by how
much fun it is to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the script, Kilroy is forced by townspeople into wearing a
``Patsy'' clown costume featuring a bright red rubber nose that at
times lights up. One character misinterprets the blinks as Kilroy's
attempt at Morse code.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird thing to read, `His nose lights up,' but when you
see it, man, it's funny, you know? Just funny,'' says Hawke.
</P>
<P>
   He sums up the play's cumulative effect of chaotic onstage
action, image-laden speech and frequent symbolism: ``It's a poem,
you know? A Vaudeville poem. It's T.S. Eliot going to the circus
and dropping acid.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he remains young onscreen and in public perception _
the tag ``eternal slacker'' often is applied to him _ Hawke is
learning to grow up. Part of being an adult, a dad, is making sure
you're understood.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, he starts and restarts, corrects and shades and
amplifies. He draws his interlocutor into complicity with his you
knows, seeks reassurance with frequent questions of his own, asked
literally or with a rising vocal inflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to figure out _ you know, my whole life has
changed, with the baby and everything? It's not the same. I can't
just go flying off to this place and to that place. So I'm trying
to figure all that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurman, he says, is in Paris, shooting a movie. He says/asks,
``With Gerard Depardieu?'' not because he doubts that the immense
Frenchman is Thurman's co-star but to ensure he's understood.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman and their daughter, Maya, will join him in Williamstown
this week, and together they will consider future movies.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing definite yet, he says. He's most excited about
``Hamlet,'' set in corporate America, with Kyle MacLachlan as
Claudius, Sam Shepard as the ghost, Julia Stiles as Ophelia and
Bill Murray as Polonius.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke, who plays Hamlet as a young filmmaker, gets to say the
``To be or not to be'' speech. Four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play with it,'' he says excitedly. ``It's like the whole
movie _ you haven't seen this version before. It's like ...''
</P>
<P>
   He stops. He gestures. He frowns. He talks through a long
digression that disses Kenneth Branagh's four-hour ``Hamlet'' as
``a snooze'' and enthuses about director Baz Luhrmann's ``Romeo and
Juliet'' for its speediness and sex appeal: ``It's about two really
gorgeous people kissing, and then they kill themselves. It's
fantastic,'' he says, his voice surging falsetto with glee on the
second syllable of his final word.
</P>
<P>
   And his ``Hamlet''? ``It's about fame and the media controlling
everything,'' he says. Pause. ``You know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
