<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-23 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IF YOU LIKE YOUR JOB, TAKE A LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you have a miserable job, you know what to
do: Make plans to quit. But if your job is somewhere in that vast
wilderness between mediocre and halfway decent, don't plan to quit
_ plan to leave.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a society where the typical employee works like mad
for 30 or 40 or 50 years and then leaps into the land of I Can Go
Golfing Forever (or its evil twin, How Am I Supposed To Live on
That?). There's a more civilized way: At least once or twice in
your career, find a way to take a leave of absence.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about something purely selfish, not taking time off
for an ailing family member or an unborn child. Personal leaves
usually fit into one of three broad categories:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pauses.
</P>
<P>
   Use these when you have a generally good job that's starting to
overwhelm you, or an opportunity in your personal life that you
don't want to miss. You might want to spend some serious quality
time with your 3-year-old son or 75-year-old mother before they
move on to different stages of life, or you might just want a
healthy break from the 9-to-5 grind.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes work gets so overwhelming that you miss out on the
good things in life. If you dash past a bed of roses, all you may
notice is the smell of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Plateaus.
</P>
<P>
   I've come across two good examples in the last month, one at the
office and one at home.
</P>
<P>
   Marcheta Catlett, an editorial assistant at the San Francisco
Examiner for seven years, just started a seven-month leave. Like
many 30-year-olds, Marcheta is at a point when the job isn't as
challenging as it used to be; she needs time to figure out what to
do next, whether it's trying for a promotion or changing jobs or
going back to school.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Cathy, became a teacher when she was around Marcheta's
age. Twenty years later, she's taking a leave to study the piano,
travel with her husband a little and decide whether she wants to
keep working full time, cut back or leave the working world
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves give Cathy and Marcheta time to make a crucial life
decision without the day-to-day stress to cloud their thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who reach a plateau hop mindlessly from one job to
another without taking the time to figure out what's really wrong _
and end up never solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Passion.
</P>
<P>
   Try something just for fun or because it might lead you to a
different career. I took a leave in 1990 to do something I always
wanted to do: write a novel. I crashed and burned, but enjoyed
every minute of it. Our paths will cross again.
</P>
<P>
   If a pile of resumes has a dozen engineers with 20 years of
experience and one who spent a year writing a novel or trekking in
the Himalayas, will it really bother you that he has worked only 19
years instead or 20? Or are you more likely to be intrigued?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, having a good reason for a leave is only the first
step. Even if your family and friends support your decision, there
are still two major hurdles: getting your employer's permission and
finding a way to survive for several months without a paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming you have no union contract or company policy allowing
for leaves, you'll have to negotiate for one. Just as you would
when asking for a raise or anything else, make it clear how the
company will benefit _ not just how you will.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a slow time of year when the boss might not mind
slicing the payroll? Would enrolling in an academic program
accomplish what you want and make it more appealing to the company?
Would you be more energized and creative when you returned? The
best argument you can have in any negotiation is that you're
already a good worker and that this leave, raise or trip to Tahiti
will make you even better. That's why you should ask for a leave as
soon as you hit a plateau, not sputter for three years.
</P>
<P>
   By that point, you might be closer to expendable than
indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   If you're one of your company's best workers and there is no way
you can get four months or six months off without pay, you're
working for an idiot. Keep that in mind as you consider future
career alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   As for money, start saving at least a couple of years before the
leave. If you go into debt to take a leave, the financial stress
might outweigh the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The finances may be difficult, but the payoff is worth it.
Consider it as an investment in your career and your life, either
in learning about yourself or chasing a dream. It could pay
dividends for decades.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His e-mail
address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
