harassment complaint form.
 &HT;     (Sexual harassment, sexual advances or other forms of
religious, racial or sexual harassment by any pupil, teacher,
administrator or other school personnel, which create an
intimidating, hostile or offensive environment, will not be
tolerated under any circumstances.) 
 &HT;    Do the girls want to fill out the form and sign it? They do. She
calls up the Duluth school system harassment specialist _ a job
title that a decade ago did not exist in the Duluth public schools
_ or, for that matter, in any other U.S. school system.
 &HT;    The specialist is a small, cheerful, 58-year-old former
special-education teacher named Judy Gillen. She works out of the
Duluth school administration headquarters, in a 6-by-10-foot
office-enclosure wedged into half a small room and decorated with
teddy bears, puppets, framed photographs of her grandchildren, a
Women's History Month poster and a big bright sign, affixed to the
front of a file cabinet, that reads: SEXUAL HARASSMENT _ IT'S
ILLEGAL.
 &HT;    There also are books, pamphlets, videotape guides and visual
aids for overhead projection. ``Sexual Harassment in Our School:
What Parents and Teachers Need to Know to Spot It and Stop It.''
``Girls and Boys Getting Along: Teaching Sexual Harassment
Prevention in the Elementary Classroom.'' ``The Hostile School
Bus.'' ``Sexual Harassment: Pay Attention!''
 &HT;    There are copies of a districtwide newsletter Gillen composes,
formerly Harassment News Notes until she changed the title, in a
