<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6484 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     06-23 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-REPEAT-art-ADV27-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 27, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a small concrete patio outside the sliding glass door
leading to my backyard. The slab is about 4 inches lower than the
door and indoor floor, and I would like to cover the concrete slab
with wood decking that will also raise the level of this patio so
that it is even with the bottom of the door opening. What is the
best way to do this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Buy pressure-treated 2x4s and fasten these to the concrete
patio with the wide (4 inch) side against the masonry as shown
here. You can fasten these sleepers down with a powder-actuated
nail gun that is made for fastening to masonry, or you can screw
the 2x4s to the concrete by first inserting lead anchors in the
masonry (after drilling holes first with a carbide masonry bit).
The sleepers should be spaced 16 inches apart. After they are down,
cover them with 2x6 decking, also made of pressure-treated lumber.
Fasten these to the sleepers with rust-resistant nails or screws.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every time we get a heavy rain we have a problem with water
seeping in where the sloping roof comes down against the back of
our brick chimney. A new roof was put on a few years ago and metal
flashing was installed in this joint, but the leak persists. We
tried caulking and applying roof cement, but this only helped for a
little while. We called in a new roofer, and he said that the job
was not done right because the original roofer did not build a
``chimney cricket'' behind the chimney. I don't know what a
``cricket'' is, but do you think this could be the problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: A brick chimney that comes up against a sloping or peaked
roof should have a cricket or saddle (both terms are used) built up
on top of the roof and in the space where the back of the chimney
meets the sloping roof. Shaped something like a miniature hip roof
that slopes to match the existing roof, it serves to shed snow and
water quickly and keeps dirt and debris from accumulating and
piling up behind the chimney. There should be flashing installed in
the joints where the cricket meets the roof and the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our apartment has old metal cabinets in the kitchen and these
cabinets are greasy and dirty looking. How can I clean the grease
and dirt off without harming the enameled finish?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can wash the dirt and grease off with any strong
household detergent or an all-purpose spray cleaner without fear of
damaging the enameled finish. Scrub with a soft brush or fine
kitchen abrasive pad, then rinse off with plenty of water.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a paneled front door made of wood and the panels have
developed several cracks, some of which go all the way through. We
tried filling the cracks with wood filler and paint, but these
repairs don't seem to last long. What can you recommend to repair
this door without replacing it entirely?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is almost impossible to effectively fill in or patch such
cracks in a thin wood panel. Your best bet is to cover the entire
panel with either reinforced fiberglass cloth (fiberglass and
resin), or by gluing a new panel of thin plywood right over the old
panel. In each case it will be necessary to remove all paint or
varnish first in order to get the glue or resin to bond properly.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``INSTALLING DECK BOARDS OVER CONCRETE
SLAB'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Wood decking is fastened to top of 2x4 wood sleepers
after these are nailed or screwed to concrete slab.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
