<HEADER>
A6492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     06-23 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO STRANGLE ANTIQUITIES ACT WILL HURT GOP
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) 
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c.1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. James Hansen, R-Utah, is still smarting over President
Clinton's
</P>
<P>
   use of the Antiquities Act of 1906 to create the Grand
</P>
<P>
   Staircase-Escalante National Monument in southeastern Utah in
1996. So
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, who is a member of the House Resources Committee and
chairs the
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee on National Parks and Public Lands, has introduced
a bill
</P>
<P>
   to limit the president's power under the Antiquities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's bill is called the `National Monument NEPA Compliance
Act`
</P>
<P>
   (H.R. 1487). NEPA stands for the National Environmental Policy
Act,
</P>
<P>
   which became law in 1969. On the surface, the bill simply
requires that
</P>
<P>
   any designation of a national monument must first comply with
NEPA. But
</P>
<P>
   it does much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also requires that any designated monument skip over
the
</P>
<P>
   environmental assessment required by NEPA and jump to the more
rigorous
</P>
<P>
   environmental impact statement (EIS). An environmental
assessment is an
</P>
<P>
   analysis to see if an EIS is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   H.R. 1487 demands more than NEPA. It requires formal hearings
during all
</P>
<P>
   phases of the development of the EIS, requires an additional six
months
</P>
<P>
   of public review on the draft EIS, then four more months of
public
</P>
<P>
   hearings on the final EIS.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before Hansen's subcommittee on June 17, John
Leshy,
</P>
<P>
   solicitor of the Department of Interior, stated: `None of these
steps is
</P>
<P>
   currently required under NEPA or the NEPA regulations. Mandating
all
</P>
<P>
   these procedural barriers for every national monument
designation, no
</P>
<P>
   matter how small or how urgent, would be contrary to both
protective
</P>
<P>
   purposes of the Antiquities Act and the flexible approach of the
NEPA
</P>
<P>
   regulations. In addition, the bill would delay Antiquities Act
</P>
<P>
   protection still further by preventing the president from
designating a
</P>
<P>
   national monument for at least 30 days after the record of
decision [for
</P>
<P>
   the EIS) is approved.`
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Hansen wants to stall the designation of any new
national
</P>
<P>
   monuments. It's a misguided jab at Clinton -- and a colossal
waste of
</P>
<P>
   time and taxpayer dollars. If the bill were to pass in the House
and the
</P>
<P>
   Senate, it is likely that Clinton would veto it. Leshy told the
</P>
<P>
   subcommittee that if the bill is `presented to the president,
the
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of the Interior will recommend that he veto the bill.`
</P>
<P>
   Hansen introduced a bill (H.R. 1127) attacking the Antiquities
Act in
</P>
<P>
   the last session of Congress. It passed in the House, but never
got out
</P>
<P>
   of committee in the Senate. Hansen has an ax to grind -- against
the
</P>
<P>
   crown jewels of this nation's heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The Antiquities Act, as Leshy pointed out, is one of this
nation's most
</P>
<P>
   successful environmental laws. Fourteen of the 17 presidents
since the
</P>
<P>
   act was passed have set aside over 100 national monuments, most
of which
</P>
<P>
   were subsequently endorsed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt, a Republican, started the move to preserve
historic,
</P>
<P>
   scientific and precious wilderness by naming Devils Tower (Wyo.)
the
</P>
<P>
   first national monument on Sept. 24, 1906. By the conclusion of
his
</P>
<P>
   presidential tenure, Roosevelt had designated 18 national
monuments,
</P>
<P>
   ending with the designation of Mount Olympus (Wash.) in 1909, a
few
</P>
<P>
   hours before he left office.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those monuments, like Mount Olympus, later became
national
</P>
<P>
   parks. Some monuments became national historic sites (Ft.
Laramie,
</P>
<P>
   Wyo.), national historic parks (Chesapeake and Ohio Canal, Md.)
or
</P>
<P>
   national battlefields (Big Hole Battlefield, Mont.).
</P>
<P>
   Utah is a shining example of the success of the Antiquities Act:
Zion
</P>
<P>
   National Park, Bryce Canyon National Park, Timpanogos Cave
National
</P>
<P>
   Monument, Capitol Reef National Park, Arches National Park,
Natural
</P>
<P>
   Bridges National Monument, and Cedar Breaks National Monument.
The
</P>
<P>
   communities surrounding these preserves understand their
commercial
</P>
<P>
   value, as well as their significance to the Americans and the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists come to Utah from every continent to spend time in
these
</P>
<P>
   special landscapes. Hansen would do well to remember his own
state's
</P>
<P>
   precious natural heritage that has been saved by presidential
</P>
<P>
   designation.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has the power to cancel the designation of any
monument, and
</P>
<P>
   has done so. Congress can also withhold funding for the
management of a
</P>
<P>
   monument. Although Hansen may smart at Clinton's designation of
Grand
</P>
<P>
   Staircase-Escalante National Monument; truth is, Congress
expanded the
</P>
<P>
   boundaries of the monument, ratified the president's designation
and
</P>
<P>
   funded its management.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Hunt of the Wilderness Society points out that the Hansen
bill
</P>
<P>
   would interfere with the emergency powers of a president to act
swiftly
</P>
<P>
   to address an imminent threat to important historic or
wilderness area.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the bill, Hunt commented, `It's an attack on what is
a very
</P>
<P>
   important tool in the conservation tool box.`
</P>
<P>
   Hunt noted that it's only recently that the environment has
become a
</P>
<P>
   partisan issue. Of the 14 presidents who set aside national
monuments,
</P>
<P>
   half were Republican. The three presidents who did not use the
</P>
<P>
   Antiquities Act were Richard Nixon, Ronald Reagan and George
Bush -- all
</P>
<P>
   Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fair to say that it was during Reagan's
administration, with
</P>
<P>
   the appointment of James Watt as Secretary of the Interior, that
</P>
<P>
   environmental issues began to split Republicans from Democrats.
Sadly,
</P>
<P>
   the partisanship continues.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's bill is an example of that partisanship. It seems
strange that
</P>
<P>
   a congressman from a state where so much beauty has been
protected by
</P>
<P>
   the Antiquities Act would blindly attack that act in the service
of
</P>
<P>
   manipulative and selfish politics.
</P>
<P>
   The American people won't buy it. This kind of
anti-environmental
</P>
<P>
   politics will be the downfall of the Republican goal to keep
control of
</P>
<P>
   Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-22-99 1629EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6495 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEA-OTTER-HNS &LR;      06-23 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-OTTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS CONTINUED DECLINE IN NUMBER OF SEA OTTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a disturbing trend, the population of
California sea otters continues to fall, raising fears that the
state's popular marine mammal will one day disappear from the rocky
coastline.
</P>
<P>
   The spring survey conducted by teams of scientists found 2,090
sea otters, indicating an overall decline of 1.14 percent from a
survey a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers had edged up to 2,377 in 1995, the highest since
reddish-brown furry marine mammal was designated an endangered
species in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists don't understand why the California sea otter is
declining in its home range from Point Conception in Santa Barbara
County to Half Moon Bay in San Mateo County. They suspect
infectious disease, water contaminants, entanglement or entrapment
in fishing gear, and starvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This continuing pattern of decline is of grave concern,
especially given our lack of understanding of the cause,'' said Jim
Estes, a marine biologist with the U.S. Geological Survey's
Biological Resources Division at the University of California at
Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by the USGS, the California Department
of Fish and Game, the Monterey Bay Aquarium and experienced
volunteers. It focused on 375 miles of California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Infectious diseases, including parasitic worms and encephalitis,
have caused about 40 percent of deaths over time, a high rate when
compared to diseases in other wild species, Estes said. But
scientists don't believe that can be blamed completely for the
decline in otter population because the death rate from disease has
been constant since 1995, the year the numbers began falling.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does reproductive failure appear to be a factor in the
decline because the otter birth rate remains unchanged, Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest year for otters was in 1998, when animal rescue
teams found 213 otters dead or ill on beaches. Scientists cautioned
that the number of dead otters was probably higher because many
animals that die sink at sea and their carcasses are never found.
</P>
<P>
   The USGS National Wildlife Health Center in Madison, Wis., has
been examining the bodies with the help of the California
Department of Fish and Game and the University of California at
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, an informal survey by the same team of scientists
that conducted the spring survey found only 1,937 surviving otters.
</P>
<P>
   After that survey, Carl Benz, head of the Fish and Wildlife
Service's recovery team for the otter, said, ``More otters are
dying each year than are being born. If this trend continues, it's
entirely possible that this species may go extinct.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 100,000 sea otters left in the world with about
98,000 living in Alaskan and British Columbian waters and the
balance along the California coast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By law, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is required to update
a recovery plan for the species. As yet, there is no new plan.
</P>
<P>
   In April, members of Fish and Wildlife's recovery team
recommended a list of studies that would cost $1.7 million per year
for five years to explore the causes of death.
</P>
<P>
   One study would investigate the ways in which otters are exposed
to acanthocephalan worms, which infest them and carry deadly
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Another would investigate possible otter drownings caused by
entanglement in the large-mesh gillnets used by fishermen.
Regulations require nets to be set in water deeper than 180 feet,
as a way to protect otters. But otters go into the deeper water,
too, and gillnet fishing is increasing in southern Monterey Bay,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the commercial fishing industries that catch live
fish for market are beginning to use more of the pots that have
funnel shaped interiors. The pots can trap curious otters that
venture inside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
