<HEADER>
A6517 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TASTE-PICKLE-SFCHRON &LR;      06-23 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-PICKLE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASTER'S CHOICE  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.    By Robin Davis 
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 Panel Prefers the Pucker Of Mrs. Fanning's Pickles 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Bread-and-butter pickles are a popular summertime
phenomenon. The sweet slices work well on burgers, and are just as
great for straight nibbling or relish trays. Those with gardens and
plenty of time put up their own pickles. The rest of us rely on
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted six different bread-and-butter pickles, two
from the refrigerator section and four off the shelf. Prices
differed dramatically, from $1.99 to $4.49.
</P>
<P>
   While the panel picked an overwhelming favorite, they also
agreed that pickles are personal. Some liked brands with more acid;
others liked more spice.
</P>
<P>
   But far and away, the panel chose Mrs. Fanning's (12 ounces,
$1.99 at Andronico's) as the best. Three of the panelists
particularly liked the spice level. One panelist described it as a
``full-flavored pickle.'' All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to Cascadian Farms (22 ounces, $3.99 at
Andronico's). Two panelists thought it was so acidic that it would
overpower many foods, but another described the flavor as clean.
Two panelists liked the crunchy texture. Three would buy it; two
might.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbies (33 ounces, $3.19-$4.49 at many supermarkets in the
refrigerator section) came in third. Four panelists thought it
tasted watery and lacked the intense flavor of other brands.
Another panelist liked the flavor but found the texture too soft.
Two might buy it, three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to Safeway (22 ounces, $2.79). Two panelists
described it as ``not very exciting'' and two others thought it was
harsh and acidic. But one dissenter liked the bold flavors and
described it as classic. One would buy it, four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Two brands scored too low to rate: Vlasic and Claussen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna
Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland
Passot chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and Menlo Park, and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
