<HEADER>
A6519 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICK-PORK-SFCHRON &LR;      06-23 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICK-PORK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with enough
leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes plus
suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus suggestions
in optional trim.    THE WEEKEND COOK: Globe-Trotting Meatballs Put Variety in Your 
 Life 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     By Maria Cianci 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; They may call pork ``the other white meat,'' but I
think of it as the versatile meat. From flavoring agent to
center-of-the plate entree, fresh and in all its cured forms, pork
gives the cook more culinary options than any other meat in the
larder.
<P>
   Underutilized _ but not to be underestimated _ is ground pork,
which imparts deep flavor to sauces, meat loaves, dumplings and
more. Take that ground pork and form it into meatballs large and
small and you have the foundation for a passel of week-long dishes.
</P>
<P>
   You can increase the versatility of the meatballs by seasoning
batches of them differently. So, herewith, one batch of ground pork
seasoned three different ways _ umpteen meatballs and dinner ideas
for a week of fast cooking.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER RECIPE: 3 PORK MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds ground pork
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, well beaten
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups fresh breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon crumbled dried sage
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce fresh ginger, peeled and minced to a puree
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, minced to a puree
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Combine the pork, onions, eggs, salt and pepper in a large bowl.
Mix well. Add the breadcrumbs. Mix well. Divide the pork mixture
evenly among 3 bowls.
</P>
<P>
   To one bowl, add the lemon zest, sage and nutmeg; mix well. This
mixture is for the Swedish-style meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   To the second bowl, add the sugar, ketchup, vinegar,
Worcestershire and cayenne; mix well. This is for the
barbecue-style meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   To the third bowl, add the ginger, garlic, soy sauce and sesame
oil; mix well. This is for the Asian-style meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   Cover all three bowls and refrigerate for at least 1 hour and up
to 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shaping the Meatballs.  &LR; Swedish-style mixture: form into about
24 11/2-ounce rounds about the size of a golf ball. Barbecue-style:
form into about 42 1/2-ounce balls. Asian-style: form into about 30
1-ounce balls.
</P>
<P>
   The meatballs may be refrigerated for a day or frozen for up to
3 weeks. To freeze the meatballs, place them on a baking tray in
the freezer until they are hard, then transfer to freezer
containers. Defrost before using.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 96 meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SWEDISH MEATBALL &LR; : 45 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 2 g fat (1 g saturated), 23 mg cholesterol, 70 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER BBQ MEATBALL &LR; : 25 calories, 3 g protein, 1 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 1 g fat (0 g saturated), 13 mg cholesterol, 45 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER ASIAN MEATBALL: &LR;   &LR; 35 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 2 g fat (1 g saturated), 18 mg cholesterol, 90 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WEEKEND RECIPE: SWEDISH-STYLE MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   Note: Serve with buttered noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   20 Swedish-style meatballs (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried cherries
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced dill
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large, nonstick saute pan over high heat. Add the oil and
heat, swirling the pan. Add the meatballs and saute until browned
on all sides; this takes about 7 minutes. Remove the meatballs from
the pan. Discard all the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Replace the pan over high heat. Deglaze with the wine. Simmer
for a minute. Add the broth and boil for 5 minutes, skimming.
</P>
<P>
   Add the meatballs and pepper. Bring to a boil, cover, reduce
heat to medium and simmer for 5 minutes. Add the cream and
cherries, bring to a boil and simmer for 5 minutes. Add the dill
and simmer for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 400 calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 15 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 25 g fat (11 g saturated), 154 mg cholesterol, 417
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: BRAISED SAVOY CABBAGE WITH PORK MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   30 barbecue-style meatballs (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 head savoy cabbage (about 13/4 pounds), cored, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon caraway seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Heat the oil in a large heavy pan over high heat. Add the
meatballs and saute until browned on all sides, 6 to 7 minutes.
Using a slotted spoon, transfer the meatballs to a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cabbage and onion to the pan and cook for a few minutes,
tossing constantly, until the cabbage is wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Add the water, caraway seeds and salt. Bring to a boil over high
heat, cover and boil for 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the meatballs and any accumulated juices, tossing them with
the cabbage. Cover and boil until the cabbage is very soft, 8 to 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 280 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g protein, 17 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 13 g fat (4 g saturated), 96 mg cholesterol, 917 mg
sodium, 4 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: SHRIMP &AMP; PORK BALL SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a light, lovely Thai soup, made especially well at
Regent Thai in San Francisco, this comes together very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2.5 ounces bean thread noodles (also called cellophane noodles)
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno pepper, halved lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   20 Asian-style meatballs (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces baby spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound shrimp (16/20 count), peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Soak the noodles in warm water for 15 minutes; drain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, combine the broth, water and jalapeno in a large pan.
Bring to a boil over high heat. Add the noodles and simmer for 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the meatballs and simmer for 4 to 5 minutes, until just
cooked through.
</P>
<P>
   Add the spinach, submerging the leaves until they are wilted, 20
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Add the shrimp and cook at a bare simmer until they are just
cooked through, no longer than 1 minute. Remove the jalapeno halves
and ladle into bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 315 calories, &LR;   &LR; 37 g protein, 19 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 9 g fat (3 g saturated), 178 mg cholesterol, 488 mg
sodium, 1 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; More Ideas for Meatballs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Pork meatballs may be frozen or refrigerated for many uses,
including:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Barley Pork Ball Soup. &LR;  Saute onions, carrots and celery in a
little oil until wilted. Add quick-cooking barley and chicken
broth; simmer until the barley is tender. Add Swedish-style or
barbecue-style meatballs and simmer until they are cooked through.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cole Slaw Meatball Sandwich. &LR;  Grill or saute barbecue-style
pork balls; brush with barbecue sauce. Brush a soft roll with
mustard, pile the meatballs inside and top with cole slaw.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pork Balls with Lemon-Caper Sauce. &LR;  Saute Swedish-style pork
balls, then add a little chicken broth, cover and simmer until they
are just cooked through. Add lemon juice, capers and pepper to
taste. Pour the very thin sauce over the meatballs. Serve with rice
or noodles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pork Ball Hors d'Oeuvre. &LR;  Saute or grill Asian-style pork
balls. Serve with a dip of wasabi and soy sauce, teriyaki sauce and
scallions or sweet-sour Thai fish sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bean Balls. &LR;  Saute Swedish-style meatballs until they are
browned; set aside. Saute thinly sliced onions and garlic until the
onions are caramelized. Deglaze the pan with chicken broth, season
with cumin. Add the meatballs, cover and simmer until they are just
cooked through. Add canned, drained chickpeas and simmer briefly.
Stir in chopped parsley. The mixture should be slightly soupy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
