<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      06-23 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, June 24:
</P>
<P>
   GROUSSAY-AUCTION (Undated) _ On June 6, the splendors of Chateau
de Groussay _ the greatest private interiors concocted in the 20th
century _ disappeared, dispersed for $26.5 million, more than $10
million above the auctioneers' estimate. By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   FARNSWORTH-HOUSE (Chicago) _ The secret I had never known, even
after 20 years of covering architectural landmarks, was that as a
result of a fight with Ludwig Mies van der Rohe _ that towering
figure from the Bauhaus whose disciples remade Chicago at
mid-century _ my father put the final touch on one of the most
famous buildings of the 20th century. By David W. Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-HOUSE (Undated) _ On February 10, when Gioang Huu Nguyen
boarded a Singapore Airline flight to Ho Chi Minh City, he was a
man in a hurry. He had one month to build his 76-year-old mother a
new house. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-HOME (North Salem, N.Y.) _ As the rumors drift along
tiny Main Street here, like a fog that just won't lift, the
citizens of this bucolic town are gearing up for the onslaught of
stone-faced Secret Service personnel, paparazzi and television
vans. It's all about Hillary Clinton's new house. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO-PAVILION (Sacramento, Calif.) _ What could be more
pleasant than relaxing in a sleek, glass-walled pavilion with views
onto a rural backdrop of pond and meandering river, where the only
disturbance is the croaking of frogs and the quacking of ducks?
That picturesque conceit has been realized in this unlikely city,
the politically active but architecturally dull state capital of
California. By Frances Anderton.
</P>
<P>
   DESK-CHAIRS (Undated) _ Desk chairs, or task chairs, as they are
now called in the trade (to distinguish them from those thronelike
executive models), are no longer just pieces of furniture bought to
match a desk. A good chair, the ergonomists tell us, is probably
the single most important office tool. By Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With how to drawing.
</P>
