</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOUSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY IS ON ALLAN HOUSTON'S SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Spurs probably don't want to know the details of
this story. At least not now. This is not the time for them to
learn about the dazzling and dangerous tale of Allan Houston. If
they learn too much about this man, whose history is equal parts
basketball and magic, the Spurs might start believing that Houston
was put here specifically to yank the NBA title from them. They
just might be right, too.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't know about the 6-foot-6-inch Knicks guard is
good enough. If they were to find out, for example, when and where
he took his first steps, they might be so spooked that they would
forget they actually lead the best-of-seven championship series,
two games to one.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, this is a warning to Gregg Popovich, Tim Duncan, David
Robinson, and the rest of the basketball band from Texas. They
should be satisfied in knowing that Houston is capable of scoring
34 points, as he did in Game 2 Monday night. They should remember
to keep a hand in his face when he shoots. And when his jump shot,
one of the prettiest you've ever seen, is incapable of being
stopped, the Spurs should simply hope that the rest of the Knicks
are not blessed with Houston's secret. If they go any deeper into
the story than that, they could find trouble where Wade Houston
first experienced joy.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in 1972, Wade was inside the gym of Ahrens Vocational
Technical High in Louisville. He was a coach there. In that gym, he
watched his young son walk for the first time. Think about that.
The first time Houston could walk anywhere, he walked on a
basketball court. And it wasn't just any court. It was located at
the intersection of First Street and a street named after a man
nicknamed ``The Greatest,'' Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Steve Kerr probably didn't know how deep his words were
when he spoke of Houston at Madison Square Garden. The Spurs guard
said he loved watching Houston shoot in Game 6 of the semifinals
against the Pacers. Kerr went on to say that Houston used to be a
more limited shooter with fewer dimensions to his game. Now, Kerr
said, there are no weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he is doing,'' Kerr said, ``is a natural evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr traces the beginning of Houston's evolution to 1993, when
the guard was a rookie with the Pistons. But the timeline goes
further back than that. It begins with the upbringing of Wade
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it basically started with him not pressuring me to go
outside and say, ``Go shoot' and ``Do it this way; do it that way,'
'' Houston said of his father. ``He let me enjoy the game and
really didn't . . . I don't think he expected me to be a good
player until I got into my last couple years of high school. That
was when he just let me continue to play the game. He guided me.
That's the type of person he is. He gave me a lot of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's father was born in a place called Alcoa, which is
about 15 miles south of Knoxville, Tenn. The locals know Alcoa
because it is the home of Alcoa Aluminum, where many people in Wade
Houston's family worked. But many NFL fans from the 1980s will
remember that Alcoa also used to sponsor a highlight-play segment
called ``Fantastic Finishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, brings us back to Houston. Since taking those
steps on that court in Louisville, he has been around or a part of
fantastic finishes his entire life. His father was an assistant at
the University of Louisville when the team won the NCAA title in
1980. Houston considers many of those players big brothers. In his
sophomore year at the University of Tennessee, playing for his
father, Houston hit a shot that defeated Auburn at the buzzer.
After some rough moments, moments that led to the loss of some
friendships, he would do the same thing in the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between good and great in this league is two
things,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy was saying Tuesday.
``Consistency and who can do it late. That's what it comes down to.
Allan is doing it more consistently and he's doing it late in the
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Come now. Let's take a look at his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5, the final second of a first-round series against the
Heat: Houston makes a shot at the buzzer to win it. The ball rolls
tentatively on the rim, a deep breath away from falling in or out.
If it had fallen off, Van Gundy would have lost his job. It went in
and the coach is here, preparing for Game 4 of the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6, a third-round game the Knicks must win to avoid a return
trip to Indiana: Houston scores 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3, a game that puts the Spurs another step closer to a
sweep: Houston scores 34 points. One of his shots was a pull-up
3-pointer on a fast break.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this is that people didn't think Houston could play
well in New York. He left the Pistons for the Knicks in July 1996.
Grant Hill immediately stopped speaking to him. Houston was married
in August and invited all of his former teammates to the wedding.
Only two _ Don Reid and Lindsey Hunter _ bothered to show up. He is
what many would call the anti-Knick. He's a nice man. He lives in a
mansion, on 4 acres of land in Connecticut, because he says it is
peaceful. He makes a point of looking interviewers in the eye,
something his father taught him and the rest of his teammates at
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had dinner with him when he first got to Detroit,'' said
Knicks assistant Brendan Malone, a former assistant with the
Pistons. ``He told me he internalizes everything. He once had a
problem with his stomach and didn't tell anybody.'' Malone said
Houston has a ``passive-aggressive'' personality, the kind of man
who would go to a party and ``head for the nearest wall and stand
around until he felt comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   He is more than comfortable now. He's hungry. As he said, ``The
first part of my position says `shooting.' '' He has learned to
demand the ball, early and late. None of this is good for the
Spurs. But really, shouldn't they have been suspicious long before
Game 3? Here they are, Texans in New York, being asked to stop a
New Yorker named Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
