<HEADER>
A6536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-23 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WINNING IS IN THE PLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no shortage of people retailing poker advice. Country
singer Kenny Rogers yawps about knowing when to hold/when to fold,
etc. etc. Ernest Hemingway stupidly advised: ``Never call; either
raise or throw down.'' But the most famous poker advice of this
century was put forward in 1957 by Herbert Yardley, a washed-up
cryptologist, one year before his death.
</P>
<P>
   Yardley's book, ``The Education of a Poker Player,'' proved to
be an unexpected sensation for its publisher, Simon &AMP; Schuster,
which eventually called up 12 printings of the tome that Poker
magazine recently hailed as ``a true classic.'' Out of print for
several decades, ``Education'' has been just been reissued by
Orloff Press of Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The book is renowned not so much for the poker advice _ of which
more later _ but for the colorful stories Yardley spins about his
gaming education. Orphaned as a teenager and raised in the farm
town of Worthington, Ind., Yardley enjoyed what biographers call a
``checkered'' career.
</P>
<P>
   Gifted at mathematics and blessed with a photographic memory, he
became one of America's first code breakers, operating the State
Department's legendary ``Black Chamber,'' which broke Japan's
diplomatic code in 1921. Yardley won the Distinguished Service
Medal for his efforts, and a few years later, got fired. The
priggish secretary of state who disbanded the cryptography office,
Henry Stimson, later proclaimed: ``Gentlemen do not read each
other's mail.''
</P>
<P>
   A vengeful Yardley promptly published a tell-all memoir, ``The
American Black Chamber Secret Service,'' which sold well, was made
into a movie, and infuriated his former employers. Shortly
thereafter, he hied himself off to China, where he worked as a
freelance code breaker for Chiang Kai-shek's Kuomintang. While in
China, Yardley crossed paths with Boston Latin's own Theodore H.
White, and with New Yorker writer Emily Hahn. Yardley tucked many
tales of derring-do into his slender, 160-page book about poker.
</P>
<P>
   So what about the advice? Everything Yardley knows, he claims to
have learned at Monty's Place, a small-time Indiana saloon swept
out by Dummy, the village idiot, and guarded by Runt, the gigantic
bouncer. Yardley's mentor James Montgomery divides the poker world
into players and ``simpletons,'' the latter existing to enrich the
former. Under Monty's tutelage, Yardley quickly becomes a
successful player.
</P>
<P>
   Monty is smart, and has taken possession of much of the county's
``real goods,'' i.e., a wagon with two fresh horses, a farm, and
even a traveling circus show, from simpletons who show up at his
poker table. Monty doesn't drink when he plays. He makes sure that
the suckers sit to his right; they'll do the betting for him. Monty
doesn't stay in a five-card game with a low pair, meaning anything
below jacks.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Monty nor Yardley would ever be caught drawing to an
inside straight. In a nutshell, here is Yardley's poker philosophy:
Bet on the cards you have, not on the cards you hope to get. (Not a
bad life philosophy, come to think of it.) In poker parlance this
translates to: Never bet on the come. Yardley's Chinese translator
violates this cardinal rule in a dramatic showdown hand with a Nazi
spy in Chungking. To find out what happens, you'll have to buy the
book.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to apply Yardley's winning formula the other night in a
six-handed game. Where Yardley sparred with Nazi spies, or
hinterland sharpies like Salty the horse trader and Hairlip Slocum,
the banker's son, I played with Michael, two Davids, a Richard, and
a Joe. I quickly learned that Yardley's dicta, which I had
half-committed to memory, might indeed help me win. But they would
never help me have fun.
</P>
<P>
   In some games, for instance, Yardley would have you play only
one in five hands while you wait for key pairs or matchups. If
you're playing for the family farm, it makes sense to be patient.
But we were playing dollar limit, with three raises. I played
almost every hand, lost some money, and had a grand time. In
Yardley's book, I will always be: A perfect (but happy) simpleton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
