 ART ADV.: A photo with RETREAT-RESPITE is being transmitted to NYT
Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-POLITICS (Washington) _ One month ago, according to NRA
spokesman Bill Powers, ``the National Rifle Association was
declared dead'' in the wake of Senate approval of a gun control
bill. Now the NRA is so emboldened by last week's defeat of similar
legislation that it plans the biggest effort in its history to sway
the presidential and congressional elections. By Michael Kranish.
1200 words. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RETREAT-RESPITE (Undated) _ An increasing number of people are
going on retreats seeking a chance for prayer, quiet meditation,
and, at some places, to be surrounded by Gregorian chanting.
Beautiful vistas of mountains, rolling hills and oceans are not bad
selling points either. By Diego Ribadeneira. 1200 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- While most scholars would be
accustomed to having their work published in academic journals,
Rabbi Shmuley Boteach's book was excerpted in Playboy. But then,
his book is titled ``Kosher Sex.'' By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- Not all of my hexes live in Texas. But
enough of them do so that I reflexively keep my left hand high when
anything associated with the Lone Star State veers into my lane of
life. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- Partisan propagandists trying to drag
class warfare into the 2000 election might ask: How can class count
if Ivy Leaguers flood the field? By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Commandments of the House of
Representatives. By Derrick Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- Herbert Yardley's classic, ``The
Education of a Poker Player,'' has been just been reissued by
Orloff Press, of Athens, Ga. By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OZAWA-SUCCEED (Boston) _ The leading contender to succeed Seiji
Ozawa at the BSO for many years was Simon Rattle, and he probably
still is, although he is no longer the unanimous favorite he once
was. By Richard Dyer. 1050 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSH (Undated) _ Will George W. Bush become the media's
next Bill Clinton? At this point, the mainstream media -- scarred
by the public rebuke of their Monica Lewinsky obsession -- appear
to have little appetite for a full-scale Bush character hunt. By
Mark Jurkowitz. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MA-UTILITIES (Boston) _ In Massachusetts, big businesses and
some municipalities and nonprofit organizations have seen
competition reduce their electric rates. Missing from the mix: Bay
State residents. That could all change, as small start-up companies
like Essential.com begin ``bundling'' electric and telephone
services. By Ronald Rosenberg. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   ONJOBS-COLUMN (Undated) -- New study finds entry-level minority
jobs are on the rise, while senior-level black managers are on the
decline. By Diane E. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ You've never heard of Brian Arena.
Neither has anyone in New Jersey. But working for New Jersey's
pension fund, Arena has made close to $1 billion for the state by
investing in Internet stocks. By Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-HOUSTON (New York) _ The Spurs probably don't want to learn
about the dazzling and dangerous tale of Allan Houston. If they
learn too much about this man, whose history is equal parts
basketball and magic, the Spurs might start believing that Houston
was put here specifically to yank the NBA title from them. They
just might be right, too. By Michael Holley. 1070 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RYAN-COLUMN (New York) _ The Wise Men have convened and
talked about the state of the NBA, beset with low scores, sagging
TV ratings and unspeakably ugly games. By Bob Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   HKO-NHL-DRAFT (Undated) _ When Sergei Samsonov walked into the
room, the scouts were speechless. They saw his broad shoulders and
stocky legs and in a split-second all of their fears about his
purported lack of size evaporated. They were sold. By Nancy
Marrapese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOMEN'S SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
