<SLUG> BC-GULLS-HUMANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE FREE LUNCH FOR ZOO'S SEA GULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco Zoo officials think they've
finally found a way to stop the swarms of divebombing sea gulls
that have turned lunchtime into the plot of an Alfred Hitchcock
horror film.
</P>
<P>
   Put the humans in a cage.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the $14,000 enclosure that has covered the Plaza Cafe
since Saturday is more like an aviary _ a woven plastic barrier
that allows zoo guests to engage their own feeding habits without
having to share with another species.
</P>
<P>
   The gulls have been a problem at the zoo for years because
visitors have consistently ignored the small forest of ``Do Not
Feed the Birds'' signs that surround the basketball court-sized
dining area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids, once they've settled in with their French fries, will
start tossing them food,'' said John Aikin, the zoo's curator of
planning and design. ``When they turn their back, the gull will
grab everything on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   In the flurry of confusion, visitors have from time to time been
nipped by a gull. And while the birds can bite hard, zoo officials
are not allowed to bite back.
</P>
<P>
   Protected under the Migratory Bird Treaty Act, the nine species
of gulls that populate the area cannot be injured or harassed, only
deterred.
</P>
<P>
   Putting paying customers under a net was not the first choice.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, zoo officials tried to strike fear into the birds
by swinging a stuffed dead gull in effigy around the area, an
unappetizing proposition that didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   They also tried to frighten them off with rubber snakes, wooden
alligators with twirling arms and a gull ``alarm'' call over a zoo
loudspeaker. They led owls and other predators into the area to
scare away the birds. They set up concrete barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, the gulls came back, leaving zoo spokesman Nancy Chan
impressed at the species' ability to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gulls know all of the feeding patterns in this place,''
Chan said. ``They know when the penguins eat, they know when the
sea lions eat and they know when the people eat.''
</P>
<P>
   With the changes, the Plaza Cafe resembles the fenced-in home
for the leaf monkeys who live a few yards away.
</P>
<P>
   The black mesh netting is 12 feet high and covers the plaza's
food outlets and dining area. Visitors enter and exit through a
plastic curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, zoo officials concede that the only way to
permanently keep the birds away from the Plaza Cafe is for visitors
to stop feeding the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Rockwood, the zoo's food service manager, said the gulls
are not always at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the guests here see the gulls as an annoyance. The other
half see it as an interactive exhibit, just another part of the
zoo,'' said Rockwood, who has witnessed frequent attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
