<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WWC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICICCO MAY STICK WITH WHAT GOT HIS TEAM WHERE IT IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Though he's talked about the need for more speed in
the lineup against the fleet Nigerians in Thursday's second World
Cup match, US women's soccer coach Tony DiCicco may end up fielding
the same 11 who blanked Denmark in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want your best athletes on the field against a team like
this,'' he said Tuesday. ``But we'll put Nigeria up on the board
tonight and look at the matchups and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds are that DiCicco will go with the starters who've lost only
eight matches in the five years he's coached them, but won't
hesitate to move them around and go to the bench if he senses a
mismatch. That could mean the Cup debut of Natick-born Sara Whalen,
who is the fastest reserve and can attack from both the back line
and midfield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a crowd
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who drew a record 78,972 at Giants Stadium (for a
$4 million gate), will be playing in another full stadium here. All
65,000 seats have been sold for the doubleheader (which also
includes Brazil-Italy) at Soldier Field, which also hosted the 1994
men's Cup opener.
</P>
<P>
   That means that US games alone will have already surpassed the
total attendance (112,000) for the 1995 tournament in Sweden with
as many as four matches still to play.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ticket sales have already passed 500,000 and will
easily eclipse the tournament record of 510,000 set in 1991 in
China, where most of the spectators were factory workers with free
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have exceeded our greatest expectations,'' said organizing
committee president Marla Messing. ``There is no mistaking that a
World Cup is going on and America is coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   America is even coming out to watch the Nigerias play the North
Koreas. The six non-US doubleheaders for the rest of the first
round are averaging nearly 22,000, with more than 32,000 tickets
already sold for the June 26 matches in Chicago that have no local
ethnic draw (i.e. Ghana-Sweden/Norway-Japan).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No speedy conclusions
</P>
<P>
   Though roughly half the US team watched Nigeria beat North Korea
on TV at their suburban hotel Sunday night, they're reluctant to
draw any firm conclusions about the Super Falcons, whom they've
never played. ``It's tough to tell anything from television,
especially about speed,'' says Brandi Chastain. ``You may get on
the field and say, hey, this isn't at all what I expected. What you
see can be an illusion, because TV plays tricks.'' . . . After
switching Tuesday's scheduled practice at Benedictine University in
suburban Lisle from early evening to mid-afternoon, DiCicco ended
up scrubbing it entirely when thunderstorms swept through the area.
In the morning, the reserves visited disadvantaged children living
at the SOS Children's Village in Lockport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
