<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WWC-SCURRY-BOS &LR;      06-23 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WWC-SCURRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULLING OUT ALL THE STOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Just kidding about the naked bungee jumping, she says.
The last time Briana Scurry half-jokingly told the world about her
celebration plans, she ended up streaking naked down a Georgia side
street with her Olympic gold medal around her neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Illustrated called me at, like, eight in the morning
one day when I was half-asleep and asked me what I would do if we
won,'' the US women's soccer goalkeeper remembers. ``And I didn't
want to be like everybody else, so I said that.''
</P>
<P>
   So this time, Scurry is saying nothing. Anyway, it's not as if
the planet will stop spinning in shock if the Americans win the
World Cup next month. They're the best team in the tournament,
they're playing at home inside full stadia, and they have the
world's most dominant keeper in the 27-year-old University of
Massachusetts grad, who has posted 50 shutouts in 86 career
matches, most recently a 3-0 blanking of Denmark in last Saturday's
Cup opener at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the US is to reclaim the title it lost to Norway four
years ago, Scurry is going to have to loom large on her line. ``We
need a big World Cup from Briana Scurry,'' coach Tony DiCicco says
flatly. ``We're not going anywhere without her.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry has started three times as many matches as any other
American keeper, and since she took over the job in 1994, her
teammates have lost only eight times. Not that Scurry is
overworked, not on a squad that wins most of its matches by three
goals or more. ``Sometimes I'm like, OK, do something,'' she
concedes. ``Come at me with a ball _ anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But once the medals are in view, Scurry will be scrambling, and
she knows it. ``If I don't have a lot to do when we're playing
Norway and China, I'm surprised,'' says Scurry, who can ensure her
mates of a return ticket to Olympus if she shuts out the Nigerians
Thursday night at Soldier Field. ``I know it's going to be a
big-time game; I know I'm going to be battling.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it was at UMass, where Scurry allowed an average
of just half a goal a game and backstopped the Minutewomen to the
1993 NCAA Final Four. Even before she was voted the nation's best
keeper, her coach told Scurry she should look into the national
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Is there one?' '' she recalls. ``Isn't that horrible?
I did not know. I'm playing college soccer and I had no clue.
Totally oblivious. He said, `Well, they won the World Cup.' I'm
like, `Cool.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry, who played her high school soccer in Minnesota, had been
oblivious about UMass before she was recruited. ``I thought it was
in Boston,'' she confesses. ``Everyone I told I said, `I'm going to
Boston.' Amherst is nowhere near Boston, of course, but it was
awesome. Whenever I see the basketball team on TV and see the
Mullins Center I'm like, `Awww.' I miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing for the national team alongside women such as Mia Hamm,
Michelle Akers, and Kristine Lilly, all of whom had been piling up
caps when Scurry was still playing for Anoka High, was nothing like
playing for UMass. It was harder _ and easier. ``I'd seen a lot of
shots at UMass, and now I would hardly see any,'' she says. ``I'd
think, I'm not earning my keep. I'm just standing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the World Cup and the Olympics, where Scurry suddenly gets
all the action she can handle and one goal allowed can be too many.
The Norwegians put one past her in the 1995 semifinals, and it was
enough to send the Americans home. So nobody was taking anything
for granted in the Summer Games, which is why Scurry offered to run
to daylight if her teammates came up golden.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we beat the Chinese in the final, everyone asked me,
what are you going to do? When? Where?'' Scurry remembers. ``It was
one in the morning, mind you. I told them, `I said I was going to
run, but I didn't say you could watch.' They said, how will we
know? I said, `Don't worry, I've got it covered.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Scurry found a secluded spot in Athens, Ga., where the
stadium was, took her clothes off, put the medal on, and did a
point-to-point dash with her roommate rolling a video camera. ``We
brought the tape back to the team party, showed it to a couple of
people for verification, and that was it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   What could Scurry do to top that? ``The Olympics were the be-all
and end-all for me,'' she says. ``As a youngster, I'd always wanted
to be in them. Now, I'd won a gold medal. So it was kind of an
anticlimactic depression thing for a few months. I was like, `OK,
now what?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The next World Cup was still three years off. But Scurry
remained on her line, piling up the caps and shutouts, and as the
months went by she could feel her competitive fires getting stoked
anew. The tournament was here, after all, most of her teammates
were sticking around, and the Norwegians still had the trophy. ``We
have to win,'' Scurry told herself, ``because we didn't win in
1995.''
</P>
<P>
   So what can Scurry do for an encore, after the run to daylight?
Maybe a little black dress, stiletto heels, and bottle of champagne
in a quiet Pasadena restaurant. Or maybe not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
