<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-PAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAK IN MAJOR FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Se Ri Pak exploded on the women's golf scene
a year ago at the McDonald's LPGA Championship at DuPont CC here in
the Brandywine Valley. She was just 20 years old, fresh out of her
hometown of Daejeon midway between Seoul and Pusan on Korea's east
coast. She led wire-to-wire in her first major as a pro, becoming
the first since Liselotte Neumann to make a major her first
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   This was huge news in her homeland, where there are just about
150 golf courses and the game is considered elitist. So what did
Pak do for an encore? She went to the US Women's Open at Blackwolf
Run GC in Kohler, Wis., and defeated Jenny Chuasiriporn on the 20th
hole of a playoff to become the youngest to win that title.
</P>
<P>
   She competed in 27 tournaments in 1998, ran away with Player of
the Year honors, and signed a lucrative contract with the Samsung
Group. She also was awarded the Order of Merit by the South Korean
government, the highest honor for an athlete. She joined Meg Mallon
and Mickey Wright as the only players to win the LPGA Championship
and the US Women's Open in the same year _ and it was just six
years after her father taught her the game.
</P>
<P>
   Pak is back to defend in the LPGA Championship, which begins
Thursday, and she played her first 18 holes here since walking away
with the title after an intense final-round duel with England's
Lisa Hackney last year. Hackney, who actually seized a brief lead
before she bogeyed the 13th and Pak birdied the 15th and 16th,
finished three shots astern, tied with Donna Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Pak severed her relationship with swing guru David Ledbetter at
the start of the year and is still searching for the right
instructor. She had been struggling somewhat, but a win last Sunday
on Father's Day in Atlantic City, capping another wire-to-wire run,
was sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give the trophy to my father,'' she said. ``It
makes a good feeling to this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory elevated her to eighth on the LPGA money list and
put her in a proper frame of mind for this $1.4 million tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week my putting was good, and I hit driver and irons
well,'' said Pak. ``Everything felt perfect. Everything's getting
better and better each week. That win makes me have more
confidence. Good timing, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak said she is still learning the game, the same thing Tiger
Woods said at the US Open last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though this is my second year, I still feel like a
rookie,'' she said. ``It takes time. Many people say, `Why?' and
`What happened to her?' and `How long do we have to wait?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure comes partly from her native land, where she won 30
times as an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week, even right after I win, they want another win,
another trophy,'' she said. ``It's not that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the defending champ here doesn't put more pressure on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same,'' said Pak. ``It doesn't change anything. I don't need
to hurry. I am just 21. I have 10 or 15 more years to play. Maybe
more. No need to push myself. I don't want to be tired in two or
three years and not want to play golf anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
