<SLUG> BC-HKO-NHL-DRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURE THINGS AWAIT BRUINS AT PICK NO. 21 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The predraft parade of prospects into the Bruins' interview area
at the club's hotel in Pittsburgh two summers ago proceeded along
pretty much as planned. The teenagers, one at a time, would meet
with the scouting staff, they'd answer question upon question about
hockey, their lifestyle, their personality, their hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   The scouts would size them up, rate them, then debate taking
them when Boston's turn came to choose. The Bruins, owners of that
No. 1 overall selection, had long declared their intentions to take
Joe Thornton. It was their No. 8 pick they were trolling for.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at them and they're all 6-3, 190 pounds,'' said
assistant general manager Mike O'Connell. ``They all look like Joe.
They all say, `I'm really going to be working out hard this
summer.' Then you look at the kid. He's chewing gum, he's got his
sandals on. They're fidgeting, they have pimply faces, they were
everything you expect in a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost all of them. When Sergei Samsonov walked into the
room, the scouts were speechless. They saw his broad shoulders and
stocky legs and in a split-second all of their fears about his
purported lack of size evaporated. They were sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was how he felt about his size,'' said Jeff Gorton,
O'Connell's top aide, on the reason they were swayed. ``The things
he would say. We'd say, `What do you think about everyone saying
you're too small to play in the league?' He said, `I will go
somewhere and play in the NHL. Don't worry about my size. If you're
worried about it, the next person who takes me won't be.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had an aura about himself. You knew he was going to
play in the league and size wasn't going to stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bruins didn't have a first-round pick because
they traded it to Colorado. Their first selection came late in the
second round, at No. 48. Again, size became an issue when they
interviewed defenseman Jonathan Girard, who is 5 feet 11 inches and
192 pounds. Once again, the Bruins challenged the player to see how
he felt about his prospects of facing bigger, stronger foes in the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm not too small to play,' '' said Gorton. ``He was
very confident. He knew he was going to play since he was a young
kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we drafted him, he came down to the table and said, `I
didn't think you guys were going to take me. You said I was too
small.' But we really wanted to push him in the interview and say
it to him and see how he would react. We didn't want to hear,
`You're right, I am small, maybe I won't play.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to push these guys on things you might think would
hold him back. When he left the interview, I bet he was agitated.
`Those Bruins aren't going to take me, they're worried about my
size. Well, I'll show them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Girard, who started the season in Boston before being returned
to his junior team in the Quebec League, is developing into one of
the Bruins' top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   So, what to make of this year, the first time the Bruins have
ever hosted the NHL draft? They are selecting at No. 21 and the
scouting staff believes they will definitely get a player at that
spot. But it has proven to be a crapshoot in the past. The last
time the Bruins picked at 21 was in 1995 when they took defenseman
Sean Brown, who was later dealt to Edmonton in the Bill Ranford
deal in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Bruins took goalie Evgeny Ryabchikov with the No.
21 pick and that certainly didn't pan out. In 1990, Boston picked
Bryan Smolinski at 21 and then dealt him to Pittsburgh in the
ill-fated Kevin Stevens multiplayer deal. The best pick at No. 21
most recently was in 1993 when Montreal got talented forward Saku
Koivu.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard when you're picking 21st, you don't know who's
going to be there,'' said O'Connell. ``Picking 21st was the third
round like 20 years ago. We expect a player who's going to play for
us in the NHL. How effective he'll be, whether he's going to be a
goal scorer or a checker, or a stay at home defenseman or an
offensive defenseman or a goaltender, who knows? We're just
drafting potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these offensive defensemen in junior hockey all of a
sudden become great defensive defensemen because they can't put up
the numbers. Likewise with the forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say by the 15th pick, we'll have it narrowed down. The
draft will narrow it down.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell and the scouting staff use the Central Scouting
rankings as a guideline, but the player it has at No. 21 might be
far down on the Bruins' list. O'Connell said the key to evaluating
talent is to go to the games. Director of scouting Scott Bradley
estimated he saw upwards of 140 games last year and said Quebec
scout Daniel Dore saw upwards of 160.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of seeing two games, you go to a third or fourth one
and stick it out,'' said O'Connell, who does a fair amount of
scouting during the season. ``That's where you get the emotion at
the (draft) table. Guys have seen him four times and maybe other
teams have only seen him twice. If you've seen him four times, then
you know. Sometimes you get the emotion at the table, a guy
fighting for him or saying you can't take him.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent pick who sparked all kinds of debate at the table was
goalie John Grahame, who was taken No. 229 overall with Boston's
seventh pick in 1994 and just led the Providence Bruins to the
Calder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said those who wanted Grahame have a bet with those in
the organization who didn't, and once Grahame makes it to the NHL,
they're going to have to ante up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a choice between two players, one a nongoalie,'' said
O'Connell. ``It got kind of humorous actually. I forget who the
other player was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' said Bradley, ``we remember who the goalie was.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie, forward, defenseman. The Bruins are hopeful they will be
able to grab a diamond in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now the consensus around the league is that
there are definitely 12 players who will make it,'' said Bruins
president/general manager Harry Sinden. ``I would say that's deep.
If there are 12 who can play, then you've got yourself a decent
draft. We're 21st and my scouts tell me there are 20 good players
in the draft.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
