<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL BOARD REVERSES BAN ON POLICE FIREARMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Board of Education voted late
Tuesday to rescind a policy to prohibit the police from carrying
guns onto school campuses, halting a measure that had pitted
officers and the mayor against education officials and community
activists.
</P>
<P>
   Following three hours of public testimony punctuated by
stomping, jeers and cheers, the board voted unanimously to drop the
ban, which would have required the police to disarm before stepping
onto school grounds during nonemergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The ban was an amendment to a broader resolution on safe
schools.
</P>
<P>
   That resolution, approved June 8, was upheld by a 4-3 vote. It
requires teachers to contact school administrators before calling
the police when problems erupt with students, unless the child
poses an immediate threat or has broken the law.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the gun ban amendment, introduced spontaneously by
board member Dan Kelly on June 8, that created the stir.
</P>
<P>
   As Kelly said Tuesday night, ``This issue has evoked a huge
amount of emotionality _ not just in San Francisco or in
California, but across the country and, I hear, as far away as
Great Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Fred Lau and Mayor Willie Brown The policy
vehemently opposed the ban. Lau said he would not disarm his
officers and that the school board was not empowered to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only I can decide whether to arm or disarm my police
officers,'' Lau said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was just before midnight Tuesday when board members
voted on the amendment and the resolution, more than 100 people
remained. About 600 people _ including city Supervisor Amos Brown
and at least a dozen police officers _ had showed up for the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Board President Juanita Owens said she was out of town when the
vote was taken June 8 on the resolution and gun amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my name off this resolution. Frankly, I was embarrassed
that this board would suggest police take off their guns,'' Owens
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Brown told the board, ``I feel we have to get rid of
this climate that suggests all police personnel (are) bad. These
are not safe times and there are reports every day of our schools
becoming less safe. We ought to have police present to keep our
schools safe.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of a handful of parents who supported the resolution to
restrict police access to campuses was Anna Schul, who said her
daughter, a student at McAteer High, was taken into custody in
March and charged with felony weapons possession for carrying nail
clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school staff found nail clippers and called police for
something that should've been handled without having police come in
to arrest my daughter,'' Schul said.
</P>
<P>
   Such incidents are impossible to confirm. Until now, the school
district has not been required to keep track of when and why the
police are called to schools.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution that remains in effect will require the district
to publish quarterly campus police intervention statistics and
establish a review committee of parents, police officers, students
and school staff members to issue a status report to the board by
next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
