<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET INVESTMENTS ENRICH N.J. PENSION FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brian Arena isn't a household name in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He should be. In fact, the Garden State ought to think about
naming one of the service areas on the New Jersey Turnpike for him,
putting him in the company of such luminaries as Vince Lombardi and
Grover Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, without any fanfare, Arena has made
nearly $900 million for New Jersey's state pension fund by shrewdly
investing in two Internet stocks _ CMGI and America Online. From
where we sit, that beats winning two Super Bowls or two
presidential elections any day of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, Arena performed this service on a state employee's
salary. He follows technology and small cap stocks for the New
Jersey Division of Investment. He didn't tell us how much he makes,
but you can bet it's a lot less than they pay on Wall Street. ``We
are all underpaid,'' joked his boss Steven Kornrumpf, the
division's director.
</P>
<P>
   Arena, who is 38, has a technical background. He was a systems
analyst for the state before he became a money manager. Well ahead
of the rest of us, he got interested in the Internet. ``I saw the
potential in that area,'' said Arena, in a nice bit of
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1994, he put some of New Jersey's pension money
into AOL, then a small, relatively unknown company. Kornrumpf
estimates the investment division eventually bought about $30
million worth of the stock. As of this week, the pension fund held
4.7 million AOL shares worth about $540 million.
</P>
<P>
   Arena also got interested in CMGI early on. The Andover, Mass.
company today is considered one of the top Internet players, thanks
to its investments in dozens of startups. When Arena invested in
the company in 1996, however, ``it was a collection of assets that
were not very well developed.'' Arena knew that CMGI had created an
early version of an Internet browser that was sold to AOL. He also
had a sense that Wall Street didn't fully appreciate the value of
CMGI's holdings.
</P>
<P>
   As they say in ``Wayne's World,'' ``Good call.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's original $18 million investment in CMGI is now
worth about $350 million. That doesn't count the $48 million in
profits the pension fund has booked by selling CMGI shares. ``If
the stock went to zero tomorrow, we would already have a recorded a
big gain,'' said Kornrumpf. CMGI is a long way from zero. It closed
Tuesday at 94 15/16, down 8 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's success does not come as a shock to those in the
investment community. ``Their pension fund is probably the best
performing large pension fund in the world,'' said Richard
Charlton, president of New England Pension Consultants, a Boston
firm that has done work for the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers back up Charlton's assertions. In the three years
ended last June, New Jersey had annual returns of 16.1 percent,
22.1 percent, and 22.7 percent. The typical public pension fund
over that same period returned 15.2 percent, 19.1 percent, and 16.9
percent, according to statistics gathered by the Independent
Consultants Cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Arena's small cap fund is no slouch either. Year to date
it has returned over 20 percent, miles ahead of the Russell 2000
Index, which is up 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The investment division manages $74 billion in pension assets.
Arena's small cap fund has just over $2 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's excellent performance has been achieved without any
outside help. State law forbids the pension fund from hiring
professional money management firms. According to Charlton, New
Jersey is one of the few states in the country that still operate
under such restrictions. Investment decisions are made by 25
people, all on the state payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Kornrumpf is understandably proud of his staff's Internet
investing. That hasn't stopped him from worrying as the stocks have
soared and more recently, plunged in value. ``The issue has been on
everyone's mind,'' said Kornrumpf. ``We have discussed it with our
board and people were comfortable where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The pension fund owns about 35 Internet stocks worth roughly
$1.2 billion. That sounds like a lot of money, but, in fact, it
only represents 3 percent of the state's equity holdings. By owning
so many different names, the fund is also buying some protection
through diversification.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take the view of a venture capitalist,'' said Kornrumpf.
``We own a basket of these and we hope to have one or two hits.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview, Arena didn't have a lot to say. He
expressed no opinion about the price of Internet stocks. ``We treat
them like any other stocks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So how much did Grover Cleveland have to say? Get the guy his
service area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
