<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-UTILITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S SAVING A BUNDLE ON ENERGY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In Massachusetts, big businesses, some municipalities,
and nonprofits have all seen how competition has lowered their
electric rates in the past 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the mix are State residents.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every household has realized a 10 percent savings on
monthly electric bills (with another 5 percent coming in
September). Those cuts were mandated by the 1997 Electric
Restructuring Act, in which the state required Bay State electric
utilities to divest their electric generating assets.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses and municipalities have begun saving money on
electricity by buying through trade and business groups, whose
collective power requirements allow them to bid competitively for
power.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no telemarketers calling John Q. Public at dinner
time to offer comparable discounts. The current cost of electric
power in Massachusetts is considered too low for competitors to
enter the residential market, and reaching consumers with direct
mail, television, and newspaper advertising is too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   That could all be about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Essential.com, a small Burlington start-up, began using the
Internet this month to offer consumers a 10 percent discount on a
portion of their electric bills, provided they also switch their
local and long-distance telephone service. A major ad campaign
promoting this bundle of services is planned for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Customers, who sign up on the Essential.com Web site will
eventually receive a single, detailed bill for all their utilities,
which they can pay by credit or debit card. During an introductory
period, the company is also handling billing by mail, but the goal
is to handle invoicing and collection over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``By using the Internet, we cut the marketing costs of reaching
individual customers for power providers and others and also
provide the consumer with the convenience of a single bill plus a
discount,'' said Akhil Garland, founder, president, and chief
executive of Essential.com.
</P>
<P>
   Essential.com is the first in an expected wave of Internet-based
companies to offer consumers discounted electric rates as part of a
package of utility services, including telephone, gas, heating oil,
propane, cable television, and even on-line grocery shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to provide customers the convenience of a single
bill, along with discounts that would make their total monthly
utility cost less than if each service were ordered separately.
</P>
<P>
   Garland said Essential.com will resell lower-priced electricity
under a contract with AllEnergy, a wholly-owned subsidiary of New
England Electric System. Essential.com will also resell Bell
Atlantic local phone service at a 5 percent discount, so customers
don't have to change phone numbers or switch services.
Long-distance charges are a flat 9.9 cents a minute, seven days a
week, with no minimum purchase, under contracts Essential.com has
with AT&AMP;T, MCI Worldcom, Cable and Wireless, and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   To receive the 10 percent electricity discount, customers must
sign up with Essential.com for two years. There are no plans to
sell electricity alone. Essential.com makes its money from the
various utilities for reselling their services.
</P>
<P>
   But the goal of a single bill is not yet a reality. Currently,
only one portion of a consumer's electric bill _ power generation _
is listed on the Essential.com monthly invoice. Electricity
generation, the deregulated portion of consumer electric bills, is
a measure of the basic kilowatt-per-hour rate known as the standard
offer. The bulk of the electric bill _ electric transmission,
distribution, and transition costs _ will still come directly from
Boston Edison or Massachusetts Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potential customer confusion is a big concern,'' said Robert
Potter, Essential.com's vice president of business development for
energy markets. He added that state regulators are working with
electric utility companies to solve the separate billing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Not far behind Essential.com is TelEnergy Inc., which has been
marketing local and long-distance telephone services to Bay State
consumers since January. The Newton firm currently provides
electricity billing services as a convenience to its telephone
service customers, but without discounts.
</P>
<P>
   With about 2,000 customers, TelEnergy expects to match the
Essential.com bundle of services shortly, according to Chris
McKeown, TelEnergy founder and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers are generally upscale, computer-savvy families,
many of whom have businesses and want a single bill for their
utility services, such as phones, electricity, natural gas, and
heating oil, rather than separate invoices,'' said McKeown.
</P>
<P>
   Like Garland, McKeown is raising additional financing to
advertise his company and raise brand awareness.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one is offering Massachusetts residential customers
discounts on electricity without the other services. Critics say
this is a shortcoming of deregulation, because the current electric
generation rates are simply too low to attract competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of deregulation say those low standard offer
rates _ climbing from 2.8 cents per kilowatt hour in 1998 to 5.2
cents in 2004 _ are benefiting consumers now and that competitors
will enter the market next year when the rate rises to nearly 4
cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are planning to introduce a residential program in the
not-too-distant future,'' said Steven Rothstein, managing director
of National Energy Choice LLC, a competitive power supplier to
medium-sized businesses, municipalities, nursing homes, and other
groups.
</P>
<P>
   It is expensive to sign up residential customers, he said,
adding that creating a separate electric bill and mailing it can
cost $1.50 to $2. Since a typical $60 per month residential
electric bill includes about $20 in electric-generation costs,
offering a 10 percent savings _ $2 per month _ is wiped out by the
cost of billing and postage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to offer real savings unless the marketing and
billing is done very efficiently, such as through the Internet, so
that is why businesses and nonprofits with $20,000-a-year electric
bills have been served ahead of residential customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The only nonbusiness group trying to obtain electricity
discounts for both business users and consumers is the Cape Light
Compact. This nonprofit, grassroots organization is negotiating a
long-term contract with an unnamed energy provider on behalf of
186,000 people living in 20 communities on Cape Cod and Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the area has the nation's sixth highest electricity
costs, the compact is seeking a five-year contract for guaranteed
electric generation rates below the standard offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think combining electricity costs with other services
is a way to benefit the residents of the Cape,'' said Robert
Mahoney, chairman of the compact.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, MassPIRG sees cause for concern in the idea of
relying on companies such as Essential.com to bring residential
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``To save money on anything, you have to buy other products.
That's troubling for the average consumer in Massachusetts,'' said
Rob Sargent, MassPIRG energy program director. ``Eventually it will
be hard for anyone to make an apples-to-apples comparison of what a
utility service costs if everything is bundled.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say that selling electricity as part of a bundle
of services will have limited appeal to consumers because the
month-to-month savings are relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some industry analysts maintain that the bundling of
energy and other services is the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of getting just very low prices for a single service,
whether it's electricity or long-distance telephone, are
numbered,'' said Donald Bradshaw, an energy analyst at the Yankee
Group.
</P>
<P>
   But others say that a company like Essential.com faces a series
of challenges. Just as 50 percent of the nation's residential
long-distance telephone customers never switched from AT&AMP;T to
another carrier, there is even greater apathy about changing
electric power providers to save a few bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selling services on the Internet is still very difficult,
compared to peddling hard goods, like books, records, and toys,
because the challenge in services is to explain who will take care
of everything if something goes wrong,'' said David Cooperstein,
senior analyst with the consumer e-commerce group of Forrester
Research.
</P>
<P>
   The risks are worth it, Garland said. ``We think we are at the
early stages of a huge market for customers who want convenience in
billing basic services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
