<SLUG> BC-WOM-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRASH-TALKING T-SHIRTS DON'T FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've been dismayed lately to encounter a series of T-shirts
with slogans proclaiming ``Your game's as ugly as your girl'' and
``You can't hold me, that's your girl's job,'' apparently you're
not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, J.C. Penney Co. ordered its stores to remove
trash-talking T-shirts manufactured by And 1, a Rosemont, Pa.,
basketball-apparel company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listen to customers, and there were customers who didn't
feel it was appropriate for us to carry the merchandise,''
spokesman Duncan Muir said Tuesday. ``On further review, we agree.
It was something we shouldn't have done.''
</P>
<P>
   And 1, which takes its name from basketball terminology, has
also come under fire for signing New York Knicks guard Latrell
Sprewell to his first endorsement deal since being suspended for
choking his coach during practice while a member of the Golden
State Warriors. The bulletin-board section of its website,
www.and1.com, is filled with heated commentary on both Sprewell and
the shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for the firm were not available for comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how many complaints J.C. Penney had received, Muir
said he could not provide an exact number but replied: ``Enough to
get our attention, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Riding on
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeannie Longo-Ciprelli, who has dominated women's cycling since
winning her first world championship in 1979, decisively won the
12-day HP LaserJet stage race in Idaho Sunday. The French cyclist,
who has won 12 world titles, took the lead during the second stage
of the 693-mile race throughout Idaho, and never relinquished it.
</P>
<P>
   Her winning time of 27 hours 21 minutes 12 seconds was 3 minutes
41 seconds better than that of her nearest competitor, Mari Holden,
of Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The international field of 107 included Tracy Timms of Brookline
and Jen Dial of Northampton. Dial finished 54th, while Timms, who's
taking time off from classes at Harvard Medical School to pursue
racing, finished 85th. Nicole Freedman of Wellesley abandoned the
race after three days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ballplayer retires
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Holmes, the former Colorado Silver Bullet who began the
season as a left fielder for the Massachusetts Mad Dogs in Lynn,
thus becoming the first female nonpitcher to play on a professional
men's team, has retired. After playing in several early-season
games, Holmes returned home to California, citing personal reasons
. . . At least three women with New England ties were named
first-team All-America in college lacrosse this spring. Emily
Mechem, who grew up in Gloucester and now lives in New Jersey, had
33 goals and 14 assists for Penn State, while Dartmouth juniors
Melissa Frazier, a defender from Berwyn, Pa., and Jacque Weitzel, a
midfielder from Annapolis, Md., represented the Ivy League champion
Big Green. In addition, Frazier was the only unanimous selection to
the All-Ivy team on defense, while Weitzel is playing this summer
on the US Women's Lacrosse Association Developmental team for the
second straight summer. Just last week, she scored two goals in a
US victory over England.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Bickelhaupt of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
