<HEADLINE>
OZAWA'S CAREER CROSSOVER LEADS TO PATH OF HIS MENTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The news Tuesday that Seiji Ozawa would leave the
music directorship of the Boston Symphony Orchestra at the close of
the season in 2002 came as a surprise to nearly everyone, but major
career moves between symphonic and operatic work occur often in the
lives of conductors. Every conductor wants both kinds of
activities, but few have managed to hold them in balance.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional route to the orchestral podium has been from the
pit of the opera house _ this was the journey traced by Arturo
Toscanini in the past, and by the Cleveland Orchestra's Christoph
von Dohnanyi more recently. But the crossover has gone the other
way. The BSO principal guest conductor Bernard Haitink, for
example, began to concentrate on opera only after decades in the
concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable why Ozawa might want the Vienna post,
despite the fact that some of its most notable music directors from
Gustav Mahler up through Claudio Abbado have run into controversy
and serious problems there. Vienna is notorious for waxing
sentimental about its music directors only after they are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the post remains one of the most prestigious in
the musical world. It was once held by one of Ozawa's principal
mentors, Herbert von Karajan, and it was at the Vienna State Opera
that another of Ozawa's mentors, Leonard Bernstein, became an
international music icon after years of controversy and
condescension in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Conductors are too easily typecast, and there is a wide swath of
the major operatic repertory that Ozawa has never been asked to
conduct because he hasn't conducted it before and, besides, he's
famous for other things. Opera was not one of his strong points
early in his career, and few who heard him conduct Mozart's ``Cosi
fan tutte'' at Tanglewood 30 years ago could have predicted what a
masterly operatic conductor he would develop into.
</P>
<P>
   In the opera houses of the world, and with the Boston Symphony,
Ozawa has conducted exotic repertory from Mozart's ``Idomeneo''
through Messiaen's ``St. Francois d'Assise,'' but he hasn't found
the opportunity to conduct many of the major operas of Mozart,
Verdi, and Wagner. As music director of one of the world's great
opera houses, he will be able to. Over and over again, Ozawa has
excelled with repertory that no one would have associated with him;
perhaps the brightest example came in the wonderful performances of
Britten's ``Peter Grimes'' that he led at Tanglewood a few summers
ago.
</P>
<P>
   (It is best to take Ozawa at his word when he says he's leaving
Boston because he wants to conduct more opera. He has never shunned
controversy and, in fact, seems to thrive on it. He stands by his
controversial decisions with regard to the Tanglewood Music Center
and a few bad reviews have never scared him.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the problem of finding a successor to Ozawa will loom
large in Symphony Hall. Finding a new music director is always
difficult, made more so by a current shortage of suitable
candidates _ there are many good conductors in the world, but few
great ones. It is nevertheless true that many good conductors have
risen to the challenge of greatness when called to lead an
irrefutably great orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the leading conductors of the senior generation, Haitink
and Andre Previn, are significantly involved with the BSO. Both are
past 70, and probably neither covets the post. Both, however, are
likely to play an increased role during the time of transition. BSO
management will probably be soliciting the advice of both.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the leading conductors of Ozawa's generation, Abbado and
Riccardo Muti, are probably not contenders. Muti has had no conn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
