<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBI'S BOOK TAPS INTO NEED FOR INTIMACY IN RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It feels slightly uncomfortable to be sitting at a cafe talking
about sex with an Orthodox rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   But Rabbi Shmuley Boteach has no qualms whatsoever. ``Too many
married couples are not having a satisfying sex life and it
shouldn't be like that,'' said Boteach, the rabbi at Oxford
University in England _ not the expected setting for a cleric
offering himself as an expert on intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   But Boteach's book, with the eyebrow-raising title of ``Kosher
Sex,'' has been a smash hit ever since it was first published in
England a year ago. It's made several bestseller lists in the
United States and has, so far, been translated into nine languages.
</P>
<P>
   While most scholars would be accustomed to having their work
published in sober academic journals, Boteach's book was excerpted
in the January issue of Playboy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't quite sure what to expect when it was published, but
I didn't think it would do so well so quickly,'' said Boteach,
dressed in a conservative dark suit and wearing a skullcap during a
visit to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But as he travels across the United States, speaking in
synagogues and giving interviews to dozens of journalists,
including the ``Today'' show's Matt Lauer, Boteach better
understands why his book has drawn so much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are really craving intimacy in relationships,''
said the 32-year-old Boteach, who has six children. ``People feel
very atomized, alienated and alone and that's why you enter into a
relationship. But relationships don't necessarily assuage feelings
of isolation so when a book comes along claiming how to find
intimacy, people want to know what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   With chapter titles such as ``Is Oral Sex Wrong?'' ``Does Size
Matter?'' and ``What about Pornography?'' Boteach's book offers a
frank discussion on how to inject fire into a married couple's sex
life.
</P>
<P>
   In writing ``Kosher Sex,'' Boteach leaned on his knowledge of
Jewish teaching and his 11 years of counseling students and others
at Oxford. ``It wasn't field research,'' quips Boteach. ``I've
heard every story under the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The book also stems from his own experiences as a child of
parents who divorced when Boteach was eight. ``I didn't just want
to come to terms with being the child of a broken home, but I
wanted to turn the pain into something positive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boteach's counsel to married couples on bringing passion into
the bedroom is distilled into an acronym he calls ``saner'' sex.
</P>
<P>
   First, Boteach recommends, sensuality, or using all five senses
when making love. ``People today make love mostly with their eyes,
but kosher sex is sex in the dark,'' he argues. ``The eyes are
meant to draw you to your partner, but after that sex should be a
celebration of the senses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A'' stands for attraction. Boteach believes that the popular
media have reduced attraction to an objective measure, based on an
idealized notion of what we should look like. ``But the beauty of
attraction is that it is a very personal experience,'' he says.
``I've seen surveys where 70 percent of married women undress in
the bathroom rather than in front of their husbands. That's
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``N'' is for nakedness, or, as Boteach puts it, ``losing all
inhibition and giving in to total submission to the instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``E'' is for eroticism. Boteach believes that the easy
accessiblity spouses have to each other has taken the fun and
mystery out of sex. One possible solution _ adhering to a biblical
stricture by abstaining from sex for 12 days a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have husbands lusting after their wives instead of
people at work,'' Boteach says.
</P>
<P>
   And ``R'' is for romance. ``Giving total sexual focus to your
spouse by offering romantic gestures for no other reason than to
tell him or her that they are special and cherished,'' Boteach
explains.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he adds, ``buying my wife a dishwasher is not a
romantic gesture because it says, `Honey, I love you. Now do the
dishes.' But buying flowers, on the other hand, is a great romantic
gesture because the flowers are going to die, but the gesture
remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Boteach says, greater intimacy is the consequence of
being willing to be more open to expressing our feelings to our
spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we expose our soft underbelly in a relationship
because so many of us have been let down or have seen others let
down,'' he says. ``But sex isn't only about being physically naked,
but also emotionally naked.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The Church of Scientology has issued an updated version of
``What is Scientology,'' which describes the practices,
administration and programs of the international church. The
1,059-page reference book is available at many public libraries.
The church claims 8 million members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
