<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETREAT-RESPITE-ART-B     06-23 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETREAT-RESPITE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONASTERIES FILL WITH THOSE IN SEARCH OF RESPITE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no room at the monastery.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not at St. Joseph's Abbey, high atop a windswept hill
in rural central Massachusetts, where guest rooms are booked
through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And not at St. Joseph Villa on the banks of the Atlantic Ocean
in Cohasset, Mass., where all the rooms are filled for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Margaret's Convent, which sits at the apex of Fort Hill,
commanding a dramatic view of Boston's downtown skyline, the
Episocpal nuns are taking reservations for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the popularity of monasteries and other spiritual
sanctuaries tucked away in bucolic settings is exploding as
frazzled Americans seek places to recharge their souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're booked like we've never been booked before,'' said the
Rev. John D. Bavaro, director of the Franciscan Center in Andover,
Mass. Hidden away in woods that run along the Merrimack River, the
sprawling former seminary building with 55 bedrooms is starting to
sell out many weekend reservations for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible wave of people we're getting,'' Bavaro
added.
</P>
<P>
   What people typically get on weekend or weeklong retreats would
never be mistaken for the Four Seasons. Many monasteries and
retreat centers offer small rooms with hard mattresses and
furniture that would not make the grade at Motel 6. Private
bathrooms also are a rare amenity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clean and comfortable, but this is not a resort,'' said
Sister Eleanor Weigand of the St. Joseph Villa Retreat Center,
where retreatants can be lulled to sleep by the sound of lapping
waves. ``But people aren't necessarily coming here for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people attending religious and spiritual retreats are not
looking for terry cloth bathrobes, a heated pool, or a nightly
happy hour. Simplicity and serenity are why people are flocking to
these centers in such significant numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Places such as the Miramar Retreat Center in Duxbury, Mass. and
St. Benedict Abbey in Harvard, Mass. have become a magnet for
people seeking to escape frenetic lives filled with faxes, beepers,
and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I turn into the driveway at Miramar I can literally
feel all the problems, all the stresses just melt away,'' said Lois
Mastrangelo, who lives near Boston and has gone on a half-dozen
retreats to the Duxbury center in the past two years. ``It's just
such a welcome feeling of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   While organized retreats _ often directed at couples, men, or
high schoolers _ are not new, retreat directors say the boom in
individual retreats has been startling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a God-shaped hole that cannot be filled with anything
else,'' said Sister Adelle Marie Ryan, the superior at St.
Margaret's Convent in Boston, which offers 16 private rooms.
``People have tried to fill it with a lot of other things and many
of them still feel dissatisfied. Plus, we have the best view of
downtown Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholics, Protestants, and even non-Christians say weekend
escapes to monasteries and retreat centers that offer time for
prayer, meditation, and spiritual advice in stunning settings all
for less than $50 a night are the best vacations going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear the same thing _ people just need to get away from the
wild, wild world of blaring horns, television, the telephone,
computers,'' said Joseph Ledoux, assistant to the guest master at
St. Joseph's Abbey, a Trappist Monastery where reservations for one
of the 11 guest rooms must be made at least six months in advance.
``We get people from New York City and it takes them a full day to
get used to the silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulette Normandin, an office manager at a medical office, has
been a repeat customer at the Franciscan Center for the past 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a date with God,'' said Normandin. ``It's an
opportunity to get off the treadmill that we live on and make time
for God, to make God a priority. I always leave feeling renewed and
refreshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rego, an administrator for a health-care organization who
spends much of her time on the road, said her yearly retreats at
the Franciscan Center provide a much-needed balance to her life.
``Trying to maintain a spiritual focus in our lives is not easy,''
said Rego, who lives in Tiverton, R.I. ``Going to the Franciscan
Center gives me a time to be still and listen to the voice of God,
which can sometimes be overpowered by the noise of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At some Catholic monasteries such as St. Benedict Abbey, which
sits high over a valley looking across to Mt. Wachusett, and St.
Scholastica, in a remote slice of central Massachuetts' Pioneer
Valley, there is the added attraction of Gregorian chanting,
popular in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a powerfully meditative form of worship, which people,
even if they don't know Latin, can enter into,'' said the Rev.
Father Andrew Koch, the guest master at St. Benedict. ``It's a very
transcendent style of worship. Retreatants are really drawn to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Retreats, however, are not necessarily solely about praying.
Monasteries and retreat centers do not require that people spend a
certain amount of time in the chapel. At Miramar, for example, many
people are attracted to the labyrinth _ a maze in the woods where
retreatants can literally become lost in their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   The center, set in a breathtaking location overlooking the ocean
with sprawling gardens filled with flowers, also has a professional
masseuse on staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of thing that would have been unheard of 30
years ago, but people are looking for a holistic approach to
sprituality,'' said the Rev. Robert M. Jones, director of Miramar
Retreat Center. ``They are looking for ways to integrate
spirituality with their work life and their family life.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Martin, a psychiatric nurse, recalls her first retreat on
a cold winter weekend in February 1996 at Gonzaga Eastern Point in
Gloucester, Mass. ``It was transforming; it felt sacred to me,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, Martin rose at 5 a.m. and, cradling a cup of coffee
to fend off the chilly wind, stood on the rocks watching the sun
rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say you get in touch with God there,'' she said. ``I came
to the retreat not knowing what to expect. And I left a more
peaceful person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
