<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6572 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE24-COX     06-23 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web a wealth of info on adding zest to dining solo
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For people who find themselves having to prepare meals for only
themselves, like young people just starting out or older folks
having to start over, eating solo can be a depressing and
intimidating experience. Even business travelers are sometimes
known to dread eating alone in a strange restaurant. So pervasive
is this phenomenon it has been given a name: solomangarephobia _
the fear of eating alone.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people who dine solo at least part of the time is
increasing dramatically. A recent survey of young people and adults
showed that between 1960 and 1990, the number of solitary diners,
at least part of the time, has increased some 16 million, tripling
the 1960s figures.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people adversely affected is also increasing,
especially among senior citizens. A survey of nearly 700 volunteers
from age 60 through their 90s showed that eating alone is the most
common factor behind poor nutrition among older people. Preparing a
meal can seem like a waste of time if you have always cooked for
others and are used to company around the table. ``Why bother, it's
only for me'' is a common refrain among solo eaters, who often fall
into the rut of relying on fast food or snacks or skip meals
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But eating by yourself doesn't have to be a reason not to
prepare healthful, delicious and enjoyable meals. There is a wealth
of information (though a dearth of recipes) available for those who
are up to the challenge. Here are just a few sites we found when we
searched ``cooking for one'' and ``eating alone'' on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ohio State University has an excellent site devoted
exclusively to seniors cooking for themselves:
www.ag.ohio-state.edu/(tilde)ohioline
</P>
<P>
   /ss-fact/0161.html. They advise to make the most of every meal
and realize that eating is a wonderful event. Some hints:
</P>
<P>
   Spice it up with herbs. Try something new to avoid boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Create an ``atmosphere'' when you eat. Don't be afraid to use
your best china or silver. Decorate the table and light a candle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At www.menshealth.com/features/
</P>
<P>
   mensconf/docs/doc58.html, you will find an article by Martin
Yadrick, registered dietitian and spokesman for the American
Dietetic Association, who writes about his father, who loves to
cook but has lost weight through the years, probably because he is
alone most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of his suggestions on how to buck the trend:
</P>
<P>
   Snack wisely. If the idea of a meal alone seldom appeals, be
sure to snack on healthy foods like precut carrots, pretzels, fig
bars or dried fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Check out what's new. More and more supermarkets are stocking
healthy prepared meals. Look for roasted chicken breasts, pasta
salads and lean roast beef. And don't forget the salad bar _ a
substantial salad can make a nutritious, filling meal.
</P>
<P>
   Make lunch your big meal. Lunch often holds more social
opportunities than dinner for both working and retired men. Don't
be afraid to fill up at noon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The article ``Cooking for One,'' at
www.shoppernews.com/c012595.html, contends that cooking for one is
no reason to punish yourself with recipes you would not serve
others. The site offers some lovely for-one recipes and a wonderful
bit of philosophy that solo eaters should keep in mind from the
ancient Roman host Lucullus, who said: ``It is precisely when I am
alone that you are required to pay special attention to the diner.
At such times you must remember, Lucullus dines with Lucullus!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An all-around good site that addresses the problem and offers
specific information about shopping and cooking for one is
``Cooking Solo'' at www.ext.nodak.edu/extpubs/yf/foods
</P>
<P>
   /he516w.htm by Joye Bond, nutrition specialist at North Dakota
State University.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other university sites specifically geared to solo seniors are
Colorado State's ``Cooking for One'' at
www.colostate.edu/Depts/CoopExt/PUBS
</P>
<P>
   /COLUMNCC/cc970918.htm and Ohio State's ``Cooking for One or
Two'' at www.ag.ohio
</P>
<P>
   -state.edu/(tilde)ohioline/ss-fact/0161.html. Both present
helpful hints in a can-do way.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One difficulty facing people who cook for themselves is a
shortage of recipes. There are lots of tips and helpful hints, but
we could find no recipes on the Internet geared to just one person.
Don't let that be a hindrance. If you are cooking for yourself, you
can cook any recipe that strikes your fancy ... just do the math
accordingly. Because it's easy enough to buy a piece of fish you
need for one serving, we chose fish recipes originally written to
serve four and tested them for one.
</P>
<P>
   Fish is a good choice to put on the menu when you're cooking. To
search out some tasty and healthful seafood recipes, see
www.geocities
</P>
<P>
   .com/NapaValley/8645/
</P>
<P>
   indexofrecepies.htmlas.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients for stir-fry dishes and salads also can be adjusted
easily. There are tons of sites with recipes, but you can start
with busycooks.miningco.com/library/weekly
</P>
<P>
   /aa090798.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Another site where you may find some interesting and imaginative
recipes is ``Thai for Two'' at users.nova1.net/(tilde)thai4two/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For the solo traveler who dreads eating alone, see
``Confronting the Stigma of Eating Alone'' at
www.abcnews.go.com/sections/travel
</P>
<P>
   /Crabby/eatsolo.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And young adults out on their own for the first time should
check out ``Single Servings'' at
www.sympatico.ca/healthyway/HEALTHYWAY
</P>
<P>
   /featurenut1.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Heloise weighs in for singles with ``Cooking for One'' at
www.creativeye.com
</P>
<P>
   /goodnews/cooking.htm.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Snapper Fillets With Lime-Orange Marinade
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Marinating time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 scant teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons minced shallot or green onion
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons fresh thyme or tarragon
</P>
<P>
   Dash ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 (4-ounce) red snapper fillet
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2-inch slices lime
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2-inch slices orange
</P>
<P>
   In a shallow dish, combine lime juice, orange juice, oil,
shallots or green onions, tarragon or thyme and nutmeg. Place red
snapper fillet in bowl, turning to coat evenly with marinade.
Marinate, skin side up, covered, in the refrigerator for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat grill or broiler. Cook fillet on grill or under broiler,
skin side up, for 3 minutes. Turn fillet, baste with marinade and
cook for 3 to 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place lime and orange slices on grill or under broiler and baste
lightly with marinade. Cook 1 minute, turning once. Serve with
fillet.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 181 calories, 24 grams protein, 6 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 29), 10 grams carbohydrates, 42
milligrams cholesterol, 75 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Snapper With Sour Cream
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 (4-ounce) snapper fillet
</P>
<P>
   3 fresh mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped onion, shallot or green onion
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Paprika and snipped parsley to garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Pat fish dry with paper towel;
place in small ungreased baking dish. In a small skillet or
saucepan on medium-high heat, combine mushrooms, onion and
margarine or butter. Cook and stir until mushrooms are golden,
about 3 minutes. Spoon mushroom mixture over fish; sprinkle with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In a cup, mix sour cream and Parmesan cheese. Spread over
mushroom mixture. Sprinkle with bread crumbs. Bake uncovered for 25
minutes. Test to see if fish flakes easily with fork. If not, cook
another 5 minutes and test until done. Remove from oven. Sprinkle
with paprika and parsley and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 262 calories, 28 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 7 grams carbohydrates, 59
milligrams cholesterol, 260 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
