 Wednesday, June 23, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-STATES-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court
substantially redraws the border between state sovereignty and
federal authority, limiting the ability of people to sue states
using federal law. In a 5-4 decision, the justices dismiss a
lawsuit by a group of state employees in Maine who sought to
enforce a federal labor law and collect overtime pay. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Lawmakers on the Senate Finance
Committee struggle to find a way to pay for proposed Medicare
coverage of prescription drugs. Unlike private insurance plans, the
government health insurance program for the elderly does not cover
the drugs. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO (Washington) _ A New Jersey man whose wife was
brutally murdered in Sarasota, Fla., urges Congress to pressure the
Mexican government to extradite one of the suspects accused in the
crime. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Since both Republican George W.
Bush and Democrat Al Gore are expressing centrist positions, the
manner in which they present themselves is as important as the
messages they convey. In their first official sorties, Bush has
emerged the winner. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
