<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPES1STTAKE-C     06-23 2073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test-kitchen secret: Simply fine recipes
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most home cooks I know have a Betty Crocker cookbook on their
shelves somewhere. I know I have two that have been with me for
decades. The first is a Betty Crocker Boys and Girls Cookbook _ a
bit wrinkled from a flood. But I used it just a few months ago to
make the castle birthday cake for a special neighbor's second
birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   The second is my mother's Betty book from the 1960s. I've used
it so much it has duct tape for binding.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury is as familiar. I know my grandfather often served
Hungry Jack biscuits to go with his infamous gravy. My grandmother
used them to make dumplings. I'm delighted to find a new use for
Hungry Jacks in the Country Apple Coffee Cake below.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell you firsthand that both the Carmelitas and the Tunnel
of Fudge recipes were a huge hit with my friends and office mates.
I've filed them in the special drawer in my kitchen where I keep
all my favorite recipes.
</P>
<P>
   And the ravioli from Betty's latest cookbook was not only great,
but it turned me on to the idea of using wonton wrappers as a
shortcut ravioli. I can't wait to stuff them with other ingredients
like cheese and greens.
</P>
<P>
   Why are the ideas that flow from the test kitchens of these two
food giants so appealing?
</P>
<P>
   Because they are simple and simply good.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes from the Pillsbury kitchens
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Country Apple Coffee Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: about 20 minutes Cooking
time: 35-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Susan Porubcan of Whitewater, Wis., created this biscuit
coffeecake that combines pastry-shop appearance with down-home
flavors. She won the grand prize in the Pillsbury Bake-Off in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter, softened, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped peeled apple (1 large), divided
</P>
<P>
   1 (12-ounce) can Hungry Jack Refrigerated Flaky Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons whiskey (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pecan halves or pieces
</P>
<P>
   Glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Using 1 tablespoon of the margarine
or butter, generously grease a 9-inch round cake pan or 8-inch
square pan. Spread 1 cup of the apples in the greased pan.
</P>
<P>
   Separate dough into 10 biscuits; cut each into quarters. Arrange
biscuit pieces, points up, over apples. Top with remaining 1/2 cup
apples. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine remaining 1 tablespoon margarine or
butter, brown sugar, cinnamon, corn syrup, whiskey and egg; beat 2
to 3 minutes or until sugar is partially dissolved. Stir in pecans.
Spoon over biscuit pieces and apples. Bake 35 to 40 minutes or
until a deep golden brown. Cool 5 minutes. If desired, remove from
pan.
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze: In a small bowl, blend confectioners' sugar,
vanilla and enough milk for a desired drizzling consistency.
Drizzle over warm cake. Serve warm or cool. Store in refrigerator.
_ From: ``The Best From 50 Years of Bake-Off Contests'' (Pillsbury
Cookbooks, $2.99)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 330 calories, 4 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 47 grams carbohydrates, 25
milligrams cholesterol, 395 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Italian Zucchini
</P>
<P>
   Crescent Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Millicent Caplan of Tamarac, Fla., won top honors for this dish
in the 1980 contest. It's a great way to make use of that bountiful
summer vegetable. It can work as a main course with a side salad,
or as a side dish at a summer barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   4 cups thinly sliced zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dried parsley flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, well-beaten
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces (2 cups) shredded Muenster or mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) can Pillsbury Refrigerated Crescent Dinner Rolls
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 375 degrees. Melt margarine or butter in a 12-inch
skillet over medium-high heat. Add zucchini and onions; cook and
stir 6 to 8 minutes or until tender. Stir in parsley flakes, salt,
pepper, garlic powder, basil and oregano.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, combine eggs and cheese; mix well. Stir in cooked
vegetable mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Separate dough into 8 triangles. Place in ungreased 10-inch pie
pan or 11-inch quiche pan; press over bottom and up sides to form
crust. Firmly press perforations to seal. Spread crust with
mustard. Pour egg mixture evenly into crust-lined pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 20-25 minutes or until knife inserted near center comes
out clean. Cover edge of crust with strips of foil during last 10
minutes of baking if necessary to prevent excessive browning. Let
stand 10 minutes before serving. _ From: ``The Best From 50 Years
of Bake-Off Contests'' (Pillsbury Cookbooks, $2.99)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 270 calories, 13 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 22 grams carbohydrates, 102
milligrams cholesterol, 775 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Tunnel of Fudge Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 2 hours, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe from the 17th bake-off contest is one of the most
popular Pillsbury recipes of all time. The cake was created by Ella
Helfrich of Houston, Texas, and originally called for a frosting
mix for the filling that is no longer available. So the Pillsbury
kitchens have updated the recipe _ but it's every bit as good. The
popularity of the bundt fluted tube pan increased after this recipe
won the contest, prompting the sole factory that produced it to go
on a 24-hour production schedule to keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 (3.4-ounce) package chocolate fudge pudding and pie filling
mix (not instant)
</P>
<P>
   1 6-ounce package (1 cup) semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (1 1/2 sticks) butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Pillsbury Best All Purpose Flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Glaze:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   In medium saucepan, combine 1 1/2 cups milk and pudding mix;
cook as directed on package. Add chocolate chips; stir until
melted. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour 12-cup bundt pan or
10-inch tube pan. In large bowl, combine sugar, butter and
shortening; beat until light and fluffy. Add vanilla and eggs; mix
well. Lightly spoon flour into measuring cup; level off. Add flour,
1/2 cup cocoa, baking powder, salt and 1 cup milk; beat at low
speed until moistened. Beat 3 minutes at medium speed. Stir in
walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve 2 cups of the batter. Pour remaining batter into greased
and floured pan. Spoon filling in ring on top of batter, making
sure it does not touch sides of pan. (You may not use all the
filling, but you should use at least 2/3 of it.) Spoon reserved
batter over filling.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for 50 to 60 minutes or until cake springs
back when touched lightly in center. Cool 1 hour; remove from pan.
Cool 1 1/2 hours or until completely cooled.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, blend all glaze ingredients, adding enough milk
for desired drizzling consistency. Spoon over top of cake, allowing
some to run down sides. Use very sharp or serrated knife to slice
cake. Best when served same day; store any remaining cake in
refrigerator. _ From ``The Best From 50 Years of Bake-Off
Contests'' (Pillsbury Cookbooks, $2.99)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 557 calories, 8 grams protein, 30 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 68 grams carbohydrates, 80
milligrams cholesterol, 230 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Oatmeal Carmelitas
</P>
<P>
   Makes 36 bars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   These bars are absolutely yummy _ the test kitchens staff served
samples to visiting food stylists, home economists and journalists.
The bars were an entry in the 1967 contest, and this recipe, too,
is one of the most requested ever. Try the bars once, and you'll
see why.
</P>
<P>
   Crust:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Pillsbury Best All Purpose Flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups quick-cooking rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups margarine or butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 (12.5 ounce) jar (1 cup) caramel ice cream topping
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Pillsbury Best All Purpose Flour
</P>
<P>
   1 (6 ounce) package (1 cup) semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 13-by-9-inch pan. Lightly
spoon flour into measuring cup; level off. In large bowl, combine
the flour, oats, brown sugar, baking soda, salt and margarine or
butter; mix at low speed until crumbly. Reserve half of crumb
mixture (about 3 cups) for topping. Press remaining crumb mixture
in bottom of greased pan. Bake for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in small bowl, combine caramel topping and 3
tablespoons flour; blend well. Remove partially baked crust from
oven; sprinkle with chocolate chips and nuts. Drizzle evenly with
caramel mixture; sprinkle with reserved crumb mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Return to oven; bake an additional 18 to 22 minutes or until
golden brown. Cool 1 hour or until completely cooled. Refrigerate 1
to 2 hours or until filling is set. Cut into bars. _ From: ``The
Best From 50 Years of Bake-Off Contests'' (Pillsbury Cookbooks,
$2.99)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 200 calories, 2 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 43), 28 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 180
milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Only the best of the best good enough for contest emerge from
winnowing process
</P>
<P>
   Creative home cooks across the country are busy cooking up new
ideas and old favorites to enter the 50th anniversary Pillsbury
Bake-Off, to be held Feb. 26-29 in San Francisco. The grand prize
has grown a bit from the original $50,000 in 1949 _ it is now $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   But before a recipe can reach that pinnacle, it will undergo a
great deal of scrutiny in the Pillsbury test kitchens. At the close
of the entry phase in October, all entries will be screened by an
independent agency to make sure they meet all the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Then each recipe will be assigned a code number, and the
entrant's name and address is removed. Coded recipes then go to
home economists who will read through them again, eliminating those
that are inaccurate, too involved or require unusual equipment or
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the field is narrowed to 1,000 entries, and from
there home economists get cooking _ sampling and evaluating every
detail of each recipe. At the same time, another team digs through
a library of publications, making sure recipes have not been
previously published or chosen as winners in contests.
</P>
<P>
   Then consumers at a number of locations around the country will
be asked to try the recipes and rate them on two general criteria:
overall appeal and quick and easy preparation. These consumers are
not made aware that they are bake-off entries, and their ratings
are kept confidential until the final judging, when they are
revealed only to the judging panel.
</P>
<P>
   By December, the field will be narrowed to 100. Notifying those
folks can be tricky for Pillsbury. Sally Peters, director of
consumer foods and publications for Pillsbury, said they've had to
use the highway patrol, the U.S. Forest Service and local CB radio
users to track down finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The final 100 contestants are given an all-expenses-paid trip to
San Francisco for the final competition, in which contestants will
have a set time to prepare their recipes and send them to judges.
</P>
<P>
   Entries for the bake-off must be postmarked on or before Oct. 18
and received no later than Oct. 22. For an entry blank, call
1-800-306-1111 or go online at www.bakeoff.com. Entries may be
submitted electronically via the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
