<HEADER>
A6576 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPES2NDTAKE-C     06-23 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: electronically via the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes from the Betty Crocker kitchens
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Goody Bars
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 bars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 35 minutes Cooling
time: 1-2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Betty Crocker recently sponsored a dessert mix contest, and the
grand prize went to the Trinity Lutheran Church Women of Birchwood,
Wis., who created this irresistible combination of a brownie, a
Rice Krispies treat and a Reese's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 pound, 3.8 ounces) Betty Crocker fudge brownie mix
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 tub Betty Crocker Rich and Creamy ready-to-spread vanilla
frosting
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup salted peanuts, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cups crisp rice cereal
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creamy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 bag (12 ounces) Hershey's SemiSweet chocolate chips (2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease (or use cooking spray) the
bottom of a rectangular pan (13 by 9 by 2 inches). Stir brownie
mix, water, oil and eggs in medium bowl until well-blended. Spread
in pan. Bake 28 to 30 minutes or until toothpick inserted 2 inches
from side of pan comes out clean or almost clean. Cool completely;
frost with frosting. Sprinkle with peanuts; refrigerate while
making cereal mixture. Measure cereal into large bowl; set aside.
Melt peanut butter and chocolate chips in 1-quart saucepan over low
heat, stirring constantly. Pour over cereal in bowl, stirring until
evenly coated. Spread over frosted brownies. Cool completely before
cutting. For bars, cut into 5 rows by 4 rows. Store tightly
covered.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 425 calories, 8 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 55), 47 grams carbohydrates, 46
milligrams cholesterol, 226 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Country Style Ribs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 hours, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to see why this recipe made it into ``Betty
Crocker's Best-Loved Recipes'' (Macmillan, $24.95). The sauce is
truly a classic taste. This summer, try finishing these off on the
grill, brushing on sauce during the last five minutes of cooking
and setting some sauce on the table.
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds country-style pork ribs
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grape jelly
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Cut ribs into serving pieces if
necessary. Place ribs, meaty sides up, in ungreased rectangular pan
(13 by 9 by 2 inches). Cover and bake about 2 hours or until
tender; drain.
</P>
<P>
   Heat remaining ingredients, stirring occasionally, until jelly
is melted. Pour over ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Bake, uncovered, 30 minutes, spooning sauce over ribs
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 340 calories, 27 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 24 grams carbohydrates, 80
milligrams cholesterol, 400 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Indian Spiced Chicken Ravioli with Tomato-Ginger Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of many of the Betty Crocker cookbooks is that they
cover the basics, like pizza crust and coffeecake, and then show
you how to make some of the more elegant dishes, too. That's
especially true of their latest, ``Betty Crocker's A Passion for
Pasta'' (Macmillan, $21.95), which includes everything from ``pasta
in a pinch'' to pasta from scratch. We especially liked this dish,
which uses wonton wrappers as a shortcut for ravioli and easy
additions of shredded carrot and ginger to give canned tomato sauce
a more exotic twist.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound ground chicken or turkey
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic, finely chopped, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated ginger root, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground red pepper (cayenne)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspon salt
</P>
<P>
   20 wonton wrappers (3 1/2-inch squares)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 medium carrot, shredded ( 1/2 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1 can (15 ounces) chunky garlic-and-herb tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh cilantro, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Mix chicken, 3 chopped cloves of garlic, 1 teaspoon ginger root,
the coriander, red pepper and salt. Place 1 tablespoon of the
chicken mixture on center of each wonton wrapper. Moisten edges of
wrappers lightly with water. Fold wrappers over filling, forming
triangles; press edges to seal.
</P>
<P>
   Melt margarine or butter in 10-inch skillet over medium heat.
Add the onion, carrot, remaining garlic and remaining 2 teaspoons
ginger root and cook for 5 minutes, stirring occasionally. Stir in
tomato sauce; reduce heat. Simmer uncovered 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While sauce is simmering, heat 4 quarts water to boiling. Drop
ravioli into boiling water; reduce heat. Simmer about 4 minutes or
until chicken is no longer pink. Begin testing for doneness when
ravioli rise to surface of water. Drain well. Spoon tomato sauce
over ravioli. Sprinkle with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 400 calories, 24 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 34), 46 grams carbohydrates, 75
milligrams cholesterol, 840 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Cream of Broccoli Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Brannen of Glenville was one of the 75 women featured in
``Betty Crocker's Best-Loved Recipes.'' A short essay written by
Brannen's mother, along with her photo, appeared beside this recipe
_ one of Brannen's favorites. She recommends using half-and-half or
milk instead of the cream for a lighter soup.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fresh broccoli
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 large rib celery, chopped (about 3/4 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped (about 1/2 cup)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dash of ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy whipping cream, half-and-half or milk
</P>
<P>
   Shredded cheese (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Remove florets from broccoli; set aside. Cut broccoli stalks
into 1-inch pieces. Heat water to boiling in 3-quart saucepan. Add
broccoli florets and pieces, celery and onion. Cover and heat to
boiling. Boil about 10 minutes or until broccoli is tender (do not
drain).
</P>
<P>
   Carefully place broccoli mixture in blender. Cover and blend on
medium speed until smooth. Melt margarine or butter in a 3-quart
saucepan over medium heat. Stir in flour. Cook, stirring
constantly, until mixture is smooth and bubbly; remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Stir broth into flour mixture. Heat to boiling, stirring
constantly. Boil and stir 1 minute. Stir in broccoli mixture, salt,
pepper and nutmeg. Heat just to boiling. Stir in whipping cream.
Heat just until hot (do not boil). Serve with cheese, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 105 calories, 4 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 69), 6 grams carbohydrates, 15 milligrams
cholesterol, 440 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
