<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6577 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     06-23 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corona's success is in marketing, not taste
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The decor at La Cazuela, a Mexican restaurant in
Cumming (GA.), is bright as a parrot, the food simple but artfully
prepared and the beer list as Mexican as you'd want.
</P>
<P>
   Tecate, Dos Equis, Carta Blanca, Negra Modelo _ they're all
there and they're not alone. There's another beer that's impossible
to ignore these days: Corona.
</P>
<P>
   With a wedge of lime jammed in its neck, a clear glass bottle of
Corona is a familiar sight not only in Mexican restaurants but
yuppie bars as well. Indeed, Corona, a brand originally made for
field hands, has become the No. 1 imported beer in the United
States, surpassing Heineken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corona's triumph,'' The New York Times prominently reported on
its business pages recently, ``is a testimony to the power of
clever marketing.'' Growing numbers of Americans, as the Times
noted, are happy to pay $6 and more for a six-pack that goes for
less than $2.50 in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be explained simply by differences in currency. Here is
a thoroughly dreadful beer, ignored a decade ago, transformed into
a beach bum's Dom Perignon. What kind of marketing works wonders
like this?
</P>
<P>
   ``The key,'' as the Times reported, ``seems to be (Corona's)
shrewd tactics in appealing to a core group of Mexicans living in
the United States while giving Corona a special cachet among
American college students and 20-somethings.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it's like the cachet that Coors enjoyed in the
'60s, except that Coors for years was smart enough to remain a
regional beer. Unable to buy it outside Colorado or the Rocky
Mountain states, college students from the East would borrow pickup
trucks and drive halfway across country to load up on a beer they
could not have distinguished from Miller High Life if you'd
blindfolded them.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you can buy Coors in Dunwoody as easily as Denver,
there's nothing particularly special about it _ not that there ever
was. But clever marketing means creating an image in people's
minds, regardless of the merits of the product.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that there are any number of Mexican beers better
than Corona _ and a few just as awful. None of them is really
exceptional (most diminish their character by adding corn) and none
is intrinsically ``Mexican.'' But such light-bodied, golden beers
as Tecate, Carta Blanca and Superior will slake the thirst while
providing a vaguely pilsner taste better than Corona. (For that
matter, so will Budweiser.)
</P>
<P>
   But these beers scarcely exist in most buyers' minds. It's the
image of that enameled, clear-glass bottle they see. And that lime
(which probably does more good than harm, given the taste without
it).
</P>
<P>
   Corona's success in the United States, the British beer writer
and judge Michael Jackson writes, ``has done a disservice to
Mexican beer. Corona is a cheaply made, watery, sweetish beer,
originally intended simply as a thirst quencher for manual
laborers.''
</P>
<P>
   And by the time it reaches distant markets (like Atlanta), it's
frequently light-struck as well.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Tim Morse, head brewer for the John Harvard's chain
of brewpubs, conducted a seminar in Atlanta. Its purpose was to
help people recognize faults in a beer. One by one, various off
flavors that had been intentionally created _ some subtle, others
sharply unpleasant _ were identified and their causes explained.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the session Morse poured into glasses a few ounces
of beer he had bought that morning in an Atlanta store. He was
careful to conceal the bottle he was pouring from, but everyone
immediately recognized a ``skunky'' taste.
</P>
<P>
   The beer was light-struck, and it was Corona.
</P>
<P>
   The cause: the transparent bottle.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason beer is usually bottled in brown. Dark glass
reduces light penetration. A green bottle _ Heineken, Pilsner
Urquell and Moosehead, among others _ doesn't do it nearly as well.
But it does it better than clear glass.
</P>
<P>
   Along with heat (prolonged storage at, say, 75 degrees or
higher), nothing destroys the flavor of beer like exposure to
light. Not just sunlight but also the fluorescent lighting of
supermarkets and package stores. Once the yeast begins to go bad,
the beer goes bad.
</P>
<P>
   And yet light is at the heart of Corona's marketing image, even
more than subliminal messages about Cancun or other tropical
locales. When Miller High Life, its golden hues visible through
clear glass, used to market itself as ``the Champagne of Bottled
Beer,'' no one took it seriously and no one thought to ask for a
lime. It was just another Milwaukee lager, more or less the same as
Schlitz. You don't see either of those old American standbys much
anymore. In fact, in many a restaurant you'll find more beers from
Mexico than from Milwaukee. A few are fine but little known. The
best-known among them would make me settle for a Pabst Blue Ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   The name doesn't make you think of cactus or Cancun, tacos or
anything remotely tropical. Bohemia, after all, was in Central
Europe, not Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But the best golden lager from Mexico might well be Bohemia,
named after the birthplace of the style. The golden Superior is
respectable but less consistent. Others, such as the amber Dos
Equis and the darker Negra Modelo, are excellent with Mexican
dishes but are closer to the maltier Vienna lager style. Bohemia is
in the pilsner style most Americans look toward, and it doesn't
take liberties in calling itself a pilsner.
</P>
<P>
   Light to medium in body, it has a nice hoppiness without being
assertive. If there's corn in the grist _ typical of Mexican beers
_ it's less than in most. It's not an especially complex beer, but
you can detect the barley malt character, something that can't be
said of most golden Mexican lagers.
</P>
<P>
   Bohemia, in fact, is better than most American mass market
lagers and comparable to many imports brewed in the pilsner style.
At La Cazuela in Cumming (Ga.), as at most Mexican restaurants,
Bohemia occupies its place on the menu without fanfare. But
longtime aficionados of that cuisine know that, along with Dos
Equis and Negra Modelo, this is the one to look for.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
