<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6579 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TESTKITCHEN24-CO     06-23 2011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TESTKITCHEN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Well known rivals General Mills and Pillsbury are researching,
testing and refining much of what America eats
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Stroll down the hallway of test kitchens at
General Mills any given day and you might hear the ground beef
sizzling in skillets in a Hawaiian-themed kitchen with faux thatch
roof, where Hamburger Helper products are tested.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the aroma of bread baking will entice you to the
blue-and-white Cape Cod kitchen, where nearly a dozen bread
machines are lining the countertops, kneading and baking the latest
bread mix.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few miles away, there's another set of kitchens _ all
sleek, with a fair touch of stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   There, each afternoon, a panel of tasters gathers round to
sample the day's projects _ perhaps a new rendition of an old
Pillsbury favorite, such as the Tunnel of Fudge Cake, or some new
trick with Old El Paso bottled salsa.
</P>
<P>
   New York and Los Angeles may be the temples of trendsetting
cuisine, but the heart of American home cooking lies here in the
heartland _ at the home of Betty Crocker and Poppin' Fresh.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 100 years, General Mills and the Pillsbury Co.
have grown up in the same Minneapolis neighborhood, competing and
co-existing, with the shared goal of getting us into the kitchen.
And they apparently succeed: Last year their combined sales totaled
more than $15 billion ($9 billion for Pillsbury; $6 billion for
General Mills), about 3 1/2 percent of all grocery store sales.
</P>
<P>
   They supply us the staples _ Gold Medal and Pillsbury flours;
the conveniences _ Hamburger Helper, Hungry Jack biscuits; and the
inspiration _ Betty Crocker Cookbooks and the Pillsbury Bake-Off.
</P>
<P>
   And, just as importantly, they're willing to do whatever it
takes to give us the confidence to use their products again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   Before any of their products or recipes reach your kitchen, they
go through a rigorous process of research and testing that attempts
to account for everything from battered old pans (you know how your
favorite cookie sheet looks) to haphazard measuring (the ``looks
about right'' approach).
</P>
<P>
   ``People always tell you their oven is right, but in the next
breath they'll say they always take things out early,'' said Kay
Emel-Powell, manager of Betty Crocker test kitchens. ``We have to
see how a product or a recipe will perform under all the
variables.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason the home economists also go by the more modern
and accurate title _ consumer food scientists.
</P>
<P>
   At Betty Crocker, the scientists and their assistants work in
seven artfully decorated kitchens _ each reflecting a different
American region or style, from Colonial Williamsburg to tropical
Hawaiian. That's because until 1985, the public was allowed to tour
the test kitchens, so the company wanted to present something more
than an industrial look. They wanted the kitchens to remind folks
of home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are three ``camera kitchens'' where the food
photography for Betty Crocker cookbooks and magazines takes place.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pillsbury Consumer Food Center, there are 20 test
kitchens to work with Pillsbury foods, Pillsbury Bake-Off entrants
and several other product lines that are a part of the company,
including Progresso and Haagen-Dazs brands. Here, the look is more
modern, with remodeling having taken place four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern beginnings
</P>
<P>
   Both clusters of kitchens are impressive, given the fairly
humble beginnings of their companies. General Mills began as a
single mill in 1866, built by Cadwallader C. Washburn on the banks
of the Mississippi in Minneapolis. It was known as ``Washburn's
Folly'' by those who were sure there would be little demand for
Midwestern spring wheat flour.
</P>
<P>
   It was no folly, and in 1880, Washburn's flour received the gold
medal at the Millers' International Exhibition, and thus became
known as Gold Medal Flour.
</P>
<P>
   In 1881, Charles Pillsbury, along with his father, George, was
attracted by the same Midwestern wheat and the same river and built
the first Pillsbury mill.
</P>
<P>
   Such close proximity between the two rivals does call for added
measures of secrecy. In fact, one reason Betty Crocker stopped
public tours of its test kitchens was concern over security. Both
companies did, however, recently agree to give a group of visiting
food professionals and journalists a peek inside their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Stages of development
</P>
<P>
   The initial stages of product or recipe development begin with
home economists, researchers, manufacturers and marketers all
brainstorming (called ``ideation'' at Pillsbury). The test kitchen
staff is expected to track trends in tastes, technologies and
techniques for cooking, along with shifting lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, both companies rely on surveys and focus groups with
consumers. They learn, for instance, that while there may be
insulated baking pans in stores, most people have ``good old
aluminum pans'' at home, explained Powell.
</P>
<P>
   They know if you take five people and ask them to measure a cup
of water, you're likely to get five different amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also monitor current periodicals and cookbooks
extensively, which helps them gauge trends. They know, for
instance, when cilantro is in and sun-dried tomatoes are out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have someone reading all the magazines and newspapers,
tracking every recipe and ingredient for our database,'' explained
Andi Bidwell, senior food editor at Pillsbury. ``We can pull up
every garlic recipe that has been printed within the last year and
test 100 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   This early brainstorming will lead to ideas for new products or
new flavors and variations on old products. At Betty Crocker, for
instance, when Americans began shifting from ground beef to chicken
as a standard weeknight meat, the idea of Chicken Helper was
hatched.
</P>
<P>
   For food products, the developers and manufacturers then take
the idea to the factory to see how it will be produced. They'll
return to the test kitchens with different versions of the product
to be tested and tasted.
</P>
<P>
   The critical phase here _ as in the testing of recipes for
cookbooks and magazines _ is known as tolerance testing. This is
where the recipe or product is prepared a number of different ways
to account for all the usual errors or practices, such as doubling
ingredients without adjusting the cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We test all our recipes using butter, margarine and Parkay,
which has a high water content,'' said Jill Crum, a home economist
and test kitchen manager for Pillsbury. ``We'll do the recipe as
written, then try it with the flour lower and the fat and sugar
higher. Then vice versa. Then at different temperatures. It has to
be acceptable in each test.''
</P>
<P>
   At both companies' kitchens, home equipment is used rather than
professional stock in order to best replicate the home kitchen
experience. Products such as bread machine mixes are tested on all
the major brands of bread machines available. And they have testers
in mountainous areas such Albuquerque, N.M., who test and write the
high-altitude directions.
</P>
<P>
   Data from each test are charted _ such as prep time, cooking
time, the type and temperature of the oven, ingredient
measurements, the utensils used and the result. Once it has passed
through the tolerance testing phase, a recipe will go to a tester
who hasn't previously seen it for a final run. ``They find the
flaws that occurred as the recipes were rewritten, like including
bacon on the ingredient list, but not saying what should be done
with it,'' said Crum.
</P>
<P>
   Contest prep
</P>
<P>
   At Pillsbury, recipe testing goes into high gear every two years
for its popular Bake-Off, the granddaddy of all cooking contests.
The test kitchens receive thousands of entries vying for the grand
prize of $1 million (up from the $50,000 grand prize in the first
contest 50 years ago).
</P>
<P>
   After an initial screening, the test kitchen will make 1,000 of
the recipes in an effort to whittle down the list of contenders to
100. Literally dozens of extra testers _ many college students
studying consumer science _ work long hours to try out the contest
entries.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Sally Peters, director of consumer foods and
publications, got her start at Pillsbury 23 years ago. She's been
testing recipes ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is not only knowing something about the science of
food,'' said Peters, ``but also knowing the culinary side of it.
You have to love food to do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just as essential to have a feel for what the public wants
to eat _ and is willing to make.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Crocker's Powell agrees. ``You definitely build up taste
and food knowledge that others don't have,'' she says. ``You also
are grounded in `Bettyness.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Crocker
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1921, Betty Crocker began as a pen name for the consumer
response department of the Washburn Crosby Co., a flour mill
founded in Minneapolis in 1866.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The surname Crocker was chosen to honor a popular director of
the company, William G. Crocker. Betty was chosen because it was a
friendly-sounding name. Women employees submitted signatures; the
one chosen is still used today.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  General Mills was formed through the merger of several
regional milling companies in 1928; Betty Crocker was maintained as
a company icon and a brand name.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Betty Crocker cake mixes hit the market in 1947, when
GingerCake first appeared on grocers' shelves. PartyCake and
Devil's Food followed soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1950, ``Betty Crocker's Picture Cook Book'' was first
published and became a national best seller. More than 200
cookbooks have been published since, along with a monthly recipe
magazine sold at grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There have been eight portraits of Betty Crocker from 1936 to
1996. While each reflected popular hairstyles and fashions of the
time, Betty has always worn a red dress, jacket or sweater with
white at her neck.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Betty Crocker Red Spoon began appearing on packages in
1954 and is used on more than 200 products today.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Betty Crocker products and sister brands include Bisquick,
Gold Medal flour, Hamburger Helper, Suddenly Salad, cereals such as
Cheerios and snacks such as Bugles, Chex Mix and Yoplait yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The seven Betty Crocker test kitchens have 31 microwaves, 26
ovens and 22 stove tops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Many longtime favorite recipes, along with new ones, can be
found at Betty's Web site _ www.bettycrocker.com.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When the first Pillsbury mill was built on the Mississippi in
Minneapolis in 1881, it was the largest mill in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the 1920s and '30s, the company expanded its line of flour
products to include pancake mixes, cereal and bakery items.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pillsbury first began to offer cake mixes, frosting mixes and
other convenience items in the 1940s and 50s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The first Pillsbury Bake-Off Contest took place at New York's
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel as the Grand National Baking and Recipe
Contest. Eleanor Roosevelt attended, and the grand prize was
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Poppin' Fresh,'' the Pillsbury Doughboy, was born in 1965
when a small group of advertising folks sat around a table cracking
open cans of Pillsbury dough while trying to think of a way to
promote the company's prepared-dough business.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the 1970s, Pillsbury purchased Totinos and the Green Giant
company. In the 1980s, Haagen-Dazs was acquired, and Martha White
flour was picked up in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other brands in the Pillsbury family include Jeno's, Old El
Paso, Progresso and Hungry Jack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pillsbury's Consumer Food Center library contains more than
5,000 cookbooks, including an antique collection dating back to the
1850s. Its database contains more than 85,000 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 20 Pillsbury test kitchens have 69 ovens, 50 microwaves
and 25 stove tops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Popular Pillsbury recipes and information about the next
bake-off, slated for San Francisco in February, can be found at www
</P>
<P>
   .pillsbury.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
