<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-POP24-COX     06-23 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Krall goes for vintage and variety
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An acolyte of a certain kind of mood evoked by the phrase ``pop
standard,'' Canadian vocalist Diana Krall has become a star by
reviving the sexy gentility of songs jazz musicians have been
bending and adapting for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she's smarter than your average throwback diva: Krall's a
pianist first, and she's no stranger to the blues. She hires
excellent musicians, including former Atlantan Russell Malone,
whose guitar work is animated by sly mutations of familiar forms.
Along with bassist Ben Wolfe, the trio finds something freshly
appealing in Cole Porter, Irving Berlin, Harry Warren and George
Gershwin, classic ``tunesmiths'' whose songs, timeless when Ella
Fitzgerald sang them, have become a well-worn currency.
</P>
<P>
   This, the third of Krall's major-label albums, is also her most
ambitious. Songs boast a greater variety of arrangements _ with
Johnny Mandel cueing an orchestra on several tracks, and the trio
swelling to quartet or quintet on others _ and help to steer Krall
away from a potential niche implied by her previous success with
the Dave Frishberg novelty, ``Peel Me a Grape.'' There's a nod in
that direction: a frisky reading of Michael Franks' ``Popsicle
Toes'' that will likely become an airplay favorite. But, mostly,
Krall sticks with vintage, such as a version of Porter's ``I've Got
You Under My Skin'' that profits from the syncopated insinuations
of bossa nova, as strings swell in the background. Effortless and
elegant, Krall is refining a sound that, without blazing trails, is
quietly reinventing the standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When
</P>
<P>
   I Look in Your Eyes''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Krall. Verve.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
