<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6583 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-COLUMN24-COX     06-23 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Taxi Driver's' terror more relevant than ever
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A grim masterpiece of the 1970s, Martin Scorsese's brooding,
bloody ``Taxi Driver'' seems more vital than ever in the wake of
recent high school shootings, not to mention such madmen as Ted
Kaczynski and the Centennial Olympic Park bomber. A new DVD
collector's edition offers a crisp audio-visual version of the
film, plus fine extras. These include an interactive version of
Paul Schrader's shooting script, selected storyboards and an
hourlong documentary on the making of the 1976 movie. (Suggested
retail price: $26.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from his Oscar-winning role as the young Vito Corleone in
``The Godfather Part II,'' Robert De Niro plays insomniac cabbie
Travis Bickle, who prowls the nighttime streets of New York,
simmering with disgust at the hookers, pimps and drug addicts
shadowing its sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not so much his puritanism and racism that spark his
vigilante actions. It's a bigger problem, his inability to connect
with other people _ specifically, Cybill Shepherd. The
cream-and-honey personification of his fantasy view of women, she's
a presidential campaign worker who's at first charmed by Travis'
alternative-airwave viewpoint, then unnerved by it. (The porn movie
he treats her to on their first date doesn't help his case.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie is quietly terrifying as it charts how loneliness and
missed connections can translate into gruesome dreams of grandeur,
helped along by a cache of heavy artillery. Plotting a masturbatory
kamikaze strike on the world, Travis focuses his efforts first on a
senator, then the prostitution ring run by Harvey Keitel, whose
jewel is 12 1/2-year-old hooker Iris (Jodie Foster).
</P>
<P>
   With slo-mo, jumpy edits and some eccentric camerawork, Scorsese
sucks us directly into Travis' head as he preps for one of the
bloodiest finales in film. Scariest of all is the deadpan ending,
which finds psychopath Travis lauded for his actions, welcomed back
into the world as a folk hero. This cynical view of the sliding
scale of fame has proved to be prophetic in the 23 years since the
movie opened. Proof of its spooky accuracy: John Hinckley Jr.'s
Travis-inspired attempt to kill Ronald Reagan, an attempt to win
the attention of actress Foster.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp cast also includes Albert Brooks as Shepherd's
amiable, dry co-worker, Peter Boyle as a taxi driver who tries to
get Travis to lighten up, and Scorsese himself, powerful as a
cuckolded husband with murder on his mind. The score, a mixture of
horror-movie stings and lush jazz lament, was by Bernard Herrmann
(``Psycho'') _ his last. The movie earned four Oscar nominations,
including best picture, actor (De Niro), supporting actress
(Foster) and original score.
</P>
<P>
   The making-of documentary on the DVD includes interviews with De
Niro, Foster, Keitel, Shepherd, Brooks, Schrader and
cinematographer Michael Chapman. One note that they hit is
consistent: The Method devotion of De Niro, who got a chauffeur's
license and drove a taxi in New York as prep for the movie, and
whose performance gave Shepherd a genuine case of the willies.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also learn more than you may want to about the bloody
makeup effects and the reason the colors are desaturated in the
climactic gunplay scenes. Interesting trivia: Foster's young friend
onscreen was actually the real girl who inspired Schrader's
teen-hooker character. Scorsese had not intended to be in the movie
(except for a cameo shot of him sitting outside the campaign office
when Shepherd makes her entrance). De Niro didn't shave his head;
that's actually a skullcap, and the Mohawk is made of horsehair.
</P>
<P>
   And for the record, in his script Schrader wrote only a
description of Travis talking to himself in the mirror. De Niro
improvised that famous riff, ``You talkin' to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the parodies, those words are spookier than ever
more than two decades after ``Taxi Driver'' came out.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
