A6589 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-ELLIOTT24-COX     06-23 0208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ELLIOTT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rhythms rule in Missy's `World'
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missy is many admirable things. Nowhere on that list, however,
is the artist's simple, stream-of-consciousness rhyme style. To her
advantage, though, when producer Timbaland's energetic drums kick
in _ as on her first single, ``She's a Bitch,'' and the charismatic
``Smooth Chick'' _ that deficiency is easily overlooked in favor of
his imaginative and muscular rhythms. Missy's a better writer, able
to make slang such as ``All N My Grill'' and ``Stickin Chickens''
into incredibly catchy songs, if not particularly smart ones. Just
as notably, when it comes to singing, the underappreciated vocalist
proves she can move easily from rap to the rankings of such young
R&AMP;B talents as Coko or Faith Evans on the emotive ``Crazy
Feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   But again, the heading on this review is ``rap'' because that's
what Missy insists upon doing most of the time. Only, passably.
</P>
<P>
   ``Da Real World''
</P>
<P>
   Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott. The Gold Mind/Eastwest. 17
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
