</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6590 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS24-COX     06-23 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recently released CD's
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison, Judith Green and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Terror Twilight''
</P>
<P>
   Pavement. Matador. 11 tracks. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Pavement was such a ramshackle outfit that
it could barely sustain a coherent song for more than two minutes.
Lo-fi as a musical designation was practically invented to describe
the quintet. Though many miss the unhinged early days, the relative
discipline of the last few albums has allowed the band's strengths
to shine. Stephen Malkmus' gift for melody could fuel a hundred
Hansons. Catchy tunes run through odd chord progressions like fudge
ripple through ice cream, a tasty treat that makes you wish for
more. These guys have never been virtuosos, but they're adept at
quirky turns of instrumental phrasing, strange tonalities and
hair-trigger timing. When those strengths combine, it's simply the
perfect mix of sweet and sour.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Wild West Soundtrack''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Overbrook/Interscope. 15 tracks. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Infectious in spite of Will Smith's almost Al Gore-like
blandness, the ``Wild Wild West'' title track wins with guest
vocalist Sisqo's energy and Stevie Wonder's classic ``I Wish''
underneath. In fact, the entire soundtrack spills over with such
remarkable combos. Remarkable in a good way when we're talking
about Lil' Bow Wow and Atlantan Jermaine Dupri's bouncy ``Stick
Up'' or the taut strings local producers Tim &AMP; Bob apply to MC
Lyte's aptly titled ``Keep It Movin.'' It's remarkable in another
way when the usually lethal rappers Eminem and Dr. Dre fire an
uninspired dud (``Bad Guys Always Die''). And the long-sought
reunion of R&AMP;B trio Guy finds Aaron Hall relegated to background
vocals on ``The Best.''
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Violin''
</P>
<P>
   Score by John Corigliano. Joshua Bell, violin, with the
Philharmonia Orchestra, Esa-Pekka Salonen, conductor. Sony
Classical. 20 tracks. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Francois Girard's new film, ``The Red Violin,'' is a picaresque
chronicle of the 350-year journey of a fine Italian instrument,
from its birth in Cremona around 1650 to a high-profile auction
today. The music is by far the most authentic thing about the
movie, which goes for melodrama and histrionics over musical
integrity. American composer John Corigliano based his score on a
bittersweet chaconne for strings, the theme of the tarot card
reader who foretells the violin's adventures. So closely has
Corigliano honored Vivaldi (a concerto grosso played by an
orphanage orchestra) and Bach (a partita played by a 6-year-old
prodigy) that you'll wonder if he's stumbled on some lost scores.
The violin's theme is a languorous lament, played by Joshua Bell (a
soloist with the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra next season) with
appropriate passion and not too much schmaltz.
</P>
<P>
   _Judith Green
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison, Judith Green and Sonia Murray write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
