<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, June 24,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISONERS _ DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ The four scraggly
thieves stopped Albana Koshe's car by the woods because they wanted
a ride, but under her tenacious questioning they provided a clue in
her dreadful quest. Yes, they said, they had been released from a
Serb jail as the Serbs withdrew from Kosovo. In jail, they said,
they worked in the kitchen cutting bread, so they knew that 150 men
from her town had been brought there. Finally, providing the answer
she dreaded, they said they recognized her brother, Alban, among
them. The world now watches ethnic Albanian refugees return to a
NATO-controlled Kosovo, but, for Koshe and thousands of others from
her region the war is over but not resolved. Their relatives are
being held prisoner and, it appears, have been taken to Serbia by
the withdrawing troops. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COKE-MAIN _ BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The Belgian government today
said it will lift its partial ban on Coca-Cola products once the
company has met certain conditions, including enhancing safety
measures at bottling plants. Coca-Cola Co. has accepted the
conditions, which also include a thorough cleaning of the plants
and better monitoring. Company spokesman Paul Pendergrass said the
company may be able to have its products on store shelves within a
few days. The government, however, said vending machines carrying
Coke products will still be off-limits to consumers until it is
more satisfied with their safety. Belgian Health Minister Luc Van
den Bossche said there is still a foul smell coming from some of
those machines. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-FRANCE _ PARIS _ The French government was expected to give
Coca-Cola the go-ahead to resume production at its Dunkirk plant.
But there are reports that a criminal investigation has begun, at
least at the local level, and Le Monde raised the question of
whether rat poison was the source of contamination on soft drinks
that were transported on fungicide-treated wooden pallets. (Holmes,
Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ ATLANTA _ A look at what analysts think the
decision in Belgium may mean for Coca-Cola, whose shares have been
under pressure since the crisis began more than a week a go, but
was higher this week. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: All stories moving in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   EPA-CHEMICALS _ WASHINGTON _ Negotiations are coming to a head
this week over a proposed EPA policy to post information on the
Internet about chemical plants that pose a possible hazard to
public safety. Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., says the postings would
be a road map for terrorists, and the industry and the FBI also are
opposed. (Dart, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS _ WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for former HUD Secretary Henry
Cisneros continued Wednesday to chip away at the testimony of his
ex-mistress, Linda Jones, at a pretrial hearing to determine
whether tapes she made of Cisneros promising money should be
admitted in Cisneros's forthcoming federal fraud trial. (Malone,
Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   V-CHIP _ WASHINGTON _ Consumer and television industry groups
Wednesday previewed a national education campaign to show parents
how to use the television ratings sustem with the new V-chip TVs.
July 1 is the federal deadline to provide TVs that allow parents to
automatically screen certain shows. (Hill, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   VETERANS _ WASHINGTON _ Veterans committees in the Senate and
House meet Wednesday to mark up bills to provide a cost-of-living
adjustment in rates of compensation paid to veterans with
service-connected disabilities. (Hall, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE _MIAMI _ Tobacco company lawyers begin closing arguments
today in a class-action suit filed by smokers. The marathon trial
began last summer, with Miami attorney Stanley Rosenblatt trying to
stick the industry with billions in payments to every sick smoker
who has ever lived in Florida. Rosenblatt won a partial victory
last year in a precedent-setting second-hand smoke trial in which
airline flight attendants argued that smoke-filled planes made them
sick. This trial has the potential for billions in damages, and is
being closely watched. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
