A6626 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMELT-WATER-HNS &LR;      06-23 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMELT-WATER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDANGERED FISH THREATENS CALIFORNIA WATER SUPPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A tiny endangered fish that lives a year,
then dies, is hanging around too long in the Sacramento-San Joaquin
Delta, prompting a water shortage for the Silicon Valley and
California's vast agribusiness operations.
</P>
<P>
   Federal environmental law protects the 3-inch-long Delta smelt,
a source of food for salmon. When the smelt swims near massive
water pumps in the Delta, the operations must slow down so the fish
don't get sucked up and killed.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown is causing massive amounts of fresh Delta water to
simply flow into the Pacific Ocean instead of to Southern
California. That has prompted the accelerated drainage of San Luis
Reservoir west of Los Banos in Merced County, a major source of
water to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   By August, Santa Clara County will have to tap its ground water
and local reserves because silty water from the lowered San Luis
Reservoir is no longer pure enough to process delicate high-tech
products or supply 1.7 million customers there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very serious problem we are facing,'' state
Sen. Jim Costa, a Democrat from Fresno, said at a special
legislative hearing on the problem Tuesday. ``What we have here is
the linchpin of the plumbing system for the state of California.
Over half of our state's population gets its water from the Delta,
and we have a system that is severely stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   For Silicon Valley computer and chip manufacturers, the crisis
means a loss of up to one-third of their water supply.
</P>
<P>
   County officials said they are concerned about health and safety
issues because local supplies aren't as pure as water from San
Luis.
</P>
<P>
   Switching to lower-quality water means substantial costs to
Silicon Valley businesses because they have to upgrade their
treatment facilities. Many manufacturing processes require
ultra-clean water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it's going to be a substantial cost and cause
substantial difficulty,'' said Walt Wadlow, assistant general
manager of the Santa Clara Valley Water District. ``We won't have
the kind of insurance in terms of water supply that we expected to
have going into the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delta smelt has become a sort of aquatic spotted owl, a
focal point for farmers and others who see environmental laws
interfering with the state's huge water needs. A 1992 federal
agreement requires 10 percent of Central Valley water be used to
protect fish and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Some Central Valley lawmakers and water agencies would like to
use the current Delta smelt crisis to change how the U.S.
Endangered Species Act effects their business needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply can't have a crisis every time a fish population
moves in the way of the pumps,'' said Timothy Quinn, deputy general
manager of the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California,
which serves 16 million people. ``The smelt are going to be in the
system next June and May, and if we're sitting in front of this
committee next year, heads should roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the slowdown at the pumps, farmers face a critical
shortage of water at the same time the summer weather is hottest.
</P>
<P>
   Many crops were planted with the expectation farmers would
receive a certain amount of water, and the supplies have already
been reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta smelt are usually out of the way of the pumps by the
end of May, but they continue to linger for unknown reasons and
officials have declined to allow the pumps to be started
full-force. On Tuesday, a gradual increase in pump capacity began,
but the damage has already been done for the summer, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put continued stress on the system due to the Delta smelt
is putting a lot of farmers at significant risk,'' said David Orth,
with the Westlands Water District, which manages federal water
contracts. ``We will not be able to meet the needs of farmers
through July and August.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delta has been described as the gills of California. The
pumping stations near Tracy were constructed in 1968 to ship water
from the plentiful Delta through the California Aqueduct system.
Southern California uses about 80 percent of the water taken from
the Delta.
</P>
<P>
   The area is the home to several endangered salmon species.
</P>
<P>
   The Splittail and the Delta smelt also are protected by the
federal Endangered Species Act. Thousands of other types of fish
are routinely sucked through the pumps, but they aren't protected
by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups testifying Tuesday said the pumps near
Tracy have sucked up and killed 100,000 Delta smelt _ five times
the allowable number. Rather than continuing policies that kill
more endangered fish, they said, farmers and water agencies should
look to other sources or reduce exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This did not start because one fish went over the take,'' said
Gary Bobker, program director for The Bay Institute. Bobker
estimated that 75 percent of the Delta smelt are in danger zones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
