<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Mitrovica, Yugoslavia) _ French troops have a
shootout with Serbs and arrest three in a town where Serbs have set
up what they say is the border of a Serb-only zone in Kosovo. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICE (Pristina) _ Developments in slow arrival of U.N.
civil administrators and police (countries not providing police
fast enough, U.N. says.) By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Gniljane, Yugoslavia) _ Story from American base
about the slow NATO troop deployment. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ARMY (Washington) _ The Army's new chief of staff, a
former commander of U.S. troops in Bosnia, gives his first
interview to reporters (at 3:30 p.m. ET), and is likely to be
grilled on the Army's slow deployment into the Balkans, the
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo and looming budget fights in
Congress. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FREEH (Washington) _ The FBI's director, Louis Freeh,
briefs reporters on Kosovo war crimes investigations. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ In a little-remarked but crucial
shift, the technocrats' 18-year domination of Mexican politics,
during which government policies have modernized the economy but
impoverished the country's working class majority, appears to be
ending. Unlike President Ernesto Zedillo (Yale Ph.D.'78) and his
two predecessors, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, (Harvard Ph.D.'78) and
Miguel de la Madrid, (Harvard M.A.'65) none of the four candidates
currently seeking the presidential nomination of the governing
party, the PRI, which has won 11 straight presidential elections
here, are technocrats. By Sam Dillon. (Eds: May hold).
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-TALKS (Beijing) _ U.S. and North Korea hold talks; Also,
North Korea still holding South Korean tourist it detained this
week. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Imrali/Istanbul) _ Top Kurdish rebel, Abduallah
Ocalan, makes final statement at his trial. Death sentence could
come within days. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-RARE-LION (Hoedspruit, S. Africa) _ Shady circus owner
who fled and abandoned his animals left behind an extraordinarily
rare Barbary lion. Matchmakers hope to revive the species. By
Donald G. McNeil Jr. (Eds: May hold.)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TIBET-DIVISIONS (Dharmsala, India) _ Sitting in a shady
courtyard near the Dalai Lama's residence, two young Tibetans, both
of them born in India, argued about what strategy would lead most
quickly to their return to the homes they have never seen. Their
perspectives represented the division of opinion that appears to be
growing here. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-STATES'-RIGHTS (Washington) _ State governments cannot be
sued against their will in state courts by people seeking to
enforce some federal right, the Supreme Court said Wednesday in a
major decision on states' rights. In a richly written 5-4 ruling,
the court said that the Constitution's ``structure and history''
shields states not only from being sued in federal courts, but also
makes them immune from individuals' state court lawsuits seeking to
enforce a federal right. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ASBESTOS (Washington) _ Supreme Court rules in asbestos
case. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABILITY-REAX (Washington) _ Reaction to disability
rulings. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FLAG-BURNING (Washington) _ The House, which always
passes flag protection amendment, takes it up Wednesday afternoon.
The real question is what happens in the Senate. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AGENDA (Washington) _ President returns from Europe with
a fairly expansive political and policy agenda. Plans to intensify
battery of Republicans for failure of gun legislation, announce a
new environmental initiative, unveil his Medicare plan and tour
poverty-mired regions from Appalachia to an Indian reservation to
talk about new investment to help the poor. Heavy fund-raising
schedule for congressional Democrats and continuing efforts to
juggle the competing Clinton, Hillary, Gore agendas. By John
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-NUDE-BEACH (LaJolla, Calif.) _ Blacks Beach, one of the
oldest and most famous of California's nude beaches, may be history
as town clamps down. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-DENTAL (Manchester, N.H.) _ Even though the vast
majority of the poorest Americans, particularly children, are
covered by Medicaid for dental care, they are not getting it. At
least, not in numbers anywhere near that of children better off and
not at levels near what they need. Why not? Several reasons,
experts say. Most dentists tend to be loath to take Medicaid
patients because the program scrimps on payments and involves
pencil-breaking bureaucracy; also, Medicaid patients, often with
transport and day-care problems, are likelier to miss appointments.
By Carey Goldberg. (Eds: May hold.)
</P>
<P>
   S.C.-POLITICS (Columbia, S.C.) _ South Carolina's primary is
going to be more crucial than ever this campaign season to
Republicans, who are showing up earlier and more often than in
years past. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-LAWSUITS (Undated) _ As a sign of the impact on gun
companies of lawsuits being filed around the country, a major
manufacturer of so-called Saturday Night specials announces it has
filed for bankruptcy. In addition, representatives of other major
manufacturers say they are willing to talk about how to better
police themselves. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
