<SLUG> BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO PUTS THE `X' ON THESE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The X Games are nearly upon us, and don't you
dare laugh, wise guy. You've been living right in the middle of the
X Games ever since you moved here, only nobody thought to give it a
name and sell T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you think about it, San Francisco is the absolutely
ideal place for the X Games, in the same way that New Orleans is
the perfect place for the Super Bowl, Montreal is the perfect place
for the Stanley Cup, and anywhere else is the perfect place for the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   We have all the X Games any town could need, and that's just at
the bike messenger hiring hall. We have all the dangerous pastimes
you could try, all the places to try them, and we don't really need
to build a single ramp, spread even a truckload of gravel, or even
move a single chair. In fact, we host the perfect X Games event on
the last Friday of every month when the bike riders and commuters
do symbiotic war at every freeway onramp.
</P>
<P>
   We are, frankly, perfect. In fact, we are more than perfect.
Give us two days for permits and brochures, and we could out-X the
X Games without breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   We could take the skateboarders to the top of Lombard Street and
give them a shove. Stop and you lose. If more than one makes it to
the bottom without leaving a trail of screams and scabs, bring 'em
back to the top of the hill, blindfold them and shove again.
</P>
<P>
   We could make them skate the Bay to Breakers, with the multiple
horrors that entails. Yes, we could dress them up as Mary
Engelbreit teapots, pregnant chickens, multiheaded nurses or
Charles Durning impersonators, lead them to the starting line with
80,000 other lunatics and send them on their way. Through the
badlands of South of Market, up the Hayes Street Hill, through the
Park and all the way to the beach _ and we'll even leave the option
of not turning left at the shoreline up to them.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, there's X and then there's X.
</P>
<P>
   Or, worst of all, we could have them ride down the stairs at
Candlestick Friday night wearing Dodger caps and shirts that read,
``Dusty Baker Likes Polka Music.'' They'd all be X-Gamers in the
X-est sense of all.
</P>
<P>
   Now you're probably not noticing a huge difference between this
and everyday San Francisco living, surely no more dangerous than
running through the Tenderloin neighborhood without shoes. You
surely won't be able to discern the difference in dress between X
Gamers and mailroom workers on casual days at Bank of America,
except for the bibs the X Gamers have to wear for television.
</P>
<P>
   But the X Games being a national matter, thanks to ESPN's need
for programming that doesn't require a rights fee, much of what the
athletes do as competition seems odd to the sheltered Midwestern
eye, in the same way that their behavior would be if they all
congregated in a mall parking lot and created a disturbance outside
Hickory Farms.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, it's actually tame stuff. Driving Grant Avenue
without swearing is an X Game. Slaloming around the street artists
around Pier 39 is an X Game. Outsmarting the meter cops is an X
Game, with a dollop of Y and Z Game on the side.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means we can't try to give our newest guests a
little more than they figured on when they arrived here.
</P>
<P>
   We could assemble the BMX riders and their lighter-than-air
bikes, and let them run the Fifth Street gantlet with the cab
drivers. Not only is that X, we can all but guarantee an X-rider or
two.
</P>
<P>
   We could also get the bladers, strap a hundredweight of Beach
Blanket Babylon hats to their heads and have a joust on Van Ness
with 2-by-4s.
</P>
<P>
   We could make them climb the Vaillancourt Fountain while
balancing hot lattes on their heads, or plunge down the stairway of
Coit Tower, or ride through City Hall with a tray full of paint
without spilling a drop. Losers would have to listen to a lecture
by Mayor Willie Brown on being neat in the palace halls.
</P>
<P>
   We could assemble the winners, match them up against our own
local team (which could be assembled in about an hour, tops), and
bet the budget surplus on our side. Not to disrespect the X Gamers,
but frankly, the X Games are what they train for, while we do them
every day just to get to work. The one is a labor of love, the
other is trying to avoid being hit by a city bus.
</P>
<P>
   In such matters, one should always side with the more motivated
group.
</P>
<P>
   And don't even start on how the post-Games party would work.
There is no evidence currently available to suggest that X Gamers
could even imagine the kind of fete San Francisco can throw, let
alone last the evening. Remember what we did just for winning a
stadium vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
