<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEREAL-BRETTHULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACE OFF FOR A GOOD CAUSE WITH HULL-O'S CEREAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars' season is over, but you can still cheer for
one of their popular players.
</P>
<P>
   Hull-O's made its debut this season in the cereal aisle and will
remain on shelves even as the Cup chase and the crease controversy
fade into memory. Right wing Brett Hull, in partnership with PLB
Sports, lends his name to the cereal with the payback being that
the profits go to Camp John Marc, a North Texas camp that helps
children suffering from catastrophic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The cereal is just one offering from PLB sports, which is based
in Pittsburgh. The company's first product was Jaromir Jagr Creamy
Peanut Butter, a partnership with the Pittsburgh Penguins. But the
product that put the company on the map was Flutie Flakes, a cereal
introduced last fall. Buffalo Bills quarterback Doug Flutie donates
his profits from that product to autism research. His son is
autistic.
</P>
<P>
   All of PLB's products are sold only in the area where the
endorser's team plays. (Omar Vizquel's Hot Salsa is sold in
Cleveland, Ed McCaffrey's Rocky Mountain Horseradish Sauce is sold
in Denver and Jerome Bettis ``The Bus'' Salsa is sold in
Pittsburgh.)
</P>
<P>
   But that is about to change. The first national product is Nolan
Ryan Texan Style Steak Sauce. The Ryan Express is donating his
profits to the Nolan Ryan Foundation, which funds the Nolan Ryan
Center for Continuing Education.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Hull-O's at Tom Thumb and Minyard stores. Nolan Ryan
Texan Style Steak Sauce is available at Tom Thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Find other PLB Sports products on the Web at www.plbsports.com.
Flutie Flakes are now available online; the rest of the company's
line will be available by mail later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
