<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-GAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING TO FEAR AT X GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fearless: adj., free from fear; bold;
courageous.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that: a concept not grasped by X Games athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really consider myself fearless,'' frowns champion
street skateboarder Danny Gonzalez of San Francisco. ``Afraid of
what? There isn't that much risk, really, by the time you get to
this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah? When last seen, on the cover of a skateboarding
magazine, the 20-year-old was flying over a chain link fence with
nothing separating him from the metal but his skateboard and a few
inches of air. Doesn't the ``X'' in X Games come from the word
extreme? Gonzalez admits that what he does might look harrowing:
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you might look at me and say `This kid's crazy.' But I've
never pushed myself so far that I'm scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconding that emotion is 20-year-old Fabiola Da Silva of Santa
Rosa, Calif., princess of vertical in-line skating with a closet
full of medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to skate with boys most of the time,'' the petite,
Brazilian-born spitfire says in broken English, ``because girls are
sometimes scared to do what I do. I don't know why, though! It's
not such a _ I don't know _ big deal? It just takes practice!''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and Da Silva are two of 400 ``alternative athletes''
participating in the upcoming X Games, being broadcast by the ESPN2
cable network. Each will compete in one of eight sports offered
during the nine-day event, which begins Friday at Piers 30 and 32
on the Embarcadero. In addition to skateboarding and in-line
skating, there will be stunt-bicycling, sportclimbing,
snowboarding, motocross, street luge and wakeboarding.
</P>
<P>
   If these X athletes have one thing in common, it's a puzzling
view of themselves as nothing out of the ordinary: average citizens
who just happen to enjoy scaling rock walls lickety-split like
Spiderman, skating up the side of a semicircular ramp (known as a
half-pipe) and finishing with a backflip, lying down on metal
planks and hurtling down twisting streets at 80 mph, stopping only
when shoe soles are ground into the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Derammelaere, 26, of Novato, Calif., is a heavy favorite
in the street luge event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it's somewhat dangerous, but any form of racing
is,'' he says. ``The thing is, you can't think about fear. You have
to put it out of your mind; get past it, or you'll get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Derammelaere, something of an X Games pinup boy with photos in
magazines from Bikini to Mademoiselle, knows whereof he speaks. He
shows a serious scar on his ankle, from an accident at last year's
X Games that left him with a shattered ankle. His lip has a small
scar as well, from being bitten by a dog unhappy with finding him
at his level on the street. He has a scar under his jawline, too,
but he's not sure where that came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the crash, I needed to get past the fear _ the idea that
something else bad could happen,'' he says. ''I had to make that
first run without being afraid. It was a crucial part of the
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Derammelaere, a graduate of Sonoma State University and a
computer programmer for Mindscape, is modest and soft-spoken _
hardly hellbent on showing-off.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. ``I'm trying to get people off that stereotype,'' he
says. ``The guys with the purple hair _ they're a novelty and why
people watch it (on ESPN2). But we are serious athletes. People
think we do this just because it's crazy, but that's only one
element. For me, it's a jumping-off point to auto racing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also bucking the stereotype is Chris Bloch of San Francisco, a
rock climber ranked fourth in the country in the speed category,
which requires him to not only scale walls the height of a
five-story building, but do it fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Climbing is the only X sport that's not based on style, but on
the clock,'' he says. ``It's all about speed, although everyone has
their own style. My own is fast-paced; I let momentum drive me up
the wall. It's like a dance _ it can be very graceful.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what he thinks he might have in common with other X Games
athletes: ``Maybe it's that everyone moves really fast through the
air? Maybe we all want to be birds! To push Earth's gravity to its
limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Also fearlessness? Bloch hesitates. ``It's not fearlessness,
exactly,'' he says. ``I don't think fear really enters into it that
much. Let's just say everyone who does this is good at calculating
risk. They have a good sense of their own abilities and
limitations. That's all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
