<P>
   Financial stories from The New York Times News Service for
newspapers of Thursday, June 24.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-STORYTELLING (St. Louis) _ The biotechnology industry
seizes on the latest corporate tool for peering into the future:
story telling. It is not contingency planning, and it is not
long-range forecasting, two somewhat more scientific methods that
companies use to anticipate problems. Rather, the method,
popularized by Shell Oil in the early 1970s, is free-wheeling
speculation, peppered with endless if's, but's and maybe's, by
people knowledgeable about an industry trying to figure out where
it is heading. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-STEARNS-SEC (Undated) _ Bear Stearns nears a settlement
with the SEC. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   QWEST-USWEST-FRONTIER (Undated) _ Trying to rescue its takeover
effort for U S West and Frontier, Qwest Communications revises its
bids, using more cash to guarantee a price. Investors have been
concerned about a 22 percent drop in Qwest's shares since the
original offer was made. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Goldman, Sachs reports
second-quarter earnings that sharply exceed analysts' forecasts,
helped by a surge in stock trading. The report is Goldman's first
as public company. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INVESTIGATION (Vladivostok, Russia) _ Foreign companies
doing business in eastern Russia are alarmed by an announcement by
the regional governor here that he would use the main successor to
the KGB to investigate whether a British businessman had illegally
obtained shares for foreign clients in a shipping company. By
Russell Working.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-BANK (Sao Paulo) _ President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
takes the extraordinary step of dismissing the entire board of
Banco do Estado de Sao Paulo, one of the nation's biggest banks,
after it wins a legal case that exempts it from paying some taxes.
By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   BESTBOOK-AD-COL (Undated) _ A new book is the latest entry in
the popular sport of picking the ``best'' ad campaigns. Many
familiar favorites are included, from Mean Joe Greene to ``1984''
to the Energizer bunny, but the book will set off debate because of
omissions and overlooked spots like `Where's the beef?' By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   KEYRATES (Undated) _ Key interest rate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
