<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LEMKE-HNS &LR;      06-23 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEMKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BIG LEAGUES TO MINORS, WITH NO REGRETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ Two years ago, Mark Lemke earned $2 million as a
member of the Atlanta Braves. Today, he makes $700 a month, sings
karaoke ballads as part of rookie hazing rituals, travels on rented
buses, gets a paltry per-diem for meals and stays in budget motels.
</P>
<P>
   It only sounds like rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke is part infield coach, part aspiring knuckleball pitcher
for the Northern League's New Jersey Jackals, who played a
doubleheader Tuesday against their Eastern Division rival, the
Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs, at Heritage Park. Laboring in an
unaffiliated, low-level baseball league hardly seems fashionable
for a man who was the Braves' second baseman for parts of 10
major-league seasons and owns a 1995 World Series ring, but Lemke
insists this is exactly where he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a lot of fun for me,'' Lemke said. ``It's kind
of like when you're a little kid playing ball. That's all it is,
really, just loving to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   His former boss, John Schuerholz, the Atlanta Braves' executive
vice president and general manager, said Tuesday night that he
wasn't surprised by Lemke's up-beat approach to his new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Mark is a guy who really loves baseball and loves to be
a part of it, and I'm sure what he's doing now is a reflection of
that,'' Schuerholz said. ``His passion for the game has been
obvious to everybody, and going from a member of world championship
teams with us to becoming a knuckleball pitcher in an independent
league ... that pretty much says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   This strange tale started May 19, 1998, near the second base bag
at Fenway Park. Lemke was playing his 31st _ and, as it turns out,
final _ game with the Boston Red Sox, against the Chicago White
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   A grounder off the bat of Mike Caruso came to Lemke, who tried
to tag Chad Kreuter between first and second and start a double
play. But when Kreuter crashed into Lemke, the 5-foot-9, 167-pound
second baseman didn't know which way was up. He suffered a
concussion, and the resulting postconcussive syndrome left him
feeling dizzy and light-headed all winter.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke, who was hitting only .187 at the time, went on the
disabled list for the fourth time in his career. Over the winter,
when it became apparent that his major-league days were over, he
envisioned himself going home to Utica, N.Y., playing a little
baseball for his brother's beer-league team and spending his days
on golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Then an old minor-league teammate, now managing in an
independent league, called with an offer Lemke couldn't turn down.
</P>
<P>
   Kash Beauchamp, who played with Lemke in 1988 at Class AA
Greenville in the Southern League and again in 1989 at Class AAA
Richmond of the International League, had a place for his old
friend on the Jackals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Mark, and what makes him great, is you'd never
know he made $2 million,'' said Beauchamp, who was selected ahead
of Kirby Puckett in the first round of the 1982 amateur draft.
``I've played 13 years in the minor leagues and I saw a lot of my
friends go to the big leagues, and I saw a lot of them change, a
lot of them stay the same. He's one of those guys who hasn't let
his stature affect him in the least. He hasn't changed since we
played together in 1988 in Greenville.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemke toyed with a knuckleball back in high school at
Utica-Notre Dame, and continued to throw one every now and then
while playing catch as a big-leaguer. But pitching, before this
year, was never an option.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackals activated Lemke one week ago, and last Friday, he
took the hill for the first time against the Adirondack
Lumberjacks. Lemke pitched the ninth inning of the Jackals' 14-4
win, striking out two on slow knucklers, but allowing three wild
pitches which led to one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lemmer just had nasty stuff out there,'' Jackals catcher D.C.
Olsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Lemke enjoys his first official foray into coaching,
the desire to play the game still burns. He's only 33 and still in
good shape, and if it not for a four-year run of bad luck with
injuries, he still could be playing for the Braves. He's not
eligible to play the field for the Jackals, though, because the
team already is at the league limit for experienced professional
players. He is considered a rookie only as a pitcher, a position he
had not played professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is the hand he's been dealt, or rather, the hand
he's dealt himself. Lemke isn't hurting for money. He doesn't need
to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play, I really do,'' Lemke said. ``I know it seems
differently, but it gives me a whole lot of opportunities to kill a
bunch of birds with one stone. And I'm just having the time of my
life doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
