<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S TOP 250 POSH REAL-ESTATE SPOTS  
  
 (NOTE: SEE SEPARATE STORY _ BC-TOP-250-AFFLUENT-TOWNS-WORTH _ FOR
LIST)  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SPECIAL ATTN: Calif., Colo., Conn., Fla., Ill.)   (Resending from June 21 for those needing)  
  
 (This ``separate buy'' financial story _ an ranking of America's
wealthiest communities _ is from the June issue of ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS FOUR EDITOR-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, AT 800 (75 WORDS),
1,025 (525), 1,700 (175) AND 2,100 (150). STORY CAN STAND IN 2,100
WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 2,250.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By LOCH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the land of the wealthy, dirt is king.
</P>
<P>
   Take a stroll through Jupiter Island, Fla., for instance. A
one-acre plot of land with 150 feet of waterfront fetches between
$2 million and $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The house sitting on that dirt might be palatial, but that
hardly matters: On this island of exclusivity, houses come and go
with alarming speed. ``There are a number of houses going up right
now, and every single one of them will eventually be knocked
down,'' says Gene Albarelle, a local broker who deals in high-end
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a speculator paid $1.65 million for an acre of ground
with a five-bedroom house on it. The house was immediately torn
down, and though its replacement has not yet been finished, the
owner is now asking $4.4 million for this small parcel of paradise.
</P>
