<HEADER>
A6729 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     06-23 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 27)  
 THE PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN AS A THEATRICAL EVENT ,
 (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the presidential qualifications of Al Gore and
George W. Bush are to be determined by their appearances in the
opening scenes of the great political saga of 2000, perhaps the
contest should be assessed by drama critics rather than political
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Since both contenders express centrist positions within
traditional Democratic-Republican constraints regarding government
expansion, the manner in which they present themselves is as
important as the messages they convey.
</P>
<P>
   In their first official sorties onto the field of battle, Bush
won with an excellent performance.
</P>
<P>
   Like the great theatrical figures of the past, he outshone
Democrat Gore and his fellow Republican hopefuls by delaying his
grand entrance into Iowa and New Hampshire until almost all of his
competitors were on stage, by generating speculation and suspense
about his stand on key issues and then by delivering a performance
worthy of such an accomplished actor as Anthony Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had about 200 reporters trailing him and covering every
nuance of his appearance. The result was a stunning debut in the
national arena.
</P>
<P>
   Gore fared less well. Announcing his candidacy at a tumultuous
rally in Carthage, Tenn., he had to shout and gesticulate like a
bombastic politician of the pre-TV era to make himself seen and
heard over the shrill cries of AIDS demonstrators and the constant
waving of placards by his enthusiastic supporters.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush spoke in modulated tones, exuding quiet charm.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor's message was no more vital to the future of
America than the vice president's, but his freshness on the
national scene and his professionally staged performance proved
that star power is as much a part of politics as of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Barrymores, the Lunts and Katherine Cornell, who
illuminated Broadway when his parents were young, Bush timed his
entrance so that it would eclipse his competitors in their
shop-worn hand-shaking, back-slapping, baby-kissing,
platitude-reciting quest for the GOP presidential garland. His task
now is to keep the momentum going.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has been a fixture on the national scene since his
failed 1988 presidential bid, now must correct his mistakes and
streak across the heavens like a meteor.
</P>
<P>
   He has only one opponent for the Democratic nomination, the
formidable Bill Bradley. Bush faces 11, although most are political
Lilliputians who are dwarfed by Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in announcing his candidacy, sought to distance himself
from Bill Clinton's tawdry sexual adventures while identifying
himself with Clinton's strong national economy and the victory over
tyranny in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemingly failed to bury the most-quoted cliche of the
campaign: Al Gore is dull and wooden.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows him sees Gore as likable, witty and
intelligent. They respect him as a man dedicated to protecting our
environment and natural resources, making government run more
effectively, improving education and, like Bush, promoting stronger
family values.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates differ on how they would save Social Security
and Medicare, improve education, deal with abortion and taxes and
control the proliferation of guns. But Bush has put distance
between himself and militant rightwingers while Gore has steered
clear of militant leftwingers.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the moment, it comes down to who has that undefinable
ingredient known as star power.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency itself confers star power on most, but not all,
of its occupants. Herbert Hoover, Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter
enjoyed it only fleetingly, and William Howard Taft possibly not at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin and Theodore Roosevelt seemingly were born to be stars,
and their brilliant aura continues to brighten the political
firmament. Woodrow Wilson's star power lay in his eloquence,
idealism and vision rather than in his physical dynamism.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Eisenhower enjoyed political stardom because he was the
most admired military hero of World War II. He remained a beloved
figure during his eight-year presidency.
</P>
<P>
   John Kennedy, the dashing young product of a much-publicized
family, possessed greater star power than his 1960 Republican
opponent, Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon Johnson, who succeeded to the presidency on Kennedy's
death, exhibited tremendous star power in 1964 as he criss-crossed
the nation, promising passage of Medicare, strong civil rights
measures, federal aid to education as well as implementation of his
war on poverty. By Election Day, when he won the biggest popular
plurality of the century, the turnout at his political rallies was
enormous.
</P>
<P>
   But the tragic quagmire of Vietnam robbed him of his stellar
position.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, a minor star in motion pictures, became a major
star in politics and continues to enjoy that designation despite
his serious health problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gore-Bush contest the question is whether both men
possess the star power to win their parties' nominations? If so,
the election in November 2000 could be a fascinating showdown
between two baby boomers from prominent, affluent families who
stand astride the political center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
