<HEADER>
A6743 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-23 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE A RECIPE FOR COCOA, SANS CHOCOLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know what's amazing about politicians?
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, a lot of things are amazing about politicians: their
breathtaking proclivity for deceit, their mind-boggling penchant
for manipulation, their shocking propensity for greed and
self-indulgence, their limitless capacity for trampling the
interests of the people they are elected to serve ...
</P>
<P>
   But the amazing trait of which I speak is the politicians'
infuriating habit of reacting to problems by proposing solutions
that have nothing to do with the problems they propose to solve.
</P>
<P>
   Take the airline passengers ``bill of rights'' that has been
bouncing around in Congress for months but was more or less
preempted last week when the air travel industry announced a
voluntary plan that's supposed to turn disgruntled customers into
happy campers. Take it, please, to quote the great philosopher and
social critic Henny Youngman.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress started pushing various versions of the
passenger-rights law in response to last winter's debacle at
Detroit's Metro Airport, where passengers were held hostage for
hours in airplanes that were unable to take off because of bad
weather. The trapped passengers were outraged and the incident
attracted much news coverage, which in turn attracted many
camera-and-microphone-addicted politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians vowed that no citizen of these great United
States would ever again be subjected to such misery as that
suffered by marooned airline passengers in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   And just how did politicians such as Sen. John McCain of Arizona
and Rep. Bud Shuster of Pennsylvania propose to fulfill their vow?
</P>
<P>
   You guessed it: by offering up laws that included no provision
whatsoever for rescuing passengers who might be ensnared in a
situation like the one in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding, folks. Not one of the passenger ``bill of rights''
proposals provoked by the winter horror in Detroit even so much as
hinted at what ought to be one of passengers' most fundamental
rights: the right to get off an airplane that isn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   If a taxicab is hopelessly gridlocked in city traffic, a
passenger can get out and walk. If a bus stalls en route to its
destination, the passengers can exit the bus and search for
another.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose you're out of luck if a subway train breaks down. But
then, nobody has to ride the subway; there are times when we
basically have no choice but to get on an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   And once you get on the plane, you have to stay on until the
self-anointed airline deities decide to let you leave.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the air travel industry can give you plenty of reasons why
it has to be this way, and some of the reasons might even make
sense. But if the politicians want to throw a fit about passengers
being trapped on airplanes and want to be seen on the evening news
promising to save travelers from such abuse at the hands of the
evil airlines, wouldn't we expect that the very first item on the
resulting passenger bill of rights would be the right to deplane
when a flight is unreasonably delayed in taking off?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's what we would expect. Which only goes to show
that just plain folks are incapable of the advanced thinking
processes employed by politicians. In a politician's scheme of
things, the only sensible approach to solving a problem is to
devise a solution that makes no reference of any kind to the
problem that needs solving.
</P>
<P>
   So. We get a passenger bill of rights that requires airlines to
give us more information about frequent-flier programs but doesn't
even mention the hostage-on-the-runway dilemma that prompted the
bill of rights in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   And now the airline industry decides to upstage Congress by
adopting its own passenger bill of rights _ which likewise fails to
include the right to deplane.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress marches on, responding to school violence with
proposals that promote pet issues such as gun control, movie
censorship and religion in the classroom but don't begin to address
the actual causes of school violence.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing. Just amazing.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
