<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CALIF-SLANG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTSPEAK TAKEN SERIOUSLY AT LANGUAGE SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SALLY McGRANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley isn't the only part of California with
its own dialect. If you're a student in San Luis Obispo, for
example, you may have spent the morning ``classing'' before meeting
some ``slocalocals'' at ``Bubble Gum Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: After attending class, you met some natives of San
Luis Obispo near an alley that students have been slathering in
bubble gum since the late '60s.
</P>
<P>
   The language quirks common in the coastal region surrounding San
Luis Obispo have found a lexicographical home. Posted a little more
than a year ago, the California Central Coast Online Dictionary
(www.multimedia.calpoly.edu/libarts/ccod) is a database of more
than 400 words with definitions, pronunciations and illustrative
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs and video footage on the site illustrate collegiate
and surfer slang. The dictionary, compiled by students from
California Polytechnic State University, is the creation of John
Battenburg, 37, a professor of linguistics and literature. A former
Fulbright scholar who taught in Tunisia and researched the death of
the Berber language there, Battenburg decided to turn his
linguistic know-how to a vernacular that was closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot to be gained by talking about how we can
describe language and what we can learn about speech communities
because of that,'' Battenburg said. ``We're not only learning about
language, we're learning something about this unique culture or
subculture on the central coast of California.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the San Luis Obispo Farmer's Market, he pointed
out a group of clothing stores. ``See there?'' he asked. ``That's
`sorority square.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sorority Square, which is actually a triangle, has its own
entry, complete with usage example, in the dictionary:
``so-ror-i-ty square /srrtI skwEr/ noun. 1. Shopping triangle
formed by Express, Gap and Victoria's Secret, which is always
heavily populated by sorority women. Is called a square to
emphasize the dippyness of sorority women.
</P>
<P>
   Humorous, San Luis Obispo. I was going to buy socks at Gap, but
the lines are so long it looks like there is a house field trip to
sorority square. (Square in the sense of being conventional and not
venturing out of the norm.).''
</P>
<P>
   The California Central Coast Online Dictionary is the result of
university initiatives to incorporate technology in its classrooms,
an effort financed by student fees garnered under what is called
the Poly Plan. (The dictionary illustrates the Poly Plan entry with
the sentence: ``I cannot believe this school is asking for more
money with this bogus Poly Plan scam.'')
</P>
<P>
   The self-described poster boy for the use of technology in
liberal arts classes, Battenburg was initiated into the world of
the Internet in 1997, after he returned to Cal Poly from his two
years as a Fulbright professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Rip Van Winkle,'' he said. ``I came into my office
and they had a new computer for me, and I asked my neighbor, a
historian, `How do you get on the Web?''' Since then, he has
incorporated into his multimedia lectures material from Web sites,
like photographs of Walden pond and audio readings of Hawaiian
Creole nursery rhymes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the dictionary is a cultural archive that can be
searched, other linguists doubt its effectiveness as a serious
reference tool, pointing to its relatively small size and spelling,
grammar and lexicographic errors. ``Lots of things you have kids
do, they aren't going to do as well as people you pay to do it,''
said Geoffrey Nunberg, the usage editor at The American Heritage
Dictionary and a consulting professor of linguistics at Stanford.
``Which doesn't mean they shouldn't do it. It's not going to be
scholarly, but so what?''
</P>
<P>
   Battenburg believes that the online dictionary is a useful
pedagogic tool that teaches students not only how a dictionary is
made, but how they should learn to examine the language around
them. It gives students ``a chance to test drive their
lexicographers' skill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly sounds more useful than any bulimic learning
system (``bu-li-mic learn-ing sys-tem noun. 1. Study method used by
Cal Poly students to memorize and regurgitate lecture information
on exams and in papers. San Luis Obispo. I have successfully
completed four years at Cal Poly utilizing the bulimic learning
system with zero retention'').
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
