<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What would cause a printer to print incorrectly with odd
lines and letters, even though it looks fine on screen and prints
OK from another printer?
</P>
<P>
   A. One thing you will want to check first is the type of cable
that you are using to connect your printer to the computer. On the
surface, a parallel cable may look just like any other, but most
printers manufactured in the last few years require what is called
an IEEE-1284-compliant parallel printer cable. Most modern printers
use bidirectional communication technology to talk to the computer,
as it can make data transfer rates 10 times faster than older
parallel connections that are not bidirectional.
</P>
<P>
   If you are seeing peculiar things on your page, like garbled
letters, weird type characters or unexpected lines that are not
visible in your document on the screen, odds are you probably have
the wrong cable. You may also get false error messages on your PC
telling you the printer is off-line or out of paper, and in some
cases, the printer just won't work.
</P>
<P>
   You can purchase an IEEE-1284 cable at most computer stores. Get
one that is shorter than six feet, because too-long cables can
sometimes cause data errors. When you plug it in, make sure it is
not lying on or near the printer's power cable so that you don't
get electromagnetic interference between the two cords. If you
change the cable and still have problems, you may want to call your
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any way to get old files off a dead hard drive, or
are they gone for good?  &QL; 
A. If your old computer went to that great desktop in the sky
because of hard-drive failure, there are several companies that
will try to save your data. That can be rather pricey (several
hundred to several thousand dollars), but if your files are
irreplaceable, it might be one of your only options.
</P>
<P>
   Most data-recovery places can handle a variety of platforms and
media, and offer a telephone number for you to get an estimate on
the cost before sending in the drive. Such services include Disk
Savers, (800) 440-1904); Drive Service (888) 272-8332, and Absolute
Recovery (760) 776-1841.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
