<HEADLINE>
NEW PALM SHOWS UP, UNATTACHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 3Com Corp.'s Palm VII handheld computer, which is now being
sold only in the New York City area, is like one of those odd,
futuristic devices that movie aliens are always accidentally
leaving behind after they touch down briefly to abduct a few
Earthlings. Later, someone finds it on the ground, pokes it a few
times, lifts the built-in antenna _ ``Hmm, I wonder what  &UR; this &LR; 
thing does?'' _ and jumps back in astonishment when the little box
comes to life and magically displays the up-to-the-minute score of
the Knicks game.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks playing in the NBA finals? Now,  &UR; there &LR;  is science
fiction. The Palm VII, on the other hand, is very real. It is a
computer from the near future, a future in which people keep little
computers in their pockets and tap into the Internet wirelessly,
gathering news headlines, trading stocks, sending and receiving
electronic mail, calling up a map for directions, paying bills,
doing personal banking, tracking down the nearest automated cash
machine, ordering theater tickets and other earthly delights.
</P>
<P>
   We have already seen the change happen to telephones. Almost
overnight, wireless phones have become nearly as popular as
traditional, wired phones. In Japan and northern Europe, one person
in three now carries a cellular phone. In this country, pagers and
cellular phones are so commonplace that when one chirps, nearly
everyone in the room instinctively twitches.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we will see the same thing happen with wireless computers.
People will still use wired computers for heavy-duty computing
tasks, but increasingly they will also carry little wireless
communicators that handle simple voice and Internet data calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII is the first of these wireless communicators to be
made available to the masses. But it is too expensive, too slow and
too limited to achieve the cult popularity of its predecessors, the
Palm Pilot and the Palm III. The user is permitted to tap into only
a limited number of World Wide Web sites, and even then only for
snippets of text, not for graphics or pictures.
</P>
<P>
   However, as a harbinger of things to come, it will appeal to
gadget lovers and information junkies. Others will probably want to
wait for the next generation of wireless data devices, expected to
arrive in the next year or two, which will offer more features
(like voice calls and faxing) and significantly higher connection
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   3Com says it is confining sales of the Palm VII to the New York
area for now because it wants to make sure the system works
properly; by late fall, the company says, the device will be sold
in all major metropolitan areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, though, it works throughout the United States _ in the
260 major cities where 3Com and its partner Bell South operate a
radio-based wireless data network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Works'' can be a relative term, however. I've been testing the
Palm VII for a few weeks in Texas and California. In Texas, more
often than not I had to move near a window or even step outside to
get a signal strong enough to connect to 3Com's radio network.
Earlier this week, just south of Los Angeles, I was never able to
get a connection and thus had to find out about the Knicks' victory
Monday the old-fashioned way: by walking 20 feet into the bar to
look at the satellite television broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII is physically and functionally almost identical to
the Palm Pilot and Palm III, except for a flip-up antenna on the
right side of the case. The dark gray device, for those who have
never seen one peeking out from the pocket of a Silicon Valley
tycoon or clipped to the belt of a computer geek, is just a bit
over 3 inches wide, 5 inches long and } of an inch thick. As the
name implies, it fits easily in the hand and weighs 6.7 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   At $599, however, the Palm VII costs hundreds of dollars more
than the basic Palm III; that little antenna, for receiving data,
costs more than its weight in gold. Users also have to buy a
monthly subscription to the proprietary wireless data service
Palm.net. The basic service plan costs $9.95 a month and entitles
the user to send or receive 50 kilobytes of data wirelessly. Each
kilobyte thereafter costs 30 cents. After Aug. 31, 3Com will also
charge a one-time setup fee of $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   The average brief e-mail message is about 1 or 2 kilobytes in
length, so the basic connection plan is good for about one message
a day. I've talked with some early Palm VII users who exhausted
their monthly allotment of kilobytes within the first week.
</P>
<P>
   The more useful the Palm VII's wireless capabilities become, the
more it costs. The ``expanded plan'' costs $24.99 a month for 150
kilobytes of messaging, which 3Com describes as 90 brief e-mails,
60 stock quotes, 30 sports scores, 30 traffic reports and 30
weather updates.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the most amazing thing about this device is how
rapidly it beams money from your credit card and transfers it
wirelessly to 3Com's bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless Internet access does not mean, in this case, the
ability to browse Web pages or download software in the same way it
is done on a desktop machine. The Palm VII uses a technique called
Web clipping, which extracts key elements of a Web page, typically
text, and presents it on the Palm's two-inch-square,
green-and-black screen.
</P>
<P>
   A small cluster of companies eager to drive more visitors to
their Web sites have agreed to create special ``Palm Query
Applications,'' or PQA's, for the Palm VII, enabling users to
select an icon on the screen and download a Web clipping or two.
The PQA's themselves can be downloaded from the Palm.net site,
www.palmnet.com, to a desktop computer and transferred to the Palm
VII via cable.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the companies with PQA's include The Wall Street
Journal, USA Today, ABC News, Bloomberg financial news, The Weather
Channel, ETrade, Fodor's and Frommer's travel guides, the OAG
flight guide, Moviefone, Etak traffic reports, Bank of America home
banking, the Pagenet and Skytel paging services, Yahoo! People
Search for access to a data base of 100 million Americans, and
United Parcel Service package tracking.
</P>
<P>
   In a case of deus ex machina, there is even Godsword.com, which
can automatically deliver a random Bible verse each day to the Palm
VII. There is even a wireless translation service, the Go Network's
Translator to Go, that does on-the-fly language conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from its pricing model, 3Com never intended for the Palm
VII to become wildly popular, like its littermates the Palm III and
Palm V personal information organizers. Rather, it is a working
prototype, a proof of concept, a first draft of a wireless device
that offers Internet access from almost anywhere. Well-heeled
information addicts and executives looking for the latest high-tech
toy will find it amusing, and some may even wonder how they ever
got by without it.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us will probably want to wait for the next
generation of wireless data network devices, perhaps something like
the Qualcomm Corporation's forthcoming PDQ phone that combines a
Palm Pilot with a cellular phone. Within months, there will
definitely be a lot of little wireless gizmos from which to choose,
ranging from smart cell phones with large display screens, to
Palm-like pocket computing devices, to in-dash computers for the
car.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless data services will eventually become ubiquitous, but
not until the industry moves to a flat-rate, unlimited access
pricing plan similar to the one that jump-started the consumer
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
