<HEADER>
A6753 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HITECH-POCKETS-AR     06-23 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HITECH-POCKETS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELL PHONE IN THE CORNER POCKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they presented their new fall collection recently, the SoHo
designers who call themselves Orfi (for the Organization for
Returning Fashion Interest) included one outfit that consisted
solely of an enormous blanket. But despite the hard work of two
models who appeared on stage with it over their shoulders, the
blanket-as-clothing concept is probably not destined to be a big
seller.
</P>
<P>
   But another, less avant-garde article of clothing from Orfi has
gained attention outside the group's loyal circle of downtown
fashion mavens. Laminated cotton men's Rifle Team pants ($260 to
$270 a pair) have been flying out of the designers' store in the
past few months because of a special feature: the pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, these are not just any old pockets. The Rifle
Team pants have a horizontal pocket on the front of each leg, 13
inches long, with a secure zipper closure and mesh lining. Never
mind house keys and a discreet comb. Each pocket can handle a
cellular phone, a beeper and an electronic scheduler _ all at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``These pants are a reaction to how people live now,'' said
Donald Hearn, one of Orfi's owners. ``This whole trend in pockets
specifically responds to the idea that when you leave the house
these days, there are a lot more things you need to carry with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rifle Team Pants are signs of an era in which electronic
gadgetry has moved from accessory to necessity. Gone are the days
when the things that went into pockets _ the pen, the wallet, the
lowly pocket protector _ were as humble as the pocket itself.
</P>
<P>
   Today's digital accessories are bulky and self-important. And
why not? After all, they are essential tools, communications
lifelines to a pants wearer's office or home. So it's up to pockets
to conform.
</P>
<P>
   From the ``lightweight, knee-length summer topper,'' as it is
called at the upscale Barneys clothing store in Manhattan
(translation: a jacket, and it sells for $396 at the store) to
Equipment for Legs, a new line of pants from the more
egalitarian-priced Dockers, pockets are being re-sized, refitted
and rethought to accommodate the sprawling collection of personal
electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple. ``As much as human beings like to look
good, we like convenience as well,'' said Christina Lindholm,
chairwoman of the department of fashion design and merchandising at
Virginia Commonwealth University in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designers can't lose sight of this new aspect of clothing _
that the customer is likely to be a working person or someone with
a very busy life who has to have the cell phone and beeper with
them to keep their day organized.''
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that the Palm Pilot is to blame. From its
inception, the Palm Pilot had designs on the pocket: its earliest
prototypes were blocks of wood that the designers carried around in
shirt pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to make sure that the size was comfortable
because a person who carries a Palm Pilot accesses it 14 to 20
times a day for two to three minutes each time,'' said Andrea
Johnson, a product manager at Palm Computing, a subsidiary of the
3Com Corp. ``It has to be easy to get to, to turn it on and off.
And people want to carry it not just when they're working but when
they're skiing, when they're backpacking, hiking.''
</P>
<P>
   But how comfortable is it to carry around an electronic
scheduler _ or even a block of wood _ in a shirt pocket?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little chunky,'' said Len Abbazia, who was the manager
of corporate communications for one of Palm Computing's smaller
competitors, Franklin Electronic Publishers, which makes the Rex
Pro, before he left the company recently. ``Put a Palm Pilot in
your left pocket and see how the whole left side of your body drags
down.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course, even the Rex Pro, which is the size of a credit
card, has special pocket needs. ``If you sit on it, you could break
the screen,'' Abbazia said.
</P>
<P>
   These are the sorts of concerns that recently prompted Levi
Strauss &AMP; Co. to hire the European designer Massimo Osti to create
a whole new vision of pants for the Dockers line. The result _ the
Equipment for Legs line _ is trousers with hidden pockets
configured to hold specific kinds of electronic devices. The pants
($120 to $130 a pair), which will arrive in stores in the United
States in September, will feature a range of pocket styles: some
will be sized to hold a Palm Pilot, others a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And the trousers are of Kevlar (often used for bulletproof
vests) or other fire-resistant fabrics, said Kim Steigerwald, a
Dockers brand manager. ``The idea is to have the pants made from
technologically evolved fabrics as well,'' she said, ``so the
pockets and the pants both have a lot of functionality.''
</P>
<P>
   The digital era is really prompting just another step in the
evolution of the pocket. The earliest pockets evolved hundreds of
years ago from pouches that hung on a string from the neck or
wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This custom probably came from Europe'' Ms. Lindholm said,
``and eventually evolved into something that they would button on
to their clothes. It is something we did see more in a peasant type
of population than among the wealthy because rich men had someone
who could carry their things for them. But for instance, on the
American prairie, women would carry something like a needle case in
a pouch because a needle was amazingly expensive and valuable
beyond hens' teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the mass manufacturing of clothing replaced custom
tailoring in the 20th century, the pocket had become a standard
feature on clothing. Certain pockets had specific purposes _ that
anachronistic little pocket-in-a-pocket on the front of jeans, for
instance, was created for a pocket watch. But the size of the
general-purpose pocket has never been standardized.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, some pocket designers are reluctant to make a
commitment to match their pockets to the specific dimensions of a
particular device. ``Because technology is changing so quickly,
these devices are almost disposable,'' Hearn of Orfi said. ``The
shape of a common cell phone you carry today may be different from
the one you have in nine months.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, designers say they have more to consider than just the
mere pocket: there's also the issue of lint. ``Pockets collect
lint, and that's not good for electronic devices,'' Ms. Lindholm
said. To prevent lint buildup, many designers are replacing
traditional fabrics in pockets with mesh.
</P>
<P>
   Mesh has other benefits as well. ``Mesh provides a way to vent a
shirt in hotter weather,'' said Devony Hastings, a spokeswoman for
Recreational Equipment Inc., a Seattle company whose rugged sports
clothing is designed to appeal to adventurous travelers. ``And the
other reason is drainage, if some people wear them in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Some pocket linings promise even more. Last fall, for example,
Barneys sold a polyester men's trench coat with a specially lined
pocket that was designed to shield the wearer from cellular-phone
emissions. Although the store no longer stocks the coat, it did
quite well, a store spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some designers and retailers are embracing digital devices in a
more general way. Take cargo pants, for example, a many-pocketed
style that has become ubiquitous in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   While the pockets were not added specifically to accommodate
current gadgetry, ``it's clear from all the pockets in cargo pants
that there's plenty of room,'' said Lonnie Fogel, a spokesman for
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, a retailer whose cargo pants ($59.50 to
$69.50) are marketed primarily to device-laden college students.
</P>
<P>
   Where will pockets go next? ``I see this as a short-lived
trend,'' Ms. Lindholm said. ``Think about it. There is no place on
my body that needs any added dimension. Where do you want the extra
bulk you get from carrying a device? Around the waist? Down on your
thigh?''
</P>
<P>
   Put that way, it makes the blanket from Orfi sound positively
slimming. Does it come with pockets?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
