<HEADER>
A6755 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVOLTA-RESURGENCE-T     06-23 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVOLTA-RESURGENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINCE ``PULP FICTION,'' TRAVOLTA HAS BOOGIED FROM ONE GREAT ROLE TO
ANOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He's a bold and impressive actor, John Travolta _ maybe
better at playing arrogance than any other actor of his generation.
Which is why his sunny, agreeable disposition is a little
disconcerting. There have been reports of the Vulcan Mind Meld that
he employs with interviewers, turning the tables on them.
</P>
<P>
   But, in Dallas to promote the new military murder mystery, ``The
General's Daughter,'' he's easygoing and open. When asked why he's
working so much these days _ he hasn't taken a break since 1994's
``Pulp Fiction'' re-ignited his career _ he strokes his
salt-and-pepper goatee and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the scripts I'm getting now are so much better,'' he
responds. ``I've gotta be honest with you, based on the couple of
scripts a year I was getting then, there was no reason to push
myself. But the material now is so much more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another period, roughly 20 years ago, when he was
offered everything under the sun. He was slated to be the lead in
``American Gigolo.'' Noted recluse and Texas native Terrence Malick
also wrote ``Days of Heaven'' for Travolta, but the actor couldn't
get free from his commitment to play the shaggy-haired chowderhead
Vinnie Barbarino on TV's ``Welcome Back, Kotter.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in the ``Saturday Night Fever'' and ``Grease'' and
``Urban Cowboy'' days, before bombs like ``Perfect'' and schlock
like the ``Look Who's Talking'' pictures had damaged his momentum.
But after ``Pulp Fiction'' led to successes including ``Face-Off''
and ``Get Shorty,'' it was as if the actor didn't want to sit
still, as if he were afraid he might miss an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   That extends to publicity; Travolta has actively pushed his
recent projects, including last winter's ``A Civil Action.'' On
press rounds in Dallas for ``General,'' Travolta's not wearing the
black Armani suit that he's sported for so many of the ``Oprah''
appearances _ like last week's, when he was smoothing down a rep
tie over his pasha's belly.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he's wearing a chocolate brown number, with an iridescent
dark-brown shirt and matching tie as he eases himself onto the
sofa. His bright, blue eyes shining as if they had been lubricated,
Travolta becomes reflective at a moment's notice; he speaks very
intently, so as not to be misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Although he gained fame for his prowess on the dance floor (see
his breakout film, ``Saturday Night Fever''), Travolta is just as
good with language. In the dialogue-heavy ``The General's
Daughter,'' Travolta plays Paul Brenner, a military intelligence
officer investigating the gruesome murder of a female captain who
turns out to be the daughter of a general with political
aspirations. He notes that he had a lot of dialogue in ``A Civil
Action'' and ``Primary Colors.'' But the difference in ``Daughter''
is that he's not winding up and delivering speeches.
</P>
<P>
   This movie, he says, pursing his lips, ``is probably the most
dialogue-heavy based on character. There's all these layers. And
that's what I love about it; you never know until he's in the
middle of the cycle of communication where he's going. (Brenner) is
very shrewd about how much he shows to people. And the humor, his
wryness is so great.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one can't help but ask him about doing a musical, given
the splash he made in ``Saturday Night Fever'' and ``Grease.'' He
can appear to be outsized and relaxed at once, shifting his weight
and sprawling on the sofa as he warms to the conversation. He seems
a natural to play Dean Martin in the biopic to be directed by
Martin Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he corrects, ``(I'll play) Sinatra.'' But in Los
Angeles, there were stories circulating that he was offered the
Martin role. And it seems like such a logical choice. When pressed
on the subject, he sits up, his eyes twinkling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They offered me Dean,'' he says, nodding, ``but I didn't say
yes to it right away. To be honest with you, I didn't know there
was a deadline on saying yes to it. My agent had said, `Look,
there's this (Dean Martin biography by writer Nick Tosches). They
just wanna develop it for you.' And Marty (Scorsese) wasn't
involved yet. And (my agent) said, `I don't recommend it because of
this and that.' But I said, `Let me think about it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was in the luxury mode of thinking, `I got time,
this is something to think about.' So, that Friday came and I
didn't know (about the deadline) and they were on Tom (Hanks). And
Tom said yes. Maybe it'd be more interesting for me to play
Sinatra. But (the script's) not done yet. It's not finished. If
they finish it, and they still want me to do it, I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be more evident that Travolta is itching to throw
himself into a musical the way he's been immersing himself in other
work in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he says, loosening his tie. ``I love the idea of
doing something musical. And Hollywood's not very for it, y'know.
You have to fight every inch of the way. They'd just as soon put
you in a legal thriller that might have more potential to the
audience. Who can figure it? All I know is I have the confidence in
it. They don't. But how do you talk someone into it?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a peculiar spectacle, to hear John Travolta _ the man who
brought new life to musicals with ``Saturday Night Fever'' and
``Grease'' after the genre was pronounced dead _ being forced to
defend the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, (`Fever') producer Robert Stigwood was music. He was the
Bee Gees. He believed in the music. You see, those guys were coming
from the record side of things. (Stigwood managed the Bee Gees and
they recorded for his label.) He understood it, like the MTV people
today, they understand those things. Studio heads don't understand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What about a place like Paramount, where he made ``Daughter.''
The studio is a part of Viacom, which also owns MTV. Travolta sits
back and smiles. ``They still don't get it,'' he emphasizes.
``Garth Brooks is gonna do a musical for them. It'll still take him
two or three years to get it off the ground, because of the
tenacity one would have to go to the studio with to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As the interview ends, Travolta mentions that a planned musical
project, ``Standing Room Only,'' based on the life of singer Jimmy
Roselli (''a would-be superstar who could've been as big as Tony
Bennett or Sinatra'') had to be postponed for a while. Gus Van Sant
had been slated to direct, but, Travolta says, ``I don't know if
he'll do it in a year. He may be on to another project. I don't
know if he would want to wait a whole year when he has other things
he could do. I could find a good director (to replace him).''
</P>
<P>
   And who would Travolta have in mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Travolta says, laughing, ``Scorsese would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7032. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
