<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-TOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE SLAYING PERPLEXES ILLINOIS TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORHAM, Ill. _ Most of the time, the trains barrel through this
small town at 70 mph, far too fast for anyone to get off.
</P>
<P>
   But now and then, one has to stop at the switching station to
let another train go by.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of June 15, one stopped long enough, authorities
believe, for Rafael Resendez-Ramirez to slip out of a boxcar,
through the woods and into a trailer home where Carolyn Frederick,
51, was caring for her 79-year-old father, George Morber.
</P>
<P>
   They were slain that morning for reasons that still puzzle
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any sense,'' Jackson County Sheriff Bill
Kilquist said this week after fingerprints found in the home were
identified as those of Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have taken from that old man anything he wanted ...
including his truck. There was no need to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Morber's truck was found a day later in a school parking lot in
Cairo, Ill., on the Kentucky border, about 60 miles south of here.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, 38, a Mexican national, is believed to have
killed at least eight people in Texas, Illinois and Kentucky during
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, authorities in Pontiac, Ill., 80 miles southwest of
Chicago, confirmed that Resendez-Ramirez is a possible suspect in
last week's slaying of Juanita Sapp, 40, whose body was found near
her apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Like the six murders credited to Resendez-Ramirez in Texas and
Kentucky, the three in Illinois occurred a short distance from
railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   All the victims have been murdered with such ferocity that law
officers think rage is the primary motive.
</P>
<P>
   Although police are withholding many details, the killer
reportedly covered each victim, as if to conceal his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are creatures of habit,'' Kilquist said. ``You know ...
it's like some people in a restaurant will take their napkins and
cover their plates after they've eaten. They're covering up their
messes.''
</P>
<P>
   The double murder here shocked and terrified the community of
about 300, unaccustomed to even petty crimes, though there are
three prison units in the immediate area. Most residents earn a
living farming or working for one of the prisons.
</P>
<P>
   George Morber was a retired prison guard, living in a trailer
home outside of town, beside a small pond that separated his
property from that of his daughter and son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   About 1:30 p.m. June 15, Donald Frederick found the bodies of
his wife and father-in-law and called the sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   Kilquist had been at the scene for about five minutes, waiting
for crime scene technicians to arrive, when he made the connection:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asking my investigator, `Who could have done this? Why
would anybody have done this?' Then I heard a noise. I looked up
and there was a train going by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Am I going crazy or did I read somewhere about
murders being committed near railroad tracks?' He said, `No, I read
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilquist contacted the FBI and Texas Rangers, who were probing
the murders in Texas, investigations that had centered on
Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a week passed before fingerprint analyses confirmed on
Monday that Resendez-Ramirez had been in the Morber home.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a week, some residents of Gorham breathed
easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people scared around here,'' said Ray Miller,
a friend of one of the victims. ``I suppose if he was going to
choose another person, though, he would have moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frightened,'' admitted Ellen Fritsche, the postmaster.
``Everybody was. People were locking their doors and they've never
done that. They were checking out their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Arena, who lives behind his bait shop a few miles from
Gorham, said his wife became nervous when he left the house to
check on his store after dark. ``She's packing her gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine _ he's a prison guard _ lives just up the
hill and my wife goes to work the same time he does. She meets him
up there and follows him into (Murphysboro).''
</P>
<P>
   After the fingerprints were identified, Morber's son, Bill, told
the local newspaper, ``Everyone is on edge and will be until this
Ramirez is caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, family members are saying little.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Frederick, driving away from his house across the pond
from where his wife died, seemed relieved that a suspect now had a
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad there's only one of them sonsabitches out there
instead of two.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
