<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV11-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JULY 11, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I always cover my floors and carpet with plastic sheets when
painting a room. However, when I last painted the baseboards in my
carpeted living room and bedroom I had a problem with some paint
from the baseboards dripping down or getting smeared onto the edges
of the carpet _ especially where the carpet has a deeper pile. I've
tried cardboard and plastic guards that I slide along as I paint,
but still get smears on the carpet. Any other ideas on how to avoid
this?
</P>
<P>
   A: An almost foolproof method is to use a wide putty knife to
force the edges of the plastic drop cloth under the baseboard as
shown here. Some paint may drip onto the plastic and into the joint
between the baseboard and the plastic, but this seal can be broken
before you pick up the plastic by pushing down on the plastic sheet
before you try to pull it out. That way none of the dried paint
will get pulled off the baseboard.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We live in a mobile home park and our water comes from a well
that the park operates, although we do have city sewer lines. Our
problem is that we get a strange odor (something like sewer gas)
whenever the water is running in the shower or in the washing
machine. The well water supply is tested by the state on a regular
basis, so we know that this is OK. Can you tell us what we can do
to solve this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Chances are that the odor comes from minerals in your well
water, although it may still be perfectly safe for drinking. If
this is the case you can install an odor-removing filter in your
water line. Small filters that fit under the kitchen sink will get
rid of the odor in the water used for drinking and cooking, but if
you want to also eliminate the odor from the water going to the
bathroom and other appliances you will have to install a larger,
``whole house'' filter in your incoming water line. There are many
companies that install and service such filtering systems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our detached two-car garage was originally near the back of
our lot and we had it moved nearer to the street some years ago,
but there was no special foundation put down for the building other
than some timbers on the ground. Now one wall is sinking and the
ground timbers are rotting. We want to save this garage, so can you
tell me what steps should be taken?
</P>
<P>
   A: Every building needs a foundation that goes down into the
ground deep enough to be below the frost level. Saving or restoring
your garage will require jacking it up (so you can excavate the
ground under it) or moving it out of the way temporarily, and then
building a proper underground masonry foundation where you want the
garage to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 20-year-old house has lap siding that is made of exterior
hardboard or pressed wood of some kind. It was originally finished
at the factory with dark brown paint or coating. On the south and
west sides which are exposed to the sun the color is starting to
fade and seems to have a whitish film over it. How can I prepare
this surface for painting it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your best bet is to contact the manufacturer of the siding to
get their recommendation. If this is impractical, then you should
scrub the surface down completely, sand lightly with fine paper and
dust thoroughly (scrubbing and sanding will remove the oxidized
paint that you think is a film). After that, apply a coat of
exterior primer, followed by one or two coats of exterior latex
house paint.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``WIDE PUTTY KNIFE PUSHES PLASTIC UNDER
MOULDING'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Forcing plastic sheet under edge of baseboard will
protect carpet against drips and smears while painting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
