<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-HEALTH-TEX     06-23 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-HEALTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN SHEDDING SUPERMAN COMPLEX, STARTING TO WORRY MORE ABOUT THEIR
HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by MEN-HEALTH-TESTOSTERONE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``stronger'' sex is beginning to toughen up, finally.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy is at an all-time high of 76.5 years in the
United States _ 73.6 years for men, who have started to close the
gender gap in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Our fathers, grandfathers, brothers, husbands and sons continue
to smoke more, eat more cheeseburgers and have fewer screenings for
serious diseases than their female counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they are experiencing life-threatening chest pains,
shortness of breath or blurred vision, millions of men say they
would not go to the doctor. A big part of the reason is attitude:
Men have traditionally believed that they just don't get sick.
</P>
<P>
   But deep down, most men don't believe that they are Superman,
and more and more men are showing that they do care about staying
healthy. Cheeseburgers or not, signs of a sea change in the way men
view their bodies and their health are clear.
</P>
<P>
   The forces of change? Everything from Bob Dole to Propecia, and
from AIDS to HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, you see men throwing their fear of gender
self-degradation to the wind and enrolling in coed aerobics
programs and even water ballet,'' says Charles Inlander, president
of the People's Medical Society, a national consumer health group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' said Inlander, who is also the author of ``Men's
Health for Dummies'' (IDG Books, $19.99), ``it was men who started
the jogging craze, went to the gym at lunchtime and asked their
employers to create on-site wellness programs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most men still believe they are bulletproof on different
levels. They believe men don't or shouldn't get sick. But that's
changing,'' said Dr. Kenneth Goldberg, former medical director of
the Male Health Institute in Dallas and a contributing editor for
``Men's Health'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still the basic fear, the denial aspect,'' Goldberg
said in a telephone interview on his way home from the first
National Men's Health Collaborative in Philadelphia. ``It's still
not socially acceptable for a man to get sick or have medical
problems. I think we've got a long way to go to get over that `I'm
invincible' attitude, but a change is in the making. It's out
there,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, who is also the author of ``How Men Can Live as Long
as Women'' (The Summit Group, $22.95), points out that the gender
gap in life expectancy is down from seven to less than six years.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have contributed to the changes in men's health
care, including the availability of more conservative forms of
therapy for erectile dysfunction and all the national media
attention to Viagra and new treatments for prostate cancer and
benign prostate disease, he said. Having a national spokesman like
Bob Dole talk about prostate cancer makes a big difference, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we continue to see women more actively involved with men's
health as well as their own,'' said Goldberg, whose newest book is
titled ``When the Man You Love Won't Take Care of His Health''
(Golden Books, $22).
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are smarter about their health. If a man took as good
care of his body as he does his car, he'd be a lot better off,''
Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The closing of the gender gap in life expectancy is also one of
the topics Gail Sheehy addresses in her new book, ``Understanding
Men's Passages,'' (Ballantine Books, $14).
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most stunning developments of the 20th century has
been to stretch the life cycle by an average of 30 years,'' Sheehy
said. ``In 1996 alone, American men added six months to their life
expectancy and reached a new high.''
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy for U.S. men has reached an all-time high of
73.6 years, 5.6 less than the 79.2 years for women. The gender gap
is more than a year closer than it was in 1990, when men could
expect to live to 72 and women to 79, according to the most recent
calculations from the National Center for Health Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Falling death rates from major diseases including heart attacks,
strokes, cancer and AIDS are helping men live almost as long as
women, Sheehy said.
</P>
<P>
   Inlander said that men's success in addressing disease has been
spurred by new screening tests and medications _ and by concerns as
simple as hair loss and as serious as AIDS that are getting men
into their physicians' office with more regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have much better screening tests for some of the health
problems that trouble men most,'' Inlander said. ``The single thing
that did the most to get men into the health care system was the
development of the PSA exam for prostate cancer. Men are absolutely
scared to death of prostate problems. Now that the PSA is
encouraged for all men beginning at age 50, more men are getting
into doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing encouraging men to seek medical help is the fact
that we have new medications to resolve certain problems, like hair
loss. It may not be the worst disease in the world, but because men
are so concerned with it, they are getting into the system
earlier,'' Inlander says.
</P>
<P>
   Also, sexually transmitted diseases, especially AIDS, are a
great concern for younger men who traditionally have avoided
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have become better educated about STDs. AIDS has become a
major scare, so a lot of younger men are approaching the health
care system,'' Inlander said. ``They are still not going to the
doctor for things like treatment for depression like they should
be, but they are beginning to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Inlander said, the role that managed care has played in
getting men into the health care system should not be discounted.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs encourage members to come in for physical exams and
screening tests including tests for prostate disease and
hypertension and diabetes and high cholesterol and skin cancer and
TB.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they are enrolled, they are able to be reached. Most men
under 30 didn't even have a doctor until they started joining
HMOs,'' Inlander said.
</P>
<P>
   While experts are happy to point to the signs that men are
taking new control over their own health, they also note that
progress does not mean complete success. Guys may now know that
they're not Superman, but they still have a lot to learn.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey, released by ``Men's Health'' magazine for
Father's Day, shows that 7 million U.S. men have not had a basic
health check in more than a decade. The survey also finds that
one-third of men would not go to the doctor even if they were
experiencing life-threatening health problems such as severe chest
pains or shortness of breath, two top symptoms of heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably explains why so many men end up in the cardiac
care unit of hospitals clutching a package of antacid tablets,''
said Michael Lafavore, editor in chief of ``Men's Health''
magazine. ``Guys still need to learn there's a big difference
between indigestion from eating too many nachos and a clogged
artery.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
