<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6784 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TENNIS-PRESIDENT-PROF     06-23 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-PRESIDENT-PROFILE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS ASSOCIATION PRESIDENT RETURNS TO REMINISCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LAURA ROLLINS HOCKADAY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Judy Ade Levering, the first woman president
of the United States Tennis Association in its 118 years, visited
her old neighborhood recently and reminisced about Arbor Villa
Park, the first steppingstone to her historic role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized how much playing in that park meant to me and how
safe I felt,'' said Levering, 60, who grew up across from the park,
bounded by 66th Terrace, Main Street and Edgevale Road. ``When I
think about schools having to have metal detectors today ... We
need to help neighborhoods get back to what is safe and wholesome
for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish every kid could grow up with a park like this,'' she
told friends and neighbors gathered for a reunion at Arbor Villa.
``Children need a place where they can play safe and learn life
skills, such as how to get along with people.''
</P>
<P>
   During the two-year term she began in January, Levering serves
as the top volunteer for the USTA, which has a $150 million annual
budget and a 121-member staff based in White Plains, N.Y. She has
been traveling throughout the world, meeting with tennis
professionals, heads of state, diplomats and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 30 Levering will welcome visitors from around the globe
to the 1999 U.S. Open Tennis Tournament at Flushing Meadows in
Queens, N.Y. The USTA owns and operates the tournament, its major
source of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Levering is warming up now for the Davis Cup quarterfinals, for
which the USTA will be host July 16-18 at the Longwood Cricket Club
in Chestnut Hill, Mass. The American and Australian teams will face
each other at the event, which celebrates the 100th anniversary of
the Davis Cup, launched at Longwood.
</P>
<P>
   Levering will be mistress of ceremonies for gala dinners in
Boston at the Harvard Club and at the John F. Kennedy Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longwood can accommodate 5,400 people,'' she said. ``Seats for
the three-day match were sold out in 81 minutes. We had 24,000
requests from people all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Solid, simple foundation
</P>
<P>
   Levering credits her family and a simple, solid neighborhood
lifestyle with shaping the skills she relies on now in her
demanding role.
</P>
<P>
   Appreciating what tennis has done for her, she initiated ``A
Plan for Growth'' while USTA first vice president two years ago.
The plan's purpose is to offer grants to foster the growth of
tennis programs in cities across the country. Levering inspired the
USTA to commit $32 million for the five-year project. The Tennis
Industry Association, representing hundreds of manufacturers,
kicked in $18 million, establishing a fund of $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   At its annual awards banquet, the Greater Kansas City Sports
Commission and Foundation recently recognized Levering for her
leadership and accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours before the banquet, Levering, accompanied by her
husband, Gordon Levering, and her brother, Carl F. Ade Jr. of
Kansas City, arrived at Arbor Villa Park for a celebration in her
honor. Former neighbor Deb Shigouri prepared gallons of lemonade
and dozens of iced cookies. Children waited on the park's single
tennis court for Levering, while others played in the pool where
she had been a summer lifeguard. And former neighbors _ still
lifelong friends _ gathered around for a hug and a handshake. Many
remarked that the former Judy Ade was the same kind, warm
individual they had always known in spite of her celebrity status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember when your mother would call, `Carlie Fred and Judy
Lou, come to dinner,' and our mother would whistle us home?'' asked
Joan Hovey Waller, a childhood neighbor who returned with her
sister, Ann Hovey, for a reunion with Levering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall always remember Judy as the friend I grew up with,''
Hovey said. ``We enjoyed many carefree days growing up around the
park, playing hide-and-seek, jacks, dolls and tennis. She had a
wonderful, thoughtful family who took me on many of their
outings.''
</P>
<P>
   Festivities got under way with city councilwoman Becky Nace
presenting Levering with a key to the city and a proclamation.
Vickie Shelton, athletic director for the Kansas City School
District, came with a box containing a big orange varsity ``S''
letter and the numbers, 56, indicating the year Levering graduated
from Southwest High School. Shelton had retrieved all the sports
memorabilia from Southwest after it closed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Sue Elias met Levering for the first time. Elias and her
family own the home where Levering lived from birth to adulthood
with her older brother and their parents, the late Carl and
Virginia Ade. After the program, Elias invited Levering for a
nostalgic visit to the blue-trimmed white stucco home at 6633
Edgevale Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Carpenter lived next door; he was Jean Harlow's father,''
Levering recalled. ``Dr. Carpenter and my father both played tennis
and got us out on the court. Dr. Carpenter was a dentist and a very
nice man. I remember a beautiful portrait of his daughter hanging
in his home. He and his wife were divorced and she had taken their
daughter to Hollywood'' where she became a legendary movie star and
died young.
</P>
<P>
   Married a boy from home
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Southwest, the former Judy Ade went to
Northwestern University where she met her future husband. Gordon
Levering, now 61, had graduated from what's now Shawnee Mission
North High School. He and Judy both graduated from Northwestern in
the spring of 1960 and married in December, following her
presentation as a Belle of the American Royal in the BOTAR Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the Leverings settled in Lancaster, Pa., headquarters
for Armstrong World Industries, Gordon Levering's employer for 37
years until he retired in 1996 as president of Armstrong Canada.
During his career, the family moved 13 times, living for a while in
Montreal and in London. They now reside in Stowe, Vt. But Lancaster
was where they reared their three children and where Judy Levering
founded a tennis association to promote neighborhood tennis,
particularly for children who had no access to it. She has now
taken her Lancaster experience to a national level, hoping to make
tennis available on a community basis for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe tennis teaches so many lessons,'' she said. ``It
starts with personal integrity, by simply calling a ball out or in.
If you gain the reputation of a cheater, it's hard to get rid of
it. You have to make decisions about where you are going to hit the
ball. If you win, you get the glory, but if you don't, you can't
blame anyone else. In tennis you are putting yourself on the line,
trying to do your best, but knowing you could be a loser.
</P>
<P>
   She's troubled by the trend of youth violence, by tragedies like
the one in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids are not learning how to deal with adversity,'' she
said. ``In tennis you can let out aggression in a healthy way.
You're not physically hurting anybody. When our schools are cutting
back on outside activities, we have to use our parks and public
facilities to the fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   Levering said that when she was a teen-ager, a friend, (the
late) Bill Fuhri, entered her in a competition at the Plaza tennis
courts. The opponent she drew was Lucille Davidson, a renowned
athlete from Lee's Summit who excelled in tennis, golf and
basketball. Davidson's championships included the 1949 Women's
National Public Parks Singles and the 1951 Canadian National
Singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She beat me handily,'' Levering said. ``I thought she was much
older but she could have been only in her 40s. Since then I've
played against some young girls, and I know they're thinking the
same thing about me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
