<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-INDEX--KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMINGWAY AT 100: A SPECIAL SECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bigger than life. A complicated icon. He was an American voice
in America's century: bold, exuberant, blustery. He honed his craft
at The Kansas City Star. Then he went on to war, to Europe and to
become literature's self-made man. He was not always easy to take.
Forget perfection, he told a fellow writer. Characters are not
symbols. ``Keep them people, people, people.'' In other words, all
humans are flawed. And redeemable. Four decades after his death,
and near the turn of another century, Hemingway's simple code still
rings loud and true.
Mining the lode
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas City woman's Hemingway search led to a monumental,
scholarly achievement. How Audre Hanneman's comprehensive
bibliographies were born.
</P>
<P>
   Birth and death
</P>
<P>
   Real life and anxiety echoed from here in one of his greatest
novels. As Pauline Hemingway was undergoing a complicated birth,
Ernest struggled with the tragic end of A Farewell to Arms.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway's world
</P>
<P>
   In words and pictures, here's a quick and colorful guide to
Hemingway's life and work. Suitable for framing.
</P>
<P>
   Also
</P>
<P>
   A jazzy voice in letters from KC ... Patrick Hemingway recalls a
few boisterous fatherly moments ... More family tales ... A major
biography covers his last 20 years ... A guide to some Kansas City
``Hemingway at 100'' events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
