<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-BASED-TV-2TAK     06-23 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-BASED-TV-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL WEB NETWORK HAS A MODEST GOAL: REPLACING TV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWODD, Calif. _ In the back office of a Hollywood studio,
Arlo Eisenberg, 25, with lamb-chop sideburns and fading black nail
polish, was staring at a three-inch-square video clip on a computer
monitor about in-line skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``MTV revolutionized television,'' he said, gesturing toward the
screen. ``But this will replace TV.''
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the plan of Eisenberg _ a program host _ his
colleagues and the management at the Digital Entertainment Network.
DEN's plan is to create Internet-only programming, low-budget,
niche shows aimed at specific audiences and released via streaming
video.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective audience includes gay teen-agers, fraternity
brothers, punk rockers and skateboarding 16-year-olds. Some Web
sites, including Showtime, are creating Internet-only shows on a
piecemeal basis, but DEN appears to be the most aggressive in
creating an entire portfolio of Web-based shows.
</P>
<P>
   The nine programs DEN is showing include ``Tales From the
Eastside,'' the story of gang members in Los Angeles that people in
the company refer to as `` `Beverly Hills 90210' in the 'hood.''
</P>
<P>
   It has 21 other shows under construction, including ``Redemption
High,'' which revolves around Christian teen-agers trying to hold
to their beliefs in the face of peer pressure and acne.
</P>
<P>
   DEN shows are shown in six-minute episodes displayed on a
three-inch-square box on computer monitors. Program schedules are
available at the DEN Web site (www.den.com).
</P>
<P>
   David Newman, president of DEN and former president of Walt
Disney Network Television and Touchstone Television, said his new
endeavor was truly a breed apart. In the background, a monitor
played ``Frat Ratz,'' DEN's fraternity house narrative; the pilot
involves a fraternity member getting an internship at a magazine
called Perfect 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shows are not about the same old white faces in the same
old places,'' Newman said. ``We're about why people flow to the Net
_ narrowcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is the underlying concept at DEN; if it is possible to
create radio and magazine content on the Net that caters to every
audience under the sun _ what is called narrowcasting _ why not
television-like content, too? Why not create shows that appeal to
every demographic group, until each one has its own version of
``Party of Five''?
</P>
<P>
   The DEN office in Santa Monica, Calif., could be a niche show
itself, one about young adults pursuing idealism and stock options.
Teeming with people _ half 20-something programmers and half
20-something writers, producers and aspiring actors _ the office is
a mix of Silicon Valley and Silicone Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The fusion of those worlds has produced big dreams. The staff
members here talk of moving beyond information, entertainment or
``infotainment'' to a new place, a land some of them called
telefusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad coinage,'' acknowledged Adam Solomon, the head of
marketing at DEN, leaning back in a leather chair in a DEN
conference room and sweeping his hands through carefully unkempt
hair. ``But we are the essence of forward movement. This is a new
stage of entertainment relevant to whoever you are, wherever you
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon appears to be a combination of high school guidance
counselor and Hollywood agent, underscoring a clear tension here
between the drives for creativity and cash. The parking lot may be
full of BMWs, but the staff insists it wants to create a better,
more diverse world.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said the best symbol of that dichotomy is Eisenberg, a
professional in-line skater and host of the DEN program
``Aggronation,'' about sports like extreme skating. An evangelist
for the cause of in-line skating (he calls himself the Happy Black
Jesus of Rollerblading), Eisenberg helps design the e-commerce
aspect of the Aggronation site to sell T-shirts and in-line skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He totally embraces capitalism, but underneath is a social
conscience,'' Solomon said. ``It's totally trippy.''
</P>
<P>
   The marginal nature of DEN's intended audiences makes television
production a very expensive and risky proposition. Industry
analysts say Web speeds are still too slow to support video-heavy
programming.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hardie, a senior analyst at Forrester Research, said that
the small audience size wouldn't attract the advertising revenue
necessary to support the programming. But Hardie said DEN deserved
credit for trying. DEN officials said they hoped to have 1.5
million individual users a month by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to take a lot of arrows, like any pioneer,''
Hardie said. ``They're going to be faulted for creating stuff that
doesn't measure up to the richness of TV. But TV is 60 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   DEN has addressed its financial challenges in three ways: it has
deep pockets and low-budget programs, and it augments the
programming with interactive elements that ordinary television
cannot offer, like offering archived programs accessible at any
time and several shows in more than one language.
</P>
<P>
   The deep pockets belong to Marc Collins-Rector and Chad
Shackley, who co-founded DEN; they are also the co-founders of the
Concentric Network Corp., one of the earliest ISPs. Along with
other investors, they have poured at least $40 million into the
project, Solomon said. DEN's chief executive is Jim Ritts, a former
commissioner of the Ladies Professional Golf Association and a
former chief executive of the Channel One Network, an in-school
news service of which Newman was president.
</P>
<P>
   In all, DEN intends to show 30 pilots in the coming months, but
they will be done on the cheap. Each 6-minute video segment and its
accompanying 15 minutes of interactive content _ viewers can get
information by clicking on actors or backgrounds, for example _ has
a budget of $15,000. That means shooting on location rather than
building sets, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the production values are still fairly high. ``The
Royal Standard,'' for example, about a young man using high-tech
gadgets to ascend to the Arthurian throne, was directed by Randal
Kleiser, who directed the films ``Grease'' and ``Blue Lagoon.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the talk of fusion, much of DEN's programming
follows the familiar patterns of the ABC ``After School Specials.''
The pilot of ``Tales From the Eastside,'' for instance, begins with
gang members trying to recruit a boy. ``Your barrio needs you,
Cholo,'' the lead gang member tells the boy in a bit of phoned-in
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The story line of another show, ``Fear of a Punk Nation,'' has
rival punk bands joining forces to save a struggling nightclub. It
sounds like a plot line that received a D in Screenwriting 101, but
Newman said the emphasis should be on the demographics of the cast
and viewers, not the story line. ``Suddenly young punk rockers have
a show of their own,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   This new so-called telefusion has impressed at least one
observer, Darren Carl, who says he knows a thing or two about what
makes Hollywood run. Carl, who owns Darren's Detail, a traveling
car-detailing service that has operated on numerous Hollywood lots
in the past 15 years, has become a regular buffer of the expensive
cars of DEN's 20-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be huge,'' he said while polishing a white
Range Rover in the DEN lot. ``Most of Hollywood is trying to redo
`The Flintstones' or `The Mod Squad.' They don't have a connection.
But these guys have the lifeline of youth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
