<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PHILLY-PRESERVATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAPPING EVERY STRUCTURE IN AN ENORMOUS PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 By DEBRA NUSSBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In the past, when staff members of the Fairmount
Park Historic Preservation Trust here wanted to find out about
maintenance needed on a historic building, they would consult paper
files in all sorts of offices, look at park maps that were 12 feet
by 5 feet and tap into ``Mike's Brain.''
</P>
<P>
   (That would be Mike DeSanto, who has been with Fairmount Park,
the city's park system, since 1981 and has decades of information
stored in his memory banks. He is now the facilities manager.)
</P>
<P>
   The park system has more than 400 buildings spread over 8,900
acres, encompassing one-tenth of the city's land. It was a
bureaucratic nightmare to get a handle on information that, when a
fire alarm went off at historic Mount Pleasant Mansion last March,
the fire department could not find the building. It has different
street addresses on utility company records and in park files.
</P>
<P>
   Fairmount Park was the site of the Centennial Exposition of
1876, and the park holds buildings from that fair and others,
including six National Historic Landmarks, along with everything
from Gothic chapels to snack shacks to Japanese gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is now mixing with history to address some of the
problems the park presents. Last year, staff members from Fairmount
Park Historic Preservation Trust, a nonprofit agency dedicated to
preservation and planning, began working with employees of the
Fairmount Park Commission, a governing body that oversees the park,
and the city, started creating a comprehensive inventory of
everything with a roof (or that should have a roof) in the park by
using Geographic Information System software made by ESRI
(www.esri.com), the Environmental Systems Research Institute, of
Redlands, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historic organizations are often timid about technology,''
said Barbara Silberman, director of the Preservation Alliance for
Greater Philadelphia's Heritage Investment Program, which provides
technical assistance to historic sites
(www.libertynet.org/historic). ``This is cutting-edge. It will be a
model for organizations nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The software can also help organizations find historical
connections among buildings, Ms. Silberman said. ``I would love to
have that kind of information,'' she said. ``How many places did
George Washington really sleep?''
</P>
<P>
   The software is used by 250,000 clients, who can call up maps
along with detailed pictures and information, said Paul Hartwell, a
marketing representative for ESRI in its Washington offices. Most
users, Hartwell said, are government agencies that use it to map
cities and towns for public works projects like repaving streets
and to aid in zoning and planning issues.
</P>
<P>
   The software has allowed the Fairmount Park trust to create ``an
intelligent map'' of the park, said Peter Godfrey Jr., a consultant
retained by the trust to help manage the Geographic Information
System project. So far, 371 buildings have been cataloged and 1,600
digital photographs of buildings have been taken.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Haavik, who is the project coordinator on the trust's staff
and took the digital photographs, is affectionately called ``the
GIS geek.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 320 pieces of information can be stored for each
building, including details on construction materials, architecture
styles, uses of the property, any leases and whether the building
is the responsibility of the park or another organization.
</P>
<P>
   The software will also help give consistent names to each
building. For example, Mount Pleasant Mansion, which was completed
in 1765, is sometimes mistakenly called Arnold Mansion because it
was owned by Benedict Arnold ``for about 15 minutes,'' said Amy
Freitag, executive director of the Fairmount Park trust and
planning and development administrator with the park commission.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold bought it as a wedding present for his bride, Peggy
Shippen. He was convicted of treason before they could move into
the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Some Philadelphians call it the Macpherson Mansion, named after
its original owner, a Scottish sea captain, John Macpherson.
</P>
<P>
   And the Case Building, now used for offices, is often called the
Golden Age Building, named after an organization that used to use
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Geographic Information System lists each building by its
proper name, and any other names associated with it are also noted.
</P>
<P>
   Since grant money is the name of the game in historic
preservation, the system is also expected to be helpful in tracking
down dates, architectural styles and other details that might be
required on grant applications.
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of the project will require Haavik, the
coordinator, to walk the park and inventory and photograph every
man-made item that is not a building. That would include poles,
fences, signs, furnishings, trash bins and sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park is so large and so spread out, and the information is
in such different places,'' he said. ``This has all been quite
daunting at times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
