A6805 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY-WRITERS-KAN     06-23 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-WRITERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTEMPORARY WRITERS SHARE THEIR THOUGHTS ON HEMINGWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I keep going back to the stories. I can't resist them. Even
now after I don't know how many times over the years I've read them
and taught them. They still are great. They'll stand forever, I
think. Or a dozen at least will stand forever. And that's a dozen
more than anybody else's.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Russell Banks
</P>
<P>
   Continental Drift, Cloudsplitter
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I never felt comfortable (in a readerly way) with
Hemingway's novels I did recognize flashing power and beauty in
much of the writing. In a way I think those strong, hard sentences
have stayed inside me as a writerly example to trim the sentence
down, though not to the irreducible minimum as Hemingway often
did.''
</P>
<P>
   _ E. Annie Proulx
</P>
<P>
   The Shipping News, Close Range: Wyoming Stories
</P>
<P>
   ``As a black author, I don't trust Hemingway's observations on
race. Not at all. And I get a bit nervous when he thumps his chest
to show his masculinity. Having said all that, I must confess that
I appreciate his attempts, flawed as they may be, to deliver the
culture of men in literature _ specifically the culture of the
sportsman, and I'm sure I felt confident about publishing three
stories that explore the world of the Asian martial arts precisely
because Hemingway made it OK for a male writer to address, without
apology, those time-honored male activities that give men a ``rite
of passage.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Middle Passage, Dreamer
</P>
<P>
   ``In a book like For Whom the Bell Tolls, you get the American
who goes abroad and seems to understand everything a bit too
quickly. There is that kind of desire to be a part of that foreign
place. It's understandable that he wants to be a part of it,
whether it's Cuba or Spain. There is an assumption that he can
articulate that place that doesn't work for me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Ondaatje
</P>
<P>
   The English Patient
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have found in reading and rereading his fiction and
nonfiction is a man deeply tied to the land. He was desperate to
find a sense of wildness, not only in the environment he chose to
inhabit but in himself. ... I also think his view of women and
gender is much more complicated than we are led to believe in the
popular culture.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Terry Tempest Williams
</P>
<P>
   Refuge: An Unnatural History of Family and Place
</P>
<P>
   ``The length of sentences, the sound of words, word choices,
it's all sound. It all happens in the mind's ear. And Hemingway was
a master controller of the mind's ear. He could make in the mind's
ear a kind of solemn incantation that had a moral valence to it. In
the way that Gregorian chant or chanted Tibetan mantras have their
sound, Hemingway has a kind of moral resonance.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Stone
</P>
<P>
   Outerbridge Reach, Bear and His Daughter: Stories, Damascus Gate
</P>
<P>
   Note: Quotes compiled by Steve Paul, from an article by him that
originally appeared in the centennial issue of The Hemingway Review
(Vol. 18, No. 2), an international scholarly journal published by
the University of Idaho Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6806 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-START-UP-GAME-REV     06-23 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-START-UP-GAME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A CYBER-MOGUL AT 25? YOU CAN DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.C. HERZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Web site cascades onto your screen. The design is slick. The
content is impressive. The rhetoric is mesmerizing: ``You dream of
creating your own business. You're fascinated by the high-tech
industry, where fortunes are made and lost as businesses scramble
to keep up with the latest technological innovations.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a pitch for The Wall Street Journal Online, or Fast
Company or TheStreet.com, or electronic banking or corporate
E-commerce ``solutions'' for small businesses. It's the teaser for
a game: Start-Up, a simulation that lets armchair Web moguls play
the role of a young, high-tech entrepreneur en route to the IPO
sweepstakes. ``If you succeed in doing so,'' the pitch continues,
``you'll destroy your competition and become the virtual Bill Gates
of the 21st century!''
</P>
<P>
   Start-Up is millennial Monopoly, and its greedy, high-strung,
go-go thrills derive from a skillful combination of reality and
fantasy. The goal of the game is to build an empire with the next
hot gadget _ a plausible scenario in the world of Palm Pilots and
Startac phones. Your products just happened to be sleeker and
sexier than anything in today's market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the hypothetical game console comes with a
high-bandwidth modem and browser for downloading DVD games (think
of it as Dreamcast Plus). The digital set-top box is also a network
computer with online program recording, playback and storage.
</P>
<P>
   Further down the pike of feasibility, Start-Up's personal
digital assistant is a mobile phone that transmits data, video and
voice over the future high-bandwidth Internet 2. The operating
system (Start-OS) includes voice recognition software (the phone is
held facing you, rather than against your ear). You can manufacture
this device with a small display that holographically projects a
full-size virtual screen image, but for the average road warrior, a
backlit LCD will do.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've designed and manufactured your gizmo, you have to
figure out how to sell it. Here, the role-playing vaults completely
over the top. All of the charts, bar graphs and marketing readouts
would look fabulous in a corporate Powerpoint presentation. There
are axes and usage curves and stick figures arrayed in quadrants
(so it must be scientific), and it's all backed up with tables of
information about sales volume from real-world retail channels _
Comp USA, Wal-Mart, America Online. Consumer research! Revenue
growth! Percentages! In color!
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to dominate your market, you have to identify
potential partners. So it's imperative to keep abreast of the
latest headlines, which are downloaded onto your desktop
``Bomberg'' terminal. The Bomberg Newswire is displayed on a box
that is much sleeker and sexier than its real-world counterpart
(and, needless to say, the graphic design is better). But the
headlines are plausible:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fujitsu to Announce High-Speed Video Processor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``China to Expand Free Trade Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``American Investors Flush With Funds: New York _ U.S. venture
capital investment last year surpassed any previous record, with
private companies receiving $24.4 billion. `The ever-increasing Dow
has left investors flush with funds _ there's no shortage of
capital out there for the entrepreneur with a good idea,' says Ian
Leming of investment house Goldsachs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. One can dream.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as you're dreaming, you might as well be plotting
world domination in a beautifully appointed office where you can
look up from the flat screen atop your beveled glass desk to gaze
out the window at skyscrapers _ the World Trade Center, from the
looks of it.
</P>
<P>
   The old Chanel commercial springs to mind: Share the Fantasy.
And that's appropriate, considering that the designers of Start-Up
are not scruffy, ill-groomed geeks in Silicon Valley; they're
French businessmen on permanent vacation from previous careers in
finance and management consulting.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Montecristo Multimedia, started with Virtual
Trading, a simulation of international capital markets designed for
a European Commission forum on the Euro. In short order,
Montecristo souped up the product, packaged it with an educational
guide to financial markets and sold it to universities and business
schools across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The game spawned a robust online tournament scene and a sequel:
Wall Street Trader '99, written in English and subsequently
translated and distributed throughout Western Europe. Aiming at
business schools, financial institutions and investment groups, the
little company struck deals with AOL Europe, Yahoo and (cough,
cough) Bloomberg. It set up a Web site affiliate program. It
started moving and grooving like the caffeine-chugging,
equity-building, high-tech poster child in Start-Up.
</P>
<P>
   The glass desks and flat screens have yet to arrive. ``We moved
last summer from a very old _ fourth floor without elevator _ small
flat to a bigger and more convenient location but we are still
miles away from the look of the interface,'' said Jean-Cristophe
Marquis, Montecristo's co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for our environment compared to Silicon Valley,'' said D.M.
Crimmins, Start-Up's chief scenarist, ``well, you know, this is
Paris, not San Jose. One-hundred-hour weeks? In Europe, that's
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the civilized Continental workweek, Montecristo
has a goal in common with countless companies in the faceless
industrial parks of Northern California and with the company in its
own game. ``In Start-Up,'' Marquis said, ``you win if you are the
market leader, which means that you have more than 50 percent of
market share. Theoretically, you can win without going public, but
I doubt that anyone would win the game without going public. Which
is our own philosophy in the real business as well.''
</P>
<P>
   So if one of the big French game publishers called up and said,
``Bonjour, we'd like to buy your company,'' that wouldn't be
acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said after a long pause, ``you haven't mentioned
the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Start-Up, published by Montecristo Multimedia; CD-ROM for
Windows 95 and 98. Demos are at www.montecristo-multi.com; the full
version, $49, goes on sale in October.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
