   KOSOVO-MARINES (Dateline TK) _ U.S. Marines manning a checkpoint
in Kosovo are shot at by unknown persons came and then returned
fire, killing two people. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BORDER (Planeje, Yugoslavia) _ Syl Shigjeqi stepped into
the shower Monday through a hole in the wall of his house, up a
ramp of rubble, over the faucet's skeleton, a shaving brush, soap
and, somehow, teacups. There is no shortage of destruction in
Kosovo, but here it is possible to see what NATO's bombs added to
it. This village and others nearby are at the foot of Mount
Pastrik, where some of the most furious fighting of the war took
place. At the time, refugees crossing the border into Albania could
actually hear the NATO bombs whistle down. Now some are returning
to see how powerful those bombs were. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ In a little-remarked but crucial
shift, the technocrats' 18-year domination of Mexican politics,
during which government policies have modernized the economy but
impoverished the country's working class majority, appears to be
ending. Unlike President Ernesto Zedillo (Yale Ph.D '78) and his
two predecessors, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, (Harvard Ph.D '78) and
Miguel de la Madrid, (Harvard M.A.'65) none of the four candidates
currently seeking the presidential nomination of the governing
party, the PRI, which has won 11 straight presidential elections
here, are technocrats. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
