<P>
   SCOTUS-STATES'-RIGHTS (Washington) _ State governments cannot be
sued against their will in state courts by people seeking to
enforce some federal right, the Supreme Court said Wednesday in a
major decision on states' rights. In a richly written 5-4 ruling,
the court said that the Constitution's ``structure and history''
shields states not only from being sued in federal courts, but also
makes them immune from individuals' state court lawsuits seeking to
enforce a federal right. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
