<P>
   CALIFORNIA-SCHOOL-AID. Why are California's poor school children
getting hundreds of millions of dollars less in federal aid each
year? The main answer is an obscure amendment inserted by Sen. Tom
Harkin, D-Iowa, into a 1997 spending bill, which penalizes states
like California that annually gain schoolchildren. The provision,
called ``hold-harmless,'' has prevailed partly because the state's
congressional delegation hasn't worked well together, partly
because of federal budgetary dynamics, and partly because big
states are outnumbered in the Senate. But all that may change this
fall, when Congress votes on its yearly education spending bill.
(900 words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-V-CHIP (FOR THE HOLLYWOOD REPORTER). Media industry
officials joined citizen groups and government representatives to
unveil a campaign to educate parents about the V-chip (300 words.)
By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-PEAKS-BILL. Some 18,000 acres in southwest Colorado
would be designated as wilderness under the Spanish Peaks
Wilderness bill that is scheduled for a hearing today before the
Senate Committee on Energy and Natural Resources. If passed, it
would be Colorado's first wilderness bill in six years. (500
words.) Sara Kugler
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-BELLUSH. James Bellush came to Congress this week
calling for his wife's accused killer to be brought to the U.S.
from Mexico to face justice. But all Bellush feels he came away
with after testifying before a House panel looking into the brutal
1997 murder were ``empty words.'' (400 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-NORWOOD-HEALTH. As things heat up on Capitol Hill with
Democrats in both chambers pushing for a debate on health care
reform, Georgia Republican Charlie Norwood is making some advances
of his own within his party. Dr. Norwood on Tuesday told House
leaders that he was not willing to compromise key parts of his
health care legislation just to please them. Because they could not
secure Norwood's support, the leaders pulled their competing bill,
which Norwood has called inadequate as far as addressing the needs
of patients. (12-15 inches.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA - RAIL - The House of Representatives on Wednesday
approved a transportation bill that includes funding for a busy
commuter rail line that connects northwest Indiana to Chicago. (300
words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-BORDER-SNOWE. Canadians crossing into the U.S. wouldn't
have to comply with tougher border restrictions under an
immigration amendment sponsored by Sen. Olympia Snowe. (400 words.)
Sara Kugler
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND-OLYMPIC. Bethesda native Todd Sweeris has set his
sights on winning an Olympic medal in table tennis following his
disappointment in the 1996 Games in Atlanta. (750 words.) By Matt
Swenson
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA-SERVICE. Liliam Lujan-Hickey of Las Vegas was honored by
Good Housekeeping magazine for her work in public service. (400
words.) By Tiffany Lynch
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-GAME-SANTORUM. Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., is the
only senator who will play in the 38th annual congressional
baseball game. (600 words.) By Lisa Fine
