<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY-RESOURCES-K     06-23 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-RESOURCES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME HEMINGWAY RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In addition to True at First Light and Michael Reynolds'
biography, Ernest Hemingway: The Final Years, these new, reissued
and forthcoming books will be of interest to Hemingway aficionados
this year.
</P>
<P>
   - Ernest Hemingway: An Illustrated Biography, by David Sandison
(Chicago Review Press; $24.95). A thematic tour through Hemingway's
life using some well-chosen, rarely seen photos.
</P>
<P>
   - Picturing Hemingway: A Writer in His Time, by Frederick Voss
(Smithsonian National Portrait Gallery//Yale University Press;
$35). A very visual catalog of an exhibit running this summer in
Washington, D.C., including Hemingway in photos and paintings, as
well as original book jackets and other memorabilia. Includes an
essay by Michael Reynolds on ``Hemingway as American Icon.''
</P>
<P>
   - Ernest Hemingway A to Z: The Essential Reference to the Life
and Work, by Charles M. Oliver (Facts on File, $50 hardcover;
Checkmark Books//Facts on File, $17.95 paperback). An encyclopedia
of Hemingway facts and reader's guide to all his works, with plot
summaries and descriptions of characters, place names, phrases and
numerous other things.
</P>
<P>
   - At the Hemingways, by Marcelline Hemingway Sanford (University
of Idaho Press; $39.95). This new edition of the memoir by one of
Ernest's sisters _ first published in 1961 _ includes the bonus of
nearly 50 years of letters between them, most of which have never
been published before. The letters include several that Hemingway
wrote during his newspaper stint in Kansas City in 1917-18.
</P>
<P>
   - Everybody Was So Young: Gerald and Sara Murphy: A Lost
Generation Love Story, by Amanda Vaill (Broadway Books; $15
paperback reissue). A portrait of a fascinating couple around whom
many creative people orbited in the Paris and Riviera of the '20s
and '30s.
</P>
<P>
   - The Hemingway Women, by Bernice Kert (Norton; $16.95
paperback). Reissue of a widely respected group biography of the
wives and other women in Hemingway's life first published in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   - Papa Hemingway, by A.E. Hotchner (Carroll &AMP; Graf; $13.95
paperback). Reprint of the 1966 memoir by a noted Hemingway pal.
</P>
<P>
   - Hemingway vs. Fitzgerald: The Rise and Fall of a Literary
Friendship, by Scott Donaldson (due in September from Overlook
Press; $26.95). A fresh look at the writing duo from a noted
scholar and biographer.
</P>
<P>
   - Bullfighting, Sport and Industry, by Ernest Hemingway (Meeker
Publications, Sacramento, Calif; 916-448-0789). This
limited-edition collectible (editions at $125 or $300) reprints an
article by Hemingway originally published by Fortune magazine in
March 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   - The Paris Pilgrims, by Clancy Carlile (Carroll &AMP; Graf; $25). A
novel that attempts to re-create Paris in the early 1920s as
Hemingway, Pound, Joyce and others were beginning to make their
mark.
</P>
<P>
   - The Crook Factory, by Dan Simmons (Avon; $24). A spy thriller
loosely based on Hemingway's counterespionage activities against
the Germans in Cuba and the Caribbean during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web
</P>
<P>
   - The Ernest Hemingway Foundation of Oak Park:
hemingway.org//Hemingway//index.html. The site of the Hemingway
birthplace and museum includes history and a good collection of
links to other Hemingway sites.
</P>
<P>
   - The Ernest Hemingway Collection at the John F. Kennedy
Library: www.cs.umb.edu//jfklibrary//hemingway_menu.html. A
utilitarian site for serious students and scholars, but including a
well-done biography and other materials.
</P>
<P>
   - Hemingway at The Kansas City Star:
www.kcstar.com//aboutStar//hemingway//ernie.htm. A guide to
Hemingway-related places in Kansas City plus text of stories he
wrote for this newspaper in 1917-18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
