<HEADLINE>
A SELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hemingway may have set an unbreakable record among American
writers _ if not all writers _ for publishing new books in each of
eight successive decades. (Except where noted, all books were
published originally by Charles Scribner's Sons.)
</P>
<P>
   - In Our Time, 1925 (Boni &AMP; Liveright)
</P>
<P>
   - The Torrents of Spring, 1926
</P>
<P>
   - The Sun Also Rises, 1926
</P>
<P>
   - Death in the Afternoon, 1932
</P>
<P>
   - A Farewell to Arms, 1933
</P>
<P>
   - Green Hills of Africa, 1935
</P>
<P>
   - To Have and Have Not, 1937
</P>
<P>
   - The Fifth Column and the First 49 Stories, 1938
</P>
<P>
   - For Whom the Bell Tolls, 1940
</P>
<P>
   - Across the River and Into the Trees, 1950
</P>
<P>
   - The Old Man and the Sea, 1952
</P>
<P>
   Published posthumously
</P>
<P>
   - A Moveable Feast, 1964
</P>
<P>
   - By-Line: Ernest Hemingway, 1967
</P>
<P>
   - Islands in the Stream, 1970
</P>
<P>
   - The Nick Adams Stories, 1972
</P>
<P>
   - Ernest Hemingway: Selected Letters, edited by Carlos Baker,
1981
</P>
<P>
   - The Dangerous Summer, 1985
</P>
<P>
   - The Garden of Eden, 1986
</P>
<P>
   - The Collected Short Stories: the Finca Vigia Edition, 1987
</P>
<P>
   - Ernest Hemingway: Complete Poems, edited by Nicholas
Gerogiannis, 1992 (University of Nebraska Press)
</P>
<P>
   - True at First Light, 1999
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
