A6841 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY-ERROR-KAN &LR;      06-23 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-ERROR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMINGWAY MAKES A MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PAUL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the fiction writer's prerogative to change facts, but
somewhere in the Hemingway annals an apparent fact became etched in
stone and no one noticed it was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In writing and recollections by him and others of his work at
The Kansas City Star in 1917-18, the stories always refer to Police
Station No. 4 on 15th Street as being part of Hemingway's beat. It
has always been identified that way in newspaper stories, books and
reference works. But Hemingway (and the others) were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You came to the Union Station from the Fifteenth Street Police
Station across a long viaduct,'' Hemingway wrote in the previously
unpublished manuscript fragment that is the subject of the
accompanying story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I covered the short-stop run,'' Hemingway told a biographer,
Charles A. Fenton, in 1952, ``which included the 15th Street police
station, the Union Station and the General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ernest was on the paper here,'' staff member and
columnist Landon Laird told Fenton in the early '50s, ``he was
always bouncing up to the now departed No. 4 police station at 15th
and Walnut to ride squad cars with Officer Bauswell and others.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that by October 1917, when Hemingway joined the
staff of the newspaper, the station had moved.
</P>
<P>
   According to city directories of the period and other documents,
the No. 4 station was located at 1430 Walnut, or the northwest
corner of 15th and Walnut, as late as 1915. But according to the
directory for the next year, 1916, Police Station No. 4 was located
at 115 W. 19th St. The building still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the correction to Monroe Dodd, assistant managing editor
for production and special projects and one of our resident
historians (he edited Kansas City: An American Story, which is
being published this summer by Kansas City Star Books). Dodd's
curiosity was piqued enough by the manuscript fragments that he did
something no one else apparently had ever done: He checked it, as
we say, finding the address discrepancy in the city directories.
</P>
<P>
   Further research led me to the historic inventory of the Kansas
City Landmarks Commission, which pointed back to a story in, of all
places, The Kansas City Star. The story was about how the Walnut
Street and Southwest Boulevard stations would consolidate into the
renovated two-story building at 19th and Baltimore: ``New Police
Station Opens Today,'' read the headline. The date: July 29, 1916.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HI-END-AUDIO-ART-     06-23 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HI-END-AUDIO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME THEATER INFILTRATES HIGH-END AUDIO'S HALLOWED HALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foul winds are blowing through the hallowed halls of high-end
audio. Some members of this closely knit fraternity are crawling
into bed with the mongrels _ abandoning their principles, in the
view of their colleagues, by succumbing to the temptations of the
home theater movement.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to buy a stereo system these days. Once you pass
the all-in-one starter-system stage, you can go to Radio Shack and
buy inexpensive stereo components. Or you can enter the world of
high-end, two-channel (two-speaker) audio, where most amplifiers
use vacuum tubes and a complete audio system is expected to include
not just a CD player but also a turntable for vinyl records _ and
cost $10,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   There's little between those extremes. Home theater systems,
based around multichannel amplifiers or receivers that are supposed
to be connected to six speakers and a television set, have captured
the mainstream market whole. (Of course, these systems will also
play stereo music.)
</P>
<P>
   High-end audio manufacturers sneer at home theater as a
perversion of what they see as their near-divine mission, the
no-compromise pursuit of the perfect reproduction of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very dedicated to two-channel,'' said Dennis Had,
president of Cary Audio Design, maker of a full line of
``monoblock'' amplifiers (you need a pair of them for stereo),
which have exposed tubes so the owner can admire the glow. In the
high-end audio press, this look is called sexy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some thought in our industry that you have to get into
home theater to survive, but I don't believe that at all,'' he
added, leaning against a hallway wall at Hi-Fi 99, a convention of
high-end audio and home-theater manufacturers in Chicago last
month. Behind him, explosions, hysterical screams and automatic
gunfire roared from the Marantz room, where a home-theater
demonstration was under way, prompting Had, visibly irritated, to
step quickly down the hall and ask someone to turn down the volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've raised three kids without television,'' he said when he
returned. ``To me the whole thing is a brain retard.''
</P>
<P>
   But to some others in his industry, Had is part of the problem.
This year, Cary began selling a home-theater amplifier _ and a
solid-state unit at that. One of his distributors asked him to do
it, Had grumbled.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in trying to come to grips with home theater. Up
and down the halls of the Palmer House Hilton, where Hi-Fi 99 was
staged, manufacturers of expensive audio equipment faced up to a
disquieting reality. To draw a crowd at the show, they had to put
in a television set, preferably a large projector, and show an
action movie, using their expensive equipment to play the bangs,
booms and blasts on the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   While home theater companies assert that the quality of their
products is now quite high, the audio companies, particularly
amplifier manufacturers, argue that home theater equipment just
doesn't sound as good as their own, sonically pure devices, most of
which use vacuum tubes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pathetic how bad the state of the art is,'' said Geoffrey
Poor, sales director for Balanced Audio Technology. The company's
best-known product is a monoblock tube amplifier with eight tubes
that produce 120 watts of power; a pair costs $9,900. Balanced
Audio Technology has 12 employees and sells 20 to 40 amplifiers a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, home theater is compelling,'' Poor conceded, but he added
that his audio equipment could give the listener a more stimulating
l experience. ``Sit in a room, turn the lights out and listen,'' he
advised. Then said: ``We're not ignoring an obvious reality. Let's
be frank. Our whole engineering effort in 1999 is dedicated to
designing a multichannel amp.'' In other words, a tool for home
theater.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the high-end manufacturers succumb, they insist that
their pure, two-channel systems sound far better _ better even than
the multichannel products now being marketed by their brethren. So
I decided to put this to a test by listening, side by side, to a
first-class two-channel product and to a high-end home theater
amplifier.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is Vacuum Tube Logic. ``Pure Tube'' is the company's
slogan. Vacuum Tube Logic's amplifiers are perfect representatives
of the two-channel audio ideal. Stereophile magazine, the voice of
high-end audio, rates this company's MB-185 monoblock amplifier
among the best of its kind. A pair costs $5,500, the price point
where the worlds of high-end audio and home theater meet.
</P>
<P>
   These are tube amplifiers, of course. The tubes are visible,
though they are behind a cage. So in the lexicon of the high end,
these amps may not be fully sexy, but they do show a little leg.
(Compare that with the Nagra VPA's, $13,000 monoblock amplifiers. A
pair of large, plump tubes project from the top. You can look, but
don't touch. The tubes heat up to 535 degrees Fahrenheit.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the other side for this comparison is the Madrigal Corp.,
maker of high-end monoblock amplifiers that many in the industry
view as solid-state reference standards. (A pair weighs 435 pounds
and costs $35,000.) A newer arm of the company makes home-theater
equipment, including the Proceed Amp 5, a five-channel solid-state
device that is a mere 119 pounds and costs $5,000. It's intended
for both movies and music. Stereophile Guide to Home Theater rates
this one among the best of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Luke Manley, president of Vacuum Tube Logic, is one of the few
high-end manufacturers who have not succumbed to home theater. ``We
don't have a TV in our home,'' he said, but he added that he would
happy if his amplifiers were used in a home-theater system. ``We'll
make as many monoblocks as you need _ two, five, seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Glazier, president of Madrigal, said: ``I absolutely do not
agree with the notion that there is anything limiting about making
a multichannel amplifier, beyond the limits of the company
designing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies lent me samples for this sybaritic comparison of
the best of home theater versus the best of two-channel.
</P>
<P>
   I first listened to the two amplifiers in sequence, playing a
piece of music using the Vacuum Tube Logic monoblocks, then playing
it again using two of the five channels on the Proceed Amp 5.
Later, I used one channel from one amplifier to power the left
speaker and one channel from the other to power the right speaker.
Then I played a piece of music in mono, turning the balance control
quickly from left to right to compare the performance of the
different amplifiers on difficult passages.
</P>
<P>
   The first conclusion from all this was that both products were
magnificent performers _ far better sounding than the notably less
expensive amplifier I usually use. For anyone who thinks all
amplifiers sound the same, this proved to me that they don't. And
in fact, there were differences even between these two high-end
products.
</P>
<P>
   Music played through the Vacuum Tube Logic amplifiers sounded
softer, sweeter and generally warmer in tone. But music played
through the Proceed amp was sharper, more precise and detailed. And
in the end, which amplifier sounded best was a purely subjective
matter of taste.
</P>
<P>
   For most music, I preferred the Vacuum Tube Logic equipment,
which is intended primarily for music. But on other pieces, the
Proceed amplifier for home theater sounded better.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the differences were subtle at best, and they will
not be heard at all unless the amplifiers are used in a
sophisticated audio system. But it is subtle differences like these
that fuel passions and drive careers in the audio industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the economics of the industry _ and sometimes-hidden
appetites of its leaders _ insure that more high-end audio
companies will slide into the home theater market.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Huey of Monarchy Audio was showing the company's SE-100
Delux Mono-block amplifier at the show _ without the aid of a
television set. ``Personally I'm not into this home theater
thing,'' Huey said. ``Anything associated with television doesn't
interest me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he conceded, his company is about to make a
home-theater amplifier _ five monoblocks strapped together. ``The
owner of the company wanted to do it,'' Huey said. ``He said it
would be nice to have one at his home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
