<HEADER>
A6853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-HOUSE-NYT &LR;      06-23 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TOWN NEAR NEW WORK WONDERS: IS THE FIRST LADY COMING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH SALEM, N.Y. _ As the rumors drift along tiny Main Street
here, like a fog that just won't lift, the citizens of this bucolic
town are gearing up for the onslaught of stone-faced Secret Service
personnel, paparazzi and television vans.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about Hillary Rodham Clinton's new house.
</P>
<P>
   And although the White House swears there is no new house _ at
least not yet _ Mrs. Clinton is widely believed to be interested in
Westchester County, and some residents here are convinced that
North Salem is just the place for the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone heard the wife of a caretaker talking in line in a
supermarket, maybe it was in Katonah, about how somebody working
for Hillary _ or having something to do with somebody who did _ was
coming to look at some property in town,'' Cipa Dichter, the
pianist, who lives in North Salem, said a bit breathlessly. ``We're
all so excited.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a personal assistant to the first lady did come to
North Salem, to check out the contemporary stone lodge of David
Liederman, the David of David's Cookies and the owner of Chez Louis
restaurant in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of Hillary's,'' Liederman said, ``so I called up
and offered my house.'' (After all, he has a couple of others.)
Initially, he offered it just for a vacation in August. Before
long, it was being scrutinized for a yearlong rental, so Mrs.
Clinton could establish residency for her putative Senate run, and
get a feel for the neighborhood, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Mrs. Clinton came to videotape the house and its
insides, the restaurateur said. But just when the Liedermans were
getting ready to break the news to the children and call the
movers, the word came back: too rustic.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as Liederman tells it, the first lady might have thought
his 40 foot-long kitchen and adjacent dining/sitting room were
unsuitable for fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kitchen is huge and all open,'' said Ms. Dichter, who with
her husband, Misha, has been a guest in the house many times. ``I
don't even know where the living room is. You want to be able to
close off the kitchen and entertain in the living room.''
</P>
<P>
   The house is also ``pretty close to the road,'' explained Ms.
Dichter, a close friend. ``Maybe Hillary should have something back
from the road,'' she continued, ``maybe behind a gate. People think
maybe the security wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   In an informal poll of real estate brokers in northern
Westchester, security is listed as a major concern of the Clintons
_ or a probable major concern, since few admitted to having been
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that she and I have talked,'' began Rhett Mitchell, the
owner of Merritt Associates in Larchmont, N.Y., ``but with the
carpetbagger thing and all, I imagine she'd want to live within her
means and get something that isn't too flashy.'' Mitchell and other
brokers speculated that Mrs. Clinton might want to live in one of
the communities in Westchester with gates and guardhouses, places
like Premium Point in New Rochelle and Manursing Island in Rye.
</P>
<P>
   (On Wednesday, Mayor Timothy Idoni of New Rochelle _ a Democrat
_ said he had written the first lady a letter, extolling the
virtues of his city. ``We have a 185-man police force in 10 square
miles, and we're home to 20 ambassadors,'' he said. ``We'd be
honored to have her.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton has to be careful, Liederman said: ``She can't
live in any community that excludes anybody or is too fancy.''
</P>
<P>
   One broker is known to have the inside track _ sort of: Jerome
Billingsley's brother was Bill Clinton's campaign manager when he
ran for president of the freshman class at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   But even Billingsley, who owns Frances Billingsley Real Estate
in Katonah, professed to be in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're looking,'' he groused, ``but you have to go
through a chain of command. They've seen our ads and called our
office, but we haven't seen her. We send things, and we don't hear
back.''
</P>
<P>
   How about using his Friends of Bill connection?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never asked,'' he said. ``I just might, though. As soon
as we get off the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone wants the first lady to move to his or her
community. ``It's turned out to be a very controversial thing,''
Ms. Dichter said. ``People around here feel very strongly _ one way
or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Feelings were also mixed when rumors hit New York City co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, they don't have a stitch of furniture,'' said one
socialite, a Democrat. Not only that, but the Clintons ``really
don't have any money at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it might be tough to pass a Park or Fifth Avenue co-op
board. In co-ops, even renters have to pass the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard she's had some problems in the city,'' said Mitchell,
the Larchmont agent.
</P>
<P>
   But Dolly Lenz, Sotheby International Realty's top-selling
broker, said she doubted that Mrs. Clinton had gotten anywhere near
a real estate broker, let alone a co-op board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty people told me she'd looked at an apartment at 30 E.
85th St, but I called the doorman, and it turns out she was just
visiting somebody,'' Ms. Lenz said.
</P>
<P>
   But she agreed, nonetheless, that it might be tough for
president and Mrs. Clinton to pass muster with one of the city's
ultra-difficult boards _ or even those that aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe a town house,'' she said. ``They wouldn't have a chance
of getting into 99 percent of the co-ops. And they might even run
into a snag with a condo.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's a Secret Service nightmare,'' she said. ``It
really disrupts a place, and any sophisticated board would know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   How about North Salem, a 75-minute train ride on the Metro North
commuter line, a horsy town, with everything from hidden estates to
raised ranches with Rubbermaid mailboxes _ along with a sprinkling
of celebrities and a reputation for privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I could see,'' Ms. Lenz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
