<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASTE OF THE FUTURE: WHAT 2000 HOLDS FOR FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - We've been browsin' 2000.
</P>
<P>
   To show you there will be life after Y2K food storage, to
convince you that you won't be stuck eating canned green beans in
darkness forever, and to put ourselves out on a proverbial, very
shaky limb (it's a hard thing, harnessing time), we bring you the
food fads of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Good news is: We'll still eat.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the far-fetched futuristic meal-replacement pill dreamed
up and anticipated by Hollywood will not be revolutionizing
culinaria.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news is: We'll eat a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The date won't be the only thing getting rounder as the zeroes
roll over on Jan. 1. According to David Pursglove, an industry
professional in Washington, D.C., who has accurately forecast food
fads since 1963 using a tried-and-true number-crunching system,
food shoppers and restaurant patrons also will be getting fatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will continue to care less and less about health and
nutrition, just wanting good taste,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at the Food Marketing Institute, the food industry's
trade association, are reporting the same trend in their research.
</P>
<P>
   So, what glories will we be gorging on?
</P>
<P>
   Blueberries, for one. Pursglove says they'll soon be replacing
the cranberry as the national favorite fruit flavor. According to
his forecast system, which predicted such crazes as wraps and
smoothies, they've been the No. 2 fruit for a while. They'll trump
cranberry when the public starts to be more aware of already
published medical research that shows blueberries act similarly to
red wine in reducing heart-attack risks. So look for
blueberry-sauced chicken and blueberry chutney, chutney being a
trend of the future itself.
</P>
<P>
   We've included recipes for these and other food fads so you can
get a hop on being hip.
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove's crystal ball also says that the sun-dried tomato
will fade in favor of the sun-dried banana, which will find its way
into mainstream dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare, expensive, and putatively healthy,'' says
Pursglove.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Zen in the kitchen. Restaurant menus will start
incorporating this to appease the growing American following of
this far-eastern philosophy, even though it may mean no more than
adding Zen to the name of a dressed-up tofu dish.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of soy, bean curd is growing through the roof. Thanks
to the recent announcement by the Food and Drug Administration that
listed soy's glories, it will find its way more and more into the
mainstream, and in very creative ways. Think chocolate soy
martinis, berry soy smoothies and soy-based hot fudge sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, creativity itself will be an obvious trend, according
Art Siemering, who authors and distributes a forecast publication
called ``Trend/Wire'' that is read and regarded by such industry
leaders as Starbucks Coffee and Williams-Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get past Y2K, provided something terrible doesn't
happen, there is going to be a great feeling of confidence washing
over people,'' he says. ``We're going to make a great leap, there
will be a general sense of possibility, and this unleashes
creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   The coffee industry is certainly feeling innovative. According
to Pursglove, toasted bran and chicory will replace the coffee bean
for the brew of choice. Actually, we've been drinking them for a
while in Postum and Luzianne Tea, we just didn't know it. Soon, we
will.
</P>
<P>
   The burrito fad will continue on its craze, but before it's
done, we'll see chocolate-strawberry burritos and, of course, bean
curd burritos. Two food fads will be combined in blueberry
burritos. (See recipe for blueberry wraps.)
</P>
<P>
   Wood-fired ovens will pop up in more places than pizza shops as
Americans get spoiled by the tempting taste they lend to food.
Polenta, for example, might get scooped up off the grill and taken
for a turn in these ovens. Polenta's hot now (trendsetter Monica
Lewinsky orders it all the time), but look for it to replace pasta
as the carbohydrate of choice. Why? It comes prepackaged in the
grocery store and it's really, really good.
</P>
<P>
   Also watch as Americans want to be where the wild things are.
Wild mushrooms will be even more popular; they're being advertised
in prime-time radio slots now. Wild game will also go mainstream,
and we're not talking duck. Think emu, ostrich and alligator.
Buffalo, even.
</P>
<P>
   Even normal things will start to get a bit weird. Creme brulee
will turn savory, filled with things like mussels. Baby greens will
be replaced by microgreens. Beef will be shunned in favor of
Argentinian beef, recently the subject of a ``Wall Street Journal''
weekend ode.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend is a big step towards the upscale, thanks to a
good economy. According to Siemering, there will be designer
everything, as in California Pizza Kitchen gourmet gone awry.
Enchiladas will contain filet mignon, there will be a fashionable
French fry, and Ralph Lauren may be set to launch a line of snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of snacks, here's where Siemering sees us getting
rounder. Hershey, that lovable maker of all things darkly
irresistible, is coming out with Hershey Bites, a foodstuff that
Siemering categorizes as a ``desk-drawer food.''
</P>
<P>
   They're easily hidden, he says, and consumed in small bites.
We're betting they're consumed in large, work-related
stress-induced quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Since we're on sweets, we'll progress to the final course of
this discourse: dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Even here, bean's the thing. Wagashi, an artistic Japanese sweet
confection made mostly from bean paste, will become as popular as
its cultural counterpart, sushi. Wagashi will start to make a major
showing in Japanese restaurants by the end of the year. By 2000, it
will be in upscale grocery stores like Trader Joe's and, as a true
food fad of the future, available online: Wagashi.com, where you
can buy kits to make this sweet at home, is set to be launched
soon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach writer Jaimee Rose at (602) 444-2243 or at
Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RECIPES &QL; 
 &QL; 
Blueberry-Onion Sauced Pork Tenderloin &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From the North American Blueberry Council) &QL; 
 &QL; 
3/4 to 1 pound pork tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup port wine or sweet sherry
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh or frozen blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler. Broil pork, turning occasionally, until cooked
through, about 20 minutes. Remove to a platter; cover to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a large skillet over medium-high heat, melt the
butter. Add onions, salt and pepper; cook until onions are golden,
about 10 minutes. Add sugar; cook until onions are caramelized, 3
minutes longer. Add port, balsamic vinegar, blueberries and
tomatoes; bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat. Thinly slice pork and serve with sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 290 calories, 11 g fat, 22 g
carbohydrates, 22 g protein, 439 mg sodium, 34 percent calories
from fat.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Blueberry Dessert Wraps &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From the North American Blueberry Council) &QL; 
3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups frozen or fresh blueberries, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 package (8 ounces) light or lowfat cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup confectioners sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Eight 7-inch flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Prepare sauce: In a small saucepan combine sugar and cornstarch;
stir in orange juice. Cook and stir over medium heat until sauce is
clear and thickened, about 5 minutes. Stir in 1 cup blueberries and
return to a boil. Boil and stir for 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare filling: In a mixing bowl, beat cream cheese until
light. Add confectioners sugar and vanilla. Beat until smooth and
creamy.
</P>
<P>
   Assemble wraps: Spread a tortilla with about 2 tablespoons of
the cheese mixture. Place about 6 frozen blueberries across the
center of each tortilla. Roll jelly-roll style. Repeat with
remaining wraps. In a medium skillet, melt 1 tablespoon butter over
medium heat; place half of the wraps seam side down in skillet and
cook turning occasionally until evenly browned, about 3 minutes.
Remove from pan and keep warm while cooking the remaining wraps.
Serve topped with hot blueberry sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 wraps.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 234 calories, 10 g fat, 31 g
carbohydrates, 6 g protein, 27 mg sodium, 38 percent calories from
fat.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy-Based Hot Fudge Sauce &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``Cooking With Soy'') &QL; 
6 ounces (3/4 cup) silken tofu
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup plain soy milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor or blender, process all ingredients until
smooth. Pour into a medium saucepan and bring to a boil over
medium-high heat, stirring frequently. Reduce heat to low and
simmer, stirring frequently, until somewhat thickened, about 10
minutes. Remove from heat and stir in vanilla. The sauce will
thicken more as it cools. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18 servings.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 28 calories, .2 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 6 g carbohydrates, .6 g protein, 6 mg sodium, 7
percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wild Mushroom Ragout with Polenta &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Modified from the Mushroom Council's recipe) &QL; 
 &QL; 
3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup thinly sliced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces wild mushrooms, such as chanterelle, porcini or morel
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   8 slices prepared polenta rounds, cut 1/2-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a large skillet, heat oil over medium-high heat. Add onion and
garlic. Cook until onion is tender, about 8 minutes. Add mushrooms,
peppers, thyme, salt and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until
vegetables are tender, about 15 minutes. Remove from heat; stir in
chopped parsley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Meanwhile, preheat broiler. Place polenta rounds on rack in broiler
pan. Broil, 4 inches from source of heat until polenta is golden
and heated through.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, arrange polenta rounds on platter. Spoon some mushroom
mixture over each round. Garnish with parsley. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 863 calories, 8 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 184 g carbohydrates, 36 g fiber, 24 g protein, 231 mg
sodium, 7.8 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
