<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-0624     06-23 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SISTER SEARCHES FOR BROTHER, REMINDS WORLD OF PRISONERS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN-0624.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ They were just four scraggly thieves
hitchhiking on a wooded roadside, but they held clues in Albana
Koshi's desperate search.
</P>
<P>
   Through her car window, they told her they had been cutting
bread in the kitchen of a Serb jail, so they knew that 150 men from
Koshi's town had been there.
</P>
<P>
   Further, prison officials told them the men were headed north
out of Kosovo province to a city in Serbia. Finally, the thieves
said, they recognized Koshi's brother, Alban(CQ), among them.
</P>
<P>
   As the world now watches ethnic Albanian refugees return to a
NATO-controlled Kosovo, for Koshi and thousands of others from her
region the war is over but not resolved. Their relatives are
missing and, it appears, have been taken to Serbia before the Serbs
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   While many in this decimated region of southwestern Kosovo were
still sifting through the ruins of their burned homes, Koshi
started a list of 300 missing men and began searching for clues.
</P>
<P>
   The trail of the missing men leads past the sad streets of
Djakovica, to execution sites and a building filled with women and
children used as human shields.
</P>
<P>
   The search has taken Koshi, a 25-year-old architecture student,
to abandoned factories, the offices of NATO commanders and an
apprehensively accepted volunteer post with the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   This week, she began leading her community in protests to draw
attention to what may become a major lingering issue as the haze of
destruction clears in war-shattered Kosovo, the southern province
of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic. Some estimate more than
1,000 men may be still held by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Daloni Carlisle of the International Committee of the Red Cross
said her group is now negotiating in the Yugoslav capital of
Belgrade with the Serb government. It seeks a list of prisoners
that it can make public.
</P>
<P>
   However, Carlisle notes that mothers still sit outside the Red
Cross office in Bosnia, awaiting word on sons taken in the conflict
that ended there in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Time is the enemy of the missing men from Kosovo. Prisoners
released during the NATO bombing report being tortured and starved.
As Shkendije(CQ) Hoda, KLA deputy commander for information in
Djakovica says, ``I hope they won't change from prisons to death
camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Djakovica was an area of heavy fighting between the KLA and the
Serbs. The civilians paid the price of Serb revenge. Most of the
town is burned out and looted. More than 100 mass graves have been
found in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO troops entered on June 12 the destruction ended. But,
dreams of family reunions are fading away and the rumors run with
false leads about missing men.
</P>
<P>
   The petit and somber Koshi is a leader in the effort to find
them.
</P>
<P>
   She has set up shop in the KLA office now. There, encouraged by
radio requests, dozens of people come daily with information about
mass graves and missing people.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA is the best resource for information. But, Koshi is not
the military type. While others around her have camouflage and
Soviet-made Kalishnikovs, she wears jeans and resists pressure to
wear a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this,'' she says in a whisper, ``I am doing just for my
brother. I have told them that.''
</P>
<P>
   Albana Koshi was two years old when Alban was born and she has
always called him ``Locka,'' (pronounced ``LOACH-ka''). It means
``sweetheart.'' He is the only boy between two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   In a picture she carries, she is pulling his long hair back into
a ponytail to prepare for high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Serious like his sister, Alban studied economics and wants to go
into business. He stays away from politics.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother is a teacher and their father worked in a travel
agency until he lost his job five years go. They lived in a tall
stone house in the old Ottoman bazaar area of town. Koshi's
great-grandfather was born in the house more than 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bazaar was meticulously destroyed by several nights of Serb
arson after NATO began the bombing campaign. The Koshi house stands
gutted.
</P>
<P>
   The Koshis moved in with three other newly-homeless families
and, like the rest of Djakovica, stayed inside for weeks eating
bread and cheese, watching television report the bombing and hiding
from Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   After a fierce battle between the Serbs and KLA separatist
guerillas on a hill near town, the Serbs told ethnic Albanians to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   The Koshis left May 10, walking to the bus station for a ride to
southern Kosovo and, possibly, Albania. But, after a few blocks,
Serb police stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   They said they just wanted to take Alban briefly and then drop
him off at the bus station.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of the war, this was what he was afraid
of,'' Albana recalls.
</P>
<P>
   As she talks, she is preparing for her fourth meeting with
Italian NATO troops. Normally stoic, she cries when asked Alban's
parting words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'You may go. I will be back soon. Don't be afraid,'''
she says in her strained English. ``He said, 'It's OK. Don't
worry.'''
</P>
<P>
   But, Alban never showed up at the bus. He was gathered with
hundreds of other young men near a park in the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the trail gets murky. Many were taken to a small
metal shop on the edge of town, which Albana has searched
unsuccessfully for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of the prisoners' wives and children were taken nearby
and held in an appliance factory. The Serb police had been using
the factory but now they stayed out, guarding the doors with guns
from far away.
</P>
<P>
   Most suspect the Serbs hoped NATO would think the factory was
still used by the police and bomb the human shields. But, three
days later they released the women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the account of the four thieves, Koshi believes many of
the men were taken to Pec, a city in western Kosovo. From there,
some were trucked to Serbia and others sent to another Kosovo city
where some were executed.
</P>
<P>
   A survivor turned up back in Djakovica and looked at a
photograph of Alban.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he saw him in the group headed for execution. But
Koshi says Alban looks much like a cousin who is also missing.
Either one, then, may have been executed. The other would be in the
Serb prison.
</P>
<P>
   She has not told her parents about the inconclusive photo
identification.
</P>
<P>
   As she searches, life slowly returns to Djakovica, an mostly
agrarian town of about 70,000. The first few stores have reopened
and bicyclists line the streets.
</P>
<P>
   But, on any corner you can find people missing relatives and
tears come quickly when they tell their stories. Koshi looks down
the main street and knows life is not normal for the people of
Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all with broken hearts,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
