<HEADER>
A6892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPA-CHEMICALS24-COX     06-23 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-CHEMICALS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DATA ON CHEMICAL DANGERS POSES A DISCLOSURE DILEMMA
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is racing to solve a digital-age quandary:
how to inform citizens about potential chemical disasters in their
communities without giving terrorists a blueprint of ways to
exploit these industrial dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the 1990 Clean Air Act, companies that make or store
hazardous chemicals have informed the federal government about
potential disasters at more than 60,000 industrial sites across
America.
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires that this information be made public.
However, heeding advice from the FBI and other security agencies,
the Environmental Protection Agency has abandoned plans to post
these ``worst-case scenarios'' on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the Internet, a terrorist, criminal or disgruntled
employee could identify the scenarios and fine-tune an attack'' to
achieve maximum death and destruction, Robert Blitzer, a private
security analyst and former FBI counterterrorism section chief,
told a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to approve this week an amendment by Sen.
James Inhofe, R-Okla., that would suspend dissemination of the
``worst-case scenarios'' for one year except to local and state
government emergency response units.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment would also require the administration to come up
with plan for making the information available to the public but
not to terrorists around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can use the information to target potential bombing
sites,'' said Inhofe. ``You can already find information on the
Internet on how to make a bomb. The last thing we need is
information collected by the EPA being used to select targets in
communities around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1990 law, the companies were required to give the EPA
a detailed report on their five-year history of accidental
releases, emergency response plans, proximity to schools and
hospitals and the worst accidents that could happen at the
facility. Monday was the deadline for companies to submit the data.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone asks for the data, the agency has 30 days to respond,
said Kim Rubey, an EPA spokeswoman. During this period, the agency
will be working with Congress to reach a solution.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is committed to both public disclosure and national
security, she said. However, she noted that some companies may have
already voluntarily put the information out on their own Internet
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The complex issue illustrates how the Internet, which allows
instant global distribution of information, has created conflicts
between national security and free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is going to come up again,'' said Ari Schwartz, an
analyst for the Center for Democracy and Technology. ``This is just
the first case.''
</P>
<P>
   In this situation, he said, it makes more sense to have the EPA
post reliable data on the Internet rather than restrict its
distribution to paper reports, which will doubtless be posted on
private Web sites anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the best way to stop a terrorist threat _ not tell
people about the dangers, or build stronger protections'' such as
buffer zones at the dangerous sites, he asked. ``Probably the
latter.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Steinhardt, associate director of the American Civil
Liberties Union, said the Supreme Court has already ruled that the
Internet is entitled to the highest protection of free speech. He
said banning online distribution of the public EPA documents
violates the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is ``futile'' anyway, he said. ``The EPA may not put
it on the Internet, but others will.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, environmental activists have said that the Internet is
the best way to get the information to the most people who live
near the chemical facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Senate staffers said Wednesday that Congress is trying to find a
compromise acceptable to all sides.
</P>
<P>
   At a Senate hearing on the issue in March, even witnesses
raising the security concerns acknowledged the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the competing interests at stake here, between
providing the necessary information to the community, which allows
them to make informed decisions on local planning and preparedness
issues, and limiting the risk associated with the distribution of
information that can be used against those same communities in a
criminal manner,'' said Robert Burnham, chief of the FBI Domestic
Terrorism Section.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
