<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, June 24, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS CoxNet layouts are for sale over
the web, through the New York Times News Service's PageExpress
service, at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   If a budget line or story is marked with photos or graphics,
those are available from the New York Times News Service at
212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The news manager is Paul Foutch, 404-526-5429,
pfoutch(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The day news editor is Tom Oder, 404-526-5887,
toder(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The night news editor is Todd C. Duncan, 404-582-7282,
tduncan(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338, artd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   COKE-MAIN _ BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The Belgian government today
said it will lift its partial ban on Coca-Cola products once the
company has met certain conditions, including enhancing safety
measures at bottling plants. Coca-Cola Co. has accepted the
conditions, which also include a thorough cleaning of the plants
and better monitoring. Company spokesman Paul Pendergrass said the
company may be able to have its products on store shelves within a
few days. The government, however, said vending machines carrying
Coke products will still be off-limits to consumers until it is
more satisfied with their safety. Belgian Health Minister Luc Van
den Bossche said there is still a foul smell coming from some of
those machines. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-FRANCE _ PARIS _ The French government was expected to give
Coca-Cola the go-ahead to resume production at its Dunkirk plant.
But there are reports that a criminal investigation has begun, at
least at the local level, and Le Monde raised the question of
whether rat poison was the source of contamination on soft drinks
that were transported on fungicide-treated wooden pallets. (Holmes,
Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ ATLANTA _ A look at what analysts think the
decision in Belgium may mean for Coca-Cola, whose shares have been
under pressure since the crisis began more than a week a go, but
was higher this week. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: All stories moving in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHECKFREE _ The stock of Checkfree, the Atlanta-based company
that makes software for online bill transactions, dropped 16
percent on news that several large banks including First Union and
Chase Manhanttan are expected to announce today that they will form
a new company to act as intermediary to route on online bills to
bank customers. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-ADS _ Knight Ridder is preparing to transform its newspaper
Web sites into a nationwide network of regional Internet portals,
hoping to target advertising to people who use the sites as their
first stop in cyberspace. The New York Times has also announced
plans to build a portal targeting upscale users. Could be that
Knight Ridder and the NYT are trying to position them as separate
entities. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
