<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-V-CHIP24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDUSTRY TO HELP PARENTS USE NEW 'V-CHIP' TO SCREEN TV SHOWS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A campaign to help parents use TV ratings and the
new ``V-chip'' to protect children from broadcast sex and violence
was previewed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can program the V-chips to block particular programs
rated under voluntary industry guidelines according to age and
violent, sexual or profane content.
</P>
<P>
   Most cable and broadcast networks use the ratings, although the
NBC broadcast network does not use content labels and the Black
Entertainment Television cable network does not use any ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires that half of all televisions larger than 13
inches sold in the United States be equipped with the chips by July
1. The other half must be equipped by Jan. 1, 2000, and all
manufacturers are on schedule to meet the deadline, said Michael
Petricone, a spokesman for the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The V-Chip Education Project,'' a partnership of the Henry J.
Kaiser Family Foundation and Center for Media Education, will get
under way next week. It includes a series of public service
announcements, an Internet site (http://www.vchipeducation.org) and
a booklet that outline how the ratings system and V-chip work.
</P>
<P>
   The chip allows parents to create their own daily TV schedule,
said Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America and chair of the TV Parental Guidelines Monitoring Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the responsibility for using this power lies
solely in the hands of Mom and Dad,'' Valenti said at a news
conference to introduce the education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Broadcasters and the National Cable
Television Association are also participating in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Tristani, chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission's V-Chip Task Force, applauded the education effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the mother of an 18-year-old daughter and a 6-year-old
son,'' Tristani said. ``I know the concerns and frustrations of
parents who want to protect their children from material they deem
unsuitable.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
