<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING AOL FREE OF COOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID EINSTEIN   
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: On my computer at home I have successfully disabled cookies
in America Online. So imagine my surprise when I loaded AOL onto my
PC at the office, only to discover that the cookies options had
disappeared. What's the story, and is there an easy fix?
</P>
<P>
   A: The story is that the version of AOL you installed at work
doesn't give you cookie control. But you can remedy the situation
easily. Just install Microsoft Internet Explorer 5 on your office
PC (ask your systems people to do it for you or get their OK to do
it yourself).
</P>
<P>
   AOL, which comes with an earlier version of IE 4, will
automatically upgrade itself to use IE 5's preferences, including
cookie options. It's unfortunate that neither AOL nor Microsoft has
bothered to tell us about this curious relationship between the two
programs, but now you know.
</P>
<P>
   To set your cookie options, go to My AOL and choose Preferences.
Click the WWW icon, which brings up the window for AOL Internet
Properties. Tab over to Security and click the button for Custom
Level. Then scroll down until you get to the options for cookies.
</P>
<P>
   NO EXPRESS RECEIPTS
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was very much interested to learn in your column that I
could get a receipt when I sent e-mail. You showed how to do this
for Outlook and Netscape. I use Outlook Express and the
instructions provided do not apply. Can I request receipts with
Express, and if not, how do I switch from Express to Outlook?
</P>
<P>
   A: Outlook Express has no provision for receipts, which can tell
you when an e-mail message you've sent has been received and/or
opened. But hey, the program is free, so you can't complain too
much. Switching to Outlook will cost you, because that program is
part of the Microsoft Office suite (which also includes Word,
Excel, etc.) And Office is expensive. The standard upgrade version
of Office 2000 costs $250, and the full version is $450. My advice
would be to use Netscape, or maybe another free program such as
Pegasus, which also supports receipts. You can download Pegasus
from www.pegasus.usa.com.
</P>
<P>
   You know what I do sometimes when I send an important e-mail? I
include a blind copy to myself. It's not as good as a receipt, but
if I get the copy back, I at least know that the message went
through the Internet the way it was supposed to. So you might try
that as a way to put your mind at rest.
</P>
<P>
   TO BUY OR LEASE
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm wondering about different ways to finance a new PC. I
know you can purchase one over time from Gateway. Dell, on the
other hand, offers what it calls a ``personal lease'' program that
I assume is like leasing a car. Which of these options do you think
is the better deal?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm thinking that financing a computer from Gateway is a
better deal than leasing one from Dell. Either way, you'll spend
about $1,775 over two years _ $74 a month _ for a $1,500 computer.
But at the end of that time, you'll own the Gateway. With the Dell,
you'll have to pay 22 percent of the original price to buy the
computer after the lease. Also, Gateway lets you trade in your
computer for a new one (the trade-in allowance is the wholesale
value of the computer at the time of the trade-in).
</P>
<P>
   TRANSLATION UPDATE: Last time, I gave out the address of a site
run by AltaVista that offers free online translations between
English and several European languages. Some readers responded that
they couldn't access the site. Invariably, it was because they were
adding ``www'' to the address by mistake. Just enter
babelfish.altavista.com/cgi-bin/translate? and that should do it.
(Remember to include the question mark at the end.)
</P>
<P>
   On the same subject, a few readers said the site doesn't do a
great job of translating. Some of the words they used to describe
it were ``garbled'' and ``garbage.'' So maybe a software package
such as Power Translator Pro from Lernout &AMP; Hauspie ($130),
Universal Translator from Language Force ($40) and Easy Translator
from Transparent Language ($42) is your best bet after all.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK: When you conduct a search on the Internet for a
name or phrase, search engines typically go out and find thousands
_ sometimes millions _ of results that include any of your search
words. But there is a way to narrow your searches considerably.
Just enclose your search phrase in quotation marks. That tells the
search engine to look for only the exact phrase.
</P>
<P>
   David Einstein is West Coast bureau chief of Forbes Digital
Tool. Got a question about computing? E-mail it to
computerssfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-16-99 2237EDT &QL;
</P>
