<HEADER>
A6954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTERNET-THERAPY1     06-23 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-THERAPY17-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
E-therapy: Affordable advice is now a click away 
By John Keilman  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you've got a personal problem, a computer and
a credit card, Susan Wright is ready to help.
</P>
<P>
   Just head to her web site _ www.advicelink.com _ fill out a
12-question survey about your troubles and offer up your credit
card number. For $25, Wright, a licensed independent social worker
in Cleveland, will e-mail her counsel back to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been an avant garde person, so I got in (on the
Internet) very early,'' Wright says of her service, which appears
to be the only one of its kind in Ohio. ``I knew what was going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was the birth of a service known as e-therapy or
webcounseling, the delivery of mental health services over the
Internet. Its methods, many believe, will lead to permanent changes
in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether that will be for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that this will become a big area
in the future, (but) the level of involvement psychologists should
have, I don't know,'' says Cheryl Meyer, an assistant professor at
Wright State University's School of Professional Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   E-therapy is virtually unstudied and unregulated. There is
little research on its effectiveness. No licensing requirements
exist. Anyone, regardless of his qualifications, can set up a web
site and charge for his advice.
</P>
<P>
   That makes many professionals nervous. Yet for now, the boards
that license psychologists, social workers and counselors in Ohio
are leaving e-therapy alone, waiting for groups like the American
Psychological Association to decide upon standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``(E-therapy) is moving so rapidly that no one knows where we
stand at this point,'' says Barbara Garwood, a member of the Ohio
State Board of Psychology. ``It's a freedom of speech issue, it's
an interstate commerce issue, it's a restraint of trade issue, it's
a protect the public issue. Holy cow, it's complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, New Albany, Ind., counselor Ed Needham was
dropping into chat rooms on topics from computers to coffee when he
noticed a curious phenomenon: Any time he mentioned his profession,
others immediately wanted to chat privately about their problems.
</P>
<P>
   That convinced him there was a desire for web-based counseling.
He built a site and ran it for free at first, though he later
decided to charge $15 a session. He guesses he had about 50 clients
until insurance worries prompted him to end the service a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a unique dynamic,'' he says. ``... You pick up on
something that's different (from office counseling) in that it's
more focused. It's definitely more intense at times ... You're
looking at a screen, and everything else tends to blend into the
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Needham believes he was one of the first mental health
professionals to use the web for treatment, and so far, he doesn't
appear to have a great deal of company. Only 162 practitioners of
Internet counseling are listed at www.metanoia.org/imhs _ a web
site dedicated to the activity. That compares to more than 28,000
credentialed counselors in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The method appears, however, to be gaining more acceptance.
Recovery Services of Warren and Clinton Counties, a public
behavioral health services provider in Lebanon, plans to put an
automated test on its web site to help people screen themselves for
alcoholism, depression, attention deficit disorder and anxiety
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   E-therapy practitioners acknowledge that their techniques are
limited. A counselor can't read body language or hear the tone of a
person's voice, and some experts say those are crucial failings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (counseling) isn't necessarily what people are
saying, it's how they're saying it. You need to look at their
non-verbal communication, and you just don't get that with
e-therapy,'' says Dr. Peter Zafirides, a professor at Ohio State
University's department of psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   E-therapy practitioners and proponents respond that e-mail and
chat rooms have their own strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Schwambach, who does e-mail counseling from her office in
Evansville, Ind., says the form inspires focus and efficiency.
What's more, it can be less expensive for patients: They don't need
to pay for a $200 hour of counseling when all they want is a brief
answer to a single question (Schwambach, who also writes a column
for newspapers, charges $1.50 a minute for her time through her web
site, www.drjudith.com).
</P>
<P>
   She also allows her Internet clients anonymity. While that's
something she says many patients desire, Zafirides says it is a
questionable virtue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the whole premise of therapy itself, there
needs to be a human connection,'' he says. ``Some of the problems
today come from people who feel more and more alienated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I have to know the person to respond to them,''
Schwambach retorts. ``If I came upon someone having an accident, I
would not feel I have to know them to be able to help them.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... I'm more of a bottom-line person. Let's deal the matter
at hand. We have to deal with what's happening right now. And I
think most people are the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also point to the lack of research on the subject and
the dearth of laws in place to govern it. A person does not need
any special qualifications to hang out a virtual shingle, and given
the Internet's fluidity and secrecy, that's a situation some
believe will never change.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have told thousands of people, you're never going to cure
the problem, because so much of it is off-shore,'' says Randolph
Reaves, general counsel for the Association of State and Provincial
Psychology Boards. ``You can't do a damn thing about people who are
sitting on an oil rig in the middle of the ocean who wants to
practice psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   While some web counselors fear national or state regulations
could hurt their competitiveness, others say they would welcome new
rules. In the absence of such guidelines, John Grohol, who runs a
Columbus-based mental health web site, says potential patients
should exercise caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it works best for milder kinds of problems,'' he
says. `` ... I think given the seriousness of some problems,
there's too much potential for danger and negative outcomes when a
person turns solely to the Internet for intervention for serious
mental disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I think we're at the point where they require
face-to-face interaction. At this time, it's better to be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   John Keilman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-16-99 1046EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
