<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SOFTWARE-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE HEADS FOR TOP ROLE IN U.S. ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By Andrew J. Glass  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON The digital code that powers the nation's computers
provided a record $141 billion upward kick to the domestic economy,
according to a study released Wednesday by a key software trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   Given current trends, the software industry's overall share of
the U.S. economy will surpass that of car, truck and motor vehicle
makers beginning in 2000, the Business Software Alliance reported.
That would mean that software makers, led by such industry giants
as Microsoft Corp., will next year exceed the value of all other
manufacturing groups in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Flush from a year that saw overall sales rise by 17.8 percent,
most of the top executives of the 18 software firms which belong to
the group spent much of the week in closed sessions with
administration and congressional leaders, pursuing their high-tech
agenda. Since the alliance's members include an ever-shifting
universe of partners and rivals, some of the most sensitive issues
facing the industry remain out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   In opening a press conference to report how the ``software
industry has emerged as one of the fastest-growing and most vibrant
segments of the U.S. economy,'' Robert Holleyman, the trade group's
president, made it clear that no questions about Microsoft's
antitrust problems with the Justice Department and 19 states would
be in order. Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, seated to Holleyman's
left, beamed with evident pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Gates did allow, however, that ``the level of dialogue with the
Congress and the executive branch has increased quite
dramatically'' in recent years. ``The Congress,'' he added, ``is
listening to this industry very well.''
</P>
<P>
   On his appointed rounds, the Microsoft co-founder has ridden
several times past the sandstone federal courthouse on Constitution
Avenue where the antitrust trial has entered a final and, possibly,
decisive phase. But his time has been otherwise spent joining the
Democrats for their weekly policy lunch, testifying before a
Republican-led technology summit of the Joint Economic Committee
and engaging in a photo-op for a a minority youth computer
education grant.
</P>
<P>
   The receptive political climate that Gates and his fellow
industry leaders found in Washington on both sides of the aisle had
been paved by increasingly generous wallets.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-1998 campaign season alone, technology companies
contributed nearly $9 million to congressional candidates. That sum
was double the 1993-94 election total. Moreover, and the industry
seems poised to up the ante even further for the 2000
</P>
<P>
   election, according to Holly Bailey of the Center for Responsive
Politics, a watchdog group that monitors money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, high tech is becoming an increasingly
prominent contributor,'' Bailey said. ``Anything that concerns the
computer industry is getting a big ear in Congress these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides releasing the report, the software group utilized the
press session to highlight its Washington agenda. Each executive in
turn, including Gates, tackled such matters as the need for
increased copyright protection, the need to end encryption export
restrictions, the Y2K computer glitch, digital signatures and
related privacy concerns and the rapid growth of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The study commissioned from Nathan Associates revealed that in
1998, the industry
</P>
<P>
   had 806,900 employees. It now has workers in every state who
earn an average of $68,900 a year. By contrast, other workers in
the private sector earn an average of $29,800 a year.
</P>
<P>
   It also also found that spending by the industry and its
employees stimulated a major ripple effect of economic activities
in other sectors of the economy. Thus, after taking the multiplier
effect into account, the demand for software employed 2.7 million
people earning $128 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, the industry estimates that currently, one
out of every four software applications are illegally loaded on
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The trade group estimates that in 1998 software theft resulted
in 109,000 lost jobs, $4.5 billion in lost wages and $991 million
in lost tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enactment and enforcement of strong copyright laws around
the world have already reduced rampant software piracy, estimated
to cost nearly $11 billion in key global markets,'' said Holleyman.
``In just eight of the world's largest software markets, by
</P>
<P>
   reducing piracy rates from their 1992 levels to the levels
experienced in 1998, our industry was able to realize nearly $4
billion in additional software sales in these eight markets in 1998
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-16-99 1625EDT &QL;
</P>
