<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARNSWORTH-HOUSE-2TAK     06-23 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARNSWORTH-HOUSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A GLASS BOX, SECRETS ARE HARD TO KEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ How could a structure as transparent as the Farnsworth
House hold a secret?
</P>
<P>
   Yet there it was, on the caption of an old blueprint that had
sat untouched in my father's library in Chicago over the decades
since his death _ ``Bld'g: Dr. E.B. Farnsworth Residence/Location:
Plano, Illinois/Architect: Wm. Dunlap.''
</P>
<P>
   William E. Dunlap? Architect of the iconic Farnsworth House?
</P>
<P>
   What about Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, that towering figure from
the Bauhaus whose disciples remade Chicago at midcentury? Wasn't it
Mies who designed this sublime archetype of the International
Style, this crystalline wafer of space framed by two horizontal
planes, stripped of ornament, serenely afloat, its every line
apparently dictated by pure reason?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. But he did not account for the mosquitoes. They were left
for my father.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edith Farnsworth, an internist, commissioned Mies to design
a weekend retreat 60 miles southwest of Chicago, on the Fox River.
As the house neared completion in 1951, they had a bitter falling
out.
</P>
<P>
   The secret I had never known _ and this, after 20 years of
covering architectural landmarks _ was that as a result of that
fight, my father put the final touch on one of the most famous
buildings of the 20th century. This was not a story he told me,
perhaps because it involved a deception on his part. Rather, I
learned of it by finding blueprints of his design for a 9
1/2-foot-high, bronze-and-steel screening system, with elegantly
pivoting doors, that once enclosed the deck of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing of my father's role, I see the house differently now. In
fact, I can almost hear the house, or rather the effervescent
voices of my parents visiting the place as a young couple. Around
them, I imagine America hitting its stride as the darkness of war
and Depression subside: Buildings sparkle with a newfound openness
and clarity; Mies, who has made Chicago his home, is the leading
architect of this transformation, and my parents are luckily,
happily, in his orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the austerity of the Farnsworth House, I can now see its
``aura of high romance,'' to borrow the words of Lord Palumbo, a
London real estate developer, who bought the house in 1972 and
opened it to the public two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I see something else: No amount of architectural refinement can
disguise the building's quirks, its frailties, its very human
provenance _ ``my Mies-conception,'' Dr. Farnsworth called it in
her unpublished memoirs _ all of which go into making it that much
more resonant.
</P>
<P>
   Begin with the fact that its floor slab hovers five feet above
ground, held in the air by eight wide-flange steel piers, as if on
stilts. The practical point of this extravagant esthetic gesture
was to protect the house from flooding.
</P>
<P>
   But though Mies researched previous flood levels, he
miscalculated badly. The house has been inundated several times;
catastrophically in 1996, when the river reached a height of 4 feet
10 inches inside the house, shattering window walls, scattering
artwork and badly damaging the central core, within which are
concealed two bathrooms and the mechanical systems.
</P>
<P>
   Another Fox River phenomenon that Mies underestimated was the
mosquitoes. Even today, they are fierce enough to be a source of
constant complaint in the guest register.
</P>
<P>
   In Mies' design, the only way to circulate air through a house
whose walls were made of solid glass was to open two small windows
at one end and the front door at the other. Without screens around
the deck, this was an invitation to bugs.
</P>
<P>
   One summer was all that Dr. Farnsworth could take.
</P>
<P>
   There was no going to Mies for help, however. In 1951, he sued
her, claiming she owed him money. She countersued, claiming she had
been overcharged. The house cost more than $70,000, or about
$450,000 today, allowing for inflation. While that is a lot of
money, something deeper must have accounted for their animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is simplistic to say that Dr. Farnsworth wanted the
house and Mies, and Mies wanted the house and the next client, such
a summation comes as close to the heart of the matter as any
other,'' the architectural historian Franz Schulze wrote in a
history and guide to the house.
</P>
<P>
   My parents, in their mid-20s when the house was built, were
somewhere in the middle. My father had studied and taught under
Mies at the Illinois Institute of Technology in Chicago. My mother,
Beth, was a patient of Dr. Farnsworth's. They socialized with her
at parties and jazz clubs. They visited the house in Plano during
construction. And as it neared completion, they stayed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   They did not exactly sleep there, however, since they were kept
awake all night while Dr. Farnsworth's poodles, in an amorous mood,
chased around the central core as if they were on a travertine dog
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that cute?'' Dr. Farnsworth said, when my mother told
her of the disturbance the next morning. While the two women
talked, just before the architectural historian Henry Russell
Hitchcock arrived for a visit, my father recorded the scene with
his Kodak Vigilant 620 camera.
</P>
<P>
   He caught a moment of weekend-in-the-country informality
wonderfully at odds with the house's formalism: My mother is in
pajamas, Dr. Farnsworth in slacks; they lounge on the cantilevered
front steps, with cups of coffee and poodles nearby.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Dr. Farnsworth asked my mother, ``Do you
think Bill would design the screens?''
</P>
<P>
   My father was then drafting part time at $1 an hour, supported
by my mother's income as a fashion illustrator for Women's Wear
Daily. Learning of the prospect, he said, ``I'm going to call Mies
and tell him there's a way to finish the screens without going to
someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Dr. Farnsworth, my father then shared his drawings
with Mies, to be certain they met with the master's approval. At
least once, Mies was reviewing blueprints in my parents' apartment
just before the client arrived to do the same thing _ requiring
some logistical dexterity to prevent a collision between the two
warring parties in the alleyway.
</P>
<P>
   The screens were installed in April 1952, three weeks before I
was born.
</P>
<P>
   Then the battle between Mies and Dr. Farnsworth played out in
court. It appeared that my father's photographs might be called
into evidence. Sending the negatives to Mies' office, he wrote,
``Beth and I personally have no quarrel with Edith and we'd prefer
if possible that you don't use any of the shots with Beth in
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please return when the smoke clears,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke did not clear, however. After Dr. Farnsworth learned
that my father had collaborated with Mies, she never spoke to him
again. And my father, who joined the firm of Skidmore, Owings &AMP;
Merrill, did not speak to me or my brother of his work at the
Farnsworth House. He was the partner in charge of Sears Tower at
the time of his death in 1973, so there were truly bigger things to
talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Mies died in 1969 and Dr. Farnsworth in 1977, having sold the
house to Palumbo. One of the first things he did was install an
unobtrusive air-conditioning system and remove the screens. ``While
they had a practical value in terms of mosquitoes, they interrupted
the flow of space and closed in an area that was intended to be
kept open,'' he explained in a telephone conversation from London.
</P>
<P>
   After the disastrous flood of 1996 and a lesser one in 1997,
Palumbo restored the house, working with the architect Dirk Lohan,
who is Mies' grandson. The central core was rebuilt, and its blond
primavera wood panels were replaced.
</P>
<P>
   It was also in 1997 that I happened to be rooting through papers
in the Chicago apartment where my family has lived for 40 years.
That was when I found 20 Farnsworth blueprints, some with my
father's name, others bearing Mies' architectural stamp. I found
tracing-paper sketches, correspondence with the metal fabricator,
60 photos and a handwritten budget: $4,566.75, including $389.25
for the struggling young architect. My mother filled in the story.
</P>
<P>
   I found no trace of my father's work when I visited the
Farnsworth House recently for the first time. But I saw abundant
evidence that the Palumbos use the place when they are in town.
Sculptures come and go. An antique maple rocking chair sits
exotically among the svelte Mies furnishings. Wine bottles fill the
stainless-steel kitchen counter. A black Trimline telephone rests
on the bedside shelf. Family pictures line the bathroom walls.
Neckties are draped decorously inside the teak wardrobe. (Pardon
the intrusion, milord.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an intrusion,'' he reassured me, ``because it shows
the human side of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   He used to keep house more ascetically, Palumbo said, but that
created a problem. ``It was becoming a shrine,'' he said. ``It was
beginning to take itself too seriously. I thought it needed
livening up.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from comments in the guest book, the bric-a-brac is
second only to the mosquitoes as a source of annoyance. ``It is
overcluttered _ I accept that,'' Palumbo said. ``But from a human
dimension, if you want to get the flavor _ for better or worse _ of
the people who own it, there have to be things around.''
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I delight in signs that the place is inhabited, that
it is not frozen as a museum but rather breathes with the needs and
whims of its owners. After all, Mies designed a monument, but my
father first made it possible to live in.
</P>
<P>
   (The Farnsworth House is at 14520 River Rd. in Plano, Ill.,
about a 90- minute drive from Chicago. Hours: Thursday through
Tuesday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.; closed on Wednesday. Admission: $15,
including a tour of the grounds, which were landscaped by Lanning
Roper. There are sculptures by Harry Bertoia, Anthony Caro, Andy
Goldsworthy, Ellsworth Kelly, Wendy Taylor and others. Telephone:
(630) 552-8622; Web address: www.farnsworthhouse.com. Reservations
are advised, as is mosquito repellent.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
