u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DEATH-OF-DIVX-NYT     06-23 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DEATH-OF-DIVX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW TEARS ARE SHED OVER DEMISE OF DIVX 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Circuit City announced the death of Divx last week, many
people in the consumer electronics industry cheered because Divx, a
hybrid DVD, may have been the most reviled new product in the
modern history of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of consumers, and the leaders of more than a dozen
companies championing the acceptance of the conventional, or
``open,'' DVD format, fulminated for years over their fears that
Divx would confuse consumers who shy away from format wars and slow
the acceptance of DVD. Paradoxically, however, Divx actually
hastened the acceptance of DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Divx was a pay-per-view DVD format jointly owned by Circuit City
and a Los Angeles law firm. They licensed production of the players
to several companies.
</P>
<P>
   A consumer who bought a Divx-equipped DVD player could buy a
Divx movie for $4.50 and play it once. Playing it again would incur
another $3.25 charge. The most-touted advantage was that the buyer
didn't need to return the movie to the video store. So there would
be no need for late-night trips to the drop-off box and no late
fees.
</P>
<P>
   A conventional DVD that can be played endlessly sells for $15 to
$30. But such DVDs can also be rented in thousands of video rental
stores for about $3 each.
</P>
<P>
   Afraid that Divx would spawn a format war and slow the
acceptance of open DVD, competing companies, led by Warner Home
Video, opened a fierce marketing campaign for DVD a year ago _ just
as the first Divx players went on sale.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster and other video-rental chains were persuaded to
begin renting DVDs, even though only a few hundred thousand DVD
players were in consumers' homes at that point. And the major
manufacturers of DVD players, including Toshiba and Sony, began
giving away five DVDs with every player sold.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other promotions spurred sales of open DVD so that by
the beginning of 1999, more than 1 million players had been sold,
one of the most successful product introductions in the industry's
history.
</P>
<P>
   That success helped hasten the demise of Divx. Hollywood studios
and retailers signed on with DVD and gave little support to Divx.
``Despite the significant consumer enthusiasm, we cannot create a
viable business without support in these essential areas,'' said
Circuit City chief executive Richard Sharp in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   As Circuit City acknowledged the demise of Divx, the company
also announced a generous program of rebates and refunds for the
roughly 150,000 people who have bought Divx players. The company
probably realized that any consumer willing to pay $400 for a
speculative new product like a Divx player is likely to be a
coveted early adopter of other new technologies that Circuit City
might sell.
</P>
<P>
   So Circuit City is offering every one of those buyers a $100
rebate. That is the difference in price between a Divx player and a
conventional DVD player. Every Divx player can also play
conventional DVDs, so by Circuit City's analysis, the consumers
come out even.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who paid the small fee to convert a pay-per-view Divx
disk to one that can be played repeatedly is also entitled to get a
refund of that fee. Consumers can pick up rebate forms at any
Circuit City store, or on the Web at  &UR; www.divx.com &LR; . Circuit City
is also selling all remaining Divx players and disks at heavily
discounted prices.
</P>
<P>
   Divx disks cannot be played unless the company's central
computer authorizes it. Circuit City will keep the system
operational until June 30, 2001. After that, Divx disks will be
worthless.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
