<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     06-23 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: NATIONAL LAWN CARE NOW! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (For release Friday, June 25)  
(rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a staff meeting the other day, it was suggested that we do a
story about how, in the summer, the grass grows so quickly that it
needs to be mowed two or more times a week.
</P>
<P>
   At first I just dismissed the idea as yet another example of the
woeful decline in American journalism, but the more I thought about
it, the angrier I became.
</P>
<P>
   Why should we _ or more specifically, I _ have to cut the grass
at all, let alone two or more times a week? The simple answer, of
course, is: Because you're too broke/cheap to hire a lawn service
to do the work for you. But why spend all that money? Aren't I, as
a taxpaying citizen, entitled to a nice, green, weed-free lawn?
Isn't there something, somewhere in the Constitution that
guarantees free lawn care to all Americans? Shouldn't, in other
words, the government cut my grass?
</P>
<P>
   Is this the king of all crazy notions? No, that would be tobacco
subsidies. Nationalized lawn care is actually an idea that's been
bandied about for some time, though it's possible you never heard
or read anything about it due to the fact that most of your major
media outlets are in the pocket of BiLCC (Big Lawn Care Companies).
</P>
<P>
   It all began on April 1, 1995, when Jeff Lindsay, an American
citizen and lawn owner, founded National Lawn Care Now!, a
``grassroots organization working for an equitable program of
nationalized lawn care in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The seed of the idea, so to speak, was planted while Lindsay was
driving around Atlanta. He noticed that the homes of poor people
often had small, weedy, unattractive lawns and that the people on
those lawns seemed tired and depressed. The only decorations he saw
were a few junked cars on cinder blocks, ``devoid of hope and
engines.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a mile away, in a wealthy area, he saw big, green, plush
lawns, lawns that were being used for parties attended by happy,
carefree people with functional cars. And then, like a 20-pound bag
of 10-10-10 fertilizer dropped on his head, it hit him: The quality
of one's life is directly linked to the quality of one's lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Poor slobs who are shackled to a crummy lawn are likely to be
shunned socially, or be the victims of persecution by neighbors who
worry about lowered property values. Ultimately, they will be
denied access to jobs, education and even health care. Even worse,
their lowered self-esteem will eventually extinguish all hope and
leave them no choice but to turn to a life of crime or politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of the founder: ``As the significance of lawns sank
into my thirsty soul like a Grand Epiphany, the stark truth almost
mowed me over: Rich people have better lawns because they can
afford them, while poor people don't. In fact, not only do the poor
have inadequate access to lawn care, many don't even have lawns at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The free-market system has failed to provide a just and
equitable distribution of lawns and lawn care, and with it we find
an unjust, inequitable distribution of self-esteem, perhaps the
most vital resource of all.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, especially if you've been drinking heavily, you
may be saying to yourself: Wow! Nationalized lawn care is a great
idea and clearly long overdue. Who could possibly be opposed to it?
</P>
<P>
   Big Lawn Care Companies, that's who. As special interest groups
go, BiLCC makes the NRA look shy and disorganized. Its
representatives have infiltrated all levels of government, all the
way up to the White House Lawn itself
</P>
<P>
   (Lindsay blames this on Reagan/Bush and the 12 Years of Hate and
Greed but I am more inclined to blame it on Jimmy Carter and the
Four Years of Lusting in the Heart.)
</P>
<P>
   Because it is rolling in green, so to speak, and stands to lose
so much, Big Lawn Care has resisted and will continue to resist all
efforts to reform our nation's lawn care policy, such as it is.
</P>
<P>
   We must not weaken. Even as we stand, sweating, on our lawns
this summer, listening to the eerie subterranean harmonies of
growing grass and mole-cricket munching, we must not waver. Even as
we pull a groin muscle yanking on the cord of the Toro, we must
stand firm, even if it's only on one leg. Even as the unchallenged
foliage threatens to lift our house into the sky like Jack's
beanstalk, we must not show fear.
</P>
<P>
   Say no to Big Lawn Care.
</P>
<P>
   Say yes to National Lawn Care. Now!
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
