<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-USENET-GROWTH-2TA     06-23 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-USENET-GROWTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD NEWSGROUPS IN NEW PACKAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Calif.)   (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ads are hard to miss. In one, a photograph of a crying
newborn is shown next to a debate about circumcision (``My advice:
do it before he has memory cells''). In another, a mustachioed
woman (``plucking hurts too much'') is told where she can find a
good place to have electrolysis.
</P>
<P>
   The eye-catching advertisements began appearing last month in
magazines and newspapers, and on billboards in New York and San
Francisco. They are selling Talkway, a commercial Web site
(www.talkway.com) that gathers, sorts and organizes messages sent
over Usenet, the sprawling collection of online discussion groups
that has been an integral part of the Internet for the last two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Talkway, though the most visible, is just one of several
entrepreneurial ventures to put a commercial wrapper around the
traditionally noncommercial Usenet and offer it through the Web.
</P>
<P>
   This repackaging of Usenet newsgroups is only one of the ways in
which the old, small-scale Internet has been transformed into the
new world of connectivity. But it is particularly illuminating
because Usenet is such a major part of Internet history.
</P>
<P>
   The repackaging makes Net old-timers cranky. But the executives
of start-ups like Talkway say they are introducing Usenet's
thousands of forums to millions of ordinary Web surfers, people who
might not use them otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Usenet was conceived in 1979 by two graduate students whose idea
was to link computers to exchange information about the Unix
operating system. Usenet grew quickly, evolving into a particularly
untamed, free-flowing part of the Internet. For years, Usenet was
the electronic conduit that carried both news and views of world
events and scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   Usenet's 45,000 or so newsgroups touch on just about any topic
imaginable, and the name of each group suggests its interest:
alt.support.sleep-disorder; rec.audio.pro; alt.fan.gwyn-paltrow;
comp.sys.ibm.pc.software.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Usenet was, like the Internet itself, a
self-selecting place. For most users, based at universities,
participating in discussions required at least a passing command of
Unix. By the early 1990s, Internet service providers, bulletin
board systems and community-based freenets had joined universities
in offering news readers, programs that enabled the reading and
collecting of messages. The number of users grew exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when people with ``aol.com'' at the end of
their e-mail addresses started posting to Usenet, they were harshly
attacked and harassed by those with ``.edu'' at the end of theirs.
To the dismay of many of those in the latter camp, the Web made
Usenet even more easily accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Usenet is owned and regulated by no one, which makes it ripe for
the picking by commercial ventures. Companies like Talkway can
simply collect Usenet discussions, put them on a Web site and offer
them to the browsing public as instant communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies are looking to aggregate an audience around
discussion and, at some point, turn that into revenue,'' said Anya
Sacharow, an analyst at Jupiter Communications, a market research
firm in New York. ``They're tapping into an existing base of people
already exchanging information.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been around Usenet for a long time say the
content is different from what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't seem to see as much in the way of long, carefully
written literary writing,'' said Ron Newman, a computer programmer
in Cambridge, Mass., who has been posting to Usenet since the
mid-1980s. ``I see a lot of things slapped off quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   By way of example, Newman pointed to the travel groups. ``It
used to be I'd see people posting long reports of the recent trips
they'd taken, describing in detail what they'd done day by day,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, such groups have turned into advice forums.
Indeed, a recent sampling of posts to rec.travel.europe showed a
preponderance of people looking for tips on car rentals and other
travel logistics. Newman said he now found the thoughtful,
discursive writing at places like Table Talk on Salon's Web site
(www.salon.com).
</P>
<P>
   Also, many of the newsgroups that have been popular among
scientists have grown too noisy for those who used to frequent
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's given up on sci.physics,'' said Scott Dorsey, a
computer system administrator who has been on Usenet since 1984.
``It used to consist of serious discussions among physicists; then
the U.F.O. people took it over.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Dorsey said, serious physicists moved their
discussion to sci.physics.research. ``Then the lunatics took it
over,'' he said. Now, like others wishing to carry on serious
discussions, the physicists have, for the most part, moved their
discussion to private mailing lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a specialist trying to carry on a discussion, it's
hard to do that when people are popping up with totally irrelevant
information,'' Dorsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, executives at Talkway and Remarq insist that Usenet
is growing. ``We've seen that the amount of space necessary to
store the messages has quadrupled over the past year,'' said Rich
Simoni, chief technology officer of Talkway. He said that the
number of Usenet users had grown in the last four years to about 25
million, an estimate that he conceded was ``nebulous at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lee, chief executive officer of Remarq (www.remarq.com),
which sells prepackaged Usenet discussions to Web portals like
Excite and Lycos, agreed with Simoni's general assessment. ``The
amount of Usenet traffic has grown tremendously over the last
year,'' Lee said
</P>
<P>
   But the number of Usenet users has not been systematically
tracked since 1995, when Brian Reid, then a computer scientist at
the Digital Equipment Corp., counted some 20 million around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, now a researcher at Bell Labs in Palo Alto, Calif., a unit
of Lucent Technologies, said: ``One of the reasons I stopped was
that the Web made the numbers plummet. I decided that whatever
Usenet did that was useful was being supplanted by the Web and I
saw no point in publishing further measurements.''
</P>
<P>
   To replace Unix-based news readers, which required knowing
commands like ``vi/.newsrc,'' Talkway, Remarq and Deja.com
(www.deja.com) use Web sites to offer an easy point-and-click
method of reading and posting messages. Usage is free (the sites
make money mostly by selling banner advertisements), and members
can customize the set of newsgroups they regularly read.
</P>
<P>
   To some old-timers, the commercialized flavor that these places
bring to Usenet is an affront to the public broadcasting
sensibility that reigned in an earlier era, when advertising on
Usenet was particularly taboo.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in 1994, when two immigration lawyers in Arizona sent
9,000 newsgroups an advertisement for their services, the outcry
among Usenet users made national news. Today, of course, such
broadcasts, also known as spam, are part of the general Internet
milieu.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Talkway and Remarq, whose executives draw a
distinction between ads they have solicited and those they have
not, have installed spam filters to keep advertising pitches from
the outside from getting into the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The first Web site to see the money-making potential of Usenet
was Deja.com, formerly Dejanews. It started in 1995 as a relatively
unadorned site, a newsgroup archive with a simple search mechanism
that Usenet regulars loved. The site recently underwent a makeover
and its board fired one chief executive and recruited another, Tom
Phillips, an executive from Internet ventures of ABC and ESPN. The
company moved its headquarters to New York from Austin, Texas, and
changed its name.
</P>
<P>
   The new site, which bills itself as a ``consumer information
exchange,'' is a somewhat confusing collection of ads and forms for
rating products and services, links to shopping sites and flashing
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Deja.com catchword is community, but the goal appears to be
directing attention to merchandise. Although Deja.com and its
for-profit brethren claim to make Usenet easier to use, their
cluttered sites are difficult to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Madere, Deja.com's founder and chief technology officer,
said the site was still evolving. ``We're trying to figure out how
to get everything to coexist on the page,'' Madere said.
</P>
<P>
   Deja.com's new interface sent its longstanding users into high
dudgeon. In anticipation of the reaction of this small but vocal
minority, the company offered the old interface as an option,
renaming it Deja Classic.
</P>
<P>
   None of the commercial ventures seems particularly eager to
promote Usenet as a brand. Talkway, Deja.com and Remarq make scant,
if any, mention of Usenet on their front pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usenet doesn't really mean a lot to people,'' said Carlos
Tribino, Talkway's vice president for marketing. ``We're really
focusing on opening the space to the entire Web audience. Some
people don't know what Usenet is, or those who do, think of it as a
difficult or intimidating environment, which is why I didn't see
any value in promoting Usenet per se.''
</P>
<P>
   To further distance itself from Usenet conventions, Talkway has
renamed the newsgroups. The group
misc.education.home-school.christian is now ``Christian
Education.'' (In deference to the conventional practice, Talkway
allows its visitors to choose a group's Usenet name.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to be accommodating while at the same time not
intimidating new users with a naming scheme that isn't even based
on English,'' said Simoni of Talkway.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist, it turns out that the dialogues in the catchy new
Talkway ads that are made to look like Usenet exchanges, are not
the real thing. They are the invention of Weiss Stagliano Partners,
Talkway's New York advertising firm. ``Actual posts inspired
them,'' Tribino said.
</P>
<P>
   The slick commercial backdrops are managing to attract people
who might not otherwise have ventured onto Usenet.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Gerould, for instance, a marketing consultant in Palo Alto
who has done work for Remarq, recently searched high and low in
cyberspace for tips on creating a Hawaiian theme for her daughter's
birthday. One parenting group on iVillage suggested Hula-Hoops.
Somebody else recommended canned pineapples on a skewer. ``That's
the level of what I was coming up with,'' Ms. Gerould said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, using Remarq, she found a Usenet group devoted to
discussions of Hawaiian culture. From there, she got pointers to
obscure cottage Web sites off the radar of most search engines.
``Had I not encountered Remarq, I might have thought to post
something somewhere, but not Usenet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gerould ended up with a highly authentic party, complete
with hula instruction from a native Hawaiian.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, the Usenet of old shows its colors. Last year,
someone posted to alt.folklore.computers, lamenting the
disappearance of Bell Laboratories, long the famous research arm of
AT&AMP;T. A few hours later, a Bell Labs veteran, Dennis Ritchie, the
co-creator of Unix who is to the world of serious Unix hackers what
Chris Evert is to the two-fisted backhand, posted a message saying
he had pinched himself and found that both he and Bell Labs were
still alive and well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it got down to a discussion of, is basic research
supported in the U.S.,'' said Ronda Hauben, co-author of
``Netizens: On the History and Impact of Usenet and the Internet,''
(IEEE Computer Society Press, 1997), who took part in the
discussion. Ms. Hauben said that such exchanges demonstrated to her
that Usenet was as vital as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become even more important,'' she said. ``It's the place
where people can discuss problems that develop and in a cooperative
way figure out what to do about the problems, either problems that
are on line, or in society in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some options for retrieving and posting to Usenet
newsgroups:
</P>
<P>
   I.S.P. ACCESS Most Internet service providers include Usenet
access as part of the service. Often that access comes as part of
the Netscape Navigator or Internet Explorer Web browsers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FREEWARE PROGRAMS Another option is a news reader program for a
PC or Mac. One popular program, a piece of freeware for the PC, is
called Free Agent (www.forteinc.com/getfa/download.htm). For Macs,
try Yet Another News Watcher (www.macupdate.com/info/36052.html). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEWSGUY: www.newsguy.com This subscription service strikes a
happy medium. You'll have to pay, but you'll like what you get. For
$25 a year, you get the basic service, which includes access to
7,500 newsgroups. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
