<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 24, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Copious amounts of rain will fall Thursday over portions of the
Ohio and Tennessee valleys as low pressure sweeps across the
region. Abundant moisture moving to the north from the Gulf of
Mexico will provide fuel for repeated heavy rains, with local flash
flooding possible. Further north, showers and thunderstorms will
erupt as a weakening cold front pushes through the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thunderstorms will develop over much of the western
Plains from Texas to South Dakota during the late afternoon. A
vigorous jet stream disturbance at 18,000 feet will ignite
thundershowers during the warmest part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the storms could approach severe limits, with damaging
winds being the greatest threat. Thunderstorms are also likely over
Florida, where the sea breeze will trigger thunderstorms in the
early afternoon near the Gulf Coast. These storms will move inland
as the day elapses.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will have another warm day with mostly sunny skies
as high pressure just off the New England coast provides mild and
more humid breezes from the south. A few puffy cumulus clouds and
some widely separated thunderstorms will develop in the mountains
of extreme northern New England during the afternoon and early
evening hours.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds and showers will continue in the Pacific Northwest,
where temperatures will remain below normal, as they have been
throughout the spring and early summer. The Southwest will be sunny
and very hot, with readings easily reaching triple digit marks in
the deserts.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The Summer Lag
</P>
<P>
   Daylight is beginning to shorten, but, the most intense heat of
summer typically accompanies the reduced daylight. Two effects
combine to cause the hottest weather to lag behind the sun. The
atmosphere is heated indirectly. Energy from the sun first heats
the surface of the earth which then warms the air above.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, 30 to 40 thousand feet aloft, the
lingering chill of the previous winter is still being erased.
Moreover, the ocean surface responds more slowly to the incoming
energy than does the land, further delaying the warming of the
atmosphere over the oceans.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
