<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUSSAY-AUCTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRANCE, PARTING GLANCES AT A PLEASURE DOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As deathbed scenes go, the last gasp of Chateau de Groussay was
particularly lively. Helicopters landed and cars lumbered up the
drive over 10 days in late May and early June, disgorging princes
and potentates, designers and decorators in the posh suburban
village of Montfort-l'Amaury, 30 miles south of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 people arrived to see the splendors headed for
the block beneath a 3,000-square-foot tent on Groussay's verdant
lawn: Canova-style busts, Berlin porcelain, neo-Egyptian side
chairs, a dazzling oddment of 18th-century sketches and paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding for the contents of the house was furious. And
satisfyingly lucrative. In a room upstairs, its owner, Juan de
Beistegui, watched the sale on closed-circuit television with all
the frenzied emotion of a sports fan watching his team pummel the
competition. Each time an object sold well above its estimate, de
Beistegui (pronounced bess-TEE-ghee) ``shrieked and cheered,'' said
a friend who was there.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, 2,416 lots later, on June 6, the greatest private
interiors concocted in the 20th century disappeared, dispersed for
$26.5 million _ more than $10 million above the estimate of the
auctioneers, Sotheby's France and Poulain &AMP; Le Fur. (The contents
of the Neuilly villa of the Duke and Duchess of Windsor sold for
$23 million.)
</P>
<P>
   The Chateau de Groussay (pronounced groo-SAY) is now just a
neoclassical shell on the market for $10 million, its 37 rooms
bare, its soulful spaces a mere memory. Yet, its mystique is such
that many experts, even many bidders, felt it should have been
preserved as a museum dedicated to the lapidary taste of de
Beistegui's uncle, Carlos, an eccentric gadfly of taste who bought
the house in 1939 and spent more than three decades grooming its
rooms and grounds before his death, in 1970, at 74.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale was a major event in the history and sociology of the
decorative arts,'' said Paige Rense, the editor of Architectural
Digest, who led the last tour of the chateau before its rooms were
stripped. The recent Onassis and Windsor sales were circuses of
pure celebrity. But Ms. Rense added, ``Groussay was a mecca.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, when the profession of interior decoration was in
its youth and more concerned with freshness, modernity and
practical living, Groussay was an international anomaly. Built
around 1815 by a French duchess, remodeled later by a Russian
emigre and then revamped by Beistegui, heir to a fortune derived
from silver mines in Mexico, where his Basque ancestors immigrated
in the 18th century, the chateau was a study in contradiction. It
was a temple to luxury and peace created in the midst of
deprivation and war; an Anglo-Russian country house plunked down in
a Paris suburb; a bucolic retreat owned by a man who loathed the
outdoors, and crucially, an atomic-age celebration of
turn-of-the-century values.
</P>
<P>
   All the more shocking, then, to realize that Carlos de Beistegui
was that rare beast in today's degree-conscious design world: a
gifted amateur. He had no training in design, no real experience,
save an overweening interest in the decorative arts. What Beistegui
did possess were a passion for beauty, a matchless eye for balance
and visual drama and an understanding that, finally, great design
is more about sorcery than about whether a fabric will handle daily
wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   Beistegui was not obsessed with lifeless replications. Instead,
he was a master of sensual decoration, concocting rooms that
recalled the scents, the sounds, the daydreams, the innocence of
his youth, suffused with memories of the English country houses
that he visited as a student at Eton and at Cambridge University.
</P>
<P>
   As a friend wrote after spending a long weekend at Groussay,
Beistegui's ``adolescence is something he has never been willing to
leave in the past.'' So the chateau ended up not only a benchmark
but also a brick-and-brocade twin to Proust's ``Remembrance of
Things Past.'' It was a house devoted to the persistence of memory
_ in some cases real, in others invented.
</P>
<P>
   Another collector would have stocked up solely on masterpieces,
but Beistegui was happy to achieve the effects he wanted through
sleight of hand and keen subterfuge. Though he ferreted out major
works, he understood that the overall effect of a room is more
important than the authenticity of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings from the world's great museums were openly copied and
thickly hung floor to ceiling in the dazzling two-story library,
the profusion causing the walls to positively pulsate with
animation. He commissioned Lucien Toulouse, a Paris cabinetmaker,
to reproduce a Louis XVI porcelain-enriched mahogany cabinet from
the royal Chateau de Fontainebleau. When a wing was added for a
private theater, Spanish weavers set to work churning out
tapestries after 18th-century cartoons by Goya. The giant Chinese
jars were either tin or plaster.
</P>
<P>
   English decorator David Hicks, who never admitted to liking much
of anything except his own work, bowed before Groussay's curiously
melancholy chic, its bracing yet comforting stew of English sofas,
South American colors and French luxury. Mark Hampton, the American
decorator, once called it the most beautiful house in the world,
marveling at its confidence. But what made Groussay more than a
rich man's temporary plaything was its subtle but ineradicable
impact on domestic designers in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   As Clive Aslet, the editor of the British magazine Country Life,
has written, Carlos de Beistegui was ``a creator of the scenery of
life.'' Designers lucky enough to enjoy his hospitality at
Groussay, the Palazzo Labia in Venice or his ancestral town house
in Paris returned home enchanted, modern Marco Polos telling tales
of outlandish glories. Just as enthusiastically, they brought his
lessons, his deliberate gestures, into their own work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why. While other midcentury traditionalists
espoused Williamsburg-style propriety, with polite pastels
reticently handled, Beistegui's palette swaggered: a pea-green
salon bordered with blue-and-white Delft tiles, a staircase lined
with russet paisley cashmere, a billiard-table-green sitting room
paved with wall-to-wall carpeting in searing sapphire blue.
</P>
<P>
   At Groussay, history was open to interpretation. The overall
impression was Anglo-Gallic, but the elements were cosmopolitan in
the extreme: Russian neoclassical chairs, wood beds carved to
resemble bamboo, Polish tables, Venetian mirrors, Art Deco
blackamoors of painted plaster, taxidermied fish under glass and a
plethora of antlers.
</P>
<P>
   When he tore down the plaster walls that encased the entrance
hall's double staircase to open the ceiling and expose the stairs'
wood skeleton, the results made most other staircases seem gutless
by comparison: the twin flights curve up to the mezzanine like a
giant polished ice tong.
</P>
<P>
   Though the improvements at Groussay were solidly grounded in
traditionalism, as a young man, Beistegui had a famous flirtation
with modernity. In the early 1930s, Le Corbusier built him a
penthouse on the Champs-Elysees, severe white rooms that the
willful heir furnished like a Surrealist bordello, with gilt and
mirrors and tomfoolery like an electronically operated hedge that
parted to reveal a view of the Arc de Triomphe.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years later, however, he retreated to his parents'
town house. What accounts for this volte-face is unknown. But when
Beistegui ventured out to buy a bachelor pad again, in 1938, he
bought an old house, historic but not landmarked, which meant he
could realize his fancies without the intrusion of
preservationists. And there he decided to immerse himself in
history, or at least, the reinterpretation of it.
</P>
<P>
   His esthetic streak remains a mystery. No one in his family _
the Beistegui clan settled in Paris in the 1880s _ was notably
creative, except his namesake uncle, a gentleman artist whose
collection of notable 18th- and 19th-century paintings ended up in
the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Groussay's celebrated library _ Cecil Beaton's
black-and-white photograph of this striking space, with its
corkscrew staircases and shafts of sunlight raking the mezzanine,
remains perhaps the most breathtaking image of any interior taken
in this century _ Beistegui was no scholar. Many of his beautifully
bound books were reportedly bought by the yard. Still, Beaton said,
``He is versed in the knowledge of most works of art and on certain
aspects of history could be considered an expert.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he entertained the odd outside commission _ salons in the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Madrid, a suite of rooms at the
Waldorf-Astoria in New York, and the library at the British Embassy
in Paris (with the designers Georges Geffroy and Emilio Terry) _
his talents were utilized almost entirely for his own pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, Beistegui conjured, inventing interiors like a
composer writing a symphony: sensitively shifting from forte to
pianissimo here, inserting a grace note there, dappling the score
with disparate allusions to other civilizations, other countries.
It was this talent for detail that kept people amazed.
</P>
<P>
   When public celebrity arrived on his doorstep in 1951, thanks to
an extravagant ball he gave at his Venetian palazzo, Beistegui
seemed genuinely perplexed by the attention. Soon he retreated from
view into a private, increasingly unbalanced realm of his own.
</P>
<P>
   There were hints that he would eventually become a recluse, even
if a series of strokes had not hurried the process along. Beistegui
was as much a mass of contradictions as his exquisite decors:
generous host but alarmingly self-absorbed, a social fixture but
largely friendless, amorous but unloving.
</P>
<P>
   A rat-faced child who swelled into Savile Row pomposity as he
grew older, Beistegui was obsessed with propriety, placement,
perfection. His manner was distant, his smile thin, his sexuality a
matter of trans-Atlantic speculation, despite energetic relations
with safely married women: those who knew him said their noble
titles intrigued him more than their physical charms.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he assiduously cultivated the role of elegant and highly
discriminating satyr. Even his citizenship was a tangle: French
birth, Mexican parents, Spanish diplomatic passport.
</P>
<P>
   The last allowed Beistegui to weather the Nazi occupation as the
nominal representative of a neutral country. The contrived passport
also freed him to create a personal pleasure dome in the midst of
continental devastation. ``Beistegui is utterly ruthless,'' Beaton
complained to his diary after a visit to Groussay in 1944, where he
photographed its chatelain and a houseful of high-caliber guests.
``Such qualities as sympathy, pity or even gratitude are sadly
lacking. He has become the most self-engrossed and pleasure-seeking
person I have met.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-volume auction catalog is probably the ultimate memoir
of Carlos de Beistegui and his singular creation. It is the house,
not the man, that was probably the greatest loss to the world. The
chateau may have been merely a beautiful stage set, its
Victorian-Edwardian glamour utterly unrelated to everyday life. But
for some, the gutting of Groussay is likely to go down in history
as the decorative-arts equal of the razing of Pennsylvania Station:
the toppling of an artistic apex where majesty and magic
intersected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wait your whole life to see something like Groussay, but
when you got there, there wasn't anything joyful about it,'' said
Mario Buatta, the New York decorator, who was among the last to see
the house intact. ``Doors were closing behind us and being locked.
It was like a funeral.''
</P>
</TEXT>
