<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS LOOK FOR WAY TO PAY FOR MEDICARE DRUG COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators studying proposals to extend Medicare to
cover prescription drugs said Wednesday they like the idea but are
perplexed about how to pay for such an historic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to provide (drug coverage,) and I believe we will
eventually provide it,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, at a
meeting of the Senate Finance Committee. ``But we cannot afford any
more rich new benefits without raising taxes or without having more
of the federal budget consumed as we go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said it was ``inhumane'' for Medicare
to not provide some drug coverage but asked, ``How do we pay for
this...benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Medicare is projected to go bankrupt in 2015 because
the number of people receiving Medicare benefits will rise sharply
as the baby boom generation begins retiring, the Clinton
administration and lawmakers of both political parties are pushing
to expand the program to cover prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   One committee member, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., doubted whether
another layer of benefits should be added to Medicare before the
program's long-term financial problems are solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot even sustain the program today,'' said Breaux. ``If
we add prescription drugs, we have to reform the entire (Medicare)
program.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare health insurance program used by 39 million elderly
and disabled Americans does not cover the cost of prescription
drugs, though it does cover the cost of drugs while a person is
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposed the expansion during his State of the
Union speech in January and is expected to unveil a formal plan
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican lawmakers have endorsed the concept because
their own internal public opinion polls show older Americans like
the idea a lot. A poll conducted for the Republican National
Committee in April showed that 70 percent of older Americans would
vote for a Democrat if he or she favors Medicare prescription drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals to expand Medicare clash with recent trends in
Congress. In 1997, for example, Congress voted to cut Medicare
payments to health care providers by about $20 billion annually
through the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gluck, representing the non-partisan National Academy of
Social Insurance, said the costs of providing Medicare drug
coverage would range from about $18 billion to $24 billion annually
if Medicare beneficiaries also pay for a portion. Gluck's proposals
depended on how much a beneficiary would pay out of pocket, ranging
from a $200 to $500 annual deductible as well as a co-payment on
each drug.
</P>
<P>
   If the government were to pick up the entire tab of drug
coverage, it would cost about $45 billion annually _ or nearly
one-quarter of the estimated $200 billion cost of the entire
Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   No committee member advocated that option and they all endorsed
the idea that Medicare recipients should share the cost of drugs
with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dummitt, a health economics specialist at the General
Accounting Office, warned that the rising costs of prescription
drugs could cause Medicare drug coverage to be more expensive than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this is a benefit, there are no easy ways to control
costs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dummitt said prescription drug spending grew an average of 11
percent annually from 1992 to 1997 compared with a 5 percent growth
rate for overall health care spending during the same time period.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 percent of Medicare beneficiaries have some
prescription drug coverage through supplemental private insurance
plans _ at an out-of-pocket cost averaging about $100 a month _ or
through insurance offered by a former employer. In most cases
retirees also pay an annual deductible and a co-payment for
prescription drugs. The remaining 35 percent of Medicare
beneficiaries have no drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said one option is to provide coverage for low-income
Medicare beneficiaries who do not qualify for Medicaid, the federal
program that pays for health care for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux, who co-chaired a bipartisan commission that examined
solutions to Medicare's financial straits, made such a
recommendation as part of the panel's final report in March. The
plan would cost about $6 billion annually and would provide people
with incomes less than $11,000 a year with drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said Breaux's plan doesn't go far enough and is
expected to propose a much broader drug coverage package.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
