</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBSIDE-WEBSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 IBM Points Its Wallet Toward E-Commerce for Small Firms 
 &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  Last month, International
<TEXT>
Business Machines Corp. kicked off a $100 million marketing
campaign to promote its e-commerce products for small businesses.
Then two weeks ago, it paid even more to buy Whistle
Communications, a Foster City company that offers easy e-mail and
Internet access to small companies.
<P>
   Both events underscore an important economic fact about the
information technology industry. ``The small-business segment is
growing more quickly than any other,'' said Peter Rowley, general
manager of Global Small Business at IBM.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp. estimates that small and midsize
businesses make up half of the $300 billion global information
technology market and that their expenditures are growing faster
than those of large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, the small-business market is growing at 11 to
13 percent per year, compared with 8 or 9 percent for larger
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But IBM, which is better known for its large computing systems
and PCs, faces a problem with the small-business market: It's very
fragmented, with thousands of large and small vendors.
</P>
<P>
   That is the reason for its concerted _ and costly _ crusade to
establish an electronic relationship with smaller businesses. The
campaign includes these features:
</P>
<P>
   _The Small Business Program, which unifies IBM products and
services for this market for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   _The Small Business Solutions Club, where subscribers, for a
small annual fee, can get discounts on products and 50 percent
savings at Hilton, Hyatt, Marriott and other hotels and resorts.
</P>
<P>
   _IBM Small Business Custom Connections (www.ibm.com), which is
designed to let small businesses create customized pages and
organize the Web according to their specific needs, including
reminders of appointments and events.
</P>
<P>
   _Business Advantage, which provides various online tools and
consulting services to help growing businesses use the Web for
communication, collaboration and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   _ThinkCenters, in which joint ventures between IBM, the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce and Small Business Administration provide
small-business owners with hands-on experience and personal
consulting. They are located in various cities, but none has been
established in California.
</P>
<P>
   Without Whistle, IBM had some products to help small businesses
establish Web sites, sell goods and services online and run their
accounting and other business operations. But it didn't have an
all-in-one system to let little companies using different hardware
and software easily connect to the Internet and send e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   IBM plans to make Whistle Communications products available to
small businesses in all industries around the world. For example, a
small mortgage broker could advertise mortgage rates on the Web,
accept online applications and communicate with customers by
e-mail. An employment agency could advertise jobs and receive
resumes online, deal with prospective employers by e-mail and
receive their fees by a secure network.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley said Whistle Communications will strategically help IBM
``capture small companies and then migrate them to our other
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Whistle had its own reasons to become part of IBM. It had raised
$35 million from venture capital investors. But Whistle CEO John
Hamm said much more was required ``to get big enough, fast enough
to influence small-business buying patterns.'' In addition to cash,
he noted that IBM ``had the brand reach we really needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Whistle and IBM's other e-commerce offerings will help small
businesses ``harness the power of the Internet and compete more
effectively,'' Rowley said. ``This levels the playing field for
small businesses and helps them appear bigger than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said IBM is on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Whistle, IBM bought a conduit into the small-business
market,'' said Dataquest analyst James Staten in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of small businesses are in the early stages of
e-commerce, like sending e-mails back and forth,'' said Boston
information technology consultant Joseph Villarosa. ``But they are
not really conducting business on the Internet. IBM is smart to see
this coming and try to help early adopters move up the chain to
larger products.''
</P>
<P>
   Other major companies may not be spending as much as IBM on
marketing. But they also are targeting the small-business and
so-called SOHO (small office, home office) market with e-commerce
products, services and information at special pages on their Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hewlett-Packard (www.hp.com) provides plenty of
information about its products, as well as expert advice, customer
success stories and other Web site resources.
</P>
<P>
   Intel (www.intel.com) has a full menu of products and services
for small business, including a glossary of terms, case studies and
information on building computer networks, growing on the Internet,
and mobile computing.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit (www.quicken.com), Microsoft (www.microsoft.com), Compaq,
(www.compaq.com), Dell (www.dell.com) and most other large hardware
and software vendors offer special information for small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
