<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETERANS24-COX     06-23 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONSTRUCTION LOAN APPROVED FOR WORLD WAR II MEMORIAL
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox news Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The long-awaited World War II memorial came a step
closer to reality Wednesday as a House panel authorized a $65
million loan for its construction and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, House and Senate panels approved giving a
cost-of-living adjustment to veterans with service-connected
disabilities. As in previous years, the COLA will be pegged to the
annual increase in the Consumer Price Index, based on the figure
released in September.
</P>
<P>
   The House Veterans Affairs Committee unanimously agreed to
authorize the American Battle Monuments Commission to borrow $65
million from the U.S. Treasury in order to spur construction of the
below-ground-level plaza to be located between the Washington
Monument and the Lincoln Memorial. It is expected to be completed
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the memorial, expected to be about $100 million, is
being raised privately. The Treasury loan would be repaid from
those private fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   House Committee Chairman Bob Stump, R-Ariz., urged Congress to
pass the legislation because many World War II veterans are in poor
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing 1,000 veterans a day. Let's get going on this,''
Stump said.
</P>
<P>
   In other business, the committee narrowly approved an amendment
by Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., that would allow veterans
to be covered by veterans benefits for emergency care provided
outside of Veterans Health Administration facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask veterans to choose VA care, but leave them out in
emergencies,'' Rockefeller said before the amendment passed on a
7-5 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Veterans Committee Chairman Arlen Specter, R-Pa., was
hesitant to approve the amendment. ``The objective is sound, (but)
I don't think we have a handle on the cost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
