<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7071 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GOLF-WEBSITES-2TA     06-23 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GOLF-WEBSITES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL GOLF, WITHOUT THE CADDIES OR CARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all sports, golf has a reputation for being among the most
averse to change. While tennis and basketball players compete with
fluorescent clothes and shaved heads, many professional golfers
wear the long pants and polo shirts that have been worn since
before the turn of the century. As if to emphasize the
conservatism, Payne Stewart won the U.S. Open this month wearing
navy blue plus fours.
</P>
<P>
   But golf has not been so reluctant to throw tradition aside and
expand onto the Web. The sport is flourishing there, with hundreds
of sites that focus on the best courses, firsthand accounts of
holes in one and what to look for in equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites that generate particular interest are those
devoted to topics like the Open, the Masters, the Professional
Golfers' Association Championship and the British Open. Online
magazines, fans sites and sports television sites chronicle each
round; the PGA site provides frequent updates.
</P>
<P>
   Reading about the competitors may inspire some weekend players.
Dozens of sites offer tips on driving (go for the middle of the
green), putting (keep in balance) and practice (do it as much as
possible).
</P>
<P>
   But people who are looking for information about equipment and
resorts may have a harder time finding it on the Web. There are
ample articles about golf courses and new equipment, but they are
often so positive that they might as well have been written by a
publicity agent.
</P>
<P>
   As George Plimpton once observed about sports writing, the
smaller the ball, the better the prose. Though little on the Web
approaches the quality of the golf writing found elsewhere, there
is plenty online to keep the enthusiast glued to the computer
screen _ at least until the game starts on television.
</P>
<P>
   PGATOUR.COM
</P>
<P>
   www.pgatour.com
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are good!'' this site announces on its logo. That
statement, golf's answer to other sports tag lines (``We Love This
Game,'' ``The Coolest Game on Ice''), sets the tone for
Pgatour.com, home to Professional Golfers' Association, which
oversees the men's and senior tour. The site chronicles the
accomplishments of hundreds of professional players in minute
detail, with a large dose of admiration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the site's boosterism, visitors can find more
than the usual updates about tournament leaders, player statistics
and records. There is also an archive of player biographies with a
few interesting, if decidedly uncritical, personal tidbits. The
site took note, for instance, that Tiger Woods made E!
Entertainment Television's list of ``World's Coolest Bachelors.''
People who prefer fancier sources of information can click on the
multimedia section. Here, they can watch video highlights from the
most recent tour, tune in to an occasional golf audio news show and
listen to a live radio broadcast for play-by-play coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The site also offers a quirky selection of articles by caddies
and professionals that give weekend players an inside look at what
it is like to be on the tour, often with not so glamorous
anecdotes. For example, Joe Ogilvie, a rookie player, talks about
his failure to make the cut in several tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he could get some advice from the regularly updated
feature Tour Tips, in which professionals like Lee Trevino discuss
golf basics. The lessons get extra points for having video clips so
that visitors can see for themselves how to play better in, for
example, the wind and sand.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its shortcomings, this site is probably among the best
on the Web focused on the professional tour, if for no other reason
than its access to the world's best players. The weakest features
on the site are those that try to sell something other than the
men's tour. Too often here, advertising masquerades as genuine
articles. The travel section is a repeat offender: It shovels
praise on the resorts that host professional tournaments. Another
is a golf equipment column that looks as if it was illustrated by a
golf equipment manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL GOLF GUIDE
</P>
<P>
   www.globalgolfguide.com
</P>
<P>
   Golf enthusiasts are drawn to images of spectacular fairways and
greens as gourmets are to photos of five-star meals. Such pictures
have probably encouraged many golfers to travel, or at least dream
of traveling, great distances to play some of the best courses in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   This site, home of the Global Golf Guide, an online compendium
of golf course, golf resort and golf real-estate images, offers
golfers the opportunity to tour famed courses via hundreds of film
clips. Visitors can view individual holes at dozens of golf clubs
in places like Scottsdale, Ariz., and La Quinta, Calif., from the
perspective of a flying helicopter or a panning camera.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most impressive clips are of the seaside fairways in
Pebble Beach, Calif., with audio descriptions. In showing the
seventh hole at Pebble Beach Golf Links, the camera zooms in from
over the ocean, following the fairway along the rugged coastline,
past its sand traps and an artfully placed lone cypress pine tree,
to the green. ``The jagged rocks of Carmel Bay are in sharp
contrast to the manicured beauty of the seventh hole,'' the
narrator says.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers looking for repeated vicarious thrills may be
disappointed. Though the virtual tours are certainly fancy, the
quality of the image hardly compares with that of a television
broadcast. The film clips are small and often fuzzy, and the audio
sometimes echoes. The tours in the panorama section are typically
more in focus. But the images, which originate from a slowly
spinning camera, show only a small portion of individual holes.
</P>
<P>
   Even less revealing is the archive of still photography from
courses around the world. But the section is still impressive for
its depth, including shots from golfing destinations like Bolivia
and Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   Do not expect to get much of an independent view of golf
courses. All of the images appear to come straight from promotional
videos and brochures, which do not focus on dead grass and lumpy
greens (unless, of course, they're in Scotland).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this site would appeal only to truly devoted
golfers. After browsing through the clips, the uninitiated may be
moved to commit heresy and say, ``Frankly, all golf courses look
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WORLD GOLF
</P>
<P>
   www.worldgolf.com
</P>
<P>
   Golf consists of much more than hitting a ball in a hole (with
an instrument ill-designed for the purpose, as Winston Churchill
once said), although that is certainly the major goal of the game.
Golf, at least as it is presented on television and through
advertising, is also an avocation that can, at its best, include
travel, fitness, tremendous mental preparation and good humor. At
its worst, golf is still associated with class, racism, bad clothes
and even worse humor.
</P>
<P>
   World Golf focuses on the sport at its best. It features a range
of information that many golfers will find useful, if not for
improving their games, then perhaps for finding a job at a country
club or getting advice about collecting old drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Instruction is taken quite seriously here. The site includes
several articles about topics like grips for putting, posture and
balance, and the proper placement of feet.
</P>
<P>
   The instruction on mechanics is insightful, though sometimes
obvious. For example, one writer advised players to putt the ball
within a 3-foot ``halo'' around the hole, which seems to be what
most golfers are already trying to do with varying degrees of
success.
</P>
<P>
   Other advice for a better golf game focused on the mental game
and fitness, which are not often mentioned on other sites. Here, a
lot of space is devoted to the mental game. An article about
overcoming blocks suggests the use of neuro-linguistic programming,
a ``technique that psychotherapists use with people who suffer from
post-traumatic stress _ victims emotionally traumatized by war,
floods, bombings, rape and the like.'' And don't forget to bend
your knees.
</P>
<P>
   When you're ready to take your neuro-linguistic programming out
on the greens, World Golf has a section in which readers offer
their own reviews of golf courses around the world. The reviews
range from the short (``not a bad course'') to detailed
shot-by-shot reports on individual holes. (``Greens could be
redone,'' a golfer said about the Oyster Bay Golf Club on Long
Island. ``They get chewed up real fast.'')
</P>
<P>
   Any criticism found there is in contrast to the site's
unimpressive reports on golf travel destinations around the world.
Like too much of the writing on these sites, the text seemed lifted
from brochures.
</P>
<P>
   For people who want to read about golf, this may be one of the
sites to visit. It is not exceptional nor is it fancy, but it does
have interesting content and a certain charm.
</P>
<P>
   LPGA.COM
</P>
<P>
   www.lpga.com
</P>
<P>
   Who has earned the most money on the women's professional golf
tour this year? What is the women's equivalent of the Ryder Cup
called? Who won the U.S. Women's Open last year?
</P>
<P>
   If you can't answer these questions, don't worry: Neither can
many die-hard sports fans. (The answers, by the way, are Karrie
Webb, the Solheim Cup and Se Ri-pak.) Facts like these are the
staple of this Web site, home of the Ladies Professional Golf
Association, the organization that oversees the women's golf tour.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the site consists of almanac-style information, like
lists of the longest hitters and the winners of all the
championships since 1950. There are also updates from recent
tournaments and biographies of several hundred regular competitors.
What the site doesn't impart is any reason to know any of these
facts.
</P>
<P>
   Women's golf has traditionally teed off in the long shadow of
the men's game. But with female stars of basketball, soccer and
particularly tennis drawing attention, you might think the LPGA
would be ready to put its stars in the spotlight. Sadly, this site
does very little to advance the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The site contains very little to get a visitor excited about the
sport. The biographies, for example, are simply dry recitations of
accomplishments and an occasional predictable aside. ``Credits her
parents and coach Kelvin Haller as the individuals most influencing
her career'' is the sort of white-bread description the site offers
for Karrie Webb, one of the hottest golfers on the tour this year.
Nor does the site contain features that might give some sense of
life on the tour, like action photographs or interviews with
players.
</P>
<P>
   One particularly disappointing section was the one devoted to
the history of women's golf, which I thought would feature pages of
information about the pioneers of the game with photographs of
equipment, clothing and players. But the reality is far less
satisfying, with each decade, beginning with the 1950s, recounted
with one unidentified photograph and a few paragraphs of
generalities about, for instance, increases in prize money and
television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, this site works only as a source of updated tour
results. It would greatly benefit from an infusion of flash.
</P>
<P>
   Here are more sources of golf-related information and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES GOLF ASSOCIATION: www.usga.com: Features one of
the most complete rule books on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   BAD GOLF MONTHLY: www.badgolfmonthly.com: A comforting
destination for golfers with a big handicap.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF ONLINE: www.golfonline.com: Offers a comprehensive
selection of playing tips, tournament reports and travel articles.
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WOODS OFFICIAL GOLF WEBSITE: www.tigerwoods.com: A fan
site for those who believe that Woods should win every tournament.
</P>
<P>
   MR. GOLF ETIQUETTE: www.mrgolf.com: Includes a primer on how to
behave on the course.
</P>
<P>
   CADDYSHACK AND HAPPY GILMORE ARCHIVE: www.bushwood.net: Features
pictures, trivia and sound clips from ``Caddyshack,'' perhaps one
of the most popular golfing films ever.
</P>
<P>
   AMATEUR GOLF ADVISOR: www.tagagolf.com: Gives tips on a number
of topics, including driving and what to look for when buying
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   TRIVIA GOLF COUNTRY CLUB: www.triviagolf.com: Tests of
knowledge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-RUSSIA-Y2K-NUKE-N     06-23 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-RUSSIA-Y2K-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FEAR RUSSIA MAY NOT HAVE THE RESOURCES TO MANAGE ITS 
REACTORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (See also RUSSIA-Y2K, U.N.-Y2K) 
 (HLW)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Deputy Atomic Energy Minister Valentin Ivanov has
good reason to promise that Russia's 29 nuclear reactors will be
free of the Year 2000 computer problem in January. The reactors, it
seems, are largely free of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ivanov said, at the nuclear station nearest to Moscow,
``the general engineer promises that he'll have a New Year's party,
and he's invited me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although American experts said they would quite likely accept
such an invitations, they still have nagging questions about how
ready the reactors are. The experts said they were unsure whether
engineers could locate and check all the microchips and other
digital improvements that have been added to Soviet-era plants over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   The experts worry that Russian engineers, adept at handling
breakdowns in sometimes creaky plants, might be overwhelmed if four
or five systems fail at once, and they wonder whether backup
systems for water and power are sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the experts wonder whether the cash-depleted
government can really oversee all the work at stations flung across
10 time zones, some so remote that it is tough to administer them
even in normal times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking it seriously,'' an American official said.
``Our concern is that they won't do enough, either because there
are some pockets in Russia that still aren't taking it seriously,
even though they've been ordered by the government to do things, or
because they lack the resources.''
</P>
<P>
   The official echoed an analysis by the Pacific Northwest
National Laboratories of the U.S. Energy Department about potential
Year 2000 flaws in Soviet-style reactors. The report found that
senior Russian officials had made reactor safety a priority, but
that ``the level of effort devoted to date varied from site to site
and organization to organization.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, American experts worry that the nuclear-energy
industry is so short of cash and time that even some obvious flaws
will go uncorrected. Those experts stress that their views are only
well-educated guesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although Americans have visited all 66 Soviet-style reactors in
Russia and surrounding nations, they have not evaluated the plants
for Year 2000 vulnerabilities. In general, they said, the
millennium bug poses a small threat.
</P>
<P>
   Most ``mission critical'' functions, including crucial water
pumps, are controlled by analog devices. Some flawed computers or
chips could force a plant to shut down, but none appears vital to
stopping reactors in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   In an emergency, a reactor can usually be shut down instantly.
But operators still need to pump cool water to the core for a few
days, until the plant is completely stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   That underscores American experts' second concern, that reactors
could be hampered by the failure of regional power grids or other
utilities and that backup systems at cash-strapped reactors might
prove inadequate. As in the West, Russian nuclear stations have
emergency backups like multiple generators. But they can be
thwarted by many factors like poor maintenance or a shortage of
diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in Western plants,'' an American said, ``the systems
don't work right all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian experts nevertheless said they were atop the situation.
The top Year 2000 official in the Atomic Energy Ministry, Yuri
Sokolov, said in March that experts had checked 97 percent of
date-sensitive reactor components. Sokolov did not say what that
review found, but he said his ministry would use all means at its
disposal to correct any flawed hardware or programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said flatly that the only computer systems with potential
problems are those that process data and that all systems that
affect critical reactor operations had, been deemed safe, as have
the systems that contain radiation at the plants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he indicated that Russian experts harbored some of the
lingering concerns that nag American scientists. Some programs that
monitor and schedule maintenance are not ready, he said. Operators
will rely on paper schedules and forgo unplanned repairs in the
period around Jan. 1. Computers that control electricity in
regional power grids also need changes, Ivanov added.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, he allowed that some secondary safety
systems involving tasks like water and fire control might have
problems. But he pledged that those and other deficiencies would be
fixed or that the systems will be under human control on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear-power industry is in dire straits. Rosenergoatom,
the state-owned company that oversees reactor operations and power
sales, owes scores of millions of dollars in debt to tax
authorities and its suppliers, and the business came under criminal
investigation in February.
</P>
<P>
   One reactor complex in eastern Russia recently went 18 months
without collecting even a kopeck from electricity customers, who
paid their bills with barter _ if they paid them at all.
</P>
<P>
   Spare parts can be at a premium, and a number of reactors are
overdue for renovation or retirement. Ivanov said that the minimum
budget for updating reactors was $1.8 million and that plant
workers will be carrying out most of the work. If others wish to
offer financial aid, he added, ``we will accept it gladly.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia, it turns out, is not the Americans' greatest concern.
The greatest potential for problems is in Ukraine, which is in even
worse financial shape. It has 14 reactors in operation.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia, home to one Soviet-style reactor, is another potential
problem spot, the experts said. The Energy Department has conducted
workshops in former Soviet nations since last year. But American
officials said it was difficult to know how extensively those
workers had inspected their equipment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-22-99 2117EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
