u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-WEBOPTIONS-WEBOPT     06-23 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBOPTIONS-WEBOPTIONS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Thin servers help companies get around Internet congestion 
 &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  One hurdle small businesses
<TEXT>
face in the e-commerce age is finding quick-and-simple e-mail
service and online access for all employees through a single
Internet connection.
<P>
   A growing number of companies are tackling the problem with
so-called thin server Internet appliances. The devices, about the
size of a toaster and as easy to use, sell for around $1,500 to
$3,000. They allow up to 100 employees working on computers in a
small office to do a variety of tasks such as:
</P>
<P>
   _Send and receive e-mail inside and outside the office.
</P>
<P>
   _Connect to and gather information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _Set up and maintain a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _Maintain privacy and security for individual and company files.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, these little boxes don't require a software
guru to set up or manage.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the leading companies in this fast-growing e-commerce
niche are based in the Bay Area. They include Cobalt Networks of
Mountain View, Encanto Networks of Santa Clara and Whistle
Communications of Foster City.
</P>
<P>
   Ramp Networks, a Santa Clara maker of routing equipment that
lets employees in a small office share the same Internet
connection, yesterday raised $57.5 million in its initial stock
offering. Ramp shares rose 52.3 percent, from $11 to $16.75, giving
the company a market value of about $335 million.
</P>
<P>
   As another sign of the importance of this market, International
Business Machines Corp. bought Whistle Communications two weeks ago
as a key part of its campaign to expand its presence in the
small-business market. No price was announced, but informed sources
say it topped $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whistle CEO John Hamm compares his company's ``InterJet''
product to the Swiss Army knife. ``It's an all-in-one device for
small business,'' he said. ``Everything you need is right there.''
</P>
<P>
   The company started 31/2 years ago to simplify the complex task
of establishing Internet communications in small businesses and to
remove the barriers preventing nontechnical organizations from
fully participating in the online revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Weiser, executive producer and partner at Compass Rose
Media in Santa Cruz, is sold on the product. ``It's the coolest box
on the planet,'' he said. ``You plug it in and don't know it's
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We produce films and commercial videos and rely on the Web and
electronic communication to an incredible degree. We couldn't do
business where we do without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiser's company learned about the product a couple of years ago
while doing a video for Whistle Communications and quickly dumped
its dedicated server and special software for the easy-to-use
Internet appliance. All nine employees are hooked up for e-mail,
and the company can quickly contact its 100 temp employees as well
as customers in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising Magic of Walnut Creek is another fan. The company,
which stamps logos and custom-printed messages on thousands of
promotional items from mugs and T-shirts to pens and paper clip
holders, had a network computer and half-dozen workstations two
years ago. But it suffered a serious bottleneck getting electronic
information to and from the company.
</P>
<P>
   Clients such as BART, Safeway and radio station K101 e-mailed
their logos and other data to a single computer with Internet
access. And all the final designs similarly had to be funneled to
hundreds of contract manufacturers through the lone Internet access
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employees started coming to me one, then two, then 10
times a day to ask if their art work had come in or been sent
out,'' recalled Vice President Hari Boukis, 33, who runs the small
business with his CEO wife, Rosalind. ``It got to the point I
wasn't getting any other work done. I was an e-mail downloader.''
</P>
<P>
   Boukis began looking for technology solutions to this
information stranglehold and discovered an ad for Whistle's
InterJet in a trade magazine. He was sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``You basically sign up with a small business ISP (Internet
Service Provider), plug one end of the box into the computer hub
and the other into a phone, enter a code number and press go,''
said Boukis. ``A child could set this up.''
</P>
<P>
   The little tan box that Advertising Magic bought from Whistle
for $2,600 in 1997 now costs about $1,500. But Boukis is happy he
didn't wait to buy the system. All eight employees are
e-mail-enabled and together send and receive up to 9,000 messages a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can also send queries and order products at the
company's Web site (www.advertisingmagic.com). Boukis said the
company picks ups as many as 15 new clients a day off the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in large part to its leap to e-commerce, Advertising
Magic anticipates reaching $1.9 million in revenues this year,
compared to $1.3 million last year and about $1 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet appliance convert is Anderson Brule Architects
in San Jose. Two years ago, the firm had e-mail coming in to just
one computer. ``It wasn't working too well,'' said project
architect Krista Falkenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients expected us all to have e-mail, but it was only
checked occasionally, and someone here might not know for two days
that there were drawings or other messages waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, all 40 employees get e-mail in a flash, and Falkenberg
notes that access to Internet research also has made the firm more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &LR;
</P>
