<HEADER>
A7080 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-STATES-RIGHTS-H     06-23 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-STATES-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REDRAWS BORDER BETWEEN STATES' RIGHTS AND FEDERAL AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday severely limited the
ability of people to sue states under federal law, and in the
process it substantially redrew the border between state
sovereignty and federal authority.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision that evoked bitter emotions among the
justices, the court dismissed a lawsuit by a group of
state-employed probation officers in Maine who sought to enforce a
federal labor law and collect overtime pay. The justices also
rejected two lawsuits accusing Florida of violating federal patent
and trademark laws.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the Constitution's ``structure and history''
shields states not only from being sued by individuals in federal
courts but also makes them immune in state courts from individual
lawsuits seeking to enforce a federal right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generation that designed and adopted our federal system
considered immunity from private suits central to sovereign
dignity,'' Justice Anthony Kennedy wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was joined by Chief Justice William Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the court's decision, the state employees in
Maine, who have a right to overtime pay under the 1938 Fair Labor
Standards Act, now have no way to enforce that right themselves.
Their only option is ask the Labor Department to sue the state of
Maine on their behalf in federal court. A lawyer for the probation
officers said Wednesday they had not decided whether to seek the
department's help.
</P>
<P>
   In broader terms, the justices' decision marked another retreat
from decades of expansively interpreted federal authority, which
began with the New Deal era. Especially in recent years, a narrow
but potent majority led by Rehnquist has emphasized that states
have powers that Congress must respect.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the court ruled that Congress had exceeded its
authority when it banned guns near public schools. It threw out the
ban in a San Antonio case, saying the law relied on Congress's
power to regulate interstate commerce but failed to show how such
commerce was involved in areas near local schools.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the court limited Congress's ability to make states
vulnerable to lawsuits in federal court, and in 1997 it said
Congress had overstepped its powers in a section of the so-called
Brady gun control law that forced states to use local law
enforcement officers to perform background checks on gun buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Vazquez, a constitutional law expert at Georgetown
University, said of Wednesday's decisions, ``The court signaled
once again that when it's faced with a dispute between state and
federal rights, states win.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the court's tilt toward state sovereignty likely will
continue so long as the five-justice conservative coalition remains
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fontaine, a Portland, Maine, lawyer who represented the
probation workers, called the ruling against his clients part of
``an extraordinary, conservative revolution against basic civil
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional division on the issue between that coalition and
the court's more liberal justices _ John Paul Stevens, David H.
Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer _ was on display
Wednesday during an extraordinarily long courtroom session that
closed the court's 1998-99 term.
</P>
<P>
   Reading portions of his 51-page opinion, Kennedy emphasized the
importance of a nation built on the idea of two distinct
sovereignties _ the federal government and the individual states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress must accord states the esteem due to them as joint
participants in a federal system,'' he said. ``Congress has vast
power but not all power.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that states ``are not relegated to the role of mere
provinces or political corporations, but retain the dignity, though
not the full authority, of sovereignty. Although the Constitution
begins with the principle that sovereignty rests with the people,
it does not follow that the national government becomes the
ultimate, preferred mechanism for expressing the people's will. The
states exist as a refutation of that concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter responded by reading for 15 minutes from his 58-page
dissenting opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's insistence that the federal structure bars
Congress from making states susceptible to suit in their own courts
is plain wrong,'' he said, adding that the court's reasoning was
``unrealistic'' and ``indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter accused the court majority of creating ``a very peculiar
state of affairs'' for those wanting to enforce their legal rights
against a state government.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maine case, 65 probation officers sued the state in 1992
in federal court, saying they were owed overtime pay guaranteed
under the FLSA.
</P>
<P>
   But while their lawsuit was pending, the Supreme Court ruled in
1996 that the Constitution's 11th Amendment, which limits the
judicial power of the federal government, shields states from being
sued against their will in federal court. With the option of
federal court blocked, the probation officers refiled their lawsuit
in state court, still depending on the FLSA.
</P>
<P>
   However, a year later, a Maine Superior Court in Cumberland
ruled that the 11th Amendment makes states immune from state court
lawsuits that would be barred in federal courts. The court also
said that the 11th Amendment makes a state totally immune from
being sued by employees who allege labor-law violations, although
it said federal labor officials still could sue the state to
enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Maine Supreme Judicial Court agreed with the
decision, and on Wednesday, the nation's highest court affirmed
that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The court's conservative coalition also triumphed in the other
two cases, one on whether states can be sued for patent
infringement in violation of federal law and the other on whether
states can be sued for engaging in false advertising.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In those decisions, the court invoked state sovereign immunity
to shield Florida from having to defend itself in federal courts
against private lawsuits attacking its program to help families
save for the cost of the state's public colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases involved a dispute between College Savings Bank, a
private company in Princeton, N.J., that sells certificates of
deposit for financing future costs of education, and the state of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the first case, College Savings Bank sued Florida, alleging
that the state's program offering a similar product violates
federal patent and trademark laws. College Savings Bank contended
that the Florida Prepaid Postsecondary Education Expense Board
violated the bank's patent for administering its CollegeSure CD.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, College Savings Bank accused the state of
making misstatements about its tuition plans in its brochures and
annual reports, a violation of the federal Trademark Remedy
Clarification Act (TRCA) of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, a U.S. District Court ruled in 1996 that the
state could not be sued in federal court under the TRCA. A year
later, the U.S. Third Circuit Court of Appeals agreed. On
Wednesday, the Supreme Court affirmed the appeals court's rulings
in the cases.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
