<SLUG> BC-SALINGER'S-DAUGHTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALINGER'S DAUGHTER PLANS TO PUBLISH A MEMOIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The daughter of the obsessively private author J.D. Salinger is
preparing to publish a memoir of her childhood and relationship
with her father.
</P>
<P>
   The book by Margaret (Peggy) Salinger, 43, is tentatively titled
``The Dream Catcher'' and is scheduled to be published by Simon &AMP;
Schuster's Pocket Books in the fall of 2000. The news comes the
same week that Salinger's carefully guarded privacy was breached by
the auction of letters that Salinger wrote to the writer Joyce
Maynard in the early 1970s. Ms. Maynard has been fiercely
criticized for writing a memoir, ``At Home in the World,'' that
included details of their nine-month romance when she was an
18-year-old Yale University student and Salinger was 53.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger's memoir is important and ``tells a story of a
child who grew up in a way that was different from what most people
experience,'' said Judith M. Curr, who noted that Ms. Salinger will
also write about her relationship with her father, who is now 80.
Ms. Curr signed the title as her first book since becoming Pocket
Book's president and publisher in April. ``I think that it will be
a wonderful book and will sell for many years to come,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The memoir, plans for which were reported in The New York
Observer this week, has had a tortured history since her literary
agent, Morton Janklow, circulated a sketchy manuscript proposal
about three years ago. Originally Ms. Salinger had signed with
Riverhead Books, an imprint of Penguin Putnam Inc., for a
seven-figure advance to write the memoir, but a conflict developed
with that publisher, Janklow said. ``She was very unhappy for
undefined reasons,'' said Janklow, who added that he urged her to
stay with Riverhead because it was unlikely that she could obtain
as much of an advance elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, he said, Ms. Salinger moved on, also severing her
ties to him with a letter from her lawyer, who also asked Janklow
to return his literary commission.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Curr said she had no doubts about publishing the book
despite Ms. Salinger's split with her previous publisher. People
with knowledge of the split said that the author and Riverhead
parted over changes that Ms. Salinger was asked to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no qualms whatsoever,'' Ms. Curr said. ``If everybody
had only one point of view in publishing we'd only have three books
published every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Curr added that Pocket Books had received no reaction to the
book from Salinger.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger did not respond to a call for comment placed
through her lawyer, Philip M. Cowan, who declined to outline the
contents of her manuscript. Ms. Salinger's current literary agent,
Robert Gottlieb, with the William Morris Agency, also declined to
comment about the book.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger received an advance from Pocket Books of more than
$250,000, which was much smaller than her arrangement with
Riverhead.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright issues came up when the book was being prepared for
publication at Riverhead. In 1987, Salinger blocked the publication
of a biography by Ian Hamilton that relied on unpublished letters
written by Salinger to his editor and friend, Whit Burnett.
Salinger copyrighted the letters to frustrate the author's plan to
quote extensively from them.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Curr said that she expected that copyright issues would
not be a concern with Ms. Salinger's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to observe all copyright laws,'' she said. ``But
it's Peggy's life that she's writing about. I don't believe it's
going to be an issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
