<SLUG> BC-ORFEU-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STUFF OF LEGEND IN A BRAZILIAN SLUM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Even before he emerged as a torchbearer
of the Cinema Novo movement here in the 1960s, the director Carlos
``Caca'' Diegues yearned to film the myth of Orpheus and Eurydice.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he admits, as he was working on the 13 movies on
his resume, including ``Bye-Bye Brazil'' and ``Xica da Silva,''
images of what a Brazilian version of the myth would look and sound
like constantly filled his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that the French director Marcel Camus had already
taken the same ancient Greek legend of a passion so strong that it
surmounts death and transferred it to one of Rio de Janeiro's
favelas, or hillside squatter settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Diegues was always convinced that he could tell the story
better. Now, after more than 40 years of dreams, delays and dashed
hopes, his persistence has paid off: ``Orfeu'' is showing in
Brazilian theaters and may be released later by Warner Brothers in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Diegues is emphatic when he says that his Orpheus ``is not a
remake of the first version, in the same sense that Baz Luhrmann's
`Romeo and Juliet' is not a remake of Zeffirelli's.'' Camus'
``Black Orpheus'' won both the top prize at the Cannes
International Film Festival in 1959 and the Oscar for best foreign
film a year later, but here in Brazil his movie has always been
regarded as overly romanticized and lacking authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian poet and playwright Vinicius de Moraes, whose play
``Orfeu da Conceicao'' was the basis for that film, even asked that
his name be taken off the screenplay, so unhappy was he with the
final result.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Black Orpheus' is not an exploitative film,'' Diegues said.
``You can see that it was made with real affection and enthusiasm.
Camus fell in love with Rio and its culture, but he made a
superficial film about something he didn't really understand. It's
as if I were to go to France to make a movie about Joan of Arc.
That's not to say I don't know anything about her. But there are
others in France who know much more than I could ever hope to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   To restore what he considered the proper tone and focus,
Diegues, who is 59, went back to de Moraes' play, which places
greater emphasis on Orpheus' relationship with his community and
parents. In the original legend, Orpheus, a poet and musician,
descends to the underworld to rescue his beloved, Eurydice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing that play at the Teatro Municipal as a teen-ager in
1956 was one of the principal formative cultural experiences of my
life,'' he said. ``It not only touched me deeply; it made me
discover things about Brazilian reality I had not imagined before
and helped set me on the road to this life I have as a maker of
films.''
</P>
<P>
   Diegues and de Moraes, who is probably best known outside Brazil
as the author of the lyrics to the song ``The Girl From Ipanema,''
became friends during the heyday of Cinema Novo, which combined
magical and social realism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, after Diegues had a worldwide hit with ``Bye-Bye
Brazil,'' the French company Gaumont offered to bankroll any movie
he wanted to make. He immediately chose ``Orfeu'' and enlisted de
Moraes as his partner in writing a new script.
</P>
<P>
   But de Moraes died just as the project was getting under way,
and then rights to the play became tied up in a complicated legal
dispute. More than a decade later, de Moraes' children asked
Diegues whether he was still interested in tackling the story, and
again he jumped at the opportunity to film ``the myth that best
explains the destiny and frustrated vocation of the Brazilian
nation,'' as Caetano Veloso, the singer and songwriter who
supervised the movie's soundtrack, said.
</P>
<P>
   Diegues, his admiration for the play notwithstanding, knew that
he could not hope to duplicate its exact mood or texture. ``This is
a film about Rio at the end of the century, not the Rio of 1956,''
he said. Since the city of today is a much more violent and callous
place, that means Diegues' version of the Orpheus legend has far
more of an edge than either of its predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
