<SLUG> BC-SOC-GORTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADED GORTER TRAINS WITH HIS OLD TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday was Edwin Gorter's first day as a Revolution foe. But
he spent it as a friend. Though player-coach Walter Zenga traded
Gorter to Miami for defender Mario Gori Tuesday, he permitted
Gorter to continue training with the Revolution at Babson College
in Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a normal thing, because Edwin has to train,'' Zenga said.
``He asked me if he could come to training and I didn't have
anything against it. It's the right thing to do, because I made a
deal with (Miami coach) Ivo Wortmann and he is expecting a player
who is in good physical condition.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Gorter went through the conditioning and stretching drills
as the Revolution prepared for Saturday's visit to Dallas. Gorter
submitted to Zenga's general bawling out of the team during a
scrimmage and concluded the session, as usual, with some
light-hearted bets on spot kicks. Then, Gorter drove his black
Volkswagen to Quincy and prepared to move to Fort Lauderdale, where
his new team will meet San Jose Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy for me to go,'' Gorter said. ``But this is the
life of a soccer player. The coaches have made a decision here and
I am sure they can live with their decision. If they lose the next
three or four games, they will have to answer for it. But, again,
that is soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed things and I said I'm not 19, I will turn 36 in
two weeks, and this is the last year of my career. I want to finish
my career in a nice way. I am happy to be going to Miami, which in
my opinion is one of the most beautiful places in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorter's experience with the Revolution was mostly
disillusioning. Former Revolution coach Thomas Rongen billed Gorter
as a rival for Marco Etcheverry and Carlos Valderrama, but midway
through the 1998 season, Gorter had been converted to a defender as
the team took desperate measures to break a losing streak. Zenga
took over as coach, and began planning for this season, even
extending the practice schedule for two weeks after the final game
of the regular season. On the final day of training in October,
Gorter was refereeing a scrimmage that concluded with a
racially-tinged fight between he and David Nakhid.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter was fined $25,000 and suspended two games by the league.
Though Gorter and Zenga seemed compatible then _ they are nearly
the same age, both speak English and Italian _ conflicts soon
became apparent. Gorter did not join the Revolution for preseason
training in Foxborough, instead meeting the team in Italy in
February. Gorter was behind on his conditioning, reasoning that he
did not have to be prepared until the third game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When Gorter finally regained his starting position, against
Columbus April 17, he was replaced in the 55th minute, leading to a
sideline argument with assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi. Gorter
started only twice more in midfield, but was effective at sweeper
in a 2-0 win over Chicago and as a substitute in a 3-3 tie with
Miami in which he converted the tying goal and the deciding goal in
the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   But though Gorter traveled with the Revolution to their last two
games, he was not listed among the substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unlucky here,'' Gorter said. ``At the beginning of the
1998 season we were playing good soccer. But then there were
injuries, red cards, players leaving for the World Cup. I
sacrificed myself, playing 10 games as libero (sweeper), doing my
best for the team. But I don't regret it. I enjoyed my life here
and I will be leaving a lot of friends and I will miss the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Gorter will be expected to fill the midfield slot left
open after Valderrama was sent to Tampa Bay in April.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Revolution appear to be establishing a midfield
with John Harkes and Jair directing the tempo.
</P>
<P>
   Gori was scheduled to arrive in Boston Wednesday night and could
play against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zenga will return to Milan after the game to visit his children.
``I have three kids and I miss them,'' he said. ``It's worth it to
see them even for one day, buy them an ice cream, then say goodbye,
I'll see you at Christmas.'' . . . Zenga confirmed the visit of
former Inter defender Giuseppe Bergomi, possibly when the
Revolution play host to Ajax in an exhibition July 21 or the D.C.
United game July 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
