<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORFEU-FILM-2NDTAKE-$A     06-23 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORFEU-FILM-2NDTAKE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
  
 RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil: its predecessors.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Brazil has a tremendous vocation for killing poor people,''
said Paulo Lins, a novelist and former slum dweller who worked with
Diegues on the script. ``Just look at all the violence that goes on
in the countryside, at the slaughter of street kids in the cities,
at the massacres of prisoners in jails. So I regard this movie as a
tragedy, as a microcosm of what goes on all the time in Brazilian
society.''
</P>
<P>
   To bring the text up to date, Diegues has added the figure of
Lucinho, the drug trafficker and gang leader who controls the
favela where Orfeu (Toni Garrido) and Euridice (Patricia Franca),
fall in love on the eve of Carnival. A boyhood friend of Orfeu,
Lucinho grows up to be as bloodthirsty, unscrupulous and ruthless
as the police whose anger he brings down on the entire community.
</P>
<P>
   The music that was crucial to ``Black Orpheus'' has also been
adjusted to reflect different times. The Camus film helped
introduce the delicate bossa nova to the outside world, but the
music most often heard in Brazilian slums today is rap, and so the
soundtrack includes not only a glorious ballad Veloso composed as a
love theme for Orfeu and Euridice and a jaunty samba, but also some
hard-hitting hip-hop by newer artists as yet unknown abroad.
</P>
<P>
   For the title role, Diegues tested ``more than 120 actors,
musicians and singers from Rio, Sao Paulo and Bahia'' before
settling on Garrido, 32, lead singer of the popular samba-reggae
group Cidade Negra, or Black City. The choice was controversial
here, because Garrido's experience as an actor was scant. But
Garrido brought other assets to the film that, he and Diegues
agree, would have been hard to find elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need a laboratory to learn about the reality this
film portrays,'' Garrido said. ``I'm a black guy who was born in a
favela, and though I was later to live among whites in Copacabana,
I understand the favela's code of honor and know what it means to
be a poor dude who lives for his art and sees it as a trampoline to
better things. I was able to draw on a life experience that is
essential to the poetic sensibility of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrido had never seen the Camus film, and still hasn't: ``Caca
didn't want me to see it, so I didn't,'' he explains. But to
Diegues, that is beside the point. ``Toni doesn't have to interpret
the role of Orfeu,'' he said. ``He is Orfeu, and the fact that he
is a musician means that he can project onto the screen all the
nobility and poetry of Brazilian popular music.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Camus film and some of Diegues' recent movies,
``Orfeu'' has become a certified box-office success here, drawing
more than a million spectators into theaters since its release in
April. But Diegues has also made a point of taking his movie into
the same favelas where many of its scenes were shot, hoping to
assure that residents unable to afford $5 for a ticket have a
chance to see their own reality portrayed on film.
</P>
<P>
   At one such session in April, several thousand people in the
Vigario Geral slum attended a showing organized on their behalf.
Afterward, there was a vigorous discussion of the movie and how the
characters and story line corresponded to daily life in their own
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   One line in particular, uttered by Orfeu and cited by
slumdwellers at all of the screenings, seems to reflect the
bitterness and sense of isolation and neglect they feel: ``The only
thing the government sends up the hill is the police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most gratifying night I have had in connection
with this film, even more than the night of the premiere,'' Diegues
said recently. ``I don't make movies to teach, I make them to
learn, and I'm happy that this movie has been able to throw light
on a subject and a reality that a lot of people would prefer to
ignore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
