<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANGOGH-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      06-23 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANGOGH-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GOGH FEVER SHIFTS TO HIS NEW AMSTERDAM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ When the Van Gogh Museum closed for
renovation and expansion in September, the focus of Vincent worship
shifted to an exhibition of ``Van Gogh's van Goghs'' traveling to
Washington and Los Angeles. In Amsterdam, however, the artist's
unwavering popularity simply assumed a different form, as $35.5
million was spent on preparing the museum to handle ever larger
numbers of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Now less than 10 months later, ``Van Gogh's van Goghs'' have
returned here to find their permanent home transformed by the
addition of a handsome new annex as well as by major refurbishment
of its main building. With the reopening Thursday, the museum can
for the first time display all 207 paintings from its van Gogh
collection and simultaneously organize temporary exhibitions in the
new annex.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of mass museumgoing, museum expansions have, of
course, become common symbols of prestige and prosperity. The
National Gallery of Art in Washington and the Louvre in Paris have
already grown, while the Museum of Modern Art in New York and the
Tate Gallery in London will soon have impressive new annexes. For
the van Gogh Museum, though, more fundamental issues were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd management was certainly a factor. When the museum opened
in 1973, it estimated that 60,000 would visit a year; by 1986 there
were 600,000 visits each year, and by 1990 annual attendance had
leveled off at 1.2 million. With the $14.5 million redesign, a new
office building has freed space for more exhibition room and a more
spacious lobby and museum shop. New lighting and air-conditioning
have also been installed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no matter how many tourists include it on their ``must see''
list, any museum dedicated to a sole, dead artist risks becoming a
mausoleum. And there lies the importance of the $21 million annex
designed by Japanese architect Kisho Kurokawa. The museum is
counting on temporary exhibitions to keep it vigorous, starting
with one dedicated to van Gogh's dealer and collector brother,
Theo, through Sept. 5, followed by ``From Cezanne to van Gogh: The
Collection of Dr. Gachet,'' which is at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Having identified the key to its future a decade ago, though,
the museum still faced opposition to its plan to place an
ultramodern building on the Museumplein, the vast expanse of green
that stretches from the venerable Rijksmuseum to the no less
revered Concertgebouw, home of Amsterdam's famed symphony
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   When the design was unveiled in 1991, an action committee was
promptly formed to block the project. Only after five years of
arguing did a Dutch court finally give the go-ahead for
construction of the annex.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was familiar because the museum itself has never been
a much loved building here. Its design was based on sketches made
in 1963 by Gerrit Rietveld, a septuagenarian architect who belonged
to the Stijl movement in the 1920s and whose modernist ideas looked
outdated when the museum was inaugurated in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Vincent Willem van Gogh, Theo's son, who ceded his
collection to the museum, answered critics with a prescient phrase:
``This was our approach, but in 25 years they will perhaps have
completely different ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. The new annex was made possible by a $18 million
donation from Japan's Yasuda Fire and Marine Insurance Co. Ltd.,
which owns one of van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' paintings. Along with
the gift came the suggestion that Kurokawa serve as the project's
architect. In accepting the deal, museum officials were
acknowledging that no attempt would be made to echo Rietveld's
building, and that the strong personality of Kurokawa's style would
inevitably make itself felt on the Museumplein.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the museum's geometric lines, the freestanding
annex has the form of a slightly rotated ellipse, itself divided
between a three-floor building and a sunken courtyard,
imperceptibly sloping so that water can trickle across it like a
broad horizontal fountain. The materials used here and their
predominantly gray colors, inspired by twilight in Kyoto, are also
unusual for Amsterdam: granite for the curvilinear facade
overlooking the Museumplein; titanium for the convex roof and
poolside elevation, and aluminum for the box-shaped room that
protrudes over the courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from the Museumplein, the annex looks somewhat bunkerlike
and, even though Kurokawa said he was seeking ``symbiosis of
environment and architecture,'' it appears to make little attempt
to integrate with its surroundings. On the other hand, viewed from
the museum or the public path separating the two buildings, where
nothing but the annex can be seen, it is both striking in
appearance and welcoming. And this impression is reinforced as
visitors take an escalator from the museum down to the sunken
courtyard, with the passage between buildings barely noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Kurokawa, 65, who already has a dozen museums to his name, again
uses the word symbiosis to describe his fusion of Japanese and
European cultures in the museum annex. Indeed, his original idea
was to turn the courtyard into a Japanese garden, although its
present austere emptiness is perhaps more appropriate. Even so,
some critics have noted that a distinctly Japanese concern for
detail is evident in the immaculate finishing of the annex's
interiors, with their wooden floors, glass and steel doors and
metal gray sun screens.
</P>
<P>
   For many tourists, of course, word that the Van Gogh Museum has
reopened is good news enough. After the museum closed last year, an
official was stationed for weeks at its entrance to explain
patiently to disappointed tourists why they could not enter this
shrine to van Gogh. Now on the museum's spacious second floor and
third-floor study area, they can study van Gogh's paintings from as
early as 1881 in the Netherlands to just days before his suicide on
July 29, 1890, in France.
</P>
<P>
   For those able to glance away from the van Goghs long enough to
contemplate the architecture, however, the courtyard gallery of the
annex is presenting a retrospective of Kurokawa's work through Nov.
14 with drawings, photographs and models of his best known projects
in Japan and Europe. The rest of the annex is given over to the
exhibition dedicated to Theo van Gogh, which includes works by
Monet, Gauguin and Toulouse-Lautrec, with whom Theo collaborated.
</P>
<P>
   For those accustomed to walking past the Van Gogh Museum,
however, there can be no overlooking the new annex. If they worry
that it looks intrusive, though, they should hold their judgment.
The entire Museumplein is being redesigned by the Danish landscape
architect Sven-Ingvar Andersson. And beside the van Gogh Museum the
Stedelijk Museum is planning its own extension, designed by the
Portuguese architect Alvaro Siza. Amsterdammers will soon have
still more to argue about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
