<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-23 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANDES RISING': MISSING MAN, RARE BIRD AND THE GREATER MYSTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD EDER   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is, or was, a children's game in which one player names
three things utterly unlike _ a locomotive, say, a wad of chewed
gum, a canary _ and another tries to weave them into a story. The
connections were strained and the narrative rickety, but it gave
the imagination a jolt. At the least it was fun, and every so often
it knocked loose an enticing image or idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andes Rising,'' as uneven as the mountains themselves and with
several mountaintop views, assembles the following:
</P>
<P>
   A California rabbi, part mystic and part chicken-soup practical,
who sets out in search of:
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged physicist, sickened by his work on nuclear
weapons, who joins the Peace Corps in Colombia and mysteriously
disappears there. He had devoted himself to studying Colombian
birds; his model and imaginary antagonist was:
</P>
<P>
   Frank Chapman, an eminent ornithologist who from 1908 to 1935
shot and set up the specimens in the vast bird collection at the
American Museum of Natural History in New York.
</P>
<P>
   From these, James Munves has put together a fanciful artichoke
of a novel. It consists of a spiral of leaves and a heart, but the
leaves are of assorted shapes and flavors, and some are missing;
and though they lead to the heart they do it erratically and only
partly attached. The heart is a parable about the conflict between
progress and the irreplaceable particulars of humanity and nature.
</P>
<P>
   Start with a few of the leaves. First: Rabbi Teitelbaum,
displaced from a comfortable California life by the importunings of
Sadie Cooper, his sister-in-law's sister-in-law's mother-in-law. A
news item has convinced her that Thomas Cooper, her physicist
son-turned-Peace Corps-bird lover, did not perish in a Colombian
rock slide nine years earlier but is alive somewhere in the
country's interior.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum must find him. The mission is comically improbable
but the rabbi, a Talmudist with cabalistic leanings, conceals a
boundlessly inquisitive spirit under his rationalization _ namely,
that ``Sadie was a widow, which it is my duty to help. Also she
happens to be the biggest benefactor of Sholom Tefila.''
</P>
<P>
   First, in Miami, he talks to a Hungarian, Arpad, who ``looked
like a fruit salad, in a green and orange shirt, yellow shorts,
white sneakers, red hair and mustaches.'' Arpad had been kidnapped
by a band of armed men in Colombia, exhibited in a cage and then
set free (Sadie's news item). The band's leader wore a watch like
Thomas' and seemed to know English (the tenuous basis for the
rabbi's mission).
</P>
<P>
   Freed along with Arpad, Teitelbaum tells us, were the birds he
had ostensibly been collecting. This crooked Papageno's catches,
though, were ``stuffed with cocaine and are now flying all over the
jungle.'' So, were the armed men after the drugs? Could they
conceivably be bird liberationists?
</P>
<P>
   It is here that Thomas makes his appearance; not in person but
in diaries that Teitelbaum locates, after a series of nervous
forays in a remote Colombian farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The diaries recount Thomas' story. There are brief allusions to
his work at Los Alamos and to his presence at an underground
nuclear explosion. There is a later conversation about the 1950s
disarmament talks between the United States and the Soviet Union.
Thomas, an adviser to the U.S. delegation, became convinced that
neither side was serious about disarming.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a sketch, jerry-built to explain Thomas' retreat
years later to the Eastern Andes to study birds for a Peace Corps
project. It contrasts with the artful and suggestive account,
tinged with mystery, of his life with the birds, his discovery of a
tanager never before seen in that part of Colombia and his refusal
to shoot specimens and bring them back to Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian authorities, anxious to justify the ornithological
project, insisted; Thomas' Peace Corps superior, though
sympathetic, turned up with a rifle to do the job. It was at that
point that the rock slide occurred: seemingly though not certainly
burying Thomas and sealing up access to the tanagers' domain.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' fate remains cloudy (though it is more jerry-building to
imply that he  &UR; might &LR;  have organized pro-bird guerrillas. How? With
whom?). So does the possibility that he might have triggered the
slide himself.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such holes and haste, ``Andes Rising'' does some
remarkable things. Munves beautifully evokes Thomas' temporary
Andes Eden. The discussion of birds, the detailed distinctions of
markings and habitat go on at length; yet they are not tedious. On
the contrary, they are uplifting. They are part of the theme.
</P>
<P>
   Their scrupulous notation signals something larger. Thomas had
fled the deadly scientific universals he had known in Los Alamos to
live among Andean particulars. Seeing his tanager just once or
twice was enough; science and scientific bureaucracy demand
reproducibility _ and dead birds.
</P>
<P>
   Against odds, the parable largely works. So does the recurring
dialogue between an unraveling Thomas and the dead Chapman, author
of classic studies of Colombian and American birds. He had brought
back 10,000 ``skins'' of shot specimens. Why shoot even one?,
Thomas demands of the ghost. ``Science is not for sissies,'' his
interlocutor retorts. ``Nature is red in tooth and claw. ``They are
more alive than we are,'' protests Thomas. ``The air goes into
their bones.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Rabbi Teitelbaum has been scrawling comments on
the pages of the diary. He is pedantic, captious, perplexed. ``Can
birds be a religion?,'' he wonders. In Talmudic fashion, though, he
wrestles until he sees that they may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Thomas saying plowshares are no better than swords? Shades
of Isaiah and Micah! A terrible question.  &UR; Everything &LR;  we do causes
suffering?!,'' the rabbi scrawls upon the ex-scientist's challenges
to civilization and science itself. He gives his answer which, in
keeping with Talmudic paradox, is no answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear of the Lord of the Universe whom no mind can fathom
and no thought can attain, we must retreat from, step back from the
abyss, tempted to jump. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Bit by bit, Teitelbaum in the Andes has wrestled Thomas'
contemporary ecological protest back to the ancient irreconcilable
mysteries. Mysteries they remain.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANDES RISING'
</P>
<P>
   By James Munves
</P>
<P>
   189 pages. New Directions. $21.95.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7089 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-0624     06-23 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-0624-1STLD-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 9th graf, deletes sentence that begins 'It seeks a list
...' and subs sentence that begins 'It called publicly Wednesday
for the Yugoslav government ...'
 &HT;    SISTER SEARCHES FOR BROTHER, REMINDS WORLD OF PRISONERS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN-0624.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ They were just four scraggly thieves
hitchhiking on a wooded roadside, but they held clues in Albana
Koshi's desperate search.
</P>
<P>
   Through her car window, they told her they had been cutting
bread in the kitchen of a Serb jail, so they knew that 150 men from
Koshi's town had been there.
</P>
<P>
   Further, prison officials told them the men were headed north
out of Kosovo province to a city in Serbia. Finally, the thieves
said, they recognized Koshi's brother, Alban(CQ), among them.
</P>
<P>
   As the world now watches ethnic Albanian refugees return to a
NATO-controlled Kosovo, for Koshi and thousands of others from her
region the war is over but not resolved. Their relatives are
missing and, it appears, have been taken to Serbia before the Serbs
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   While many in this decimated region of southwestern Kosovo were
still sifting through the ruins of their burned homes, Koshi
started a list of 300 missing men and began searching for clues.
</P>
<P>
   The trail of the missing men leads past the sad streets of
Djakovica, to execution sites and a building filled with women and
children used as human shields.
</P>
<P>
   The search has taken Koshi, a 25-year-old architecture student,
to abandoned factories, the offices of NATO commanders and an
apprehensively accepted volunteer post with the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   This week, she began leading her community in protests to draw
attention to what may become a major lingering issue as the haze of
destruction clears in war-shattered Kosovo, the southern province
of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic. Some estimate more than
1,000 men may be still held by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Daloni Carlisle of the International Committee of the Red Cross
said her group is now negotiating in the Yugoslav capital of
Belgrade with the Serb government. It called publicly Wednesday for
the Yugoslav government to release the list of names of Kosovar
Albanians being held in Serb prisons.
</P>
<P>
   However, Carlisle notes that mothers still sit outside the Red
Cross office in Bosnia, awaiting word on sons taken in the conflict
that ended there in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Time is the enemy of the missing men from Kosovo. Prisoners
released during the NATO bombing report being tortured and starved.
As Shkendije(CQ) Hoda, KLA deputy commander for information in
Djakovica says, ``I hope they won't change from prisons to death
camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Djakovica was an area of heavy fighting between the KLA and the
Serbs. The civilians paid the price of Serb revenge. Most of the
town is burned out and looted. More than 100 mass graves have been
found in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO troops entered on June 12 the destruction ended. But,
dreams of family reunions are fading away and the rumors run with
false leads about missing men.
</P>
<P>
   The petit and somber Koshi is a leader in the effort to find
them.
</P>
<P>
   She has set up shop in the KLA office now. There, encouraged by
radio requests, dozens of people come daily with information about
mass graves and missing people.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA is the best resource for information. But, Koshi is not
the military type. While others around her have camouflage and
Soviet-made Kalishnikovs, she wears jeans and resists pressure to
wear a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this,'' she says in a whisper, ``I am doing just for my
brother. I have told them that.''
</P>
<P>
   Albana Koshi was two years old when Alban was born and she has
always called him ``Locka,'' (pronounced ``LOACH-ka''). It means
``sweetheart.'' He is the only boy between two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   In a picture she carries, she is pulling his long hair back into
a ponytail to prepare for high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Serious like his sister, Alban studied economics and wants to go
into business. He stays away from politics.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother is a teacher and their father worked in a travel
agency until he lost his job five years go. They lived in a tall
stone house in the old Ottoman bazaar area of town. Koshi's
great-grandfather was born in the house more than 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bazaar was meticulously destroyed by several nights of Serb
arson after NATO began the bombing campaign. The Koshi house stands
gutted.
</P>
<P>
   The Koshis moved in with three other newly-homeless families
and, like the rest of Djakovica, stayed inside for weeks eating
bread and cheese, watching television report the bombing and hiding
from Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   After a fierce battle between the Serbs and KLA separatist
guerillas on a hill near town, the Serbs told ethnic Albanians to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   The Koshis left May 10, walking to the bus station for a ride to
southern Kosovo and, possibly, Albania. But, after a few blocks,
Serb police stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   They said they just wanted to take Alban briefly and then drop
him off at the bus station.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of the war, this was what he was afraid
of,'' Albana recalls.
</P>
<P>
   As she talks, she is preparing for her fourth meeting with
Italian NATO troops. Normally stoic, she cries when asked Alban's
parting words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'You may go. I will be back soon. Don't be afraid,'''
she says in her strained English. ``He said, 'It's OK. Don't
worry.'''
</P>
<P>
   But, Alban never showed up at the bus. He was gathered with
hundreds of other young men near a park in the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the trail gets murky. Many were taken to a small
metal shop on the edge of town, which Albana has searched
unsuccessfully for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of the prisoners' wives and children were taken nearby
and held in an appliance factory. The Serb police had been using
the factory but now they stayed out, guarding the doors with guns
from far away.
</P>
<P>
   Most suspect the Serbs hoped NATO would think the factory was
still used by the police and bomb the human shields. But, three
days later they released the women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the account of the four thieves, Koshi believes many of
the men were taken to Pec, a city in western Kosovo. From there,
some were trucked to Serbia and others sent to another Kosovo city
where some were executed.
</P>
<P>
   A survivor turned up back in Djakovica and looked at a
photograph of Alban.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he saw him in the group headed for execution. But
Koshi says Alban looks much like a cousin who is also missing.
Either one, then, may have been executed. The other would be in the
Serb prison.
</P>
<P>
   She has not told her parents about the inconclusive photo
identification.
</P>
<P>
   As she searches, life slowly returns to Djakovica, an mostly
agrarian town of about 70,000. The first few stores have reopened
and bicyclists line the streets.
</P>
<P>
   But, on any corner you can find people missing relatives and
tears come quickly when they tell their stories. Koshi looks down
the main street and knows life is not normal for the people of
Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all with broken hearts,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
