<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, June 24. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-STATES-RIGHTS (Washington) _ State governments cannot be
sued against their will in state courts by people seeking to
enforce some federal right, the Supreme Court said Wednesday in a
major decision on states' rights. In a richly written 5-4 ruling,
the court said that the Constitution's ``structure and history''
shields states not only from being sued in federal courts, but also
makes them immune from individuals' state court lawsuits seeking to
enforce a federal right. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ASBESTOS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court sets aside a
$1.5 billion landmark settlement that was to have resolved the
claims of as many as 186,000 victims of asbestos poisoning against
Fibreboard Corp., one of the leading makers of products using the
fire-retardant substance. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   AMA-UNIONS (Undated) _ After its members viewed themselves for
decades as elite professionals who did not need a union, the
American Medical Association voted yesterday to seek to unionize
doctors in a move described as an effort to level the playing field
with powerful managed care organizations. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BORDER (Planeje, Yugoslavia) _ This village of 29
families _ nearly all the men are bakers __ was more or less
leveled in near-daily attacks by NATO planes in the weeks before
the peace agreement was signed. This village and others nearby are
at the foot of Mount Pastrik, where some of the most furious
fighting of the war took place. At the time, refugees crossing the
border into Albania could actually hear the NATO bombs whistle down
before exploding. Now some are returning to see the damage NATO has
done, and nearly everyone thinks NATO nonetheless has an obligation
to help them rebuild. By Ian Fisher. With photos. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MARINES _ U.S. Marines manning a checkpoint in Kosovo are
shot at by unknown persons came and then returned fire, killing two
people. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE-LEAGUE-TUTORS (Chicago) _ In another sign that American
childhood has become a serious venture, some parents are paying $70
an hour, sometimes more, to private coaches to sharpen the skills
of their Little League ballplayers. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AGENDA (Washington) _ President Clinton returns from
Europe with a fairly expansive political and policy agenda. Plans
to intensify battery of Republicans for failure of gun legislation,
announce a new environmental initiative, unveil his Medicare plan
and tour poverty-mired regions from Appalachia to an Indian
reservation to talk about new investment to help the poor. Heavy
fund-raising schedule for congressional Democrats and continuing
efforts to juggle the competing Clinton, Hillary, Gore agendas. By
John Broder.
</P>
</TEXT>
