<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESK-CHAIRS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THOROUGHBREDS OF DESK CHAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desk chairs, or task chairs, as they are now called in the trade
(to distinguish them from those thronelike executive models), are
no longer just pieces of furniture bought to match a desk. A good
chair, the ergonomists tell us, is probably the single most
important office tool.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who sits for more than two hours a day should invest in
an ergonomically designed seat, said Dr. Gregory Lutz, the chief of
physiatry and an assistant professor of rehabilitation medicine at
the Hospital for Special Surgery in Manhattan. A good chair should
support the curvature of the lower spine, Lutz said. ``But no two
people are shaped alike,'' he said, ``so a proper desk chair must
be adjustable.'' Indeed, sitting long hours in a chair with a
straight back can be a source of great pain, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Designers are heeding the experts' advice by creating chairs
that mimic the shape and even the articulation of the human
skeleton. Chairs can now move effortlessly with the body and give
support in the appropriate places.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Newman, an orthotist in Philadelphia, also advises people
to look for a chair that has not skimped on the quantity or the
quality of foam padding. ``You shouldn't have to put a seat insert
or back support into a good desk chair,'' Newman said. ``With
inferior foam, your sit bones will bottom out.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree, though, that lack of movement during the day is a
major culprit in back pain. Movement increases circulation and
lubricates the spine. But modernity conspires against mobility:
E-mail keeps us posted at our desks, and electronic gossip makes
jaunts to the water cooler less frequent. Try to break for 10
minutes every hour, doctors advise. Walk, stretch, go and gossip.
</P>
<P>
   1. The Hag Capisco chair won a silver award for its ergonomic
design at this month's Neocon, the office furniture trade show in
Chicago. The Equestrian model, with its saddle seat and stubby
arms, permits full mobility. Sit frontward, sideways or backward;
the saddle shape keeps legs comfortably apart. The height of the
seat, lumbar support and head rest are adjustable, as are seat tilt
and depth. If saddles are not to your taste, the chair can be
ordered with a round or ``waterfall'' seat. It's $575 at BP
Associates, 200 Lexington Ave. (32nd Street), New York.
</P>
<P>
   2. Niels Diffrient's Freedom Chair was also a silver award
winner at Neocon. Once the height of the seat, back and head rest
are set, no further adjustments are necessary, because the frame,
modeled on the human spine, shifts position with the user. The head
rest automatically slides into place as the chair reclines. The
synchronized arm rests also move in tandem so that they are always
at the same level. Fully loaded, with a head rest and a gel seat,
the chair is $875 from Humanscale, (800) 400-0625.
</P>
<P>
   3. The Scio chair by Hag is smaller and less elaborate than the
Capisco, but it's fully adjustable. The tilt adjusts automatically
in response to the movements of the user. It is $375 from BP
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   4. Neocon's gold medal went to the Leap chair, by Steelcase. The
upper and lower back adjust separately, and the chair's ``spine''
conforms to the user's back. When the chair reclines, the seat
glides forward, but the user's visual field is unchanged. It's
$1,050 from Steelcase, (800) 227-2960 or www.steelcase.com.
</P>
<P>
   5. The adjustable Tom chair, by Tom Deacon, a Canadian
industrial designer, has a seat that actually extends in front
without leaving a gap in the back that could create an incorrect
seat position. It has a flexible back made of durable
glass-reinforced nylon. The chair can be ordered in three seat
depths and two seat widths. It's $770 from Keilhauer, (800)
724-5665 or www.keilhauer.com.
</P>
<P>
   6. Alexander Polakov, a 6-foot graphic designer at Designframe,
a Manhattan studio, has used his Pezzi Hi-Fit exercise ball as a
seat for a year, as have four other designers at the studio. For
anyone without back or spine problems, it's a comfortable
alternative to the traditional desk chair. Legs are kept at the
proper angle for sitting (knees lower than hips), and they remain
comfortably apart and flexible. Because the ball gives, the body is
constantly moving, just as it should be. The exercise ball is
$27.25 from the Equipment Shop in Bedford, Mass., (800) 525-7681.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
