<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-MEN-BOS &LR;      06-23 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS BEGIN FLOWING ABOUT DISNEY `DEATH TRAP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a place of clean streets, pastel homes, wide front porches
and a town square worthy of a movie set. It is life as Disney has
designed it. And there is no design for death in a place called
Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But sudden and violent death has struck Celebration, Fla.,
(population 2,200) four times now in recent months and lawyers in
Florida and families in Attleboro are now asking questions _ legal
questions _ about how well the town, a Disney subsidiary, designed
its roadways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this a death trap,'' said William Osborne, attorney for
an 18-year-old who plunged to her death in a man-made pond in
Celebration last November.
</P>
<P>
   As the bodies of three Attleboro, Mass. men, who died in those
same waters near Disney World last September, were prepared for a
final journey home Wednesday their families consulted funeral
directors _ and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated about sluggish response to requests to search the
pond and puzzled by the design of the roadway that leads to it,
relatives of Scott Renquin, 35, Dan Nelson, 32, and Roger
DesVergnes, 31, are considering a courtroom fight against a planned
community where they died and its owner, the corporate titan named
Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three families have voiced the opinion that this needs to
be done to see if Disney or Celebration (the planned community
opened by Disney in 1994) or both are responsible for this,'' said
Julie Renquin, Scott's sister-in-law. ``We're going to speak to a
lawyer about all that.''
</P>
<P>
   If the families file suit, they could join an emerging legal
fight on behalf of Sarah Kuser, the Casselberry, Fla. teenager who
died there two months after the Attleboro men's vehicle jumped the
curb into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no barricades,'' said Osborne. ``There were no
signs. There was nothing to alert people that this was a dead-end.
All you saw was a black void.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said Kuser was speeding when struck the curb
and went into the pond. Toxicology reports placed her blood-alcohol
level at .15, or nearly double Florida's legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Orlando said Wednesday that autopsies on the three
Attleboro men are complete, but the causes of their deaths are not
being released until later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said police notified them that the each of the
men, found Monday submerged in the sports utility vehicle they
rented at the Orlando airport last September, carried wallets with
identification.
</P>
<P>
   The pond, about 200 feet across at its widest point, is at the
end of an isolated stretch of road that ends at a T-intersection
just a few yards short of a steep 15-foot embankment leading to the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Waters, a spokeswoman for Celebration, said the posted
speed limit is 35 mph, and there is a stop sign with a flashing
light on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   She said that work being done now to erect a wall where the
vehicles plunged into the pond is not a response to the four
fatalities there last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been part of our long-term development plan since
before April 1998,'' Waters said. ``But our hearts go out to these
families. This is clearly a very unfortunate situation. We have
taken every step on our part to make sure those roads meet or
exceed all standards for construction, signage and visuals.''
</P>
<P>
   But Matthew Ryder, Renquin's brother-in-law, said the families
want to know whether there has been ``wrongdoing'' that contributed
to the deaths of the three vacationing men. He said a family friend
has referred them to an attorney in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issue here is that they created a dangerous
situation,'' said Osborne, who said his lawsuit on behalf of
Kuser's family is imminent. Osborne, who said he has sued Disney
before, expects a vigorous fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney and Celebration have got risk managers with a lot of
experience and it's going to be a real fight for anybody bringing a
case on behalf of these three gentlemen,'' said Osborne. ``Disney
is a big force here in Central Florida. Disney's image is very
squeaky clean and they're very conscientious about protecting that
image.''
</P>
<P>
   The intersection where the accident occurred was designed by
Celebration's consultants. Local county officials made sure the
roadway met its standards. Waters said the road is now in the
process of being accepted by the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about five different jurisdictional agencies who
play a role there,'' the Celebration spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Wood, a Boston attorney who has defended towns as well as
private citizens in lawsuits over roadways, said the would-be
plaintiffs in the case have their work cut out for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody saw the accident,'' Wood said. ``It's going to be
difficult to assess if they were driving responsibly or what their
state of mind was at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's going to present some challenges of proving
they went off the road because of road design,'' she said. ``But
the more times it happens, the stronger the case for the plaintiffs
that there should have been a warning.''
</P>
<P>
   A warning is precisely what Maurice Ross said he wished he had
when he, too, plunged into the retention pond on Nov. 15, precisely
one week after Sarah Kuser's Toyota sank into the water there.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and a friend were returning from Pleasure Island at 2 a.m.,
trying to find the on-ramp to Interstate 4. When he spotted what he
believed to be a highway entrance ahead, he headed for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those guys from Attleboro were just like me,'' Ross
said in a telephone interview Wednesday. ``They thought it was an
entrance to get on I-4. The next thing they knew, they were
airborne. They keep saying it's the driver's fault, but people are
going to make the same mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who with his friend managed to scramble to safety, added:
``Personally, I just think they should close it down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Brad Liston contributed to this report from
Florida.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
