<HEADLINE>
DIAMOND MP3 PLAYER ADDS LISTENING TIME 
INTERNET CAMERA TO CAPTURE THE BEST OF BABY VIDEOS 
HOW DO THEY DO IT? THE SCIENCE OF SPORTS, ONLINE 
SOUPED-UP BATTERY TO HANDLE THOSE POWER-GREEDY LAPTOPS 
STICKIES AND HIGHLIGHTER PENS ARE PUT TO WORK ON THE WEB  
A HANDHELD TRUE TO ITS NAME, WITH A KEYBOARD FOR THE PATIENT 
SOFTWARE WILL HOLD YOUR HAND WHEN YOU SWITCH COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (rk) 
(No byline) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good deal of the talk at this year's PC Expo, the annual
computer fair in New York, was about MP3, the sound-compression
software that has teen-agers' Internet connections humming and
music-industry professionals nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Multimedia Systems, which made portable MP3 music a
household term with its Rio 300 player last fall, has introduced an
improved model. Called the Rio 500, the new player features twice
the 32-megabyte storage of the Rio 300 and can be upgraded to 96
megabytes of flash memory (providing more than two hours of music).
It sells for $269, $100 more than the original Rio 300 now costs.
</P>
<P>
   The new player, which is smaller and has a larger LCD screen,
also uses a more secure downloading scheme to help ensure that
products will not be illegally obtained or copied easily, which is
a major concern to many music company executives, who have been
slow to embrace MP3. And unlike the old player, the new one can
read various compression formats besides popular MP3 music files,
including long-playing books on tape.
</P>
<P>
   The new player was one of several changes at Diamond, including
the spinning off of a new company, Rioport, which will concentrate
on developing Rio portable players, and the software that enables
them to download and play MP3 music and other files from the
Internet, as well as on providing a special portal Web site to make
downloading simpler and more secure.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3 portable market is starting to get crowded. Creative Lab
has released the Nomad, which comes with an FM radio tuner and
voice recorder, and Samsung has released Yepp, which, at 2.3
ounces, is the smallest of the three MP3 portables. The Yepp also
has a radio, recorder and a 500-name telephone directory, making it
the first one with a PDA-style feature.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   Internet Camera to Capture The Best of Baby Videos
</P>
<P>
   As if MP3 wasn't confusing enough, here comes MPEG-4. At PC
Expo, Sharp Electronics introduced the Internet Viewcam, the first
consumer product to use MPEG-4, a new video-compression format.
That means you won't just be getting baby pictures over the
Internet; you'll be getting baby video.
</P>
<P>
   The MPEG-4 format squeezes videos into files that can be quickly
uploaded and downloaded from the Net over dial-up modems. The
camera, which also works as a digital still camera, sells for $699
(available online at www.sharp-usa.com), is slightly larger than a
pack of cards and is 8.5 ounces with batteries and memory card.
</P>
<P>
   Because the videos taken with the Internet Viewcam are
compressed, the movies aren't exactly theater quality. But Sharp
expects a lot of interest in the camera and the format. ``Which
would you rather send in e-mail?'' said D. Michael Lyons, an
associate vice president for marketing at Sharp. ``One JPEG image
or 10 seconds of video?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   How Do They Do It? The Science of Sports, Online
</P>
<P>
   Skateboarders may have a reputation for being public nuisances,
but even their most vocal critics must admit that some of their
tricks are pretty cool. How, for example, do skateboarders manage
to leap over chasms while still keeping their boards with them,
seemingly stuck to the soles of their shoes _ a maneuver known as
``the Ollie''?
</P>
<P>
   The secret, as any good boarder could tell you, has to do with
rotation around multiple axes. The physics of this trick, and many
others, is explored on Skateboard Science
(www.exploratorium.edu/skateboarding). It's one of several sports
science resources developed recently by the Exploratorium, a museum
of science and art in San Francisco, and is one of the few
scientific sites to use the word ``McTwist.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   Souped-Up Battery to Handle Those Power-Greedy Laptops
</P>
<P>
   At three-eighths of an inch thick and a little larger than a
sheet of standard office paper, the new battery from Electrofuel
looks like a miniature welcome mat.
</P>
<P>
   On closer examination, this lithium-ion superpolymer power pack
promises welcome relief: Almost doubling the previous record of
rechargeable batteries, the superpolymer battery, called the Power
Pad, can run power-greedy laptops for more than 15 hours, the
company said. In many cases, that is about 10 times the battery
capacity of many portable computers on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Pad 160 computer battery, which sells for $499, is
encased in a titanium shell, fits beneath a laptop and connects by
way of the computer's AC adaptor.
</P>
<P>
   The two-pound battery can also power, among other things,
cellular telephones, camcorders and PDAs.
</P>
<P>
   At a demonstration this week at the PC Expo, a Power Pad
provided the energy to drive an electric-motor-assisted bicycle.
And you could slip it into a saddle bag.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   Stickies and Highlighter Pens Are Put to Work on the Web
</P>
<P>
   A new company called Keeboo is bringing yellow stickies and
highlighter pens to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Keeboo has created software that enables people to pull together
materials from online and off-line, bind them together in a virtual
book, apply something like digital Post-It notes, highlight
passages and send the book through e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The recipients do not need Keeboo software to open the attached
books. They need only to click on the e-mail message's attached
``.exe'' file, which will open the book in their Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as the new communication medium for the Web,''
Michel Safars, Keeboo's president and CEO, said at an unveiling of
the software at PC Expo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The software, which is free and can be downloaded at
www.keeboo.com, uses the old-fashioned book as an organizational
guide. (The name Keeboo is a playful rearrangement of the letters
in ``book.'') To create a book, users drag icons of Web addresses
or Windows folders and drop them into the blank pages of Keeboo.
</P>
<P>
   A table of contents appears and is updated with each drop. A
window of editing tools, including highlighter pens and stickies of
varying colors, hovers near the Keeboo pages to help make the
freshest Web page look like an old library book.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Handheld True to Its Name, With a Keyboard for the Patient
</P>
<P>
   Though the latest handheld computers look and feel less like
handhelds and more like notebook computers, with bigger keyboards
and screens, Hewlett-Packard's recently released Jornada 680 aims
for a happy compromise: a handheld that actually fits in the hand
yet offers a keyboard almost big enough to type on.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing just over a pound, the 680 ($899) is smaller than a
paperback novel and about half the size and weight of its Jornada
820 sibling ($999). Though Hewlett-Packard says the 680's keyboard
is only three-quarters of the size of a standard keyboard, limited
touch-typing is possible with patience and practice. A built-in 56K
modem provides quick Internet connections, and the 680's 6.5-inch
color screen sharply displays Web pages containing graphics and
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The screen is touch-sensitive; a stylus is used for tapping
icons and choosing menus. The built-in pocket-size Windows CE
applications are compatible with their full-size Microsoft
counterparts on a desktop computer, which the 680 can connect to.
</P>
<P>
   The 680's rechargeable battery is estimated to last up to eight
hours. An optional expansion card connects the 680 to a desktop
monitor or projector, serving up Powerpoint presentations on the
road without having to haul a heavier notebook PC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Hutsko
</P>
<P>
   Software Will Hold Your Hand When You Switch Computers
</P>
<P>
   Making the transition from an old computer to a new one can be a
hassle. You've got to redo your shortcuts, reorganize your desktop
and reset the toolbars on your applications.
</P>
<P>
   So Miramar Systems, a software company based in Santa Barbara,
Calif., has created a piece of software, Desktop DNA, that
remembers everything for you and then transfers those settings into
your new computer. Neal Rabin, Miramar's chief executive, says home
users will be able to buy the software for $69 by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey
</P>
