<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-PHILHARMONIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMON RATTLE WILL DIRECT BERLIN PHILHARMONIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra on Wednesday elected
the British conductor Sir Simon Rattle to succeed its chief
conductor, Claudio Abbado, who is to step down from one of
classical music's most prestigious posts in September 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Rattle, 44, who made his name as chief conductor of the City of
Birmingham Symphony Orchestra in Britain, will be the sixth head of
the Berlin Philharmonic in its 117-year history. The orchestra's
dominant postwar conductor was Herbert von Karajan, who was
succeeded by Abbado in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote by the 112 full-time members of the orchestra, Rattle
was chosen over Daniel Barenboim, musical director of the German
State Opera in Berlin and the Chicago Symphony Orchestra. Berlin
Philharmonic chairman Rudolf Watzel said Rattle was elected ``by a
great majority'' and had accepted the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   An intense search for a new chief conductor began as soon as
Abbado, 66, announced last year that he would leave the post to
concentrate on his personal life. Numerous candidates were
considered, but in recent weeks German and British newspapers
reported that the contenders had been reduced to Rattle and
Barenboim.
</P>
<P>
   Rattle, who has frequently worked with the Berlin Philharmonic,
won plaudits from Berlin critics this month when he conducted the
orchestra in programs that included music by Mozart, Mahler and
Boulez. But some critics have also noted that Rattle was less
experienced in Bruckner and Schumann, whose works are also central
to the orchestra's repertory.
</P>
<P>
   During his 17 years as chief conductor in Birmingham, Rattle,
who was born in Liverpool and began his career as a percussionist
in the Royal Liverpool Orchestra at age 15, proved himself an
innovative and dynamic leader, turning the Birmingham Symphony into
a worthy competitor among the well-established London orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   Abbado welcomed Rattle's selection, and said he expected him to
continue the artistic developments under way, including widening
the Philharmonic's repertory to include more contemporary
composers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
