<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EXPLAINER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO: CRUCIBLE OF ETHNIC HATRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People outside the Balkans _ including such leaders as President
Clinton _ have often overstated the degree of historic enmity among
the Serbs, Croats, and Bosnians, the principal ethnic groups in the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But in the case of Serbs and Albanians _ each of whom outnumbers
the Bosnians, Slovenians, Croats, and other ethnic groups of the
region _ the rivalry is in fact bitter and centuries old.
</P>
<P>
   And Kosovo, a province seen as important to early Serbian
history, has always been the central area of contention.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle of Kosovo in 1389 marked Serbia's decline from its
period of greatest power and glory. Regaining it from the Ottoman
Turks, who were to rule it for the next 500 years, became essential
to the dream of restoring Serbian prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian lore hardly recognizes the existance of Albanians in
that era, and where it does, it portrays Albanians as allies and
favorites of the Turkish occupiers, who shared their Muslim
religion.
</P>
<P>
   But Albanians assert, with support from comparative linguists
and other researchers, that they descended from native peoples
dating to Greek and Roman times. They say they had been in Kosovo
for centuries before Slavic peoples, including Serbs, migrated
south into the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Both Serbs and Albanians view Kosovo as part of their national
heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs regained control of Kosovo in 1912 _ during the land-grab
that occurred during the disintegration of the Ottoman Empire _ and
at that time drove Kosovar Albanians from the cities and into the
mountains south of Djakovica and Pec.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, roles were reversed, with Albanians dreaming of
regaining land that had been theirs, but was lost to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops were driven from the province during World War I,
and when they returned they were confronted by Albanian guerrillas,
who were not suppressed until 1924. Then, in World War II, when
Serbia fell to Germany, Germany's Italian allies encouraged the
Albanians to attack and harass the Kosovar Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovar Albanians fiercely resisted Yugoslav Communist
forces after the war, and it took six months of fighting and 48,000
Albanian deaths before Kosovo was subdued.
</P>
<P>
   Then, however, the Communists under Tito tried to appease the
Albanians, just as they tried to do with the Slovenians and Croats,
in an effort to build a Yugoslavian identity. The Albanians were
given broad autonomy within Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With a much higher birth rate than the Serbs, Albanians
constitute 90 percent of the Kosovo population. And throughout the
1980s there were signs _ such as strikes by students and miners _
that Albanian nationalism was on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic, who built his political career on the
defense and encouragement of Serb nationalism, responded in 1989 by
withdrawing Kosovo's autonomy, which led to a declaration of
independence in Kosovo in 1991, around the same time that Slovenia
and Croatia were making similar moves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIETNAM-HOUSE-ART-NYT     06-23 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-HOUSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MOM, A HOUSE A WOLF CAN'T BLOW DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Feb. 10, when Gioang Huu Nguyen boarded Singapore
Airlines Flight 25 from Kennedy Airport to Ho Chi Minh City,
Vietnam, he was a man in a hurry. He had one month to build his
76-year-old mother, Phung Thi Khu, a new house.
</P>
<P>
   As he ran to catch the plane that day, Nguyen had no blueprints.
The house, so vivid in its details, existed only in his mind. The
outside would be gray concrete, and inside, it would be painted
pale pink, like the azaleas that bloom in late winter and early
spring. The living room would open onto a porch, a common
vernacular style throughout Vietnam, so the breezes and sunshine
would flood the interior. It would be embellished with French
colonial touches, like the slender columns flanking the porch.
Light would be filtered through delicately filigreed metal screens.
The house, with gleaming tile floors, would have a roof that didn't
leak, a bathtub with hot and cold running water and a toilet that
flushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dream,'' said Nguyen, 44, who works as an assistant
cabinetmaker for Dakota Jackson, the furniture designer whose
factories are in Long Island City, Queens. ``I did not have time to
draw.''
</P>
<P>
   But he had had time to plan. He had been dreaming about this
house for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was not his first house. In 1970, just before he joined the
army in Saigon _ now Ho Chi Minh City _ Nguyen and his father, Vang
Nguyen, built a house for the family, but it was not a sturdy
place. The front sported a tin roof, while the back roof and the
sides of the house, the parts the public did not see, were made of
gasoline drums, cut open and pounded flat. ``It flooded every time
it rained,'' Nguyen said. Water poured through the roof and seeped
in over the threshold. Next door was a chicken coop.
</P>
<P>
   Although the house had electricity, amenities were few. The
bathroom was a small room with a hole in the ground for a toilet
and a bucket of water, drawn from the private well, for bathing.
Three bedrooms housed eight people: his parents and the six
youngest of their nine children, including Qui, who is mentally
retarded, a result of Agent Orange, Nguyen said. ``Qui,'' he said
quietly, ``means precious.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Nguyen became a carpenter; in 1985, he switched
to construction, eventually becoming a contractor. ``I quit being a
carpenter,'' he said through an interpreter, ``because I knew I
wanted to build a new house.'' Between the desire and the reality,
however, was a stretch of 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the year his father died, Nguyen and his wife, Anh
Tuyet Thi Vu, who works as a manicurist, came to the United States
with their three children. They settled in Flushing, Queens, where
he found work as a waiter and cook. The move was simple. Like so
many immigrants, including his wife's family, who had already moved
to this country, he wanted to make more money, not just for himself
but for the family. ``I promised my father I'd send home $100 a
month to support my brother Qui,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he learned that there was cabinetry work at Dakota
Jackson's. He remembered the date he reported for his new job.
``March 23, 1996,'' he said. He makes $7.75 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Over three years, he managed to save $3,000 toward building the
house _ a little more than half of what he needed. He also hoarded
his vacation days. Then, last December, he borrowed $5,300 from
friends and his wife's family. He was ready to go home. He called
one of his brothers in Vietnam, who has a telephone. His brother
hopped on a motorbike, picked up his mother and sped her back to
the phone. Nguyen told her he wanted to come home and build her a
new house.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said that seeing me was enough,'' he said, ``and that I
didn't have enough money.'' But he insisted. ``She was old, and I
wanted her to be comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got home to Baria, a town of 45,000 people two miles
south of Ho Chi Minh City, he spent a day shopping. He bought
poplar for the scaffolding, stones for the foundation and steel for
the frame. He bought mortar and bricks, gallons of pink paint and
bags of cement. He bought folding steel panels for the front door,
which would open onto a deep, sheltering porch facing the street.
(In Vietnam, he said, guests are expected to drop in
spontaneously.) For windows, he bought iron grills at $25 each. He
had apportioned $5,300 of his budget for materials and labor,
$2,000 for gifts to his relatives and $1,000 for his air fare and
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen assembled a crew of 14, paying everyone $4 a day, the
local going rate. The crew _ men and women, family and friends _
worked seven-day weeks. ``The main workers were construction
workers,'' he said, ``and some of the women carried materials.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers arrived at 7 in the morning. As is Vietnamese
custom, they took a break around 9 for tea, coffee and cigarettes.
Later in the morning, the family provided lemonade and iced coffee
with condensed milk to accompany noodles or sticky rice with
grilled pork. At the end of the working day, they ate another
snack, usually small steamed crabs or boiled chicken. When his crew
went home, Nguyen ate dinner, then went back to the site and kept
on building. ``I couldn't sleep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first job was to knock down the old house, salvaging bits of
tin and wood planks. (During the construction, his mother, a
brother and his wife, and Qui, who live together, moved to the
homes of brothers and sisters.) Then the crew dug the foundation,
erected the steel frame, stacked and mortared the bricks, wired the
house, laid the plumbing, tiled the floor and raised the corrugated
aluminum roof.
</P>
<P>
   With trowels, they coated the exterior with gray cement. Inside,
they painted the walls azalea-pink, a flower that to the Vietnamese
signifies a bright future. ``My mother chose the color,'' Nguyen
said. ``It makes her happy and not lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   The roof still needs insulation, but inside the spotless home,
Nguyen's mother is radiant. In mid-March, her children moved her
into the new house, where she shares a bedroom with Qui. Her other
son and daughter-in-law have the second bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Nguyen family know that this is a house that
American money has built, Gioang Nguyen doesn't romanticize his
life in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that living here is not a heaven,'' he said. He
emigrated because their father had died, and he was the eldest son,
the one who was to start over. He has been able to send his oldest
children to college, but Nguyen himself has not had time to master
English, getting by with what he learned in high school.
</P>
<P>
   And he is always homesick. ``In Vietnam, people are closer to
each other,'' he said. ``Every Sunday, I would take my children to
visit my parents or my brothers and sisters. In New York, I rarely
visit my wife's relatives. People are too busy to pay attention to
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nguyen retires, it will, not surprisingly, be in Baria. ``I
want to go back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
