<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANZMANN-FILM-ART-NYT     06-23 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANZMANN-FILM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST BLOODHOUND GENTLY TRACKS TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been exactly 55 years since Maurice Rossel,
a young Swiss investigator for the International Red Cross, visited
the infamous Theresienstadt concentration camp in Czechoslovakia
and, in a masterstroke of Potemkin manipulation by the Nazis, wrote
a glowing report about the ghetto amenities of its ``privileged
Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Little could Rossel have imagined that, as surely as he let
himself be fooled by the Germans' ironhanded domestic tableaux of
uncomplaining Jewish internees, he would be diligently tracked down
across the decades by Claude Lanzmann, the director who created
``Shoah,'' the classic nine-and-a-half-hour film of Holocaust
testimony wrought from 350 hours of painstaking interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the debut of a new film Wednesday night, a riveting 65
minutes of testimony from an urbanely unapologetic Rossel, the
audience at the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum sat and witnessed
the sheer creative patience of Lanzmann, a 73-year-old bloodhound
of a Frenchman who carefully shied from speculating deeply about
what he has delivered to history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the film,'' he said in gentle puzzlement to one
member of the audience who demanded to know why a moment of
epiphany, of melodramatic self-accusation, could not have been
evinced from Rossel during the several hours of interview by
Lanzmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see this,'' Lanzmann said simply, gesturing at the movie
screen. The interview of Rossel, in which he was masterfully
plumbed rather than excoriated, had just concluded with the Red
Cross investigator's defending his report. All the while the
director, so amiable, so relentless, confronted him with fact after
fact about the Theresienstadt ghetto, from its four-burner
crematorium to the faked synagogue and playground of the Nazis'
``beautification program'' in advance of the Red Cross visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sign it again,'' Rossel declared of his report, patiently
chain-smoking as he looked back to Theresienstadt from the vantage
of 1979, when he was a comfortably situated 60-year-old. It was
then that Lanzmann, a veteran of the French Resistance, finally
bearded him with infinite politeness as Lanzmann was midway through
his Aeneid of a masterwork, interviewing sundry Holocaust survivors
and perpetrators across 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lanzmann left that interview 20 years ago with the conviction
that the very ``architecture'' of his core film, ``Shoah,'' and the
peculiarity of Rossel's performance _ ``what it is to know and not
to know'' _ dictated the stand-alone film now unveiled as ``A
Visitor from the Living.'' The title is an inexact translation of
the phrase Rossel used in recalling how the camp's silent,
wide-eyed internees (whom he retrospectively terms Israelis, not
Jews) had looked upon him as ``un vivant qui passe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this was very strong,'' Lanzmann said of the footage,
taken with a single 16-mm camera that required reloading breaks
every 11 minutes, the same as for all the ``Shoah'' interviews. The
director used the breaks to calm Rossel and bolster mutual respect.
(``I did not want to hurt him, to scare or frighten him.'')
</P>
<P>
   Artfully prodded to look back, Rossel defended his lasting
impression that Theresienstadt housed ``very rich Jews'' and
Prominenten _ German Jewish leaders buying their way out of trouble
in decent circumstances _ not varied throngs doomed for
extermination, as Lanzmann documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that no one ever said, `This is a farce,'''
Rossel said defensively of the mute Jews he glimpsed in their play
acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you saw was the terror of the Jews,'' Lanzmann responded,
recounting elaborate Nazi stagecraft and death warnings before the
Red Cross visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passivity is so hard to swallow,'' said Rossel, clinging
to this point as the camera mercilessly closed in on his eyes
edgily dancing about the past.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Lanzmann's ferocious technique of remembering each bit of
testimony flashed clear as he reminded Rossel how he initially
described his mission in the ghetto visit: ``My task was to see
beyond what I was seeing.'`
</P>
<P>
   Lanzmann offered a pained smile in emphasizing this idea, so
much at the heart of Holocaust history, in an interview before the
film debut of Rossel. ``He was deceived by himself,'' said the
director in a tone of sad understanding of the vagaries of
anti-Semitism. ``That is what is fascinating _ his face and what he
does not let himself say.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever polite in his perseverance, Lanzmann once more tracked down
Rossel two years ago when the film was ready, seeking the
interviewee's permission to present it to the public. (There will
be a second showing Thursday night in Los Angeles at the Directors
Guild of America Theater.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He sent me a strange letter, a beautiful letter,'' Lanzmann
related, describing how the once-eager 25-year-old inspector was
now 80 and infirm with palsy. ``I don't remember the man I was as
at that time,'' Rossel wrote. ``I believe I am wiser now or more
insane, and it is the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanzmann paused to savor that idea as if it explained the
passion of his own work. ``I like what he said very much. He asked
me: `Please be pitiful. Don't make me look too ridiculous.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But he is not,'' the hound of the Holocaust concluded most
insistently. ``He is everything but ridiculous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7109 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BORDER-ART-2TA     06-23 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BORDER-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVARS RETURN TO RUBBLE, WITHOUT RANCOR FOR DESTRUCTIVE FORCE OF
NATO 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANEJE, Yugoslavia _ Syl Shigjeqi stepped into the shower
through a hole in the wall of his house, up a ramp of rubble, over
the faucet's skeleton, a shaving brush, soap and, somehow, teacups.
There is no shortage of destruction in Kosovo, but here it is
possible to see what NATO's bombs added to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everything here,'' said Shigjeqi, 33, a baker, who came
back Wednesday to see what little was left of his home. ``Hot water
heater. Shower. Washing machine. It was very nice. Modern.''
</P>
<P>
   This village of 29 families _ nearly all the men are bakers,
with bakeries around Kosovo and Serbia __ was more or less leveled
in near-daily attacks by NATO planes in the weeks before the peace
agreement was signed with Serbia. The residents of this and other
villages in the Has region left their homes shortly after NATO
began its bombing in late March. The area became a NATO target
because several thousand Yugoslav army soldiers were dug in there
and in houses abandoned by Albanians, fighting off an offensive by
the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   This village and others nearby are at the foot of Mount Pastrik,
where some of the most furious fighting took place. At the time,
refugees crossing the border into Albania could actually hear the
NATO bombs whistle down before exploding.
</P>
<P>
   Now some are returning to see the damage NATO has done.
</P>
<P>
   In Shigjeqi's yard, a Yugoslav army truck rests on its back. In
his basement, the Serbs have left dozens of empty ammunition boxes.
Several houses have crumbled to the point that it is hard to tell
where one began and the other ended. A 6-foot-long unexploded bomb
lies in a depression in the village's center. The paw of a gray dog
is near the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, yes, it was NATO,'' Shigjeqi said. Despite the
destruction, the villagers said they do not blame NATO for toppling
their houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Serbs who are guilty,'' said Qerim Vorfaj, 45, also a
baker, whose house was destroyed. ``We are glad the Serbs aren't
here anymore. May NATO live billions and billions of years.''
</P>
<P>
   But nearly everyone here thinks NATO nonetheless has an
obligation to help them rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope somebody helps us,'' said Arif Shigjeqi, 61, like
most people in Planeje a relative of Syl Shigjeqi. ``We left
Albania, we get back and what's here? I have 25 people in my
family. I don't know where to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three days in a row I have come here, just looking,'' he
added. ``How can I live here? It's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Other villages along the Albanian border show similar
destruction, largely as a result of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In Milaj, the next village toward the border, German soldiers on
Wednesday posted mine warnings along the edge of the rubble. In the
town lay unexploded Serbian grenades and a twisted artillery piece.
</P>
<P>
   In Gorozhupe, a border town that was heavily bombed by NATO and
was the scene of fighting between the KLA and Serbian forces,
Serbian helmets, gas masks and camouflage uniforms lay in a
courtyard surrounded by several buildings that appeared to have
been burned from the inside. Zepa Binaj, 56, an ethnic Albanian who
owns one of the homes, said that Serbs hiding from NATO attacks
destroyed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what they have done,'' said Mrs. Binaj, her hands shaking
as she smoked a cigarette. She has seven children, and they built
her the house, now scorched and littered with rifle shells.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very, very poor,'' she said. ``I had enough trouble
raising them all. But you can see what they built me.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the NATO bombing and the fighting between Serbs and the KLA
went on for days after the peace agreement was approved by the
Serbian Parliament and even after it was signed. In fact, the
fighting and bombing seemed to intensify as peace neared,
inflicting some of the saddest casualties of the war.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, villagers in Rogove, another town in the Has
region, unearthed the bodies of two men, cousins named Asllan
Berisha, 34, and Besim Berisha, 24, who died in a firefight with
Serbian soldiers on June 4, the day after the Serbian Parliament
accepted the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   The men had been hastily buried by the Drinit te Bardhe River.
On Wednesday, the two men _ who hid and fed KLA fighters _ were put
into carved coffins, the red and black Albanian flag taped to the
lid, and taken to be mourned at their families' houses before being
buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear anybody,'' said Sefir Berisha, Asllan's
father, as his son's coffin was placed on two cinder blocks on
their front lawn. ``Nobody can cry. Nobody can say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fitim Hoti, 25, one of the men who survived the attack, with
bullet holes in his hand and shrapnel wounds, said he, the Berisha
cousins and a fourth man had fled, carrying arms, when Serbian
soldiers came into town. They hid by the river, thinking that they
would not be be pursued by the Serbs because of the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the Serbs followed and the cousins were killed
fighting them. ``It was their last offensive. Whatever they found,
they just destroyed it,'' he said of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even as returning villagers are finding bodies of ethnic
Albanians, it is something of a mystery why there appeared to be no
bodies of Serbian soldiers here in Planeje, given how badly damaged
the town was. Here and there the smell of rotting flesh rose from
the rubble, but there was no way to tell if it was human or animal.
</P>
<P>
   Bajram Shigjeqi, 40, said he believed that hundreds of Serbian
soldiers had died on Mount Pastrik but that the bodies had been
taken away by the withdrawing troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to show the world that the Serbs didn't have
soldiers or arms or ammunition here and that NATO attacked
civilians,'' he said. ``But thousands of them were here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
