<SLUG> BC-DREAM-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVE END TO CITY BALLET'S CELEBRATION SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Ballet will continue celebrating
its 50th anniversary at its summer home in Saratoga Springs, N.Y.,
in July. But this week's performances of George Balanchine's
``Midsummer Night's Dream'' will bring the company's anniversary
season at the New York State Theater in Manhattan to a close on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It is a festive end to a job more than well done. After a
mammoth display of 100 ballets, the company goes out with one of
Balanchine's most spectacular and poetic productions. Darci Kistler
and Peter Boal, both dancing gloriously, led the first cast of
``Dream'' on Tuesday night with temperament and energy.
</P>
<P>
   Few ballet treatments of Shakespeare have the refinement that so
eloquently colors Balanchine's combination of narrative and
pure-dance divertissement. Many a ``Romeo and Juliet'' turns into
choreographed drama on the ballet stage. But in his 1962 version of
``Dream,'' Balanchine knew that dance had to add its own dimension
to the text. His approach is more musical than literary, with a
score composed of pieces by Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   Wit runs through the two acts. There are hordes of arm-flapping
children as little bugs, and there is no sweeter moment than when
they yawn and lie down to sleep. But the ballet's grandeur lies in
the way Balanchine turns the tale in Act 1 into a pure-dance
distillation of the same story in Act 2. Here the vision is
abstract, with the reconciliation of quarreling lovers embodied by
a sublime duet, danced to perfection by Jock Soto and Wendy Whelan.
</P>
<P>
   Both seemed to swim through the music on Tuesday. Ms. Whelan,
amazingly centered in her toe work, knew nonetheless how to bring
off the beautiful final image when she sank luxuriantly into a
swoon and then twisted into a second swoon as Soto held her with
one arm.
</P>
<P>
   As ideal lovers, this pair is not the mirror image of Titania
and Oberon, the fairy monarchs who rule the first act but never
dance together in an adagio. Titania does have an anonymous
cavalier: Charles Askegard, in a debut, showed off his usual fine
versatility. Ms. Kistler's fairy queen was in her element, bold but
also playful in a duet full of departures from conventional
classical partnering. At one point, Titania and her cavalier face
each other in a social-dance position. Yet Ms. Kistler raises her
leg in ballet's attitude position.
</P>
<P>
   Boal's Oberon was commanding from the start; he flew about the
stage with dynamism and speed, detailing the small steps that
expanded into his astonishingly large leaps. Albert Evans' jolly
Puck complemented Boal's power with extraordinary lightness.
</P>
<P>
   Debuts came from Carrie Lee Riggins, a streamlined butterfly,
and Jennie Somogyi, seductive as Hippolyta. Ms. Somogyi pushed too
hard in her fouettes and went off balance, but her jetes, with
front foot extended further at the last minute, offered a
breathtaking image of sustained flight.
</P>
<P>
   The acting in Act 1 tended toward too much realism. But
Alexander Ritter, in a debut as Lysander, stylized his unhappy
lover to more persuasive effect. Riolama Lorenzo (Helena), Pascale
van Kipnis (Hermia) and Sebastien Marcovici (Demetrius) rounded out
the quartet of mortals.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Savoye's moment as Bottom in a donkey head was timed to
comic perfection, and Ms. Kistler danced endearingly with him. Hugo
Fiorato conducted a seemingly happy orchestra and chorus, with
Beverly Myers and Gale Limansky as soloists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
