<HEADER>
A7112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-23 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: LOVED STRICTURES IN A LENIENT AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Upon learning of the imminent arrival of a new
edition of The Elements of Style, Strunk and White's concise and to
many seminal guide to American language, I went back to the current
edition, and in 10 minutes of perusal I was reminded of things
needed to sharpen one's writing skills. I was certainly struck with
the realization that everyone who writes, whether it be books or
journalism or corporate reports, should go back to this or a
similar work every few years for a refresher. The fourth edition of
Elements will be in bookstores in several weeks, and it could
become an unlikely but tremendously amusing and helpful beach read.
</P>
<P>
   The third edition was published in 1997, 92 pages in paperback,
and the new one has grown by 36 pages, mostly through the updating
of references to reflect not only current facts but also the modern
concern with inclusion and diversity. For instance, a fact change:
The speed limit on the New York Thruway has risen to 65 mph from 55
mph. But more important, ``she'' now alternates with ``he'' in the
examples. And in the illustrations of principles, contemporary
writers, often women, are used. Thus, in discussing the rule of
keeping the subject and the principal verb of a sentence together,
Toni Morrison's ``Beloved'' has displaced Wordsworth's
``Excursion'' in the example.
</P>
<P>
   There are other changes. Another new feature includes such
common terms as air-conditioning and word processor. Writers are
urged to become more direct and personal, with the implied third
person ``the writer'' changed to the second person ``you'' in the
book's commands.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, commands. When the book was originally put together by
William Strunk Jr. in 1919 for his students at Cornell University,
its decrees of linguistic precision were snapped out like military
orders. That tone more or less remained when one of Strunk's
students, E.B. White, the New Yorker magazine writer known for
graceful and stylish prose, put the book together in 1959 and made
it into the icon we now know as The Elements of Style (Allyn &AMP;
Bacon).
</P>
<P>
   White polished it for a 1972 edition, removing what he called
``bewhiskered entries,'' and updated it again in 1979 for a third
edition. By then, for many writers, it had become known simply as
``the little book.'' So far about 10 million copies have been sold
in hardcover and paperback, most to college and smart high school
students, said the publisher, William Barke, who refuses to reveal
how large the first printing of the new edition will be. About
400,000 copies would not be surprising. Advance copies of the book
are not available.
</P>
<P>
   This edition has a foreword by Roger Angell, also a New Yorker
writer noted for graceful style, who is White's stepson. Angell
said he really didn't much want to do the introduction but finally
decided to write it because the originally proposed foreword ``had
some careless, common mistakes'' and ``didn't sound very much like
Andy White.'' He said his sister-in-law, Allene White, ``was on
watch'' as sort of the family Praetorian Guard of the work.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. White says that the publisher sent the galleys to the
Whites ``out of the goodness of his heart'' but that sending them
``to the White family was like sending raw meat to a cage of
lions.'' She added: ``When push comes to shove, we shove so well,
we make so much noise. Essentially it now has the same point of
view as White had.''
</P>
<P>
   These days there are other antidotes for illiteracy, and one in
particular some writers consider even better than Elements. That is
``Simple and Direct: A Rhetoric for Writers'' (HarperCollins) by
Jacques Barzan, who said that he felt that even though ``Elements
awakens a bad writer to things he or she should be aware of, it
doesn't grapple with the possibilities of the good things'' a
writer needs. There is also for many The New Fowler's Modern
English Usage (Oxford University Press, 1996), but its critics have
complained that the latest edition has taken Fowler out of the book
and that it has lapsed into a passive acceptance of some changes
that are not praiseworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Passive acceptance is not what Strunk and White are about, and
that probably accounts in part for the book's appeal and its
diverse fans. Annik La Farge, associate publisher of Simon &AMP;
Schuster's trade division, said: ``It's not only a tool for writers
but for publishers also. It helps you think in a clear and focused
way. If I ever get to such an elevated position as publisher, I
might send a copy to every writer and editor.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a sort of Roto-Rooter for prose. Doug Johnson, the
producer of C-Span's ``Book TV,'' said he started in radio, which
is ``a writerly medium, and sometimes everything you had on paper
was all clogged up; this helped unclog it.'' He said he kept it
``close by, on my shelf over my shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   E.B. White once said in an interview that while he used the book
and held firm to its fundamentals, he also ignored it at times.
</P>
<P>
   In the first paragraph of this column I used the word
``certainly'' to add weight to a thought. The little book calls the
use of this word a mannerism that is ``bad in speech, is even worse
in writing.'' In the third paragraph I used the word ``feature.''
Elements said that is a hackneyed word usually adding ``nothing to
the sentence in which it occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   One is cautioned: ``Do not dress words up by adding ly to them,
as though putting a hat on a horse.'' I did it in the first
sentence of the second paragraph, using the word ``mostly.'' I was
rather lazy; I should have rewritten the sentence to make the word
``most'' enough. Now I see that ``rather'' as a qualifier is among
the ``leeches that infest the pond of prose, sucking the blood of
words.'' Who knows how many more misuses I wrote befogging the
reader?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
