<SLUG> BC-HKO-NHL-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE, DAFOE IN RUNNING FOR NHL AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Hockey League will pay tribute to its best and
brightest in Toronto Thursday night when it presents its annual
major awards at the Air Canada Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Two Bruins are in the running _ Ray Bourque is a candidate to
capture his sixth Norris Trophy as the league's top defenseman, and
Byron Dafoe is among the three finalists for the Vezina Trophy,
given to the best goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Former Boston University star Chris Drury has been nominated for
the Calder Trophy as the rookie of the year. Drury, who plays for
the Colorado Avalanche, has plenty of awards already. He pitched
Trumbull, Conn., to the Little League World Series championship 10
years ago, captured the NCAA title in his first year at BU, and won
the Hobey Baker Award as college hockey's top player his last year
there.
</P>
<P>
   Drury has an excellent chance to take the Calder, won last year
by Bruins left wing Sergei Samsonov. His competition is teammate
Milan Hejduk and Ottawa's Marian Hossa. Drury's and Hejduk's
nominations mark the first time in 10 years that teammates are
finalists for the award. Brian Leetch and Tony Granato were
nominees in 1989 as members of the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   For Bourque, it is his 14th time as a finalist in 20 seasons and
his first since 1996. In addition to Bourque's five first-place
finishes, he took second in the balloting another five times and
was third three times.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Bruins' captain was third in points among the
league's blueliners with 57, 10 of them goals. He also was third in
ice time, averaging 29.5 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   The other two nominees are St. Louis's Al MacInnis, whom many
feel will capture the trophy, and Detroit's Niklas Lidstrom.
MacInnis has been a finalist five times, finishing behind Bourque
in three of the years Bourque won it. It's the second consecutive
nomination for Lidstrom, who finished second to Los Angeles's Rob
Blake last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe received his first nomination this year. He was third in
the league in goals-against average (1.99), second in save
percentage (.926), and was tied for fifth in victories with 32.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe's competition is Buffalo's Dominik Hasek, who has won the
award four times, including the last two years, and Toronto's
Curtis Joseph, who earned his second nomination and his first since
1993, when he finished third while a member of the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr, and Ottawa's Alexei Yashin are
the finalists for the Hart Trophy, given to the most valuable
player.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates to win the Selke Trophy as the top defensive
forward are Ottawa's Magnus Arvedson and two players who opposed
each other in the finals _ Dallas's Jere Lehtinen, who won it last
year, and Buffalo's Michael Peca, who took it in 1997 and finished
second last season.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas's Ken Hitchcock, Ottawa's Jacques Martin, and Toronto's
Pat Quinn are nominees for the Jack Adams Trophy as coach of the
year, won last season by the Bruins' Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   The three finalists for the Lady Byng Trophy for gentlemanly
play are recently-retired Wayne Gretzky, no doubt the sentimental
favorite, Anaheim's Teemu Selanne, and Lidstrom.
</P>
<P>
   The other awards that will be presented include the inaugural
Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard trophy, given to the top goal scorer
(Selanne with 47); for the second year in a row, Jagr will collect
the Art Ross Trophy as the NHL's top point scorer (127); Dallas
netminders Ed Belfour and Roman Turek (since traded to St. Louis)
will be given the William M. Jennings Trophy for allowing the
fewest goals during the regular season (168). The Bill Masterton
Trophy for perseverance, sportsmanship, and dedication to hockey
will also be presented as will the King Clancy Trophy for
leadership and humanitarian contribution to his community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
