A7117 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITTLE-LEAGUE-TUTORS-     06-23 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLE-LEAGUE-TUTORS-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ADDED BOOST FOR THE LESS GIFTED ON THE FIELD OF DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. _ Hoisting a bat that looked huge on a
10-year-old, Benjamin Gold stood nervously at the plate under his
floppy orange Orioles cap.
</P>
<P>
   His parents watched from lawn chairs behind the backstop. His
tutor studied the play from behind the first-base line, pointing a
video camera at Benji for a post-game critique.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's moving around too much in the box _ and dropping his
hands,'' the tutor, Mark Venditti, had noticed during Benji's first
at-bat. Between innings, he had talked to the boy about making an
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Benji took a mighty swing and tapped the ball toward the
pitcher's mound, then scampered toward first base. It was good
enough for an infield hit. And the runner on third base made it
home, so Benji was credited with a crucial run batted in, an RBI.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that American childhood has become a serious
venture, parents like Loren and Debbie Gold are paying $70 an hour,
sometimes more, to private coaches to sharpen the skills of their
Little League ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   For the Golds, who harbor no illusions about athletic
scholarships or big money in the professional leagues, hiring a
tutor seemed a logical way to help a child whose heart was broken
into pieces with every strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it for his self-esteem,'' said Mrs. Gold, a 43-year-old
employee recruiter. ``He was getting to the point where he just
wanted to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard last year,'' Benji agreed. ``When you strike out,
you know, and people say you should be off the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents find themselves in a spot these days. The increasingly
competitive nature of childhood makes parents feel practically
obligated to give their children every possible edge in academics
and athletics. And yet, the rigors of self-improvement for children
_ preschoolers now go to foreign language camps _ can take an
exacting toll on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message used to be, `Be the best you can be,'' said
Cynthia Kowa-Basler, a middle-school counselor in Dixon, Ill. ``Now
the message is simply, `Be the best.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kowa-Basler said one eighth-grade student sat and wept in
the counselor's office because he did not believe he could live up
to his parents' expectations. The counselor scheduled a meeting
with the parents to deliver her professional advice in the bluntest
of terms: ``Back off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golds, who have two children, share the ambivalence of many
parents. On one hand, they want to encourage Benji and their
daughter, Samantha, to take piano lessons, play sports and
participate in social activities. But they fear an overload.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, who is 11, has talked about feeling ``stressed out''
by all of her activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an 11-year-old starts talking about being too stressed,''
Mrs. Gold said, ``it makes you stop and wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Beck, a sociologist at Northwestern University, said
child rearing has taken a more management-style approach,
especially among parents who are well-educated and successful. In
some ways, he said, children have come to be seen a bit like growth
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an earlier generation, parents were younger, going at life
without much of a plan, a little courageous and a little foolhardy,
a kind of what-the-heck attitude,'' Beck said. ``But many of
today's parents are more serious. They put off having children for
a career. And having had success in their careers, they use the
same goal-oriented principles when it comes to raising their kids.
They study what's needed for success. They look at the competition.
It's all a very rational, very market-oriented approach.''
</P>
<P>
   In his novel ``Wobegon Boy,'' Garrison Keillor suggested that
parents of an earlier time seemed to have better things to do than
obsess about their children. ``They did not read books about
parenting, and when they gathered with other adults, at Lutheran
church suppers or family get-togethers, they didn't talk about
schools or about the prevailing theories of child development,'' he
wrote. ``They did not weave their lives around yours. They had
their own lives, which were mysterious to you.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In part, parents have become more intimately involved in the
activities of their children because they now must act as
chauffeurs, carting their children from piano lesson to tennis
court to soccer match, driving minivans to the league games that
have replaced the unchaperoned pickup games of the old
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Today's crop of parents can scarcely take sole blame for the
image of the overzealous Little League parent. Accounts of
bothersome parents ranting from the bleachers go back to the days
before the 60-year-old Little League.
</P>
<P>
   But today's frenetic competition among children, and among the
parents of children, has turned up the pressure to win. It is
perhaps not surprising then, in a service economy where almost
anything can be taught and anyone trained, that Junior's batting
flaws are something to be repaired by a service that advertises in
the Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   When a child goes into a slump, plenty of parents pick up the
telephone and call Grand Slam USA, one of the many places around
the country that now provides baseball instructors to boys and
girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Monday morning, we get the frantic calls from parents,''
said Leland Fisher, an owner of Grand Slam, in suburban Palatine.
``They'll say, `It's an emergency _ the boy struck out twice on
Saturday _ we need help right away.'''
</P>
<P>
   While the average young ballplayer still relies on pals or a
parent, private tutoring has become a familiar part of the social
landscape around the country, said Lance Van Auken, a spokesman for
Little League Baseball Inc., in Williamsport, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not any doubt that there's a lot more private
instruction out there,'' said Van Auken, who noted that a big
portion of the students were girls, trying to win college
scholarships in softball. ``There are no hard numbers, because it's
privately done by parents. But you hear a lot of anecdotes.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for instruction has also popularized baseball camp. A
handful of such camps a generation ago has grown to a big business,
Van Auken said, with dozens and dozens of camps around the country,
especially in the South.
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Hlavacek, 14, practices batting, he takes tips from
an instructor who works as a professional scout. The help has paid
off. The boy, who just graduated from the eighth grade in the
Chicago suburbs, has a red-hot batting average of over .500.
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Allison, who is entering her senior year of high
school, takes lessons for fast-pitch softball. She has also been an
outstanding ballplayer, and hopes to play on a college team.
</P>
<P>
   To their father, Jerry Hlavecek, who pays more than $100 a week
for the lessons, the private instruction has helped their talents
soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to play the sport at a higher level, this is the
only way you're going to get there,'' said Hlavacek, a business
executive. ``How do you think Ken Griffey learned to hit? Somebody
taught him, that's how.''
</P>
<P>
   Many parents and children say it works better to have a
professional as coach, rather than a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confrontation that normally happens between a father and
son _ it doesn't happen,'' Hlavacek said.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Michael, agreed. ``You don't really listen to your
dad,'' he said. ``He sometimes yells. And sometimes, he doesn't
know what he's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiring a coach also helped domestic relations in the McEnerney
home in Mount Prospect, northwest of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband didn't want to get into any more arguments with my
son,'' said Maureen McEnerney, whose 14-year-old son, Matthew, and
17-year-old daughter, Christie, take private lessons. ``My kids now
love the game even more. Plus they get along better with their
dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McEnerney, a hairdresser, and her husband, William, an
electrician, get the impression that other people think hiring
sports tutors seems excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, it's like playing a musical instrument,'' Mrs.
McEnerney said. ``It's a mechanical thing. It's a matter of
studying and learning.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The day after his latest ball game, Benji went to the ball park
to train under the eye of Venditti, a 26-year-old software salesman
who played two seasons with the Zanesville (Ohio) Greys in the
independent Frontier League. Venditti tutors four players on
Benji's Orioles team. In all, he works with about 20 players, from
age 8 through high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atta boy, Benji,'' Venditti called out, as Benji swatted a
line drive. ``You're doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gold and her husband, Loren, watched the practice from
their lawn chairs, praising their son afterward _ ``Nice lesson,
Benji,'' they said. Gold, a 45-year-old electrical engineer, said
he worked long hours and could not spare much time to play with
Benji himself.
</P>
<P>
   But even if he had time, Gold would not be much help. ``I was no
ballplayer,'' he said smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Not all fathers bow out like Loren Gold. Around the batting
cages of the league are fathers who strut like Babe Ruth, sounding
as if they know everything about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, the owner of Grand Slam in Palatine, says he cringes at
what he sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid will be crying, `I don't want to play, I don't want to
play,' and the father is pulling him along,'' Fisher said.
``Sometimes, the biggest thing the instructor does is simply build
up the kid's confidence. After all the criticism from the parent,
they need to be told they're all right.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Fisher said, the instructors will turn the tables
and give an overbearing father a taste of his own medicine. The
instructor will ask the father to step into the cage and try his
luck with a bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he's liable to see that it's not so easy, after all,''
Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Or he must face the fact, he added, that the child's lack of
skill was just an inherited trait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
