<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLDEST-SHIPS-BOS &LR;      06-23 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDEST-SHIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIPS DISCOVERED DEEP IN MEDITERRANEAN SAID OLDEST KNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year was about 750 B.C. when the two ships set out from the
Mediterranean port of Tyre, now in Lebanon, on what should have
been a routine voyage, each carrying a cargo of about 10 tons of
wine in ceramic jugs called amphorae. Then suddenly a violent storm
blew in, sinking the two Phoenician ships in more than 1,000 feet
of water.
</P>
<P>
   There they lay, unknown and undisturbed in the sand and muck,
until less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's when they were finally located, photographed and sampled
by famed oceanographer Robert Ballard, discoverer of the Titanic,
and a team of archeologists and engineers from Harvard University,
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution, and others. The ships are the oldest ever found in
deep water anywhere in the world, Ballard said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient ships are remarkably well preserved, Ballard said,
because they have remained in such deep water. ``The great depths
that exist in the oceans, the absence of sunlight, the great
pressures, seem to preserve history far more than we thought,''
said Ballard, director of the Institute for Exploration in Mystic,
Conn., at a press conference Wednesday in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ballard and other researchers, with the help of a
US Navy nuclear submarine, found _ while searching for the wreck of
an Israeli sub _ several ancient Roman ships in the central
Mediterranean off Sicily, and it was during that expedition that
the submarine also located other possible wrecks off the Israeli
coast. But it was not until this month that the scientists were
able to return to check out these other finds close-up using
cameras on a deep-diving robotic craft called Jason developed by
Woods Hold Oceanographic Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear from this discovery, as well as that off Sicily in
1997, that the deep ocean holds great promise to the field of
archeology,'' Ballard said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the recent development of sophisticated deep-diving craft
like Jason, most shipwrecks had been found only close to shore and
in shallow water. The oldest ship ever found anywhere was a trading
ship dating to 1300 B.C., close to the Turkish coast. Only two
other wrecks older than the new finds have ever been discovered;
all three of the older wrecks were in water shallower than 200
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Using Jason's remote-controlled arm, the team was able to
recover 15 of the amphorae from the two ships, whose exact location
they will not divulge because of fears that treasure hunters might
plunder the archeologically valuable wrecks. The team will not
attempt to raise the ships themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Although the amphorae were intact, the wine within had long ago
seeped out and been replaced by sand.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University archeologist Lawrence Stager said he was able
to determine the age of the wrecks because of the distinctive shape
of the amphorae, which were the universal, standardized shipping
containers of antiquity. ``We were able to actually date the ship
by looking at the amphora style, and it came out to a period about
750 to 700 B.C.,'' he said Wednesday. This was about the time that
Homer, a little further west in Greece, was starting to compose his
famous epic poems.
</P>
<P>
   The amphorae had distinctive mushroom-shaped lips that were
typical of Phoenician containers, Stager said. The ships were
probably headed for ports in northern Africa, most likely either in
Egypt, or Carthage, a Phoenician colony near present-day Tunis.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenicians were the leading seafaring people of their time,
which lasted from 1200 to 146 B.C., but little has been known about
the specifics of their trading routes, the amount and types of
cargoes they carried, and who their trading partners were. The
discovery of these ships could help to open up a whole new chapter
in the research on this ancient maritime culture, the researchers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ships, one about 58 feet long and the other about 48 feet,
were found between 1,000 and 3,000 feet deep, 30 miles off the
coast. The larger of the two is now the biggest pre-classical ship
ever found, the team said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the ships, the team found heavy stone anchors,
crockery for food preparation, a wine decanter, and an incense
stand. The items all point to an origin in Phoenicia, which was
located in present-day Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard said that ``more important discoveries should come in
the near future that could significantly alter our present
understanding of ancient maritime trade.'' Already, the earlier
find off Sicily of Roman ships dating from 100 B.C. to A.D. 400
proved a once-controversial theory that the Romans navigated long,
deep-water trade routes, rather than staying close to shore as some
scholars had believed.
</P>
<P>
   These ancient finds should provide a kind of reality check when
compared with the descriptions in literature and art from that
period, the researchers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
