<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN PROVINCIAL PREMIER STIRS FUROR OVER POLITICAL
ETHICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: this replaces SAFRICA-RARE-LION, which has been held) 
(bl) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The new governor of a South African
province, whose scandals he promised to clean up, came under fire
Wednesday for saying that he felt it was acceptable for politicians
to lie to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The new premier of Mpumalanga province, Ndaweni Mahlangu, cited
President Clinton as an example. Lying ``wasn't the end of Bill
Clinton's life, and I personally don't find it to be a very bad
thing,'' Mahlangu said. He was defending his reappointment of a
finance officer whom he said had admitted lying about signing
promissory notes in what may have been a fraud scheme.
</P>
<P>
   As opposition parties and religious figures attacked him
Wednesday, Mahlangu apologized and said he had made the remark in
jest. But reporters who heard the remarks Tuesday said that
Mahlangu seemed perfectly serious.
</P>
<P>
   The African National Congress at first gingerly defended
Mahlangu, saying he might have been quoted out of context and had
been asked for a written explanation of what he meant. But if he
was correctly quoted, said ANC spokesman Smuts Ngonyama, the remark
was ``inappropriate, unfortunate and totally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying politicians ought to lie ``goes against long-held moral
values of the ANC,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is particularly sensitive, because the ANC is
experiencing an internal over corruption. Because corruption is so
endemic in many African governments, the ANC is eager to appear
squeaky clean. But after having played down the problem for years
and pointing out that the old government had several corruption
scandals, Nelson Mandela and Thabo Mbeki, who succeeded Mandela as
president this month, scheduled an anti-corruption conference for
this year and conceded that some party leaders, particularly in
local government, appeared to be enriching themselves. Mandela and
Mbeki condemned those figures as traitors to the struggle for black
liberation.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy around Mahlangu arose because he appointed to
his Cabinet two men under investigation by the Heath Special
Investigation Unit, a national anti-corruption team headed by Judge
Willem Heath. Wednesday, a court invalidated some of the $170
million of promissory notes that provincial officials have issued.
The collateral was control of some of the most precious assets of
the province, its stunning mountain and river-canyon parks.
</P>
<P>
   The case has embarrassed the province. Besides mortgaging the
parks, officials are accused of having awarded themselves contracts
to provide helicopter, lodging and other services.
</P>
<P>
   One reappointed former Cabinet member who was just named the
chief financial officer, Jacques Modipane, is accused of having
signed $57 million worth of the illegal notes. He denied that and
accused staff members of having forged his signature. But Mahlangu
said Modipane later privately admitted having signed the notes.
</P>
<P>
   The premier defended that, saying, ``This was not a grievous
enough mistake to send anyone to the guillotine.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to elaborate, he said: ``It is nothing new. Many
politicians publicly deny they did certain things but then later
admit to them. It is accepted, and it not unusual anywhere in the
world. It wasn't the end of Bill Clinton's life and I personally
don't find it to be a very bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath said Wednesday that he was personally surprised that
Modipane had been reappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The citation of Clinton amused South Africans. The national
radio network, SAFM, opened a short segment on political lying with
a tape of Clinton's saying, ``I did not have sexual relations with
that woman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
