<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENGLAND-FESTIVAL-ART-     06-23 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGLAND-FESTIVAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: LIVELY MODERNISM IN A FISHING VILLAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALDEBURGH, England _ When the sun beats the rain, as it did over
the weekend, and the wind does not chill your bones but rushes
cloud patterns of navy blue and ocher across the North Sea, this
little town on the Suffolk Coast can seem one of the best places on
earth to be in early summer.
</P>
<P>
   Its cultural weather, too, is inviting. Aldeburgh was never
overwhelmed by the presence of Benjamin Britten, who lived here for
more than 30 years, and it has not been overwhelmed by the music
festival that has continued for almost a quarter century since his
death. The place has strong literary associations.
</P>
<P>
   Its beach is lined with fishing boats and with tar-painted huts
where the morning's catch can be bought. It has kept, almost
intact, its Victorian architecture of brown and garnet brick. It
has a robust and substantial character of its own into which the
annual festival fits.
</P>
<P>
   And that festival has a character of its own. This year composer
Thomas Ades begins his stint as its artistic director, and while
the programming is suitably marked by his fascinations (with
Couperin and musical machines, for instance), the essence remains
what it was when Britten was alive _ and not for sentimental
reasons, but because this is a mix that works.
</P>
<P>
   The festival brings great music and great performers to a place
a hundred miles from anywhere _ a place that happens to have, in
the Snape Maltings, one of the world's great concert halls. Other
local buildings, especially the 15th-century churches, house music
appropriate to them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a special thrill this year to hear the magnificent
light-washed church at Blythburgh filled with the intricate and
sensuous polyphony that was new when it was being built: the music
of John Dunstable and his immediate predecessors, sung by the four
men of the Orlando Consort with beautiful tone and companionate
phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   But new music is just as important at Aldeburgh as the venerable
or venerated, and Ades' appointment is a strong signal that the
festival is determined to stay lively. This year's events started
with a new production of his opera ``Powder Her Face,'' and during
this second weekend he conducted the BBC Symphony in a program that
included his own ``Asyla'' and ``Tributes'' for strings by the
Danish composer Per Norgard, whose music was featured also in a
chamber recital.
</P>
<P>
   Norgard is a composer who probably works at his best on a big
scale, for ``Tributes,'' with homages to Bartok, Lutoslawski and
Sibelius, was far more impressive than his smaller pieces. It
helped that the BBC musicians were playing so well for Ades in what
was only his second concert with a big orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   As a conductor, Ades is the same kind of musician he is when
composing or playing the piano: completely assured, incapable of
ugliness and adept at presenting ideas with the maximum force and
freshness. Norgard's music typically has a gangling sort of motion,
with layers and elements moving at different speeds and the harmony
held together with a fair dash of hope and luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tributes'' was like that, but it also had gestures that came
across as vivid surprises: a whisk of upward-vanishing glissando in
the first section, and later some brilliant textures of harmonics.
It was let down only by a program note not up to Aldeburgh's usual
high standards.
</P>
<P>
   Ades and the orchestra were also in top form in two rare works
from early in the century _ Janacek's ``Fiddler's Child'' and
Sibelius' incidental music for Hofmannsthal's play ``Everyman'' _
where again Ades' strong grasp of gesture was a big plus. The
Sibelius score includes one haunting song and some dark slow
movements, including one for string orchestra that, in this
performance, kept repeating its same searing strokes with resolute
strength and accuracy until the strings were eventually smothered
by gong crashes.
</P>
<P>
   In his own music, Ades, aided by his players and the superb
Maltings acoustics, had one hearing so much magic with exceptional
clarity. In the sprinkled fantasies of the first and last movements
of ``Asyla,'' he seemed to be stirring up stars, and the third
movement had, alongside oddity and power, humor. Aldeburgh should
try to keep him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
