<HEADER>
A7138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      06-23 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDOWER SEEKS EXTRADITION OF SUSPECTED KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Florida, New Jersey, Texas)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The husband of a woman who was brutally slain in
her Florida home with her four young children nearby urged Congress
Wednesday to pressure Mexico to return the suspected killer, who
remains in a Mexican jail as he fights extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Jose Luis Del Toro Jr. fled to Mexico after
allegedly shooting Sheila Bellush on Nov. 7, 1997, with a
.45-caliber pistol and slashing her throat with a kitchen knife in
the laundry room of her Sarasota, Fla., home.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's 2-year-old quadruplets were found near their
mother's body when the police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Bellush, who was 35, was killed six weeks after the Bellush
family moved to Sarasota from San Antonio. Bellush had two other
children from a previous marriage, and her oldest daughter found
the body the day of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   With his voice cracking and choking back tears, Jamie Bellush,
who has since moved his family to his parents' home in Newton,
N.J., pleaded with lawmakers to change the U.S. extradition treaty
with Mexico and withhold financial aid from it and other countries
that ``interfere in our criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to stop playing patsy politics with Mexico,''
Bellush, who turned 37 Wednesday, told the House Government Reform
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 18 months of requests to return him to the United States
for trial, Del Toro remains jailed in a Mexico, where he has filed
numerous appeals to fight extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accuse him of being the triggerman in a
murder-for-hire conspiracy. Bellush's former husband, Allen
Blackthorne, a San Antonio businessman, has been a suspect in an
alleged conspiracy, but has never been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne's former golfing partner, Daniel Rocha, is serving a
life sentence in Florida for his role in the killing. Samuel
Gonzales, who is Rocha's friend and Del Toro's cousin, admitted
involvement in the killing and has agreed to cooperate with the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1980 treaty, Mexico has the right to refuse extradition,
if the defendant faces capital punishment in the United States.
Mexico has no death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sarasota prosecutor Earl Moreland wanted Del Toro to
face trial in Florida, he agreed to waive the death penalty in
exchange for Del Toro's return. However, Moreland said at the
congressional hearing, Bellush was killed in ``such a cold,
calculated manner'' that it is ``undoubtedly a case where the death
penalty was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John L. Mica, R-Fla., who chaired the hearing of the
subcommittee on Criminal Justice, Drug Policy and Human Resources,
said the Del Toro case was not an isolated one. Mexico has refused
more than 275 extradition requests by the United States over the
past decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cases include murder and illegal narcotics
trafficking,'' Mica said. ``I am concerned that Mexico has become a
haven for murderers and drug lords.''
</P>
<P>
   He referred to Bellush as ``one of the most compelling witnesses
I've ever heard in my 10 years in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really am appalled that Mexico, as a neighbor and an ally,
can allow such injustice,'' he said, adding he is appalled that the
U.S. government continues to provide money to foreign governments
``when they continue to flout our laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blows me away the way we just stand there and allow people
to trample all over our judicial system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., who testified beside Bellush at the
hearing, said when U.S. citizens are accused of a crime in the
United States, Mexico should have nothing to do with the
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Miller slammed the Clinton administration for not renegotiating
the extradition treaty with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if Timothy McVeigh had fled to Mexico?'' Miller asked,
referring to the man sentenced to death for his role in the bombing
of the Oklahoma City federal building in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sort of high-profile murder will it take before the
administration realizes that closing this escape route from justice
should be a priority?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The House has approved a resolution asking the president to
renegotiate the extradition treaty with Mexico. However, the
administration has resisted, saying that it would lead to many more
renegotiations of treaties around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lee Warren, a deputy assistant U.S. attorney general, said
Del Toro's extradition case is now before an appellate judge in
Mexico, but that the system there ``is painfully slow and prone to
corruptive influences.''
</P>
<P>
   But Warren said that although the delays ``have been frustrating
... justice will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren also said officials at the Justice Department have
requested an investigation into who is financing Del Toro's legal
challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
