<HEADLINE>
DRUG SHOWS PROMISE IN FIGHT AGAINST PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Officials at SafeScience Inc., a Boston biotechnology
company, are reporting promising results in initial human tests of
a new type of cancer drug designed to block the disease and appears
to have few side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, known as GBC-590, was given to men with incurable
prostate cancer whose blood contained rising amounts of PSA, or
prostate-specific antigen, a substance associated with worsening
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   After the drug was injected, PSA levels stopped rising in 14 of
22 patients and dropped ``modestly'' in four others, said Dr. Clark
Springgate, chief medical officer for SafeScience, in an interview
Wednesday. GBC-590 drug was given for up to four weeks, and
following withdrawal of the drug, the PSA levels began to rise
again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Phase I trial to test the safety of the drug was
carried out at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston under the
leadership of Dr. Christopher Logothetis, a renowned prostate
cancer specialist. He was unavailable Wednesday but was quoted in a
company statement as saying the drug was well-tolerated, and that
``we observed interesting qualitative changes'' in PSA levels,
including the fact that the levels increased after the drug was
stopped. ``We look forward to participating in the Phase II trial
for GBC-590,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is currently no effective treatment for prostate cancer
that has metastasized, or spread, beyond the prostate gland.
Springgate and senior vice president Richard Salter said that the
encouraging results have prompted a quick move ahead to larger
Phase II trials in patients with less-advanced prostate cancer in
which the efficacy of the drug would be tested.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is one of a new category of cancer drugs called
``lectin inhibitors'' because they interfere with cell-to-cell
signals transmitted by proteins called lectins and corresponding
lectin receptors. Springgate said that GBC-590 disrupts the ability
of metastatic cancer cells to recognize each other, which blocks
the further spread of the cells.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the drug might have to be given for long periods of
time to keep cancer in check, because it is not designed to kill
cancer cells. But that may be possible, said Springgate, because
the drugs caused ``no serious or even moderate adverse effects at
the doses that were tested.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Oh, a prostate cancer specialist at Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute, said it was difficult to comment on the results
because they are not yet available as a scientific paper. He said
he would be ``cautiously optimistic'' about a drug like GBC-590
that shows some effects in Phase I trialis.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned that it's not clear that a drug that stabilizes
PSA levels is necessarily halting the cancer _ particularly when
the patients were studied for only two months, as in this case.
``It may be affecting PSA levels independent of the cancer cells,''
said Oh.
</P>
<P>
   The SafeScience officials said that GBC-590 has also showed
promise in initial tests on other cancers. They said that it will
be tested at Beth Israel Deaconess in Phase I trials against
advanced pancreatic cancer, another type of cancer for which there
is currently no good treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
