<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MISSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
700 FROM ONE TOWN STILL MISSING, FAMILIES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ Hundreds of faces of the missing were
spread out Wednesday on a Formica table at the headquarters of the
Kosovo Liberation Army _ snapshots of teenagers with awkward smiles
and proud fathers holding children.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the 700 ethnic Albanian men family members and
human rights workers say are still unaccounted for after they were
held in makeshift prisons here in the basement of a winery and in
factory warehouses by Serb forces who picked them up in a sweep of
this ravaged town in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only hope that they are still alive somewhere, probably
in prison in Serbia,'' said Abdulla Guta, 34, who was eventually
released by the Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   While explaining that his two brothers and four uncles have
never been seen since, Guta broke down in tears, saying, ``We have
no idea where they are. They are in the hands of criminals, they
are in the hands of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Guta said he and some 1,200 other men, women and children were
picked up by Serb forces in a three-day sweep that began on May 9.
Serb forces known as the MUPs, or special police, went through the
streets and to the bus station rounding up families who had
mustered courage to try to escape for the hills that lead to the
border of Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the men were told that they would only be held briefly
to conduct parafin tests to establish if they had been in contact
with gunpowder, and so those who knew they were not fighters, such
as Guta and his family, obeyed the orders with great fear and some
hope that they would be reunited with their families in less than
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   They were taken in covered army trucks, he said, to the basement
of the Ereniku Winery on the industrial outskirts of this town.
There, they were beaten and denied food while the Serb soldiers
drank through the supplies of wine and, based on the discarded
syringes that littered the dark hallways, may have been shooting
heroin. He said he was beaten with the butt of a rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Selected detainees, but not all, were given the parafin tests.
Women and children were taken to a large motor assembly plant.
</P>
<P>
   After six days he was released along with about 500 others,
including what appears to be all of the women and children. But the
other 700 have never been seen since.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Guta was at the front of a demonstration along with
hundreds of families of the missing who marched through the center
of town holding pictures of the missing.
</P>
<P>
   The march circled through town and ended at the KLA headquarters
in a converted theater. The families handed over pictures of their
loved ones and KLA officials began compilings lists of all those
missing. The picture of just how many are still missing has only
emerged in the last few days as the towns ethnic Albanians have
finally been able to talk and compare stories.
</P>
<P>
   People were desperate for information and asking those who were
held and released if they had seen their brothers and sons inside
the detention centers.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Miller, a human rights investigator for Amnesty
International, said there were certainly hundreds of detainees
still being held inside Serbia and that the Serbian Justice
Ministry has begun to hand over lists of those imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   The detainees fall into many different categories, including
political prisoners, KLA soldiers who were apprehended, and
apparently civilians who were arbitrarily arrested and never
released.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said Serb forces have used the parafin tests before in
sweeps of ethnic Albanian men dating back to last fall, in the
mounting tension in Kosovo before the Serbs unleashed their full
campaign of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that the parafin tests are notoriously inaccurate,
and cited an FBI report from the 1950s that establishes this. Even
if evidence of residue is found it can come from a host of other
sources, such as fertilizers and even kitchen matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a matter of great concern to us,'' he said. ``The fate
of these people is unknown, and the prisoners of conscience and
especially the innocent civilians still held will be a priority in
our efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   But human rights workers' efforts may be complicated by the fact
that NATO negotiators who made the peace deal with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic failed to include a clause
guaranteeing the International Committee of the Red Cross access to
all prisons to ensure that Kosovo Albanians didn't disappear into
Serbian jails.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is now in negotiations with officials in Belgrade
and hopes to get permission soon to help search for the missing.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Djakovica, a warren of stucco homes on cobbled
streets, was ravaged in the ethnic cleansing. Now there is block
after block of houses burned to the ground and left in rubble by
Serb forces and masked paramilitaries who went house to house in
perhaps the most horrific evidence of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Xhulana hid in her home with her husband and two
sons throughout the ethnic cleansing rampage which took place in
several waves of intensity. On May 10, thinking that perhaps things
had quieted down, her son, Labinot, 24, took the risk of walking
300 yards down a cobble-stone lane to check on his ailing and
elderly uncle.
</P>
<P>
   He never came home.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors say they saw him get picked up by the Serb forces.
Wednesday a family friend, Avni Zhubi, 70, told Xhulana, who asked
that her last name not be used, that he had seen her son in the
basement of the winery. He was alive but had been badly beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Labinot was a medical student at Pristina University before the
war broke out, his mother says, and every time she sees his medical
texts piled on his desk she weeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only want to see him again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nexhat Musa, a spokesman for the KLA, said based on information
they have been able to gather from those who were held and
released, the approximately 700 missing men were to be transferred
to Pec, a city on the northern border of Kosovo near Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Recent information is that they may have been taken to the
Leskovac prison in Serbia after Serb troops withdrew from Kosovo
last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
