<SLUG> BC-EDISON-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON EDISON, COMMONWEALTH ELECTRIC MERGER EXPECTED TO BE OK'D 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Shareholders of the parent companies of Boston Edison
and Commonwealth Electric are expected to approve a $4.4 billion
merger Thursday, but consumer and business advocates fear it will
be a bad deal for 1.3 million eastern Massachusetts energy
customers.
</P>
<P>
   At separate meetings, owners of BEC Energy and Commonwealth
Energy System are expected to support combining the holding
companies into a new business called NStar. Federal approvals are
expected soon, and because it involves holding companies, the
combination is not subject to state approval.
</P>
<P>
   However, BEC and ComEnergy operating units still face a grueling
rate-setting proceeding before the state Department of
Telecommunications and Energy. The proceeding turns on how they
will recoup a $502 million merger premium being distributed to
shareholders and another $450 million for meshing the companies, a
bill they want to be largely paid by customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We oppose this merger unless there are substantial changes,''
said Judy Silvia, vice president for energy programs with the
5,200-member Associated Industries of Massachusetts, the state's
leading business lobby. ``To ask for close to $1 billion from
customers and not guarantee savings, that's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Edison and ComEnergy have offered to freeze their customers'
electric distribution rates for four years. They assert that over
40 years, customers will save more on their monthly bills than they
would pay shareholders for the merger premium.
</P>
<P>
   ComEnergy spokesman Peter A. Dimond said Wednesday the merger
will allow the combined companies to ``invest in the kinds of
technology needed to provide the highest levels of public service
for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics call the proposed four-year rate freeze a sham. Late
last month, Attorney General Thomas Reilly argued that ``no
assurances are present that harm will not be visited on customers .
. . The rate freeze deprives customers of rate decreases, to the
enrichment of shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies have proposed charging customers $20.6 million a
year for 40 years for the acquisition premium plus interest, and
$13.5 million for 10 years for merger-related costs such as
integrating computer systems. Those figures compare to projected
net operating savings of $532 million during the first 10 years of
the merger, according to Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   And critics contend that while they want state promises they can
recoup costs from customers, the utilities are offering no
comparable guarantee they will pass on the expected savings.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Sargent, energy program director for the Massachusetts
Public Interest Research Group, said he fears that based on what he
called their recent anticonsumer record, state utility regulators
will ``be happy to let them pass on the cost of the merger premium
and keep all the savings for shareholders. It's a `heads, the
utility wins; tails, the consumer loses' approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said they could not comment because the
matter is under review.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company's Boston Edison, ComElectric, ComGas, and
Cambridge Electric units would continue to exist as operating
companies, identified on trucks and bills as NStar subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Edison serves 633,000 customers in Boston and 39 other
communities, and through an unregulated joint venture with RCN
Communications has begun offering cable, Internet, and telephone
service locally.
</P>
<P>
   ComEnergy has 373,000 electric customers in areas including
Cambridge, Cape Cod, New Bedford, and Plymouth, and 239,000 ComGas
customers in 51 eastern Massachusetts communities.
</P>
<P>
   Through attrition and leaving vacancies unfilled, the companies
expect to trim about 300 of their current 3,900 jobs, or about 7
percent. Edison chairman Thomas J. May will be chairman and chief
executive of NStar, with ComEnergy chief Russell D. Wright taking
the president and chief operating officer positions and a seat on
the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   May has said he wants to grow the combined company to 2 million
customers by the end of next year, but recent New England utility
combinations lead some analysts to think the new NStar is more
likely to be a takeover candidate than acquirer.
</P>
<P>
   ComEnergy's executive offices will move to the Prudential
Center, freeing up 100,000 square feet of premium office space at
their current headquarters in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Merger terms call for Edison shareholders to get NStar stock on
a 1-for-1 basis. ComEnergy shareholders will get 1.05 NStar shares
for each 1 CES chare. Owners of both companies can choose to get
$44.10 a share in cash, up to $300 million total. The new stock is
intended to be distributed on a tax-free basis.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Stock Exchange trading Wednesday, BEC stock closed
unchanged at 42 15/16, down nearly 10 percent from a 52-week high
of 44 15/16. ComEnergy was down 3/16 at 42 3/4, close to its
52-week high of 43 1/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
