<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0624-COX     06-23 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MARINES KILL ONE, INJURE TWO AT KOSOVO CHECKPOINT AS ETHNIC
TENSIONS REMAIN
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-PRISONERS-0624.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Kosovo _ Coming under fire, U.S. Marines killed one
gunmen and wounded two others in southern Kosovo Wednesday in the
latest incident illustrating the dangers facing NATO troops as they
try to keep the peace and construct some semblance of authority.
</P>
<P>
   No Marines were injured in the incident and an investigation was
underway late Wednesday to determine the identity and ethnicity of
the gunmen, according to Marine officials. There were earlier
reports that two assailants had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The gunfight came as four foreign ministers from European
countries visited the war-shattered province and as NATO troops
were straining to bridle the ethnic tensions that have continued
between the majority ethnic Albanian population in Kosovo and the
minority Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the 11th day since NATO troops entered to oversee
the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces and Serb paramilitary and police
who had been terrorizing Kosovar Albanians during the 78-day NATO
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 NATO troops are now in the province and they are
being joined by a steady flow of returning ethnic Albanian
refugees. According to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
about 206,000 of the estimated 860,000 refugees who fled the
province have returned to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is now in formal control over the province
and U.N. spokesman Kevin Kennedy said Wednesday that committees
will soon be formed to recommend how to build the institutions
Kosovo is sorely lacking, from police to courts to healthcare
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But most observers agree that work will be nearly impossible if
tensions in the province are not eased. The foreign ministers of
Germany, France, Great Britain and Italy urged returning refugees
-- as did U.S. President Bill Clinton while visiting refugees in
Macedonia Tuesday -- not to seek revenge against Serb civilians
staying in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Minister Robin Cook toured a site of a mass
execution and graves of ethnic Albanians, stressing that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic be brought to justice. Milosevic is
under indictment for war crimes perpetrated against ethnic
Albanians during the NATO air war by a tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Other ministers echoed Cook's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace cannot be built on revenge, but it must be built on
justice,'' said German Foreign Minister Joshka Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers were met in Pristina, the provincial
capital, by dozens of ethnic Albanians clapping and cheering
``NATO!''
</P>
<P>
   But, there was less harmony around the province as ethnic
tensions continued to surface and NATO troops were forced into
becoming increasingly aggressive in their work.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern city of Mitrovica, where French peacekeepers
have been trying to keep a lid on tensions between Serbs and ethnic
Albanians, French Defense Minister Alain Richard defended the
actions of his soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians there have complained that the French were
giving preferential treatment to the Serbs. French peacekeepers
looked on Tuesday as Serbs menaced some people wanting to cross a
bridge to a side of town with the main hospital, many ethnic
Albanian homes and almost the only open food shops.
</P>
<P>
   The French soldiers were simply trying to permit all Kosovo
residents ``to live in safety,'' Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in Mitrovica, NATO announced that Tuesday night a Serb
gunman broke into an ethnic Albanian home. The Albanian family fled
and, after the gunman opened fire on French troops, he was
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   British troops in Pristina, just about 100 yards from the
meeting of the foreign ministers, searched an apartment belonging
to a Serb family and confiscated what one soldier called a ``small
armory'' of machine guns and shotguns. The apartment belongs to the
relatives of two Serb soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, their ethnic Albanian neighbors had
placed a note on the door telling the family they had 24 hours to
flee.
</P>
<P>
   But, the hottest spot of the day was in the farming village of
Zegra in southeastern Kosovo, where the Marines were manning a
checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   A BBC report said the Marines fired after a man left a social
club, fired his Soviet-made Kalishnikov rifle in the air and then
toward the Marines. Capt. Gabrielle Chapin, public affairs officer
for the Marines in Kosovo, said that one man was killed and then
civilians nearby showed the Marines where other wounded gunmen were
hiding.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines apparently convinced them to surrender and took
three into custody. Two of them were injured and flown to a Marine
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Chapin said the area is populated by both Serbs and Albanians
and it was not clear who opened fire or who intervened to help. The
gunmen were not in uniform, which could indicate they were not
members of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, the only uniformed
military presence in Kosovo besides NATO and Russian peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Zegra is also where Marines had a standoff with about 100 armed
KLA members last week, which ended with the rebels being forcibly
disarmed.
</P>
<P>
   The first and only NATO fatalities so far in Kosovo occurred
Monday when two British demolitions experts died trying to remove
unexploded NATO cluster bombs from a school yard.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the European Union said Wednesday it will spend
$500-$700 million over three years and hopes to raise an equal
amount at two donor conferences later this year and from the World
Bank to fund efforts to undermine Milosevic's rule, and help
Yugoslavia recover from bombing damage once he's out of power.
</P>
<P>
   EU Commissioner Hans van den Broek said the 15-nation EU will
subsidize free press and pro-democracy projects in Serbia, where
Milosevic has muzzled the media and made it a propaganda tool of
his government and in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which helped broker the peace accord, had wanted the
West to pay for all war damage to Serbia as well as its Kosovo
province. But the United States and NATO allies have refused give
any money to rebuild Yugoslavia while Milosevic is in power. Serbia
is the dominant republic in Yugoslavia, which also includes
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
