<SLUG> BC-CMGI-SHARES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI SHARES FALL AMID ALTAVISTA RUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares in CMGI Inc. have fallen as much as 12 percent this week
on rumors the Andover, Mass. Internet-ventures company might buy
Compaq Computer Corp.'s AltaVista search service, a move some fear
might interrupt what has been CMGI's hot track record in the
on-line sector.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI shares fell to as low as 91 Wednesday in Nasdaq trading
before recovering to close at 98 15/16, down from 103 on Monday.
Some analysts attributed the declines to concerns a purchase of
AltaVista would move CMGI in an unfamiliar direction. The company
has traditionally made small investments in flourishing Internet
start-ups such as Lycos Inc. As an established Internet brand,
AltaVista would probably command a far higher price.
</P>
<P>
   Neither CMGI nor Compaq would comment on whether they are in
talks, adding to the uncertainty that seemed to spook the market,
said Forrester Research analyst Paul Hagen. ``I start wondering if
maybe it's a change of business for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI has indicated in recent months it may make investments in
larger companies. But the stock decline is an ironic reminder of
how shareholders might regard a major financial commitment by CMGI
chief executive David Wetherell. In February he withdrew his
support for a proposed merger between Lycos Inc. and elements of
USA Networks after other Lycos investors expressed little patience
for the proposed long-term benefits of that arrangement and drove
down Lycos shares. (The proposal ultimately collapsed.)
</P>
<P>
   For AltaVista, however, analysts said a deal with CMGI might
provide a clean outcome. The San Fransisco-based search service has
seemed adrift since Compaq acquired it as part of its larger
purchase of Digital Equipment Corp. in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Digital set up AltaVista to show off the speed of its Alpha
processors, but Compaq has given the devices a less-than-prominent
position in its strategy. Compaq also said in January it was
considering selling public shares in AltaVista.
</P>
<P>
   But Compaq has yet to clarify its intentions and now its
attention is devoted to finding a new chief executive to succeed
Eckhard Pfeiffer, who was dismissed in April amid disappointing
sales of Compaq's hardware products.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AltaVista is falling behind competitors. The service
received 9.49 million individual visits in May, according to the
Media Metrix Inc. rating service in New York, compared with 31.8
million visits for Yahoo Inc. and 15.1 million visits for
Excite.com.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq doesn't disclose AltaVista's revenue, but analysts
believe the service and others owned by Compaq _ Zip2.com and the
Shopping.com Web site _ together have revenue of about $250
million.
</P>
<P>
   A standard selling price of 10 times that revenue would be $2.5
billion, a figure the Wall Street Journal Wednesday reported was
the midpoint of prices under discussion for the service, citing
sources it didn't name. On Tuesday, Internet columnist Dan Dorfman
also reported the companies were in talks.
</P>
<P>
   Some CMGI shareholders found the possibility of a purchase
intriguing. Alex Cheung of the Monument Internet fund in Bethesda,
Md., suggested a deal ``might not be a bad move for CMGI'' because
it could be packaged with services offered through Lycos, in which
CMGI holds roughly a 20 percent stake. But he called himself
``neutral'' on the prospects, noting it would be a major commitment
for CMGI, whose total market capitalization is about $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But others said they would be surprised if Compaq executed such
a strategic deal now, rather than leave the decision to the new
chief executive it will eventually hire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a key strategic decision for the company and one I'd
prefer they allow the new person'' to make, said Phil Rueppel,
analyst at Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown securities in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq shares fell 3/8 Wednesday to close at 23 7/16 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
