<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER BACK IN HIS ELEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As it turned out the sentence was for six years. Six
years in exile from a place he cherished.
</P>
<P>
   There would have been time off for good behavior, except, as Jim
Courier is saying, ``When you're a first-round loser around here
for three straight years they don't invite you into the big show. I
haven't been very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, when the 28-year-old exile returned to ``the
show,'' as he calls it, that verdant isle where every tennis player
in the world longs to hang out _ Wimbledon's Centre Court _ Jim
Courier was very good. He had to be because one of his successors
as a French Open champion, No. 10 ranked Carlos Moya, was playing
as though he had no idea that Spaniards are supposed to regard
grass as poison ivy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I did everything right,'' sighs the rugged, handsome
young Mallorcan whose shoulders have probably popped a few door
frames. ``I serve and volley good. I run down balls. But Jim beat
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not by much. ``Charlie did do everything right,'' applauds
Courier. ``I'm amazed at how fast this clay-court guy has picked up
the grass game. He has the idea, and doesn't want to be typecast as
a one-surface player. I kept thinking eventually he'd break down.
But no. So at the end I had to go into an extra gear _ I'm glad I
could.''
</P>
<P>
   At 2-2 in the stretch-run fifth set, Courier kicked himself in
as though he had spurs on his sneakers. He could hide his fiery
hair beneath a white cap, but not his flaming shotmaking.
Zip-flap-whang-crunch-flutter-smack-whir . . .
</P>
<P>
   It was two-legged overdrive, and his No. 61 ranking looked
suspicious, fraudulent, like the computer had print-out thrombosis.
This was the old No. 1 stuff. Putting together four games as
forcefully and finely tuned as you'll see _ seizing 16 of the last
19 points _ Courier won driving, 6-3, 3-6, 7-6 (7-1), 3-6, 6-2, and
was in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of an elevation, a pimple to such as Pete Sampras, but
Himalayan to Courier, the way he'd been groping around here since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   That's the last time the local nabobs asked him into Centre, and
he was very good then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great occasion, the final, and I had a good shot,''
Courier remembers, with a sniffle. Not a sentimental choking up,
but ``a cold, that's all. I've got a cold. Maybe I should keep it,
the way I played today.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tight '93 final (7-6, 7-6, 3-6, 6-3), the first of
Sampras's five championships. And if Pete hadn't rescued a critical
set point in the second with a desperate swan dive volley, Courier
might have departed as champion, adding Wimbledon to his two French
and two Australian crowns that nevertheless assure him a future
niche in the Hall of Fame at Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of those scarce birds who've flitted in all four major
finals, having lost the 1991 US Open to Stefan Edberg. And, like
Andre Agassi, he is picking up the pieces of a brilliant career
that seemed smithereened, and pasting them together again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man Courier has inspired all of us,'' says Agassi. Andre
happened to be occupying a front-row box as Jim crashed a monster
forehand return to conclude the victory with a knockdown, leaving a
lunging Moya sprawled on the turf.
</P>
<P>
   Courier smiles at the memory. ``Yeah, I knew Andre was there,
cheering for me. I love it. He's done some inspiring, too, with
that great French Open performance. I'm ecstatic for him. You know,
this has been a year of the American guys coming together. We're
starting to feed off each other. It started up the road in
Birmingham with me and Todd (Martin.)''
</P>
<P>
   That was their unlikely April Davis Cup triumph, 3-2, over
Britain in the persons of Tim Henman and Greg Rusedski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Pete (Sampras) is back on the team for Boston. That's what
he and US tennis needs,'' Courier says. ``It's the right message.
And I haven't given up on Andre. The door's open for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all grown up,'' says Courier of the finest
other-than-Australian male tennis generation, the Americans of the
'90s: Agassi, Courier, Michael Chang, Martin, Sampras, MaliVai
Washington, accounting for 20 major singles titles. ``We've gotten
over our past jealousies and envy. We're not finished yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier, obviously the leader, has grown the most even though
his ranking has plummeted from No. 1 to the deceptive 61. ``I think
I became Jim Courier again last fall when my longtime physical
problems were over, my right biceps fully healed.'' He'll never be
quite the guy who won those majors in 1991-92, terrorizing foes
with his backside boogie, a quick shuffle to the left to deliver a
paralyzing inside-out forehand.
</P>
<P>
   But in the five-set Davis Cup victories over Henman and
Rusedski, where heart and cool mattered most, he was the man of
presence and the winning touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting ready for my Boston summer,'' he laughs,
knowing the reporter is from that neighborhood. ``Davis Cup against
the Aussies, and the US Pro in August.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis Cup has been Jim's Grand Slam,'' says Agassi. ``It means
the most to him. It means a lot to me, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi said he would never play again when the US Tennis
Association obtusely, rudely fired his friend, Dr. George Fareed,
the team physician of many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was poorly handled and could be rectified,'' says Courier.
Agassi says, ``I would reconsider playing if . . .''
</P>
<P>
   If USTA president Julia Levering did the right thing by
apologizing publicly and returning Fareed to the team staff?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that would have to happen,'' Agassi says.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for Courier: Sjeng Schalken, the Dutchman who won the US
Pro two years ago and will return this summer. ``With a little
luck,'' Courier smiles, ``I could get a rematch with Henman.''
</P>
<P>
   That would earn the exile another visit to ``the show.'' ``I'd
like that,'' Courier says. ``It was exciting to be back. I did
everything right except the bow'' _ toward the Royal Box, on
entering. ``I did a lousy bow.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he can find a bowing coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
