<SLUG> BC-HKO-GRETZKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY, AS EXPECTED, TAKES FAST SKATE INTO HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's official: Wayne Gretzky is taking the express lane into the
Hockey Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The voting took place early Wednesday afternoon, and the result
was announced not long afterward in Gretzky's native city _ Toronto
_ that the selection committee unanimously voted to make the Great
One the 10th player to bypass the three-year waiting period for
induction.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent player prior to Gretzky to have the waiting
period waived was center Mario Lemieux, who retired from the
Pittsburgh Penguins after the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, 38, was the only player chosen for induction. The two
others selected were former referee Andy van Hellemond and Scotty
Morrison in the builders category.
</P>
<P>
   In April, when it became clear the New York Rangers would end
their season without making the playoffs, Gretzky revealed what had
been speculated for weeks _ that he would retire after 20
remarkable seasons. He holds 61 records, many of which are never
expected to be equaled, and left pro hockey as its career scoring
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Gretzky's retirement, the Hall of Fame's selection
committee, of which Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden
is a member, unanimously voted to waive the waiting period for the
NHL's most prolific scorer. That decision was later supported by
the Hall's board of directors, paving the way for Gretzky to be
inducted this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky tallied 894 goals and 1,963 assists in 1,487
regular-season games. He played on four Stanley Cup teams while a
member of the Edmonton Oilers, and in 208 career playoff games
registered 122 goals and 260 assists.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his prolific production, Gretzky was a dynamic
and classy ambassador off the ice. He is credited with the rise of
hockey's popularity in the Sunbelt, which began when Gretzky left
Edmonton and was traded to the Los Angeles Kings on Aug. 9, 1988.
Since then, teams have sprouted up in such warm-weather locales as
Anaheim, San Jose, Tampa, and South Florida, and Minnesota moved
its franchise to the toastier climes of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he knew the day was coming, Gretzky was very
gracious in showing his appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty special day for all of us,'' he said. ``As
Scotty said, we're all overwhelmed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
