<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE-PERSONNEL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE EASES MUST-STAY ORDER FOR DEPARTING PERSONNEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2ndgraf to reflect partial lifting of order; T'Jae in 3rdgraf
is CQ.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force said Wednesday it had partially
lifted orders that had prevented thousands of officers and
enlistees from retiring or leaving the service during the Yugoslav
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Easing the so-called stop-loss order, a rarely used provision
that kept key personnel in uniform past their separation and
retirement dates, will allow them to leave the Air Force as
previously planned.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force spokeswoman T'Jae Gibson said a small percentage of
European-based personnel supporting Operation Allied Force, the
recently ended air war against Yugoslavia, will remain affected by
stop-loss for now. Almost 18,000 Air Force personnel remain
deployed in Kosovo support roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the end of hostilities, withdrawal of Yugoslav troops
from Kosovo and the redeployment of forces home, it is appropriate
to begin releasing our people from stop-loss,'' said Col. Lynn
Pratt, chief of the Air Force's military personnel policy division.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to end stop-loss, which was last ordered in 1990 as
the Persian Gulf War loomed, had been in the works. Defense
Secretary William Cohen this week said an end of stop-loss order
was expected as U.S. forces return to their home bases.
</P>
<P>
   Two airmen at Randolph Air Force Base in San Antonio, who were
among the 6,000 personnel previously cleared to leave the service
before being ordered to stay, agreed the stop-loss policy wasn't a
fix for an Air Force ravaged by a loss of pilots and others in
critical jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody kind of believes it is a short-term solution
to a lot of long-term problems that have existed for many years
prior to this action,'' said Lt. Col. Gary Pickett, an instructor
pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Band-Aid,'' said Sgt. Vibol Ros, a computer network
administrator at Randolph.
</P>
<P>
   Stop-loss only can be imposed in time of war, national emergency
or when reservists are ordered to duty, as they were when President
Clinton mobilized 33,102 men and women in April during the height
of the NATO-led air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
