<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LOTTERY OFFICIALS HOPE NEW SCRATCH-OFF GAMES BOOST LAGGING
SALES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Armed with a new state law, Texas Lottery
officials Wednesday announced new scratch-off games that will
improve players' chances of winning and, they hope, boost lagging
ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also is negotiating for possible participation later this
year in a multistate, on-line game that would offer a mega-jackpot,
lottery Executive Director Linda Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said she was optimistic the lottery will see an increase
in revenue, with Gov. George W. Bush's signature of a new law that
eases a two-year-old cap on total prize payouts.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery sales dropped by more than 17 percent in fiscal 1998,
the first decline suffered by the game since its inception in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials put much of the blame on a cap imposed by the
Legislature in 1997 that limited prize payouts to 52 percent of
gross lottery revenue. Before then, prizes had averaged about 60
percent for scratch-off games.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 844 by Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston, which was signed
by Bush over the weekend, allows as much as 57 percent of lottery
revenues to be spent on prizes. Prize payouts for some scratch-off
games will actually be higher _ as much as 65 percent _ offset by
payouts for on-line Lotto jackpots that will remain at 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have an opportunity now to put up or shut up,''
Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that ``Bingo,'' a scratch-off game with a 65 percent
prize payout, was introduced last week. Eight other scratch-off
games with similar, higher payouts will be launched between now and
the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means is that our players will win more in prizes,
and they'll win more often, like they did prior to the reduction in
the payout.'' Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to restore payout levels to where we were
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Lottery Commission doesn't plan to change the
payout for on-line Lotto jackpots, Cloud said officials are
considering increasing prizes for lower-level winners _ those
players who match three, four or five of the six Lotto numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said Texas Lottery officials also were negotiating to join
a multistate, on-line game called ``The Game of the Century,''
which would run from October through December.
</P>
<P>
   If details are worked out, it would be Texas' first
participation in such a multistate offering. The final jackpot for
such a game could easily surpass the highest yet recorded in Texas
Lotto _ $75 million, which was shared by five winning tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not a done deal yet,'' Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have other lotteries participating with each other,
you have a lot of meeting of the minds and state regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The lottery director said the cap on prize payouts wasn't the
only reason lottery sales dropped from more than $3.7 billion in
fiscal 1997 to less that $3.1 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She said cuts in lottery advertising, new casinos on Texas
Indian reservations and in nearby states and unfavorable publicity
from an administrative scandal that rocked the Lottery Commission
in 1996 and 1997 also could share the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a combination of factors,'' she said. ``I
think we've overcome most of the other factors, and now the prize
payout will be a telling story here, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the drop in revenue, the lottery still contributed $1
billion to the state budget last year, Cloud added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very profitable game for Texas and will continue to
be,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
