<P>
   Lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-STATES-RIGHTS (Washington) _ Thrusting the doctrine of
state sovereignty well beyond existing boundaries, the Supreme
Court places sharp new curbs on the ability of Congress to make
federal law binding on the states. In three cases, all decided by
identical 5-4 votes on the last day of the court's 1998-99 term,
the justices made states immune from suits by state employees for
violations of labor law; by patent owners for infringement of their
patents by state universities and agencies, and by people bringing
unfair competition suits over states' activities in the
marketplace. By Linda Greenhouse. (We plan to move the story by
7:45 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) 2,300 words.
</P>
