<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OZAWA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OZAWA SIGNS AGREEMENT WITH VIENNA STATE OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN LARSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As Seiji Ozawa made it official Wednesday at a Vienna
press conference that he's stepping down from the Boston Symphony
Orchestra in the fall of 2002 to become music director of the
Vienna State Opera, the classical music world reacted to the news
and began speculating on Ozawa's successor.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa, 63, who flew to Vienna from Germany for the announcement,
said, ``I think I will enjoy the last directorship of my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the (Vienna) opera house has a wonderful orchestra, a
wonderful chorus and very good music staff and very good singers,
... and that is a very happy thing for a conductor.'' He fills a
position that has been vacant since 1991 when the only previous
music director of the opera, Claudio Abbado, retired. Ozawa's
contract is for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The BSO said it will form a committee this summer to begin a
search
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa's replacement; since several other major orchestras are
also seeking music directors (including the New York Philharmonic
and the Philadelphia Orchestra) competition will be intense.
</P>
<P>
   Names of possible Ozawa successors in the rumor-mill initially
included the 44-year-old Brittsh conductor Sir Simon Rattle, but
Wednesday he accepted the podium of the Berlin Philharmonic. Others
who were the focus of speculation include James Levine of the
Metropolitan Opera, Christoph Eschenbach, a frequent guest with the
BSO, and the young American conductor Robert Spano. Meanwhile,
Ozawa's colleagues and fans are recovering from the shock and
preparing to feel bereft; while others are feeling -- well, not so
bereft:
</P>
<P>
   --John Williams, Boston Pops Conductor Emeritus: ``It's a great
loss to have Seiji leave, particularly at a time when his genius is
flourishing. The good news is we'll have him for another three
years. I know the BSO so intimately, I've conducted it for 20
years; Seiji has revitalized it. His stewardship has had
outstanding results; the new young players are superb.''
</P>
<P>
   --Ellen Highstein, newly appointed director of the Tanglewood
Music Center: ``It's not as if I have to start crying right now, I
have four more years with him at TMC. Seiji is a remarkable
educator and thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   --Richard Ortner (who resigned as director of the Tanglewood
Music Center last year, and who is now president of Boston
Conservatory of Music): ``It had to come, it's the natural course
of things. Ozawa's stepping down presents some truly exciting
opportunities for the BSO. The conductors from whom the orchestra
may choose a replacement are very interesting.'' He declined to
name names.
</P>
<P>
   --Joseph Hearne, BSO bass player: ``I'm a big fan of Seiji's.
``I'll miss him but I get the feeling he'll be often in Boston.
There is no apparent successor, but when Fiedler died they said
they'd never replace him. Then John Williams came. I'm hopeful
there'll be somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   -- LLoyd Schwartz, Boston Phoenix music critic: ``The saddest
thing about Seiji leaving is that he never fulfilled the promise I
had hoped for when he first came. He was a burst of fresh air, and
then kind of got stale awfully quickly. I wish him well. My fantasy
is that (Pierre) Boulez would replace him. I'd be happy to see a
young conductor like Bob Spano take over and grow into the
orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   --Leon Kirchner, composer: ``Nowadays conductors become leaders
before they have really matured. When they are leaders the
give-and-take and the critical relationships stop, and their
development stops and they don't grow. I think so highly of Seiji.
He has a great memory and intellect and strength of mind. He thinks
with his whole body. He was enormously gifted when I first met him
at Tanglewood and he won the prize. I feel he never developed his
full potential. If it were possible to get Levine - he's so
extroardinary in the classical and romantic repertoire. David
Zinman, or Asa-Pekka Salonen are good with new music.''
</P>
<P>
   --Peter Gelb, president of Sony Classics, former assistant
manager of the Boston Symphony: ``The Vienna State Opera, along
with the Met and La Scala, are the most important opera companies
in the world; it makes sense for him to go there. To lose Seiji to
Vienna is an indication of how successful an orchestra the BSO is.
But he will not be an easy act to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   --Jerome Rosen, violinist who played under Ozawa in the BSO:
``I'm so happy for the younger players in the orchestra, because
they will have the chance to look at something different.''
</P>
<P>
   --Gunther Schuller, conductor, author, composer: ``no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Spano, conductor of the Brooklyn Philharmonic Orchestra
who had just received the news of the maestro's departure: ``uh, no
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   --Harry Ellis Dickson, conductor and former BSO player: It would
be nice if we had an American conductor for a change. No matter who
comes, the BSO will continue to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   --Harry Shapiro, retired BSO hornist, now manager of the TMC
Orchestra: ``I was sad to hear it. Seiji has been a terrific friend
to me. On the other hand he loves opera, he talks about it all the
time. He wanted to bring opera to Tanglewood, but, you know, budget
problems and all. You know, they say Seiji doesn't show the
emotion, but he has his own way of showing emotion, that's right
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   --Keith Lockhart, conductor of Boston Pops: ``People are are
lining up asking me is it a good thing, a bad thing, is it tragic?
I tell them, this transition has gains as well as losses. It's
certainly good for Seiji. Any other step in the music world would
be a lateral step for him. As far as the BSO is concerned, there
are always elements in turning the soil over and starting over
again that are good for an organization. But you lose this
relationship it took a quarter of a century to build. But I know
he'll continue to be a resource to the orchestra for years,
especially at Tanglewood. So we'll have our cake and eat it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard Dyer of the Globe staff contributed to this report. Wire
service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
