<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSES-PUBERTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL NURSES TO DISCUSS EARLIER TEACHING ABOUT MENSTRUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With research showing the onset of puberty occurring in some
girls as early as eight, playground teasing once reserved for the
early endowed 11-year-old is being aimed at girls as young as
third- and fourth-grade, school officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday _ in an effort to teach young girls about puberty
before they go through it _ the National Association of School
Nurses will convene a group of national school health experts in
Providence, R.I. to consider teaching girls about menstruation
earlier in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   There are complex emotions that come with having a body that is
mature, but a mind that is not, the group said. And with a recent
US Supreme Court ruling making schools liable for not intervening
when students are sexually harassed, educators say there is a
heightened urgency to teach all students respect for body
development early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most school nurses are aware of girls having their first
menses earlier,'' said Dr. Judith Robinson, executive director of
the National Association of School Nurses. She and educators in
Massachusetts said most girls are taught about menstruation around
fifth-grade in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to teach them earlier. And if you teach them about the
respiratory and circulatory system and then the reproductive
system, it can work,'' Robinson said. ``We don't want these girls
to be frightened by the changes their bodies are going through.''
</P>
<P>
   For mothers who grew up learning about sexuality in embarrassing
parent-daughter nights in seventh- or eighth-grade, teaching girls
about the birds and bees when they are still hoarding Beanie Babies
is a jarring thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I was in fourth-grade when it happened and I was
ten and that seemed so young,'' said Linda Thomson, a parent of a
kindergarten girl. ``Then you say it could even happen younger and
I can't imagine it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her community has some of the most progressive and early
reproductive lessons for girls and boys: a voluntary lesson as
early as third-grade that includes parents.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 30 years puberty's onset was believed to usually
start between 9 and 12, according to the National Association of
School Nurses. Historically, it began even later, although exact
ranges or ages are not available.
</P>
<P>
   But a 1997 study from the American Association of Pediatrics
suggests puberty's onset is now occuring as early as age 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a definite answer as to why,'' said Dr. Marc R.
Laufer, chief of gynecology at Children's Hospital in Boston. He
said the leading theory is that menstruation can be triggered by a
certain amount and type of body fat. For many reasons, children's
body fat can appear earlier.
</P>
<P>
   More striking, the study notes how much earlier African American
girls develop compared to Caucasian girls. The survey of 17,077
girls between 3 and 12 showed that between ages 7 and 8, 15 percent
of Caucasian girls and 48 percent of African American girls had
some breast development, pubic hair, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Laufer say the reason for the disparity is also uknown.
</P>
<P>
   He was so concerned with the number of young women saw who
didn't know how to deal with their body development, Laufer
co-opened the Center for Young Women's Health at Children's
Hospital this month _ specificially designed to help young women
deal with their changing bodies.
</P>
<P>
   School staff and parents say they want children to understand
the changes their bodies are going through, but worry talking about
sexuality with immature youth can lead to experimentation many
children are not ready for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stick the formality of reproduction in fifth-grade, and I
think it is in a good grade, it shouldn't go younger,'' said Diana
LeBlanc, assistant wellness director for Lynn, Mass. public
schools. LeBlanc says her district's school nurses look out for
girls who are showing breast development early and counsel them
one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a continuum. There is always a few starting earlier and
some starting later. We try to teach to the middle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some regular teachers who are pressed to teach about
sexuality may have trouble talking about the subject to any grade,
much less younger students.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to consider most teachers didn't have health
education,'' said Nancy Strunk, HIV/Sexuality education program
coordinator for Boston Public Schools. ``They learned what they
know from their mothers who didn't have health education either. It
can be uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   She tries to encourage reproductive discussions in fourth-grade,
but most of it takes place in fifth and sixth grades.
</P>
<P>
   In response to lack of expertise by some teachers, Strunk and
health coordinators in other districts are increasingly hiring
outside groups to give weeklong body development lessons to girls
and boys, usually with parental permission or involvement. They
stress they are not teaching sex education _ but about sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are teaching them about sexuality and skills so they don't
get pregnant, so they resist peer pressure,'' Strunk said. ``Just
because you are able to bear a child doesn't mean you
should...that's what we teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some parents say they may be able to handle the academic
talk on sex earlier _ as long as they are part of the conversation
or asked about it first.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter is so aware today of different areas of
sexuality,'' said Cheryl Sydorko, whose eight-year-old daughter was
in a combined second and third grade class this past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advertising is out there and she has observed so much. I'd
rather see her educated than be frightened with no facts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
