<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITY-REA     06-23 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITY-REAX-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVOCATES FOR DISABLED ARE STUNNED, EMPLOYERS RELIEVED, BY RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (See also SCOTUS-STATES-RIGHTS, SCOTUS-ASBESTOS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ROBIN TONER and MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   c.1999 N.Y. Times News
Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Advocates for the disabled, declaring that a
majority of the Supreme Court fundamentally misunderstood the
purpose of the Americans with Disabilities Act, began Wednesday to
scramble for legal and political strategies to counter the court's
ruling this week that limited the law's protections.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, was one of the chief sponsors of the
1990 law, raised the possibility of seeking ``some kind of
legislative remedy'' to override the court's holding, but added:
``It's unclear where we go from here. I think this will send a
shock wave through the disability community.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, business groups heaved a collective sigh of relief.
``The great fear was a dramatic expansion in lawsuits, with a lot
of people without clearly defined disabilities clearly empowered to
seek legal relief,'' said Stephan Bokat, general counsel for the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``That was very, very scary for
employers.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue was a set of three employment-related decisions in
which the court held that people who could function normally when
they wore glasses or took medication could not generally be
considered disabled, despite their physical impairments, and thus
did not fall under the Americans with Disabilities Act's
protections against employment discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates asserted that the ruling created a bizarre catch-22,
in which those who managed to correct and cope with their
disability would lose protection against discrimination because of
it. ``Really, what they're not getting is that this isn't the old
model of disability where you're supposed to be so unable that you
get some kind of government dole,'' said Arlene Mayerson, directing
attorney of the Disability Rights Education and Defense Fund, an
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it's about is a whole new image of disabled people being
independent and able and wanting to participate and work,'' Ms.
Mayerson added. ``It's just so completely contrary to that notion
that if someone takes something that mitigates the disabling
effects of their impairment, which enables them to participate
more, that they're then cut out of protection under the Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said he feared that people with conditions like
controlled diabetes or epilepsy would now be subject to employment
discrimination, perhaps by employers fearing the added health
insurance costs of having people with those conditions on the
payroll. ``I don't know how many people with disabilities are going
to be denied jobs before people recognize the wrongness of this
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Christopher Bell, a former associate legal counsel for
disability cases at the Equal Employment Opportunities Commission
and a partner with the law firm of Jackson Lewis, which represents
employers, asserted that the court's ruling was a reasoned
response. ``The Supreme Court, in whacking back the definition of
disability, may have saved the ADA, like whacking back a bush will
help it grow,'' he said. ``It could have trivialized disability,
entitling half of America to accommodation, but there would have
been a political backlash.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell added that employers should not read too much into the
decision. ``Employers need to be careful not to leap to the
conclusion that anyone taking medication is no longer covered,'' he
said. ``This raises the bar for disability coverage, but it really
only means that truly disabled people can make a claim.''
</P>
<P>
   The employment decisions that were handed down this week
overshadowed another ADA-related decision that was considered a
major victory for disability rights groups. That decision, in a
case brought against the state of Georgia by two women with mental
impairments, held that isolating disabled people in large
institutions when there was no medical reason for their confinement
was a violation of the federal disabilities law.
</P>
<P>
   As advocates for the disabled met in Washington on Wednesday,
that decision, known as the Olmstead case, was a reason for
celebration. ``Olmstead is huge,'' said Christine Griffin,
executive director of the Disability Law Center in Massachusetts.
``The court has said that unjust isolation equals prohibited
discrimination under the ADA, and we couldn't be happier about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the employment decisions clearly rankled those who were
instrumental in pushing through the disabilities act. ``Where it
leaves the ADA is with a huge gaping hole right at its heart,''
asserted Professor Chai Feldblum of Georgetown Law School, who
helped draft the original law.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers for the disabled said it would take time, and
substantially more litigation, before the full impact of the
court's ruling was clear. ``I would not characterize it as a good
news, bad news decision,'' said Catherine Hanssens, director of the
Aids Project of the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund. ``I
would characterize it as a bad news, but doors still open
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for business hailed the ruling as providing a
much-needed degree of clarity in a difficult area of law. ``It
provides a greater certainty for business people,'' said Thomas
Hungar, a partner with Gibson Dunn and Crutcher, the
Washington-based law firm that represented United Parcel Service,
one of the parties in the three cases that prompted the court's
ruling. ``It resolves the inconsistency in lower court rulings on
this issue of threshold, which frankly is in everyone's interest.
And it allows everyone to bring the focus back to the truly
disabled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 1954EDT &QL; 
