<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-23 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF BELATEDLY MANAGES TO SOLVE DE SWARDT'S GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When Martina Hingis earned an unwelcome opportunity to
spend some quality time with Mom, it was supposed to greatly
enhance Steffi Graf's chances to cuddle with the Wimbledon ladies'
singles trophy for the eighth time in her incandescent and recently
revived career.
</P>
<P>
   But the No. 2 seed briefly _ and shockingly _ found herself
staring at a spot in the abyss alongside her immediate superior
Wednesday. While a Centre Court crowd sat benumbed, Graf dropped
five of the first six games to 38th-ranked Mariaan de Swardt.
Though she did not recover in time to salvage the first set, she
asserted the form that has carried her to 22 Grand Slam crowns,
dispatching de Swardt, 4-6, 6-3, 6-2, in 1 hour 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Graf advanced to the third round and avoided the
cataclysmic fate that befell top seed Hingis in her opening match
Tuesday. Playing without her imperious mother, Melanie Molitor, on
the premises for the first time, Hingis was jolted by qualifier
Jelena Dokic, 6-2, 6-0. Later that night, she withdrew from the
doubles with what was officially and vaguely described as a
recurring medical problem _ most likely a bruised ego _ and
immediately departed the All England Club, perhaps to rejoin her
mother, mend a reported rift, and figure out what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Though this doesn't leave a clear patch of grass for Graf _ not
with the likes of Lindsay Davenport, Monica Seles, defender Jana
Novotna, and Venus Williams still on the prowl _ she wasn't
expected to encounter such resistance from de Swardt, with whom she
had split two career meetings, losing the most recent in 1995. But,
fresh from her galvanizing upset of Hingis in the French Open
final, her first major title since 1996, Graf inexplicably found de
Swardt to be a mystery in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way she was serving,'' said Graf, ``there was not very
much I could do. I started serving pretty poorly, and she was going
for her shots. I felt a little under pressure on my serve. Instead
of concentrating on what I wanted to do, I was worrying about what
she was going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Graf, who entered the land of tennis fossils last week when
she turned 30, showed that she isn't ancient history just yet,
making the first set competitive, if not successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it started at 5-1 when I came back to make it 5-4,''
she said. ``That is when I personally felt much better, and I think
that made it turn around for me.''
</P>
<P>
   She was never threatened thereafter, but that doesn't mean she's
taking crown No. 8 for granted, even with Tuesday's upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, that is funny,'' she said. ``You always ask me
about the finals, and I just won my second round. You know, I'm not
having an easy road here.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Hingis, at least she's still on it.
</P>
<P>
   The other prime women contenders in action Wednesday experienced
no such perils. Fourth seed Seles blitzed Marlene Weingartner, 6-0,
6-0; No. 6 Williams handled Elena Tatarkova, 6-3, 6-4; and No. 8
Nathalie Tauziat dispatched Amanda Hopmans, 6-3, 6-4. The most
notable casualty was erstwhile child prodigy Jennifer Capriati,
whose recent victory at Strasbourg _ her first title in six years _
signaled her return from the teenage wasteland that had derailed
her career. She was bounced by Seda Noorlander, 6-1, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, the suspense was minimal as Pete Sampras
solidified his stature as the Green Monster. The top seed and
defending champion again proved that grass is his elixir, disposing
of Sebastien Lareau, 6-4, 6-2, 6-3, in a tidy 1:21.
</P>
<P>
   After a desultory start to his year _ punctuated by his
bypassing the Australian Open to work on his celebrity golf game
and his second-round ouster from the French Open _ Sampras won the
Queen's Club Wimbledon warmup on God's sod. Now he's on course for
his sixth Wimbledon, which would enable him to tie Roy Emerson's
all-time men's standard of 12 Grand Slam singles titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm where I want to be right now in the tournament,'' said
Sampras, ``and I must admit that winning Queen's was what I needed.
I'm where I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Where he doesn't want to be is in a state of obsession over
Emerson's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about it playing, you know, I'm really not,''
said Sampras. ``Just to be put in this position is an effort in
itself, but I'm not consumed with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras did acknowledge that he found some inspiration in
watching his once and future US Davis Cup teammate, gritty veteran
Jim Courier, outlast 12th seed Carlos Moya, the former French king,
in a five-set survival test on Centre Court, 6-3, 3-6, 7-6, 3-6,
6-2. And speaking of Boston-bound Davis Cuppers, the runner-up
prize for most arduous male victory of the day went to seventh seed
Mark Philippoussis, who outlasted Australian teammate Mark
Woodforde, 6-7, 7-6, 7-6, 6-4. Presumably, they'll be back on
speaking terms by next month's Cup quarterfinal against the
Americans at Longwood.
</P>
<P>
   Third seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov also struggled a bit, beating
qualifier Paradorm Srichaphan, 6-7, 6-4, 7-6, 6-4. The only other
Top 10 seed to complete his match, No. 9 Greg Rusedski, gave his
hometown crowd nothing to fret about, eliminating qualifier Arvind
Parmar, 6-3, 6-4, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   And making Sampras's day a little sunnier, his French conqueror,
Andrei Medvedev, the runner-up in Paris, displayed no staying power
on grass, falling to Daniel Nestor, 6-1, 7-5, 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
