<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7210 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-0624-COX     06-23 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE SAYS TAPES BY EX-MISTRESS COULD BE USED AGAINST CISNEROS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge said Wednesday that secretly-made
tapes could be used against former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros
if they demonstrate that he was being blackmailed by his
ex-mistress when he certified to FBI officials that he was not.
</P>
<P>
   In pre-trial jousting, U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin
warned that he would not allow into evidence all 34 tapes recorded
by Cisneros's ex-mistress, Linda Jones, and offered by the
prosecution. But he indicated he might take some tapes from
prosecutors ``if they can show that the (taped material) itself was
an extortion document.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is scheduled to go on trial in September on charges
brought by independent counsel David Barrett that he lied to the
FBI and concealed more than $250,000 in ``hush money'' to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's encouragement to the prosecutors came after the
defense team appeared to be making headway in their drive to
whittle away at Jones's credibility. Jones backtracked Wednesday on
her denials a day earlier that she had planned to seek a book deal
to cash in on her seven-year relationship with Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night I did remember a conversation with (Lubbock, Texas,
lawyer) Bruce Magness that he would like to go to New York'' to
inquire about a book contract, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that ``I still didn't recall'' writing several
chapters of a book that defense lawyers have entered into evidence.
But she acknowledged that her lawyers were seeking to sell film
rights to her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was with my knowledge,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, known also by her married name of Medlar, is serving a 3
1/2 year prison term in Carswell, Texas, for bank fraud arising out
of her financial dealings in her hometown of Lubbock. And in her
third day of testimony, Cisneros's legal team bore down on her
record of lying, including admissions that she misled federal
officials at 11 meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1994, in every way , shape and form, the witness has
committed perjury and obstruction of justice, and lied repeatedly
to the FBI and is in jail for lying,'' attorney Barry Simon told
the judge at day's end. ``And the government offers us this
witness!''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has admitted to concealing the fact that she duplicated
her tape recordings of Cisneros, used a Radio Shack ``boom box'' to
delete portions that she considered to be harmful to herself, and
put all of the originals in a dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Simon argued that all the tapes should be tossed
out. ``They are copied and they have been massively played with,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal prosecutor countered that if the voice could be traced
to Cisneros, the evidence was valid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each and every one of these tapes is a non-hearsay
statement,'' said prosecutor Mark Jackowski. He cited admissions
``out of the defendant's own mouth'' that Cisneros made payments to
Jones that far exceeded the $10,000 a year that he reported to FBI
agents when he was under consideration to become housing secretary
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, the former mayor of San Antonio where Jones worked as
his political fund-raiser, served in the federal housing post until
his indictment in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin, who is not expected to rule on the tapes until next
week at the earliest, opened the door to allowing at least some of
the recordings into the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution has a problem,'' he said. ``They have to take
the evidence where they found it. They didn't invent Medlar
(Jones).''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, three days of hearing Jones admit repeatedly
to lying brought this comment from the judge:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question, I'm astounded when I sit here and listen
to what happened in this case. I guess there are people who don't
know how to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he must now determine whether Jones was telling the
truth now.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Simon answered: ``We're going to bring in witnesses to
say she's lying today from the witness stand.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
