<HEADER>
A7213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-23 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: ECONOMIC PACKAGE APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to galvanize a slowing economy, fight unemployment
and stabilize the euro, the Cabinet approved an economic reform
package that would cut billions from the budget in the next four
years. The package combines reductions in social spending and
subsidies with tax cuts for businesses and an increase in fuel
taxes. The plan is expected to be voted on by Parliament in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: BLAIR PUTS OFF ULSTER TRIP
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair postponed a planned trip to Belfast
until next week and warned that his push for resolving a dispute
over paramilitary disarmament by next Wednesday represented the
``last chance'' to avoid a return to bloodshed in Northern Ireland.
Blair said he was staying in London to attend the funeral on Friday
of Cardinal Basil Hume, the leader of the Catholic Church in
Britain. Blair will discuss Ulster with his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, who will also be at the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: `CARLOS' LOSES COURT APPEAL
</P>
<P>
   France's highest court confirmed the life sentence being served
by Ilich Ramirez Sanchez, 50, the international terrorist who calls
himself Carlos the Jackal, for the murder of two French police
agents and a Lebanese informant in Paris in 1975. He was convicted
in December 1997 and has been in French prisons since his capture
in 1994. Austria wants to extradite him to be tried for the 1975
kidnapping of OPEC oil ministers in Vienna, in which three people
died.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: VOW ON BASQUE PEACE
</P>
<P>
   In the annual State of the Nation debate in Parliament, Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar vowed to press for a lasting peace in the
Basque region, where the rebel group ETA has observed a cease-fire
since September, halting 30 years of separatist violence. Aznar
promised a ``flexible'' policy for the 439 convicted or suspected
Basque rebels in Spanish jails. Some 134 Basques have been released
since the cease-fire began.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: TOLL IN CLASH CLIMBS
</P>
<P>
   The death toll has climbed to at least 68 after two days of
fighting between government soldiers and left-wing guerrillas in a
mountainous northern region. government forces have suffered the
bulk of the losses in the combat, which began when the country's
largest rebel group began a drive on the headquarters of the leader
of Colombia's most feared paramilitary group. Army units were
airlifted into the area to challenge them, but ended up suffering
their highest level of casualties in any confrontation with the
rebels this year.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: POLLUTION ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   The senior environmental officials of Latin America's largest
cities, with a total population of 68 million, acknowledged in a
statement issued in Mexico City that their residents ``suffer a
threat to their personal health'' because of air pollution. They
called on their own local and national governments to improve air
quality, and on owners of polluting cars to ``assume social
responsibility for their actions.'' The statement was signed by
officials from Mexico City, Buenos Aires, Rio de Janeiro, Sao
Paulo, Bogota, Colombia, and Lima, Peru.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: PLEA ON FOREIGNERS
</P>
<P>
   The National Human Rights Commission, a government agency, has
asked Congress to give foreigners the right to appeal when the
President expels them from the country, the newspaper Reforma
reported. Under the Constitution, President Ernesto Zedillo can
summarily expel any foreigner deemed undesirable. Since January
1998 he has thrown out 55 foreigners accused of meddling in
politics in the state of Chiapas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
