<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER UPSETS MOYA AS AGASSI PROVIDES SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ For starters, Jim Courier, whose habitual
first-round departures from Wimbledon in the past three years had
been made in obscurity on the hintercourts, had to remember how to
make his bow to the Royal Box as he marched onto Center Court.
</P>
<P>
   That pleasantry conquered, he turned his attention to turning
back a gallant serve-and-volley fusillade sent his way by
12th-seeded Carlos Moya. Moya, the 1998 French Open champion,
briefly held the No. 1 ranking this spring and briefly floored
Courier Wednesday by defying a tradition of Spanish baselining and
sprinting to the net like Fred Perry.
</P>
<P>
   But the 61st-ranked Courier, who had not reached the third round
here since his run to the Wimbledon final in 1993, got there
Wednesday by fending off Moya for 3 hours 3 minutes. The 6-3, 3-6,
7-6 (7-1), 3-6, 6-2 upset was, Courier felt, in doubt until the end
of the fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   ``He served and volleyed every point except for three in the
match,'' said Courier, who countered the Spaniard's aggression with
a string of perfect returns, all of them wrought as much from
desperation as good intentions. ``I kind of had to. I don't know if
I can return much better than I returned in that match, and he just
kept coming up with great volleys all the time, and I was thinking,
`OK, he's not a natural serve-and-volleyer, eventually he's going
to break down, and he never did.'''
</P>
<P>
   With a crisp crosscourt forehand pass at match point, Courier,
who has not won a Grand Slam title since 1993 and last summer
skipped the U.S. Open while debating early retirement, gained
Wimbledon's third round for the first time in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Courier, a hero in the first round of Davis Cup this April in
Birmingham, England _ where he beat Tim Henman in the first match
and outlasted Greg Rusedski, 8-6, in the fifth set in the fifth and
deciding bout _ finally seems to be translating his patriotic team
fervor to the individual tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi, who cited Courier's Davis Cup theatrics as
inspirational to his own first French Open title run earlier this
month, sat in the Center Court stands as a gesture of solidarity
Wednesday. And Pete Sampras, who rejoined the Davis Cup team for
the second round after watching Courier, joked about the new
camaraderie the veteran threesome share.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of love in the air, huh?'' said Sampras, who
zipped into the third round Wednesday with a 6-4, 6-2, 6-3
dissection of 100th-ranked Sebastien Lareau of Canada that was
equal parts magic and mechanics. The five-time champion now faces
595th-ranked Danny Sapsford of Britain, a realist who remarked that
there is probably a far better chance of a second coming during the
third round than a victory against Sampras, now 41-1 over the past
six years here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is not to be overconfident,'' said Sampras, now
five victories from tying Roy Emerson's career record of 12 Grand
Slam titles. ``I'm where I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Paul Goldstein of Rockville, Md., the 112th-ranked
Wimbledon first-timer who disposed of another seeded Spaniard, No.
16 Felix Mantilla, 6-2, 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 6-2. Goldstein's next
challenge is 87th-ranked Daniel Nestor of Canada, who Wednesday
ousted Andrei Medvedev, the French Open runner-up to Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, Goldstein was busy graduating from
Stanford, where he rubbed elbows with Tiger Woods and Chelsea
Clinton and obtained a degree in human biology. ``The area of
concentration is socio-economics of race, whatever that is,'' said
Goldstein, who admitted there is no obvious link between his field
of study and his field of play. ``It just means that when guys
figure out how to beat me and I'm losing first round every week, I
might be able to go out and get a job somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   While Courier used his return to reach the third round,
seventh-seeded Mark Philippoussis and ninth-seeded Greg Rusedski
relied on their serves. Philippoussis used 38 aces to thwart his
33-year-old Davis Cup teammate, Mark Woodforde, 6-7 (4-7), 7-6
(8-6), 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, and remain on track for a fourth-round
serve-fest with Rusedski, who needed only 17 aces to subdue
455th-ranked Arvind Parmar, 6-3, 6-4, 7-6 (7-3). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2002EDT &QL; 
