<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMA-UNIONS-(TRIMS)-NY     06-23 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-UNIONS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATED BY MANAGED CARE, MEDICAL ASSOCIATION WILL UNIONIZE
DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association, whose members viewed
themselves for decades as elite professionals who did not need a
union, voted Wednesday to form a union for doctors in what it
called an effort to level the playing field with powerful managed
care organizations.
</P>
<P>
   At a delegates meeting in Chicago, the 290,000-member
association jettisoned its anti-unionization stance because so many
doctors complain of feeling powerless in their dealings with health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Several health industry experts said the decision by the AMA,
long a pillar of conservatism, underlined how sweeping the changes
have been in the health-care industry and how frustrated and angry
thousands of doctors have become.
</P>
<P>
   The 152-year-old medical association, which represents 34
percent of the nation's doctors, down from 45 percent a decade ago,
also felt pressure to act because several of the nation's most
powerful unions were already aggressively seeking to unionize
doctors in moves that eroded the AMA's base and made it seem timid
and behind the times in fighting for its members.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the AMA voted to set up a branch that will work to
unionize two groups of doctors _ salaried employees and medical
residents _ which together represent about one-third of the
nation's 620,000 practicing physicians. The association also said
it would work to unionize some of the nation's 325,000
self-employed doctors, but to do that it needs to persuade Congress
to give these doctors the right to bargain collectively.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to reassure patients that the AMA was not forsaking the
Hippocratic oath, the association's leaders insisted Wednesday that
an AMA doctor's union would never strike if it were to jeopardize
patient care. AMA leaders said repeatedly that a major reason for
favoring unionization was to pressure HMP's and hospitals to
improve patient care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective here is to give America's physicians the
leverage they now lack to guarantee that patient care is not
compromised or neglected for the sake of profits,'' said Dr.
Randolph D. Smoak Jr. chairman of the association's board of
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA envisions trying to set up dozens of union locals for
doctors around the country over the next five years. Industry
experts estimate that nearly 40,000 doctors now belong to unions,
and the AMA is expected to work to significantly increase the
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major step for an organization that had been
slipping,'' said Dr. Barry Liebowitz, president of the Doctor's
Council, a New York-based union of 2,500 doctors that is the
nation's oldest union of attending physicians. ``The endorsement of
a doctors union by the AMA gives an enormous psychological boost to
the movement to unionize doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   The association approved the unionization measure in a tense and
close vote by show of hands. Association officials said no formal
count was conducted. The debate was so fierce that while the
association's board had recommended against forming a union
affiliate, the association's 494-member House of Delegates rejected
the board's advice in reaction to pro-union rumblings across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   An AMA survey found that 88 percent of doctors favored salaried
physicians organizing to negotiate with hospitals and managed
care-organization.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in private practice are not allowed to unionize because
federal labor law permits only people described as employees to
unionize. Indeed, when self-employed doctors have sought to
unionize, they faced the threat of antitrust charges of conspiring
in restraint of trade.
</P>
<P>
   In its resolution Wednesday, the AMA vowed to lobby for a
federal antitrust exemption that would enable self-employed doctors
to engage in collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Troy M. Tippett, a delegate from Pensacola, Fla. who voted
against the unionization resolution, said unionization was
inappropriate for professional groups and would only help the
minority of doctors who are considered employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A union is not the answer for medicine,'' said Tippett. ``The
union can do noting to deal with the payers, like insurance
companies. Unions can do something for you only if you're an
employed physician.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At a House Judiciary Committee hearing on Tuesday, officials
with the Justice Department and Federal Trade Commission testified
against granting an antitrust exemption to self-employed doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission continues to believe that such an exemption
would be bad medicine for consumers,'' Robert Pitofsky, the trade
commission's chairman. He argued that with such an exemption,
health-care costs would jump, and consumers would face higher
co-payments and insurance premiums
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission continues to believe that competition among
health care providers and among health plans is an important tool
for controlling costs, providing consumer choice and promoting
innovation and high quality,'' Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The association's president, Nancy W. Dickey, disagreed,
insisting that an AMA-backed union would focus on improving patient
care. Many doctors have complained that managed care organizations
dictate treatment decisions, overload them with paperwork and force
them to see a set number of patients per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients should feel good that the doctors now have another
tool to try to influence insurers and managed-care companies that
have become so large and aggressive that their contracts with
doctors often don't allow doctors to practice the best quality of
medicine,'' Dr. Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   But many health-care experts questioned whether the unionization
move was as altruistic as the doctors suggested. ``I don't really
believe this is being done for patients,'' said Howard Berliner, a
professor of health policy at the New School for Social Research in
New York. ``This is happening because doctors' incomes, doctors'
sense of autonomy are getting killed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   AMA officials took pains to assert that they would be different
from other unions. They said doctors in an AMA union would never
strike _ a vow not taken by most other doctors' unions. And they
also said that unlike traditional unions, an AMA unions would not
focus on mundane matters like pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Several association members said the group was steering a middle
course between conservative older doctors who opposed unionization
and more activist younger doctors, many of whom are salaried.
Forgoing strikes pleases more conservative doctors, as does the
association's talk that it will not drum up support for unions, but
will instead provide unionization help to any members who ask.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, officials at other unions vowed to compete
with the AMA's efforts, asserting, for example, that the AMA would
not be as effective in bargaining because it was taking its biggest
weapon _ striking _ off the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to form an ersatz, quasi labor union that will
not use all the tools available, such as the possibility of
strikes,'' said Robert L. Weinmann, president of the Union of
American Physicians and Dentists, which recently organized 800
doctors working for Los Angeles County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
