<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ASBESTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT VOIDS $1.5 BILLION ASBESTOS SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (see also SCOTUS-STATES-RIGHTS, SCOTUS-DISABILITY-REAX) 
(bl) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday set aside a $1.5
billion landmark settlement that was to have resolved the claims of
as many as 186,000 victims of asbestos poisoning against Fibreboard
Corp., one of the leading makers of products using the
fire-retardant substance.
</P>
<P>
   The justices concluded that the claimants' lawyers had a
possible conflict of interest between getting the most for their
clients and striking a quick deal that would garner huge legal
fees. They also found that the lower court that approved the
agreement that would have sharply limited any other lawsuits
brought against Fibreboard had failed to consider that there was
almost certainly more money available for the claims, particularly
since Fibreboard was only contributing $500,000. (Fibreboard was
sold to Owens Corning two years ago for $515 million.)
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 decision clarified the standards for class-action
lawsuits and raised the barriers for corporations to turn to the
courts to resolve large and complex product-liability complaints in
issues like tobacco, breast implants and handguns.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, companies in cases involving such products as
cigarettes, orthopedic bone screws, diet pills and pesticides have
tried to limit their liability by striking settlements that
prohibit any current or future claimants from dropping out of the
cases to file their own suits. But Wednesday's decision will make
it far more difficult for defendants to reach such settlements
without either paying top dollar or resorting to bankruptcy
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was also a repudiation of a small group of
plaintiffs' lawyers who had tried to settle the cases facing
Fibreboard, which had managed through skillful negotiation and
legal tactics to structure a deal in which its insurers would have
paid all but $500,000 of the proposed settlement. The $1.535
billion deal at the center of Wednesday's decision was struck in
August 1993, on the eve of an important appeals court hearing, in a
coffee shop in Tyler, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Both the majority opinion Wednesday by Justice David H. Souter,
and concurring and dissenting opinions by other members of the
court, called upon Congress to find a solution to ``the elephantine
mass of asbestos cases'' and expressed deep frustration with the
procedural rules that have limited the ability of judges to resolve
the asbestos crisis facing state and federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The final toll of asbestos-related health problems remains
unknown, in large part because illnesses often occur many years
after exposure, although one judicial study concluded that there
may be as many as 265,000 deaths by the year 2015 and many millions
more health problems from exposure to asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   The court cases, which have so far been sharply limited in their
ability to resolve hundreds of thousands of cases, have nonetheless
taken many millions of dollars from the companies to pay for
lawyers, money that would otherwise have been used to help victims.
Indeed, the study described in Wednesday's opinions noted that 61
cents of every dollar that would otherwise be available for victims
of asbestos exposure is now going to lawyers and for other
transactional costs.
</P>
<P>
   While the House Judiciary Committee is set to hold hearings next
week on new legislation that would set up an administrative agency
to resolve asbestos claims, opposition from trial lawyers, the
AFL-CIO and some asbestos manufacturers have in the past blocked
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision, Ortiz vs. Fibreboard Corp., No. 97-1704,
was the second time in two years that the High Court had analyzed
the class-action rules embodied in Rule 23 of the federal Rules of
Civil Procedure to strike down a major asbestos settlement. In
1997, the justices threw out a $1.3 billion class action settlement
that had been reached by 20 large asbestos makers.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Amchem Products vs. Windsor, the court concluded
that the asbestos victims had interests that were too diverse to be
represented in a single class-action lawsuit. The justices also
found a serious conflict in the way the settlement treated current
asbestos victims and those whose exposure to asbestos had not yet
manifested serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after handing down the Amchem decision, the justices
asked a federal appeals court in Texas to apply its principles in
reconsidering the $1.5 billion settlement in the Fibreboard case.
In contrast to the Amchem settlement, the Fibreboard settlement was
binding on all current and future claimants against the company on
the theory that there was a highly limited amount of money that was
available to Fibreboard.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of these differences, the appeals court appeared
to make short shrift of the Supreme Court's decision in the Amchem
case, affirming the Fibreboard settlement in a five paragraph
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But in asking the High Court to reverse the appeals court,
Professor Laurence Tribe of Harvard Law School began his brief with
the rather unorthodox style. ``Some people just can't take a
hint,'' he wrote of the 5th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, which
had appeared to largely ignore the 1997 case.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the majority of the Supreme Court agreed. Souter's
opinion was laced with criticisms of the reasoning of the appeals
court and district court that had approved the settlement. The
justices faulted the lower courts for failing to undertake an
independent evaluation of the potential insurance funds available,
simply accepting the settlement terms at face value. While a
proposed settlement might ordinarily be good evidence of the amount
of money available for claims, the court said, the potentially huge
fees for the plaintiffs' lawyers may have unfairly tainted the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a strictly rational world, plaintiffs' counsel would always
press for the limit of what the defense would pay,'' the court
wrote. ``But with an already enormous fee within counsel's grasp,
zeal for the client may relax sooner than it would in a case
brought on behalf of one claimant.''
</P>
<P>
   The court concluded that the proposed settlement's distribution
scheme was unfair and that it had unfairly excluded too many
asbestos victims. The Justices also said that by only giving up
$500,000, Fibreboard had failed to supply enough money to justify
the requirement that no claimants may opt-out of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Stephen G. Breyer, joined by
Justice John Paul Stevens, maintained that the court should have
given more latitude to district courts to find remedies to resolve
the explosion of asbestos litigation. Breyer also concluded that
the settlement would have made far more money available to the
claimants than they might otherwise get as long as Congress fails
to address the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
