<SLUG> BC-CALIF-NUDE-BEACH-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT NUDE BEACH, CLOTHING ISN'T OPTIONAL ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ In the sports shop at the Torrey Pines Gliderport,
on a wind-swept bluff above the Pacific, a stack of curious signs
hang for sale above the racks of brochures on hang-gliding and
parasailing, with the cheery exhortation: ``Buy Me, $19.95.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs are reproductions of a local cultural artifact:
``Swimsuits Optional Beyond This Point. San Diego Muni. Code
56.53.'' When a young tourist bought one with a sheepish grin this
afternoon, he asked for directions to the slender strip of sand
hundreds of feet below.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right down those stairs,'' the clerk said, pointing
toward the ocean. ``But it's not nude anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For as long as anyone can remember, that strip of shoreline,
Black's Beach, has been one of the most famous of the nude beaches
that dot the California coast, drawing free-spirited sun worshipers
from San Diego and around the world to its isolated stretch of hot
black sand and cold, roiling surf. But it has not been a legal nude
beach since 1977, when a local voter referendum narrowly revoked
the landmark 1974 ``clothing optional'' ordinance memorialized in
the souvenir sign. And after this week, if the authorities have
their way, much of it will not be a nude beach in practice, either.
</P>
<P>
   After two decades of genial non-enforcement, local officials
decided to crack down on the bare skin in response to recent
complaints about lewd behavior and semipublic sex on some parts of
the 1,200-foot-long city beach, and signs announcing the ban are
going up this week. When a two-week grace period ends, bathers
caught lounging in the buff will be subject to a $135 misdemeanor
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was happening was that grandma and grandpa would be out
tide-pooling with Johnny from Wisconsin, and the kid would look up
and say, ``Oh, Granny!'' said Scott Tillson, chief of staff to City
Councilman Harry Mathis, who represents the La Jolla district and
took the lead in the decision to enforce the existing ban on nudity
after receiving complaints this spring. One complaint had it that a
topless woman was asleep on the beach and woke up to find a man
standing over her fondling himself.
</P>
<P>
   A series of meetings ensued, Tillson said, and officials decided
that the decades-long assumption of ``no harm, no foul'' no longer
prevailed and that tougher enforcement was needed, especially since
nude bathers had begun encroaching into the more populated strip of
beach closest to civilization.
</P>
<P>
   But dedicated nudists will not be entirely out of luck. Black's
Beach is the informal name for what is actually two parks: Torrey
Pines City Beach, on the south end near the Scripps Pier, and
Torrey Pines State Beach, stretching north below the renowned
Torrey Pines Golf Course. Though nudity is not legal on the state
beach, either, it is the most isolated stretch and local officials
say the state lifeguards have told them they have no intention of
changing their longstanding practice of simply looking the other
way.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``For years, there have been periodic attempts to enforce the
ban,'' said Lieut. Brant D. Bass of the San Diego City Lifeguard
Service, as he patrolled Black's Beach in his bright orange pickup
truck under a brilliant sky Wednesday. ``But people would blow a
whistle when they saw a state ranger coming, and cover up.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, getting to Black's Beach is no easy feat. There are
gentler descents available at the north and south ends, but the
heart of the beach is accessible only over a rickety path of old
wooden stairs and slats dug into the hillside below the gliderport,
or an even more vertiginous plunge known as the ``goat trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, unsuspecting hikers mistake one worn ribbon of
dirt or another for a trail, and wind up having to be rescued by
lifeguards and paramedics from a crag along the way. It is a bit of
a thrill, and more than a bit of a workout, to scramble down the
trail, with hang-gliders casting shadows that seem at first like
some leftover pterodactyl on the wing, and even at the base of the
bluff yellow and black signs warn: ``Unstable Cliffs Stay Back!''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Johnson, 28, an aspiring actor, and Darleen Pestana, 25, a
student at San Diego State University, have lived in San Diego most
of their lives, but came to Black's for the first time only last
week. Wednesday, on their second visit, they lay placidly on their
backs in the altogether on a bright blue blanket whose
black-and-gold-flecked mica chips absorb every ray of the broiling
sun. They rolled over discreetly as a reporter approached with pen
and notepad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would just really be too bad if people didn't have a place
like this to go,'' said Johnson, whose perch on the city-controlled
section of the beach will soon be officially off limits. ``It's a
long beach, and most of it is regulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillson, the City Council staff member, said that lifeguards
reported fewer problems with disorderly conduct at Black's than at
almost any other San Diego beach, and that nudity had been accepted
at Black's since well before it was officially sanctioned, and then
banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, it's been a nonproblem,'' he said, ``and we
expect it will become a nonproblem again.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Black's regular, a fit, 40-something man who was wearing
only surfer sunglasses as he strolled along the waterline with a
bucket stretched above his head, declined to give his name or
occupation. But he said he had been coming from his home in
downtown San Diego for seven years, and he acknowledged that there
had been some problems lately with people ``abusing the privilege''
of walking around naked.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added in his best Thoreauvian spirit: ``No doubt about
it, it's a wonderful place. A person who can't get naked and get in
touch with nature can't get in touch with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
