<SLUG> BC-LEUKOSITE-PROSCRIPT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEUKOSITE ACQUIRES PROSCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LeukoSite Inc., seeking to expand its pipeline of promising
drugs, Wednesday said it acquired ProScript Inc., a privately held
biotechnology company with an anticancer compound in early clinical
trials, for $2.3 million in LeukoSite stock plus $430,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase comes nearly 4 1/2 months after LeukoSite completed
the $14.5 million cash purchase of CytoMed Inc., a struggling
biotechnology company with two drugs in clinical trials. All three
firms are based in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``With ProScript, we are getting a group of first-rate
scientists along with two late-stage compounds and great drug
discovery platform for future drugs all at a bargain price,'' said
Augustine Lawlor, LeukoSite chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ProScript, a 7-year-old company, has struggled in recent years
with a spate of top management changes and difficulty raising
additional funding for human clinical testing of its drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has also downsized its operations from 42
people earlier this year to about 25, has a research collaboration
with Hoechst Marion Roussel Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that this acquisition offers significant scientific
and business synergies for the future,'' said Dan Burns, president
of ProScript, who is leaving the company.
</P>
<P>
   For LeukoSite, which last week announced positive results from
its pivotal 93-patient clinical trial for an injectable drug,
called Campath, to treat the most prevalent form of adult leukemia,
the ProScript acquisition will enable the company to expand its
cancer-fighting drug treatments. ProScript's proposed drug, called
PS-341, is a new class of antitumor chemotherapeutic agents.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, LeukoSite said it will raise $14.4 million in a
private placement of 1.5 million unregistered shares of LeukoSite
common stock with HealthCare Ventures LLC, already the company's
largest shareholder and Perseus Capital LLC, a recent investor.
With the sale of the new shares, HealthCare will own 20 percent of
Leukosite while Perseus will have a 7 percent ownership, said
Lawlor. Both transactions, which the company self-managed, are
expected to close in July.
</P>
<P>
   LeukoSite shares closed at 11 1/2, up 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
