<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-HINGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS RUNS HOME TO TAKE A BREAK FROM HER `GREAT LIFE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Home is where her mother is, so that's
where a despondent Martina Hingis flew Wednesday, a day after
becoming just the third top-seeded woman ever to dissolve in
Wimbledon's opening round. And where the 18-year-old Swiss star
went, soap opera-ish rumors followed:
</P>
<P>
   Are she and her mother, Melanie Molitor, on the outs because
Hingis has put her dalliance with Swiss player Ivo Heuberger ahead
of her practice regimen? Or because Molitor has expressed an
interest in opening a coaching stable and making Jelena Dokic, the
129th-ranked qualifier who trounced her daughter here, her first
nonfamily client?
</P>
<P>
   Has Hingis, a player who made all the right moves on the court
and off, and earned three Grand Slam titles and the No. 1 ranking
at age 16, reached the end of her idyll at 18? Have her family ties
frazzled and has her multimillion dollar shoe-and-clothing deal
with Tacchini dissolved without a replacement in sight?
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to take a break and recover again; it has been a great
life so far, but I just probably need a break,'' Hingis said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the teen-ager blamed a heel injury for her abrupt
withdrawal from doubles with Anna Kournikova, the player she had
hand-picked to replace Jana Novotna after dismissing Novotna,
Wimbledon's defending singles and doubles champion, as too old and
slow. But against Dokic on Tuesday, it was Hingis who looked
sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after behaving like a brat and self-destructing to a
chorus of Gallic boos in her French Open final against Steffi Graf,
Hingis seemed to wear a straitjacket during her 6-2, 6-0 loss to
the 16-year-old Dokic, a Grand Slam debutante. Their meeting had an
eerie symmetry: Dokic was the youngest player in the draw and
patterned her game on that of Hingis, who at 16 became the
century's youngest Wimbledon champion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Afraid to alienate the crowd the way she had in Paris, Hingis
accepted her defeat here passively, and later disclosed this was
probably the loneliest loss of her career because it came on the
heels of her decision to take a breather from her omnipresent
mother. A desire for mutual independence, Hingis said, was the
reason for their split, which she termed a private-life issue.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic, who practiced with Hingis at her home in Trubbach,
Switzerland, before the French Open and had been invited by Molitor
to train at their new home at the Saddlebrook resort near Tampa,
Fla., said she blocked any feelings of sympathy for Hingis. ``I try
not to think about that,'' Dokic said.
</P>
<P>
   But several other players, including Kournikova, sounded in on
Hingis' miseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got to do what she's got to do,'' said Kournikova, who
reached the third round with a 7-5, 6-4 defeat of Maria Vento
Wednesday. ``There's a lot of everything on us, and when you lose,
especially in the first round of a Grand Slam, you feel like you
lost everything. But I'm sure she'll come back strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Capriati, disheartened by a 6-1, 6-3 loss to
126th-ranked Seda Noorlander, said onlookers shouldn't be so quick
to turn Hingis' troubles into tragedies. ``It's like when they're
on top and everything's great, it's great,'' said Capriati, who was
a Grand Slam semifinalist at 15 and on the ropes at 18. ``But as
soon as there's one little thing that shows a little imperfection,
the vultures can't wait to knock them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, a longtime Saddlebrook resident who practiced there
with Hingis this spring, added, ``My advice would be to block out
all the press and negativity and not let that control the way she
feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hingis and her mother are contractually committed to
their move to Saddlebrook, where the player purchased a $500,000
home, there has been no arrangement made yet with the Dokic family.
Kevin O'Connor, the resort's marketing director, said any
invitation to Dokic would very likely exclude her father, Damir,
who was expelled from the Edgbaston tournament two weeks ago for
verbally abusing line judges and being arrested on a drunk and
disorderly charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the agreement between Martina, her mother, and Jelena Dokic
is still in place, then I would expect to see her at Saddlebrook,
but after what happened here, I'm not sure what the plans are,''
said O'Connor, who maintained that the split between Hingis and
Molitor is more rite-of-passage than rift. ``They made that
decision outside of tennis, and made it knowing what the
consequences might be here. The mother is completely willing to let
Martina try new scenarios if that's what she wants to do; that's
the kind of confidence she has in her. They know there'll be other
Wimbledons.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
