<SLUG> BC-KOREA-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND NORTH KOREA MEET ON SUSPECTED NUCLEAR ARMS SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ An American envoy met with high-level North Korean
officials here Wednesday to report on the United States' recent
inspection of a suspected nuclear-weapons complex in North Korea
and to lay the ground for more talks later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection, which occurred in May, found no evidence that
the site was being used to produce weapons.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Embassy officials here stressed that the talks between the
American envoy, Charles Kartman, and Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye
Gwan were unrelated to the increasing tension between North and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   A skirmish in the Yellow Sea last week resulted in the sinking
of a North Korean torpedo boat and the deaths of at least 20 North
Korean sailors.
</P>
<P>
   That battle has overshadowed and perhaps scuttled talks between
North and South Korea that started in Beijing this week. The two
sides met for just 90 minutes on Tuesday before the talks broke
down, with North Korea demanding an apology for the skirmish. Both
sides insist that the other fired first.
</P>
<P>
   No talks between the Koreas took place Wednesday, and South
Korean delegates said they were waiting for a phone call from the
North on when the talks could resume.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the U.S.-North Korean meeting seemed positively
cordial. While the American delegation did not comment, Kim told
reporters that he was ``ready to talk about any issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The American inspection team's conclusion that the North Korean
complex at Kumchangri was not making nuclear weapons has cleared a
significant obstacle to improving relations with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a 1994 agreement, a consortium of nations is
providing the impoverished country with fuel and power plants in
exchange for its pledge to freeze its nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
   That as well as a host of other issues relating to a peace
settlement for the Korean peninsula will be up for discussion at
talks involving the two Koreas, China and the United States,
scheduled to be held in Geneva, probably later this year.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
