<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AGENDA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH WAR OVER, CLINTON RENEWS FIGHT FOR HIS DOMESTIC AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Washington Memo) 
(rm) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the conflict in Kosovo more or less behind him
and impeachment a fading memory, President Clinton is eager to
reassert himself in the familiar realms of domestic policy and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides described the president, who returned from a
weeklong trip to Europe early Wednesday, as eager to shed the
unaccustomed mantle of wartime commander and to devote his full
energies over the next several weeks to what he truly loves:
verbally punishing Republicans over domestic policy matters like
gun control and health care.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of war and scandal, Clinton has had
little space lately in which to exercise his powers of public
persuasion on domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   But starting on Friday with an address to a group of
presidential scholars, Clinton hopes to focus public attention on a
long list of pent-up proposals, from an increase in the minimum
wage to tax credits for poor neighborhoods. As his tenure in office
winds down, the president is returning to more traditional
Democratic themes that he had until now largely muted in an effort
to fashion a third way between the orthodoxies of the dominant
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in a long time, the decks are clear for
resetting the agenda and defining the universe of the possible,''
said Joel Johnson, the newly appointed senior adviser to the
president for policy and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three weeks, Clinton plans to unveil a Medicare
proposal with a popular new prescription drug benefit and to travel
the country recycling a number of tax-cut proposals and spending
initiatives from his State of the Union message in January.
Presidential aides expressed hope that the Republican-run Congress
will enact some of Clinton's proposals, but they seem perfectly
content to use legislative gridlock as a weapon of partisan
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also be trying to advance the political ambitions
of his wife and his vice president, as well as raising millions of
dollars to help Democrats regain control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant initiatives that the president will push in
coming weeks are a plan to try to ensure the long-term solvency of
Medicare and proposals to bring private sector investment to the
nation's poorest regions.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between promotion of those policies will be several
fund-raising forays, visits with leaders from South Korea, Egypt
and Israel, announcement of the removal of the bald eagle from the
list of threatened species and an undetermined number of photo
opportunities to attack Republicans for quashing a gun-control bill
in the House and for bottling up new regulations governing health
maintenance organizations in the Senate. The White House sees those
as hanging curve balls that Clinton intends to swat out of the
political park _ repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address, Clinton proposed setting
aside 15 percent of anticipated federal budget surpluses over the
next decade to shore up Medicare, the government health plan for
the elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration has delayed release of its plan as it
struggles to reconcile competing political and financial interests
behind one of the most popular programs of guaranteed benefits to
all who qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is set to release his plan next Tuesday, meeting his
self-imposed deadline of the end of June by one day. Aides were
stingy with details, saying the president had not yet approved the
final provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a universal, affordable benefit that will ask
Medicare beneficiaries to pay a modest premium for benefits that
are substantially better,'' John Podesta, the White House chief of
staff, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The ``modest premium'' is a monthly cost that Medicare
beneficiaries will be asked to pay for prescription drug coverage,
expected to fall somewhere between $20 and $90 a month, with a
partial subsidy for the poorest recipients. But Podesta would not
be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The drug benefit seems popular with the elderly and abhorred by
the pharmaceutical industry, which sees it as a wedge for
government price controls. It is certain to set off a ferocious
fight on Capitol Hill that will almost certainly continue well into
the 2000 campaigns for Congress and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, eyeing his legacy, will spend four days in early July
touring depressed regions of the country, traveling from eastern
Kentucky to the Mississippi Delta to a South Dakota Indian
reservation to the Watts neighborhood of Los Angeles. The trip
comes late in his second term because Clinton has not been willing
before now to draw attention to the pockets of poverty that belie
the nation's general prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the president's anti-poverty plan is to inspire
private businesses to increase investment in what the president
likes to call ``untapped markets'' within the borders of the United
States. He has proposed a set of tax initiatives to help companies
open businesses in depressed areas and bring the fruits of the
economic expansion to the regions it passed by.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A subtext of those visits is the nation's continuing racial
friction and the uneven economic performance of minorities in
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real reflection of how the president looks at the
world,'' Podesta said. ``He wants to use the mechanism of
government to encourage partnership with the private sector to
spread the benefits of the great economy we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta said these programs, modeled on federal programs to spur
private investment in less-developed nations overseas, attract
bipartisan support and have a chance to win passage in the current
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Podesta also said that the president intended in coming weeks to
redeem some promises from the State of the Union and other
policy-setting speeches. Among them are a planned lawsuit against
tobacco companies to recover billions of dollars in federal health
care costs related to smoking, proposed tax credits for child care
and medical costs arising from long-term illnesses and a $5 billion
program to finance school construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
