<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-23 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE GOREBUSH ERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Relying on poll numbers as they denounce reliance on
pollsters, establishment politicians and the Boys on the Bus have
leapfrogged primary elections to decide _ nearly a year and a half
before Election Day _ that the contest is between George the Dubyuh
and Albert the Gee.
</P>
<P>
   How wrong they may be. One of the anointed may make a terrible
gaffe under stress or lose his voice or suffer an unexpected
malady. The smug linearists may be panicked by a grass-roots
emergence of a Fresh Face. Lovers of real contests will focus on
erosion of Gorebush leads and on exciting gains by John McBradley.
</P>
<P>
   But let us assume, arguendo, that conventional wisdom takes us
right through the conventions. This assumes that the old saying of
jockeys at a muddy track is true, and ``front-runners stay clean.''
</P>
<P>
   How would these non-races within each party affect our party
politics and our near-term governance?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Gorebush Era. Back when primary campaigns decided
nominations, the adage was: Lean toward the party partisans in the
primaries, then swing back toward the middle in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that differences between liberals and conservatives
were front and center until the nominees emerged. The dedicated
dominated, and the far left and far right got in their licks _
extracting promises that, when broken, at least caused
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   But during Gorebush, the race is to the swiftest to the center.
Gore is untroubled by the whining of the lefties who want to bust
the budget, and Bush is serene at the yammering of the righties who
wave litmus paper in his face. This is good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   What is good is that it frees the nominees from having to make
deals with extremists. What's bad is that it fuzzes up legitimate
debate about ideology and leaves the electorate with a choice
between personalities and campaign styles.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Michigan, we see a state that will not decide either
party's nomination but is one of the battleground states that could
decide the election. Bush is here Thursday and Gore will be here
(third time in a month) Friday. They're raising money, but the
strategy of both is to treat this as a swing state in the election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is wooing the auto industry with assurances that emission
control is good for jobs. Bush is wooing Hispanics by speaking
Spanish to them, and I don't know what he's promising. Gov. John
Engler may be behind Bob Dole, John McCain and Colin Powell on the
Bush V.P. list, but can taste White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the emphasis is on the endgame nearly 18 months
from now, not so much the primary election here next February. The
-media's question is not ``Who will win the Michigan primary?'' but
this self-hating prophecy: ``Which of the likely primary winners
will win bigger than the other, auguring victory in the general
election?''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the significance of the Gore-bush Era, stretching from
now all the way to Jan. 20, 2001, and what it will do to
governance, the favorite word of political scientists, except for
``polity'':
</P>
<P>
   _It marks the unofficial end of the Clinton Era. (Eras, in my
neat world, cannot overlap.) Pictures of the Clintons in full
battle gear talking to troops and commiserating with refugees in
Kosovo mark the beginning of their New York campaign. That makes
sense for them, because the torch has just been passed to
Gore-bush, the 18-month successor.
</P>
<P>
   _Anything Bill Clinton does now is seen as a function of how it
helps or hurts Gore. Anything the First Candidate, Hillary Clinton,
does in New York will be seen in the light of how it subtracts
money and attention from Gore and helps Bush. Together they are now
running a major state campaign, not a major nation.
</P>
<P>
   _That makes Gorebush the effective president. Congress knows it,
deferring to the new, dual loci of power. The ambassadors to
Washington and the foreign press corps know it, abandoning Samuel
Berger for Gore's Leon Fuerth and Bush's Condoleezza Rice, or
Fuerthrice.
</P>
<P>
   Is this interminable interregnum a good thing for our polity?
(Got it in.) I'm not comfortable with the temporary coalition. I'd
rather see an elected president stick to his last, and watch a
couple of good prelims before the Main Event.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
