<HEADLINE>
MCHALE TAKES HALL NOMINATION IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin McHale wanted Wednesday's sessions with reporters delayed
until late afternoon. He had a tee time, after all, and, as he put
it, ``a guy has to have some fun in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale never lost sight of that philosophy in his 12 years as a
Celtic, a career which was recognized Wednesday with the
announcement of his election to the basketball Hall of Fame. He
constantly looked for the fun in the game and generally found it,
winning three titles in Boston and earning a reputation as one of
the premier power forwards in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost feel embarrassed being honored for something you
enjoyed doing so much,'' he told reporters in a conference call.
``You want to thank them. You want to say, `Thank you for allowing
me to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McHale was one of five announced Wednesday as members of the
Hall's Class of '99. Joining him will be John Thompson, Wayne
Embry, the late Fred Zollner, and Billie Moore. Thompson and Embry
both played briefly in Boston as Bill Russell's backups while
Zollner was an early owner of the Pistons and Moore a successful
women's coach at UCLA and Cal. St.-Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   They will be inducted Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Missing again, for the third time, was McHale's Boston teammate
Dennis Johnson, who said from his home in Florida, ``I just didn't
make it. People don't make it. I'm one of those people. Would it
have been an honor? Sure. But it's not going to stop me in my
quest. I'll just sit and wait until the next time.'' Added McHale,
who frequently praised his Boston teammates for his success, ``It
would have been special to go in with DJ. I think he'll get in. I
wish it was this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Among others coming up short were Maurice Cheeks, Sidney
Moncrief, Jo Jo White, and Chet Walker.
</P>
<P>
   McHale, now the basketball operations chief of the Minnesota
Timberwolves, knew of his selection earlier in the week; it was
hardly a shock. But Wednesday was the only day he could do a
conference call and he asked the Timberwolves to delay two sessions
with reporters until late in the day because of a golf date with
Minnesota assistant coach Jerry Sichting. He is scheduled Friday to
go away with the coaching staff on a ``draft retreat.'' The
Timberwolves have two first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   McHale said he had not decided whom he would choose to present
him at the induction ceremony; an inductee gets to name two
presenters, one of whom must be in the Hall of Fame. He also said,
unconvincingly, that he hadn't really given the Hall of Fame all
that much thought, even though he was a lock to make it and had
been named as one of the top 50 players of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more special to me because it's reflective of the teams I
played on and the players I played with,'' he said. ``I was a
product of being allowed to play with other tremendous players. The
success we had as a team is the reason I was elected to the Hall of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics won a title in McHale's rookie season, 1980-81.
Boston acquired him with the third pick of the 1980 draft after the
Golden State Warriors took Joe Barry Carroll and the Utah Jazz
selected Darrell Griffith. The Celtics also got Robert Parish in a
trade the day before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first year, that's as much fun as I ever had playing
basketball,'' he said, mentioning teammates Tiny Archibald, Larry
Bird, M.L. Carr, and Chris Ford. ``Those guys were phenomenal. . .
. This is as much for my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, of course, made his professional name as the head
coach at Georgetown, but he backed up Russell for 74 games over two
seasons in the mid-1960s. Embry, an executive with the Cavaliers,
backed up Russell for the 1969 season, during which Johnny Most
gave him the nickname, ``Wayne the Wall.'' That makes 28 members of
the Hall of Fame with ties to the Celtics, although some (Pete
Maravich, Dave Bing) are fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   McHale was anything but. He spent his entire, 12-year career in
Boston, often played for less than the going wage because he
enjoyed it there, and was often lost in Bird's considerable shadow.
He said Wednesday that was never a problem with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the better basketball player,'' McHale said of Bird.
``Everyone knew Larry was the leader. I didn't think I was taking a
back seat to him. We were teammates. He did things to help me. I
did things to help him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
