<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7252 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZMAGS24-COX     06-23 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web still big news in mainline magazines
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Internet has spawned a host of specialized
business publications, but still, the Web continues to dominate the
covers of traditional magazines. The latest batch is a case in
point, with cover stories on ``Internet anxiety'' in Business Week
(June 28), ``a 300 year plan for the Internet'' in Forbes (July 5),
and ``I got my job online and soon you will too,'' in Fortune (July
5).
</P>
<P>
   Business Week explores the way traditional corporations are
responding to ``a radically new business model'' based on the
computer and finds that reactions are ``part envy, part fear and
part resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's like this: ``You're Merrill Lynch when Schwab.com comes
along. You're Barnes &AMP; Noble when Amazon.com hits big. You're Toys
``R'' Us when eToys shows up.''
</P>
<P>
   With these upstarts building huge war chests of capital in
record time, Business Week says old-line rivals ``are furiously
mapping out survival strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, venture capitalist Masayoshi Son, 41-year-old founder
and president of Softbank Corp., has not only created an Internet
empire, ``he's just getting started on what he calls a 300-year
business plan,'' says Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the long view characteristic of his culture, he told
Forbes the Internet will eventually expand its reach ``and Web
stocks will go only one direction _ up.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Forbes, Son's deal-making has carved out a bigger
chunk of the Internet economy than Bill Gates of Microsoft or Jerry
Yang of Yahoo!, having invested $1.7 billion in more than 100
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune looks at a more practical aspect of the Internet: job
seeking and headhunting by computer, a practice the magazine says
is already being used by the likes of Cisco, Marriott, Motorola and
Prudential.
</P>
<P>
   ``In January 1998, 17 percent of Fortune global 500 companies
were actively recruiting on the Net,'' Fortune says. ``Just a year
later, that figure was 45 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Spicing up your portfolio
</P>
<P>
   Most people invest in stocks via mutual funds, which spread the
risk and offer professional management. Two publications look at
the fund industry at midyear.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Funds (July) magazine discusses strategies and funds it
says ``could yield a 100 percent return on your investment in five
years or less.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the strategies are using sector funds, which invest in one
industry group, such as health care; focus funds, which limit
holdings to a small number of high-growth stocks; and chameleon
funds, which change strategy as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Individual Investor (July) says it's time to rethink some of the
old wisdom from the early days of the fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is told, for example, that past performance is no
guarantee of future results. But in the ``new math'' of fund
investing, ``past performance predicts a lot more than we ever
suspected,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
