<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7253 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-STATES-HNS &LR;      06-23 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-STATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT HIGH COURT ENHANCES STATES' RIGHTS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bitterly divided Supreme Court on Wednesday shut
the courthouse door on most people and companies seeking to recover
money from states they believe have violated their federally
protected rights.
</P>
<P>
   In three 5-4 decisions, the high court struck down federal laws
that give individuals and businesses the right to sue states for
money damages.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting sharply along ideological lines, the court said the
Constitution's 11th Amendment grants states ``sovereign immunity''
from facing such lawsuits in state and federal courts. The only
exception to this legal protection occurs in the limited number of
cases when states waive their right to immunity or are being sued
for denying an individual or a company ``equal protection'' or
``due process'' under the law, rights the 14th Amendment reserves
to individuals and businesses, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting justices assailed the majority for misreading the
Constitution and said the ruling will allow states to thwart
congressional efforts to protect people and businesses from
governmental abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Police Organizations, echoing the
dissenters, expressed concern that the decisions will allow states
to circumvent federal laws, such as those that protect the rights
of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the court's decisions Wednesday, the justices held
that Maine probation officers could not sue the state in federal or
local court to recover overtime pay guaranteed under the federal
Fair Labor Standards Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the Supreme Court is willing to sacrifice the officers'
rights on the altar of a glorified and exalted version of state's
rights,'' said Robert Scully, NAPO's executive director. ``The
ability of states to nullify federal laws by refusing to enforce
them, an issue prior to the Civil War and during desegregation in
the 1950s and 1960s, is once again at the forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia,
Anthony M. Kennedy, Sandra Day O'Connor and Clarence Thomas formed
the slim majority in the three cases. They said the protection of
states from lawsuits in federal and local courts is deeply rooted
in the American system of federalism, which calls for a central,
national government and 50 semi-autonomous state governments.
</P>
<P>
   But the court's liberal wing dissented, accusing the majority of
validating the outdated and constitutionally suspect doctrine of
sovereign immunity that was designed to protect kings, not states,
from being sued in their own courts.
</P>
<P>
   The majority's steadfast preservation of the immunity means that
many people and companies with valid federal claims for monetary
relief from states now have nowhere to turn, said dissenting
Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Stephen G. Breyer and
Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kennedy, writing for the majority in the Maine case,
said congressional efforts to allow citizens to hold states
accountable for violations of most federally protected rights are
unconstitutional and undermine the separation between federal
authority and state sovereignty that the Constitution's framers
carefully crafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Congress legislates in matters affecting the states, it
may not treat these sovereign entities as mere prefectures or
corporations,'' Kennedy wrote. ``Congress must accord states the
esteem due them as joint participants in a federal system, one
beginning with the premise of sovereignty in both the central
government and the separate states. Congress has ample means to
ensure compliance with valid federal laws, but it must respect the
sovereignty of the states.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, the Supreme Court blocked a bank's effort to
bring a federal false-advertising claim against a state-run board
in Florida that administers an advance college payment plan. In the
third case, the same bank, College Savings Bank, sued the Florida
board for patent infringement.
</P>
<P>
   College Savings Bank, which provides similar services on a
national basis, had argued in vain that Florida had waived its
sovereign immunity by abandoning its governing role and engaging in
the federally regulated business of collecting and dispensing funds
to college students.
</P>
<P>
   In the third case, College Savings also argued that the Florida
Prepaid Postsecondary Education Expense Board had violated the 14th
Amendment's due process clause by copying the bank's patented
CollegeSure CD, essentially an annuity contract for financing
college tuitions.
</P>
<P>
   But Scalia, writing for the majority in the false-advertising
case, said a state does not forfeit its constitutional right of
immunity when it chooses to engage in a business, even one heavily
regulated by the federal government. Rehnquist, in a separate
majority opinion, rejected the 14th Amendment claim, saying the
constitutional provision does not apply to patents.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenters Souter, Breyer and Stevens each took the
extraordinary step of reading significant portions of their
objections from the bench, a gesture the justices reserve for
themselves when they have deep philosophical disagreements with the
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Souter assailed the court for holding fast to an antiquated
legal safeguard that protects states from having to comply with
federal law. Referring to sovereign immunity, he added that ``it
would be hard to imagine anything more inimical to the republican
conception, which rests on the understanding of its citizens
precisely that the government is not above them, but of them, its
actions being governed by law just like their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer, dissenting in the false-advertising case, said a state
waives its sovereign immunity when it engages in a business, as
Florida did by essentially becoming a bank for future collegians.
Echoing Souter, Breyer called the sovereign-immunity doctrine
outdated and ``more akin to the thought of (British King) James I
than James Madison,'' a leading framer of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, dissenting in the patent-infringement case, assailed
the court's rigid adherence to sovereign immunity despite the harm
its enforcement can do to citizens' rights. ``Today, this court
once again demonstrates itself to be the champion of states'
rights,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In handing down the three decisions, the high court completed
the last public day of its 1998-1999 session. The court will meet
again in public Oct. 4, the first day of its 1999-2000 term.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
