u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHECKFREE24-COX     06-23 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECKFREE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rivals' move hurts CheckFree shares
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three major banks said Wednesday they were forming a
company that will compete with CheckFree by electronically
delivering bills to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   The news that Chase Manhattan, First Union and Wells Fargo would
form a company called the Exchange, and that the banks planned to
start presenting electronic bills to consumers by fall, gouged 23.7
percent out of CheckFree's stock price. Shares of the Atlanta-area
based electronic payment processor closed at $28.75, down $8.93
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   More than 16 million shares were traded, better than 20 times
its daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan, First Union and Wells Fargo are all CheckFree
customers, representing 20 percent of its revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, CheckFree and existing shareholders, including Chairman
and Chief Executive Pete Kight, sold 3.8 million shares at $39.
Kight's 658,122 shares brought $25.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Wednesday, Kight said the timing was
coincidental. Kight said the Exchange is not a threat to CheckFree
and might help it. He said the banks' interest in electronic
billing will increase attention on the industry, which ultimately
will benefit CheckFree.
</P>
<P>
   ``No informed person should view this announcement as anything
other than the emergence of yet one more group trying to find a
meaningful role in what everyone regards as a very attractive
market,'' Kight said in a statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bolen, an analyst with J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co., is recommending
investors buy shares of CheckFree. Bolen said he does not think
investors overreacted. He said the Exchange will do nothing more
than present bills, which would only cut into part of CheckFree's
business.
</P>
<P>
   But for the online bill-paying and bill-presenting industry, a
kind of race has begun. Few question that more and more people will
get and pay bills online. The question is where _ at a high-traffic
Web portal or at a bank Web site?
</P>
<P>
   Banks were slow to adopt and market the service, which pushed
CheckFree to try to strike distribution deals with Internet
portals. CheckFree announced a deal with one Internet portal,
reported to be Yahoo!. The feature is expected to be available by
fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Gartner Group research shows people who pay bills online
prefer do it at their bank's Web site instead of a portal, by a
factor of 8 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Avivah Litan, an analyst with Gartner Group, said the Exchange
deal is a big deal to investors because it means CheckFree has more
competition. Litan said she thinks the banks will eventually add
bill-paying functions to the bill-presenting feature they plan to
offer in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``signals that more banks will get going and build
their own service,'' she said. ``But can the banks execute quicker
than CheckFree and the portals? Our research shows that consumers
prefer banks over portals. The question is will the lead (time)
mean a lot in terms of consumer share?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
