A7257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKE24-COX     06-23 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyers face off in tobacco class-action case
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Maybe it's because they've been dueling every day in
court for nine months, or because there are billions of dollars at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, tempers flared Wednesday as the first
phase of a landmark class action lawsuit against the tobacco
industry drew to a close, with opposing lawyers shouting each other
down before they were halted by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of emotion and a little bit of that came
out,'' Miami-Dade County Circuit Court Judge Robert Kaye told
jurors, whom he had ordered out of the courtroom while tempers
cooled. ``Please disregard that.''
</P>
<P>
   The dust-up came between Stanley Rosenblatt, who brought the
first-ever class action lawsuit against the industry, and Philip
Morris attorney Robert Heim.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing remarks, Heim tried to argue that the case boils
down to the choices made by individuals to smoke despite the known
health risks.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt flew to his feet to object, saying Heim was violating
a ruling by Judge Kaye that the issue of smokers' choices should
not be considered during the trial's first phase.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye agreed, and appeared to gently scold and calm the lawyers
during a lengthy sidebar conference.
</P>
<P>
   But venom between the two sides still crept into the lawyers'
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   In two days of closing arguments, Rosenblatt repeatedly
portrayed cigarette companies as deceitful, scheming, profit-hungry
giants who ignored and even tried to cover up the dangers of their
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``These shameless purveyors of an unhealthy product have done
everything they could to hook people,'' Rosenblatt argued, citing
internal industry memos that discussed ways to increase market
share among smokers called ``young adults.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They called them young adults but those were code words for
teen-agers,'' Rosenblatt said. ``That's where the money is and they
know that better than anybody. If you hook a 14-year-old, look at
all the years he'll be smoking. By the time he gets to be 60, at
two packs a day, that's profit, pure profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt accused the companies of ignoring the health risks of
smoking and keeping vital research from the public, all the while
manipulating nicotine levels to make their product even more
addictive. His complaint charges them with fraud and conspiracy, as
well as negligence in making a defective, dangerous product.
</P>
<P>
   The six jurors have sat in the ornate but dilapidated downtown
Miami courtroom since October. Also watching from the gallery at
times have been stock market analysts, who know an adverse verdict
could cripple the already-battered industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the most dedicated spectators have been a dozen or so sick
smokers, some of whom bear surgical scars and can talk only with
the aide of buzzing, hand-held amplifiers.
</P>
<P>
   They will appear before jurors if Rosenblatt wins the trial's
first round.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding has been divided into three phases. In the first
part, now ending, jurors will be asked to decide whether the
tobacco industry is responsible for the smokers' illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   If so, a second phase will begin with individual representatives
of the class presenting their cases, and jurors asked to rule on
how much in damages they should receive.
</P>
<P>
   The trial's third phase would involve damages for the entire
class, both compensatory and punitive.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple setbacks in jury trials in the past few years,
tobacco companies have recently won several cases, with juries
generally agreeing with their long-held argument that the dangers
of smoking have been widely known for decades and that smokers are
responsible for choosing the habit.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry has also agreed to pay hundreds of billions of
dollars over the coming decades to settle lawsuits with dozens of
state governments that wanted reimbursement for treating sick
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt's class-action suit has the potential for adding more
billions _ some observers estimate up to $200 billion _ to the
industry's bill.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's blue-chip team of lawyers has focused its defense
on the issue of public awareness and claims that some 50 million
smokers have successfully quit the habit. In his closing arguments,
Heim showed jurors a giant chart labeled ``Mountain of Awareness,''
which he said was a huge obstacle to accepting the plaintiffs'
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 33 years there have been warnings on cigarette packages,''
he said. ``If somebody started smoking a pack a day in 1966, they
would've had the opportunity to see those warnings 200,000 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Heim also downplayed the significance of numerous industry
documents, introduced by Rosenblatt, which the plaintiffs said
showed the industry's conspiracy and deceit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were millions and millions of documents over the course
of 50 years,'' Heim said. ``It's not fair to take documents out of
context. If you read only the negative articles in the newspaper
about (Miami Dolphins quarterback) Dan Marino, you might think he
was a terrible quarterback. But you've got to read all of the
articles.''
</P>
<P>
   Heim also labeled as ``vicious'' Rosenblatt's assertion that the
industry targeted teens, hoping to hook them for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a reprehensible charge and it hasn't been proven in
this courtroom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry lawyers were expected to complete their closing
arguments today, with the case going to the jury Friday after a
short rebuttal argument by Rosenblatt.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the jury room, the six-person panel will have thousands
of documents to consider, along with a 40,000-page trial
transcript.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
