<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-HEALTH24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Healtheon, WebMD continue Net deals
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Still a couple months shy of their high-stakes merger,
Healtheon Corp. and WebMD Inc. continue to forge deals aimed at
boosting visibility _ one is with an Internet star, the other with
an icon of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon announced Wednesday that its name and information, as
well as links to its own site, will be carried on Yahoo!, the Net's
leading search service. Atlanta-based WebMD, which is slated to
merge with Healtheon in September, has similar deals with CNN's Web
site, Excite and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an agreement with WebMD was announced by Reader's
Digest, which made its name decades ago as a publisher of magazines
and shortened books aimed at Middle America. Reader's Digest has
invested $13 million in WebMD and will have its own site advertised
on the sites of WebMD's investors. The announcements gave Healtheon
stock a healthy bump, apparently on the notion that the company has
taken another step toward leadership of the potentially lucrative
health care sector of the Net.
</P>
<P>
   However, visibility apparently comes at a price. Although
Healtheon and Yahoo! did not release financial details, the
agreement calls for Healtheon to sponsor several features on
Yahoo!, including a poll offered to visitors and a health-chat
area. That implies that Healtheon is paying Yahoo! for the right to
appear on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon's arrangement does not yet represent the largest
health care presence on Yahoo!. Atlanta-based Adam.com supplies
about 10,000 pages of health care information to Yahoo! on all
manner of diseases and conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Adam and Yahoo! have also not released details of the
arrangement except to say that Adam does not pay for its presence.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangements reflect the growing power of Yahoo in serving
``communities of interest'' on the Net, said Ford Cavallari,
executive vice president for the Internet practice of the
Renaissance Group, Boston-based consultants. ``They have so much
power they can get people to pay them.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD's founder, Jeffrey Arnold, has been named the most
effective start-up chief executive by the editors of The Standard,
a printed and Internet magazine that covers the Net economy.
</P>
<P>
   Among other awardees were Alan Greenspan as most influential
thinker and Bill Gates of Microsoft as most influential investor.
Microsoft is investing $250 million in the Healtheon-WebMD merger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
