<HEADLINE>
RAGE OF ANOTHER HEMINGWAY FREE-LANCER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Ernest Hemingway &LR; 's granddaughter  &UR; Lorian &LR;  vents her anger in
the July issue of GQ about the publication of Hemingway's fictional
memoir, ``True at First Light.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The words are his,'' she writes of the forthcoming Scribner's
book, which she says was not ready for publication, ``but they fall
hollow and are without the grace and purpose and ultimate
redemption that might have been brought to this rambling, flawed
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   In an excerpt quoted in the New York Post, Hemingway accuses her
father,  &UR; Gregory &LR; , and his two brothers,  &UR; Jack &LR;  and  &UR; Patrick &LR; , of
being mercenary. The three ``are delighted to roll out a magic
carpet of a manuscript every decade or so just to remain on the
high end of solvency.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers and publisher are ``simply in the business of
peddling Hemingway as if he were a QVC home-shopping network
item.'' She says they are ``confusing legacy with the benefits of
early retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANOTHER CONCERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to BBC Music magazine, a South African reader
comments on the death of violinist-conductor  &UR; Yehudi Menuhin &LR; . In
Port Elizabeth, the writer's hometown, ``we recall his visits in
the time of high apartheid. The day after his formal concert in the
white civic center, he insisted on giving one in the black ghetto,
refusing a fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers brought their babies, old and young sat spellbound and
a garland was placed over his shoulders. Thanking his audience for
the musical traditions of Africa and India, he told them, `My
playing for you is an exchange and not a gift.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD WISHES TO KING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stephen King &LR; , recuperating from being hit by a car at the
Central Maine Medical Center, has been showered with get-well
wishes and gifts, reports the Lewiston (Maine) Sun Journal, in a
story forwarded by  &UR; Alice Barnes &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Among the care packages was one from the nearby Lewiston Public
Library, which had been the beneficiary of a gift from the Stephen
and  &UR; Tabitha King &LR;  Foundation. The library sent three or four books
about baseball (because the title of his last book, ``The Girl Who
Loved Tom Gordon,'' was in homage to the Boston Red Sox pitcher),
Homer's ``Odyssey'' (which King had publicly praised) and a
collection of  &UR; Dylan Thomas &LR;  poems that included the ``do not go
gentle'' warning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Hillary Clinton &LR;  is to be on the first cover of  &UR; Tina &LR; 
 &UR; Brown &LR; 's Talk magazine, but the speculation is about what's going
to be inside this much-hyped publication. Among the stories
assigned, says New York magazine, is ``Civilians Who've Slept With
Celebrities'' and a piece by  &UR; Al Pacino &LR; 's ex-girlfriend on having
a baby. ``Could give Cosmo a run for its money,'' says New York,
which may be jealous of a newsstand rival.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 1956 wedding album inscribed by  &UR; Princess Grace &LR;  of Monaco
to her sister,  &UR; Peggy &LR; , sold at a Sotheby's auction for $4,887,
reports Art &AMP; Auction magazine, which asks, ``How do these things
end up in public sales?''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Juliet Schor &LR; , author of ``The Overspent American,'' points
out that she'd described the assertion quoted here last week, that
Americans are ``overly entitled and spoiled,'' as an example of the
thinking of a ``conservative jeremiad,'' and it's not her thinking
at all. While she does believe that Americans spend too much, she
thinks it's a result of profound social dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Game show host  &UR; Bob Barker &LR;  will travel to Washington on July
14 to show legislators a movie on elephant abuse in India, reports
Roll Call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MILLENNIUM RENTAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The duke and duchess who live in Alnwick Castle in
Northumberland, England, are advertising the opportunity to rent
their 1,000-year-old place for the holiday, four days for $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   An ad in Architectural Digest tastefully omits mention of the
couple's name but does say that the duke and duchess are restoring
an 18th century walled garden on their property (which probably
means they won't want to be bothered bringing you more towels).
</P>
<P>
   Guests may use the castle's 12 bedrooms, five reception rooms,
dining room, music room and two-story library ``filled with antique
books and fine art.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is so sensual. There's something magic about these
people's hands and the way that they caress a knife or handle a
naked potato.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Heidi Diamond &LR;  of the TV Food Network, telling the New York
Times why chefs are perceived as hunks.
</P>
