 Wednesday, June 23, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston
Chronicle sports stories, please call 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: SERIAL-KILLER; HINDU-PRIEST-SEX; and
AIR-FORCE-PERSONNEL.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Senators studying proposals to
extend Medicare to cover prescription drugs struggle to find a way
to pay for the proposal. Although Medicare is projected to go
bankrupt in 2015 because the number of people receiving Medicare
benefits will rise sharply, the Clinton administration and
lawmakers of both political parties are pushing to expand the
program to cover prescription drugs. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-STATES-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court severely
limits the ability of people to sue states under federal law, and
in the process it substantially redraws the border between state
sovereignty and federal authority. In a 5-4 decision, the justices
dismiss a lawsuit by a group of state employees in Maine who sought
to enforce a federal labor law and collect overtime pay. By MARK
HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO (Washington) _ A New Jersey man whose wife was
brutally slain in Sarasota, Fla., urges Congress to pressure the
Mexican government to extradite one of the suspects accused in the
crime. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER (Undated) _ Police in Lexington, Ky., say there
have been ``confirmed sightings'' of Rafael Resendez-Ramirez at
homeless shelters and soup kitchens in Louisville over the past
several days. The Louisville police also said the suspected serial
killer has relatives in the area. Resendez-Ramirez, who is on the
FBI's Most Wanted List, is wanted in the slayings of several people
in Illinois, Kentucky and Texas. By LISA TEACHEY and S.K. BARDWELL.
</P>
<P>
   HINDU-PRIEST-SEX (Houston) _ A Texas jury gives a Hindu priest
convicted of sexually assaulting a 21-year-old Arkansas woman 10
years probation. The judge also adds stiff probation rules,
including 180 days in jail and banning Bhogeshwernand Sharma, 37,
from practicing as a priest. But that doesn't mean Sharma's
problems are over. Prosecutors charged him with a new sexual
assault as he was being led out of the courtroom. By STEVE BREWER.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Armed with a new state law,
Texas Lottery officials announce they have begun increasing the
prize payout for scratch-off games in an effort to win back
players. Texas also is negotiating with several other states on
possible participation in a multistate mega-jackpot lottery that
would be a first for Texas. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE-PERSONNEL (San Antonio) _ The Air Force says it has
partially lifted orders that had prevented thousands of officers
and enlistees from retiring or leaving the service during the
Yugoslav bombing campaign. The rarely used provision kept key
personnel in uniform past their separation and retirement dates. By
SIG CHRISTENSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA (New York) _ The New York Knicks try to even the NBA
Finals at two games apiece tonight in Game 4 with the San Antonio
Spurs at Madison Square Garden. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (St. Louis) _ The Houston Astros, fresh from a
marathon game Tuesday in which they lost 4-3 in 14 innings, face
the St. Louis Cardinals again today. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Since both Republican George W.
Bush and Democrat Al Gore are expressing centrist positions, the
manner in which they present themselves is as important as the
messages they convey. In their first official sorties, Bush has
emerged the winner. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
