A7272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-23 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINES KILL ATTACKER IN KOSOVO FIREFIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ For the second time in as many days, US
Marines exchanged gunfire with armed attackers inside Kosovo,
killing one man and injuring at least two others after a lengthy
standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials were unsure Wednesday night whether the
gunmen, dressed in civilian clothes, were Albanians or Serbs. But a
Pentagon spokesman said the assailants were clearly to blame for
the exchange, opening fire on the Marines near the farming town of
Zegra. No US soldiers were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was the second such incident involving US troops
dispatched to keep the peace in Kosovo, and came as military
officials from the five NATO countries guarding the province
struggled to calm tensions between ethnic Albanians flooding back
into their towns and the few Serb civilians who still remained.
</P>
<P>
   In villages across Kosovo, houses were seen burning Wednesday,
the result of naked vengeance on the part of ethnic Albanians,
officials said. The sharp increase in retaliatory attacks coincided
with a flood of new refugees returning home, as well as with the
further discovery of what were believed to be mass grave sites,
including one in northern Kosovo that contained as many as 180
dead.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials pleaded with aggressors on both sides for peace.
But even British Foreign Minister Robin Cook was moved to demand
further action against Yugoslav leaders after a firsthand glimpse
of the devastation. During a visit Wednesday to the town of Velika
Krusa, one of the seven crime scenes cited in the war crimes
indictment of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and the site
where 105 men and boys were believed killed, Cook said he felt
``rising indignation against the people who had ordered these
atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had any doubts about the justice of the campaign we were
waging to liberate Kosovo from this terror, they have been
banished,'' Cook said after visiting the town, where human remains
lay scattered, and where a courtyard was filled with body bags.
Cook said he felt ``increasing distress and pity for these people
who were herded into two rooms and shot through the windows and
through the doors. They must have known they were going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the amassing of physical remains, a group of
independent analysts Wednesday assessed the economic damage of the
11-week NATO bombing campaign, putting the cost of rebuilding
Yugoslavia alone at more than $29 billion. However, the price of
reconstructing Kosovo was not included in the analysis performed by
economists from the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
_ and it was far lower than the $100 billion reconstruction
estimate made by Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Western officials remained insistent that no aid to
Yugoslavia would come while Milosevic retained power. Although
European nations are widely expected to help rebuild Kosovo _ a
cost that the European Commission said Wednesday would be roughly
$1.03 billion a year for three years _ the European Union's
External Relations Commissioner said Wednesday it was ``out of the
question'' that Serbia would get its share under the current
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Cook repeated his pledge to have Milosevic brought to trial,
saying: ``We are not going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops, meanwhile, were preparing to join the NATO
peacekeeping force, and could arrive in Kosovo as soon as Friday,
assuming a parliamentary vote approves the mission. Their
deployment comes after an initial squabble between Russian and NATO
leaders over what role Russia would play, and whether Russian
soldiers would be required to report to NATO leaders.
</P>
<P>
   That earlier dispute was solved last week. But questions over
Russian involvement took a new twist Wednesday, as US officials
admitted they believed Russian mercenaries had been involved in the
Serb army itself, fighting against the Kosovo Liberation Army
during the 78-day war.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon, describing the Russians as
``soldiers of fortune,'' said the information was based on reports
from members of the KLA. He also said they were ``not in any
official capacity and did not represent the Russian government in
any way.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Bacon said, the Pentagon had reason to believe there was
``a relatively small number of Russians there operating on their
own as volunteers, possibly as mercenaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could almost describe them as soldiers of fortune
and in our world today such individuals are frequently found in
areas of conflict around the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians, meanwhile, poured into the region again
Wednesday, alarming aid workers and draining food and water
supplies. Rupert Colville, a spokesman for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees said as many as 207,000 refugees had
streamed back inside Kosovo in the last eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a phenomenal rate _ absolutely staggering,'' Colville
said.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived in towns looted and black with soot, their homes in
many cases burned to the ground or emptied of all possessions. In
turn, many openly sacked the homes of Serb neighbors who had fled _
or Serbs themselves _ causing near panic among NATO soldiers and
underscoring what many believe is the need for more peacekeeping
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, US soldiers engaged in a gun battle with a group
of four men they found firing shots into the air in a small town in
central Kosovo, according to Brigadier General John Craddock, the
commander of Task Force Falcon. No one was killed. Three of the men
were arrested. Two of them were wearing uniform shirts, but could
not be identified as Albanians or Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in the incident in Zegra, US Marines were called to a
report of a disturbance in a home at approximately 5:30 p.m.
Several men carrying AK-47 machine guns began firing on them,
Pentagon officials said. The Marines fired back, killing one,
injuring at least two, and taking one into custody. The injured
attackers were flown by helicopter to a military hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell you that in the last 48 hours, for the first
time, we have become the target of violent acts,'' Craddock said,
speaking from Prizren in a conference call with reporters at the
Pentagon. ``Again, no US forces injured or hurt at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   US Major Trey Cate, a spokesman for the multinational Kosovo
Force (KFOR), said early Thursday that officials did not know
whether the attackers were Serbs or Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was Serbs or Albanians, we would respond
even-handedly in any case,'' he said. He also added that the
violent outburst ``underscores the danger of the mission. But it
also shows that the KFOR forces will do everything under the robust
rules of engagement to preserve a safe environment, and that is
exactly what these Marines did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Sennott reported from Pristina; Kornblut from Washington. Globe
correspondent Kurt Pitzer also contributed to this report from
Kosovo.)
</P>
</TEXT>
