<SLUG> BC-R-NICKELODEON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKELODEON CELEBRATES 20 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to correct spelling of slug and hed)  (jt) 
 By JAY HANDELMAN    
 c. Sarasota Herald-Tribune    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like its young viewers, Nickelodeon has been growing up before
our eyes, though it's hard to believe the cable network that
changed the face of children's programming is ready to celebrate
its 20th birthday this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the story of the youth-oriented cable network that
slimed its way to popularity. Sliming, for those unfamiliar with
the world of Nickelodeon, is the dumping or throwing of a
lime-green goopy glop on contestants on ``You Can't Do That on
Television.'' Their offense? Uttering the words, ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon actually started April 1, 1979, with a magazine-type
series for pre-schoolers called ``Pinwheel.'' It could be seen only
by cable customers in Buffalo, N.Y., and Columbus, Ohio. Now, 20
years later, the network is available in 75 million homes, and a
lot of them must be tuning in at least at some point each day. It
has been the No. 1-rated cable network for three straight years.
</P>
<P>
   It has achieved that success partially by smartly targeting
different audiences at different times of the day. Midday is
marketed for the youngest viewers and is dubbed Nick Jr., while
late afternoon is for slightly older kids after they get home from
school. Early evenings are earmarked for the family, with shows
like ``Kenan &AMP; Kel,'' ``Doug'' and ``Rugrats,'' the network's most
popular series.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the anniversary, Nickelodeon will show favorite episodes
and series that have aired since its birth. The look back airs from
6 a.m. to 10 p.m. Saturday and 1 to 4 p.m. Sunday. Saturday's
offerings will include five hours of first episodes of every
original Nick animated series, a collection of game shows, specials
and live action series. Special episodes featuring celebrities
before they were stars will be shown Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Nickelodeon's growth came after it became part of the
MTV Networks (MTV and VH1) in 1984, and got the kind of financial
support it needed for program expansion and all-important
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Nickelodeon reached an entirely different audience
by turning over its prime-time and overnight schedule to reruns of
old prime-time hits, like ``Donna Reed'' and ``Dennis the Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who doesn't believe in the power of marketing only has to
look at Nick at Nite. This was a lineup of reruns that had long ago
lost their novelty. But packaged as event programming that helped
us recapture our still longed-for past, Nick at Nite quickly
grabbed attention. It also spawned the creation of the spinoff
network, ``TV Land,'' on which viewers can see classic TV shows 24
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon has had a simple philosophy nearly since the
beginning, when network officials credit interviews with young
viewers for setting them straight. In focus groups, the kids told
network executives that they just wanted to be kids because they
were scared about growing up.
</P>
<P>
   So, in 1985, according to the network's printed history, ``Nick
was re-launched with a new identity, focused on giving kids what
they wanted, not what grown-ups thought was good for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Herb Scannell, president of the various Nickelodeon franchises,
said the original network has led to many changes in kids' TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We debunked a lot of the myths of kids' television _ that boys
wouldn't watch shows starring girls, that you couldn't make scary
shows without delving into a lot of violence _ and we did it in a
consistent manner by knowing our audience and putting kids first,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Family Channel is taking a different approach to
reaching the young audience. In October, it is launching two new
gender-specific channels, boyzChannel and girlzChannel.
</P>
<P>
   Though the networks are still months away, there was much
criticism in education circles when they were announced because of
concern that the two channels will play to stereotypes of trucks
and guns for boys and dolls for girls.
</P>
<P>
   Nick's original programming philosophy might not have set well
with the crowd that had long supported the more education-oriented
programming on PBS, but the channel has served its own teaching
function. Its programs are certainly better than most of the
toy-inspired junk that passes for after-school syndicated
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon has the most popular kids' programs on the air, led
by ``Rugrats,'' which began in 1994 and has grown so popular that
it inspired a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   The network also has perhaps one of the best kids' shows on any
television network _ ``Nick News,'' in which host Linda Ellerbee
treats young viewers with intelligence in reporting the news from
around the world. Ellerbee has just the right touch in treating
kids as if they're smarter than most other broadcasters give them
credit for.
</P>
<P>
   While the broadcast networks (NBC, CBS, ABC) once ruled Saturday
morning television with kids' shows, Nickelodeon has bumped them
aside. Each of the big three has tried different approaches, with
NBC turning over time for ``Saturday Today'' and going after an
older teen-age audience with its ``Teen NBC'' lineup of such shows
as ``Saved by the Bell'' and ``Hang Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon also has been good for Florida and jobs. More than
1,800 episodes of its programs have been taped or filmed at the
Nickelodeon Studios based at Universal Studios Florida.
</P>
<P>
   And Nick is the home to ``Blue's Clues,'' the prize of Nick Jr.
In this season, preschool viewers are asked to help Steve solve
puzzles presented by his puppy, Blue. Forget all those scary and
sad rumors you may have heard. Actor Steven Burns is very much
alive, just like Nickelodeon itself.
</P>
<P>
   Happy 20th birthday!'
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Handelman is the television critic for the Herald-Tribune
in Sarasota, Fla., which is a member of The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group. This article was distributed by The New York Times
News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
