<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MARINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINES AND SERBS EXCHANGE FIRE IN SOUTHEASTERN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZEGRA, Yugoslavia _ Local Serbs in civilian clothes opened fired
Wednesday night on a checkpoint manned by U.S. Marines here,
provoking a firefight that killed one Serb and wounded two others,
one severely, American officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth Serb was arrested after the Marines, backed by armored
vehicles and helicopter gunships, ended an hour-long standoff by
storming a house where the Serbs had retreated, the commander of
the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit, Col. Kenneth Glueck, said. No
Marines were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The firefight erupted just after 6 p.m. in this village in
southeastern Kosovo that has been roiled by tensions between Serbs
and Albanians. The gunfire underscored the ongoing volatility of
NATO's operation in Kosovo, 12 days after the first peacekeepers
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time American troops came under direct fire.
On Monday night, soldiers from the 82d Airborne Division were fired
on near the city of Urosevac, though they did not return fire and
no one was injured. Three people were detained in that incident.
</P>
<P>
   Zegra is a small, remote village south of Gnjilane, where,
unlike other cities and villages, many Serbs have remained after
the withdrawal of Yugoslavia's Serb-dominated army and police
units. Marines have manned checkpoints there for more than a week.
Last Thursday they disarmed a company of fighters from the Kosovo
Liberation Army in the village, seizing scores of weapons and
arresting six KLA leaders after they paraded through in a show of
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of a hot spot between the two factions,''
Glueck said at the Marines' headquarters on a hilltop near the
village of Cernica.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the streets were dark and deserted, but
gunshots could still be heard in the distance. ``They're firing
like crazy tonight,'' one Marine said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why the Serbs opened fire on the checkpoint,
which was on the main road through Zegra. There were some two dozen
Marines in the area, near a schoolhouse they have turned into a
field headquarters, but there had been no apparent signs of new
tensions. A firefight raged for several minutes, until the Serbs,
already wounded, fell back into a house not far from the road.
</P>
<P>
   When reinforcements arrived, including the armored fighting
vehicles, the Marines surrounded the house, while Cobra helicopters
hovered overhead. Serbian translators, using megaphones, tried to
defuse the situation by telling those inside to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave them an opportunity to surrender,'' Glueck said.
After nearly an hour, the Marines stormed the building. The two
wounded Serbs were taken by helicopter to the Army's field hospital
near Urosevac, some 15 miles away. Colonel Glueck said he believed
that one or two more Serbs had escaped. ``They faded into the
crowd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Yugoslavia's army and special police have withdrawn
from Kosovo, NATO has been trying to impose order on the province.
On Tuesday, NATO's senior commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, said that
the allies needed to move more quickly to build up their forces.
NATO now has 20,000 troops, but officials said it could take until
late July before the entire contingent of more than 50,000 arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the American sector, Brig. Gen. John Craddock,
said Wednesday that the United States now had 4,500 of its
contribution of 7,000 troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops have by and large been welcomed by Kosovo's Albanian
majority, but their biggest challenge has been defusing
confrontations between Serbs and the Albanians who are returning
home in droves after fleeing President Slobodan Milosevic's
crackdown this spring. Rarely have NATO troops faced direct
military challenges to their authority, but military commanders
here say there is little they can do to disarm the entire country,
making incidents like the one Wednesday a lingering threat.
</P>
<P>
   Glueck said military police would investigate the incident, but
he ruled out aggressive action to root out weapons in Zegra or
elsewhere. ``If we know where the guns are, we'll go after them,''
he said, ``but we're not going to go house to house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
