<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECH24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free speech out of reach, Moyers fears
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bill Moyers, frequently dubbed the Conscience of
TV News, is worried.
</P>
<P>
   He worries about a lot of things _ racism, violence, corruption,
drugs, moral values. But lately he's been pondering the sorry state
of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been chewing over this for a long time,'' Moyers said in
his soft Texas twang during a phone interview from New York. ``I've
been following this story of money and politics and the changing
character of the media for years, and I've been concerned about
what's happening to our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   What's happening, Moyers concludes in his PBS special ``Free
Speech For Sale,'' is that free speech is guaranteed only to those
who can afford it. Often that means wealthy corporations, which
saturate the media with political advertising or buy companies that
cover the news, effectively smothering other voices.
</P>
<P>
   As he says in the introduction, the First Amendment was intended
to guarantee that ordinary citizens could ``get our two cents'
worth into the public debate, but what the framers of our
government didn't reckon with is that two cents doesn't buy much
these days. You can say what you want, but if you really want to be
heard, we're talking big money.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyers' program cites three cases that should cause concern.
</P>
<P>
   First up is a state legislator in North Carolina, a feisty woman
who sought to force the powerful hog industry into dealing with
waste-disposal problems. A consortium of hog industry leaders,
calling themselves Farmers for Fairness, waged a massive
advertising campaign against Republican Cindy Watson. She had no
money to buy ads to counter the group's negative charges, and she
was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised that people assumed the best about this
group in North Carolina,'' Moyers said. ``Apparently nobody had any
insight into what we call a `front group.' I would have thought
somebody would have exposed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up is the $40 million ad campaign waged by the tobacco
industry to defeat the McCain Tobacco Bill. Although the popular
bill, sponsored by Sen. John McCain, (R-Ariz.), seemed a shoo-in
when it left committee, it died in the Senate after a media blitz
shifted the debate from health issues to big government and big
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Moyers takes on the Telecommunications Act of 1996,
which received bipartisan support and was championed as positive
for the public because it included regulations about labeling
offensive program content on television and adding more educational
shows for children.
</P>
<P>
   What the act also did, however, was give $70 billion worth of
new channel space, owned by the public, to the broadcast networks
as part of the transition to all-digital broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no public debate because the media did not want to
discuss what it was doing,'' says Charles Lewis, director of the
Center for Public Integrity, in the program. ``They're all going to
make billions of dollars over the next several years, and the last
thing they want to do is have a discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The three network newscasts paid scant attention to the
Telecommunications Act and even less coverage of the channel space
giveaway, according to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Moyers says he wasn't surprised that TV news kept the story
under its corporate hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's intrinsic in human nature to serve your own interests,''
he said. ``That's a real danger. ABC probably wouldn't do a story
on the effect of merchandizing Disney movies either.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, of course, is owned by Disney. NBC is owned by General
Electric, and CBS has an interest in several other media outlets.
It's this concentration of media ownership that makes truly
objective network news coverage all the more difficult, Moyers
says.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his 25 years in journalism, Moyers has worried about
the effect of money and the media on politics. His latest
investigation did nothing to ease his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's alarming and disturbing that my grandchildren may
grow up in a society where their political worth is determined by
their net worth,'' he said. ``Money has always been a force but now
it's the force. It's the combination of direct advertising and a
media that's devoted to the bottom line that squeezes out
information people need as citizens. The marketplace of ideas
continues to shrink.''
</P>
<P>
   What can we do about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Think critically and analytically,'' Moyers said. ``If you see
a show, ask who's doing it and what are they trying to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
