<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS END MIXED AFTER LATE BUYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks ended mixed Wednesday after some late buying
lifted the main gauges from their daily lows while long-term
interest rates continued to climb.
</P>
<P>
   With Federal Reserve policy-makers expected to decide next
Wednesday to raise the rate on overnight loans between banks by
one-quarter point, investors and traders debated the growing
possibility that one such increase might not be enough to head off
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weight on equities,'' said John Manley, equity
strategist at Salomon Smith Barney, referring to competition from
bonds for investors' cash. ``We actually think there may be three
increases before it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks bore much of the brunt of the uncertainty over
rates in a week with little other economic news and with companies
not due to report second-quarter profits until next month.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, down 4 3/8, to 130 5/8, and American Express, down
2 1/8, to 122 5/8, were the two biggest factors in the 54.77-point
loss suffered by the Dow Jones industrial average, which finished
at 10,666.86, down five-tenths of a percent. At midday, the Dow's
slump was nearly 105 points. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
fell 2.82 points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 1,333.06.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the NASDAQ composite index pushed into
positive territory, finishing with a gain of 17.86 points, or
seven-tenths of a percent, to 2,598.12.
</P>
<P>
   This reflected strength in high-technology issues, which have
regained some investor favor despite the runup in interest rates.
Cisco climbed 2 3/8, to 61 7/8, and Altera rose 4 5/8, to 40 5/16,
after an analyst raised the semiconductor company's target price.
Beyond.com jumped 7 1/4, to 32 7/8, on speculation that it will be
bought by Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   3Com warned of lower revenue in coming quarters and slumped 4
3/8, to 27 1/8, apparently benefiting the shares of larger rival
Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   With little else besides the uncertainty over the Fed's action
and corporate profit warnings to focus on, analysts said it was not
surprising that markets tended to be defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of an upside surprise are low relative to the
chances of a bigger correction,'' said Al Kugel, senior investment
strategist at Stein Roe &AMP; &AMP; Farnham in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Another company warning of lower profits was Crown Cork &AMP; Seal,
which cited weak European economies in lowering expectations for
the second time in nine months. The stock skidded 3 1/2, to 28
15/16. Goldman Sachs reported earnings that far surpassed
expectations, but the stock fell 3, to 65, in a mixed brokerage
group.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks advanced with crude prices after inventories fell
unexpectedly. Chevron, recommended by Banc of America Securities,
climbed 2 1/2, to 92 5/8, while Mobil and Exxon gained 1 1/2 and 1
1/8, respectively. Drug issues were mostly lower.
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan Materials, one of three stocks to be added to the S&AMP;P
500, jumped 4 1/4, to 46 15/16. Network Appliance rose 3 1/2, to 48
5/16, and Best Buy was up 2 9/16, to 63 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume grew to a still-moderate
731.8 million shares, with declining issues surpassing advancing
ones by 1,760 to 1,259. New Lows outnumbered new 52-week highs by
67 to 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
