<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ARMY-ART-NYT &LR;      06-23 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ARMY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHIEF OF STAFF WANTS MORE AGILITY AND POWER FOR U.S. ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army's new chief of staff on Wednesday vowed to
redouble the Army's efforts to become a more agile yet powerful
force, acknowledging that the service was ill-prepared to move 24
Apache helicopter gunships and artillery into Albania in the early
stages of the Balkans air war.
</P>
<P>
   On his second day as the Army's 34th chief of staff, Gen. Eric
Shinseki said the Army was organized and equipped to have an
armored brigade of soldiers and tanks battle-ready in 96 hours in a
potential hot spot like Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   But a place like Tirana, Albania, with poor rail connections, a
shallow port and a limited airfield, proved a logistical nightmare
for Army commanders, who jockeyed to bring in military equipment
alongside relief supplies bound for refugees pouring out of nearby
Kosovo. Even after their long-delayed and costly arrival, the
Apaches never flew a combat mission in the 78-day air war.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki, speaking to reporters at the Pentagon, said he had
ordered the outlines of a plan be drawn up within six months to
make the Army's heavy forces more mobile and its lighter forces
more lethal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're asked to go to a place like Tirana, we accept a
certain amount of challenge with that,'' said Shinseki. ``But we're
looking at using that as a case study to say, OK, how would we do
that better in the next Tirana or in the next Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenges of operating in the Balkans are no surprise to
Shinseki, who served two years as the top Army general in Europe
and commander of NATO peacekeeping forces in Bosnia before he
became vice chief of staff last November.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his experience with Russian peacekeepers in Bosnia,
Shinseki played down the latest dispute over Moscow's decision to
send 200 Russian soldiers into Pristina ahead of the NATO vanguard,
and said Russian forces in Kosovo would work well with NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience in Bosnia was that when given the proper
directions, they complied with them,'' the general said.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki, an armored officer who served two tours in Vietnam and
was seriously wounded twice, predicted that landmines and
``radicals,'' both disaffected Serbs and rebel Albanians, posed a
much a greater threat to NATO troops as they begin the process of
rebuilding Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard work is about to start,'' he said. ``The conditions
we'll face in Kosovo are not much different than what I faced in
Bosnia.``
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki said U.S. and NATO forces could expect to stay in
Kosovo ``at least four years, if our experience in Bosnia is any
lesson.'' NATO peacekeepers have been in Bosnia since December
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is contributing 7,000 U.S. troops to the NATO
operation in Kosovo and nearly that many in Bosnia. With the
Clinton administration committed to sending much larger forces in
the Persian Gulf and Korean peninsula, if crises erupt there,
Shinseki warned that the 480,000-soldier Army ``may not be enough''
for the far-flung missions.
</P>
<P>
   As the Army's role in NATO's peacekeeping force begins to take
hold, the Air Force announced Wednesday it is phasing out a
suspension on retirements imposed to retain pilots and others
deemed critical to the air war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
