<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS &LR;      06-23 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS' EX-LOVER ADMITS REPEATED LYING TO SAVE CIVIL SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Linda Jones testified Wednesday that her repeated
lies drove a federal investigation into the ``hush money'' former
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros allegedly paid her following the
collapse of their extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 50, said her lies under oath about the authenticity of
her secretly recorded telephone conversations with Cisneros also
kept a skeptical state judge from dismissing her civil lawsuit
against Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a case with severe legal problems and in danger of
being thrown out unless you did something drastic?'' Brendan
Sullivan, a lawyer for Cisneros, asked as he quizzed her about her
motives in lying in the civil suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were desperate for money, weren't you?'' Sullivan asked as
he continued to hammer at Jones's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' came her reply.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had claimed the tapes were original, but she admitted
earlier this week all were copies and some of the recordings had
been edited to delete her threats to expose Cisneros' payments, if
he quit sending her money.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted under cross-examination Wednesday she lied to the
state court, the FBI and Independent Counsel David Barrett. It was
her third day of testimony in a hearing that appeared likely to
last through the week and possibly have to be resumed later.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's investigation of Cisneros, 52, led to a 21-count
indictment charging him with conspiring with Jones and two of his
aides to conceal $250,000 he paid her following the explosive
public disclosure of their affair in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Mark Jackowski said Cisneros tried to conceal the
``hush money'' to protect his nomination in 1993 by President
Clinton to be secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   The government wants to introduce 34 tapes of telephone
conversations between Jones and Cisneros at his trial, which is
scheduled to open Sept. 7. The tapes are key to the government's
case against him.
</P>
<P>
   Jackowski said the tapes are an admission ``out of his own
mouth'' that Cisneros was paying her in excess of $10,000 per year
and to underscore ``his intent and his motives'' to hide the scheme
to protect his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones, a former San Antonio fund-raiser who also was known
by her married name, Linda Medlar, admitted this week that none of
the tapes is original, and five have been altered.
</P>
<P>
   She repeatedly said she lied about the authenticity of the
tapes, once to resurrect her civil lawsuit against Cisneros that
was later settled out of court for $49,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jones pleaded guilty to 28 criminal charges as a result of
Barrett's investigation into Cisneros in Texas. She is serving a
42-month prison sentence and agreed to testify in exchange for a
reduction in her jail term.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Simon, another attorney representing Cisneros, joined the
effort to discredit her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every way shape or form, the witness has committed perjury,
obstruction of justice, lied repeatedly to the FBI, lied repeatedly
to the IRS, and is in jail for lying,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the government offers this witness?'' he asked U.S.
District Judge Stanley Sporkin.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he would rule when the hearing concludes on
whether the government can introduce the tapes during the trial,
and he noted that the government often has the right to use
evidence it uncovers.
</P>
<P>
   But he also hinted that the government's case has a problem,
most notably Jones's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astounded when I sit here and listen to what happened in
this case,'' Sporkin said after Jones was excused from the witness
stand for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there are people in this country who don't know how to
tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was San Antonio's mayor when he admitted affair,
setting off a swirl of publicity that Jones said ruined her ability
to stay employed and sent her to a hospital to be treated for
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros served as Clinton's housing secretary from 1993 to
1996. He is president of the Los Angeles-based, Spanish-language
television network Univision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
