<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-STOCK24-COX     06-23 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chairman vows to buy everybody a Coke
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now the real work begins for the Real Thing.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola must restore consumer trust in Belgium, France and the
rest of Europe where its drinks created a health scare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the company is keenly aware that these circumstances
surrounding product quality go to the heart and soul of its
brands,'' said Marc Cohen, a beverage analyst with Goldman Sachs.
``They must do everything possible to re-establish and secure
consumer confidence in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts spoke with one voice Wednesday after
Belgium told the company it could begin producing its beverages and
selling them in stores again _ after meeting several conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a clear need to be in the consumer's face saying,
'We're still a product you can trust,''' said Deutsche Bank analyst
Scott Wilkins. ``This is not an issue about money. It's more
important than that. It's an issue about the long-term health of
the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   At a bare minimum, Wilkins said, the company needs to double its
traditional marketing expenditures in most of continental Europe,
even though it will affect the bottom line in the short-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The near-term emphasis has to be this is an old, quality name
you can trust,'' Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester knows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is relevant to us is making sure we do everything
possible to reassure the Belgian consumers that they can completely
trust our products and the health and safety of our products,''
Ivester said Wednesday in Brussels at his first news conference
since the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will spend whatever is required from a marketing standpoint
to ensure that Belgian consumers can once again enjoy Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's top executive also was featured in TV commercials
aired Wednesday evening in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all the Belgian people who drink our products, I want to
say that I'm personally very sorry for any discomfort or
inconvenience,'' Ivester said in the 90-second TV spot. ``I thank
you for your patience with this situation. Most of all, I want you
to know that all of us at Coca-Cola are committed to working very,
very hard to earn your trust again.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Ivester said the company will try to get
a Coca-Cola in the hands of every Belgian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the first things I'll do is buy everybody in
Belgium a Coke,'' he said. ``We have a process in place that we
think can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with an aggressive, multimedia advertising and marketing
campaign, analysts did not know how long it would take for
Coca-Cola to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't have here is a precedent, so we don't know how
quickly the product will rebound,'' Wilkins said. ``They have to
get the product on the shelves and watch the reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   In its 113 years as an Atlanta institution, Coca-Cola has never
had a bigger recall and ban of its products. In fact, it has had a
reputation for a high degree of quality that it will likely exploit
in its marketing efforts, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the positive news in Belgium, Coca-Cola closed down 87
1/2 cents Wednesday at $61.75 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises, the bottler that owns the
two plants at the center of the crisis, dropped 25 cents to $32.37
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
