<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HINDU-PRIEST-SEX-HNS &LR;      06-23 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINDU-PRIEST-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINDU PRIEST GETS PROBATION IN SEXUAL ASSAULT OF ARKANSAS WOMAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ark.) 
 
By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Jurors gave probation Wednesday to a Hindu priest
convicted of sexual assault, but he did not avoid the wrath of the
judge, who called him an embarrassment to people of all faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as though your conduct is more that of a snake-oil
salesman than a Hindu holy man,'' state District Judge Ted Poe told
Bhogeshwernand Sharma, 37, after imposing the 10 years probation
and $10,000 fine for the sexual assault a 21-year-old Little Rock,
Ark., college student who had sought Sharma's spiritual guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Poe gave Sharma 180 days in the county jail and imposed many
conditions on his probation. He must not act as a priest, except
for his own family, and must also pay the victim's counseling
bills, plus restitution in an amount to be determined later.
</P>
<P>
   He must also register as a sex offender, not leave the county
without Poe's permission, take sex-offender counseling and post a
public notice about his crime in a yet-to-be-determined publication
or public venue.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, prosecutor Kelly Siegler told Poe that a new sexual
assault charge had just been filed against Sharma.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma, who had earlier mouthed a silent `thank you' to the
jurors who had given him probation, shook his head as Siegler
talked about the new charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready right now,'' Siegler said afterward. ``I can get
it indicted tomorrow, and we'll go to trial next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated Sharma's punishment for about three hours.
Earlier, they sent Poe a note saying they were deadlocked 11-1 in
favor of probation. Jurors declined comment as they left.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma was convicted of sexually assaulting the 21-year-old
woman on or about April 3, 1998, at his home in Harris County,which
includes most of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; She says Sharma told her he needed to cleanse her womb with
his ``holy sperm.''
</P>
<P>
   She says Sharma bullied her and said the sex merely was part of
a sacred ritual to fight ``evil spirits.'' She also says he told
her she would become barren, get sick and possibly die if she
talked of the ``ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, her mother and her mother's sister all sought
Sharma's help with various medical problems when he was in Arkansas
in September 1997 for a prayer service, according to testimony. The
mother and aunt say during that visit Sharma coerced them into sex
at separate times, always using the same pretext of blessings and
rituals mixed with odd prophecies and threats.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma returned to Arkansas in October 1997 to ``convert'' the
mother and daughter to Hinduism and they visited him and his family
in Houston in April 1998. That's when the daughter says Sharma
assaulted her.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma has not been charged in Arkansas with the alleged
encounters with the mother and aunt. But they were allowed to
testify in this trial.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year-old Hindu woman who came forward during the trial says
that on Jan. 6 _ days before he was charged _ Sharma had sex with
her, impregnated her and she had an abortion, Siegler said. The
woman's father subsequently called Sharma and his family, and
shortly after that the defendant was seen at a Houston passport
office.
</P>
<P>
   Because he had already been charged at that time, his bail was
revoked for the charge on the April 1998 case, Siegler said. The
20-year-old and her relatives say that in February Sharma's family
talked them out of going public. They didn't call the prosecutor
until this week.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler said the 20-year-old woman was in court Wednesday and
agreed to cooperate with authorities after it became clear that
Sharma was going to get probation.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Siegler said, another local woman came forward to
say she had also been assaulted by Sharma the same way as the
Arkansas women. It was unclear whether charges would be filed in
her case, but Siegler said she would testify in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler was disappointed with the sentence but said she would
file new charges against Sharma as long as they come in.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old and her mother said they were also disappointed
by the jury's verdict and urged others to come forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't come out, it's going to harm them for the rest
of their lives,'' the young woman said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Katherine Scardino said jurors were right to
give Sharma probation. She added that she knew nothing about the
new case and didn't know if she would continue to represent him.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino had presented testimony from Sharma's family and
friends who said he had never been alone with the three Arkansas
women. She also accused them of lying.
</P>
<P>
   But Siegler scoffed at that, saying the women had no reason to
lie, and the alibi witnesses were nothing more than
``co-conspirators.''
</P>
<P>
   That, among other things, angered Scardino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of (Siegler's) antics in the courtroom have been
pretty absurd and bizarre. ... Enough is enough. We have murderers
who don't get this kind of bad treatment,'' Scardino said later.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler responded, ``The trial is not about Katherine Scardino
and me. The trial is about a man who is raping women right and
left, and that's all it should stay about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
