<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIERKER-HNS &LR;      06-23 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TODD ACKERMAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Astros manager Larry Dierker checked out of Methodist Hospital on
Wednesday, seemingly as mischievous and wry as ever but also a bit
humbled.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight days after successful brain surgery to remove a
life-threatening mass of tangled blood vessels, Dierker indulged in
his usual tongue-in-cheek humor while reflecting on life's
unpredictable nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``After successive days of looking out my window and seeing only
dark clouds, today was the first time I saw the sun,'' Dierker, 52,
said at a hospital news conference. ``I took that as a symbol of my
new freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, wearing an Astros cap on his shaved, scarred head, said
he was deeply touched by fans' outpouring of affection and the
Astros' hanging his jersey above his usual dugout seat. ``You might
think it would make you feel like a big shot,'' he said, ``but it
had the opposite effect on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, Dierker feigned a near fall off the podium,
as if still unstable from surgery. He broke into a grin as a few
people gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker suffered a grand mal seizure in the eighth inning of a
June 13 game in the Astrodome against San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure, which resulted in suspension of the game with the
Astros leading 4-1, was diagnosed the next day as having resulted
from a condition known as arteriovenous malformation (AVM), the
second-leading cause of fatal brain hemorrhaging..
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rob Parrish, Dierker's surgeon, said Wednesday that an
electroencephalogram showed the ``seizure focus'' was removed in
the surgery. He said Dierker may be taken off anticonvulsive
medicine after the season, though he could have to take it
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish downplayed Dierker's next stage of recovery, saying his
wife, Judy, will have the toughest job.
</P>
<P>
   She said she has a lot of work ahead, ``staying at home and
helping Larry be a couch potato,'' and Dierker said he plans to
listen to a lot of music, write thank-you notes to get-well cards
and see his son's baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said Dierker should be able to return to managing after
the mid-July All-Star break _ ``certainly not before'' _ although
he will continue to be evaluated ``a day at a time, a week at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, noting that he is having no trouble finding the right
word in conversation or doing crossword puzzles, marveled at the
surgery's apparent lack of negative effects. Indeed, he noted, he
is coming out of the hospital with ``a slimmer waist, a forehead
tuck and, hopefully, brighter.''
</P>
<P>
   But he kept returning to how moved he was by the reaction to his
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been a little concerned this year that perhaps my
poker-face style _ I don't hug players or slam things or charge
umpires much _ left players unsure how much I care,'' said Dierker.
``But after seeing their reaction to this, the way they hang up my
jersey _ even when they're on the road, for instance _ I no longer
have that concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found out a lot from this, and most of it makes me feel
better, not worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he plans to watch games from the press box during
the homestand that starts tonight and hopes to stay involved in
team decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor's orders to keep away from extended periods of
difficult work during my recovery doesn't mean I have to stop
thinking,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
