<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVOLVING-CONDUCTORS-     06-23 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVOLVING-CONDUCTORS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTEBOOK: WHO'S CONDUCTING WHICH ORCHESTRA? AND WHY?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Ind., Mass., N.Y., Ohio, Pa., Texas)  (rk) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the announcement on Tuesday that, come 2002, Sir Simon
Rattle will be the next music director of the esteemed Berlin
Philharmonic, at least one seat has been grabbed in the game of
musical chairs among conductors vying for music directorships of
some eight or so important orchestras. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another seat opened on Tuesday when the Boston Orchestra
announced that Seiji Ozawa, now in his 25th season as its music
director, would step down, also in 2002, to take charge of the
Vienna State Opera. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is probably just coincidence that so many posts are opening
up simultaneously. Now that the Berlin vacancy has been filled ,
the orchestras in New York, Philadelphia, Atlanta, Houston,
Indianapolis and Cincinnati as well as Boston will all need new
music directors in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pressures of being the music director of a major urban
orchestra today must be a contributing factor to the current
restlessness. All aspects of the job are under question: has the
subscription-concert format served its purpose? How does a
conductor find the right balance between serving older repertory
and fostering the creation of new works? How do you entice young
people accustomed to amplified music to symphony concerts? Will
emerging technologies in instruments and recording soon make
musicians in formal wear playing centuries-old music on
centuries-old instruments seem hopelessly dated? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is notoriously hard to find out the real story behind the
courtship of conductors: who wants what post and who is wanted?
Judging from the secrecy of their deliberations, you would think
orchestras were dealing with international security.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been speculation that Rattle coveted the post in
Boston, where he has been an acclaimed guest conductor, and that he
therefore demurred when the Philadelphia Orchestra dangled its
directorship before him. Perhaps, convinced that Ozawa was in
Boston to stay, he took Berlin, a position many in the music world
believe Ozawa once wanted for himself. So on virtually the same day
that Sir Simon takes Berlin, Ozawa gives up Boston, which came as a
surprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the field of classical music could do itself
a lot of good by giving up the horse-race aspect of the story and
looking at the larger questions. What is Ozawa's legacy? Why did
Berlin go for Rattle? What are the lessons to be learned from it
all?
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa's record in Boston has always been hard to assess, for you
get different takes depending upon whom you ask. Just 38 when he
accepted the music directorship in 1973, he brought vitality and
undeniable talent to the job. His memory is astonishing. His
technical skills are often incomparable. He can pull together a
gargantuan piece like the Berlioz Requiem with stunning efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, on its best nights _ for example, an arresting
concert performance of Strauss' ``Elektra'' at Boston's Symphony
Hall in 1988 _ the orchestra could sound incandescent.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the chemistry has long been off, as many critics have
felt and said, quite bluntly. Ozawa ``continues to pilot the Boston
Symphony toward mediocrity,'' the New Yorker critic Alex Ross wrote
recently. At best, as a conductor Ozawa's work in the last decade
has been uneven.
</P>
<P>
   But there is even more to question in Ozawa's handling of other
aspects of the job. A music director must be not only a strong
conductor and orchestra builder, but also a leader of the cultural
community, someone with ties to composers, especially local
composers; someone who can reach out to other cultural and
educational institutions. Ozawa, who reared his family in Japan
during his tenure in Boston and still lacks fluency in English,
never convincingly filled that role.
</P>
<P>
   I was a critic in Boston in 1993, the year of Ozawa's 20th
anniversary with the orchestra, when something telling happened:
for the first time, he walked across the street from Symphony Hall
to the New England Conservatory and conducted the student orchestra
in Bartok's Concerto for Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The young musicians were thrilled, Ozawa was inspired, the
performance was fabulous and the good will generated was salutary.
Why, you wonder, did it take him 20 years? Another music director
might have done it annually.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the upheaval that Ozawa instigated during the
summers of 1997 and 1998 at the Tanglewood Music Center, the
respected training institute for young musicians at the summer home
of the Boston Symphony Orchestra in western Massachusetts, seems to
have been an attempt to create a lasting legacy any way possible.
</P>
<P>
   He essentially forced out the longtime directors of the program
and assumed creative leadership himself. Whether this was warranted
can be fairly debated. But Ozawa never satisfactorily delineated
exactly what the problems were that this painful shake-up was meant
to rectify. To many of the faculty who resigned in protest, it
seemed like the impulsive act of a frustrated man still yearning
for artistic respect.
</P>
<P>
   Tanglewood will recover. And for Ozawa, Vienna could be an
invigorating move. Meanwhile, even his biggest champions in Boston
may feel that the time has come for change at the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   It is well known that Daniel Barenboim, the music director of
the Chicago Symphony and the German State Opera in Berlin, was the
other finalist for the Berlin post, and wanted it badly. Barenboim,
56, was the establishment choice. He is a dedicated and utterly
honest musician and a resourceful technician. His performances have
rectitude and insight. For Chicago, he has probably been a healthy
antidote to the hyperkinetic Sir Georg Solti, who was there for 22
exciting years.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin has gone with the younger man, Rattle, 44, a conductor
about as far removed as anyone could be in temperament and
repertory from the tyrannical, traditional Herbert von Karajan, who
ruled the Berlin like Wotan. Rattle has eclectic and interesting
tastes in repertory and a genuine connection to contemporary music.
He is approachable, affable and well-liked by musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Given his impressive 18-year commitment to the City of
Birmingham Symphony Orchestra, during which he turned a provincial
ensemble in an industrial English city into a vibrant orchestra of
international significance, he is a role model of a music director
as a cultural leader. In choosing him, Berlin is clearly hoping for
Rattle to rejuvenate a great orchestra that sometimes seems
encrusted in tradition. More power to him.
</P>
<P>
   I have always felt that American orchestras, in particular, are
too quick to turn to great eminences who are more often than not
European. This is not to suggest that youth is always best. German
maestro Christoph von Dohnanyi was nearly 56 when he become the
music director of the Cleveland Orchestra, and few people contest
that this was an inspired choice. His music-making is at once
distinguished and exciting. He is an uncanny orchestra leader,
revered by his players. He is also an exceptional case.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His recently announced successor will be the Austrian Franz
Welser-Moest, and the wisdom of this choice will have to be proved
over time. Welser-Moest has youth (38) and dedication.
</P>
<P>
   From the performances I have heard him conduct, especially as a
guest with the Philadelphia Orchestra in New York, he seems a good,
solid, intelligent but not notably inspiring musician, and he has
not, at least in this country, been a significant advocate of
living composers. But the Cleveland may be the best in the country
right now, so you have to assume that its administrators know what
they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   In bringing Kurt Masur to the New York Philharmonic, the
orchestra also went for a senior, proven conductor and musician.
Masur's reverence for the standard Germanic repertory and his
sometimes aggressive interpretive approach has opened him to fair
criticism. But he was brought in to restore excellence and
confidence to the Philharmonic and this he has done.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Masur, whose outspoken defense of political freedom in
East Germany made him a hero there, has also tried to be a cultural
leader in New York, reaching out to local ensembles like the Harlem
Boys Choir and collaborating with the Lincoln Center Jazz
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   When he conducts a work like Bernstein's Dance Suite from ``West
Side Story'' you have to say, however stiff his rhythm, his heart
is in the right place. Overall, his tenure will probably be seen as
a strong one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the time has now come for some rejuvenation there as well.
Masur's contract runs through 2002. Will the orchestra board have
the daring to take a chance on a fresh candidate?
</P>
<P>
   When Leonard Bernstein was selected as music director in 1957,
he was no eminence, but a 39-year-old dynamo, not to mention the
first American-born music director of a major American orchestra.
And that worked out pretty well, most would say.
</P>
<P>
   Right now in town there is a young conductor doing remarkable
work with the Brooklyn Philharmonic, Robert Spano. Would the
Philharmonic be willing to go with a musician like him? Not likely,
if history is a guide. But with the remarkable number of vacancies,
the Philharmonic and other orchestras may be forced into taking
some chances. And that could be for the good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
