<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7305 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERT-INDIANA-ART-2T     06-23 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERT-INDIANA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILED IN MAINE, THE CREATOR AND PRISONER OF `LOVE'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Scott Sutherland writes on art and culture from Portland, Maine  
 By SCOTT SUTHERLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VINALHAVEN, Maine _ It is typical of the contradictions that
define Robert Indiana that he fled New York for an out-of-the-way,
fog-drenched Maine island, only to buy the biggest, brashest house
in town.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's home is a former Odd Fellows Hall called the Star of
Hope, an immense and aggressively Victorian structure that dwarfs
the small brick post office next door. The Star of Hope is the
grandest and most peculiar building in the village of Vinalhaven, a
lobstering hamlet on Vinalhaven Island, once famed for its granite
quarries and an hour by ferry from the midcoast port of Rockland.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's conspicuous home, not surprisingly, along with his
reputation as a famous, gay, eccentric artist, has made him a
tempting target for generations of local youths looking to prove
their mettle. The house took such a beating on Halloweens _
clapboards splattered with eggs, windows broken by rocks _ that two
years ago Indiana had the top two stories temporarily wrapped in
heavy plastic, a la Christo, to protect it from Halloween high
jinks.
</P>
<P>
   The Star of Hope, battered though it may be, has been Indiana's
refuge for more than 20 years, ever since he left New York in 1978
after weathering almost a decade of critical derision. He had
created a sensation in 1966 with a showing of his ``Love''
paintings at the Stable Gallery and was hailed as a central figure
in the Pop movement that included Lichtenstein, Rosenquist and
Warhol.
</P>
<P>
   But his ``Love'' success was also his undoing. Indiana had
failed to copyright the image, which dovetailed prophetically with
the Zeitgeist of the late 1960s; the love generation, the summer of
love and ``All You Need Is Love'' helped propel Indiana's ``Love''
into the mainstream with astounding velocity, and the artist,
despite repeated attempts, was powerless to control his creation as
it popped up on T-shirts, key rings, coffee mugs and paperweights.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana himself contributed to the ``Love'' saturation in a
variety of ways, including editions of unsigned prints,
18-karat-gold rings and 330 million 8-cent postage stamps. ``Love''
was as ubiquitous as the American flag, and, for a while at least,
arguably more popular.
</P>
<P>
   But as the culture embraced the image, the art world, convinced
it smelled a sellout, attacked Indiana; John Canaday, an art critic
for The New York Times, suggested that Indiana make ``Money'' his
next popular image. He mounted later shows in an attempt to reclaim
the ``Love'' image as an artistic creation, but his efforts were
too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   By 1978, feeling cut off from the New York art world he'd been a
part of since 1954 _ and having lost the lease on his five-story
Bowery studio _ Indiana packed up his voluminous belongings and
relocated to the Star of Hope, which he had used as a seasonal
studio since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The demands of the laborious move _ which Indiana calls
``hellish'' _ and of transforming the derelict Star of Hope from a
studio into a home seriously curtailed his art production. He
showed only sporadically throughout the 1980s and didn't emerge
with a significant new body of work until 1994, when his ``Hartley
Elegies,'' a series of large, dynamic oil paintings dedicated to
the Maine painter Marsden Hartley _ who, like Indiana, was
tormented by Vinalhaven youths during a summer visit to the island
in 1938 _ were first shown in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's output continues, in the form of paintings, prints and
sculpture. His art is still characterized by the words, numbers,
colors and hard-edge geometries that defined his work in the '60s
and '70s _ ``I am still a painter of signs,'' he likes to say _ and
refers directly to significant moments in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his work, though, is inspired by the nightly news; the
Monica Lewinsky scandal and the death of Joe DiMaggio prompted
Indiana to begin a new series of Marilyn Monroe ``sex goddess''
paintings, one of his favorite subjects in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   And he is getting shows. A current retrospective at the Portland
Museum of Art, ``Love and the American Dream: The Art of Robert
Indiana,'' which runs through Oct. 17, is the second major show of
his work in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Musee d'Art Moderne et d'Art Contemporain in
Nice, France, mounted an Indiana retrospective, the first major
showing of his work since 1991. Another major show is tentatively
planned for Tokyo next year. Could it be that, at age 70, Indiana
and his meticulously painted signs are on the verge of finding a
new millennial audience?
</P>
<P>
   ``Any show helps attract and educate people,'' Indiana said in a
recent interview. Then, as if by reflex, he added, ``But it's what
the press has to say about it that makes it or breaks it.''
</P>
<P>
   His prickly relationship with the news media _ craving the
attention, yet wasting little time in blasting an assortment of
critics and publications _ is just one of the contradictions of
Indiana's life on Vinalhaven.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely leaves the island and almost never answers his phone,
yet he clearly relishes social contact. He lives an exile's life in
Maine while keeping close tabs on the New York art scene he left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   His place in American art history is assured, but he continues
to fight for respect from an art establishment that he believes
undervalues him. And despite the recent shows of his work, he
laments that they didn't happen in New York.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that the Museum of Modern Art has never been
interested in a retrospective of my work,'' said Indiana, as he
puffed a cigar in the Star of Hope's comfortable, purple-walled
living room. He was dressed casually in jeans and a baseball cap,
sported large round glasses and a mostly gray beard, and wore a
``Love'' wristwatch. ``It's not a matter of whether people
understand my work; it's a matter of whether it's ever seen, which
it hardly is, and it's hardly ever appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney Museum appreciates one of Indiana's large ``Love''
paintings enough to include it in the second part of its ``American
Century'' show, opening in September. Karl Willers, an associate
curator of the show, points to the cyclical nature of art fashion
as a way of suggesting that Indiana may yet get his due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is always up for re-examination,'' Willers said.
```Love' has been a blessing and a curse for him, in the sense of
how people might approach his larger body of work. But he's
produced an astounding body of work over his lifetime, work that is
immediately recognizable and stands up to that of any of his Pop
contemporaries.''
</P>
<P>
   But that Pop label has also been a problem for Indiana, mostly
because he was never really Pop to begin with. It's a common
misperception that Indiana looked to culture to create ``Love,''
when in fact it was ``Love'' that helped create the culture that
produced Woodstock. ``Nobody includes him in the core of Pop
artists anymore,'' said Aprile Gallant, who organized the Portland
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He isn't detached from his subject matter, he handpaints
everything and there's a lot of personal content in his work. But
the art world likes movements, and that's been part of Bob's
problem. No one knows where to put him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gallant said she hadn't seen enough of Indiana's recent
output to say how it might shape his reputation _ or whether it,
too, would be eclipsed by the long shadow cast by ``Love.'' But she
added that many of his new projects seem concerned with reflection
and trying to square the past with the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work now is an awful lot about trying to assess his
career,'' Ms. Gallant said. ``He's held on to many of his works for
years, like a diary, and he's returning to those.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a sunny former sail loft across the street from the
Star of Hope, Indiana is putting the finishing touches on six
sculptures, created from sections of old ship masts, that he began
in the early 1960s. One piece lists place names that essentially
chart his life, starting with New Castle, the Indiana town where he
was born Robert Clark in 1928. (He changed his name to Indiana in
1958 after he moved to New York.).
</P>
<P>
   The list continues with Indianapolis, Chicago, Skowhegan,
Edinburgh, Coenties Slip, the Bowery, Vinalhaven. ``Why wouldn't
I?'' he replied, when asked why he would dig out old, unfinished
work. ``Things need to be taken care of. My regret is that they
weren't done a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana insists that he doesn't regret his move to Vinalhaven,
which he admits ``has not made for many happy years.'' A low point
came in 1990, when he was arrested and charged with hiring a young
island man for sex, but a jury cleared him in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the controversy only reinforced Indiana's outsider status
among the clannish islanders. ``The match of lobstermen and artists
is not exactly made in heaven,'' he said. ``But this is a very good
place to get work done.'' He does so with the help of a bevy of
assistants, whom he refers to as ``my boys,'' and peppers his
art-making with breaks to tend a menagerie of pets, including a
gaggle of geese he fondly calls ``my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana is in exile, but it seems to suit him. In the Star of
Hope's purple living room, a ``Love'' wall hanging dominating one
end, Indiana gestured around himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a prisoner of this building _ the dogs, the pipes in the
winter, the geese, the plants; there's too much to worry about to
leave,'' he said. ``But it's not all that different than when I was
in New York. I never entered into the scene the way Warhol did. I
was never very comfortable uptown. I was usually in my studio
downtown, painting signs _ charting the course, as I put it a long
time ago. That's what I'm still doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
