<HEADLINE>
FBI FORENSIC TEAM TRIES TO IDENTIFY VICTIMS OF KOSOVO WAR CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A team of FBI forensic investigators began the
grisly task of investigating two sites in western Kosovo on
Wednesday in an effort to identify victims of two mass killings
cited in the war crimes indictment of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The sites are in the vicinity of Djakovica, a town in a sector
of Kosovo under the jurisdiction of Italian troops. One is a house
in which war crimes prosecutors have said that 20 Albanians were
gathered in April and shot dead by Serbian troops.
</P>
<P>
   A second site outside Djakovica is believed to contain the
bodies of about a half-dozen Albanian men killed in March by
Serbian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said initial surveys at the sites suggested that
someone had tried to cover up the killings, in some instances
moving bodies to avoid identification of victims.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday announcing the opening of the
inquiry, FBI Director Louis Freeh said it was not yet clear whether
U.S. investigators would examine other sites of reported
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The province of Kosovo is now one of the largest crime scenes
in history,'' Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-member team of agents sent there include forensic
scientists who will try to determine who died at the two sites. The
agents will seek to retrieve blood samples, clothing, spent
cartridges and other evidence including DNA samples that will be
shipped back to the FBI lab in Washington for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law enforcement personnel are part of an international war
crimes investigation that is being conducted under the authority of
the International War Crimes Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia in
The Hague. Other investigators from countries like Britain, France
and Canada are already in the province or are expected to arrive
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The barbarous killings at the house in Djakovica have been the
subject of numerous accounts from refugees who fled the region as
Serbian troops stormed through the area after the NATO bombing
began in March.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees who escaped said Serbs had pulled women and children
from their homes and herded them into a basement where soldiers
executed them. Afterward, the house was burned, allegedly to
conceal the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment against Milosevic, which was returned in May by
the war crimes tribunal, said: ``On or about the early morning
hours of 2 April 1999, Serb police launched an operation against
the Qerim district of Djakovica. Over a period of several hours,
Serb police forcibly entered houses of Kosovo Albanians in the
Qerim district, killing occupants and then setting fire to the
buildings. In the basement of a house on Millosh Gilic Street, the
Serb police shot the 20 occupants and set the house on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment added that 19 of the 20 victims were believed to
have been women and children.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of people believed to have been killed at both
locations are listed in the indictment against Milosevic and four
other Yugoslav and Serbian leaders. The FBI will try to identify
the bodies at the sites to match them with the victims listed in
the indictment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
