<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7310 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-POTTER-SPI &LR;      06-23 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POTTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS OF `HARRY POTTER' BOOKS HAS BUYERS, AND BOOKSELLERS,
SCRAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Just three weeks after ``Harry Potter and the Chamber
of Secrets'' hit American bookstores, young readers already are
placing advance orders for the third installment of J.K. Rowling's
phenomenal fantasy series.
</P>
<P>
   Look for ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban'' in U.S.
bookstores on Sept. 8, a week earlier than the original release
date.
</P>
<P>
   September originally was chosen for the U.S. publication of
``Chamber of Secrets,'' the second Harry Potter book. Instead,
``Chamber'' showed up in American bookstores on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved it up because of customer demand,'' said a
spokesperson for Scholastic Inc., which has U.S. rights to the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Booksellers say Scholastic decided to move fast after impatient
fans began buying the British version of the series, published
months earlier by Bloomsbury Children's Books and available in that
country as well as Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Some early birds got ``Chamber of Secrets'' through
Amazon.co.UK, the British version of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with competitive pressure from the giant Internet
bookseller, some Seattle bookstores stocked the British ``Chamber
of Secrets'' earlier this year until Scholastic pressured them to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic's stance put booksellers in a tough spot. In terms of
buzz, ``Harry Potter'' is to children's books what ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' is to movies, and everyone wants a
piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't keep `Harry Potter' on the shelf,'' said Chauni
Haslet, owner of All for Kids Books &AMP; Music in Seattle. ``It's the
first magical page-turner we've had in years.''
</P>
<P>
   Targeted at kids 8 to 12 years old, the series captivates
readers of all ages. ``It has been the book for families to read
together,'' Haslet said.
</P>
<P>
   She stopped selling the British ``Chamber of Secrets'' in late
January at Scholastic's request because, she said, ``we feel it's
important to play the game honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   Christy McDanold, owner of the Secret Garden Children's
Bookshop, in Seattle's Ballard neighborhood, said, ``I don't know
what's legal, but I don't see any reason to thumb noses at
Scholastic.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she added, ``Many, many of my customers got the British
version.''
</P>
<P>
   McDanold said she had to promise Scholastic in writing that she
would not sell ``Prisoner of Azkaban'' before the official U.S.
release date.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the British version of ``Azkaban'' comes out July 8,
two months before Scholastic's U.S. edition. You can get it then
through Amazon.co.UK.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Amazon.com says Scholastic's concerns about the
British edition are overblown. Spokesman Paul Capelli said
Amazon.com sold fewer than 2,000 copies of the British ``Chamber of
Secrets'' in the United States _ a figure that calls into question
how much competitive pressure the Internet seller really created.
</P>
<P>
   Capelli said Scholastic, despite its protests, may have
benefited from early circulation of the British edition because of
the word-of-mouth excitement it generated.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, back-door maneuvers soon will become unnecessary as
Scholastic moves to close the gap between British and American
publication dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the fourth book comes out, they'll be
simultaneously published, to stop all this,'' said Patricia
Johnson, children's book buyer at University Book Store in Seattle,
which continued selling the British ``Chamber of Secrets'' after
other stores pulled it.
</P>
<P>
   J.K. Rowlings was a single mother on public assistance when she
created ``Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone,'' writing at a
cafe while her baby daughter napped. The book went on to become the
British Book Awards Children's Book of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The American edition, ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone''
appeared a year later.
</P>
<P>
   As fast-paced as a Nimbus Two Thousand flying broom, the series
unfurls the magical adventures of a boy named Harry, who (shades of
Roald Dahl) suffers life with loathsome, mean-spirited relatives
who don't appreciate him.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he finds sanctuary, and his true calling _ at the
Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, which has all the
stuffy conventions and petty rivalries of a typical British
boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Star Wars,'' the books explore the tension between good
and evil, but in a kid-size, happy-ending kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter'' caused little stir at first, and Rowling's
first American tour last fall went largely unnoticed. Then National
Public Radio featured the book in late November, setting off a
buying frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a line at the counter within five minutes,'' said
Secret Garden's McDanold. ``We had people calling in on their cell
phones.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the race was on to get the second book into the
hands of customers, many of whom were willing to pay $6 or $7 more
for the less handsome British edition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Warner Bros. has optioned the film rights to the
first two books of what, ultimately, will be a seven-book series.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Amazon.co.UK has posted a brief plot summary for
the upcoming ``Prisoner of Azkaban.'' Here's the scoop:
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter is now in his third year at Hogwarts. The
atmosphere is tense as the sinister prison guards of Azkaban are
called in to guard the school. Harry and his friends Ron and
Hermione soon discover why wizards live in fear of Azkaban.
</P>
<P>
   Booksellers can't think of any book in recent memory that has
caused such excitement. Philip Pullman's unfinished ``Dark
Materials'' trilogy (``The Golden Compass'' and ``The Subtle
Knife'') is the only work that comes close.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Pullman's books _ which are darker and more complex than
``Harry Potter'' _ already have placed advance orders for the
concluding volume, ``The Amber Spyglass,'' which originally was due
out this October from Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, they'll have to wait until May 2000. Pullman, who spent a
lot of time on promotional tours, reportedly needs more time to
polish the manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, we'll just have to be wild about ``Harry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
