<HEADLINE>
STARR COULD CALL HILLARY CLINTON AS WITNESS IN HUBBELL TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, may call
Hillary Rodham Clinton as a witness in the criminal trial this
summer of her former law partner, Webster Hubbell, a lawyer
familiar with the case said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision by Starr on whether to seek testimony from the
first lady in the Hubbell trial, scheduled to begin in August in
federal court in Washington has not been reached, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But the trial will certainly deal with Mrs. Clinton's role as a
lawyer in Little Rock, Ark., in connection with a land deal
criticized as a sham by federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Clinton, the trial could come at an awkward moment,
just weeks after she is expected to announce her candidacy for the
Senate from New York. In addition, Starr and his aides are
considering producing a report on the investigation into the
Whitewater real estate venture and other controversies in which the
First Lady has become embroiled.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell has pleaded not guilty to charges that he sought to
conceal from Federal regulators the role he and Mrs. Clinton played
in a complicated land transaction in Arkansas that helped lead to
the collapse of a savings and loan institution.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, a former chief justice of the State of Arkansas and
once the No. 3 official in the Clinton Justice Department, was
charged with 15 counts of fraud, making false statements and trying
to impede two federal regulatory agencies and with perjury before a
Congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment concerns a real estate development known as
Castle Grande, for which Mrs. Clinton did legal work. The
indictment does not mention Mrs. Clinton by name but refers more
than 30 times to the ``1985-86 billing partner'' on the Castle
Grande account, a description of Mrs. Clinton's role in the
transaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
