<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7323 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-PARTIES24-COX     06-23 1786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-PARTIES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's an entertaining thought: Party on the cheap
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Blow off those mavens of style who insist that
you must have champagne and caviar to entertain with flair. Not
true in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where creative spirits run high, you do not have to
have a lot of money to have a lot of style. Look at the many
practioners around you _ the thousands of musicians and 100,000
college students, not to mention all the other folks who do not
have high-dollar, high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   While their funds may be limited, their sense of fun is
boundless. They maximize their strengths, swap their talents and
seek unusual opportunities to entertain smoothly and smartly on a
shoestring.
</P>
<P>
   Even local party pros, when put to the test, can create magic
with a minimum of moolah. It's a matter of rethinking the dollar,
the dinner, the drinks. It's a matter of entertaining Austin-style.
</P>
<P>
   Angelica Bautista and Omar Hernandez, who are among the 12,000
graduate students at the University of Texas, opt to go native _
entertaining with foods from their homelands. Bautista, an
anthropology Ph.D. candidate from Mexico, stirs up chicken mole,
enchiladas called entomatadas, guacamole and rice. Hernandez, a
communications Ph.D. candidate from Venezuela, makes arepas, a
stuffed corn cake resembling a gordita.
</P>
<P>
   Married to Hernandez (they met at Robert Mueller airport more
than five years ago), Bautista says graduate students ``have no
money at all for parties or anything.'' So they either have
potlucks, especially with large groups of 20 to 30, or they cook
the meal and let guests bring drinks.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening, Argentine reggae played in their married
student apartment as the couple put together an informal dinner
party for nine for less than $50. Hernandez gave guests a lesson in
arepas, a Venezuelan corn cake made from masa.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bag of meal costs $1.59, and you can make a lot of arepas
for that,'' he said as he shaped half-cup balls of dough into
patties for baking either in a skillet or an Oster electric arepa
maker his family gave him.
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, arepas are sold at areperas, cafes that specialize
in these corn sandwiches from breakfast to late night. You can get
them with all kinds of fillings _ beef, cheese, pork, tuna,
chicken, beans _ and it's not uncommon to go for arepas at 5 a.m.
after a night on the town.
</P>
<P>
   This is good comfort food: warm corn cake, crispy on the
outside, soft inside. It is split, buttered and filled with cheese
or a flavorful tuna mixture, spiked with a picante habanero oil for
those who dare.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bautista has dipped corn tortillas in a tomato-sour
cream sauce and filled them with cheese and poblano strips for rosy
enchiladas called entomatadas, which she garnished with chopped
lettuce, sliced radishes and salsa verde.
</P>
<P>
   The couple cooks about three times a week, and friends look
forward to their food.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to get together and enjoy seeing each
other,'' Bautista says. In addition to good food, they have music
and often dance.
</P>
<P>
   At Jay Nazz's house, music is a given ingredient in
entertaining. The drummer for Reckless Kelly, an award-winning
alternative country band, Nazz can keep a beat in the kitchen, too.
He entertains his fellow band members and friends with stuffed
pasta shells, a thrifty but tasty pasta dish that feeds 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I buy is a money issue,'' says Nazz. ``I don't have a
whole lot of money to buy a lot of food, but these recipes don't
take a lot of ingredients. They are the right mixture of
ingredients to give the right taste, an expensive taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Nazz has been cooking a couple of years now, getting lessons
from his mom, whom he visited recently in North Carolina, picking
up her stuffed artichoke recipe. ``She's an old-school Italian
cook,'' he says. Hence, his stuffed shells specialty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to cook your mom's things because you know what they
are supposed to taste and look like,'' says Nazz, who has yet to
master her sauce, eggplant Parmesan or lasagne. Those are his next
goals, but touring on the road with the band doesn't allow much
kitchen time.
</P>
<P>
   When the band first started out, Nazz says, they often stayed at
people's houses on tour because the price was right. He and Willy
Braun, the lead singer, would repay their hosts' hospitality by
cooking for them. They also do the cooking for their annual
Christmas party.
</P>
<P>
   Nazz figures he entertains a couple of times a month. Of course
that varies with the tour schedule, and the next couple of months
will find them on the road out West.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing his trademark overalls _ one of 16 pairs _ Nazz talks
about garlic and the stuffed mushrooms he made the night before as
he fills jumbo pasta shells with ricotta cheese. The aroma is
wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   He cooks to music. Not Reckless Kelly's _ he hears that all the
time. But more to classical or even the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Nazz loves this newfound cooking hobby. ``It's calming. And it's
nice to smell those smells I used to smell in my house.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends and band members don't mind, either. It's good food.
Makes for a good party. With a little music, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Arepas
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups precooked white corn meal
</P>
<P>
   Fillings:
</P>
<P>
   Butter
</P>
<P>
   Tuna (recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   Chicken, beef or pork
</P>
<P>
   Cheese slices
</P>
<P>
   Cotija cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Picante (recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   Pour warm water in a large bowl, add salt and slowly add
cornmeal. Knead until smooth. Using a 1/3 cup measure, scoop up a
ball of the dough and shape in hands into a circle about 4 inches
in diameter and 1/3 inch thick. Repeat with remaining dough. Heat a
nonstick skillet over medium. Place arepas in skillet and cook like
a pancake until light brown and crispy on both sides. Remove from
skillet and place on racks in 350-degree oven and bake for 10-15
minutes until done through. (Dough also can be cooked in an
electric arepa maker.) Keep warm in a covered basket until ready to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Split arepa like a gordita or biscuit, cutting almost
all the way through. With a knife, remove soft interior if desired.
(Interior can be spread with butter and sprinkled with cheese and
eaten like grits.) Spread inside with softened butter. Sprinkle on
grated cotija cheese. Fill with sliced cheese (Havarti or Swiss) or
tuna filling. Spoon on picante if desired.
</P>
<P>
   P.A.N. is the brand of masa often used for arepas.
</P>
<P>
   Picante
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 habaneros, chopped, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients and use to dress arepas or other foods.
Very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Tuna filling
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium potatoes, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, chopped 1/2 green pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cans water-packed tuna, drained
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Oregano to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   In olive oil, saute chopped potatoes for 10 minutes. Add onion,
garlic and green pepper and cook. After 5 minutes, add the tuna and
the salt, pepper and oregano to taste. Cook 5 more minutes.
Sprinkle in cilantro. Serve warm in arepas.
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for 12 arepas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Omar Hernandez
</P>
<P>
   Entomatadas
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Oregano to taste
</P>
<P>
   Oil
</P>
<P>
   1 package (24-count) white corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces sliced panela cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 poblano chile, sliced into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cotija cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Combine tomato sauce with sour cream, adding oregano to taste,
and a teaspoon of oil. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Soften corn tortillas in hot oil. Dip in sour cream sauce. Fill
tortilla with a slice of panela, and a thin strip of poblano. Roll
up like an enchilada and place in a casserole dish. Repeat until
all tortillas and sauce are used. Sprinkle cotija cheese on top.
</P>
<P>
   Heat casserole in 350 degree oven until cheese melts, about 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 12-16.
</P>
<P>
   Mole
</P>
<P>
   4 ancho chiles
</P>
<P>
   3 pasilla chiles
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces unsweetened chocolate, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ground roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Water or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   Place chiles in 2 cups boiling water and cook until softened.
Drain; remove seeds and stems from chiles. Blend the softened
chiles with chocolate, spices and peanuts, adding water or chicken
broth (about 2 cups) to desired consistency. Place oil in saucepan
and stir in about 1 teaspoon cornstarch until brown. Stir mole
sauce into cornstarch mixture, stirring until it boils and gets
thick. Add water or broth, if necessary. If you like a sweet mole,
add turbinado sugar to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3 cups mole, enough to serve 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the mole over vegetarian ``chicken'' patties cut into
strips. Or for nonvegetarian mole, put 3 cups cooked chicken into
mole sauce. (Broth from cooking the chicken can be substituted for
the water in mole sauce.) _ Angelica Baustista
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed Shells
</P>
<P>
   1 box large pasta shells (about 48 count)
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds ricotta cheese, part-skim or whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mozzarella cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Chopped parsley (enough to be visible in a spoonful)
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts spaghetti sauce such as Aunt Millie's, Classico or
Prego
</P>
<P>
   Grated Parmesan cheese, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta shells according to package directions until not
quite tender. (They will continue cooking in oven.)
</P>
<P>
   Blend ricotta with grated mozzarella. (If you freeze mozzarella
briefly, it will be easier to grate.) Stir in parsley and beaten
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff each pasta shell with a couple tablespoons of the cheese
filling. Place shell in a baking pan or dish. Repeat until all
shells and filling are used. Pour spaghetti sauce over shells. (If
desired, enhance spaghetti sauce by putting about a tablespoon of
olive oil in a saucepan, and adding some chopped onion and garlic.
Cook until tender; then stir in jarred sauce.)
</P>
<P>
   Place shells in oven at 325 degrees and bake for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves about 12. Sprinkle with Parmesan cheese if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Tortellini Alfredo
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cheese tortellini
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint half and half
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter
</P>
<P>
   Handful grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cook tortellini according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in half and half over low heat. Pour over drained
tortellini. Sprinkle with Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4. _ Jay Nazz
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
