<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNLEY24-COX     06-23 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNLEY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digging gently into history
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Their bones have been prayed over and dug
for. Still, the five sailors of the Confederate submarine H.L.
Hunley are missing.
</P>
<P>
   But as early as today, just one more shovelful of dirt could
uncover their whereabouts, solving one of the many mysteries
surrounding the Hunley, the first submarine in naval history to
sink an enemy ship.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeological curiosity and a determination by Confederate
heritage groups to provide proper burial for the Hunley's original
crew are driving this week's search for bones beneath The Citadel's
football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Here in South Carolina, where the flying of the Confederate
battle flag atop the Statehouse in Columbia has caused rancor, a
preacher prayed Wednesday that the search for the Hunley's original
crew would turn out differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope as we move toward the future, we will remember the
past so that we will be delivered from pride or prejudice or
racism,'' the Rev. Leon Thompson told the 20 volunteer diggers,
most belonging to the Sons of Confederate Veterans and other
heritage groups.
</P>
<P>
   Though some wore the red-and-blue emblem of the Rebel battle
flag on caps and shirts, the volunteers said they felt compelled to
dig out of reverence for their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get them home properly,'' said 58-year-old
volunteer Jeanne Weil, a member of the South Carolina Ladies
Auxiliary spending long days underneath Johnson-Hagood Stadium, the
suspected burial site.
</P>
<P>
   Old historical documents and recently conducted
ground-penetrating radar suggested the ``men of the torpedo boat''
who drowned in 1863 were buried in Charleston's old Confederate
naval cemetery. Abandoned in the late 1940s when the city built the
massive steel-and-concrete stadium, now home to The Citadel
Bulldogs, the graveyard is partly underneath the bleachers and
partly in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they are there,'' said Randy Burbage, chairman of
Charleston's Confederate Heritage Trust, which organized the search
for the Hunley sailors. ``But we just haven't found them yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery late Tuesday of two possible burial shafts hasn't
yet panned out in a discovery of remains.
</P>
<P>
   Digging resumes today, after Wednesday afternoon's discovery of
a distinct, 2-foot-wide rectangle of dark brown earth. Hemmed in by
concrete footings for the stadium's girders, the spot resembles the
outline of a grave shaft.
</P>
<P>
   The find came after a backhoe had peeled back a 20-by-60-foot
section of asphalt just inside the stadium's cinderblock back wall.
Workers with blunt-nosed shovels dug carefully through two feet of
fill dirt containing scraps of centuries-old glass and metal, rusty
nails and pork rib bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiram Walker _ I don't think that is from the Civil War,''
joked 43-year-old volunteer John Dangerfield, holding up a liquor
bottle cap.
</P>
<P>
   A skeleton could lie just inches below the possible burial
shaft, heightening excitement among the volunteers digging in muggy
heat. But deputy state archaelogist John Leader said he doubts that
the possible grave shaft discovered Wednesday belongs to one of the
five Hunley crewmen.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Leader said, it probably contains another of the
Confederate sailors or marines buried in the old cemetery,
originally a pauper's field for Charleston sailors.
</P>
<P>
   A 1993 excavation discovered 13 Confederate graves under the
stadium's parking lot, near where the third day of searching
resumes today.
</P>
<P>
   Leader is looking for evidence of a trench with four or five
burial shafts. Officials believe that at least four of the Hunley's
victims were buried in a mass grave. It is possible, they say, that
relatives of one of the crewmen buried his body elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of those puzzles of history,'' said Leader, a burly,
bearded researcher who drew onlookers whenever he kneeled to scrap
the sandy brown soil with a wooden-handled trowel. ``We have to
figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hunley tale, like the search for its crew, is laced with
intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   The original crew died in the first of three fatal sinkings of
the cramped 40-foot-long submarine, praised as an engineering
marvel and condemned as a casket of steel.
</P>
<P>
   For the war-ravaged Confederacy, it was a secret, last-ditch
weapon to crack the Union's blockade of Charleston's harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The first crew died when human error caused the submarine to
dive before its hatches were fastened. Moored in the harbor, it was
hoisted back to the surface and prepared for a second crew of
eight, who died just months later during a practice dive. Those
sailors are buried in Charleston's Magnolia Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1864, the Hunley made history when it sank the USS
Housatonic, a federal blockade ship. It would be another half
century, during World War I, before another submarine would sink an
enemy ship.
</P>
<P>
   In darkness, Union sailors peppered the Hunley will gunfire as
it approached to detonate explosives against the Housatonic's hull.
Just minutes into its retreat, the submarine and its crew of nine
sank in 30 feet of water four miles off Sullivans Island, near
Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   The historic assault is chronicled in a Turner Network
Television movie, ``The Hunley,'' to air July 11. Organizers of an
ambitious, $20 million project to recover, preserve and display the
submarine in the Charleston Museum hope the national premier will
boost fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the Hunley's discovery in 1995, the recovery project
is backed by state and federal agencies, including the U.S. Navy.
The support of heritage groups has not caused rancor, as did the
Confederate flag debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it deals with the Confederate side,'' said South
Carolina Sen. Glenn McConnell (R-Charleston), who is instrumental
in the Hunley project. ``But it is about history and heritage, not
politics. It is a story that anybody can identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   If the two missing Hunley crews _ the one believed to be under
the stadium and the one in the sunken submarine _ can be recovered,
they will be buried in Magnolia Cemetery along with the third
Hunley crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission of the Hunley project is to reunite the boat and
its crews,'' McConnell said. ``We call it completing the journey.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
