<HEADLINE>
FOR OWNER OF THE MAIDS, SUCCESS STORY ENDS _ SADLY _ IN BUYOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ Four months ago, I wrote a business feature
about Alice Errett, owner of The Maids franchise in Overland Park,
Kan., who went to extraordinary lengths to hire, train and
transport entry-level workers from Wyandotte County to her cleaning
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The account generated uncommon feedback. Errett earned
amazement, praise and new business from people because of her
commitment to employ the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   She also lost a couple of clients because they learned ``those
people'' were cleaning their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Alice doesn't clean here anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Maids International, the Omaha, Neb.-based franchise
company, bought her out and began operating the business last week.
The company retained her long-time assistants, Ron Schmidt and
Andrea Matthes, to handle day-to-day management.
</P>
<P>
   Errett and corporate officers of The Maids differ slightly on
why the change occurred, but all agreed she had a successful
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't force me to sell,'' Errett said, ``and they never
said I was getting bought out because I didn't do things their way
... but I think, under it all, I was a problem child.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have individual operators deciding what to put on
their Big Macs. I wasn't standardized like they were. ... I had a
knock-down-drag-out with them at one point about our hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   After the article appeared about Errett's hiring efforts,
someone at headquarters (Errett said she confirmed the source) sent
a copy of it back to her with the words, ``It's too bad it's come
to this'' written across the page.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Hoeffner, director of The Maids' six _ soon to be seven
_ company-owned franchise locations, said there was nothing behind
Errett's buyout except a company plan, begun in April 1998, to
acquire some of its franchises in ``geographically representative''
locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice was a big sister to us when we opened the Wichita
franchise in 1995,'' Hoeffner said. ``I don't know of any negative
feedback about her franchise. It was her business to run, and she
did it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Whiting, executive vice president at the Omaha headquarters,
agreed that the company wanted to acquire the key Kansas City area
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice has been very innovative in what she developed, and
she's done some things we were able to communicate to some of our
other franchises about working with social service agencies and
hiring,'' Whiting said. ``Realistically, I think we can carry that
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Errett is sure they can. The company-owned shop won't have to
pay itself the 7.1 percent royalties on gross sales that she paid
weekly. Already they've given raises to staff and run an employment
ad worth several hundred dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, though, Errett left thinking ``they busted my chops'' for
doing things differently.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she got a great buyout price. There are no income worries
this summer while she takes a break and plays with her son. The
best thing about the buyout, she said, is the freedom to try
something new.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she hopes to head for Albania. She thinks a relief
agency might want project managers who can pay their own way and
help out in postwar rebuilding efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
