<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFULS ARE NEW (OR OLD?) BREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ An entire generation of Mexicans has been governed
by presidents who had never won office before and who were chosen
by their predecessors in part because of their Ivy League
credentials and fluent English.
</P>
<P>
   These presidents, foreign-trained economists, have modernized
the economy while impoverishing the country's working class.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a little-remarked but crucial shift, politicians are
taking over politics again in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike President Ernesto Zedillo (Yale, Ph.D., '78) and his two
predecessors, Carlos Salinas (Harvard, Ph.D., '78) and Miguel de la
Madrid (Harvard, master's, '65), none of the four candidates
currently seeking the presidential nomination of the governing
party known as the PRI, are technocrats. In Mexican usage, a
technocrat is a foreign-trained expert, usually an economist, whose
career has been built in the bureaucracy rather than in party ranks
or in elected posts.
</P>
<P>
   Three are from the PRI's old guard, known as the dinosaurs, and
all are professional politicians. And so are the likely nominees of
Mexico's two main opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the end of government by technocracy, thank
goodness,'' said Agustin Basave Benitez, a former PRI congressman
who heads the political science department at the local campus of
the Monterrey Technical Institute of Higher Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six candidates seeking the presidential nominations from
the three main parties, only Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who appears
to be Zedillo's preferred candidate, has a profile even remotely
similar to that of Mexico's three most recent presidents. Labastida
was trained in Mexico as an economist, but he does not speak
English and was elected to a state governorship.
</P>
<P>
   His most vigorous rival for the PRI nomination, Roberto Madrazo
Pintado, a lawyer who resigned recently as governor of Tabasco
state, is campaigning to arouse popular anger against the
technocrats and their economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Anger at the technocrats is not new. In a 1996 party convention,
rank-and-file members rewrote the rules to require previous
election to some government post as a prerequisite for PRI
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI simply could not endure one more technocrat,'' said
Enrique Krauze, a leading Mexican historian. ``The technocrats made
a fetish about having studied in Ivy League schools, as though that
guarantees sound political behavior, but this isn't so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They put Mexico in step with the trends of globalization and
the free market,'' he said. ``But they acted with too much haste
and in some cases tolerated corruption. This is a pity, because now
their policies are under attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The tensions between the technocrats and the traditional
politicians first emerged in the late 1970s under President Jose
Lopez Portillo, when the technocrats advocated more long-term
economic planning, while the politicians urged populist spending of
the country's oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Portillo followed the advice of the politicians until oil
prices crashed in 1981, forcing a peso devaluation. Then, when
choosing his successor under the Mexican tradition known as the
dedazo, or the tapping of the candidate, Lopez Portillo turned to
de la Madrid, his Harvard-trained budget minister.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute within the PRI over economic policies has continued
intermittently through three presidencies, during which the
technocrats have led Mexico into the North American Free Trade
Agreement, sold off state-owned industries, and eliminated many
government regulations. During the same period, the purchasing
power of the country's minimum wage has eroded to its lowest levels
in decades, according to government figures.
</P>
<P>
   The party split has also focused on how forcefully to resist
opposition parties' electoral advances. When de la Madrid took
office in 1982, the PRI controlled the Congress, and every state
governorship and legislature. Over the years since, opposition
parties have taken control of the Congress and the governments of
Mexico City and 10 of the 31 states.
</P>
<P>
   PRI hardliners who have urged a vigorous defense of the party's
long monopoly on power have been nicknamed dinosaurs because of
their apparent allegiance to a bygone era of authoritarian control.
All three technocrat presidents have ceded ground magnanimously to
the opposition early in their terms, but have switched to tougher
tactics later.
</P>
<P>
   Partly in an attempt to resolve the mounting rivalry between the
PRI's two wings, Zedillo earlier this year voluntarily relinquished
his right to select the PRI candidate. The party has scheduled its
first nationwide primary for Nov. 7 to pick the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Four men registered before a deadline expired last week. Three
are from the party's traditionalist wing. All four earned their
basic degrees at Mexico's National University.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, 46, studied law. He was elected to the Senate and
Congress and has held many senior party posts. He gained popularity
among PRI hard-liners by defying opposition leaders who criticized
his 1994 campaign for governor of Tabasco, when he spent tens of
millions of dollars, dozens of times the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Bartlett Diaz, 63, received a law degree from the
National University. He also has a Ph.D. from the University of
Victoria in England. He was elected governor of Puebla, a post he
held until January. Opposition parties accuse him of having
presided over a string of election frauds during his tenure as
Secretary of Interior under de la Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Humberto Roque Villanueva, 55, also has a law degree. He has
served as party president and as the head of the PRI's
congressional delegation. In that post he earned a reputation for
hard-line rhetoric, referring to the center-right and center-left
opposition parties, respectively, as ``fascists'' and
``dictators.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, 56, holds a Bachelor of Arts in economics from the
National University. He was elected governor of Sinaloa in 1986,
and has also served in the appointed posts of secretary of energy,
agriculture and interior. Since February, analysts have been
calling him the president's preferred candidate, although Zedillo
has never formally endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say he appears to be an intermediate figure between the
PRI's traditional politicians and the technocrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida is the best bridge between the PRI's two sectors
that Zedillo could find, because he understands the economy, and he
can also handle political questions,'' said Luis Rubio, a political
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Rubio and others said that Labastida emerged as the favorite
partly because three leading technocrats have resigned or fallen
from political favor during Zedillo's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Serra Puche (Yale, Ph. D., '79) resigned as Zedillo's
first finance secretary amid the peso devaluation in 1994. His
successor, Guillermo Ortiz Martinez (Stanford, Ph. D., '77) was
accused by the opposition of mishandling the $65 billion bank
bailout. Zedillo named him to head the central bank. Angel Gurria
Trevino (Harvard, course work, '75), who succeeded Ortiz as finance
minister, lost his temper last year under questioning by
congressional deputies during a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technocrats have been turned into mincemeat during this
presidency,'' said Jaime Sanchez Susarrey, a prominent newspaper
columnist based in Guadalajara.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
