<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7328 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEETING-PBS-KAN &LR;      06-23 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEETING-PBS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC COMMUNITY LEADERS HOLD TOWN MEETING ON VIOLENCE FOR PBS
CAMERAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With five cameras recording their every word
and movement, about 60 community leaders in Kansas City staged a
town hall meeting Tuesday night at the studios of KCPT, Channel 19.
</P>
<P>
   Their comments will air in edited form on a new PBS program this
fall on combating violence and hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeking Solutions,'' which will air in September, is produced
by Hedrick Smith, who served as moderator for the meeting. Smith is
a Pulitzer Prize-winning former correspondent for The New York
Times and author of several books.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is show courageous, compelling
examples of people coming up with solutions to violence in their
community,'' Smith said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said his researchers conducted interviews throughout
Kansas City, as well as Boston, Los Angeles, Dallas-Fort Worth,
Omaha, Neb., and other cities before deciding on the stories that
would be told in ``Seeking Solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those stories involves residents of the Blue Hills
neighborhood in Kansas City in their successful effort to shut down
drug houses. Before the taping, the group watched a 10-minute
segment on Blue Hills that was produced for the program.
</P>
<P>
   The segment concluded with Lillian Anderson, a Blue Hills
resident, saying: ``If you want your neighborhood back, you can get
it back. Remember, there is more of us than them.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith then interviewed selected members of the audience,
including councilman Alvin Brooks and Jim Nunnelly, administrator
of Jackson County's anti-drug COMBAT program.
</P>
<P>
   The Ewing Marion Kauffman Foundation of Kansas City is
underwriting $200,000 of the $1.5 million to produce ``Seeking
Solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's company has filmed segments in Kansas City for previous
documentaries. The 1994 series ``Challenge to America'' featured
students from Linden West Elementary School and Blue Springs High
School. The company also filmed at the General Motors Fairfax plant
in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
