<SLUG> BC-BOMB-SCARE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIEFCASE CAUSES BOMB SCARE ON A KANSAS CITY BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAWNA A. HAMEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A brown leather briefcase left on a bridge in
Kansas City Wednesday snarled morning rush-hour traffic for almost
90 minutes until a police robot opened it and found only papers.
</P>
<P>
   A motorist traveling southbound on Interstate 35 about 6:15 a.m.
called 911. He told police he had seen a man put down a briefcase
near the bridge's southbound lanes and walk away, said Sgt. Glen
Rumbaugh, supervisor of the Kansas City Police Department bomb and
arson unit.
</P>
<P>
   Police closed both southbound lanes and one northbound lane.
</P>
<P>
   Rumbaugh said that he was not aware of any bomb threats and that
police rarely shut down an entire bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portions of a bridge may be shut down for a person jumping or
an accident,'' he said, ``but not bombs, and not here.''
</P>
<P>
   The bomb unit's new $150,000 robot, Bob, checked out the
briefcase and then forced it open with a high-pressure shot of
water. It contained business papers.
</P>
<P>
   A Wichita, Kan., businessman staying at the Station Casino
called police early Wednesday and reported that his briefcase had
been stolen. Police said they thought the thief dropped it on the
bridge when he found nothing of value in it.
</P>
<P>
   Rumbaugh pointed out that bridges and public buildings ``have
become the targets of terrorists lately, and if what was in that
briefcase really was a bomb, it would have disrupted traffic in
Kansas City for months.''
</P>
<P>
   The 400-pound robot, which was bought this year with a federal
public safety grant, has helped police locate and defuse pipe bombs
and suspicious packages. It also can detect and contain hazardous
chemicals or biohazards such as anthrax or hydrochloric acid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was definitely no danger to any of the bomb technicians,
because Bob did all the work today,'' Rumbaugh said. ``But this
very easily, very easily, could have been an explosive device.
Especially now, at this time of year when all the fireworks are
available, who knows what it could have been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
