A7331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-COKE-NYT &LR;      06-23 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-COKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGIUM ENDS BAN ON COCA-COLA PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The Belgian health authorities ended a
10-day ban Wednesday on products of Coca-Cola Co., permitting it to
resume production in Belgium of sodas that were blamed for 249
cases of vomiting, cramps and other illnesses that shattered
European confidence in the world's best-known brand.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola welcomed the relaxation, promised a Coke giveaway here
in coming days, offered to pay the medical costs of anyone who
became ill and reiterated the company's contention that its sodas
are safe. But in a Continent riven by scares over the safety of
supermarket products ranging from genetically modified soybeans to
contaminated chicken, it remained doubtful that the heavyweight
public relations campaign by the company and its chief executive,
M. Douglas Ivester, had stilled Europe's mistrust. The Belgian
authorities said they still had not determined the exact cause of
the sickness that led to the biggest recall in Coca-Cola's 113-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Coca-Cola's problems appeared to worsen in France.
Belgian officials said a ban on imports of Coca-Cola products from
a plant in Dunkirk, France, would be maintained until the French
authorities had finished their inquiries into contamination there _
including unconfirmed reports that rat poison might have been the
cause. Some 28,000 Coca-Cola product vending-machines in Belgium
were also to remain out of action until checked for impurities.
</P>
<P>
   To end the ban, Coca-Cola agreed to five Belgian conditions
relating to cleanliness and safety standards. Ivester said that
production would resume immediately and that he expected Coca-Cola
products to be back in Belgian stores within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he announced plans to buy everyone in Belgium a Coke
and was photographed drinking from a bottle of Coke at a news
conference, questions persisted.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Van den Bossche, Belgium's interior minister who is also in
charge of public health, said at a news conference that Brussels
did not accept the Atlanta-based company's explanations for what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Van den Bossche also suggested that some people might have been
too quick to assume that Coca-Cola was the cause of their symptoms.
He called it ``an unintentional overreaction on the part of the
exposed persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite earlier indications that France might lift its ban on
Coca-Cola, Sprite and Fanta, the company's best-sellers in both
countries, French officials said the restrictions remained in
force. The outcome of a separate inspection of Coca-Cola plants in
Belgium by the European Union remained unclear, as did the future
of restrictions on Coca-Cola products in Luxembourg and the
Netherlands. Portugal, Italy, Spain and Germany are also conducting
investigations into scares relating to Coke.
</P>
<P>
   In a further twist, Van den Bossche disclosed Wednesday that
Belgium's investigation had been slowed by a previously secret
inquiry into whether the contamination of Coca-Cola products in
Belgium was linked to a murky extortion attempt last May in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The purported blackmailer, the Belgian minister said, threatened
to contaminate Coke if he was not paid ``several million marks.''
But inquiries established that ``there was no link between what
happened in Germany and what happened here,'' Van den Bossche said
at the news briefing, where he spoke from a table festooned with
small bottles of Coke _ a statement of public confidence in public
health marred only by his smoking of several cigarettes in front of
the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Van den Bossche took over the public health portfolio after the
Belgian government collapsed on June 13 in a scandal over the
contamination of animal feeds by the cancer-causing chemical dioxin
that led to the withdrawal of a wide array of poultry and meat.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's crisis began on June 7 when 30 schoolchildren
reported illnesses linked to drinking Coke with what Ivester, in
his first public appearance since the scare began, called an
``off-taste and an off-smell.''
</P>
<P>
   Van den Bossche said that the symptoms of the illnesses included
``stomach ache, dizziness, cramps, vomiting, nausea and in some
cases hyperventilation'' but that there was no clear pattern. Some
who became ill reported having drunk from bottles of Coke and
others from cans of Coke, sugar-free Coke and Fanta. The reports of
illness were spread among the towns of Bornem, Bruges, Harelbeke
and Lochristi.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian official said the company had highlighted two
problems _ contaminated carbon dioxide used at a bottling plant in
Antwerp and the contamination of the outside of cans transported on
wooden pallets. However, he said, there was no ``conclusive
evidence'' of a link between those problems and the symptoms
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most plausible hypothesis for explaining the problems that
have arisen over the past few weeks is the occurrence of an
accident during production or transport,'' Van den Bossche said. He
also said there was only a ``remote chance that the root causes of
these problems will ever occur again if the root causes of the
incident are taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   He listed five conditions for the resumption of Coca Cola
production: the use of fresh raw materials; thorough cleaning of
plants and installations; enhanced safety measures; the
introduction of a monitoring system for production, products and
complaints, and the ``removal and disposal'' of products that may
have been contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola plants in Antwerp and Ghent ``may resume production of
all Coca-Cola brands,'' he continued, while imports from the plant
in Dunkirk will remain banned pending French investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, appearing at a separate news conference in Brussels,
surrounded by security staff, translators and executives, reacted
to criticism that Coca-Cola was slow in responding to the crisis.
Asked if he would resign, he said he would not, and he said he had
maintained an initial public silence at the request of the Belgian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately set about promoting the messages Coca-Cola will
apparently use to restore confidence. ``Nothing is more important
than protecting the public health,'' he said. ``Our products are
completely safe, both in Belgium and worldwide.'' He dismissed the
reports of rat poison in Dunkirk as a rumor and said: ``It is
doubtful to me that that is an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say how much the European crisis had cost but
said the company had used an ``abundance of caution'' in responding
to it.
</P>
<P>
   He also said customers would be invited to return Coca-Cola
products to retailers for refunds. ``I think one of the first
things I'll do is buy everyone in Belgium a Coke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those people who got sick will be able to apply to have medical
expenses reimbursed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester also gave his first public explanation of the problem,
saying that sulfur used in the production of carbon dioxide _ the
source of the bubbles in sodas _ had not been cleansed as it should
have been. He acknowledged that since the company supplying the
carbon dioxide, Aga Gas of Sweden, had insisted that its supplies
were uncontaminated, ``it could have been something in the
handling'' that caused contamination. And he said wooden pallets
had been contaminated with creosote, contrary to company rules
forbidding its use.
</P>
<P>
   Several large Coca-Cola bottlers said Wednesday that the events
in Europe had had no effect on their business in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think generally people in the United States are not aware of
it,'' said Cookie Rice, a bottler in Springfield, Mo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
