<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QWEST-USWEST-FRONTIER     06-23 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-USWEST-FRONTIER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QWEST TO SWEETEN OFFERS FOR US WEST AND FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Qwest Communications International announced Wednesday that it
would sweeten its unsolicited offers for both US West, the smallest
of the regional Bell telephone companies, and Frontier Corp., one
of the nation's largest long-distance companies, only days after
both companies had spurned its advances.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Nacchio, Qwest's chief executive, said he was upping the
unsolicited offers the company made last week in an effort to bring
the already-betrothed companies to the bargaining table. Last
March, Frontier Corp. agreed to be acquired for $10.8 billion by
Global Crossing, Qwest's rival, which is also in the race to expand
telecommunications networks overseas. Global also agreed to merge
with US West last month in a deal valued then at $37 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both Qwest and Global are communications industry upstarts vying
for old-line phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Nacchio threatened to break up those mergers last week in a
hostile offer valued at $55 billion for the two companies. Qwest's
stock price dove 24 percent on June 14 after investors panned the
offer. In Qwest's revised bid, Nacchio proposed that Frontier
shareholders would get $20 in cash and $48 in Qwest stock if it
agreed to be acquired by Qwest; US West shareholders would get $69
in Qwest stock.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he said he was offering shareholders what the two
boards had hinted at wanting _ downside protection in case Qwest's
stock plummets further. Qwest has guaranteed those offers in stock
or cash as long as shares do not fall below $30.50. But that is not
much protection, given where Qwest's stock is currently trading.
Qwest's shares closed Wednesday at $32.5625, $2.75 less than
Tuesday's closing price but only 6.3 percent above $30.50.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Frontier shareholders would get $63 per share in
Global Crossing stock, and US West shareholders would get about $61
in stock based on Global's stock price Wednesday. That offer, too,
has downside protection in case Global's stock falls. But, unlike
Qwest's shares, Global's stock is currently trading well above the
bottom of that range. It closed Wednesday at $45.875, down $1.5625.
The Frontier deal is also expected to close in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have what Qwest and Global Crossing need to grow
_ cash and customers. The two-year-old Qwest has been around longer
and is further along in its plans to develop a global network than
is Global Crossing, which went public barely a year ago. Most of
Global's plans are still on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   But because US West and Frontier already have merger agreements
with Global, they are barred from talking to Qwest unless their
boards decide that Qwest's offer is ``superior.'' Both US West and
Frontier said they were in receipt of the revised Qwest proposals
and would review them.
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio sounded highly confident that his bid would win, despite
the criticism he has faced recently from analysts and shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to our shareholders,'' he said. ``I think it's time
for their boards to listen. If they've been honest about what their
concerns are, I see no reason why they wouldn't open the door and
let us in.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Nacchio's supporters maintain that the battle between
Qwest and Global is not personal, at times Nacchio sounded almost
defiant, as if he were challenging his upstart rival. When one
reporter asked if Nacchio would be interested in acquiring Global
Crossing for its international assets, for instance, he scoffed.
``Let's face it, all Global Crossing has is one cable under the
sea,'' he said. ``I don't need 200 employees and a couple of vice
chairmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio admitted Wednesday that when Qwest made the first offer
last week, executives had ``guessed wrong'' about what shareholders
and the board would be willing to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we been able to have a discussion, we could have crafted
this in a different way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What is now unclear is what steps the US West and Frontier
boards will take.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Burnett, president of Merger Insight, warned that in a deal
like this, with the stocks so volatile, it could still take many
weeks for a real winner to emerge. ``I think it brings him more to
a level playing field,'' said Burnett. ``But it's not a clear
enough overbid. It does demonstrate how determined Nacchio is and
that he's willing to stick around.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Global Crossing said it would not revise its
offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
