<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWO WIRELESS COMPANIES TO MERGE IN $3 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Voicestream Wireless and Omnipoint, two regional wireless
communications companies seeking to expand their national presence,
said they would merge in a cash and stock transaction valued at
nearly $3 billion. The merger will allow the new company to cover
much more of the country than either company could cover alone,
with licenses in 17 of the top 25 major markets.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN SACHS TOPS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Reporting its first quarterly results as a publicly traded
company, Goldman Sachs exceeded analysts' forecasts. With strength
in market trading and investment banking, Goldman posted
second-quarter earnings of $624 million, or $1.30 a share,
excluding one-time charges associated with its initial public
offering last month. That was up 30 percent from pro forma results
for a year earlier and well above analysts' estimates of $1.07.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED AS NASDAQ RISES
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed after some late buying lifted the main gauges
from their daily lows. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 54.77
points, to 10,666.86, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
declined 2.82 points, to 1,333.06. But the Nasdaq composite index
gained 17.86 points, to 2,598.12.
</P>
<P>
   SEC TO DISCUSS LATER TRADING
</P>
<P>
   In the discussions of when after-hours trading will come, one
thing is clear: Investors do not yet need to start burning the
midnight oil. The SEC plans an industry ``summit'' on the matter on
June 30. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL PRESIDENT OUSTS BANK BOARD
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso dismissed the
board of Banco do Estado de Sao Paulo, one of the largest
government-controlled banks, after it opposed an important tax.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT WARNING AT ADVANCED MICRO
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Devices said that it would report a
larger-than-expected second-quarter loss because of steep declines
in the price of microprocessor chips.
</P>
<P>
   LEHMAN CENSURED AND FINED
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers has been censured and fined $100,000 as part of
its settlement of regulatory charges that included an accusation
that it did not comply with market rules intended to provide public
investors with a fair share of ``hot'' initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   PENSION SHARE VALUATION IS UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has ruled that privately owned companies may use
different methods to value company shares that workers buy outright
and those that they purchase in a retirement plan. The case
involved Soundview Technology of Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK COMPILES TOP AD CAMPAIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Another entry in the Madison Avenue version of beauty pageants
arrives today as Random House publishes ``The 100 Best TV
Commercials ... And Why They Worked.'' The book is based on work by
Leo Burnett in Chicago, which in 1996 compiled a list of the top
100 spots. The book presents an updated version of the Burnett list
and includes spots such as the ``1984'' commercial for the Apple
Macintosh computer and the Energizer bunny.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT WITNESS GOT $250,000
</P>
<P>
   A witness for Microsoft in its antitrust trial disclosed during
cross-examination by a government lawyer that he was paid $250,000
for his testimony and related work.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT TO SELL EQUIPMENT TO LEVEL 3
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies agreed to sell up to $1 billion worth of
equipment to Level 3 Communications for transmitting phone calls
using Internet technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
