<HEADLINE>
QUOTATION OF THE DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: This quotation refers to BC-KOSOVO-BORDER-NYT, which moved
in ``i'' news file.) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's the Serbs who are guilty. We are glad the Serbs aren't
here anymore. May NATO live billions and billions of years.''
</P>
<P>
   _QERIM VORFAJ, whose house in Kosovo was destroyed by NATO
bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7345 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-WADDELL24-COX     06-23 1830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WADDELL24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waddell: `Things happen for a reason'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If there is no sense of intimidation as the
franchise's two most crucial days approach, it is because Don
Waddell believes that when you're in control, you have no reason to
be fearful. ``You're only afraid when there's things you have no
control over,'' he says, and drafts don't qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Thrashers' success in their inaugural NHL season
will hinge on an expansion draft Friday, and the future will be
tied in part to a selection of amateurs the following day. But
Waddell, the Thrashers' general manager, feels no uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Fear is when your father disappears, leaving your mother to
raise five children alone in a two-bedroom house in an open sore of
a neighborhood in Detroit. Fear is when a race-fueled riot erupts
in your high school, and somebody grabs you and shoves you in a
library safe for protection. Fear is when you have a gun held to
your head _ twice _ while working at a convenience store, or a
stick is jammed in your eye in a summer hockey league and it nearly
blinds you.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL club that won't recall you from the minors even though
you scored 95 points as a defenseman, the torn knee cartilage in a
pre-Olympic tournament that prevents you from playing on the most
famous U.S. hockey team in history _ those are things you can't
control.
</P>
<P>
   Not player drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, I've had some very high moments and very low
moments,'' Waddell said. ``But things happen for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell was hired as the general manager a year ago. His
unlikely evolution to that position started with a telephone call
in February 1987. He had played what he believed was his final
hockey game for the IHL's Toledo Goaldiggers the previous spring
and had gone into private business.
</P>
<P>
   Portable toilets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're in a start-up business, there's two things you
want to know: 'Can you afford it, and is there a need for it?' ''
Waddell said. The answer to both was yes. Waddell started with 50
units _ the official term _ and five years later the business had
grown to 1,500. He was flush with success.
</P>
<P>
   But everything happens for a reason. The phone call was from a
desperate general manager for the Flint Spirits. ``He says, `I need
you to play. I only have 11 players.' I said, `When's the game.' He
says, `Three o'clock.' Now, it's 11, and I'm two hours away. I hung
up the phone and I asked my wife, `Do you want to go to a hockey
game tonight?' She says, `Sure, where?' I said, `Flint. By the way
I'm playing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell grabbed his skates, which he hadn't worn for 10 months,
drove through for some fast food and headed to Michigan. ``As
they're playing the national anthem, I'm lacing up my skates,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the story goes: Flint convinces Waddell to stay on
for the remainder of the season (10 games), then come back the
following year as player/assistant coach, then stay for two more as
head coach and general manager. A hockey executive is born.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell went on to start an IHL expansion franchise in San Diego
and build a winner, leading to another job with Orlando, leading to
the assistant general manager's job with the Stanley Cup champion
Detroit Red Wings and a year later had his name engraved on the
trophy. It was a nice contrast to his playing days, which included
seven years in the minors, one in Europe and one lone NHL game _
with Los Angeles against the New York Rangers in 1980-81. On his
first shift, he got bumped by a teammate, and Ranger defenseman Ron
Greschner skated around him and scored.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ranger Tom Laidlaw, Waddell's college roommate, said,
``After the goal, Don sat down on the bench, then he went back to
the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell actually hung around with L.A. a few weeks but never
suited up and finally asked to be sent back to Saginaw. The
following year, he was named the IHL's best defenseman, with 26
goals and 69 assists. But the Kings never called.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep thinking you're going to get another chance down the
road,'' Waddell said. ``It probably didn't hit me until I was in my
30s when I thought, `Well, when you open the record books, my name
will be there. There's a lot of zeroes there, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell is thankful today he can read those zeroes. In 1984, he
returned to Detroit for the summer after playing in Germany.
Against his better judgment, he accepted a friend's invitation to
play in a summer hockey league. ``The guy begged me to play because
I was well-known in the area. The problem with those leagues is
there's always some guy who wants to make a name for himself by
taking a shot at somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   First game, first period. Waddell caught the butt-end of a stick
in his left eye. He suffered a fractured orbit, detached retina,
torn muscles and several cuts. He needed two major surgeries and
wore patches on both eyes for 20 days in the hospital. He was told
he would never play again, but was back on the ice five months
later.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if there were any lingering problems today, Waddell
joked, ``Yeah. I can't see the ice more than 100 feet in front of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has learned to deal with setbacks. As a player, in addition
to the eye injury, he came within weeks of playing on the 1980 U.S.
gold-medal team. He was a collegiate All-Star twice at Northern
Michigan University but broke a leg as a junior, again as a senior,
made the Olympic team anyway, then injured a knee just before the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 20 years old, you don't realize what a big part
that would play in U.S. hockey history. I was disappointed. But I
was happy for those players.''
</P>
<P>
   He watched the gold-medal clincher alone in his dorm room. ``I
cried a little, but it was happiness, not bitterness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Waddell, the person, has overcome more than injury. His
father, Tom, was gone most days, laying pipe for the gas company.
When Don, the fourth of five children, was 10, Tom left for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decided to leave his wife and kids and ran away with
another woman,'' Waddell said. ``Three hours after he leaves, he
gets into a car accident that kills the woman and leaves him
crippled. How's that for a story? You didn't know whether to feel
angry or sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Waddell worked two jobs to keep her children clothed,
fed and in hockey and Catholic school. Tom Waddell was an alcoholic
with permanent spinal damage and rarely had contact with the
family. Don once went five years without seeing him until Tom
surprisingly showed up one day at NMU Marquette.
</P>
<P>
   Some emotional wounds eventually healed, but Tom's health
worsened. Cancer struck in his throat and stomach. Chemotherapy
didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody showed up for dad's funeral,'' Waddell said. ``He
was 40-something years old living in a nursing home. But he looked
like he was 70.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell paused, then added, ``For all this to happen to me and
to be sitting here doing this, I'm fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell prefers not to say he was poor growing up. But put it
this way: When he was 12, a local hockey coach wanted him to play
for a traveling all-star team. ``He shows up and sees six of us
living in this two-bedroom house,'' Waddell said. ``We didn't have
what you would call upscale furniture. A week later, he sends my
mother a couch.''
</P>
<P>
   That house on Auburn Street is gone. It was torched one New
Year's Eve by rowdy parties, fortunately when nobody was in it.
Waddell: ``I was the happiest guy in the world because it forced
her to get out of the city.'' Everything happens for a reason. The
son helped purchase a new home.
</P>
<P>
   Living in the inner city had its dangers. Cody High School,
which Waddell attended for two years before transferring to Bishop
Borgess, was rife with racial tensions and the scene of a riot his
freshman year. ``I went to pick him up from school,'' Jacqueline
said, ``and there were five or six of us who were put in a safe
until the National Guard came.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline also remembers one time when the Open Pantry, where
Don was working, was held up and a gun was pointed at her son's
head. Waddell said it happened twice. Jacqueline: ``I'm sure he
didn't tell me everything.''
</P>
<P>
   He also didn't tell her about the 10 times a year he hitchhiked
450 miles from the Northern Michigan campus on the Upper Peninsula
to Detroit and back because his car couldn't make it that far.
Despite the transportation problems, Waddell excelled in hockey at
NMU _ he is a member of the school's sports hall of fame _ and
earned a degree in business.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers president Harvey Schiller said he was impressed that
Waddell ``had done everything in hockey from taping ankles to
driving the Zamboni,'' and it's not far from the truth. In San
Diego, he accepted a job as GM and was announced at a news
conference the same day, although he was informed just before
entering the room that the media expected an announcement on an NHL
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he mentioned the IHL at the press conference,'' Cheryl
said, ``you could sort of see everybody's shoulders kind of
slump.''
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference, the San Diego owner told Waddell that
the team had no offices and left town before ever telling him his
salary. A month passed before Waddell signed a contract. He didn't
hire a coach until a week before training camp. The next year, the
coach was fired in a cost-cutting move, and Waddell named himself
as replacement. But the Gulls did well, winning a record 62 games
in his third season. Waddell was named IHL Executive of the Year,
an achievement he duplicated in Orlando when his first-year Solar
Bears went to the league finals. That was enough for Detroit
general manager Ken Holland, who hired Waddell as his assistant a
year later.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he remained in relative obscurity until Schiller selected
him over NHL vice president Brian Burke, Dallas assistant Les
Jackson and others to head the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't bother me,'' Waddell said. ``My background makes
me believe if you do a good job, you'll be rewarded for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiller viewed him as a problem-solver. No wonder. Jacqueline
still remembers the time her car broke down on the way to work and
she called Don, then 16, for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a ride to work and asked Don if he could jump the car
with a friend,'' she said. ``When he showed up at work, he had his
car and my car. Know what he did? He started my car, drove it for
two blocks, got out, drove his car for two blocks, then my car,
then his. He must've done that for 2 1/2 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   It was never a problem. Don Waddell was in control.
</P>
<P>
   DON WADDELL FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Position: General manager of Atlanta Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: Aug. 19, 1958, Oakville, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 40.
</P>
<P>
   _ Education: Bachelor's degree, business management, Northern
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family: Wife Cheryl and daughter Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
