<SLUG> BC-RUN-SPRINTERS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confident Jones sets lofty goals: 5 golds
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ It's not enough that she's been ordained the best
sprinter of her era. It's not enough that her style is so
distinctive that it can be spotted on any track, her torso as erect
as a drill sergeant's, a gold chain bounding from her neck, her
thick thighs concealed under a conservative one-piece lycra outfit
and cycling shorts. It's not enough that she has charisma Michael
Johnson would die for, a stage presence and a smile that Nike will
milk through the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Marion Jones just has to go where no track athlete, man or
woman, has ever gone _ winning five gold medals in an Olympic
Games. To her, it is hardly an impossible dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five gold medals is not just talk,'' Jones said confidently.
``It's possible. If any athlete can do it, it's myself. I was born
with a lot of talent, but I'm also a hard worker. I love to be on
top.''
</P>
<P>
   In the insular world of track and field, Jones' potential has
never been a secret. She was a schoolgirl record-breaker in the 200
before taking leave to play point guard for the North Carolina
basketball team. Then last year, her second full season on the
track circuit, Jones ended with a No. 1 world ranking in the 100
and 200 meters and the long jump. She became the first American to
reign over three events in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Later this summer, she is expected to win gold in all three
individual events, plus gold for a leg on the 400-meter relay, in
the World Championships in Seville, Spain. In Sydney next year, the
grand design calls for her also to run a leg on the 1,600 relay.
</P>
<P>
   Can she go 5-for-5 on the Olympic stage? Perhaps, if she doesn't
stumble in the long jump, where her technique lags considerably
behind her speed.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast, some say.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is more than a year off. Injuries can flare up. Fresh
stars might rise or old stars reappear.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the rush to coronate a new queen is Gail Devers, 32,
two-time defending Olympic 100-meter champion and a hurdler who is
not about to step aside. She hasn't been heard from lately, sitting
out to nurse a hamstring injury while Jones won 35 of 36 finals
last year and dropped her 100 time to 10.65 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But Devers is back, keenly aware that her new challenger has
raised the level of competition beyond what she faced from Merlene
Ottey and Gwen Torrence in the last two Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not driven by other people's goals,'' said Devers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, however, would welcome a rival, someone to push her
closer to world records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of sad last year because she had the injuries, but
if Gail's in a race, I know I'm going to up my performance and run
faster,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The stars will not collide when the U.S. Track and Field
Championships begin today with heats in the 100 meters. The meet
serves as a qualifier to the World Championships, and Jones has
elected to skip the 100 and accept a pass into the worlds as
defending champion there. This week, she'll look to qualify for the
worlds in the 200 and long jump, while Devers competes in the 100
dash and 100 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of amassing five golds in Sydney is immense. Carl
Lewis (1984) and Jesse Owens (1936) never won more than four in a
single Games. Florence Griffith Joyner won three in 1988. Michael
Johnson, the standout in Atlanta, won a pair.
</P>
<P>
   The chance to run for Olympic glory and gold never has been
closer, and Jones is praying she doesn't miss out again: ``My main
goal is to stay healthy and bring home W's.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
