<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Malaise of violence spreads in Brazil
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Where have you gone, Pele?
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's soccer king, taking in the opening weekend of the
Women's World Cup in the United States, missed the raucous finale
to the Paulista league that served as an ugly reminder of the mess
that is domestic soccer in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's former sports minister was castigated by the soccer
establishment for pushing through anti-corruption reforms, but
Pele's worst fears about the state of the game _ those on the
field, anyway _ were borne out in the finals of his home state of
Sao Paulo on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A full-fledged brawl between Palmeiras and Corinthians resulted
in the match being abandoned in the second half with the score even
at 2-2. Corinthians, which led 5-2 on aggregate, was awarded the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was sparked by Corinthians forward Edilson, who scored
the game-tying goal in the 76th minute. A few moments later, he
received a pass and instead of attacking, he tauntingly juggled the
ball with his feet, off his chest and down his back. That prompted
Palmeiras players Junior, Paulo Nunes and Zinho to charge him,
literally kicking and screaming. Both teams rushed the field,
trading punches and kicks, and Edilson soon raced to the dressing
room. In perhaps the most gruesome scene, Palmeiras striker Oseas
was seen fighting with a Corinthians ball boy.
</P>
<P>
   Tostao, Pele's teammate on Brazil's legendary 1970 World Cup
championship team, wrote in a syndicated newspaper column that
soccer in Brazil is ``the most violent in the world.... Players and
coaches disrespect each other on the field, while referees and
their assistants are under enormous pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad blood between Palmeiras and Corinthians has existed for
years. Palmeiras, which won the South American club championship
last week over Deportivo Cali of Colombia, decided not to contest
the Paulista outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We apologize for everything that has happened,'' Palmeiras
coach Luis Felipe Scolari said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Edilson was dropped from Brazil's Copa America roster
by coach Wanderley Luxemburgo, who said he didn't like the player's
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Brazil, Flamengo defeated Vasco de Gama 1-0 Sunday
to win the Carioca championship, for Rio de Janeiro state, by a 2-1
aggregate.
</P>
<P>
   Schmeichel goes to Portugal
</P>
<P>
   Former Manchester United goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel, has signed
with Sporting Lisbon after eight years in England. Terms were
undisclosed.... Barcelona unloaded unproductive Brazilian forward
Sonny Anderson to Olympique Lyon for a French record $20 million
and picked up Dani from Mallorca for $15.5 million.... Mallorca,
the Cup Winners' Cup finalists, sold striker Marcelino to Newcastle
in a four-year, $9.32 million deal.... French World Cup captain
Didier Deschamps has signed with Chelsea for $4.77 million over
three years.... Defender Giuseppe Bergomi has been released by
Inter Milan after 22 years with the club.... German libero Lothar
Matthaus said Tuesday he will leave Bayern Munich in March to join
the New York/New Jersey MetroStars of Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia: Arkan stashes cash
</P>
<P>
   As the president of Yugoslav first division team FC Obilic,
Zeljko Raznatovic apparently personally pocketed the $2 million the
club received for the transfer of star player Ivan Vukomanovic to
French champion Girondins de Bordeaux. The fact that Raznatovic is
more commonly known as the Serbian Arkan who is under a war crimes
indictment has raised more than a few eyebrows but has resulted in
no action thus far from European soccer authorities. Bosman
backlash?
</P>
<P>
   Responding to concerns about spiraling transfer fees, UEFA
president Gerard Aigner said in a German interview last week that
he supports limits on the number of foreigners in European domestic
leagues. Aigner, speaking to Kicker magazine, agreed with FIFA
president Sepp Blatter that a minimum of six homegrown players
should be fielded in league games. The ceiling is in direct
contrast to the Bosman Ruling of 1995, when the European Court
banished nationality restrictions for players from European Union
countries. Expect more legal wrangling to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
