<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JUNE 24
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-Y2K-POLL-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 20,
about a poll of corporate managers involved in Year 2000 computer
projects misstated the position of Gary Beach of CIO Magazine,
which was a sponsor of the poll. He is the magazine's publisher,
not its editor.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ONLINE-OUTAGES-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 20,
about technical challenges facing Internet commerce misstated the
extent of a 14-hour service interruption at Intuit Inc.'s Turbo Tax
site on April 12. It affected only the site's electronic filing
function, not its tax preparation service.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HALAL-BUTCHERS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 1,
about halal meat shops referred incorrectly to the rules of food
preparation they follow. Islamic law, which shares some common
ground with the Jewish dietary laws of kashruth, forbids the
consumption of meat from some cloven-foot animals but not others.
It forbids pork, for example, but allows consumption of beef, lamb
and goat. The article also referred incorrectly to a Queens street
where halal stores are clustered. It is Main Street. (Ocean Parkway
is in Brooklyn.)
</P>
</TEXT>
