<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-FRANCE24-COX     06-23 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-FRANCE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    France officials check reports that rat poison caused Coke
illnesses
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It was supposed to be the day when Coca-Cola's troubles
in France ended.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the health scare over the company's beverages took an
odd twist Wednesday amid reports that rat poison may have caused
some illnesses among consumers who drank Coke products from a plant
in Dunkirk.
</P>
<P>
   French prosecutors confirmed that they have opened a judicial
investigation, following a Le Monde newspaper report that the
government was examining the possibility of another contaminant.
One prosecutor, Francois Muguet, said rat poison was detected on
the outside of one soft-drink can at the Dunkirk plant, but no link
to illnesses had been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Jean-Yves Naouri told Reuters that recent
government tests on the company's brands included a look at rat
poison and ``all of those tests came back negative.''
</P>
<P>
   The top executive of Coca-Cola said he was ``very doubtful''
that the substance caused any illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that with any situation that's getting a lot of media
attention, there's a number of rumors that take place,'' Chairman
M. Douglas Ivester said Wednesday while in Brussels, Belgium,
dealing with the soft drink crisis there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work through the government officials on any reported
rumor, and we will chase any of those down. I have not heard that
particular rumor, but certainly if it is reported to us, we will
follow through on it,'' Ivester said. ``It is very doubtful to me
that that's an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has maintained that the source of illnesses linked to
the Dunkirk plant, which is owned by Atlanta-based Coca-Cola
Enterprises, was fumes from the outside bottom of cans. The cans
were transported in wooden pallets that had been treated with a
fungicide.
</P>
<P>
   Le Monde quoted French health and food specialists as saying
that similar food-contamination cases occurred at this time last
year, because it's the period when companies routinely step up
their use of pest control for spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the judicial probe, which was opened Monday,
came as French health officials were poised to lift the partial ban
on the sale of Coca-Cola products from the Dunkirk plant.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific tests conducted last weekend on Coke beverages from
the plant found no contamination. But the results were forwarded to
the French Food Safety Agency, which will make a final
determination.
</P>
<P>
   French Health Minister Bernard Kouchner has also said that
health inspectors have found no relation between illnesses and the
Dunkirk products. Like the results of a study commissioned by
Coca-Cola, he suggested the health complaints could be
psychosomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
