<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-MAIN24-COX     06-23 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ban on Coke lifted, but probe continues
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Coca-Cola today begins scrambling to get its
soft drinks back on supermarket shelves here, even as health
officials remain baffled over why nearly 250 people became sick
after drinking the company's brands.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days after restricting the sale of Coke products, Belgian
officials Wednesday cleared the way for the company to get back in
the marketplace. Coca-Cola estimates it will take two weeks to get
in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   M. Douglas Ivester, the company's chairman and chief executive
officer, wasted no time in seeking to regain the faith of Belgian
consumers, who have been among Europe's most dedicated Coke
drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the calls to Coca-Cola's toll-free hotline in
Brussels have been demands for the return of their favorite soft
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, we let the people of Belgium down,'' Ivester
told reporters at a news conference at the expansive Palais de
Congress. ``We are sorry for that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Health Minister Luc Van den Bossche announced his decision to
end restrictions on the sale of Coca-Cola's leading brands, he
expressed frustration that scientists have been unable to pinpoint
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Coke products have been tested for 15,000 toxic substances, yet
the government says nothing has been found to explain why first
children and then adults experienced nausea, dizziness and vomiting
after drinking them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know with certainty the cause,'' Van den Bossche told
reporters. ``We're taking a risk, that's true, but not a big
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   To minimize this risk, Van den Bossche is requiring the soft
drink giant to destroy its existing stock, start over with fresh
ingredients, clean its plants and put procedures in place to make
sure there is no repeat of these incidents. Coke immediately
accepted these conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, reporters took Van den Bossche to task for lifting the
restrictions before clearly identifying the source of the
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the table in a government building from which he
issued his statement also was adorned with a dozen Coke bottles,
raising the suspicions of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Van den Bossche, who chain-smoked throughout his news
conference, insisted that he didn't cave in to the American giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't negotiate,'' he snapped, stressing that he set the
terms for Coke's return to grace.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Ivester's lieutenants for days have been frustrated
to the point of anger by what they considered to be Van den
Bossche's imperious style of dealing with them, the chairman heaped
praise on the minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the minister's obligation to the people in these
times of deep sensitivity regarding public health issues here,'' he
said, indirectly referring to a scare over the discovery that some
Belgian meat had been exposed to the cancer-causing substance
dioxin. ``Nothing _ I repeat, nothing _ is more important than
protecting the public health.''
</P>
<P>
   The dioxin scare has been sufficient here to cause the ouster of
the government in national elections held this month.
</P>
<P>
   A new start
</P>
<P>
   Today, Coca-Cola will begin destroying soft drinks it has
stockpiled and any returned for a refund by consumers. Coke
executives said they did not know how much of the company's product
must be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Ivester seemed relaxed and even took a
gulp from the open glass bottle Coke placed on his rostrum when
prompted by a TV reporter.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual unknown here a week ago, the chairman has become a
familiar face during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he appeared in full-page ads nationwide bearing his
personal message of contrition and reassurance. Wednesday night,
there he was again in 90-second commercials aired after news
broadcasts that also showed him at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the world's largest soft drink company said Coke
executives had met more than 25 times with the government over the
past few days trying to find a resolution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Coke has said the illnesses were caused by small amounts of a
contaminant in the carbon dioxide used to carbonate drinks at its
Antwerp, Belgium, plant and when a fungicide used to treat wood
pallets at its Dunkirk, France, plant got on the exterior of cans.
Both plants are owned by Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises, the
largest soft drink bottler in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the government's scientists and the toxicologists
commissioned by Coke determined that these substances were present
in amounts too small to account for the illnesses, Ivester said he
was satisfied that the symptoms were caused by the ``off smell and
off taste'' caused by these substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have presented an abundance of scientific data,''
he said. ``We served millions of drinks every day in Belgium. We
have very stringent quality control procedures in place, and in
this case a couple of our quality control procedures broke down.
... Our products are completely safe, both in Belgium and
worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   However, lawsuits already are in the works. The director of St.
Mary's School near Antwerp has reportedly taken initial steps to
sue Coke. Odilon Hermans, the school's director, told The
Associated Press that four students who drank Coke two weeks ago
are still too sick to return to classes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 280 students at his school, 39 became sick after drinking
Coke products, and 15 spent a night in the hospital, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government left in place a ban on Coca-Cola products from
the company's Dunkirk, France, bottling plant until French
authorities cleared production there.
</P>
<P>
   It also will maintain a ban on Coca-Cola vending machines in
Belgium. Ivester said that problems were found with 20 of the
company's 28,000 vending machines here, but the company would empty
all, inspect them and restock them, a process expected to take a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machine sales provide some of the highest profit margins
in the Coke system.
</P>
<P>
   Van den Bossche said the Coca-Cola issue had become more
complicated when he was informed that there had been an extortion
attempt linked to Coca-Cola in Germany during the second week of
May. A ransom payment of several million marks had been demanded on
May 18, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation by Belgian authorities, he is satisfied
that there is no connection with the situation in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
