largest soft drink bottler in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the government's scientists and the toxicologists
commissioned by Coke determined that these substances were present
in amounts too small to account for the illnesses, Ivester said he
was satisfied that the symptoms were caused by the ``off smell and
off taste'' caused by these substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have presented an abundance of scientific data,''
he said. ``We served millions of drinks every day in Belgium. We
have very stringent quality control procedures in place, and in
this case a couple of our quality control procedures broke down.
... Our products are completely safe, both in Belgium and
worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   However, lawsuits already are in the works. The director of St.
Mary's School near Antwerp has reportedly taken initial steps to
sue Coke. Odilon Hermans, the school's director, told The
Associated Press that four students who drank Coke two weeks ago
are still too sick to return to classes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 280 students at his school, 39 became sick after drinking
Coke products, and 15 spent a night in the hospital, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government left in place a ban on Coca-Cola products from
the company's Dunkirk, France, bottling plant until French
authorities cleared production there.
</P>
<P>
   It also will maintain a ban on Coca-Cola vending machines in
Belgium. Ivester said that problems were found with 20 of the
company's 28,000 vending machines here, but the company would empty
all, inspect them and restock them, a process expected to take a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machine sales provide some of the highest profit margins
in the Coke system.
</P>
<P>
   Van den Bossche said the Coca-Cola issue had become more
complicated when he was informed that there had been an extortion
attempt linked to Coca-Cola in Germany during the second week of
May. A ransom payment of several million marks had been demanded on
May 18, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation by Belgian authorities, he is satisfied
that there is no connection with the situation in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
