<HEADER>
A7362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-JURY-BOS &LR;      06-23 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-JURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS JURY SAYS IT CAN'T DECIDE IN CASE AGAINST CARDIOLOGIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The jury in the Reggie Lewis medical malpractice case
says it is unable to reach a verdict as to whether Lewis's chief
cardiologist, Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., was negligent in diagnosing
and treating the heart condition that killed the Celtics star.
</P>
<P>
   But the 15 jurors reported to Superior Judge Thayer
Fremont-Smith late Wednesday that they had reached verdicts on the
two other cardiologists sued for malpractice by Lewis's widow.
</P>
<P>
   Those verdicts, involving consulting cardiologists Peter L.
Friedman and Mark A. Creager, will remain secret until the jury
either resolves its deadlock on Mudge's liability or convinces
Fremont-Smith that it is unable to agree on a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Fremont-Smith Thursday morning will read the jurors additional
instructions aimed at reaching a verdict on Mudge, after which the
panel will resume deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the partial verdicts on Friedman and Creager
and the disagreement over Mudge's negligence followed 32 hours of
deliberation over five days.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Friedman and Creager had worked to portray their
clients as minor players who were asked by Mudge to consult on the
case but who had no direct role in Lewis's diagnosis or treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Exiting the courtroom, attorneys for the three doctors declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the jury must resolve three basic issues: whether
Mudge, Friedman, and Creager provided Lewis with negligent medical
care; whether such negligence contributed substantially to the
player's death; and, if it did, how much money Lewis's wife and two
children should receive as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the 15 jurors must agree in order to reach a verdict
on each of 16 questions. Ten of those questions are to be answered
only if the jury finds that negligence by any or all of the doctors
contributed to Lewis's death, and are aimed at determining the
amount of damages Donna Harris-Lewis and her children should
receive.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to Fremont-Smith by the jury foreman shortly
before 8 p.m., the panel reported that it had ``come to a decision
on questions three and five,'' which ask whether Friedman and
Creager provided negligent medical care to the former Celtics
captain.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which was read aloud in the jury's presence in a
Suffolk Superior courtroom, also said that ``at this time we have
come to a decision that the jury is deadlocked'' on question one,
which asks whether Mudge provided negligent medical care. ``We
await your instructions,'' the letter concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``probably everybody's pretty tired,'' Fremont-Smith
asked the jurors to continue deliberating this morning, for a sixth
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, tomorrow, after further due deliberations, you find
yourselves still deadlocked,'' he continued, ``then I will take at
that time your verdicts'' regarding Friedman and Creager.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis has accused the three cardiologists of failing to
diagnose her husband with a life-threatening heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth cardiolgist, Dr. John D. Rutherford, now in practice in
Texas, settled out of court with Harris-Lewis in April, on the day
that jury selection began. Details of the settlement have not been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors' lawyers have argued that the player's death was
caused by his failure to follow doctor's orders to avoid strenuous
exercise. They also contend that Mudge was unable to accurately
diagnose Lewis because the player did not tell him that he had used
cocaine until two weeks before he died.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis vehemently denied that her husband used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis collapsed and died of heart failure while shooting baskets
at Brandeis University on July 27, 1993, 11 weeks after he had been
discharged from Brigham and Women's Hospital by Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and his wife had sought out Mudge after a group of leading
cardiologists dubbed the Dream Team had diagnosed Lewis with a
serious heart problem that could end his career.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge reached a far different conclusion, announcing at a May
1993 news conference that Lewis had a benign fainting disorder, not
a life-threatening heart condition. With monitoring and drug
treatment, Mudge said, Lewis would be able to resume his basketball
career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
