<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      06-23 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS STALL SENATE TO FORCE DEBATE ON HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.D., Idaho, Okla., Ga., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate was paralyzed for a third straight day
Wednesday as Democrats pressed for immediate consideration of
legislation to define patients' rights within their health
insurance plans. Republicans rejected the Democrats' timetable and
terms, and leaders from both parties sought in vain to devise a way
around the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats continued to block action on an agriculture spending
bill _ and threatened to similarly impede any other legislation _
until they got a solid promise of a full-fledged debate, within the
next few weeks, on new regulations for health maintenance
organizations and medical insurers.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans refused to grant Democrats the conditions they
sought for that discussion, and as hour upon hour of negotiations
failed to yield any agreement, the Senate was left in a surreal
state of suspended animation, with the empty time being eaten up by
hourly or even twice-hourly attendance calls.
</P>
<P>
   The tense standoff was a sign of just how contentious the
subject of HMOs and insurance companies was shaping up to be, not
just in the Senate but also in the House. The impasse also showed
that both parties had come to see the political stakes surrounding
the issue, which directly affects scores of millions of Americans,
as extremely high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get votes,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the minority
leader, referring to 20 amendments Democrats want to add to the
Republican health care bill that would be the starting point of any
floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either that, or we'll sit on the Senate floor looking at
each other,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans questioned the disruptive parliamentary methods
Democrats were using to achieve their goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure you get there by punching American farmers in the
face,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   In a strict party-line vote, a Senate committee approved a
Republican bill in March, but there is no firm date for its
consideration on the floor. Democrats say that the bill's
protections for patients are feeble and few. They are convinced
that if they can introduce all their amendments and force a
point-by-point dissection of the bill's provisions, they can
embarrass Republicans and lure some of them to vote with Democrats
on aspects of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been emboldened in that thinking by the Senate's
debate over gun control, in which close examination of some
Republican proposals forced Republicans to retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are trying to prevent that approach. In part, they
seem to sense that certain Democratic provisions will play better
in the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want our members to go through a lot of votes that can
be misconstrued for political purposes,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of
Oklahoma, the Republican whip.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Republican bill and the Democratic proposal, rival
versions of which have come to be known as a patients' bill of
rights, address Americans' fears that HMOs and insurers are placing
a zest for profits above a concern for patients.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals of both parties create processes by which patients
can appeal treatment decisions to external arbiters. But
significant portions of the Republicans' plan apply only to about
48 million Americans in health care plans not regulated by the
states, while the Democratic proposal would affect about triple
that number of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal also gives a patient's primary doctor
more discretion in determining the medical necessity of a treatment
and removes current hurdles that prevent many patients in HMOs from
suing the organizations for botched decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the Democratic plan involves too much federal
meddling in matters best governed by states and will drive up
costs, prompting employers to diminish the number of people to whom
they offer medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that Democrats were doing the bidding of trial
lawyers, who contribute heavily to the Democratic party. Democrats,
in turn, said that Republicans were the marionettes of large
corporations and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the House Wednesday, 167 Democrats put their names on a
petition to force consideration of the Democrats' managed-care
proposal in the chamber. Speaker J. Dennis Hastert has pledged a
debate and votes this summer on a proposal by House Republicans,
but Democrats do not like it.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats would need 218 signatures to succeed and there
are only 211 Democrats in the House. Even so, the issue is a tricky
one for Republican leaders, who must remain aware that last year,
when Democrats held five fewer seats, the Democratic proposal was
defeated by only six votes, 216-210.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a compromise proposed by Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., has
a number of supporters and more closely resembles the Democratic
position.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Senate Republicans offered Democrats a four-day
debate in mid-July, but Democrats held out for an explicit
guarantee that they could present all of their amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they haven't got an alternative,'' said Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., noting that the chamber was at a standstill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
