<HEADER>
A7365 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-THEATER-ART-2TAKE     06-23 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PLACE SEX IS SELDOM TAKEN SERIOUSLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Sylviane Gold, who reviews dance for Newsday, has been a theater
critic for The Wall Street Journal and other publications.  
 By SYLVIANE GOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sex may mean a great deal in our lives. But somehow
it doesn't count for very much in our drama. No, I have not
forgotten about the stacks and stacks of plays whose plots turn on
romance, or on adultery or incest, or the newer ones that work gay
or feminist changes on these well-worn themes.
</P>
<P>
   Western theater is peopled with distinctly sexual characters:
Oedipus, Gertrude, Camille, Willy Loman. But the plays they appear
in are not primarily about sex. Plays _ serious mainstream works by
serious writers that shed light on the role of sex in the human
drama _ are actually few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   This curious fact was underlined this past season not just by
the grim, long-running sex farce in Washington but by the unusual
presence of two plays on Broadway that (italics)did(end italics)
take on this big subject. In a culture in which sex looms as a
major presence in everything from music videos to painting, from
novels to advertising, Patrick Marber's ``Closer,'' running at the
Music Box Theater, and David Hare's ``Blue Room,'' which closed
this winter after a sold-out run at the Cort, stand out as the sole
explorations of sex in what was widely hailed as Broadway's season
of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Scanning the past for similar plays with similar themes will
yield very few examples. Trying to remember how our best
playwrights have handled the subject brings the realization that
either, like Lanford Wilson and Tony Kushner, they haven't really
devoted entire plays to it or, like Tom Stoppard and Caryl
Churchill, they've treated it comically.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes playwrights appear to be writing about sex _ Peter
Shaffer in ``Equus,'' David Rabe in ``Hurlyburly,'' David Henry
Hwang in ``M. Butterfly'' _ but are in fact using sex to pursue
other themes (creativity, male hubris and cultural imperialism,
respectively).
</P>
<P>
   In Alan Ayckbourn's ``Communicating Doors'' last year,
Mary-Louise Parker played a prostitute in black leather; the play
had numerous strategically placed doors, like a sex farce. But it
was actually a metaphysical meditation on the permeability of time.
</P>
<P>
   Hare's play is an adaptation of Arthur Schnitzler's ``Reigen,''
which follows a chain of sexual encounters in turn-of-the-century
Vienna and which Schnitzler considered too obscene to produce.
(It's more familiar to us as ``La Ronde,'' thanks to Max Ophuls's
film version.)
</P>
<P>
   Hare borrows Schnitzler's pleasingly straightforward scheme of
changing one sexual partner in each scene until, after 10
couplings, we end with the same streetwalker who began the chain.
Not one of the couples, not even the husband and wife who dally
with each other between their dalliances elsewhere, could even
remotely be described as in love.
</P>
<P>
   Hare's concern here is not romance or even physical release.
With the exception of the streetwalker, for whom sex is a living,
the characters in ``The Blue Room'' use sex as an escape route, a
temporary, mechanical respite from routine, like a coffee break.
</P>
<P>
   For the four people Marber examines in ``Closer,'' sex is not
quite so casual. Sex has an urgency and import that makes them
desperate. Not for them the old saw that all's fair in love and
war; for them, sex and war are identical. And they fight on two
fronts: to win the object of their desires and to humiliate the
competition. Sex is not a sublime pleasure but a supreme weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Love 'em or hate 'em, and there are critics in both camps.
``Closer'' and ``The Blue Room'' can be shocking in their
preoccupation with their characters' libidos. Indeed, these
characters (italics)are(end italics) their sex lives. Unlike so
many contemporary plays that include sexual interludes and frank
dialogue but really care more about other matters, these plays
would make no sense without the sex scenes and the sex talk.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Brantley classed them with last season's Off Broadway
production ``Shopping and ... ,'' Mark Ravenhill's look at the
sexual preoccupations of a pair of nihilistic drug addicts, as
anti-romantic comedies about the joylessness of sex.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the reams of propaganda that have emanated over the
last four decades from Hugh Hefner and Dr. Ruth and the whole ``Joy
of Sex'' industry, it's interesting that playwrights who do bother
to look at sex see it rather differently. Perhaps Tolstoy's maxim
about happy families applies as well to happy sex; maybe it's just
too boring to write about.
</P>
<P>
   Writers who (italics)have(end italics) dramatized stories that
pivot on the sexual natures of their characters _ Paula Vogel in
``How I Learned to Drive'' and Christopher Hampton in ``Les
Liaisons Dangereuses'' _ don't draw a pretty picture. Even when sex
is used by playwrights to amuse, as in farces and musicals, it
tends to be seen as a chaotic and destructive element in life
rather than a wholesome one.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only way to write a play in which sex is the
dominant theme is to create characters whose libidos dominate their
personalities _ monsters, by definition. Christopher Durang's ``Sex
and Longing,'' one of the few American sex comedies, took as its
main character a nymphomaniac who needed sex every 15 minutes;
critics were not amused.
</P>
<P>
   A play like Caryl Churchill's ``Cloud Nine'' (1979), in which
sex is at once funny, serious and good for you, is a real rarity.
</P>
<P>
   There have been periods in theater history, of course, when sex
was on the front burner: Jacobean playwrights like John Ford hung
bloody revenge plots on it and Restoration writers made witty sport
of it. But it shouldn't really surprise anyone that when Noel
Coward and George Bernard Shaw and Eugene O'Neill brought sex into
their plays, they did it in a gingerly way: they were writing for
audiences that didn't talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   When Mae West starred in her 1926 play about a prostitute,
``Sex,'' she spent 10 days in jail for her efforts. What
(italics)should(end italics) surprise is that the theater of our
own time seems not to have thoroughly assimilated the changes of
the late '60s and early '70s that transformed the rest of the
culture.
</P>
<P>
   This was the period that saw songwriters trade in
June-moon-spoon lyrics for ``Voulez-vous coucher avec moi ce
soir?'' It saw bedroom scenes become de rigueur in movies made for
grown-ups. After ``Lady Chatterley's Lover'' was ruled not obscene
by a federal appeals court in 1960, novels were free to enter the
bedroom in explicit detail, and ``Portnoy's Complaint'' did away
with any remaining taboos in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
