<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7367 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-THEATER-ART-2NDTA     06-23 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-THEATER-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in 1969.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As early as the '30s, modern dance choreographers had been
putting pelvic thrusts and grinds on stage, and by the '60s and
'70s, choreographers were routinely representing sex acts.
</P>
<P>
   When Kenneth Tynan devised ``Oh! Calcutta!'' in 1969, it was
meant to blast through the hypocrisy and shame that had kept this
crucial part of life off the stage for so long. Although it was
just a collection of skits, and mediocre ones at that, it was
nonetheless seen at the time as a breakthrough. (When the 1976
revival closed in 1989, the New York Times critic Frank Rich
checked out the final performance and found it ``antediluvian.'')
</P>
<P>
   But all that came of ``Oh! Calcutta!'' was a slew of ripoffs.
Who remembers ``The Dirtiest Show in Town''?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the cultural ferment of the period had
no effect at all on serious theater. Downtown experimenters like
Richard Schechner, Charles Ludlam and Richard Foreman made
audiences ready for anything. Iconoclastic young playwrights like
Terrence McNally, Sam Shepard and Leonard Melfi depicted sexual
situations and used sexual language that paved the way for a play
about an incestuous child molester, like Ms. Vogel's ``How I
Learned to Drive,'' which would have been unimaginable in the
1950s. (And the odds on its winning a Pulitzer Prize would have
been very long indeed, even in the '60s and '70s.)
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Vogel is an exception. Most dramatists took advantage of
the looser language and the fewer costumes rather than reaching for
the more daring subject matter made available by the sexual
revolution. A single David Mamet play probably contains more
obscenities than Alexander Woollcott heard in a lifetime of
theatergoing. And nudity no longer surprises anyone; it's even in a
play about a John Donne scholar, for heaven's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you probably have to go back to 1987, when the Royal
Shakespeare Company production of ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses''
arrived in New York, to find Broadway characters like those in the
plays of Hare and Marber, characters whose personalities are
expressed entirely through their sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   The relative absence of such characters from our stages, both on
Broadway and off, is peculiar for many reasons, not the least being
that theater itself springs from fertility rites. The first
theatrical performance may well have been a crude and lewd
representation of the sex act in some tribal ritual, and European
theater traces its roots to Dionysian festivals in ancient Greece,
with actors cavorting in abbreviated tunics and leather phalluses.
</P>
<P>
   Such entertainments didn't meet with the approval of the early
Christians, of course, and soon the form itself disappeared in
Europe. Given that theater next developed as a vehicle for
conveying the Gospel, it's little wonder that erotic elements were
not as prevalent as they were in the arts of the East.
</P>
<P>
   And while Western playwrights have found ways even in less
liberal periods to indicate that sex can be a driving force in
human destiny (think of Shakespeare's Othello, Racine's Phedre,
Strindberg's Miss Julie, Arthur Miller's Eddie Carbone), our
theater has for the most part been more comfortable laughing at
this crucial subject than exploring it.
</P>
<P>
   The sex drive, and society's response to it, has been used to
entertain audiences by Aristophanes and Feydeau and a slew of
British farceurs. Right now, Peter Ackerman's Off Broadway play at
the Promenade, ``Things You Shouldn't Say Past Midnight,'' offers
three beds and three pairs of sex partners. No one thinks of Mamet
as a comic playwright these days, but his breakthrough play, you
may recall, was ``Sexual Perversity in Chicago,'' a comedy about
the mating rituals of four proto-yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   Like comedies, musicals seem braver about venturing into the
sexual arena than dramas do. Perhaps because song and dance numbers
can so readily stylize sexual content, perhaps because of their
ancestral roots in burlesque and vaudeville, Broadway musicals seem
to deal more readily with issues of sex than straight plays do.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway musicals even dared to take on the sex industry,
however cavalierly, in ``Sweet Charity,'' ``The Best Little
Whorehouse in Texas'' and ``The Life,'' among others. Several
seasons back, before Hare tackled ``Reigen,'' Michael John LaChiusa
had turned the Schnitzler play into a much-admired musical, ``Hello
Again,'' at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it isn't just playwrights who feel more comfortable
dealing with sex in conventionalized, distancing formats. The
fourth wall is a highly transparent barrier: it's really no barrier
at all. And things that we don't mind watching at the movies or
reading in a novel can sometimes make us cringe in the theater. But
playwrights are supposed to be showing us our selves.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no question that you walk out of ``Closer'' feeling
as if you've had its four characters on a dissecting table and
picked through their very innards. By telling us about their sex
lives, Marber has exposed them far more deeply than if he had
written a play about their families or their friendships. Yet his
play is one of a mere handful that look at this complex and
compelling part of the human experience.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is a peculiar complaint. After all, food is even more
essential to life than sex, and we don't see too many plays on that
subject. The theater seems none the poorer. But dinner is about
bread; sex is about our connections to other people. Is there a
better definition of what theater should be?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
