<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      06-23 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DEFENDS NEW FOREIGN-ISSUES GAFFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and JULIE MASON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday that a
pro-abortion rights politician would have a chance to become his
running mate if he won the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time Bush _ who says he personally opposes
abortion _ has stepped away from the anti-abortion stances that
have been required of Republican presidential candidates for the
last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day of a campaign and fund-raising swing, Bush also
defended his mix-up of two new Eastern European countries that was
his latest international-issues gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   In Richmond, Va., on Tuesday, a reporter from Slovakia, a
breakaway republic from the former Czechoslovakia, asked Bush about
his country. Bush responded by praising the country and recalling a
meeting in Texas with its foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bush met in April with the prime minister of Slovenia,
a breakaway republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big world, and I've got a lot to learn. But should I
be fortunate enough to be elected, I'll be ready,'' Bush said. He
has been receiving briefings from foreign policy experts from the
administrations of presidents Reagan and Bush, his father.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has been criticized for lacking foreign policy
knowledge when he referred to Kosovars as Kosovoians; Greeks as
Grecians; and East Timorese as East Timorians.
</P>
<P>
   On the running mate question, Bush recently said he would not
try as president to overturn Roe vs. Wade with a constitutional
amendment, but would work toward policies that discourage abortion,
like the parental-notification law recently enacted in Texas. Last
week, Bush said that his Supreme Court appointees would face no
litmus test on abortion or other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rule nothing out. The most important criterion will be: Can
the person be president of the United States?'' said Bush, as
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, a Bush supporter who favors abortion
rights, stood at Bush's side during a visit to the Blessed Virgin
Mary Catholic School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I will want to know whether the person can help the
ticket,'' Bush said. ``But other than that, I haven't made any
other determinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, also seeking the GOP
nomination, promised last week that his running mate, if he were
nominated, would oppose abortion rights, as would his Supreme Court
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidate Gary Bauer, who has been persistently
critical of the governor's stance on abortion, called Bush's
remarks about a running mate ``deeply disappointing, but not
surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the third signal that Governor Bush has given
that the sanctity of human life is not a high-priority issue for
him,'' Bauer said. ``I am assuming the next thing we will hear is
that he wants to change the Republican Platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Lambert, a Republican National Committee member and
president of the Texas Home School coalition, said he hopes Bush
will not abandon the pro-life movement in choosing a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the governor, I think, is being magnanimous in trying to
reach out across the party, I think ultimately he will pick someone
who does hold his same, pro-life viewpoint,'' Lambert said.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert said it's nothing less than what's expected by party
rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a vast majority of folks in the party who would
expect him to pick someone in keeping with his own philosophy,''
Lambert said. ``If you look at his efforts behind the scenes in the
Legislature to get parental notification passed, I think it's
indicative of the way he feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge said that even if Bush named a supporter of abortion
rights as his running mate, ``We (in the GOP) have a history of
honoring the vice presidential selections, and I think that will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there would be some who would be displeased and
disapprove, but I think the majority of Republicans give the
benefit of the selection process to the man, to the individual,
they nominate for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appeal to social conservatives so far has been limited to
issues not likely to upset a general election audience. On Monday
in South Carolina, Bush promised that if elected president he would
push for increased federal funding for sexual abstinence education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it would be ``presumptive'' to talk about specific
politicians as potential running mates before winning the
nomination. But he praised Ridge as ``a good man,'' who has been a
good governor for his state.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, who stood quietly during the questioning of Bush, last
year was told by the bishop of the Erie, Pa., diocese he was no
longer welcome at church-sponsored events because of his views
favoring abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   But in May, former Christian Coalition director Ralph Reed, an
unofficial adviser to Bush, told a Pennsylvania audience that
Ridge's views would not necessarily mean religious conservatives
would reject him as a possible vice presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis is on the vice part, and he's not setting the
policy,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Catholic school, Bush promoted programs in which parents
could use tax-supported vouchers to send their children to private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge lost a legislative battle earlier this week to create a
private school voucher program for Pennsylvania. Bush lost a
similar battle in the Texas legislative session that just ended.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would use the presidency as a ``bully pulpit'' to
promote voucher programs in the states, but he indicated he would
not push for a federal voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, education governance issues _ how states determine
to provide a menu of opportunity to parents _ should be up to the
states,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush deflected a question on whether he might support
federal income tax credits for the parents of private school
children by saying, ``I'll talk about that when I lay out my budget
and tax plan.''
</P>
<P>
   During his meeting with students at the Catholic school, a black
child asked him whether he would be willing to put racists in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will send people to jail if they commit a crime,'' said
Bush, who opposed a hate-crimes bill to enhance penalties for
race-motivated crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the child that people should tell racists that this
nation will not tolerate racism and bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure that (racism) is a jailable offense,'' Bush
said. ``But all of us should scold somebody who doesn't treat a
fellow person with respect.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
