<P>
   (NYT33) WASHINGTON -- June 23, 1999 -- BIOTECH-STORYTELLING,
6-23 -- Jeremy Rifkin in his Washington office. Last week, the
activist who was once described by critics as the ``abominable
no-man,'' took on another role: Intrigued by an invitation to an
industry meeting at one of biotechnology's inner sanctums, Rifkin
went to the headquarters of the Monsanto Co. in St. Louis to offer
up his vision of the future. ``I've never been to a meeting like
this in the 23 years I've been talking about these issues,'' he
says. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) IN NEW YORK HARBOR -- June 23, 1999 --
NY-OYSTER-HOMECOMING, 6-23 -- Benjamin Longstreth, the project
manager and New York City coordinator for Baykeeper, a private
environmental group, at the location where on Friday 10,000 bushels
of ancient oyster shells will be spread on the bottom of New York
Harbor to see if drifting oyster larvae begin to settle there and
grow. ``We're trying to give nature a kick start,'' he says. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) DHARMSALA, India -- June 23, 1999 -- TIBET-DIVISIONS,
6-23 -- Tibetan Buddhist monks walking on a street in Dharmsala. In
this remote Indian town, thousands of Tibetans have been awaiting
deliverance for nearly 40 years. Their political and spiritual
leader, the Dalai Lama, 64, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989,
is a devoted pacifist. How long he can keep exiled Tibetans united
around his nonviolent principles is the question that envelops
Dharmsala. (Stephen Kinzer/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. -- June 23, 1999 --
LITTLE-LEAGUE-TUTORS, 6-23 -- Mark Venditti coaches Benjamin Gold
as Gold's parents look on in the background. In another sign that
American childhood has become a serious venture, parents like Loren
and Debbie Gold are paying $70 an hour, sometimes more, to private
coaches to sharpen the skills of their Little League ballplayers.
(Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) LA JOLLA, Calif. -- June 23, 1999 -- CALIF-NUDE-BEACH,
6-23 -- Ronda Colis prepares to post a sign prohibiting nudity on
Black's Beach, just north of La Jolla. After two decades of genial
non-enforcement, local officials decided to crack down on the bare
skin in response to a rash of recent complaints about lewd behavior
and semi-public sex on some parts of the 1,200 foot-long city beach
(Dave Gatley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- June 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ARMY, 6-23 -- Gen.
Eric Shinseki, the U.S. Army's new chief of staff, talks to
reporters on Wednesday in his first interview since being
appointed. Shinseki was a former commander of U.S. troops in Bosnia
and was questioned on the peacekeeping mission in Kosovo and
looming budget fights in Congress. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- June 23, 1999 -- SCOTUS-DISABILITY-REAX,
6-23 -- Participants in a conference on the rights of the disabled
outside the conference hall on Wednesday. Resolving one of the most
pressing questions of Federal disability law, the Supreme Court
ruled on Tuesday that people with physical impairments who can
function normally when they wear their glasses or take their
medicine generally cannot be considered disabled and therefore do
not come within the law's protection against employment
discrimination. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- June 23, 1999 -- SCOTUS, 6-23 -- Tourists
outside the Supreme Court building on the final day of the Court's
1998-99 term, Wednesday. When the court's work was over, two
Federal laws had been declared unconstituional, one 35-year-old
precedent was explicitly overturned, and one 15-year-old precedent
was effectively dead. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 23, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VILLAGE-2, 6-23 -- A French soldier escorts a group of
ethnic Albanian women to the north side of town on Wednesday.
French peacekeepers have been trying to keep a lid on tensions
between Serbs and ethnic Albanians for several days. Serbs menaced
some people wanting to cross a bridge to the side of town which has
the main hospital, many ethnic Albanian homes and almost the only
open food shops. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 23, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VILLAGE-1, 6-23 -- French Marines patrol an area of the
northern Kosovar village where homes were looted and burned on
Wednesday. French peacekeepers have been trying to keep a lid on
tensions between Serbs and ethnic Albanians for several days. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- June 23, 1999 -- LANZMANN-FILM, 6-23 --
Claude Lanzmann, the director of ``Shoah,'' has a new Holocaust
film. ``I knew this was very strong,'' Lanzmann says of the
footage, taken with a single 16-millimeter camera that required
reloading breaks every 11 minutes, the same as for all the
``Shoah'' interviews. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PLANEJE, Yugoslavia -- June 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BORDER-3,
6-23 --Ethnic Albanians Rrushe and Syl Shigjeqi walk past what is
left of their village on Wednesday. A Yugoslav army military
vehicle lies destroyed at left. There is no shortage of destruction
in Kosovo, but here it is possible to see what NATO's bombs added
to it. This village and others nearby are at the foot of Mount
Pastrik, where some of the most furious fighting of the war took
place. At the time, refugees crossing the border into Albania could
actually hear the NATO bombs whistle down. Now some are returning
to see how powerful those bombs were. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) PLANEJE, Yugoslavia -- June 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BORDER-2,
6-23 --A general view of the village on Wednesday. There is no
shortage of destruction in Kosovo, but here it is possible to see
what NATO's bombs added to it. This village and others nearby are
at the foot of Mount Pastrik, where some of the most furious
fighting of the war took place. At the time, refugees crossing the
border into Albania could actually hear the NATO bombs whistle
down. Now some are returning to see how powerful those bombs were.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) GOROZHUPE,Yugoslavia -- June 23, 1999 --
KOSOVO-BORDER-1, 6-23 -- Zepa Binaj, an ethnic Albanian, weeps
inside what is left of her home on Wednesday after returning to her
village. There is no shortage of destruction in Kosovo. This
village and others nearby are at the foot of Mount Pastrik, where
some of the most furious fighting of the war took place and where
NATO airstrikes caused alot of damage. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) HALLSVILLE, Texas -- June 23, 1999 --
TORNADO-SHELTER-COX, 06-23 -- Michael Coles, 7, watches as a
tornado shelter is put in at the Tall Pines Mobile Home Park. ``We
realized we didn't have anywhere for people to go in the park, or
anywhere else in Hallsville,'' said Duane West, the landlord of the
community of 3,000 5 miles east of Longview, Texas. ``It's a
service I feel most landlords should provide their tenants.''
(Jessica Williamson/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ROXBURY, Mass. -- June 23, 1999 -- RETREAT-RESPITE-BOS,
6-23 -- Sister Adelle Marie Ryan, on the third floor deck of St.
Margaret's Convent, which sits at the apex of Fort Hill, commanding
a dramatic view of Boston's downtown skyline. The Episocpal nuns
are taking reservations for the year 2000. These days, the
popularity of monasteries and other spiritual sanctuaries tucked
away in bucolic settings is exploding as frazzled Americans seek
places to recharge their souls. (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- June 23, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 6-23
-- All garden hoses may look alike, but they are distinguished by
their length, diameter, and their construction. When buying a hose,
consider the size of your property and where you intend to use the
hose. If your lawn is 50 feet long, but you often wash your car in
the driveway only 15 feet away from the faucet, it may be better to
buy two 25- foot hoses. You can couple them together when you water
the lawn, but use only one to wash the car. (Edward R. Lipinski/New
York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ATLANTA -- June 23, 1999 -- AUSTINPOWERS-DOLL-COX, 06-23
-- Thousands of talking action figures, based on the hit movie
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' may disappear from Toys
``R'' Us stores after Tamatha Brannon of East Point, Ga. complained
that her son was exposed to the secret agent's catch phrase ``Do I
make you horny, baby? Do I?'' ``My son is not old enough to be
talking about sex, and I think Toys ``R'' Us should be responsible
for putting something that's inappropriate for kids on their
shelves,'' said Mrs. Brannon at an impromptu press conference with
her son, Marvin, 11. (Marlene Karas/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ALDEBURGH, England -- June 23, 1999 -- ENGLAND-FESTIVAL,
6-23 --The composer Thomas Ades, artistic director of the Aldeburgh
Festival in Suffolk. The festival brings great music and great
performers to a place a hundred miles from anywhere - a place that
happens to have, in the Snape Maltings, one of the world's great
concert halls. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BARIA, Vietnam -- June 23, 1999 -- VIETNAM-HOUSE-3, 6-23
-- The Nguyen family gathering March 8 at Phung Thi Khu's new
concrete and brick house. Standing, from left: Cuong, a nephew; Y,
51; Dung, 48; Gioang, 44; Quang, 42; Anh, 39; Tam, 37; Linh, 35;
Tho, 33, and Qui, 28. In front, Phung Thi Khu, 76, who moved in two
weeks later. (Gioang Huu Nguyen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BARIA, Vietnam -- June 23, 1999 -- VIETNAM-HOUSE-2, 6-23
-- Sunlight and air are filter through the lacy iron grillwork in
Phung Thi Khu's new house, built in 1999. Her old house flooded
whenever it rained. (Gioang Huu Nguyen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BARIA, Vietnam -- June 23, 1999 -- VIETNAM-HOUSE-1, 6-23
-- In Baria, Phung Thi Khu's old house, built in 1970, had
electricity, but no running water; 8 people lived there. Her son,
Gioang Huu Nguyen, has built her a brand new house, with gleaming
tile floors, a roof that doesn't leak, a bathtub with hot and cold
running water and a toilet that flushes. ``It was a dream,'' says
Nguyen, 44, who works as an assistant cabinetmaker for Dakota
Jackson, a furniture designer. (Gioang Huu Nguyen/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- June 23, 1999 -- DESK-CHAIRS-2, 6-23 -- The
adjustable Tom chair, left, by Tom Deacon, a Canadian industrial
designer, has a seat that actually extends in front without leaving
a gap in the back that could create an incorrect seat position.
(Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo) Alexander Polakov, a six-foot
graphic designer at Designframe in Manhattan, has used his Pezzi
Hi-Fit exercise ball as a seat for a year. For anyone without back
or spine problems, it's a comfortable alternative to the
traditional desk chair. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- June 23, 1999 -- DESK-CHAIRS-1, 6-23 -- A
good desk chair, or task chair, as it is now called in the trade,
is probably the single most important office tool. From left, the
Hag Capisco chair ($575) has a saddle seat which keeps the legs
comfortably apart; Niels Diffrient's Freedom Chair ($875) has a
frame modeled on the human spine; the Scio chair by Hag ($375)
adjusts automatically in response to the movements of the user; the
upper and lower back adjust separately on the Leap chair, by
Steelcase ($1,050). (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-HITECH-POCKETS-2, 6-23
-- The sprawling collection of gadgets that are becoming part of
our everyday life, such as cell phones, pagers, and electronic
organizers, are inspiring clothing lines that accomodate these
so-called ``pocket'' devices. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-HI-END-AUDIO, 6-23 --
Madrigal Corporation's high-end monoblock amplifier, top, and
Vacuum Tube Logic's two-channel amplifier. While home theater
companies assert that the quality of their products is now quite
high, audio companies, particularly amplifier manufacturers, argue
that home theater equipment just doesn't sound as good as their
own, sonically pure devices, most of which use vacuum tubes.(Carol
Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-POCKET-PROTECTOR, 6-23 --
Made possible by the same heat-sealing process used to make World
War II flak jackets, the pocket protector was intended as an
advertising giveaway, emblazoned with a company logo. But this
simple polyvinyl chloride product evolved into something far more
culturally symbolic: it became the ultimate emblem of nerdiness.
The Massachusetts Institute of Technology Museum gift shop sells
these for $1.25. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-WEB-BASED-TV-3,
6-23 -- David Newman, president of Digital Entertainment Network
(DEN), in one of DEN's sets. DEN's plan is to create Internet-only
programming, low-budget, niche shows aimed at specific audiences
and release them via streaming video. Newman, former president of
Walt Disney Network Television and Touchstone Television, said his
new endeavor was truly a breed apart. (Kim Kulish/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-HITECH-POCKETS, 6-23 --
The sprawling collection of gadgets that are becoming part of our
everyday life, such as cell phones, pagers, and electronic
organizers, are inspiring clothing lines that accomodate these
so-called ``pocket'' devices. Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch's cargo pants,
left, and Rifle Team pants by Orfi, a group of designers in the
SoHo area of Manhattan, include a multitude of pockets for the
gadget-laden. (Tony Cenicola, left, Nancy Siesel/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-WEB-BASED-TV-2,
6-23 --Elsie Escobar, right, and Maurice Compte, stars of ``Tales
From the Eastside,'' the story of gang members in Los Angeles,
produced by the new Digital Entertainment Network (DEN). DEN's plan
is to create Internet-only programming, low-budget, niche shows
aimed at specific audiences and release them via streaming video.
(Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-WEB-BASED-TV-1,
6-23 --Arlo Eisenberg, a program host at Digital Entertainment
Network (DEN). DEN's plan is to create Internet-only programming,
low-budget, niche shows aimed at specific audiences and released
via streaming video. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SEATTLE, Wash. -- June 23, 1999 -- CIR-STOPPING-SPAM,
6-23 -- Julian Haight, creator of Spam Cop, a Web site that tracks
the origin of unsolicited junk E-mail, in his home office. Haight's
page allows the user track unsolicited spam to its source and then
complain about it to the proper authorities. (Larry Davis/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ROSHARON, Texas -- June 23, 199 -- -GOOD-CROPS-HNS, 06-23
-- It has been a good year for corn on Rodney Mowery's farm just
south of Houston. The tall corn is in stark contrast to 1998 and
1996, when Mowery's fields were withered by drought. Out of 250
acres last year, about 160 acres were so ``horrible'' they didn't
warrant running through a combine, Mowery said. Texas farmers are
hoping for bumper crops for the first time since in 1995. (Camilla
McElligott/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
