</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan sidelined with sore hand
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brian Jordan missed Wednesday's game with a sore right
hand, after getting hit by a Mike Thurman pitch in the fourth
inning of Tuesday night's game. The good news after the game was
that it wasn't broken. The bad news on Wednesday was that it was
still very tender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was broken,'' said Jordan, the Braves' leading
run-producer with 57 RBIs, which had him tied with Sammy Sosa for
fourth in the National League. ``It's a bad day. Today I feel more
of the pain. Yesterday it was numb from all the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who had missed only one other game this year and is
second on the club to Andruw Jones in games played, continued
playing in Tuesday night's game until he came up to bat again, but
it hurt too much to swing a bat. Jordan is hoping he can take a
pain-killing shot if necesssary and be ready to play by the weekend
series against the New York Mets at the latest.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams started in right field on Wednesday and Ryan
Klesko moved into the cleanup hole in the order. Jordan was one of
a steady stream of Braves players headed for the training room on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez was placed on the disabled list Wednesday for his
sprained knee, retroactive to Monday, which means he'll be eligible
to come off on July 6 at home against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz battles
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz is set to make his second start since his disastrous
outing against the Orioles, when the seven runs he allowed called
into question the state of his tender elbow. But with his outing in
Arizona since then, when with the benefit of a home-run saving
catch by Jordan he shut out the Diamondbacks for six innings,
Smoltz (8-2) can take confidence into today's start against the
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Baltimore game there were some questions,'' Smoltz
said. ``When I had a chance to think about it, it was just a bump
in the road. I just realized what I went through last year, I may
have to go through that again. I'm good enough to win, just like
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz knows he's in for a fight this season to see if he can
pitch beyond some of the limits his elbow would seem to have in
store for him. To do it, he's made a change in his fastball
delivery that will takes some stress off the elbow. He's also given
up on the idea of pitching into the eighth and ninth innings
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter has declared himself ready to return to action the
next time the Braves need him to start against a left-hander. In
the mean time, Hunter is available for pinch hitting duties, which
he did for the first time Tuesday night since he sprained his left
ankle in Houston. He's still wearing an air-cast on the ankle and
says he's about 85 percent.... Lopez was paid a visit on Wednesday
by Davis Loftin, a 17-year-old from Dothan, Ala., whom Lopez
visited in the hospital last Nov. 23 when he was in Dothan for a
charity event. Loftin had undergone three brain surgeries and was
in and out of a coma after a car accident. Loftin, who arrived at
Turner Field in a wheelchair, stood for Lopez and took a few steps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
