<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METHODISTS-GAYS-NYT &LR;      06-23 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER GAY MARRIAGE SPLITS PROMINENT CHURCH NEAR ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the governor on one side and a prominent
congressman on the other, a leading United Methodist church in the
Atlanta suburbs split this week in the latest case of what has
become a crisis in the church on the issue of same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   A breakaway group, led by the former pastor of the First United
Methodist Church of Marietta, had its first official service
Sunday. Attending and signing up to join the breakaway
congregation, named the Wesleyan Fellowship, were Rep. Bob Barr, an
influential Republican member of Congress, and his wife, Jeri.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes, a Democrat, chose to stay at First United
Methodist, which has about 5,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of about 450 families was the latest development
in a series of reprimands and threats between the Marietta church
and its regional conference that began in November 1997 when the
board of trustees of Emory University, an Atlanta institution
founded by the Methodist Church, ruled that same-sex marriage
ceremonies could be conducted on its campus under limited
circumstances. None have been performed to date.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor of First United Methodist at the time, the Rev.
Charles Sineath, an Emory alumnus, said same-sex unions should not
be allowed on United Methodist Church property, like Emory. When he
found out that Bishop Lindsey Davis, head of the North Georgia
United Methodist Conference, was part of the trustees' unanimous
vote, Sineath could not be reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   The board's ruling, along with his concerns about the
denomination's commitment to fundamental Christian beliefs, led
Sineath to leave his congregation and the United Methodist Church
altogether, taking with him a flock of similarly disenchanted
churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, who was married at the church, said, ``We left First
United because Charles is our pastor, and we think the very
fundamental, Biblical principles he stands for are important.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes declined to comment, but in a speech June 17 to the North
Georgia United Methodist Conference, he said that one of the duties
of a Christian was ``to be tolerant and forgiving, and,
unfortunately, many confuse that with weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, the debate on same-sex unions has strained the
denomination nationwide to the point that many Methodists fear the
possibility of a schism in the country's second-largest Protestant
denomination.
</P>
<P>
   The debate goes back at least to last year. On Aug. 11, five
months after a church court acquitted a United Methodist pastor who
conducted a marriage ceremony for a lesbian couple, the church's
judicial council ruled that same-sex unions could not be held in
United Methodist churches and that pastors involved in such
ceremonies could be defrocked.
</P>
<P>
   The California-Nevada conference is trying to decide whether it
should move for a trial against 68 United Methodist pastors who
publicly blessed a lesbian union in January in protest of the
council's decision.
</P>
<P>
   With factions on both sides pulling at the denomination's core,
the question is how much longer the 8.4 million United Methodists
will worship in the same house, said the Rev. Lyle Schaller, a
retired Methodist pastor from Illinois who is an expert on church
trends.
</P>
<P>
   What happened at First United Methodist of Marietta, which has
golf carts to shuttle members of its upper-middle-class
congregation from the parking lot, is a good example of how serious
the issues have become, Schaller said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Brannan, a 12-year member who decided to stay at First
United Methodist, said, ``Reverend Sineath's leaving left us
groping around in the dark, looking for where do we go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict was a critical moment for the Marietta church, said
the Rev. Sam Storey, the interim pastor, and has put a severe
strain on several marriages and friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Many who attended First United Methodist, including Sineath,
said they saw Davis' vote in the Emory case as a betrayal of their
values. In retaliation, the board of stewards for the Marietta
church withheld its annual $235,985 payment to the conference in
January 1998. The church later released the money, but only after
demanding that none of it be paid to any national agency of the
United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   A task force commissioned in January by the stewards to examine
the state of the United Methodist Church concluded that the
national church had begun to hedge on issues like the factuality of
the virgin birth, the physical resurrection of Jesus Christ, and
homosexuality as sin. But experts suggest there is no evidence that
the church has been officially moving away from the traditional
view on the first two issues. On homosexuality, the church forbids
ordination of non-celibate homosexuals and same-sex unions. But
others hold different opinions within the national church, which
has caused the divisive debate.
</P>
<P>
   In April, largely in reaction to the report from First United
Methodist's task force, Davis wrote to Sineath denouncing the
report and saying he could not allow the Marietta church to
continue in its direction of ``unfairly playing on people's fears
and bias.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, there was little peace between the Marietta
church and its conference. When Sineath came up for reappointment
in March, he was transferred to another church. First United
Methodist's board again voted to withhold its money from the
conference, and several members began talking about forming a new
church.
</P>
<P>
   Sineath chose to retire instead of accepting a transfer, and was
then fired by Davis when he accepted an offer to lead the breakaway
group.
</P>
<P>
   The situation left many lifelong members of First United
Methodist with a tough choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving First Marietta was the most difficult decision I've
ever made,'' said Frank Smith, 63, a member for 31 years. ``But we
were very disappointed in our bishop's vote, and, reading the
report, there came a time when we could no longer support the
national church.''
</P>
<P>
   When First United Methodist was the host of a reception for
Sineath a week ago, the receiving line lasted two hours. Even many
of those who decided to stay at First United Methodist called
Sineath a hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in this church disagrees with what's
happened nationally,'' said Storey, the interim pastor. ``But we
chose to stay within the system and make our views known.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
