<HEADER>
A7379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-OYSTER-HOMECOMING-     06-23 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OYSTER-HOMECOMING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING UP BEDS FOR THE LITTLEST OYSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (subs 15th graf to note project was approved by N.J. Dept. of
Environmental Protection and U.S. Army Corps of Engineers) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is about as simple as science gets: Spread
10,000 bushels of ancient oyster shells on the bottom of New York
Harbor near the Statue of Liberty, and see if drifting oyster
larvae settle there and grow.
</P>
<P>
   But if the experiment planned for Thursday works, it could
portend a revival of a long-missing link in the ecology and marine
commerce of the waters around New York City. Before the harbor
became choked with pollution, oysters were abundant: the islands
now known as Liberty and Ellis were known to the Dutch as the
Oester, or Oyster, Islands. At the turn of the century, more than 1
million bushels of oysters were harvested each year around the
harbor, from Raritan Bay to the East River.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the oyster restoration project, its designers
say, is simply to reestablish the mollusks so they can help consume
algae, which can deplete oxygen and suffocate fish, and create a
reef, where oyster colonies and fish can find shelter.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists also say they hope that oysters from New
York Harbor will eventually end up on the plates of restaurant
diners. Once mature, the oysters could be transplanted to cleaner
waters and then flushed of any lingering bacteria in tanks, as is
now commonly done with clams, said Benjamin Longstreth, the project
manager and New York City coordinator for Baykeeper, a private
environmental group in Sandy Hook, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager of the Grand Central Oyster Bar, Michael
Garvey, when informed of the project, said he was hopeful, but
cautious. ``If the oysters are able to grow that means the system
as a whole is getting much better,'' Garvey said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a long time, however, before New York City oysters
are listed along with the Cotuits and Chincoteagues on the Oyster
Bar's daily shellfish list, he said. ``It's a great idea,'' he
said. ``But for now, it's a noble experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiment has only become possible in recent years. Oysters
largely vanished in city waters early this century, ravaged by
overfishing, suffocated by plumes of raw sewage and buried by silt
washing down the Hudson River from upstate farms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the raw sewage is mostly gone, farming is fading and there
is no oyster harvest at all between Long Island and Delaware Bay,
according to fisheries biologists. The result is that the harbor,
which is seeing a revival of all manner of marine creatures, is
probably hospitable to oysters, Longstreth said.
</P>
<P>
   They just lack good homes _ for oysters, that means hard
surfaces full of nooks and crannies where the tiny larvae can
settle, out of reach of crabs and fish.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they need heaps of submerged oyster shells.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, a scattering of oysters has been seen
around the harbor and up the Hudson in Yonkers on piers, anchor
chains, even submerged grocery carts _ enough to provide a few
larvae, Longstreth said. But without a broad bed of shells, it is
unlikely that a large colony can be established, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mature oysters produce clouds of microscopic larvae that drift
on the tide until they find a hard surface. Those that settle in
the open are almost all eaten by predators. Those that make their
way into a tight space can survive and eventually reproduce, said
Dr. Mark Luckenbach, a marine ecologist at the Virginia Institute
of Marine Science in eastern Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Luckenbach, who was consulted by the Baykeeper group last
winter, has been overseeing the building of artificial oyster reefs
around the Chesapeake Bay, in hopes of reestablishing vast natural
reefs that were completely destroyed by fishing over the past
century. The new reefs will be kept off limits to harvesting,
acting as a reservoir of larvae that can disperse around the bay,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's Bureau of Aquaculture has been building shell
reefs to encourage the establishment of wild oyster colonies for 12
years, said John Volk, the bureau director. And oyster farmers have
used the technique to bolster their cultivated underwater beds for
generations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the restoration work around the country has taken
place in the center of a bustling urban harbor surrounded by
millions of people, Longstreth said. ``We're trying to give nature
a kick start,'' he said. The $35,000 project, which was approved by
the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection and the U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers, is being financed with grants from the Pew
Charitable Trusts, the Victoria Foundation and New Jersey Sea
Grant, Longstreth said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Longstreth oversaw final preparations, as a towering
crane on the waterfront in Elizabeth, N.J., deposited thousands
upon thousands of oyster shells onto a barge. The shells had been
dug from Maryland beds more than 1,000 years old and trucked to the
pier.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, they are scheduled to be towed to a spot in New Jersey
waters near the Statue of Liberty. A New York City Fire Department
fire boat will wash the heaps of shells from the barge into the
harbor with water cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Longstreth said the dumping was timed to precede the first burst
of spawning by the few resident oysters around the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Then it is a matter of waiting for the tides to carry the larvae
to the right spot. Divers will inspect the shells several times
late this summer and in the early fall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If no oysters settle naturally, the next step will be to add
some imported live oysters to the bed of shells to seed the area
with larvae, he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Waldman, a biologist for the Hudson River Foundation, a
private group that is not involved in the project, said the time is
right for the oyster's return.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important part of the local fauna and it's been
kind of forgotten,'' he said. ``Finally, water quality is clean
enough where it's probably a good bet to help these things along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
