<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSIT-BILL-NYT &LR;      06-23 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSIT-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TRIM, TRANSIT BILL CLEARS THE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Wednesday overwhelmingly approved a
$44.5 billion transportation spending bill, after fiscal
conservatives used a parliamentary maneuver to strike from it the
money needed to pay for running the Federal Aviation
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The move, by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., had the blessing of the
House leadership and averted another crippling slowdown of one of
the 13 spending bills that will finance government operations in
the fiscal year that begins on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's outcome does not mean that the FAA will be left
without the money to pay its costs, including the salaries of the
nation's air traffic controllers and air safety inspectors. Rather,
the sum for the agency will be decided by a House-Senate conference
committee. The Senate's version of the transportation bill, though
not yet passed, would allot the agency about $250 million less than
the $5.9 billion the House had envisioned, and Coburn's effort
makes it likely that the lower number will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't saying we don't want an FAA,'' Coburn said. ``Our
goal is to get spending under control in the House and at the same
time to have adequate funds for the FAA.''
</P>
<P>
   Before passing the bill, on a vote of 429-3, the House also gave
another nod to fiscal conservatives by cutting from it $300 million
that had been designated for airport improvements. This cut had
little practical effect, since the money was from an unused balance
in the current fiscal year and had simply never been spent in any
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the conservatives won a $1 million cut from the
$158 million proposed for administrative functions of the
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 annual spending bills, the transportation bill is only
the third that has been passed by the House. And the Democratic
minority maintained that none of the day's developments did
anything to avert a looming political showdown later this summer,
when the House will have to consider the largest domestic spending
bills, those for labor, education, health, housing and veterans
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Even many moderate Republicans say the spending limits required
by the Republican budget blueprint are so tight, and the cuts
required by them so deep, that these bills will not be able to win
House passage, much less get signed into law by President Clinton.
Democrats said Wednesday that against those bigger sums, the
savings being forced through now by conservatives were nearly
meaningless. ``It's one of these pretend schemes,'' said Rep.
Martin Olav Sabo, D-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   But the victories won by the conservatives Wednesday kept them
from thwarting their leadership and stalling the transportation
bill. Last month Coburn tied up the floor for days by offering
amendment after amendment to the agriculture bill, undercutting
efforts by Speaker Dennis Hastert to pass that and other spending
bills in an orderly fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The two largest chunks of the transportation bill are $27.7
billion for highway spending and $5.8 billion for mass transit.
Both of those figures were mandated by last year's highway bill,
which, to the consternation of conservatives, was the largest
public works legislation ever enacted by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The mass transit spending, an increase of $407 million over the
current level, drew praise from New Yorkers, who are fighting
against a provision in the Senate version that would reduce that
financing by capping the percentage of total mass transit aid that
could go to any one state. The cap would strike hard at New York
and California, which together account for nearly 50 percent of the
nation's mass transit commuters.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., said the Senate version of the
bill could result in a loss of $160 million to New York state.
``Unlike the bill on the Senate side,'' Congresswoman Maloney said,
``the House version understands that each city and state has
different needs. The same senators who may support caps for mass
transit I would assume would be opposed to similar caps on highway
spending.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
