<HEADER>
A7383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      06-23 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEKS IOWA LEVERAGE IN THE CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (jt) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is trying to use the broad support
for his presidential campaign among the Republican political
establishment in Washington to help him compete in an high-profile
straw poll in Iowa in August.
</P>
<P>
   In an internal memorandum, Sara Taylor, a Bush campaign official
in Iowa, has outlined a plan for 50 major corporate and trade
association lobbyists and other Washington insiders who back Bush
to each persuade at least 15 people in Iowa to participate in the
poll there.
</P>
<P>
   Several candidates have portrayed the event, set for Aug. 14, as
a significant early demonstration of support in Iowa, the state
that historically holds the first presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he plans to compete aggressively in Iowa. And
while the non-binding straw poll amounts to little more than a
``beauty contest'' and has nothing to do with the actual caucuses
early next year, some campaigns have said the poll may be a
make-or-break competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush memorandum was obtained by a rival campaign and passed
on to The New York Times in the hope of revealing Bush's reliance
on the Washington establishment. The memo also demonstrates the
degree to which the Texan's campaign is competing intensely in the
event and how it is seeking to transform Bush's wide support in
Washington into an impressive showing in Middle America.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations for Bush in the event are quite high given that
he has overwhelmed the Republican field in opinion polls and
contributions. The goal of the effort, Ms. Taylor wrote, is to
``organize through supportive Washington Trade
Associations/companies to mobilize and turnout 700 Iowans who would
probably not otherwise attend'' the event.
</P>
<P>
   She explained, ``As your crew identifies friendly national
organizations that will encourage their Iowa members to participate
in the straw poll, we, in this office, will work the membership
through the identified key leaders of that organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, said there
was nothing improper with turning to Washington insiders for an
event in which only Iowans can take part. ``These organizations
represents Iowans,'' she said. ``Their members are Iowans. This is
part of a good organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum listed roughly 50 lobbyists that the Bush
campaign is seeking to enlist, including officials of Associated
Builders and Contractors; United Airlines; the National Association
of Home Builders; National Beer Wholesalers; National Mining
Association; Bell South; National Restaurant Association; Union
Pacific; National Association of Manufacturers; American Trucking
Association; US West; Blue Cross/Blue Shield; Microsoft Inc., and
Consolidated Edison.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
