<SLUG> BC-CALIF-TREASURER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN STATE NEEDS TO INVEST STRATEGICALLY, TREASURER SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- State Treasurer Philip Angelides wants to borrow
a page from the business world to direct the investment of
California's bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with the Daily News editorial board Wednesday, the
former Sacramento developer criticized the way bond money for
infrastructure has been spent in the past _ without what he said
should have been a well-thought out plan. He said the state doesn't
use a comprehensive and cost-effective approach in allocating these
funds _ which is used for the construction and maintenance of
schools, parks and transportation, among others.
</P>
<P>
   As he unveils the Debt Affordability Report today, Angelides not
only follows his predecessors in recommending the amount of bonds
the state can afford to issue, but he also is implementing his own
vision of how the bond money should be spent. The report's title is
``Smart Investments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The state doesn't have a strategic investment plan,'' he said.
``If you look at any corporation ... they never start the debate
with how much money they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelides also said that by taking care of California's
environment and helping to redevelop the inner cities, all
residents and businesses will benefit. The result will be a better
quality of life, reduced crime and poverty and a more educated work
force, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some really good ideas,'' said Jean Ross, executive
director of the California Budget Project, a nonprofit policy
research group in Sacramento. ``What's different is the treasurer
is using his position as a bully pulpit.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Angelides has been aggressively promoting his vision
across the state. On Wednesday, he kicked off a nine-day campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Zaremberg, president of the California Chamber of Commerce
in Sacramento, said he agrees with the treasurer's ideas in
general. But he thinks Angelides doesn't adequately address some
obstacles to his vision.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Zaremberg said it's hard to build condominiums and
apartment complexes in urban areas because of the potential of
frivolous construction lawsuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
