<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATMS-ATMS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wells to Use ATMs That Talk  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Threatened with a class-action lawsuit, Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. agreed
yesterday to become the first bank in the United States to install
talking automated teller machines for the blind.
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  The technology still is being developed, but ATMs eventually
will be installed at all 1,500 Wells locations in California.
</P>
<P>
   Wells _ which is working with NCR and Diebold, its principal ATM
vendors, to develop the machines _ promised to install 20 of them
in the Bay Area and Los Angeles and San Diego counties within the
next 12 months. It said it will have 100 machines in place by Sept.
1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Don Brown, a 40-year-old San Francisco resident and one of four
blind individuals who would have been the lead plaintiffs if a suit
had been filed, said the agreement ``extends the concept of access
for disabled people beyond physical access.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained: ``We already have the curb cuttings and the
wheelchair ramps, but now that we are in the information society,
access has to include access to information.''
</P>
<P>
   Most ATMs already have braille on the keypads _ but only 10
percent of blind people know braille. And those who do know braille
still can't read the silent instructions on the ATM monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that when he banks after hours, he either must take
along a friend to help with the ATM or seek assistance from
strangers in the ATM line, ``which is probably not the most secure
way of dealing with financial matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The talking machines will be equipped with headphones to ensure
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Information on account balances and the size of withdrawals or
deposits, which now appears silently on ATM monitors, will be
recited by recorded voice through the headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Blind users will be instructed how to use the keypad to deposit
money, withdraw money, transfer funds or buy stamps _ a special
feature offered by Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Haeg, a Wells Fargo spokesman, said there will have to be
an ``orientation of some sort'' to familiarize blind customers who
don't know braille and can't use the keypad.
</P>
<P>
   Wells accepted the plan after more than four years of
negotiations with the California Council of the Blind and the
Disability Rights Education and Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Feingold, a Berkeley lawyer representing the Council of
the Blind, said her client had a strong case under the Americans
with Disabilities Act, which guarantees the disabled equal access
to public facilities.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to say whether other banks have been threatened
with lawsuits. But she added: ``If I ran a bank, I would pay
attention to this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann DeFabio, a spokeswoman for Bank of America, said that ``in
the past, we have been approached by the council'' but that no
lawsuit was threatened. She said BofA has been working on the
development of talking ATMs with manufacturers ``for several
years'' and plans a pilot project for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Haeg said Wells Fargo decided from the start ``to view this as a
business opportunity, pure and simple. There was never any
resistance by our management. We're in the service business, our
competitive advantage is better service, and this was a great
opportunity to offer service to a very important segment of our
customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't know how many Wells customers are blind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
