<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCEXPO-PCEXPO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 IMac Knockoff Is Really a PC in Disguise  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Tucked away in a corner of the huge PC Expo trade show is a
translucent, curvaceous computer with built-in monitor and Internet
connections that comes in five bright colors.
<P>
   It sure looks like an iMac, but it's a Windows-based PC that
costs a third less than the trend-setting Apple model and even has
a floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   Future Power, an 8-month-old Santa Clara company with backing
from a major Korean manufacturer, unveiled the iMac look-alike at
this week's PC Expo in New York City. Called E-Power, the new
machine is scheduled to go on sale in early September for $799.
</P>
<P>
   It's designed for users who like the iMac's hip styling and easy
setup but don't want to pay $1,199 or want the wider variety of
software available for Windows, according to Future Power
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The E-Power comes in five colors: sapphire, amethyst, emerald,
ruby and topaz. The iMac is available in tangerine, lime,
strawberry, grape and blueberry.
</P>
<P>
   While the iMac has been a huge hit with Apple fans, the E-Power
exhibit, sitting in the shadow of the huge Compaq booth, attracted
scant attention from the PC-centric crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The initial version of the E-Power will come with a 400-MHz
Intel Celeron chip, 64 megabytes of memory, a 6.4-gigabyte hard
drive, a 40x CD-ROM drive and, unlike the iMac, a standard floppy
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Like the iMac, it will have not only a 56 kilobit-per-second
modem, but also a built-in Ethernet networking port that can run at
either 10 or 100 megabits per second. The Ethernet port, which is
not built into most consumer PCs, makes it easy to connect cable
modems and other high-speed Internet access devices to the E-Power.
</P>
<P>
   The system will have two free connectors for the Universal
Serial Bus, a data channel, also used in the iMac. That makes it
possible to add external peripheral devices without most of the
hassles of traditional PC expansion ports.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the E-Power will have one internal slot, so users
can plug in a circuit board with extra features _ something not
possible with the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Software preinstalled in the E-Power will include Windows 98,
IBM's Lotus SmartSuite package of productivity applications and
other educational and entertainment titles. Future Power is backed
by Daewoo Telecom, a division of one of Korea's major industrial
conglomerates. The group already manufactures 300,000 PCs per
month, Future Power officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Future Power has no connection to Emachines, another
Korean-owned company that sells inexpensive PCs called etowers.
</P>
<P>
   Future Power executives said they don't think that their design
will infringe on any of Apple's intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Reynolds, a vice president at Dataquest in San Jose, also
didn't think there would be any legal issues, though he couldn't
guarantee that Apple won't try to sue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
