<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7393 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     06-23 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST  &HT;     Online Journalists Hope Association Will Improve Their 
 Credibility 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Online journalists want some respect.
<P>
   The nascent Online News Association wants to get it for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Net, after all, is the medium that brought us Matt Drudge's
unsubstantiated rumors (some of which turned out to be true),
paid-for book recommendations on Amazon.com, and Pierre Salinger's
online ``proof'' that TWA Flight 800 was shot down by a missile.
</P>
<P>
   The association, a month-old trade group that already has 100
members, aims to restore credibility and establish some standards
after such debacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all very much believe in the value of producing credible,
compelling journalism and want to foster that in this medium. It's
a medium that doesn't always have a reputation for that level of
quality,'' said Jamie Heller, editor of strategic ventures at
TheStreet.com and treasurer of the association.
</P>
<P>
   The group plans to institute prizes (online scribes feel shunned
by the Pulitzers and the National Magazine Awards) and foster a
collegial atmosphere that will help shape the new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You face so many issues, it's so great to have a group of
colleagues you can bounce things off of,'' Heller said. She can ask
fellow members: ``How do you operate in a medium that has no
deadlines? How do you set up your newsroom? What kind of use do you
make out of things like hit reports on stories? What kind of
technology do you use to publish your stories?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's creating a network of people who are facing the same
challenges,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Jaroslovsky, the managing editor of the Wall Street Journal
Interactive Edition and the president of the ONA, said people first
discussed forming a group when they would see each other at trade
shows. The idea finally came to fruition with a small amount of
seed money from Dow Jones, the Journal's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The group will educate people about online journalism. For
instance, online sports journalists have been denied media access
to some athletic events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sponsoring body said, `We don't want to accredit you
because we have our own Web site, and you're competition,'''
Jaroslovsky said. ``To deny professional journalists the
opportunity to cover an event is not acceptable. We wouldn't stand
for it in print or broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaroslovsky said organizations like TheStreet.com or Cnet's
News.com, ``which have grown up around the Web, are every bit as
entitled to respect as the New York Times and the Wall Street
Journals and the CNNs of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Membership is $50 a year. The association's Web site is at what
Jaroslovsky called ``the euphonious
 &LR; www.onlinenewsassociation.org &LR; . We wanted  &LR; www.ona.org &LR; ,'' he
said, ``but the Ontario Nurses Association beat us to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SETTING THE STANDARD STRAIGHT: As a magazine that publishes both in
print and online, the Industry Standard faces just the sorts of
issues that the Online News Association plans to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   One of the thorniest: corrections. An online news purveyor has
the option of smoothing over its mistakes without ever alerting the
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Like many online news purveyors, the Standard tells its readers
when it corrects an article. It even maintains a page of such
miscues, at  &LR; www.thestandard.com/articles &LR;   &LR; /corrections/ &LR; . But the
page had a technological problem: Each correction provided a link
to the full story, which appeared in its corrected form on the
screen. But when the reader printed the story, the original version
would show up, error and all.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, an April 19 story about Salon.com said that
Hambrecht and Quist was handling the initial public offering.
Wrong! It was W.R. Hambrecht, a different bank. The Standard posted
a correction, and the story was repaired. But click on ``print this
article,'' and the original, erroneous version would show up.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving an inquiry, editor Jonathan Steinberg said the
problem was ``a technical glitch which we were not aware of,'' and
he had it fixed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Another change in the works: He's rethinking a policy under
which sources can complain about a story, and if he thinks there's
a likelihood their complaint will hold up, he'll grant an
``injunction'' of sorts and pull the story until the issues are
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a complex story, it can take several days to determine
if the complaint is legitimate or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But on those occasions when he'd yank a story, he said,
``Suddenly, there's a story out there that mysteriously
disappeared.'' Some people saw it, maybe some sites link to it, and
it's no longer up.
</P>
<P>
   That has him mulling a change in policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to be in a situation where you're pretending
that something you published on your Web site, for however short a
period of time, never existed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a lot of interesting issues that arise,'' he
said. ``There are not very well-worked-out conventions about how to
deal with these things.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
