<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-AIRLINE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 American Taking Reno Air Flights Under Its Wing  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
American Airlines said yesterday that it will fold Reno Air's 150
flights a day into its own operation by August 31.
<P>
   No jobs will be cut as part of the merger, American executives
said, and ticket prices are expected to remain competitive because
American still must compete against United Airlines, Southwest
Airlines and Alaska Airlines for passengers going up and down the
West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation announced yesterday follows last December's
purchase of Reno Air for $124 million by American. Since then,
American has been developing a plan to integrate the two systems.
</P>
<P>
   American is picking up all of Reno Air's flights and routes,
with the exception of service to Vancouver, Burbank and Tucson,
Ariz., that overlapped with existing service by American.
</P>
<P>
   When completed, the merger will beef up American's north-south
service on the West Coast, which was the primary reason for the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Reno flights that are being converted into American flights
include 14 flights a day from San Francisco International Airport
to Los Angeles and Orange County and 32 flights a day from San Jose
International Airport to Las Vegas, Los Angeles, Portland, Reno and
Seattle. Reno Air did not serve Oakland International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to flights added through the merger, American said
it plans to create 20 new West Coast flights to 19 cities in July.
That includes direct flights from San Francisco to Dallas-Forth
Worth and Chicago; flights from San Jose to Orange County, San
Diego, New York and Tokyo; as well as one additional flight from
Oakland to Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making a serious commitment to expanding and
strengthening American's presence in the West,'' said Mike Gunn,
American's senior vice president of marketing who made a sweep
through California yesterday promoting the consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   By August 31, all 2,000 former Reno Air employees will be
wearing American Airlines uniforms and all airport signage will
change from Reno to American.
</P>
<P>
   The Reno Air name will live on, in the form of aircraft paint,
for a few months longer. It will be January before the 25 ex-Reno
aircraft will be refurbished to conform to American's look and
feel. First-class cabins will be added, and both first-class and
coach sections will receive new cabin interiors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
