<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-AT&AMP;T </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S.F. Board President Opposes AT&AMP;T Cable Plan  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The president of San Francisco's Board of Supervisors yesterday
opposed a proposal that would block competitors from offering
high-speed Internet service over AT&AMP;T's cable TV lines.
<P>
   At a meeting of the board's Public Utilities and Deregulation
Committee, Supervisor Tom Ammiano said he would vote against a
proposal recommended by the city's telecommunications department
because he believes that consumers should be able to select
high-speed access from a multitude of providers, not just AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The city department's proposal would allow AT&AMP;T, which recently
bought TCI, to control Internet access over the cable lines.
Instead, Ammiano said he will offer a substitute proposal and
scheduled a closed-session vote by the full board on the matter for
July 6.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is whether San Francisco customers will have one or
several choices for high-speed Internet access via cable TV lines.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans to offer super-fast Internet access over TCI's cable
lines. TCI customers will get the service through ExciteAtHome, an
Internet service provider that offers cable modem service at speeds
up to 100 times faster than a traditional dial-up modem.
ExciteAtHome is 40 percent owned by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But Ammiano and other board members want AT&AMP;T to allow other
Internet service providers, like America Online, to be able to
offer high-speed Internet access over TCI's cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like AOL want to let their customers gain access to
their own content through fast cable modems. Aside from building
their own cable systems, however, the only other way for AOL and
other ISPs to access cable lines is to lease them from providers,
like AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, if a TCI customer wanted to use a cable modem to
access AOL, he or she would have to sign up with ExciteAtHome for
$40 a month and pay another $20 a month to AOL. With open access,
customers only would have to pay AOL and wouldn't have to go
through ExciteAtHome to get online.
</P>
<P>
   To force AT&AMP;T's hand, the Board of Supervisors has tried to make
``open access'' a condition for approval of the AT&AMP;T/TCI merger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When AT&AMP;T bought TCI last year, it had to apply for a transfer
of control of TCI's cable franchise. The board is the body that
will approve that transfer.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has resisted allowing open access, saying it's not
technically feasible and arguing that municipalities cannot impose
such requirements. The company also has said open access would
delay its planned upgrade of TCI's cable systems across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a federal judge in Portland rejected AT&AMP;T's
arguments, saying cities do have the right to impose conditions
when approving a franchise transfer. The judge said, in a decision
that AT&AMP;T is appealing, that the telephone giant should be forced
to open its cable lines in the Portland area.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's competitors were hopeful that San Francisco would follow
Portland's lead and try to impose open access. For the past four
months, San Francisco and AT&AMP;T have been wrangling over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, Julia Friedlander, who heads the city's
telecommunications department, recommended a proposal that critics
called weak and said would give AT&AMP;T a monopoly over high-speed
access.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation said AT&AMP;T would only have to provide open
access in San Francisco if a precedent was set and AT&AMP;T ``agreed''
to provide it in another city. It would not require that AT&AMP;T open
its lines even if a legal ruling, such as the one in Portland, was
upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Friedlander admitted that the city wanted stronger language but
said AT&AMP;T was unwilling to commit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she recommended that the board approve the current
proposal because it included a provision guaranteeing that AT&AMP;T
would upgrade its cable system in San Francisco within four years.
If the city doesn't approve the negotiated agreement, she said,
AT&AMP;T could walk away from the upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a matter of risk for the city,'' Friedlander said.
``If the ordinance is not adopted, it's possible the (cable) system
will not get rebuilt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ammiano and two other board members said the proposal was
insufficient and would lead to an AT&AMP;T monopoly over high-speed
Internet access. ``This is an anticompetitive arrangement,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Yee, another board member, said if AT&AMP;T wants to walk
away from San Francisco, ``Fine, we'll have other people come in
and provide service.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Patch, an attorney representing AT&AMP;T, said the company
is not against open access but resents government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city should conclude that the far better public policy
here is that competition and not regulation should pick the winners
in the Internet service area,'' Patch told the board.
</P>
<P>
   He said competitors already have other ways to offer high-speed
access, such as over digital subscriber lines and via
satellite. &UR;  &LR; ``Forced access simply does not work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a coalition arguing against AT&AMP;T disagreed, saying open
access is what stands between San Francisco retaining its status as
America's ``most wired city'' or stalling on the information
superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement, as it stands now, would create a local
monopoly stranglehold on cable Internet access,'' said Katie Roper,
director of the Bay Area Open Access Coalition. ``Just like
Portland, San Francisco has a right to expect and demand open
access.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
