<SLUG> BC-BANKS-BANKS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wells Fargo, 2 Other Banks Launch Firm to Speed Online
Bill  Delivery 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Three major banks, including San Francisco's Wells Fargo, said
yesterday they are starting a company to promote online delivery of
bills to consumers.
<P>
   New York's Chase Manhattan and North Carolina's First Union will
join Wells Fargo in the venture, which will build a computer
switching system linking billers to financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Those institutions, in turn, will use their Internet sites to
deliver bills to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Formation of the for-profit company, tentatively named the
Exchange, brings the much-hyped but long delayed technology a big
step closer to widespread availability, the banks said. The company
will begin operating by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, different groups of banks and vendors are developing
their own systems using software languages that can't communicate
readily with other systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Exchange will use technology that will connect the separate
systems, potentially uniting billers, financial institutions and
consumers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to jumpstart the industry,'' said Wells Fargo
executive vice president Sharon Osberg, the bank's chief of online
financial services.
</P>
<P>
   First Union already offers bills over the Internet on a limited
basis and Wells Fargo plans to begin doing so by October. But
experts say growth will be limited until there is a single set of
standards that billers and financial institutions can use
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In online billing, consumers receive their bills electronically
when they go to their checking accounts on the Internet. They can
pay bills with a mouse click and their accounts will automatically
be debited.
</P>
<P>
   Under previous home banking setups, consumers could pay online
by keying in vendor information but bills were still delivered by
regular mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
