<SLUG> BC-RIO-RIO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Diamond's New Rio Offers More Music  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Diamond Multimedia Systems Inc. today will introduce a new version
of its Rio handheld digital music player that will store more music
than the original, play encrypted songs and come in four colors.
<P>
   Due out on store shelves in the fall, Diamond's new Rio PMP 500
will hold up to two hours' worth of music, about twice as much as
the original PMP 300. The new Rio, which will retail for $269, can
be upgraded with optional memory cards to store even more songs.
</P>
<P>
   The new version will come in three translucent colors _ gray,
teal and purple _ in addition to the basic black.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the new Rio will be compatible with Macintosh computers;
the original only worked with Windows-based PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the new Rio will be able to play scrambled as
well as unscrambled music.
</P>
<P>
   Both Rios are about the size of a pager and play music that has
been converted into the MP3 format, a method for storing, playing
and sharing audio on computers.
</P>
<P>
   When the first Rio came out in November, music companies had no
way to prevent people from copying music from a CD into the MP3
format and sharing it with others _ for free _ over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the first Rio _ an estimated 125,000 were sold
_ forced the recording industry to find a way to encrypt, or
scramble, music to thwart MP3 pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The first Rio, which now sells for as low as $119, can only play
music that has not been encrypted. Although the music industry
still has not agreed on a standard for encryption, Diamond says the
new Rio will be able to play copyright-protected music no matter
what standard is adopted.
</P>
<P>
   It also will play not just MP3 songs but also music stored in a
variety of other formats, including Microsoft's upcoming Windows
Media Audio.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst predicts that the Rio and other handheld digital
audio players could be a hot gift item by this Christmas, although
so far, only the original Rio MP3 player is on U.S. store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the lead in the market and we want to leverage that
lead,'' said David Watkins, president of RioPort Inc., a new
division of San Jose's Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio demonstrated the potential for sales of digital music
over the Internet. RioPort will try to cash in on that potential by
selling music, audio books, foreign language lessons and other
audio products over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hardie, an analyst with Forrester Research Inc., said the
RioPort and the new Rio should keep Diamond, which is being
acquired by chipmaker S3, at the forefront of the market as other
competing devices start to appear later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Labs Inc. of Milpitas, for example, is developing its
Nomad MP3 player that also has an FM radio. Sony Corp. is also
working on its own digital music player.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time, I've been concerned because Diamond had
the market in their hand and they weren't doing anything,'' Hardie
said. ``They were sitting there resting on their laurels.''
</P>
<P>
   In related news, Musicland Stores Corp., which owns video and
music stores including Sam Goody and Suncoast, launched a series of
new Web sites to sell CDs and videos online.
</P>
<P>
   Musicland Vice Chairman Keith Benson said the online sites could
eventually sell digital music directly to consumers through the
Internet or even at existing stores.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is not concerned the digital music revolution will
replace his traditional stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see this as a big negative to stores,'' Benson said.
``The Internet will be a transfer of market from stores, but since
the entire record industry is growing at about 6 to 7 percent per
year, nobody's going to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
