<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER MOVES TO KENTUCKY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ill., Ky, Texas) 
 
By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ The search for suspected serial killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez is now focusing on Kentucky because he has
relatives in the Lexington area and a man matching his description
was recently seen in Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Lexington police, along with a multi-agency task force
headquartered in Houston, believe the 38-year-old Mexican national
has returned to Kentucky, where the first of the string of eight
murders occurred in August 1997. Resendez-Ramirez was formally
charged Wednesday with the murder of University of Kentucky student
Christopher Maier and the rape of Maier's girlfriend, police said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Resendez-Ramirez was charged with the June 15 murders
of two people in Jackson County, Ill., about 50 miles from the
Kentucky state line.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they had received reports that he was seen last
week at two homeless shelters in Louisville, and possibly a third
time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The description we have of Rafael Ramirez was he was wearing a
white shirt, blue jeans, carrying a baseball cap. That was verified
through independent sources in Illinois,'' said Lexington Police
Sgt. Mark Barnard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sightings in Louisville indicated the same clothing
description from independent sources, with the baseball cap being
brown in color he was carrying or wearing at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnard said workers and patrons at the shelters were shown
pictures of Resendez-Ramirez and confirmed that he was the man they
had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is about 5-foot-7, 145 pounds. He uses many
aliases and changes his appearance frequently, although he is
believed to need prescription eyeglasses. He has scars on a right
fingertip, left arm and forehead, a faded tattoo of a snake on his
left forearm and, possibly, a tattoo of a flower on his left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army shelter in Louisville would not discuss the
reported sighting there, but the director of the St. Vincent De
Paul Center in that city said a man fitting Resendez-Ramirez's
description ate in their kitchen Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that it was him, but a person fitting the
description given to us by the FBI generally fit the man,'' said
center director John Cecil. ``In Louisville, Kentucky, that man
would stand out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cecil said the man was at the shelter about 20 minutes, just
long enough to eat. The center does not require patrons to sign in
or out for meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was no different from all the other people we serve in the
kitchen,'' Cecil said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not been sighted in Lexington, Barnard said
authorities here plan to hand out about 1,000 pocket-sized cards
with Resendez-Ramirez's picture to homeless shelters and the
Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that Rafael Ramirez is somewhere in the state of
Kentucky,'' Barnard said. ``We know he has family members here. We
know he has been here. This is where the earliest murder that we
had originates from... So there's a cell for him to operate out of
here somewhere or some knowledge that he has in the Lexington area.
That's got out interest high... And we are taking every
precaution.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnard would not elaborate on who the family members were,
saying only they were established citizens and were cooperating
fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is on a killing spree,'' said Assistant Lexington
Police Chief F.D. Root said. ``Certainly he is acting with reckless
abandon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Five of the murders Resendez-Ramirez has been linked to occurred in
Texas. On Dec. 17, 1998, the stabbed body of Dr. Claudia Benton was
found in her home in West University Place.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, the bodies of Norman and Karen Sirnic were found in
Weimer, Texas. On June 4, the bludgeoned body of Josephine
Konvicka, 73, was found in her Fayette County home. One day later,
Noemi Dominguez's beaten body was found in Houston in her home in
the 6900 block of Van etten. Her stolen car was found later in Del
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Last week George Morber, 80 and his daughter Carolyn Frederick,
52, were found dead in their home in Gorham, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In northeast Texas, Hughes Springs police are trying to
determine if a palm print left at the Oct. 2 slaying of 87-year-old
Lefie Mason match those of Resendez-Ramirez. Mason's home in the
small town north of Tyler also was near train tracks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
