<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7401 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTING-COMPUTING_S     06-23 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-COMPUTING </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A/Dave Einstein  &HT;     Pros and Cons Of Cable Modems 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I'm thinking about getting cable Internet service, which
recently became available in my community. But I've heard that it's
not really as fast as they say and that it can get pretty slow if
there are too many subscribers. Practically speaking, what kind of
speeds should I expect? Also, what if I want to connect a second PC
in my house to the service? Does that cost extra?
<P>
   A: Companies like AtHome say their cable modem connections
deliver the Internet up to 20 times faster than a 28.8
kilobits-per-second modem, which would make it 2.9 megabits a
second. In reality, however, you're never going to see that kind of
speed. The average user will get anywhere from 300 to 800 kilobits
per second. And yes, the speed does drop if a lot of people in a
local area are using the service at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the over-inflated claims, however, cable Internet
service is still a great deal, even at about $40 a month. That's
twice the price of the average dial-up connection. But the cable
connection doesn't tie up your telephone line. If you're an
Internet junkie, that's important. And best of all, the cable
service is always on, so you don't have to dial in each time you
want to use it.
</P>
<P>
   As to your other question, adding a second PC to a cable modem
account generally costs $5 to $10 per month. The service providers
say they have to charge for it because each PC connected through
the cable needs its own dedicated Internet address. Au contraire.
With a home-networking package such as AnyPoint from Intel, a
second PC in your home can share the primary Internet connection
for free, whether it's from a dial-up Internet service provider or
a cable service. Both PCs can be used simultaneously to surf the
Web, with no appreciable loss of speed. But bear in mind that
AnyPoint costs $189. So if you don't really need a home network,
you might be better off biting the bullet and paying the cable
company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Talk's Cheap _ Word Isn't
</P>
<P>
   Q: My new PC came with Microsoft Works. It's a pretty bare-bones
suite of applications, and the word processor that's included just
isn't going to cut if for me. I'd like to get Microsoft Word, but I
know it's pricey. Are there any alternatives to Word that could do
the job and save me some money?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: You're right about Word being expensive. In fact, the
latest version, Word 2000, will cost you about $320. (You also can
get it as part of the Office 2000 suite for $450.) The most
cost-effective alternative probably is Word Pro 97, a full-fledged
word processor from Lotus which carries a street price of $62.
</P>
<P>
   You also might try hunting around for a program called Microsoft
Home Essentials. At under $100, it's a helluva deal _ comes with
Word 97 (the version that Word 2000 replaced) as well as versions
of Microsoft Money and Encarta, the CD encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   But Home Essentials may be hard to find because it appears that
Microsoft has phased it out (probably because it was cannibalizing
sales of Word and Microsoft Office). If you can't find Home
Essentials in any stores, try locating a used copy on eBay or one
of the other online auction houses. Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Scanner SetUp
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd like to add a scanner to my system, but there's no place
to plug it into my computer. I already have a Zip drive connected
to the parallel port on the back of the PC, and my printer is
plugged into the pass-through port on the back of the Zip drive.
Any suggestions for a way to connect a scanner?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: You have a couple of options. One is to get a switch box,
which will let you run multiple devices off the single parallel
port on your PC. A simple switch box with two connections costs as
little as $7. Boxes allowing for more devices cost up to $50. Your
other option is to buy a scanner that uses a USB connection rather
than a parallel port (assuming that your PC has a USB port and that
you have Windows 98 or a later version of Windows 95 that supports
USB).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Optimizing your hard drive with Windows' Disk Defragmenter can
improve your system's performance. (It takes information that's
strewn around the disk and puts it back in order.) But defragging a
big drive can take more than an hour. So take advantage of the
Maintenance Wizard in Windows 98, which lets you run the Disk
Defragmenter at a scheduled time when you don't have to use the PC.
Go to Start/Programs/Accessories/System Tools, click Maintenance
Wizard, and follow the instructions.
</P>
</TEXT>
