</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFTER-HOURS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: EXTENDED TRADING HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that after-hours trading is coming. But nobody
seems to know when.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ says it can be ready this fall, but prefers to wait until
next year. The New York Stock Exchange says it does not want to be
ready this year, and will wait until next year at least. Several
upstart electronic trading networks say they are ready to go as
soon as July. And the Securities and Exchange Commission, in a
solution befitting a government agency, wants to have a meeting to
select a committee to begin discussing the issues.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: Investors do not yet need to start burning
the midnight oil.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt Jr. said he would
convene a meeting June 30 to explore the issues raised by
after-hours trading with the major stock exchanges, brokerage firms
and consumer groups. The meeting will be co-sponsored by the Big
Board and the National Association of Securities Dealers, which
oversees the NASDAQ Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   Following the meeting, the three sponsors will select working
group participants to iron out details about extended trading
hours, including issues of investor protection and education,
clearance and settlement of trades, other trading conventions like
trading halts and dissemination of market data, and options market
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summit will begin an industrywide effort to address issues
raised by after-hours trading that impact our U.S. capital
markets,'' Levitt said in a statement. ``Our goal is to insure that
market integrity and investor confidence remain strong, regardless
of when the markets are open.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, U.S. stock markets are open from 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Various proposals for evening-hours trading call for sessions to
extend from 5 p.m. to 9 p.m. or thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   But institutional investors and small brokerage firms, among
others, have objected to the plans, in part because they do not
want to have to staff their offices late into the evening. Critics
also say that the after-hours markets, with fewer participants,
will be less liquid, causing stock prices to be more volatile and
less reflective of a company's real value.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of after-hours trading say that individual investors
want to be able to trade at night, when they have more time to
research their investments. In a digital world, they say, it no
longer makes sense to restrict their trading activity to a few
hours that are most convenient to people on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear what effect, if any, the SEC's summit meeting
will have on the possibility that some private networks will allow
individual investors to begin trading after hours this year.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has said it will not stand in the way of the electronic
communications networks, or ECNs, that want to start evening
trading this year. But the commission has said it will keep a close
eye on them.
</P>
<P>
   Among those ECNs is Eclipse Trading, which has received
investment commitments from two big Wall Street brokerage firms,
Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
Two others, Wit Capital and Island ECN, a subsidiary of Datek
Online Holdings Corp., have said they want to offer extended
trading hours by next year.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ, meanwhile, said last month that it would begin planning
to extend its trading hours as soon as this fall. But it insisted
that it wanted all parties to coordinate the start of after-hours
trading. When the Big Board said it would wait until 2000, NASDAQ's
plans became less clear.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance at the National Press Club in Washington on
Wednesday, NASD chairman Frank Zarb said the smartest thing would
appear to be delaying after-hours trading until next year.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ officials said that while they could be ready for
after-hours trading this year, they would have to shift computer
programmers to that effort from other tasks, namely preparing for
the Year 2000 change-over and preparing for a switch to the
reporting of stock prices in decimals.
</P>
<P>
   That is not all going on at NASDAQ. Zarb said the NASD is
interested in building a futures trading business, which would
start with Treasury debt instruments and expand to other products.
The organization is also considering spinning off its regulatory
subsidiary and converting the NASDAQ Stock Market to public
ownership, complete with an initial public offering of shares in
the market.
</P>
<P>
   With so much on its plate, NASDAQ officials say they would not
be upset if evening trading in the United States was delayed until
next year. That would put the start date closer to that of its new
NASDAQ-Japan venture, which is expected to start up in the fourth
quarter of 2000. NASDAQ-Japan will offer trading of the 100 largest
NASDAQ stocks in Japan during Japanese market hours.
</P>
<P>
   Together with evening trading hours in the United States, the
NASDAQ-Japan proposal would provide NASDAQ investors with a
semblance of around-the-clock trading _ close to 24 hours a day, if
not seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors want it, so extended hours will be a reality,'' Zarb
said Wednesday. The big question is when.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
