<HEADER>
A7420 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VERN-FRAUD-KAN &LR;      06-23 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERN-FRAUD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI REP. VERNON THOMPSON FACES FRAUD CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri Rep. Vernon Thompson, his son and
two others conspired to steal more than $250,000 in federal
anti-poverty funds from low-income apartment developments in Kansas
City, federal prosecutors charged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged in a 22-count indictment were Kevin R. Sallard and
Tuscon D. Redd, the owner and operator of a company that managed
several federally subsidized multifamily housing projects in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   According to the charges, as part of the alleged scheme Sallard,
40, and Jamil Thompson, 22, worked as straw employees of Redd's
management company, Omega Realty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about public funds that were intended to improve
the lives of financially disadvantaged people that ended up lining
the pockets of privileged people,'' Chris Whitley, a Justice
Department spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's attorney, Greg Vleisides, maintained his client's
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Mr. Thompson denies all of the charges,'' Vleisides
said. ``Without seeing the evidence, I think it's a weak case. By
the time we're done with it, we'll be able to prove Mr. Thompson
did not act improperly.''
</P>
<P>
   Redd's attorney, John P. O'Connor, said he had not yet seen the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he appears in court he'll be entering a plea of not
guilty,'' O'Connor said. He declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Sallard did not return calls to his home. Jamil Thompson did not
return calls to the Thompson home Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Sallard and the Thompsons worked
with Redd from April 1997 through May 1998 to misappropriate more
than $250,000 from accounts maintained to operate low-income
housing developments managed by Omega Realty.
</P>
<P>
   All four defendants were charged with conspiracy. In addition,
Vernon Thompson faces five counts of mail fraud for allegedly
working with Redd to mail more than $3,400 in fraudulent payroll
checks for work that his son and Sallard never performed.
</P>
<P>
   Redd, 44, faces 11 additional mail-fraud counts and five
money-laundering charges for allegedly concealing the theft of
$112,509 through five bank transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Jamil Thompson faces four mail fraud charges, and Sallard faces
one.
</P>
<P>
   The charges allege that after the funds were transferred into
Omega Realty accounts, the four then used the money for their own
benefit. They also created ``false and misleading'' documents at
Omega Realty and the housing developments to conceal the
conspiracy, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Redd, who recently filed for bankruptcy in Kansas City, claiming
almost $500,000 in debts, faces the harshest potential sentence of
the four, 135 years in prison and $6.75 million in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Thompson could face 30 years in prison and $1.5 million
in fines. Jamil Thompson could be subject to 25 years in prison and
$1.25 million in fines. The maximum Sallard faces is 10 years in
prison and $500,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations into Vernon Thompson and his businesses began in
1997 after The Kansas City Star reported that he twice lobbied a
state agency on housing issues that ultimately benefited his
construction-supply business.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Thompson listed himself on state disclosure records
as an employee of the Citizen Housing and Information Council, a
nonprofit agency that co-developed Basie Court Apartments and
Martin Luther King Village.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, then-Jackson County Prosecutor Claire McCaskill
announced a state investigation into those and other housing issues
raised by The Star. Federal authorities later joined the probe.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation expanded early last year, when the newspaper
raised questions about bingo operations operated by two nonprofit
corporations that Thompson led. State records revealed that bingo
games operated by the nonprofits did not account for some $64,600
in profits as required by state law.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 56, has represented the 37th House district _ which
covers part of Jackson County _ since his election in 1986. He is
chairman of the House Urban Affairs Committee, which handles much
of the state legislation that deals specifically with Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Since the state and federal investigations began in 1996 and
1997, Thompson has lowered his profile in the House.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 1998 session, Thompson drew criticism
when he missed 13 of the House's first 20 floor sessions without
explanation, though his attendance improved after that.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is the second member of the Missouri General Assembly
to be indicted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, former House Speaker Bob Griffin pleaded guilty to one
count of fraud and one count of accepting a bribe from political
consultant Cathryn Simmons. Griffin is serving a four-year prison
sentence in Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
