<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INVESTIGATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOAK, DAGGER AND STRONG-ARMING IN THE RUSSIAN FAR EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By RUSSELL WORKING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VLADIVOSTOK, Russia _ Investors in the Russian Far East are used
to working with risks: the currency is fragile, deposits disappear
when banks close, and companies can be taxed out of existence
before they show a profit.
</P>
<P>
   But a new threat this week has rattled foreign business groups
here: a regional governor announced Monday that he was using the
main successor agency to the KGB to investigate whether a prominent
British businessman had illegally obtained shares for foreign
clients in Russia's biggest shipping company.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was followed by a demonstration Wednesday,
attended by ranking government officials, against foreign investors
in Russian shipping fleets.
</P>
<P>
   The Primorsky regional governor, Yevgeny Nazdratenko, said at a
news conference Monday that he had asked the Federal Security
Service, known as the FSB, to look into the business dealings of
British investor Andrew Fox, who serves on the board of Far Eastern
Shipping Co.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after Fox, who owns a brokerage firm,
Tiger Securities, said Nazdratenko had threatened to jail him in an
attempt to extort 7 percent of the shares of foreign investors
represented by Fox. The governor was also said to have demanded
that a candidate of his choosing be appointed general director and
that a new board be elected.
</P>
<P>
   Nazdratenko denied making the threat and maintained that Fox
misunderstood him in a meeting June 3 in which they discussed the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman's accusation spurred Vladivostok's
government-dominated media into a weeklong series of Soviet-style
denunciations of Fox. On Tuesday, the tabloid Novosti accused Fox,
who is also the honorary British consul in Vladivostok, of wanting
to sell Far Eastern Shipping's fleet, so that ``we will have to
close all the maritime academies of Russia and delete Russia from
the list of seafaring countries.'' Even such national papers as
Izvestia published articles attacking Fox in their Far Eastern
editions.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the drumbeat of accusations from the governor's
office and in the media boiled over into a demonstration. Fox's
competitors at a refrigerated shipping line named Vostoktransflot,
who had also been assailing him all week, hired buses to bring
maritime academy students, sailors, captains and others to downtown
Vladivostok for a demonstration, company officials confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1,000 people showed up to denounce Russian
businessmen close to Fox as ``agents of imperialism.'' The city's
mayor, Yuri Kopylov, denounced a Russian journalist whom he
glimpsed interviewing a business partner of Fox's. ``She won't be a
reporter for long,'' he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the region is courting South Korean and Japanese
investors to rebuild two major ports, Nazdratenko blamed foreigners
for ruining the Russian Far East's limping economy. He called for
the nationalization of strategic industries, including shipping. In
a rambling statement that included attacks on NATO, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and the Chinese, Nazdratenko said Fox
``only fulfills the will of other states that want Russia not to
have anything,'' and added, ``He has his masters that he works
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox left the country last week amid the accusations and fears of
imprisonment. Reached by phone in London, he laughed when told of
Nazdratenko's latest accusations. ``I don't even think he knows
what he's talking about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the attacks against him have sent a chill through foreign
business executives in the Russian Far East, many of whom had
gathered in a Vladivostok hotel late last week for a U.S.-Russian
conference largely devoted to trade.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners asked about the Fox affair were almost all upset. A
longtime Western businessman in Vladivostok who did not want to be
identified by name said the attack was all the more unnerving
because of Fox's stature as one of the early investors in the
Russian Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who has lived in Vladivostok since 1992, estimates that
Tiger Securities has brought in $30 million to $40 million in
investment to companies in Primorsky, the southeastern finger of
Russia flanked by China and the Sea of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried about the attacks, because Andrew was one
of the most successful foreigners in town,'' the businessman said.
``He was kind of a legend, really. People always talk about Andrew
Fox _ he's got his hands in everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Consulate in Vladivostok sent a letter asking
Nazdratenko to disown the comments attributed to him and to leave
Fox alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kalicki, a Commerce Department official who was visiting
Vladivostok as a part of a working group from the U.S. West Coast
and the Russian Far East, said, ``We told him that first of all we
hope they will make sure that they will take no action of the sort
suggested in the report, and that secondly that they will issue a
statement making clear that this is not the attitude of the
administration here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nazdratenko has wielded increasingly unchallenged power in the
Primorsky region. Courts sympathetic to the governor have
invalidated the elections of political rivals this year. His
administration owns the only printing press in Primorsky, and the
governor's allies head the two television stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
