<HEADLINE>
NYC SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR SHAKES UP LOW-PERFORMING SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew on Wednesday announced a
shake-up of New York City's lowest-performing schools, encompassing
56 of the system's 1,100 schools and nine of its 32 district
superintendents. He said that to continue to allow schools to fail
would be ``unforgivable.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which was unanimously approved Wednesday at a
meeting of the Board of Education, Crew will close 13
low-performing schools and take direct control of 43 others,
including three high schools and 40 elementary and middle schools.
In those 40, he will offer a 15 percent raise to every teacher who
agrees to work longer hours and commits to staying three years.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal negotiated with the United Federation of Teachers and
endorsed by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Monday, those schools will
add 40 minutes of instruction a day, along with five days for
teacher training at the start of the school year. Class sizes will
be reduced, strict curriculums will be adopted and all children
will be required to go to summer school. Most of the $40 million
cost will come from state aid, Board of Education officials said,
adding that money would not be cut from other school programs to
compensate.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the city's 32 superintendents are being removed, Crew
said: Two are being dismissed, one will be transferred to another
job in the schools and two are retiring. Four more have been put on
notice that he is concerned about their performance, and that they
will undergo a yearlong probation, in which they will be supervised
by Crew and his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   He will close 13 schools that have failed to meet state
standards and that could have been closed by the state at the end
of June. Three of those schools will be closed by next week and
their students transferred to other schools, while the rest will be
phased out over two years. The 13 schools will be replaced with new
schools, and many of their principals and teachers will be removed
or transferred to other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is the strongest single action that Crew has taken since he
became chancellor in October 1995, and since a state law was passed
in December 1996 giving him increased central control over what had
been a decentralized school system for nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he could no longer tolerate large pockets of failure
across the city, and reacting in part to dismal scores in reading
and math released over the last two weeks, Crew said, ``The system
simply cannot be a tale of two cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said the overhaul was the culmination of more than four
months of planning and the experience he has gained since taking
over the New York City school system, with its 1.1 million
students, in October 1995. He said he waited until now to act so
decisively in part because he lacked the power until the new state
law came into being, but also because he wanted first to impose
higher standards and then to give people fair notice that they
would be held accountable for meeting them.
</P>
<P>
   Crew has done all the things he announced Wednesday before, but
never on such a grand scale. Over the last three years, he has
removed or pressured into retirement eight superintendents,
according to aides. He has also closed 24 schools, up to seven in a
single a year, though the plans for some of those closings predated
him. Shortly after he took office, he created what he called the
chancellor's district, putting 13 failing schools under his direct
supervision in an effort to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education president William Thompson Jr., a close ally
of Crew, praised the chancellor for ``a gutsy move to take over
this many schools at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew announced his overhaul just two weeks after both state and
citywide tests showed a decline in achievement. Two-thirds of the
city's fourth-graders failed a new state reading and writing test,
and one out of five scored in the bottom level, meaning that they
can barely read or write. Math scores on a citywide test dropped 10
points, and scores even declined in third-grade reading, a
centerpiece of Crew's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The city has more schools on a state list of failing schools _
97 _ than ever before in its history, and state Education
Commissioner Richard Mills has threatened to close them down if
they do not improve.
</P>
<P>
   Crew has also been engaged in a very public feud with Giuliani,
who has labeled the school system dysfunctional and advocated the
abolition of the central Board of Education and its replacement
with a mayoral agency.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest test of Crew's plan will be his ability to turn
around the 43 schools that he has taken under his direct control.
He gave himself a deadline of two years to do that, although he
could well be gone by then. His current contract expires in a year,
with a two-year option to renew.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking change in those schools, which are scattered
throughout the city, is the package of financial incentives he is
offering to the teachers and paraprofessionals who work in them.
The package was negotiated with the United Federation of Teachers
and signed off on by Giuliani on Monday, aides to Crew said,
although City Hall is not paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes raises of 15 percent _ $6,000 for a
midlevel teacher _ for teachers who agree to work 40 minutes more
each day and to go through a week of training in the summer. The
teachers' union has long resisted calls for merit pay, and this
agreement skirts that issue by providing the payments to all
teachers in a school, regardless of experience, test scores or
other criteria based on performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
