<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONES-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICESTREAM AND OMNIPOINT ANNOUNCE $3 BILLION MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Voicestream Wireless Corp. and Omnipoint Corp., two regional
wireless communications companies seeking to expand their national
presence, said Wednesday that they would merge in a cash and stock
transaction valued at nearly $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will provide the new company with coverage of a far
broader swath of the country than either company has alone, with
licenses in 17 of the top 25 major wireless markets. The combined
company would provide service to more than a million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Following the merger, Voicestream will be the country's largest
provider of wireless service using the technology known as GSM, for
Global System for Mobile Communications. GSM, the dominant format
for wireless service in Europe, has been adopted in this country
mostly by smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   As nationwide wireless carriers like AT&AMP;T, Sprint and Nextel
have beefed up their networks and expanded their marketing, smaller
regional carriers like Omnipoint and Voicestream have found it
harder to compete. By expanding its so-called footprint, or the
portion of the map covered by its communications services, the
newly merged company hopes to attract more customers and save on
marketing and back-office costs.
</P>
<P>
   In the transaction, which is expected to close in the fourth
quarter, Omnipoint shareholders will receive cash and stock valued
at about $32 a share, a 55 percent premium to the company's recent
stock price. Omnipoint has about 53 million shares outstanding,
making the purchase part of the transaction worth about $1.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hutchison Telecommunications Ltd. of Hong Kong, a
major shareholder in Voicestream, has agreed to invest $957 million
in the newly merged company.
</P>
<P>
   Voicestream has also agreed to invest $150 million in Omnipoint
prior to the close of the merger, including approximately $100
million to be provided immediately. Including assumed debt, the
entire transaction can be valued at $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a further component of the deal, Cook Inlet Region Inc., a
native Alaskan corporation, is to invest in a joint venture to
acquire certain licenses held by Omnipoint. Cook Inlet Region will
own 50.1 percent of the venture, and Voicestream will own the
remainder.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Cook Inlet Region, the newly merged company will
have licenses to provide service to more than 175 million people in
the United States, said John Stanton, who will remain chairman and
chief executive of Voicestream following the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Smith, currently chairman of Omnipoint, will become a vice
chairman of the combined company and will focus on developing the
new company's wireless data strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Omnipoint shareholders will receive $8 a share in cash and 0.825
share of Voicestream common stock for each of their Omnipoint
shares. Omnipoint shares rose 6.25 cents, to $20.8125 Wednesday,
while Voicestream shares rose 12.5 cents, to $29.50.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutchison investment will raise its ownership to 30 percent
of the combined company, assuming the exercise of certain
conversion rights in convertible preferred securities that it owns.
Prior to the merger, Hutchison owned 24 percent of Voicestream.
</P>
<P>
   Voicestream, which was spun off by Western Wireless only a month
ago, was advised in the transaction by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. Allen &AMP;
Co. and Lehman Brothers advised Omnipoint.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2246EDT &QL; 
