<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHO'S WHO OF TOP PLAYERS CONTEND FOR RYDER CUP POINTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ Imagine a U.S. Ryder Cup team this fall without
Fred Couples, Justin Leonard, Tom Lehman and Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   It could happen. Only the top 10 players in the Ryder Cup points
standing through Aug. 17 will automatically qualify for the team.
And as of Wednesday, neither Couples (No. 13), Leonard (No. 15),
Lehman (No. 19), nor Janzen (No. 21) were in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the race for Ryder Cup points will be one of golf's
summer subplots, including this week, when many of the PGA Tour's
top players compete in the Buick Classic at Westchester Country
Club. Couples, Leonard, Lehman, and Janzen will be playing at
Westchester, along with three of the top seven players in the world
ranking: David Duval (No. 1), Vijay Singh (No. 4), and Ernie Els
(No. 7).
</P>
<P>
   This year's U.S. Ryder Cup captain, Ben Crenshaw, is also
playing Westchester, and he will add two captain's picks to the 10
players who automatically make the team. As Crenshaw stood in front
of his locker Wednesday, he paused to look at the latest Ryder Cup
points standings. If Ryder Cup veterans like Couples, Leonard,
Lehman and Janzen don't make the team on their own, Crenshaw's two
picks could become even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an interesting next few months,'' said
Crenshaw, who will captain the team that faces Europe, Sept. 24-26,
at the Country Club in Brookline, Mass. ``I think when it's time to
decide, one of the picks will become fairly obvious. But that last
pick will keep me up at night. In fact, it already is.''
</P>
<P>
   While Crenshaw pondered what would happen this fall, others were
concentrating on what would happen this weekend. The Buick Classic
is the first PGA Tour event since Sunday's thrilling conclusion to
the United States Open, won by Payne Stewart, who made a 15-foot
putt on the final hole to defeat Phil Mickelson by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Although some top players like Tiger Woods and Davis Love 3d
took this week off, many players were looking forward to competing
again. Duval, who is still looking for his first major
championship, was deeply disappointed after finishing tied for
seventh at the U.S. Open, but he insisted that he had regrouped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot more ready than I thought I would be,'' said Duval,
who enjoyed taking batting practice with the Mets on Tuesday. ``I
expect myself to be prepared and ready to play well when I tee it
up. Those are my expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning 11 tournaments since October 1997, Duval secured a spot
on the Ryder Cup team months ago. But while he was looking forward
to his first Ryder Cup, Duval had a different take on the biennial
competition than some players.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Stewart said he would shake teammates by the throat
who weren't excited about the Ryder Cup, Duval smiled and said,
``He better not put his hands around my throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Duval expanded on his view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm looking forward to it,'' he said. ``But you talk with
the players, and it's a tough week. There's a lot of pressure. I'm
not saying I'm not going to be ready to play. I'm like any
competitor. But I don't see it as the end-all, be-all thing in golf
that a lot of other people seem to view it as.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, those players who are not in the top-10 Ryder Cup standing
hope that their push to make the team leads to better play. Duval,
Woods, Stewart, Love, and Mark O'Meara are No. 1 through No. 5,
respectively, in Ryder Cup points, and appear to have made the
team. Hal Sutton (No. 6), Jim Furyk (No. 7), Mickelson (No. 8),
Jeff Maggert (No. 9), and Steve Stricker (No. 10) complete the top
10 at the moment, but John Huston (No. 11), Steve Pate (No. 12),
Couples, Jeff Sluman (No. 14), and Leonard remain in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't play better, I won't be on the team,'' said
Couples. ``To be part of it would be awesome, but if not, there are
better players around now than me. But the whole thing is winning
it. I've been on five Ryder Cup teams and I've won twice. It's an
honor to play, but we've lost the last two, and when you don't win,
it's kind of tough to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, who played in his first Ryder Cup in 1997, wants to
help the United States change its Ryder Cup fortunes. But to do
that, Leonard will have to play well this summer. And he hoped this
week would be the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has everything to do with how I plan my schedule, this time
of year,'' said Leonard. ``It's a goal I want to achieve, and if I
don't, I'll be disappointed.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
