<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S PRESIDENT OUSTS BANK BOARD THAT OPPOSED TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ In an effort to reassert control over unruly
factions in the government bureaucracy, President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso has dismissed the board of one of the largest
government-controlled banks after it opposed an important tax.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso on Tuesday evening ousted the 10 highest-ranking
executives of Banco do Estado de Sao Paulo SA, known as Banespa,
including the president, Joao Alberto Magro. The bank had sought a
court order aimed at freeing itself from paying a 0.38 percent tax
on financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The tax, which this year is expected to raise at least 7 billion
reais _ now $3.9 billion _ is considered essential in containing
the nation's budget deficit, a lingering worry among investors
concerned with the long-term health of the Brazilian economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want people questioning this tax in the courts,''
said Walter Molano, head of Latin American research at BCP
Securities in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The latest source of dissent, from a bank ranked as Brazil's
sixth-largest and controlled by national authorities, came at a
time when the president's ability to limit crises within the
government has been called into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an extreme example of how Cardoso can't control his
executive branch,'' said David Fleischer, a political science
professor at the University of Brasilia.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Cardoso has had to deal with the resignation of
the appointee to head the federal police after the candidate was
accused of torture during military rule in the 1970s. That episode
followed a dispute between high-ranking aides on economic
development policy and a scandal over the freewheeling use of
military jets by Cabinet ministers for personal trips.
</P>
<P>
   Although the president's popularity rating has slipped to its
lowest level since he took office in 1995, his swift move against
Banespa is seen by some as a turning point. Earlier this week, the
president promised ``zero tolerance'' of dissent within the
government in an effort to strengthen his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Banespa has been a burden, with a history of bad loans. It is
scheduled to be privatized in October.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's largest privately owned banks, along with several
foreign institutions, are preparing bids for Banespa. ``Barring
strong opposition from unions, there is every indication Banespa
will be sold this year,'' said Erivelto Rodrigues, head of Austin
Asis, a banking-analysis firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
