<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE ANALYST WAS ACTUAL AUTHOR OF KOSOVO ESSAY ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The mystery over the fake Shalikashvili essay has been
solved _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   A 2,000-word essay harshly critical of the Clinton
administration's handling of the Kosovo crisis _ erroneously
attributed to former Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen. John
Shalikashvili _ has circulated widely over the Internet for the
past month, prompting the retired Army general to publicly deny its
authorship two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   George Friedman, a defense analyst and author from Austin,
Texas, has stepped forward to claim ownership of the article, which
accuses the Clinton administration of entering the Kosovo conflict
with insufficient military force. It also predicts that NATO
partners are moving toward a new collective security policy to
minimize U.S. leadership in the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, who runs a global defense analysis firm in Austin with
his wife, Meredith Friedman, said he wrote the essay, ``The World
After Kosovo,'' as an article posted on his Internet Web site _
www.stratfor.com _ on May 3. Several weeks later, they began
hearing that the article was being recirculated under
Shalikashvili's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our own analysis'' of the impact of Kosovo, said
Friedman, who with his wife wrote ``The Coming War with Japan''
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like the retired general, Friedman said he was angered and
frustrated over the misidentification, but decided to ``let the
thing die quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few modalities (on the Internet) to solve this
kind of problem,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said neither he nor his computer-savvy colleagues have
been able to determine how _ or why _ his name was removed and
Shalikashvili's name was added to the essay. William Arkin, who
writes a column on Internet and defense issues for The Washington
Post, noted last week the essay was circulated as an attachment on
e-mail and had not been posted on the World Wide Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
