<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIANS GATHER AT CAPITOL, REMEMBERING GAMES' IDEALS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They gathered on the steps of the Capitol, more
than 100 American Olympians _ from Fred Pollard, who has spent a
lifetime describing how it felt to be a black man confronting Adolf
Hitler at Berlin's 1936 Games, to Beth Botsford, a 16-year-old
double gold medal winner in 1996 who was late for Wednesday's
Olympic Day festivities because she would not miss her morning swim
practice.
</P>
<P>
   They came to uphold and salute the Olympic movement, living
monuments to its ideals, arriving in the nation's capital at a
time, not coincidentally, when the Olympic spirit could use a
boost. Several disquieting months of investigation into the abuses
of the bidding process for host Olympic cities was a ubiquitous
smirch to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   But under a brilliant sun, the jewels of American international
athletic competition from seven decades congregated, 47 gold medal
winners in all, their stories a reminder, in most cases, of a time
when Olympic athletes sold shoes and taught high school between
their workouts.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was much like a family reunion, with hugs on arrival
followed by the exchanging of pictures _ of children,
grandchildren, great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Davenport, a gold medal hurdler who cherished the Olympic
experience he first encountered in 1964 so much he chased it into
the Winter Olympics as a bobsledder in 1980, chatted with the 1948
gold medal sprinter Harrison Dillard _ one generation's preeminent
hurdler swapping stories with another. Jim Ryun and Billy Mills,
American distance running royalty, posed for pictures. The gymnast
Bart Conner, when he wasn't critiquing the cartwheel technique of
attending children, drifted in and out of several conversations
with his fellow Olympians, at home it seemed whether the sport
being discussed was track or swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a saying amongst ourselves,'' Conner said. ``There are
no former Olympians. We all have respect for each other's
accomplishments, secure in knowing our success wasn't an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can luck your way into money or fame. You can win the
lottery tomorrow. You can't luck your way into the Olympics. Being
an Olympian has a tag of credibility. It's something we'd like to
preserve.''
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the subtext to the day, which was officially a
celebration of a worldwide Olympic Day. While the athletes may have
been a sideshow to the corruption of the International Olympic
Committee's site selection process, it was these Olympians who felt
a responsibility to offer perspective and solutions to restoring an
ideal they heartily embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I took away from the Olympics wasn't a gold medal,'' said
Mills, whose victory in the 1964 10,000 meters was one of the most
stunning in American Olympic track and field history. ``I took away
an understanding of the dignity and character of global diversity.
That's the power of the Games, and it's the only platform of its
kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our downfall was a profit-at-all-costs mentality. We have to
monitor that. Establish accountability with responsibility,
achievement with consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyomia Tyus was the two-time defending Olympic champion at 100
meters when she retired after the 1968 Games at 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have been just getting started,'' Tyus said Wednesday.
``But I had to find a 9-to-5. That's the way it was then.''
</P>
<P>
   Now working for the Los Angeles school district, she has watched
the U.S. Olympic team blossom with the benefit of huge corporate
sponsorships, and she has watched as the Olympic Games have grown
into something bigger and different than they were for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the spirit of the Games and the will of the athletes is
the same,'' she said. ``We were all brought up with morals. At
times like these, we just have to remember them.''
</P>
<P>
   The swimming champion Donna de Verona, like other Olympians
Wednesday, worried that the negative publicity about the
International Olympic Committee dealings would have too lasting an
impact on potential American corporate sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some departures already,'' she said. ``Sponsors
don't like to be associated with anything negative. When people
looked behind the curtain and saw the indulgences, it was a
betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like today puts the focus back on the athletes. And,
by the way, the system was antiquated and needs to be changed. What
happened is a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end Wednesday, the festivities were part picnic, part
commemoration, a reunion in the classic sense because everyone
vowed to do it again next year. Eras were joined and generations
were bridged.
</P>
<P>
   Botsford, meanwhile, left the picnic a bit early. The Sydney
Olympics are 14 months away. She had an evening swim practice she
could not miss. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
