<SLUG> BC-ADVANCED-MICRO-LOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCED MICRO TO REPORT LARGER-THAN-EXPECTED LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Advanced Micro Devices Inc. said Wednesday that
it would report a larger-than-expected second-quarter loss because
of steep declines in the price of microprocessor chips.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter that ends Sunday, the company said it would have
an operating loss of about $200 million, including various charges
for reorganization, and revenue of less than $600 million, of which
about $250 million will come from microprocessors. That compares
with $632 million in the first quarter. Based on about 146 million
shares outstanding, the loss would come to about $1.37 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts had been expecting a loss of about 40 cents
a share, according to First Call Corp., which tracks company
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro made its warning after the close of the market
but had alerted reporters and analysts late Tuesday to an
announcement. Assuming the worst, investors drove shares of
Advanced Micro down by $1.0625, or 5.5 percent, to $18.1875.
</P>
<P>
   After a loss of $128.4 million, or 88 cents a share, in the
first quarter, Advanced Micro's warnings raised doubts that any
company other than Intel Corp. can profit in the microprocessor
business. In May, National Semiconductor Corp. said it was exiting
the business less than two years after buying its way in with the
$550 million acquisition of Cyrix Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the pricing model for personal computer
microprocessors has been permanently altered. With a $500 personal
computer offering most of the performance and features of a $1,500
PC, nearly all of the industry's growth has shifted to the low end.
</P>
<P>
   There is no room for a $500 microprocessor in a $500 PC, so the
bulk of Advanced Micro and Intel's sales volume has shifted to less
expensive chips. With technology no longer a driving factor, price
is the primary consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, Advanced Micro, based in Sunnyvale, Calif.,
suffered because of its inability to manufacture projected volumes
of its K6-2 microprocessors, particularly the faster chips that
command higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the company's management said it had surmounted these
production difficulties but that aggressive price cuts by Intel,
coupled with the liquidation of Cyrix inventory by National, had
driven down the average selling price of its chips to $60 this
quarter from $78 in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray market activity and three official price cuts by Intel
dashed our hopes,'' said Advanced Micro chairman and chief
executive W.J. Sanders III in a conference call with analysts. He
said Intel was offering smaller PC manufacturers deals on obsolete
circuit boards as well as development services and marketing
support. ``Intel is actually priced below us, and on these packaged
deals they are substantially below us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel can afford deep discounts on its low-end products, partly
because it has the most efficient manufacturing operations in the
business, and partly because they are offset by premium pricing for
high-end processors used in work stations and servers. Advanced
Micro has lacked a high-end offering, but announced Wednesday that
it was shipping the Athlon processor, formerly known as K7, in
speeds as high as 600 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said that he expected average prices of the K6 family of
chips to continue to fall but that this would be offset in part by
substantially higher prices for the Athlon series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
