<SLUG> BC-BESTBOOK-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A TIME OF LISTS AND DEBATING THOSE LISTS, A NEW BOOK CHOOSES THE
100 BEST TV COMMERCIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's millennial fever. Maybe it's the fact that television
has reached maturity, at least chronologically if not emotionally.
Or maybe it's just the fad for compiling lists.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, there has been a rush to designate the
``best'' commercials and advertisements ever made _ and an ensuing
rush to debate the choices.
</P>
<P>
   The trade publication Advertising Age, for instance, recently
offered a list of the 100 best campaigns as part of a special issue
titled ``The Advertising Century.'' TV Guide, in a special issue
coming out on Monday, will present ``the 50 greatest TV commercials
of all time'' as determined by the votes of a panel that included
this columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Another entry in the Madison Avenue version of beauty pageants
arrives Thursday, as Random House publishes ``The 100 Best TV
Commercials ... And Why They Worked'' (Times Business, $29.95) by
Bernice Kanner, a longtime advertising journalist.
</P>
<P>
   The book, being introduced at the 46th International Advertising
Festival in Cannes, France, is based on work by the Leo Burnett Co.
in Chicago. In 1996, Burnett compiled a list of the top 100 spots
as selected by the agency's senior creative executives and leading
professionals throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The book presents an updated version of the Burnett list,
continuing its classification of commercials by categories like
demonstrations, music, fantasy, blockbusters and humor.
</P>
<P>
   One goal of the book is ``to energize our industry that this
caliber of ideas, which can create tremendous success for a brand,
can be sold'' to clients, said Michael Conrad, vice chairman and
chief creative officer at Burnett, who wrote the forward for the
book.
</P>
<P>
   It is also meant, he added, to encourage copywriters and art
directors ``to take risks, to avoid cliches'' because such ``fresh
and new thinking and ideas'' can pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what values predominate among the commercials, Conrad
replied that most ``set a new standard, create a paradigm shift''
in competitive consumer product fields by striving successfully to
``own the major benefit'' in the market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the low-key Volkswagen Beetle commercials by Doyle
Dane Bernbach were focused on ``reliability and economy,'' he
added, while anthemic spots for Marlboro cigarettes by Burnett were
centered on ``flavor, which in tobacco is what you want to own''
and humorous spots for Heineken beer by Lowe Howard-Spink, part of
the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies,
concentrated on ``refreshment, which is to beers what flavor is to
tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   Many commercials included in the book are spots that turn up on
most lists of all-time greats. Among them are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ The larger-than-life ``1984'' commercial for the Apple
Macintosh computer, by what is now the TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of TBWA
Worldwide, part of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   _ The warm and fuzzy paeans to Coca-Cola featuring the football
star Mean Joe Greene and singers atop a hill, by McCann-Erickson
New York, owned by Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two surrealistic spots saluting British Airways by what is now
the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   _ The commercial by Ally &AMP; Gargano promoting Federal Express
that introduced a character who became known as the fast-talking
man.
</P>
<P>
   _ The initial spot in the long-running campaign for Energizer
batteries, also by what is now TBWA/Chiat/Day, in which a pink
bunny kept ``going and going and going'' through make-believe spots
for coffee, nasal spray and wine.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hilarious spot by Doyle Dane, now part of the DDB
Worldwide Communications Group unit of Omnicom, about an actor in a
fictitious food commercial whose occupational hazard, heartburn,
requires Alka-Seltzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's chic to say you're immune to advertising, you're smarter
than advertising,'' Ms. Kanner said, ``but it does invade our
pores.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing the book ``made me like advertising more,'' she added,
``because I was right in the heart of the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the frustrations inherent in narrowing choices, Ms.
Kanner said: ``Some countries aren't represented at all. There are
no Canadian commercials or Mexican commercials. There's nothing for
Levi's from the United States, though there are a couple for Levi's
from Europe. And the Wendy's commercial `Where's the beef?' was one
of the best ever but it wasn't on the list, so it's mentioned in
the description of another Wendy's commercial, `Russian fashion
show,' that was.''
</P>
<P>
   To try rectifying the imbalances, Ms. Kanner selects an
additional dozen commercials for praise in the final chapter in the
book. These are among those commercials:
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Do you know me?'' campaign for American Express, by
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, part of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   _ The commercial that introduced the lying salesman for American
Isuzu Motors, by Della Femina, Travisano &AMP; Partners.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Mikey'' spot for Life cereal from Quaker Oats, by Doyle
Dane.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the book omits or overlooks numerous commercials that
many would consider among the best. Here are some:
</P>
<P>
   _ Spots with dancing cigarettes for Old Gold and Lucky Strike,
from the early days of television.
</P>
<P>
   _ Commercials pairing the animated beer pitchmen Bert and Harry
Piel, for Piel's beer, with voices supplied by the comedians Bob
Elliott and Ray Goulding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spots for Budweiser and Bud Light beers from the campaigns
starring the frogs and the boastful ``Yes I am'' man.
</P>
<P>
   _ A visit to a re-created ``1949 auto show'' for the VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   _ An elaborate production number with the dancer Ann Miller for
Heinz Great American Soups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Any Nike commercials featuring Michael Jordan, particularly
those teaming him with Spike Lee and Bugs Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   DDB, its predecessors and subsidiaries landed the most
commercials on the list of 100, with 20, followed by Burnett with
10 and BBDO Worldwide, owned by Omnicom, with 8. Of the 100 spots,
42 were made in America, followed by Britain with 28 and France
with 8.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, some errors flaw the text of the book. A British Heinz
beans commercial is listed as from ``19TK,'' as in the proofreading
symbol for information to come. (The date is 1988). And in a
description of a commercial for Mates condoms, the spot is compared
with those of other condom makers, ``who'd pitched their brands
largely to Cassanovas.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder those other spots didn't make the list. How large a
market could there be for products aimed at amorous fans of Peggy
Cass?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
