<HEADLINE>
AS OTHER CRIMES CONTINUE TO FALL, KILLINGS INCREASE BY 6 PERCENT
OVER 1998 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The number of killings reported so far this year in
New York City has risen 6 percent over the comparable period last
year, driven by an increase in homicides in Manhattan and Brooklyn.
The rise comes as other types of crime continue to drop and six
months after the city recorded its lowest annual number of
homicides since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, major crime in the city has dropped 10 percent from
this time last year. And the increase in homicides, to 290 from
273, is still well below the 330 recorded at this time in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As of June 13, reported crime had dropped in every borough, in
the subway and in public housing, according to preliminary data
from the Police Department. There were fewer reported rapes,
robberies, burglaries, grand larcenies and car thefts.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, though, slayings have gone up 27 percent from the
comparable period last year, to 56 from 44. In the Washington
Heights section of upper Manhattan alone, the number jumped to 14,
up from 5 by this time last year. In Morningside Heights, near
Columbia University and Harlem, there was only 1 homicide by this
time last year but there have been 4 so far this year, including
the slaying of Jacqueline Frezza, a 34-year-old marketing
consultant, who was killed by a bicycle-riding gunman who shot her
as she left her building. There were only 4 homicides in
Morningside Heights all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, killings are up 19 percent, to 125 so far this year
from 105 in the comparable period last year. In the Bronx, killings
are down 23 percent, to 59 from 77 in the comparable period last
year. In Queens those numbers are up 6 percent, to 47, from 44 in
the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicides come in cycles,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir
said in an interview Wednesday. ``We were seeing earlier in the
year a significant increase in domestic-related homicides, and we
have done things to try to address that. Homicides are still at the
lowest point in 35 years. There is no guarantee that the numbers
will be lower than last year, but that is still the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
