<SLUG> BC-BKN-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McHALE, THOMPSON HEADLINE ADMITEES TO HALL OF FAME  
(jt) 
 By JERRY BREWER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Thompson, who was never hesitant to speak out on
issues ranging from race to college basketball eligibility
standards during 27 years as Georgetown coach, joined Kevin McHale
of the Boston Celtics on Wednesday as the headliners of the
Basketball Hall of Fame class of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, normally vehement and brash, spoke softly in a
telephone interview after the results of the election were
announced here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the period that ends all sentences,'' Thompson said of
his election. ``It's always more effective to whisper than to
shout, and now I get to whisper, `I'm in the Hall of Fame.'''
</P>
<P>
   Also elected to the Hall of Fame, which is based in Springfield,
Mass., were Wayne Embry, the former Cincinnati Royals center and
general manager of the Cleveland Cavaliers; the late Fred Zollner,
who helped found the National Basketball Association and owned the
Fort Wayne Pistons, and Billie Moore, the first women's coach to
lead two different schools (UCLA and Cal State-Fullerton) to
national titles.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who has a weekday morning radio show in Washington,
retired last January. He inherited a 3-23 team in 1972 and complied
a 596-239 record, reaching the Final Four three times and defeating
Houston for the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament
championship in 1984. He coached the U.S. Olympic team to a bronze
medal 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson boycotted two games in 1989 in protest of Proposition
42, an NCAA rule that linked financial aid to athletes' academic
performance, arguing that it hurt minority students. The rule was
overturned by a U.S. District Court in March.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who was Bill Russell's backup in the Boston Celtics'
1965 and 1966 championship seasons, was influential in the
development of such current National Basketball Association stars
as Allen Iverson, Patrick Ewing, Dikembe Mutombo and Alonzo
Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   McHale, whose revolutionary post moves are still mimicked today,
played 12 seasons and won three titles with the Celtics in the
1980s. He was part of one of basketball's greatest frontlines _
McHale, Larry Bird and Robert Parish.
</P>
<P>
   McHale, now vice president for basketball operations for the
Minnesota Timberwolves, averaged 17.9 points, 7.3 rebounds and shot
55 percent in his career. He was a seven-time All-Star and a
three-time member of the NBA's all-defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get honored for something you have so much fun doing,
it just doesn't feel right,'' he said Wednesday. ``I never thought
of it as work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
