<HEADLINE>
SUMMER READING SELECTIONS FOR YOUNG READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With summer break, kids finally have time to read for
fun. Here's a look at some of the newest and best titles, from
picture books to meatier chapter books for older readers.
</P>
<P>
   We've also added a ``lemon alert'' to high-profile books that
left us puckered and perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to read? Here goes:
</P>
<P>
   Picture books
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion and the Unicorn,'' by Shirley Hughes (DK Ink,
$17.95). Ages 5-8.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has to be brave in wartime _ even Lenny, a little boy
who endures loneliness, bigotry and cruel teasing when he's
evacuated to a country estate during the London Blitz. He clutches
a lion-and-unicorn medal for courage, but in the end must find his
own inner strength. This book shows unusual depth of feeling, in
sensitive prose and emotionally wrought watercolors _ all enhanced
by thoughtful page design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too Big!'' by Claire Masurel, illustrated by Hanako Wakiyama
(Chronicle, $13.95). Ages 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie wins a giant, blue-and-white-striped dinosaur at the
carnival and wants to take it everywhere. But it's too big! When
Charlie gets sick and has to stay in bed, ``Big Tex'' proves to be
just right. Charmingly told, charmingly illustrated, in a delicate
retro style that's sweetly hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swine Lake,'' by James Marshall, illustrated by Maurice Sendak
(Harper Collins/Di Capua Books, $15.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   A lean and mangy wolf sneaks into a porcine performance of the
Boarshoi Ballet, hoping to satisfy his taste for, er, art. To his
surprise, he does just that, as the toothsome piggies live to dance
another day. Marshall wrote this lighthearted tale shortly before
his death seven years ago. Sendak, his best bud, turns it into a
memorable pas de deux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eloise in Paris,'' by Kay Thompson, illustrated by Hilary
Knight (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   In this reissued 1957 classic, Eloise, a bon vivant with a flair
for melodrama, describes her exciting trek from New York's Plaza
Hotel to the City of Light. The story is rather wordy and
sophisticated for young children, who might find the original
``Eloise'' more their speed. But it's a fun read-aloud, and
Knight's comic drawings are full of joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morning, Noon and Night,'' by Jean Craighead George,
illustrated by Wendell Minor (HarperCollins, $15.95). Ages 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   A Newbery Medalist with a sure grasp of nature, George achieves
a Margaret Wise Brown feel in this lyrical ode to the rhythms of
the day, from East Coast to West. Poetic in feel, it's a wonderful
bedtime story stunningly illustrated with wildlife scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mystery of Mineral Gorge,'' by Julia Van Nutt, illustrated
by Robert Van Nutt (Doubleday, $15.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a theory about the bloodcurdling screams coming
from Mineral Gorge each night. Could it be the ghostly Woman in
White? When 10-year-old Lucky and three other ``Cobtown heroes'' of
1844 face the mystery head-on, they uncover a happy surprise. The
fright factor is very low voltage in this pleasantly suspenseful
yarn, illustrated in a lighthearted, nostalgic style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cook-A-Doodle-Doo!'' by Janet Stevens and Susan Stevens
Crummel (Harcourt Brace, $17). Ages 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by his famous great-grandmother, the Little Red Hen,
Big Brown Rooster enlists some helpers to whip together a tasty
strawberry shortcake. What Turtle, Pig and Iguana lack in
experience, they make up for in enthusiasm as they learn the value
of teamwork. Crummel's exuberant pictures are a delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luba and the Wren,'' by Patricia Polacco (Philomel, $16.99).
Ages 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   Polacco, a master storyteller, puts a Ukranian spin on the story
of The Fisherman and His Wife. Here a generous peasant girl named
Luba wins unlimited wishes from a rescued wren. Luba desires
nothing, but her hard-working parents have an insatiable list of
demands. In the end, of course, they get their comeuppance. With
warm, affectionate pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bark, George,'' by Jules Feiffer (HarperCollins, $14.95). Ages
2-5.
</P>
<P>
   George is a dog that doesn't bark. Instead, he goes meow,
quack-quack, oink or moo. George's mother takes him to the vet, who
ceremoniously dons a rubber glove and gets to the bottom of the
problem. This minimalist book is over in a flash, but it's fun
while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierre's Dream,'' by Jennifer Armstrong, illustrated by Susan
Gaber (Dial, $15.99). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Lazy, foolish Pierre is napping under an olive tree when a
circus pitches its tent nearby. When he awakes, he assumes the
circus is a dream. Pierre joins the circus stars in feats of
derring-do, confident that no harm can befall a dreamer.
Imaginative, with rich, brilliantly hued pictures that are worth
lingering over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Birchbark House,'' by Louise Erdrich (Hyperion, 235 pages,
$14.99). Ages 9-12.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by her Ojibwa heritage, Erdrich presents an Indian
counterpart to Laura Ingalls Wilder's ``Little House'' books.
Omakayas, a spirited 7-year-old of 1847, rejoices in the
traditional rhythms of life on Lake Superior but also faces hunger,
white encroachment and the devastation of smallpox. Erdrich borrows
freely from ``Little House in the Big Woods''; her drawings even
resemble Garth Williams' beloved ``Little House'' pictures. But her
voice _ warm, lyrical and with a trace of sadness _ is wholly her
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skellig,'' by David Almond (Delacorte, 183 pages, $15.95).
Ages 9-12.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, a young English boy, has much to contend with _ a
deathly ill baby sister, preoccupied parents and the strangeness of
a new home. Then he explores the ramshackle garage and discovers
Skellig, a thin, pale creature covered in dust and cobwebs. Skellig
_ part man, part owl, part angel? _ grows strong in the care of
Michael and his friend Mina and in turn transforms their lives. A
beautifully mysterious story about love and beauty and the power of
rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Hive for the Honeybee,'' by Soinbhe Lally, illustrated by
Patience Brewster (Scholastic, 226 pages, $16.95). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   Bees aren't the easiest creatures to warm to, fuzzy though they
are, but Irish writer Soinbhe Lally makes them surprisingly human
and sympathetic in this metaphorical novel about destiny and
choice. Original and compelling, this thoughtful story unfolds
through the eyes of Thora, a stolid worker bee whose sense of the
possible is challenged by two maverick drones. As Thora learns to
dream, her rebellious friends find nobility in the cruel destiny
that awaits all drones.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Her Majesty's Request: An African Princess in Victorian
England,'' by Walter Dean Myers (Scholastic, 146 pages, $15.95).
Ages 9-up. Non-fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Myers stumbled on the story of Sarah Forbes Bonetta in a packet
of old letters in a London bookshop. Intrigued, he pieced together
the near-fantastic life of this West African princess, who was
rescued from sacrificial death by a British naval officer who was
trying to stop the slave trade. The child grew up in England,
living a privileged life under Queen Victoria's protection. Sarah's
story, illustrated with historic photos, is riveting and not a
little sad, for this dignified princess never really found her
place in life. Myers, a highly respected black writer, cuts through
the complexities of race, class and identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragweed,'' by Avi, illustrated by Brian Floca (Avon Camelot,
$15). Ages 8-12.
</P>
<P>
   Ragweed, a naive country mouse, hops a freight train and ends up
in an urban jungle, in this engaging prequel to Avi's acclaimed
``Poppy'' and ``Poppy and Rye.'' Ragweed's mentor is Clutch, a
green-haired hipster mouse who clues him in to the hateful stalkers
of F.E.A.R. (Felines Enraged About Rodents). There's a serious
message about intolerance, but Avi keeps it light, with plenty of
oddball characters and narrow squeaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holes,'' by Louis Sachar (Farrar, Strauss, Giroux, 233 pages,
$16). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of the National Book Award and the Newbery Medal, this
deftly woven story takes us to Camp Green Lake, a barren wasteland
where young inmates spend their days digging holes, supposedly to
build character. When a hard-luck kid named Stanley Yelnats lands
there for a crime he didn't commit, the truth about Camp Green Lake
and his own tangled history begins to emerge. Suspenseful,
thought-provoking and filled with dark humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ties That Bind, Ties That Break,'' by Lensey Namioka
(Delacorte, 154 pages, $15.95). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, as China goes through cultural upheaval, a spirited
little girl from a wealthy family refuses to have her feet bound.
Later, her big, ``peasant'' feet render her unmarriageable, forcing
her to make her own way in a changing world. Namioka, a Seattle
author who was born in Beijing, brings an authentic voice to this
engrossing story, with an afterword on the history of foot-binding,
and Victorian corsets and modern spike heels. For readers 9 to 12,
see ``Child Bride,'' by Ching Yeung Russell, illustrated by
Jonathan T. Russell. (Boyds Mills Press, 133 pages, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   LEMON ALERT
</P>
<P>
   ``Life's Little Fable,'' by Patricia Cornwell, illustrated by
Barbara Leonard Gibson (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $16.99). Ages 5-up.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell, a popular writer of grim adult mysteries, here proves
that writing children's books isn't as easy as it looks. (Some
Seattle booksellers murmur that this picture book would not have
seen daylight if not for Cornwell's marquee value).
</P>
<P>
   Here a boy named Jarrod frolics innocently in a land without
gravity or shadows. Things take an unexpectedly nasty turn as
Jarrod nearly succumbs to the evil pond god who lured his father to
his death. It ends on an implausibly happy note.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness in children's literature can be a fine thing, but this
story is downright creepy, and the plot crumbles like bad pie
crust. For instance, Jarrod knows he can climb trees and never fall
because ``he's daring and doesn't like rules.'' But if there's no
gravity, why a rule against climbing trees? And why don't the deer
and squirrels float too?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nova's Ark,'' by David Kirk (Scholastic/Callaway, $17.95). All
ages.
</P>
<P>
   This tale of a futuristic robot astronaut is slick, poorly
written and strangely lacking in soul. What it has, however, is 3-D
computer-generated imagery in Kirk's trademark lurid colors and a
publicity push that exploits the fame of his best-selling ``Miss
Spider'' books. In fairness, Kirk's older fans will probably be
intrigued by his Nova artwork, featured in The New York Times Book
Review's holiday '98 issue. But by themselves, catchy computer
graphics are a thin excuse for a children's book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
