<HEADER>
A7562 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-OKUI-LADN-(SLANG)     06-23 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-OKUI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRING TO THE PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT PURDUE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mas Okui's 57-year love affair with fishing the
Eastern Sierra began not with rods and reels but string and a
safety pin _ and barbed wire and armed guards.
</P>
<P>
   Okui was in the fifth grade in 1942 when he and his family were
rousted from their Burbank home and transported to Manzanar
Relocation Center, a World War II internment camp in a dry,
desolate and wind-swept sliver of the Owens Valley. He was one of
more than 110,000 Japanese-Americans imprisoned in U.S. camps from
1942 to 1945; the closest town to Manzanar is Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Bairs Creek trickled through the southwest corner of Manzanar,
Okui recalled, exposing him and his friends to trout fishing for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would try to trap them, run them into a corner and catch
them with our bare hands,'' said Okui, now 67, a retired history
teacher living in Woodland Hills with his wife of 43 years, Aki.
``We also tried a string with a pin on the end, but that didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, a rifle-toting guard tossed a bag of drop lines _ small
wooden frames wound with string _ over the barbed-wire fence. Okui
didn't catch anything memorable, but he has been hooked on fishing
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Today Okui is regarded as one of the finest fly-anglers in the
area, and many say his knowledge of Hot Creek _ a trophy
fly-fishing stream about 85 miles north of the long-ruined but
never-forgotten Manzanar site _ is unsurpassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the better fishermen in Southern California, if
not the Western United States,'' said George Chapman, 79, of
Woodland Hills, who with Okui is a member of the San Fernando
Valley-based Sierra Pacific Flyfishers club. ``On Hot Creek he has
all the trout named and knows their hangouts. He knows every rock,
nook and cranny.''
</P>
<P>
   Okui's unique fly-tying and iconoclastic casting methods have
elevated him to guru status among some anglers. In the
Japanese-American community, he is known as a proud historian
dedicated to preserving the heritage of the Japanese-American
experience. He taught history and government classes for nearly 30
years at Canoga Park and Gardena high schools.
</P>
<P>
   After Manzanar, Okui graduated from San Fernando High and later
joined the Army. While stationed in Europe, he was smitten with the
notion of fishing the same Pyrenees streams where Ernest Hemingway
had wet lines. He got lost, met Basque sheepherders and caught a
few fish.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he found himself back in California. Here he concentrated
on bait-fishing Hot Creek because he couldn't figure out how to
fly-fish among the weeds. In his living room hangs an eight-pound
brown trout he hooked in the waters east of Mammoth Lakes, well
before the famous creek became a catch-and-release fishery.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, Okui began fly-fishing with colleagues at
Gardena High and spent summer vacations traveling to hundreds of
streams in the West with Aki and their two sons, Matt and Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few streams in the Western U.S. I haven't
fished at some point,'' Okui said. ``I've met some of the best
fishermen in the country. My philosophy is very simple: Go to a
stream you haven't fished before and give it three days; because if
there's a guy who's really good on that stream, you're going to
meet him during one of those three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Okui also formulated his own fly-tying style, as well. While
many anglers spend countless hours _ and dollars _ meticulously
matching their flies to the color and shape of the insects trout
favor, Okui, in keeping with his unassuming demeanor, has a simple
plan:
</P>
<P>
   ``First, they've got to work. They've got to be easy to tie. If
they are dry flies, they've got to be very visible. They've got to
be durable. And they've got to be cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Call him a frugal angler. His fishing methods have certainly
been shaped by his teacher's salary. Tough, long-lasting flies are
just one example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught 21 fish with one fly before I stopped using it, just
to see how durable a fly would get,'' he explained. The thrifty
Okui also often employs a 35-year-old reel he bought at a fire sale
for $15. The paint might be long worn off, but it catches trout
with the best of them. And while anglers have been known to spend
$500 or more for a top-flight fly rod, Okui prefers a rod
custom-built for him for $97.
</P>
<P>
   The fly-angler has developed an unorthodox method for tying
extra-long leaders. On Hot Creek, he casts leaders ranging from 16
to 22 feet, far longer than those used by most fly-anglers. This
technique allows him a 20- to 30-foot, drag-free float of the fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the drag-free float, the more fish are going to hit
that fly,'' he explained, because the current isn't forcing the fly
downstream at an unnatural pace.
</P>
<P>
   Okui said about two dozen fishermen have bought into this
unusual fishing system, including one of his former Gardena High
students, Dennis Tsuyuki. ``If you watch a modern fly-fishing video
and then watch Mas, you'd say, `What the hell is wrong with this
guy?' '' noted Tsuyuki, a vice president at Universal Studios.
``But it really works. His leader formula is probably the best I've
used.''
</P>
<P>
   Okui teaches fly-tying and fly-fishing classes through Sierra
Pacific Flyfishers and donates all his proceeds to an organization
that sends schoolchildren on field trips to Washington, D.C. He
also serves as curator of the Manzanar Project of the Eastern
California Museum in Independence and leads tour groups at the
Japanese-American National Museum in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels he was wronged as a child, but it's not with a
vengeance. Instead, he wants to ensure that it doesn't happen
again,'' Chapman said. ``He's all-American, that's for sure. But he
doesn't want people to forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Some friends claim Okui's memories of two-and-a-half years in
Manzanar drive him to excel on the waters of the Eastern Sierra.
Not so, Okui said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly-fishing is the only activity I know of, other than
meditation, where you can cleanse your mind,'' he noted. ``At this
point in my life, the things I'm interested in are going
fly-fishing, working at the museum and having fun. Life is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proof that the American system works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
