<DOCNO> NYT19990623.0506 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7565 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-FERRIGNO-SPI &LR;      06-23 1600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FERRIGNO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER OF HARD-KNUCKLED NOVELS LIVES A WARD CLEAVER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Kirkland neighborhood is peaceful and suburban,
with broad lawns, well-kept homes and outsized vehicles. About the
only menacing note in this comfortable enclave of family life east
of Seattle is sounded by a curbside sign: ``Warning! Crime Watch
Neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign, though, does not tell the whole truth. This is not
only a neighborhood where crime is watched. This is a neighborhood
where crime is hatched, twisted schemes of one kind or another,
drug deals, phone pranks, sex scams, double crosses, even
murders-for-hire.
</P>
<P>
   They are all hatched in one house and in one room, a small
sanctuary of air-conditioned cool over the garage. Here, thriller
writer Robert Ferrigno sits at a computer and concocts his noir
excursions into the seamy side of life in Los Angeles, particularly
Orange County, a place of sun-baked California dreams and
all-American excesses where there is, as he puts it, ``vast
ambition and no interest in working for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between that L.A. terrain and this suburban street
could not be more stark, which is just the way Ferrigno likes it.
Here the 51-year-old writer, whose novels resonate with menace and
eroticism, lives a resoundingly normal life with his wife and four
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live a Ward Cleaver existence here _ something I never
thought I could achieve,'' Ferrigno relates. ``I consider myself
officially retired from a previous life that killed a lot of my
friends, those times of staying up all night and professional
gambling, times when I would either have $10,000 in my pocket or
have to do day labor, plus years of living in bad neighborhoods
with their intrigues, their interesting characters and their vivid
street dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the excesses of Ferrigno's previous life has been
wasted, as the many readers of his hard-knuckled novels can attest.
They provided the plot fodder for his much-noticed first novel in
1990, ``The Horse Latitudes,'' and four subsequent thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrigno's latest is ``Heartbreaker'' (Pantheon, 307 pages,
$24), which many critics and the author are calling his best novel,
one that abundantly displays the extra time and creative attention
lavished upon it by the writer and his new publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heartbreaker'' is a page-turner with verve and sass. It is
rife with snap-crackling dialogue, sardonic humor and torrid love,
all Ferrigno trademarks, but honed this time to stiletto sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feelings are a little hurt,'' remarks one character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run them,'' advises another, ``under the cold-water tap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heartbreaker'' opens when Val Duran, former Miami undercover
cop, flees the Flamingo City after extracting retribution for a
drug lord's murder of his partner, which he had to witness, in
horror, from a distance. Duran settles into a subterranean life in
L.A., working as a tech adviser on crummy movies while guarding his
privacy in hopes of not leaving any trail the drug lord can track.
</P>
<P>
   Then Duran, against his best intentions, falls for a Kyle
Abbott, a fiercely independent marine biologist, and soon finds
himself ensnared with her wealthy family, including her Hollywood
pretty-boy stepbrother. Kilo, as he is nicknamed, turns out to be
enmeshed with two scary partners (one femme fatale, one bruiser of
a Gulf War combat vet) in a plot to murder his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heartbreaker'' soon becomes like a runaway freight train
barreling down three tracks at once _ the drug lord closing in on
Duran, his burgeoning relationship with Kyle and the unfolding of
the heinous murder for inheritance. And along the way, even the
careful reader is kept deliciously off-kilter with fiendish
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   As one character observes, ``Ain't nothing certain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heartbreaker'' began with just two images in Ferrigno's fervid
imagination, the sort of cinematic snippet that floats into his
mind in the pre-dawn hours or in the last moments before sleep at
night.
</P>
<P>
   He saw a man forced to watch the murder of a friend and a
Hollywood hunk tied down on a bed, both images of profound
helplessness. He would spend months letting the images develop
until he was ready to sit down at his computer and try to figure
out ``how these people might fit together.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how Ferrigno's books have all been born, but little
about the rest of the process of writing ``Heartbreaker'' would
follow his usual pattern. The difference this time was that the
writer was working with Sonny Mehta, a legendary New York literary
figure who is head of the Knopf Publishing Group.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta not only headed the company publishing Ferrigno's new
novel, he served as its editor, a line-by-line, take-your-time
editor of the old school now nearly extinct. So the writer not only
spent more than twice as long on ``Heartbreaker'' as his previous
novels, he benefited from an editor who gave him both intense
attention to every detail and a long leash to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being on the phone with Sonny for five hours one
day, going over a section of the book line by line in order to cut
three pages,'' Ferrigno recalls. ``I told him at one point that I
thought I had to do something a certain way and he said to me, `You
don't have to do anything any way.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There was such a sense of freedom working with him _ that was
why this was the happiest experience I have had on a book. On my
first book, I didn't know what to do; on this book, I tried to
forget everything I'd learned before.''
</P>
<P>
   What did not change, however, was Ferrigno's basic mindset. His
novels are character-driven, rather than plot-driven (``I don't do
procedurals; I'm more interested in inhabiting the skins of the bad
guys and the good guys''). And Ferrigno, who readily admits he
skipped sections of ``The Silence of the Lambs'' because the
violence was ``too graphic, too real,'' prefers to render menace
more than actual violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a morality to my work,'' he stresses.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a distinctly cinematic quality to Ferrigno's
thrillers. They seem virtually camera-ready, as Hollywood has
recognized. Ferrigno's novels have been optioned repeatedly for
films, although none has actually made it to the screen. The writer
is disappointed about that, but past experience has made him savvy
about the fickle ways of filmdom.
</P>
<P>
   As Ferrigno relates, ``I remember when the option first lapsed
on `The Horse Latitudes' and I wanted to cry _ I thought, `My God,
does that mean my book is not any good?' Now I think of the money I
receive for film options as free money. I got six figures from the
option for `Heartbreaker' and that recently lapsed and somebody
else may soon be optioning it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrigno, a soft-spoken and unassuming straight shooter, is a
remarkably successful commercial writer, well-compensated for his
talents. He has been from the outset when ``The Horse Latitudes''
earned a publisher advance with foreign rights of almost $500,000
and a Time magazine rave as ``the most memorable fiction debut of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't appreciate that at the time,'' he admits. ``I didn't
realize how rare that was with a first book.''
</P>
<P>
   That early success was sweet revenge for Ferrigno, who had quit
his job as a feature writer at the Orange County Register to pursue
his novelist's dream, a leap into the unknown that prompted the
paper's editor to warn Ferrigno ``you'll never make newspaper wages
again.'' Ferrigno never has made newspaper wages again; his have
always been higher.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he credits his newspaper journalism for turning him into
a writer, despite his master's from the writing program at Bowling
Green University in Ohio. Ferrigno honed his journalism skills on
alternative weeklies in Seattle for the now-defunct Seattle Sun and
later as one of six co-founders of The Rocket, a rock music paper,
before moving to the big leagues of Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to write there _ learned to write fast, be incisive
and to get to it,'' he emphasizes. ``People then spent 25 cents for
a paper and they didn't spend that to read me. So I figured I had
to trap them, engage them in such a way that they could not stop
reading me.''
</P>
<P>
   His days as a professional poker player also contributed to the
writer that Ferrigno is today. He spent five years earning his
living playing cards at gaming tables in Seattle private clubs and
in Las Vegas casinos. He still makes a couple of pilgrimages to Las
Vegas every year in order to keep his gambling skills current,
which also benefits his writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poker is about learning to scope out your opposition,''
Ferrigno says. ``It's more about character than cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this self-described ``expatriate L.A. writer'' seems
totally at home in his suburban Seattle milieu, the wood stove in
the family room, the framed kid art, the rustic wood glider for two
out back. But he is nowhere more at home than in his study, where
the bookshelves hold editions of his books, both American and
foreign, testament to this writer's goal achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal has always been to be one of those writers who, when
you open one of their books, you see a list of the books that
writer has written,'' Ferringo stresses. ``That list shows you're
someone who's in the game for the long run. It's just like in
gambling: It's nice to have all the money at the end, but there's
also something about being in the game right until the end. Then
you're a player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
