<SLUG> BC-TV-CBC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBC WORTH TUNING INTO FOR SOME SUMMER FARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a French-Canadian surname like Levesque, I'm genetically
predisposed to watching CBC Television. This is especially true in
the summertime, when U.S. networks go on vacation, figuring there
aren't enough people watching TV to warrant the introduction of
fresh new programming.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, my need for Canadian programming went
unfulfilled unless I went to the trouble of snagging the
over-the-air signal from CBUT in Vancouver, B.C. This exercise
involved propping a small TV set on the kitchen counter, tilting it
slightly with the help of ``The Joy of Cooking,'' and pointing the
antenna in the general direction of the Yukon.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't do this too often, because the picture was fuzzier than
the memory of a Seattle Mariners executive, and it was no fun
sitting three inches from the screen trying to follow the puck on
``Hockey Night in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, TCI Cable upgraded my neighborhood and restored CBC
Vancouver to its rightful place in my cable-channel universe, so
now I can watch ``The National'' with Peter Mansbridge and
``Broadcast One'' with Gloria Macarenko, without leaving a
noseprint on the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Canadian broadcasters, part of the CBC's mission is
to ``Canadianize'' programming. It's a government rule, a safeguard
against being swallowed up by the Hollywood entertainment gorilla.
So, while CBC's affiliates still air ``The Simpsons'' and ``The
Wonderful World of Disney,'' they concentrate on original stuff
created in Canada for Canadians (and Americans who happen to live
near the border).
</P>
<P>
   This honeymoon is still quite new, so I may be guilty of the big
gush. But I know there are readers out there who share my affinity
for CBC, even if the quality varies widely.
</P>
<P>
   CBC is best known for its news and public-affairs shows. It also
does sports pretty well, and some of its sketch comedy is a riot,
though I have no idea what it is that people find amusing about
``The Red Green Show.'' (Last week, when I was at the Banff TV
Festival, the stars of the show _ Steve Smith and Pat McKenna _
were much funnier in person. Still, Smith reports that ``The Red
Green Show'' is the best money-raiser for PBS stations stateside
during their begathons.)
</P>
<P>
   The weakest programming on the CBC schedule continues to be
Canadian-produced dramatic series, whose production values don't
quite measure up to their best U.S. counterparts. But buoyed by
audience response to shows like ``Da Vinci's Inquest'' and
``Nothing Too Good for a Cowboy,'' the CBC schedule next fall will
continue with the Canadianization effort, which began three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new series this fall are ``P.R.,'' a comedy about the
entertainment industry, and ``In Tha' Mix,'' a drama about two guys
producing a campus hip-hop radio show. Short-season series include
``These Arms of Mine,'' a six-episode drama about friends and
lovers in Vancouver; ``Cover Me,'' a three-part miniseries about
elite agents fighting international terrorism, and ``Jake &AMP; Jill,''
a six-installment romantic comedy. The major effort next season
will be a 30-hour documentary series titled ``Canada: A People's
History.''
</P>
<P>
   'Scuse me while I stock up on the Molson.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   The season finale of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' originally
scheduled to air May 25, will be broadcast July 13 at 8 p.m. on The
WB Network. The episode involves high school students rising up in
arms against a demon mayor, so The WB decided to delay the
broadcast rather than air it so close to the date of the Columbine
High School shootings in Littleton, Colo. ... Why is this man
smiling? Jeff Smulyan, who sold the Seattle Mariners to the
Over-the-Bill Gang currently seeking a $60 million increase in its
allowance, graces the cover of this week's Broadcasting &AMP; Cable
magazine. Though undervalued by Wall Street, Smulyan's
Indianapolis-based Emmis Communications Corp. (16 radio stations,
six TV stations, six magazines) has grown steadily over the years.
In the past 18 months, Emmis has spent more than a billion dollars
on acquisitions and investments, none involving major league
baseball. ... Electronic Media reports that NBC is negotiating with
``Profiler'' star Ally Walker to release her from her contract. The
three-year-old series, produced by NBC Studios, reportedly will
replace Walker with a new character. ... Here's some fodder for the
next backyard barbecue. A survey commissioned by Illuminations, the
yuppie candle company that has stores in Seattle and Bellevue,
reveals that 51 percent of 423 respondents nationwide say watching
Martha Stewart on TV stresses them out, and that Dan Rather is more
stress-inducing than Peter Jennings or Tom Brokaw. ... Fans of
``Another World'' may find consolation in knowing that four
characters from the daytime soap, which is ending its 35-year run
this week, will show up temporarily on ``As the World Turns'' later
this summer. Procter &AMP; Gamble Productions, which owns both shows,
will have Jake and Vicky McKinnon (Tom Eplin and Jensen Buchanan)
and Lila and Cass Winthrop (Lisa Peluso and Stephen Schnetzer)
making brief stops in Oakdale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
