<SLUG> BC-STOCK-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ALLOWS 2 PRICE LEVELS IN STOCK PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a decision with broad implications for privately
owned companies and their workers, a federal judge in Manhattan has
ruled that such concerns may use different methods to value company
shares that workers buy outright and those that they purchase in a
retirement plan.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in the case of an executive with a Connecticut
brokerage house who sought $6 million in March 1996 as fair market
value for 120,000 shares of his employer's stock. But the company,
Soundview Technology Group of Stamford, Conn., said the shares had
a book value of $696,000.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Pollack, a senior judge in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, ruled that Soundview may use different techniques to
value shares sold in its stock purchase plan and in its 401(k)
profit-sharing plan so long as the methods are reasonable and are
consistently applied.
</P>
<P>
   He also held, after a three-day trial, that book value was a
reasonable proxy for fair market value in determining how much to
pay departing employees for Soundview shares held in the 401(k)
plan.
</P>
<P>
   In publicly traded companies the value of shares can be
determined from trading in securities markets. But millions of
Americans work for companies whose stock does not trade publicly
and, therefore, whose value is more difficult to determine. The
issues in the Soundview case are more likely to arise in employee
stock ownership plans than in 401(k) plans, which tend to be
invested in mutual funds and securities that can be easily valued.
</P>
<P>
   The case was complicated by the fact that the plaintiff, Arnold
Owen, had been one of five top executives at Soundview, was a
trustee of the 401(k) plan and had hired appraisers to value the
shares of Soundview in the 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, the U.S. Department of Labor told Soundview
that its valuation of its shares in the 401(k) plan was improper
and violated the Employee Retirement Income Security Act, the 1974
law governing retirement plans. It also found that the book value
technique used by Soundview understated the value of Owen's shares
by at least 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department noted that in 1991 it had threatened to sue
the company unless it properly valued shares in the 401(k) plan, a
threat reiterated in the Feb. 10 finding.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack held that the Labor Department investigation and
findings were irrelevant to Owen's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The judge not only ruled against Owen, but found him so lacking
in credibility that he decided all issues in favor of Soundview and
said he must pay Soundview's legal costs because he brought the
case in bad faith. The amount will be determined later.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack, in a 29-page opinion, also suggested that had Owen
bought his 120,000 shares outside of the 401(k) plan he might have
been entitled to more money. But the judge held that as a
sophisticated executive who had signed key documents, Owen knew or
should have known how his Soundview shares in the 401(k) plan would
be valued.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with nonmarketable shares are required to use fair
market value for their shares in 401(k), employee stock ownership
and similar retirement plans, said David West, the senior
retirement plan specialist at Gibson, Dunn &AMP; Crutcher in Los
Angeles. Book value, the pricing technique used by Soundview, may
or may not represent fair market value, West said.
</P>
<P>
   John Reichman of Wachtel &AMP; Masyr, one of Owen's lawyers, said
the decision would be appealed and that he expected the Labor
Department would join in that appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
