<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TAPIA-AYALA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S NOT A GAMBLER, BUT BOXER AYALA TRYING TO BEAT ODDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Like many innocent out-of-towners, Fort Worth's
Paulie Ayala needed to have the betting line on his title fight
against World Boxing Association bantamweight champion Johnny Tapia
spelled out for him yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia-Ayala occupies a prime spot on the big electronic board in
the Race &AMP; Sports Book at the Mandalay Bay Resort &AMP; Casino, site of
their scheduled 12-rounder on Saturday night. As of yesterday
afternoon, the odds on Tapia successfully defending his 118-pound
title stood at minus-$600. The odds on Ayala, the WBA's No.
2-ranked contender, were listed at plus-$400.
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean to prospective bettors, innocent or
otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   ``Minus-$600 is a heavy favorite for Tapia,'' said Marc Ratner,
executive director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission, and a
participant in the final prefight news conference here. ``When
you're laying 6-to-1, that's a pretty good favorite. In other
words, if you wanted to bet on Tapia, you have to put up $600 to
win $100. If you want to bet on Ayala, you bet $100 and you can win
$400. There's no value, as they say, to betting on the favorite.
You get much better odds when you bet on the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the odds nor the explanation, however, lightened Ayala's
mood before he and trainer Henry Mendez took their seats on the
dais at the hotel's Events Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those odds are crazy. But I don't bet,'' Ayala said. ``I throw
in some change in the slot machines, but I don't bet. But I bet _ I
mean, I'm confident _ I'm going to win. This is a business trip
really. There's no joking or gaming around for me. I'm here to
fight, make money and go on home. I'm not here to leave some of it
in the casino, for the decorations.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after their final news conference in Los
Angeles, Ayala and Tapia dutifully sat through their guaranteed
final news conference with promoter Bob Arum of Top Rank, Inc.
Clearly, the mix of a whirlwind promotional tour that began so
amicably last month had clashed with the demands of training camp,
and the realization that someone is going to suffer a serious
career setback in two nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we were in LA on Tuesday,'' said Tapia, 32, of
Albuquerque, N.M. ``I'm tired of this ... . And I'm anxious to get
to him \RAyala\S. You don't even know. I'm tired of looking at him
at press conferences. I'm tired of talking into the mike. It's time
to put up. Ain't nobody taking my belt away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Freddie Roach said Tapia _ a three-time champion despite
repeated bouts with cocaine earlier this decade _ definitely had
slipped on his game face.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they changed opponents tomorrow, we don't care,'' Roach
said. ``Johnny's getting a little fed up with me in the gym. He
peaked on Friday, our last day of sparring. We're just maintaining
right now. We haven't boxed since that day, and we won't box until
we see Paulie.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Tapia (46-0-2, 25 knockouts), Ayala's formal remarks were
clipped after what he also considered a wasted trip to a club in
Hollywood to pump up pay-per-view sales on Showtime Event
Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do my part for the promotion,'' said Ayala, 29. ``But
it messed up my \Rtraining\S schedule. I left Vegas at 7 in the
morning and got back at 5 in the afternoon. I went to the gym at 6
and wound up running at 9 at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm through selling tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he really was not. When it came time for Ayala (27-1,
12 KOs) to stand behind the microphones and shower yet another
round of praise upon his opponent, he flicked on the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me seven years to get my first title shot, so this
one's come a lot faster,'' said Ayala, who suffered a sixth-round
technical loss against then-World Boxing Council champion Joichiro
Tatsuyoshi in Japan on Aug. 23. ``I'm just ready to fight. I'm
looking forward to a very intense night of boxing. I'm confident
and looking forward to being the WBA bantamweight champion of the
world.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
