r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-MOORE-LADN-(SLANG     06-23 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MOORE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S MOORE ELECTED TO HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Billie Moore, the former UCLA and Cal
State-Fullerton women's basketball coach who won two NCAA
championships, was elected to the Basketball Hall of Fame on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moore joins ex-Boston Celtic Kevin McHale, former Georgetown
coach John Thompson and two contributors, Wayne Embry and Fred
Zollner, to form the class of 1999. The induction ceremony is Oct.
1 in Springfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned and a little in awe,'' Moore said. ``A lot of
people have asked me how I feel. I'm the type of person who has to
think about things before I decide how I feel. I'm still thinking
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   In eight years at Fullerton State, Moore was 140-15 and won the
1970 NCAA title. In 16 seasons at UCLA, she was 296-181 and won the
1978 title. She coached Ann Meyers and Denise Curry, and she guided
the United States to the silver medal in the 1976 Olympics in
Montreal _ the first Olympics for women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, she was a pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told those players that there would be a lot more Olympic
teams, but there would only be one first Olympic team, and we were
proud to be the first,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore learned of her induction Tuesday evening after returning
to her Orange County home from a round of golf. She shared the news
with her family, then waited for the official announcement
Wednesday morning. The phone hasn't stopped ringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't really sunk in yet,'' Moore said. ``It's so
different for me because basketball is such a team sport and this
is an individual honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore retired from UCLA after the 1993 season. Like John Wooden,
she has opted for the shadows, not wanting to pressure her
successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Current Bruins coach Kathy Olivier) asked me to wait to come
back until she was ready,'' Moore said. ``So two years ago, I went
to a few games. She's feeling more comfortable. If I had that team,
I'd feel more comfortable, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
