<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SUPREME MISCHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 24:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court ended its 1998-99 term on two deeply
disturbing notes. On Tuesday it significantly weakened protections
afforded by a federal law barring discrimination against people
with disabilities. Wednesday, in three separate decisions delivered
in a morning of high drama, it significantly strengthened the power
of the states in the federal system while weakening those of the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The states' rights decisions were particularly alarming.
Although basic civil rights protected by the 14th Amendment are not
affected, the decisions will make it harder to enforce uniform
policies on matters of national concern like the environment or
health. They also provide further evidence of the increasingly
bitter ideological split among the justices over how to balance
federal and state powers. Finally, they confirm the narrow but
nonetheless decisive control of a coalition of five conservative
justices.
</P>
<P>
   These five _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Associate
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony Kennedy and
Clarence Thomas _ have been steadily whittling down the legitimate
authority of the federal government in a series of 5-4 decisions
since 1996. This same group, supposedly opposed to judicial
activism, has now declared two federal laws unconstitutional and
left important precedents in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   One of the states' rights cases involved an attempt by state
probation officers in Maine to enforce their right to overtime pay
under the Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938. Writing for the
majority, Kennedy said that the Constitution's ``structure and
history'' not only shielded states from lawsuits in federal courts
but also gave them immunity from state court lawsuits seeking to
enforce a federal right. In other words, he seemed to suggest, the
Maine probation officers have a federally protected right to get
paid for overtime work, but no effective way to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   In the same cramped spirit, the court invoked the doctrine of
sovereign immunity to protect Florida from having to defend itself
in federal courts from legal challenges to its program to help
families save for tuition in the state's public universities. A New
Jersey bank with a similar tuition-savings program had brought two
suits, saying that Florida had violated federal patent law as well
as federal trademark law. The court ruled for Florida in both
cases.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the court's main focus was the Americans with
Disabilities Act. In a humane and soundly reasoned ruling, it
upheld by a 6-3 vote a 1991 federal regulation that barred states
from segregating mentally disabled individuals in a state
institution when a small supervised group home in the community
would be medically and socially more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the court used three other cases to
narrow the law's reach in the vital area of employment
discrimination. In its core 7-2 holding, the court declared that
individuals with physical impairments that can be easily corrected
so they can function normally are not ``disabled'' and therefore
are not entitled to protection under the Act _ even though the
disabilities cost them their jobs. As Justice John Paul Stevens
countered in a forceful dissent, that ``crabbed version'' of the
law ignores its intended purpose, which is to protect anyone with a
disability from being discriminated against because of it.
</P>
<P>
   The unhappy result of the court's final 48 hours is thus two
glaring legal anomalies. People with federally protected rights
have no realistic way to enforce them against states. People
considered sufficiently disabled by employers to be denied a job
are now seen by this court to be insufficiently impaired to
challenge that decision under the Disabilities Act. All in all,
this was not a worthy exit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
