<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER STACKS THE METS' DECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven superb innings, seven overpowering strikeouts
and four victories in his last four starts have made it pretty
clear that the staff's ace, Al Leiter, has found his way back into
the New York Mets' deck. And oh, how that deck has been stacked
lately, as the Florida Marlins unfortunately discovered for the
second straight game Wednesday night, losing by 6-3 to a team that
has won 13 of its last 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   A three-run fifth helped bury the Marlins before 25,116 fans at
Shea Stadium. Edgardo Alfonzo with a 3-for-4 night and three runs
batted in, and Roger Cedeno with two steals, his 40th and 41st of
the season, were a big part of it.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied 2-2, Cedeno led off the fifth with a line
drive single and had Marlins starter Brian Meadows (5-8) worried
enough to pitch out. Cedeno stayed _ for a pitch. But on the next
one, he stole second _ his second theft of the night and 41st of
the season _ when catcher Mike Redmond sailed his throw.
</P>
<P>
   After Rey Ordonez sacrificed Cedeno to third and Leiter grounded
out to second, Meadows walked Ricky Henderson. It was a mistake to
leave men on the corners for Alfonzo, who finished the game 3 for 4
with three runs batted in. His homer in the third cut a Marlins
lead to 2-1. His first-pitch single up the middle this time put the
Mets up for good, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   When John Olerud doubled down the right field line to chase
Alfonzo and Henderson home, the Mets were on the verge of getting
the 11th victory against one loss from its starting rotation in the
last 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, on the night Bobby Bonilla got his first hit
since June 11 _ a pinch-double in the seventh _ Mike Piazza's club
tying hitting streak ended at 24 games. It was a frustrating night
for the Mets' catcher, who got slammed in the back when Bruce Aven
swung through a Leiter pitch for a strikeout in the seventh. In the
eighth, Piazza misjudged a foul pop off the bat of Preston Wilson
that sent him head over heels in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   And at bat, he went 0 for 4, leaving him tied with Hubie Brooks
(1984) for the club record in consecutive games hit safely.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clearly Leiter's night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's doing anything different, but he's getting
different results,'' said manager Bobby Valentine. ``He's a little
more healthy. And he's also changed the grip on his change up which
is giving hitters a different look.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, it hardly looked as if Leiter, who was
signed before the season for $32 million over four years to anchor
the Mets staff, would duplicate his recent good form. After winning
three straight starts - including a three hit, eight strikeout gem
in a 4-3 win over St. Louis last week _ the left hander struggled
with his control early in Wednesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring the leadoff hitter Luis Castillo, Leiter yielded
singles to Alex Gonzalez and Aven, then walked Kevin Orie to load
the bases. He looked as if he might escape trouble when he fanned
Danny Bautista, but then Preston Wilson squibbed a single over the
outstretched glove of Alfonzo at second base to chase Gonzalez and
Aven home for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets inched back in the third when Cedeno (2-3, 2 runs
scored) led off the inning by putting his quick wheels to work and
dribbled a perfect bunt down the third base line that Orie couldn't
handle.
</P>
<P>
   On the next pitch, he got the jump on Meadows and blitzed down
the base line for his 40th stolen base. After Ordonez laid down a
sacrifice bunt to move Cedeno to third, the Marlins pulled the
infield in for Leiter and dared the .045 hitter to drive one by
them.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't need to. Leiter took the count to 1-2 and tomahawked a
chopper over the mound that was fielded by Gonzalez, but not in
time to get Cedeno, and the Mets were down, 2-1. His RBI, followed
by Alfonzo's homer in the fourth cleared the way for Leiter to
befuddle the Marlins hitters with crisp fast balls and fluttering
off-speed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up a run scoring single to Gonzalez in the seventh, but
Alfonzo got it back the next inning when he drove Melvin Mora, who
was running for Bonilla, home with his third hit of the night. With
Armando Benitez pitching the eighth and John Franco recording his
18th save in 19 opportunities by pitching the ninth, the Mets
pitching _ starting and relieving _ suddenly looks formidable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It might even get better, for Bobby Jones is expected to come
off the disabled list soon and earlier in the day, the Mets called
up the hard throwing Octavio Dotel from Triple-A Norfolk, where he
was 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   After six years in the minor leagues, Dotel will make his major
league debut Saturday night against the Braves in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long, slow climb for the Dominican right-hander,
one that may have ended Wednesday when the Mets decided to send the
struggling Jason Isringhausen back to Class AAA Norfolk, and a new
assignment in the bullpen there, and bring up Dotel in his place.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets may be hoping he is up to stay. In 12 starts with
the Tides, Dotel, 23, had a 3.99 earned run average and was second
in the International League with 84 strikeouts. He brings a
six-year 55-25 record from the minors, and confessed Wednesday that
he thought he might have arrived in the majors sooner. But
Valentine said the slow rise helped the right-hander master command
of four pitches: fastball, curve, slider and change-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He moved up the organizational ladder properly,'' Valentine
said. ``Everything I know about him makes me confident he could be
a successful major league pitcher. He showed he had command of his
pitches. He was consistent. He was striking guys out, but he wasn't
walking a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's here, Dotel said his goal is simple: to stick.
``They think I'm ready, that's why I'm here,'' he said. ``Now I
want to find a way to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
