<SLUG> BC-LEHMAN-CENSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN BROTHERS CENSURED AND FINED $100,000 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers, one of the nation's largest investment banks,
has been censured and fined $100,000 as part of a settlement of
regulatory charges that included an accusation that it failed to
comply with market rules intended to ensure that public investors
get a fair share of hot initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The violations involved $16 million worth of stock sold as part
of four offerings that went to market between April and December
1996, according to NASD Regulation, an arm of the National
Association of Securities Dealers, which announced the settlement
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the offering problems, regulators also cited the
firm for violations of rules governing short sales _ which are
sales of borrowed stock by investors who hope to profit on a
subsequent decline in the price _ and on disclosure of sales
charges to mutual fund purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   William Ahearn, a spokesman for Lehman, said the firm would not
comment on any details of the case, which arose in the course of a
routine NASD examination of the firm that began early in 1997.
While Lehman neither denied nor admitted any wrongdoing, it did
submit a letter to NASD regulators indicating that it had improved
its record-keeping procedures to prevent such violations in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The Lehman settlement comes amid continuing regulatory concern
about whether big brokerage houses are shortchanging the public by
using scarce shares in hot initial offerings to reward big clients
or attract potential clients, a practice known as spinning.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Goldsmith, the executive vice president of NASD
Regulation, said that while the Lehman case did not deal directly
with the spinning issue, it reflected the same regulatory premise:
that brokers should make a ``bona fide public distribution'' of hot
initial public offering shares, defined as new issues that trade at
a premium in the market, immediately after they begin trading.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman was accused of selling shares to investors who should not
have been allowed to buy, failing to adequately determine whether
other purchasers could legally buy shares, and inaccurately
reporting to regulators the percentage of each of the disputed
offerings that had been sold to public investors.
</P>
<P>
   According to Goldsmith, the sanctions against Lehman, higher
than in many typical cases involving offerings-allocation rules,
reflected the large number of shares that were incorrectly handled
_ more than 1.1 million _ and their aggregate market value.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the violations involved shares of Pharmaceutical
Product Development Inc., which went public in April 1996;
Thermoquest Corp., which went to market in May 1996; Rofin-Sinar
Technologies Inc., which was first sold in October 1996, and Memco
Software Ltd., which went public in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to regulators, the short-sale violations occurred on
14 separate days between July 1995 and February 1997 and involved
violations of NASD rules requiring that short sales on a stock that
is declining in price be transacted at a price at least 1/16 higher
than the previous bid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lehman had failed to fully notify customers about
sales charges involved in approximately 4,100 mutual fund
transactions worth about $165 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
